<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-ADS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TRUTH BENT IN ADS FOR SCHOOL INITIATIVES  &HT;     By JOHN WILDERMUTH 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Truth has been a casualty in a pair of hot races involving two
educational initiatives. The battle over ballot measures on school
vouchers and school bonds is flooding the airwaves with TV and
radio spots that are more aggressive than accurate.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, the campaigns for Proposition 38 and Proposition 39
have run the most visible media campaigns in California, bombarding
voters with their own contrasting views of political reality. Who's
doing the fudging, however, depends on who you talk to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed that (school voucher opponents) are getting away
with saying so many things that aren't true,'' said Chris Bertelli,
a spokesman for Proposition 38, the school voucher initiative.
</P>
<P>
   But the opponents have their own complaints about the
pro-voucher ads, which feature young schoolchildren talking about
their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yes on 38 TV ad in Spanish is deceptive and offensive to
the Latino community in California,'' said Hector Chacon, a
Southern California school board trustee. ``Prop. 38 will prevent
our children from succeeding by abandoning the public school
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar complaints echo from the Proposition 39 camp, which is
fighting for a measure that would reduce the present two-thirds
vote requirement to pass school bonds to 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to combat the ridiculous and false statements
being made in the (anti-Prop. 39) ads,'' said Rick Claussen,
campaign manager for the school bond effort.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of SCHOOLAD (70523 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``They're not running the most straightforward campaign,''
countered Sheri Annis, a spokeswoman for the Proposition 39
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Even Gov. Gray Davis has gotten involved _ in a way not to his
liking.
</P>
<P>
   Although Davis is chairman of the anti-voucher campaign and has
done a television ad for the effort, he has found himself the
unexpected star of a pro-Proposition 38 TV spot.
</P>
<P>
   The ad shows Davis saying in his January State of the State
address that ``California schools still rank near the bottom of the
50 states. That's not good enough for me, and it's certainly not
good enough for the children of California.''
</P>
<P>
   If the governor thinks California schools are lousy, the ad
suggests, parents should vote for vouchers to improve their
children's education.
</P>
<P>
   Both the governor and the anti-voucher campaign are crying foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawyers sent all kinds of letters to the `Yes' side telling
them the footage was used illegally,'' said John Lenzner of the
``No on 38'' campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Political advertising has never been held to the same standards
as courtroom testimony, so it's no surprise that the best response
to many of the claims being made might be ``yes, but ... .''
</P>
<P>
   When voucher backers claim that Proposition 38 will bring a new
renaissance to California education, for example, they don't
mention that no state has ever run a voucher system before and the
promised results are largely guesswork.
</P>
<P>
   And while opponents charge that Proposition 39 puts no limits on
tax increases, there aren't any limits now, even without the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of SCHOOLAD (70523 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  One reason the two school campaigns might be nastier than usual
is that they both repeat earlier efforts. In November 1993, a
school voucher effort lost big, due largely to a flood of money
from teacher groups opposed to the plan. And last March, voters
rejected Proposition 26, which would have required only a majority
vote to pass school bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of Proposition 39 are hoping that familiarity will
breed contempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voters didn't go for 50 percent, so now (Prop. 39 backers)
are trying 55 percent,'' Annis said. ``We think the voters will get
a little perturbed at having to vote on something they already
rejected once this year.''
</P>
<P>
   But both voucher and bond advocates argue that they are bringing
new and improved measures to the voters and expect new and improved
results.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't Proposition 26 again,'' said Claussen. ``Now we're
keeping the supermajority vote and adding new accountability
procedures, which makes this different and much better.''
</P>
<P>
   The arguments against the proposals haven't changed much,
however, and neither have their advocates. The anti-voucher effort,
for example, again is backed by education money and supported by
many state and local political powerhouses.
</P>
</TEXT>
