r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLA     09-08 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL AX FALL ON JOHNSON?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Davey Johnson has never been told he would lose
his job as Los Angeles Dodgers manager should the team fail to make
the playoffs this season.
</P>
<P>
   There was, however, an understanding that anything shy of the
playoffs, given his often-chilly relationship with general manager
Kevin Malone, would result in his termination despite having one
year and $1.5 million remaining on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are 73-67, just got pummeled by Pittsburgh and are
10 games behind San Francisco in the National League West, and they
trail the New York Mets by 7 games in the wild-card picture. In
other words, Johnson has 22 games remaining in his two-year tenure
as Dodgers manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things you'd like to improve, and improve at a
faster pace,'' Johnson said. ``I've been here two years, and came
here late in the first year, and in two years I'm in the playoff
picture. I don't feel real good about not being five or six games
up. In this game, you want to fit and you want to make it work, and
if somebody decides something different, that's not even an issue.
That's not a part of my issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Though a decision already appears to be imminent, the brain
trust said it will evaluate everything after the season ends, Oct.
1 in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides will bring their issues. There are reasons to side
with management and there are reasons to side with the manager:
</P>
<P>
   __ Keep him _ Even though the Dodgers are 150-152 in Johnson's
two years in Los Angeles, he remains the winningest active manager.
He's 1,135-879, a winning percentage of .564. Atlanta's Bobby Cox
is second at 1,603-1261(.560). Johnson's won a World Series and
qualified for the playoffs six times.
</P>
<P>
   __ Dump him _ Malone questioned Johnson's managerial strategy,
saying the Dodgers needed to manufacture more runs. Malone said
they needed to bunt more, needed to situational hit better, needed
to improve fundamentals and needed to improve on their record
(12-33) when they don't homer.
</P>
<P>
   __ Keep him _ The Dodgers have a payroll of $98 million, but
they don't have a fourth or fifth starter worth their salt. Kevin
Brown, Chan Ho Park and Darren Dreifort are a combined 37-21 with a
3.49 ERA. But the Dodgers tried Orel Hershiser, Mike Judd, Carlos
Perez, Matt Herges, Eric Gagne and Ismael Valdes in the fourth and
fifth spots, and they've responded by going 7-25 with a 6.70 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   __ Dump him _ The club has no consistency. The Dodgers beat
Philadelphia three straight and seemed to have some fight left.
They turned around and got swept for the first time in 12 years by
the Pittsburgh Pirates, getting outscored 28-4. In Johnson's
tenure, the Dodgers' longest winning streak is six games.
</P>
<P>
   __ Keep him _ There is no depth in the minor-league system. When
center fielder and leadoff hitter Devon White went down for nearly
three months with a partially torn left rotator cuff, Todd
Hollandsworth and F.P. Santangelo wound up playing center field and
leading off, roles in which they were miscast. The team had nobody
to turn to in the minors and didn't have enough talent to make a
trade.
</P>
<P>
   __ Dump him _ Johnson said in spring training he had everything
he needed, i.e., a better bullpen and better bench. Trading leadoff
man Eric Young was an issue, but Johnson said Hollandsworth and
White would be able to handle the load. Instead, the Dodgers'
leadoff men are batting .238 with a .313 on-base percentage. The
Dodgers' top spot in the batting order has scored 86 runs, ahead of
only the seventh, eighth and ninth spots.
</P>
<P>
   __ Keep him _ Gary Sheffield missed 11 games with a viral
infection, Mark Grudzielanek missed six and nearly everyone else
was stricken with the illness and missed some time. There was also
the cloud from Wrigley Field incident hanging over the season for
three months, and it's still not resolved since 21 members of the
organization were subpoenaed for a pair of criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   __ Dump him _ The club spent $98 million so talent could be
mixed and matched to overcome the loss of a player or two for a
certain period of time. And the only lengthy injury that could have
ailed the Dodgers was the loss of White for 71 games. Kevin Brown
suffered a broken right pinkie, but it kept him out for only two
weeks and the type of injury that could devastate a season was not
present.
</P>
<P>
   __ Keep him _ Johnson's a veteran manager with a veteran team.
Matt Herges was the only rookie on the roster for the whole season.
Many players in the clubhouse, despite some differences of opinion
at some point during the season, said Johnson is the perfect
manager for this collection of players. Shortstop Alex Cora and
third baseman Adrian Beltre are the only two starting position
players with less than five years of experience at the major-league
level.
</P>
<P>
   __ Dump him _ Johnson still doesn't communicate with many of his
players. The back-biting that became commonplace last September
isn't around now, but players still wonder about their roles and
often turn to the front office for answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Davey has done the best job any coach can possibly do
under the circumstances,'' Sheffield said. ``To take nothing away
from anyone else, I think Davey has handled the situation probably
as best as anyone could, and to be honest, we just haven't
responded as a team. It's not a reflection of the manager, it's a
reflection of looking in the mirror and saying, 'Do I put the team
first?' `'
</P>
<P>
   Managing general partner, CEO and chairman Bob Daly would not
comment on the managerial issue, other than to say that Johnson is
the club's manager under contract. Malone said he wanted to focus
on the rest of the season, and that Johnson was the manager and is
under contract for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that comes after Daly told Johnson in early July the
Dodgers needed to play with more fire. And after Malone criticized
Johnson's managerial style at the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   The organization hoped that stating those things publicly would
motivate the Dodgers. Instead, it brought a death watch over the
club once it started playing poorly. That subsided for a while last
month when Malone said Johnson would remain for the rest of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the cast of players in here and we're sitting (10)
games out of first place,'' Dodgers catcher Chad Kreuter said.
``Where we have faltered as a team, and this involves players _
this does not involve the coaches or anything _ we have faltered in
that we have not done the things to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those include moving guys over when needed, getting bunts
down, making defensive plays and being a smart player out there.
There's been too many mental mistakes made and each one of us is
guilty of it, so to say we underachieved is probably a good
statement, a true statement. I think it falls on the players.''
</P>
<P>
   The disappointment for the season falls on the players, but when
a team spends likes the Dodgers and doesn't win, especially when it
sells itself as a contender, someone else will take the fall.
</P>
<P>
   That appears to be Johnson. He has a few more punches left in
him when a decision is made on his future, but it apparently will
take an unforeseen turn of events for him to make it to a third
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
