<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN EXPLOSIVE RALLY, YANKS SWAMP ROYALS, 7-3 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Chili Davis played the last two seasons with
the New York Yankees and walked away believing they defied the old
sports axiom that you cannot turn on your intensity like a light
switch. The Yankees, Davis told a friend, were absolutely capable
of doing that, and did it all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Davis would have smiled if he had been watching his old
teammates Thursday night. They gave away a game in the ninth inning
Wednesday, and then Thursday night, they failed to score in the
first eight innings, even though the Kansas City Royals' Dan
Reichert issued nine walks.
</P>
<P>
   On the verge of a disheartening 1-0 loss, the Yankees exploded
for seven runs in the top of the ninth and went on to a 7-3
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Denny Neagle pitched eight strong innings, improving his record
to 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees (79-58) have a sturdy six-game lead in the American
League East as they prepare to play the Red Sox four games in four
days _ a three-game weekend series in Boston, and then a makeup for
an early-season rainout at Yankee Stadium on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens will pitch against Boston's Tomo Ohka Friday in
Clemens' first Fenway Park outing since his disastrous playoff
start last fall; Clemens lasted only two innings in Game 3 of the
American League Championship Series, allowing five runs.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly half of the 110 pitches thrown by Reichert were strikes,
and he tied a club record with all the walks, but incredibly, he
was in a position to win after the Royals scored a run in the
eighth. Ricky Bottalico came on to pitch the ninth inning for
Kansas City and walked Jose Canseco before Scott Brosius singled;
Chuck Knoblauch, pinch-running for Canseco, advanced to second.
</P>
<P>
   Kris Wilson replaced Bottalico, and the pinch-hitter Luis
Polonia bunted toward third. Wilson came off the mound, fielded the
ball and threw toward third, attempting to get the force play _ and
missed his target by several feet, the ball bounding down the line.
Knoblauch scored the tying run, Brosius reached third and Polonia
went to second. The Royals' infield moved in, and Jose Vizcaino
pulled a single through the right side, driving in the go-ahead
run. The Yankees added five more runs, the last on a two-run homer
by David Justice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
