<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-WHITE-SOX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROGERS ROLLS, THEN IS ROCKED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Kenny Rogers was perfect for 4 1/3 innings Thursday
night, conjuring up images of that brilliant night in 1994 when he
retired 27 consecutive hitters against the California Angels. But
when Carlos Lee singled with one out in the fifth, that vision went
poof in the warm humid night.
</P>
<P>
   It was replaced by another vision, this one more real and
relevant to what has been happening to Rogers lately. Rogers'
terrific pitching performance turned to disaster faster than Scott
Sheldon can switch positions in the middle of an inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago White Sox scored five runs off Rogers and Jeff
Zimmerman in the sixth inning to erase the Rangers' 5-1 lead and
Chicago went on to a 10-6 victory at Comiskey Park on Thursday
night. The victory gave the White Sox a split of the four-game
series and denied the Rangers a chance to win their first series of
any length since July 24-26, when they took two of three from the
Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were able to contain the rampaging White Sox for the
first two nights with the pitching of Ryan Glynn and Doug Davis.
They weren't so lucky with Rick Helling on Wednesday and Rogers on
Thursday, their two best pitchers who have hit a slump heading down
the home stretch.
</P>
<P>
   They may be tired. They may have lost that adrenaline edge that
can sustain tired players on teams with a chance to win. They may
be making bad pitches, which is their basic theory. But they are
not winning.
</P>
<P>
   Helling is 0-3 with a 9.12 earned-run average in his past five
starts. Rogers, even though Zimmerman got the loss last night, is
0-4 with a 6.00 ERA in his past six starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt fine; I wasn't tired,'' Rogers said. ``I just made a
couple of bad pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Said manager Johnny Oates, ``He may have run out of gas after
throwing 70 pitches, but my personal opinion is fatigue wasn't any
part of what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers retired the first 13 hitters he faced before Lee lined a
single to center in the fifth. Paul Konerko's single moved him to
third and he scored on Herbert Perry's sacrifice fly. Rogers got
out of that inning, but he got into immediate trouble in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny looked like he was cruising through the first 13
batters,'' Oates said. ``Give Carlos credit. That pitch was just
off his shoetops. We got out of that, but things started unraveling
in the sixth.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers walked Charles Johnson leading off the inning and, after
getting ahead with two strikes, hit Ray Durham. Those were the two
batters that irritated Rogers and Oates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walk the first guy of an inning and hit Durham, I basically
created that inning by not getting guys out I should have,'' Rogers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Graffanino followed with a single into the left-center gap
to score one run, and Frank Thomas then lined a two-run double into
the same general direction, making it a 5-4 game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitch to Thomas wasn't that bad, down and in,'' Rogers
said. ``But he's good hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates brought in Zimmerman to stop the bleeding, but Magglio
Ordonez jumped on a first-pitch slider _ also down and in _ and hit
it deep over the left-field fence to make it a 6-5 game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitch was where I wanted it,'' Zimmerman said. ``Ordonez
usually looks first pitch away, and I wanted it on the inner third
of the plate. But they're a good hitting team. When they get hot,
they can really get going.''
</P>
<P>
   Streaks are part of baseball, both good and bad. For Rogers and
for Helling, right now it's bad.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
