<HEADER>
A5840 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-ESTATE-TAX-SFCHRON &LR;      09-08 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESTATE-TAX-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HOUSE FAILS TO OVERRIDE ESTATE TAX VETO  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House failed to override President Clinton's
veto of estate-tax repeal Thursday, with four Northern California
Democrats who originally voted for repeal backing away, one after a
telephone call from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Estate-tax repeal resonates in the Bay Area, where soaring house
prices and swollen stock portfolios threaten to subject many people
to the tax who consider themselves middle class.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats Zoe Lofgren of San Jose, Anna Eshoo of Palo Alto, Tom
Lantos of San Mateo and Sam Farr of Carmel all originally voted for
repeal but switched sides with 10 other Democrats to sustain the
veto.
</P>
<P>
   The 274-to-157 vote to override fell 14 short of the required
two-thirds majority, with 53 Democrats voting in favor, down three
from the original 56. Democrats also picked up most of their 11
members who were not present for the original vote.
</P>
<P>
   Lofgren spokesman Ron Eckstein said Clinton called the
congresswoman from New York Thursday to give ``the assurances she
needs to make sure the president will ... continue to work on
solving the problem of middle-class property owners and estate
owners who are in high-property-value areas that would be hurt by
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other Bay Area Democrats who originally voted for repeal _
Walnut Creek's Ellen Tauscher and Napa's Mike Thompson _ sided with
the override attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The original bill proved popular with many Democrats, but their
leaders urged members to hold party lines to support the
administration in a critical election year. Control of the House is
at stake, and Vice President Al Gore is focusing his White House
bid on an assault against GOP nominee George W. Bush's tax cut
plan, which includes estate-tax repeal.
</P>
<P>
   Praising Democrats for sustaining his veto, Clinton echoed
Gore's campaign language, saying the bill ``would take us back to
the days of deficits, high interest rates and fiscal
irresponsibility'' and would provide ``a huge tax break for the
most well-off Americans at the expense of working families.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign quickly responded: ``Gov. Bush believes it's
wrong to make people who have already paid taxes pay them again
when they die. When he is president, there will be no veto to
override because he will sign the abolition of the death tax into
law.''
</P>
<P>
   The estate tax _ which Republicans deride as the ``death tax'' _
starts with a 37 percent rate on inheritances worth more than
$675,000, rising to 55 percent on estates over $3 million. With
various surcharges and generation-skipping taxes, the rate can
reach as high as 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP bill would have gradually phased out the tax over 10
years, with most of the cut occurring at the end of the period. It
would have reduced government revenue by $105 billion over the next
10 years, and $50 billion a year when fully phased in.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would have signed a Democratic alternative that
would have immediately cut estate tax rates by 20 percent and
increased the exemption for farms and small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Eshoo said she switched sides because the GOP bill was never
altered to meet Democratic objections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very much for giving people a sensible and needed tax
break for their properties, especially as a Californian and
especially as someone who helped bring about this economic
prosperity,'' Eshoo said.
</P>
<P>
   But she said the GOP bill would have ``blown a hole'' in the
budget and that she was pushing a new compromise measure that she
said could be wrapped up in a year-end budget bill.
</P>
<P>
   But GOP leaders said they plan to make the estate tax veto a
campaign issue, waiting until the next congress (when they hope
Bush will be president) to push again for full repeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously this will be part of the campaign,'' said GOP whip
Tom DeLay, R-Texas. ``We'll let the American people decide by their
own votes. If the American people really want this tax relief,
we'll have a Republican Congress with a Republican president who
will sign it.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay accused Democrats of wanting to spend the surplus. ``The
president doesn't want tax relief,'' DeLay said. ``He wants to keep
this money in Washington so he can spend it, and Gore is the same
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Farr, who had originally voted for repeal, angrily accused
Republicans of being ``more interested in a political message.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were really interested in pure tax reform and helping
the people you're talking about, you would have gone down and
worked out with the president something he would sign,'' Farr said.
``But this is just total repeal, and you knew that he would veto
that, and that is mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans insisted that the Democratic alternative was a sham.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately this targeted approach touted by President
Clinton and Vice President Gore will target American families right
out of relief,'' said sponsor Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said the existing exemption for family farms and small
businesses _ which Democrats would have increased _ is so complex
that only 3 percent of businesses and farms qualify. Of those that
do, Dunn said, two thirds are then challenged by the Internal
Revenue Service and ``are forced to pay thousands of dollars in
attorneys' fees to defend themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one way to rid the code of this immoral, unfair
and economically unsound tax, and that's to eliminate it,'' Dunn
said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats sought to make the veto a campaign issue of their own.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., and Senate Minority
leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., held a press conference denouncing the
attempt to override the veto and touting Gore's economic agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always been tremendous unity in this party between the
presidential campaign and the congressional campaigns,'' Gephardt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other California Democrats joining the override attempt included
Santa Barbara's Lois Capps, Modesto's Gary Condit, and Visalia's
Cal Dooley. Only one Republican, Doug Bereuter, R-Neb., voted to
sustain the veto.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have made nine attempts to override Clinton vetoes,
but only two _ on the line-item veto and securities litigation _
prevailed by passing both the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   House leaders will make another attempt next week to override a
Clinton veto, this one on the so-called ``marriage penalty.''
Republicans are picking out a few of their most popular tax bills
to either gain legislative victories or draw a contrast with the
White House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 0035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
