<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-CUNNINGHAM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS ISSUE CALL TO ARM TO RANDALL CUNNINGHAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Head coach Dave Campo said ``this'' is precisely
why the Cowboys signed two-time MVP quarterback Randall Cunningham
in the off-season to back up Troy Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, 37, however, didn't have ``this'' in mind when he
chose the Cowboys over a number of free-agent suitors.
</P>
<P>
   He could have stayed in Minnesota or gone to Detroit if he
wanted the burden of carrying the hopes of a team two games into
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, here Cunningham is, set to start for an injured Aikman on
Sunday against the Arizona Cardinals in what is considered a
crucial game for the Cowboys after last week's season-opening
meltdown against the Philadelphia Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was prepared as any backup to do whatever,'' Cunningham
said. ``But I wasn't thinking this. My friends were telling me, `We
thought maybe you could get a couple of reps every once in a while,
maybe some mop-up reps. We didn't think you get in there that
quick.' ''
</P>
<P>
   If Cunningham and the Cowboys have their way, his stay in the
lineup will be brief. Although no timetable has been set for
Aikman's return from the concussion he suffered Sunday, he could be
back for next Monday's game against the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   And that will be the plan no matter how well Cunningham plays in
Aikman's stead.
</P>
<P>
   Campo snapped at any queries about Cunningham's possibly winning
the Cowboys' starting job with a brilliant performance. Two years
ago, Cunningham led the Vikings to a 15-1 record and won the league
MVP award after subbing for an injured Brad Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a question,'' Campo said. ``Troy is our
quarterback. This particular week, Randall is our quarterback. We
will go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham said accepting a lesser role would have been tough on
him years ago, particulary during his days in Philadelphia from
1985-95.
</P>
<P>
   He credits his new outlook to maturity and a spiritual rebirth,
which dates to 1996 when he sat out of football for a year after
retiring from the Eagles. Cunningham said he signed with Minnesota
in 1997 looking to fit in any way he could. He said the situation
with the Cowboys is the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been frustrating back in my egotistical days,''
Cunningham said. ``I'm humbled now. I know my role. I understand
it. I'm approaching it just like Minnesota when Brad was the
starter. Troy has done a lot in Dallas with three Super Bowls. I
pray for Troy to be healthy and continued greatness. The emphasis
for me is to be a role player and use my strengths to help this
team out.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, the Cowboys are hoping Cunningham can recapture
some of the greatness he showed in 1998 when he passed for 3,704
yards and 34 touchdowns. Campo said visions of backup quarterback
grandeur is what prompted the Cowboys to sign Cunningham to a
three-year contract in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a plan involved when we signed Randall, now we'll
get to see what happens,'' Campo said. ``We think he can win games
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Running back Emmitt Smith _ pointing to Jason Garrett, Rodney
Peete, Steve Beuerlein and Bernie Kosar _ said the Cowboys have
never had a problem rallying around a backup quarterback. He said
Cunningham's illustrious resume and the vivid memories of the
``whippings'' he put on the Cowboys during his stops in
Philadelphia and Minnesota simply give the Cowboys more reasons to
believe they can get back on track against the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Conveniently overlooked in the Cunningham equation was his
disappointing 1999 campaign, when he led the Vikings to a 2-4 start
and was benched. Campo discounts any suggestions that the 15-year
veteran has diminished skills. In fact, Campo says the Cowboys plan
to tweak the offense to take advantage of Cunningham's mobility.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not any different physically than he was two years ago,''
Campo said. ``And talent-wise he is very good at this point. You
have to be aware of his ability to scramble. He can run with ball.
He can throw the ball. You could see anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham promises a better performance against the Cardinals
than he showed against the Eagles on Sunday when he was plagued by
communication failure and rust.
</P>
<P>
   It was his first real game action since October. Cunningham
didn't get off the bench in the final 10 games of last season, and
he played sparingly in the 2000 preseason because of bursitis in
his throwing shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been cramming a lot,'' Cunningham said. ``I know the
plays, the protections, the blitz protections. Playing \RSunday\S
helped me get back in the flow after not playing as much as I
wanted last year. I'm anxious to play and do well.''
</P>
<P>
   And then go back to the bench. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
