<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
EMMITT SMITH EXPECTED TO PLAY SUNDAY DESPITE BRUISED RIGHT HAND
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Emmitt Smith gave the already gun-shy Cowboys a
scare Thursday when he was forced to leave practice with a bruised
right hand.
</P>
<P>
   Results of the X-rays on the running back's hand were negative.
Smith, 31, is expected to play Sunday night at Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very encouraging,'' said owner Jerry Jones, who has had
to deliver injury statements every day but one this week on three
of his top players: Joey Galloway (season-ending knee surgery),
Troy Aikman (concussion/out this week) and now Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through Thursday's practice, Smith took a helmet to the
hand during a nontackling, short-yardage drill. He returned 45
minutes later with his hand iced and covered by a beehive-size
wrap.
</P>
<P>
   Smith broke the same hand last season Oct. 8 against Minnesota.
Surgery the next day, using a plate and screws, repaired the
fracture, located just behind the big knuckle of the ring finger.
</P>
<P>
   Trainers are eager to compare the October 1999 X-rays with
Thursday's X-rays ``just to be real cautious,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's return from his broken hand in 1999 _ he sat out one
game _ coincidentally enough, came at Arizona in a 13-9 loss, with
Jason Garrett subbing for the injured Aikman at quarterback. That
day, Smith rushed for 127 yards on 29 carries while wearing a
protective cast on his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has carried the ball in his left hand throughout his
career. His right hand guides him.
</P>
<P>
   In light of all that has happened this week, Jones described the
feeling when Smith was at a local hospital Thursday in one word:
``Numb.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Smith returned, Jones _ tipped off to the positive
news only five minutes earlier _ ran across the practice field to
greet his running back.
\Nsubheds:Concern for the Valley That the Cowboys do not yet have
an agreement to relocate training camp to Pepsi Park in the
Sharyland Plantation development apparently is not a good sign for
the Rio Grande Valley group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the status,'' Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said
Thursday. ``But I am concerned that for the length of time that
we've been dealing with the Valley \Rnearly two years\S and haven't
gotten something consummated ... well, that should concern
everybody as to whether we can get something done.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said that returning to Midwestern State University in
Wichita Falls for a fourth year is still a possibility.
\Nsubheds:Cardinals of habit After Sunday's loss against
Philadelphia, the Cowboys probably can expect to encounter
opponents' blitz packages throughout the season. Tight end Jackie
Harris said, however, that although the Cowboys will be ready for
the attack he doesn't expect Arizona to blitz more than usual,
which historically hasn't been much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams still have their own personality,'' said Harris, an NFL
veteran of 144 games.
</P>
<P>
   Harris added: ``This week, the Cardinals \Rdefensively\S have
something extra for them to prepare for: Randall Cunningham. He's a
guy who can move around.''
\Nsubheds:Goodrich thinking 'Skins Rookie cornerback Dwayne
Goodrich hopes to makes his NFL debut a week from Monday night at
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Goodrich returned to practice this week after nursing a strained
hamstring for a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels tight,'' the Cowboys' top draft pick said. ``But I'm
really excited to be back practicing. I woke up feeling good about
myself again.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
