<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME-GROWN YOUNGSTERS ARE STARS' PLAN FOR FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock will not arrive in Vail, Colo., Saturday for the
opening of Stars training camp in a particularly pleasant frame of
mind.
</P>
<P>
   It's not his team he's irritated with; that may or may not come
later. It's ingrates like you and me.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think, Hitch said this week in so many words, we'd have
learned to put a little trust in him and general manager Bob Gainey
by now.
</P>
<P>
   If you're like me, you've probably spent the days since late
June, after the Stars were beaten by the New Jersey Devils in six
games in the Stanley Cup Finals, awaiting the team's next Ed
Belfour-Brett Hull-type move.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Stars were back in the finals, but barely. If not for
Belfour's spectacular performance in the conference championship
series, the Stars would never have gotten past Colorado. And though
they fought back, the Stars were dominated by New Jersey in the
finals.
</P>
<P>
   So what difference-maker would Gainey and Hitchcock bring in
this off-season? Would they strike big and trade for disgruntled
but flashy Ottawa star Alexei Yashin? Take a chance on a big stick
like Eric Lindros? Sign malevolent but talented free-agent forward
Claude Lemieux?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: None of the above.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did they go out and bring in a veteran defenseman to anchor
their third defensive pair, as they have in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, the Stars instead added free-agent center Shaun Van
Allen and forward Ted Donato, solid players but not the kind that
grab splashy headlines.
</P>
<P>
   That's caused at least some minor grumbling among the media and
fans, who had hoped for a little more flash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of \Rticked\S off about that,'' the almost always
affable Hitchcock admitted. ``Anybody who knows our organization
knows what we're about and that we've had a strong belief in
development from within. We've nurtured players along here at a
very deliberate time frame, players like \RBrad\S Lukowich,
\RRichard\S Jackman, \RMarty\S Turco, guys who have been players in
our organization for three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have this opportunity to put them into our lineup and
bring them along. We want to make the transition from old team to
younger team without missing a beat. Last year was Year 1, this is
Year 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Not missing a beat is fine. Missing the boat is what some of us
worrywarts are concerned about.
</P>
<P>
   The inexorable closing of the ``window of opportunity'' we've
talked about so often in relation to the Cowboys can be applied to
the Stars now as well.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans such as Craig Ludwig, Brian Skrudland and Guy
Carbonneau, key players in the Stars' Stanley Cup march two years
ago, are already gone. Belfour will turn 36 in April and Hull is
already there. Joe Nieuwendyk turns 34 Sunday and Mike Keane joins
him in May. Even forever-kid Mike Modano hit the dreaded 3-0 mark
in June.
</P>
<P>
   Shouldn't Gainey and Hitchcock be trying to squeeze one more Cup
out of this group while they're all still viable players?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our core is set up long-term,'' Hitchcock countered. ``We want
to be a franchise that wins long-term. That's our goal. we don't
want to win just one Stanley Cup. We want to be good every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We slid four young players in last year and we want to slide
three or four in this year. We'll be a younger team with bigger
potential. I think that's smart management.''
</P>
<P>
   To some of us, it smacks of what the Rangers tried to do this
summer with disastrous results. Then again, there should be no
surprise that the management philosophy of the two organizations
might be similar, because both are owned by Tom Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   What the Stars are hoping to avoid is the same trapdoor that the
Detroit Red Wings have fallen through. Remember them? Two years ago
they were the team everybody wanted to emulate. Now they're just
old and basically forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils, remember, won the Cup in June with a plethora of
young, basically unknown but very talented players, like Donato,
for example, who the Stars hope can join Nieuwendyk and
Langenbrunner on the second line. Van Allen will attempt to fill
Carbonneau's big skates on the checking line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have players _ \RGrant\S Marshall, Langenbrunner,
\RRichard\S Matvichuk, \RDarryl\S Sydor, _ who are really eager for
a bigger bite of our team,'' Hitchcock said. ``If we just keep
bringing in stop-gap people, we don't allow ourselves to develop
chemistry from within. We don't want to make that mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last season when we had to play players who were younger, like
Jon Sim, he responded, so it's his turn to grab a full share here
and see how he does. People like \RRoman\S Lyashenko and
\RBrenden\S Morrow aren't going to get worse, they're going to get
better. They're good players and we need to give them that
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you continue to shut out younger players, you crash and
burn in a big way.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens this week in Vail is more about ice time than it is
playing spots. Hitchcock has a pretty good idea ``who's'' going to
play. It's how much that has yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
   The cast is set and the starring roles are filled by familiar
faces. Modano, Hatcher, Zubov, Hull, Lehtinen, Nieuwendyk,
Matvichuk, Sydor, Belfour. You know them well.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who had hoped for another major addition to the cast
will just have to trust that Gainey and Hitchcock know what they're
doing.
</P>
<P>
   You have to admit, their track record looks pretty good.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 0039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
