<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-SIMMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRIS SIMMS WANTS TO REGULAR GUY AS HE AIMS FOR PERFECTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A television set in the corner of the room spits
out an endless stream of sports highlights, capturing the undivided
attention of Texas quarterback Chris Simms.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a familiar face fills the screen. Before the smiling
blond in the burnt orange jersey utters a sound, Simms changes
channels. It is an exercise Simms began long before most of his
interviews involved questions about whether he or Major Applewhite
should start Saturday for the sixth-ranked Longhorns in their
season opener against Louisiana-Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   The sophomore counts ESPN's ``SportsCenter'' among life's basic
pleasures. But he plans to go a lifetime without seeing his own
``SportsCenter'' moment. Simms hates watching himself in action, as
a pinpoint passer or a public speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real critical of myself,'' Simms said. ``I never feel like
I do anything good enough to make myself happy.''
</P>
<P>
   That underlying insecurity explains why the 6-foot-5, 222-pound
son of a former NFL quarterback has experienced recurring
nightmares about underthrowing open receivers throughout fall camp.
It justifies Simms' compelling need to finish first in wind sprints
during Longhorns practices. It offers insight into why Simms has
summoned cornerback Roderick Babers, his close friend and
suitemate, for midnight games of catch in the courtyard outside
their dormitory.
</P>
<P>
   As much as he relishes being the son of Phil Simms, former Super
Bowl most valuable player, Chris acknowledges that his desire to
make his own name on his own terms has shaped his perfectionist
personality and fueled a relentless drive that few outsiders
appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely,'' Simms said. ``I've gone through that a lot in my
life. I don't know if people really thought I was a very good
athlete until high school. If they did, it was only because my dad
was who he was. I always took that very personally. I enjoy proving
people wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   That led to Simms' cocoon mindset, one he said has served him
well in his ongoing battle with Applewhite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The less praise I hear, the better I like it,'' Simms said.
``As long as they say something good about someone else, I'll go
out the next day and work hard so I can beat him, whatever it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Babers, like Simms, said the biggest misconception about the
quarterback dubbed ``Golden Boy'' is that he was born to play
football because his father, Phil, won two Super Bowls in 15
seasons with the New York Giants. Nick Gallo, a former high school
teammate who plays for Rutgers, said Simms has the ``strongest work
ethic'' of any player he has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how much natural ability he really has,'' Babers
said. ``He's the guy in front, all the time, when we work out. He
goes running on his own. You wouldn't think Chris Simms would want
to do that. But he's willing to pay the price to be the best.
That's why we look up to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most fellow members of Texas' 1999 signing class, Babers
admitted he had concerns after watching Simms unload his personal
belongings from a white limousine (provided by an Austin hotel,
over Simms' objections) during his first day on campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking, `Here's a guy from a family that's pretty well
off. He's going to come down here and be a stuck-up kid. He's going
to think he's all-world,' '' Babers said. ``But he completely threw
me for a loop when I met him. He's down-to-earth. He believes in
hard work. His family taught him a lot of great, real-world values.
It's unusual to see someone from his background with those
values.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unusual'' could serve as a blanket description of the
left-hander from Franklin Lakes, N.J., who has taken a majority of
the snaps with Texas' first-team offense during fall drills and is
expected to become a focal point of the Longhorns' attack as the
season progresses.
</P>
<P>
   Simms was tough enough, as a high school freshman, to chew out
team trainers when he thought they asked too many questions while
checking for a possible concussion. He was sensitive enough, three
years later, to write a poem to his high school sweetheart for a
class assignment even though he knew it meant taking heat from his
buddies. Danielle Puleo, Simms' girlfriend for the past four years
and a student at the New York School of Interior Design, still has
the poem.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to music, movies and clothes, Simms' taste runs
toward yesteryear. His favorite band is Led Zeppelin, a group that
reached its zenith of popularity before Christopher David Simms,
20, was born on Aug. 29, 1980. Simms' favorite film is ``The
Godfather,'' an epic from the 1970s. His wardrobe includes
bell-bottoms and necklaces that would have been trendy at a Vietnam
War protest rally.
</P>
<P>
   Witty and chatty, Simms is quick to converse and joke with
strangers. At the dining hall, he loads up on candy and ice cream.
Regardless of the endeavor, Simms is more likely to set his own
agenda than follow the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   That happened during recruiting when both parents urged him to
attend Tennessee because of an imminent job opening at quarterback.
Instead, Simms went with his instincts and signed with Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other guys admire him for that,'' defensive end Cory
Redding said. ``I'll be glad to tell my kids someday that I played
with Chris Simms. He's a special guy. Everything around him that
you think would affect him in a negative way, Chris handles it in
the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes the ongoing debate about whether Simms, the
nation's top-ranked quarterback signee in 1999, or Applewhite,
holder of 37 school records, should be the Longhorns' starter. For
Simms, the situation brings back vivid and painful memories of a
protracted quarterback battle in 1991 that led to Jeff Hostetler
supplanting his father as the Giants' starter after New York won
Super Bowl XXV.
</P>
<P>
   As the controversy raged, an 11-year-old Chris Simms stared up
at a tackler in a youth-league football game who unleashed a series
of obscene comments about the Giants and his father before
shouting, ``Hostetler rules!'' Simms recalled crying the day his
father announced he'd been benched.
</P>
<P>
   Simms has shared those sentiments with Applewhite. Although he
favors a one-quarterback system because it makes for ``less turmoil
within the team,'' Simms said he's willing to abide by coach Mack
Brown's decision to leave the situation open-ended, at least for
the time being. And he will harbor no ill feelings toward
Applewhite, no matter the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly wouldn't want to be at home in 20 years thinking,
`Oh, I hated college because of Major Applewhite,' '' Simms said.
``That would be stupid. We get along. I think we're both mature
enough to realize that it's all on the field. And outside of that,
we have fun and joke around.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as long as the jokes don't hit ``too'' close to home. Simms
laughed this week when told that Applewhite expressed gratitude
that Simms had hidden his knee brace only ``a couple of times''
during fall drills. Applewhite's humor fell flatter last November,
shortly after Simms made his lone career start in a 20-16 loss to
Texas A&AMP;M. Stricken with food poisoning, Applewhite sat out the
first three quarters and was unable to rally the Longhorns after
replacing Simms in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few days after the A&AMP;M game, he joked, `OK, don't poison my
food this week,' '' Simms said. ``He made me mad. Actually, I was
like, `Don't ever say that again.' I really turned on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Simms is positioned to be the quarterback Texas coaches
turn to for the majority of playing time in a season filled with
national championship hopes. To meet those expectations, he must
produce some ``SportsCenter'' highlights.
</P>
<P>
   If Simms has his way, he will wear out his remote control
changing channels to avoid seeing them.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
