<SLUG> BC-FBC-TWO-AT-QBS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN TWO DEEP BE TOO DEEP AT QUARTERBACK?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Texas Longhorns are ranked in the top 10 and one of a
handful of teams considered as legitimate national championship
contenders. But around college football, there is one question
above all when it comes to coach Mack Brown's team:
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's the quarterback?''
</P>
<P>
   Brown will answer that question _ at least for the season opener
against Louisiana-Lafayette _ Saturday when he selects either Major
Applewhite or Chris Simms to take the first offensive snap. But the
Applewhite-Simms debate figures to be a seasonlong sideshow. Brown
has been down this road before. He rotated two quarterbacks on a
1997 North Carolina team that went 11-1.
</P>
<P>
   And the Longhorns are not alone in their two-quarterback
quandary. (It's not a controversy _ yet.)
</P>
<P>
   More and more coaches, it seems, are struggling choosing between
two quarterbacks of equal ability and talent. All coaches must make
their decision based on their team's needs, but some coaches
believe the quarterback is the team leader and should never share
the role.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama coach Mike DuBose is not one of those coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good part of having two quarterbacks is you've got depth
in case of injury or off days,'' DuBose said. ``The negative aspect
is that it allows people outside the program to second-guess and
wonder if you're making the right choice or decision.''
</P>
<P>
   DuBose, who alternated Andrew Zow and Tyler Watts in the final
two games last season, decided against sticking with a gimmick that
produced 68 points against Florida and Michigan. Before the Crimson
Tide's opener against UCLA on Saturday, DuBose said Zow, a junior,
would start while Watts, a sophomore, would play.
</P>
<P>
   Zow completed eight of 23 passes for 92 yards and Watts was
3-of-7 for 27 yards. Alabama's 35-24 upset loss was more a result
of sloppy tackling than poor quarterback play. However, DuBose's
handling of his quarterbacks will add to the heat provided by an
unexpected loss. 'Bama fans, who live to analyze and critique their
team, no doubt will find a way to ignite a quarterback controversy
with the fuel of the UCLA loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to do what's best for this football team, and
nothing else,'' DuBose said.
</P>
<P>
   Some coaches, like Arkansas' Houston Nutt, always choose a No.
1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a big guy on alternating quarterbacks,'' Nutt said.
``I want one guy stepping in the huddle with 10 sets of eyes
looking at him. And all those eyes hear one voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida coach Steve Spurrier, whose team upset Florida State in
1997 by alternating quarterbacks each snap, doesn't see playing two
quarterbacks as a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get in a situation where two quarterbacks are about
equal, then you should play both of them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, though, won the national championship in 1996 with
Danny Wuerffel, the clear-cut, no-debate starter, at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Utah coach Ron McBride is splitting time between seniors Darnell
Arceneaux and T.D. Croshaw, even though McBride said it goes
against his training. He has never used a two-quarterback system in
10 seasons as the Utes' coach. One of his quarterbacks is resigned
to sharing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand \Rthe two-quarterback system\S, but I'm not a fan
of it,'' Croshaw said. ``I do think we can hurt teams because of
our different styles. And if one of us happens to be struggling,
the other can come in and pick up the team.''
</P>
<P>
   The last team to win a national championship playing two
quarterbacks was Nebraska in 1970 (Jerry Tagge and Van Brownson).
Last year, Arizona played two quarterbacks (Keith Smith and Ortege
Jenkins) but finished 6-6 after being ranked No. 4 in the
preseason.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Auburn was ranked No. 1 and couldn't decide between
three quarterbacks. All three played at Tennessee _ and the Tigers
lost.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State, using Stanley Jackson as a starter and Joe Germaine
as a backup, won 10 of its first 11 games in 1997. In the
regular-season finale against Michigan, Buckeyes coach John Cooper
switched. He started Germaine, who struggled and brought in
Jackson, who failed in relief. Final score: Wolverines 20, Buckeyes
14.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to worry about the intangibles, the chemistry, the
leadership, the morale of the football team,'' Cooper said. ``A
coach has to do what's best for the football team and not worry
about what anybody else thinks. The biggest downside is if you play
two and you lose. The whole secret to making it work is winning.''
</P>
<P>
   There it is. Simple.
</P>
<P>
   For Texas _ or any other team _ that attempts to utilize two
quarterbacks, contentment of the players and the fans comes with
winning. Losses, not the coaches or the quarterbacks, create
controversy. \Ntagtop:Wendell Barnhouse, (817) 390-7760
\Ntagbottom:wbhoops\Nstar-telegram.com
\Nsubheds:Double QB dose
</P>
<P>
   A look at some of the Division I-A teams that have two
quarterbacks who are both in position to be starters. Team
Quarterbacks Texas Major Applewhite, Chris Simms Alabama Andrew
Zow, Tyler Watts Tennessee A.J. Suggs, Joey Matthews Colorado Bobby
Pesavento, Zac Colvin Utah Darnell Arceneaux, T.D. Croshaw Florida
Jesse Palmer, Brock Berlin LSU Josh Booty, Rohan Davey Oregon Joey
Harrington, A.J. Feeley Georgia Tech George Godsey, Andy Hall
Maryland Calvin McCall, Shaun Hill Pittsburgh John Turman, David
Priestley Central Michigan Pete Shepherd, Derrick Vickers Temple
Devin Scott, Mike Frost nn
</P>
</TEXT>
