<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-BELFOUR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELFOUR SEEMS READY TO PROVE THAT HE CAN BE `BETTER' AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Eddie Belfour rolled into town Tuesday so, of
course, Wednesday had to be spent taking care of the errands that
accumulate after a summer away.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars goalie's first stop was Cole's machine shop in Denison
to work on his skate-sharpening jig.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was up there, and one of his staff on the computer had on
his screen saver `Eddie's better,' '' Belfour said. ``I started
laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   He hadn't thought about those words since the Reunion Arena
crowd chanted them during Game 7 of the Western Conference Finals
last May. The crowd's serenade was its answer to Colorado Avalanche
goalie Patrick Roy's assertion that he was the better goalie. They
thought the Stars' victory, led by Belfour, proved otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Stars leaving this afternoon for Vail, Colo., where
training camp commences Saturday, the better question is:
</P>
<P>
   Can Eddie be better this season?
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, for one, are hoping he doesn't have to be all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want him to be that good,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
clarified. ``We just don't want to have to ``need'' him to be that
good for us to get points.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Stars were predictable for good portions of last
season. When Belfour was good, they were good. When Belfour wasn't,
they weren't.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars returned to the Stanley Cup Finals, which tells you a
little something about Belfour's season.
</P>
<P>
   He finished with a 2.10 goals-against average in 62
regular-season games. He proved equally stifling in the postseason,
allowing less than two goals a game. He almost single-handedly
defeated Colorado in the Western Conference Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he isn't satisfied. He wants more this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm motivated to be back and definitely looking forward to
another great year,'' Belfour said. ``Any time you go that far in
the playoffs and fall short, it definitely makes you want to come
back and be stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hitchcock: ``I think he has some specific goals. He's very
determined. He really wants to have a heck of a year. He wants to
go back to the top again. Where he's at, he looks the same to me as
he did halfway through last year.''
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of last season, Belfour had established himself as
arguably the best goalie in the NHL. His stellar play in the
playoffs sealed the distinction in most people's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour, well, he simply thought he had done what he had been
doing all along.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that nobody in the media or awards-voting circles
noticed simply served as motivation for him. He liked the fact that
few gave him a lot of credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, any time for me someone said I couldn't do
something or put me down, I love to try to prove them wrong,''
Belfour said. ``I know what I can do inside. I know what I am
capable of doing. This team gives me the opportunity to show what I
can do.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 0045EDT &QL; 
