<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DON'T FLINCH, TAKE IT FOR THE TEAM  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This baseball thing is getting exciting, with
the Giants and A's heading for a World Series showdown, assuming
both teams manage to clear a few minor hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the time of year when writers start campaigning for
their personal MVP candidates. I'm not a sportswriter (don't be
fooled by these nachos and Tums), but I'd like to put in a good
word for my man.
</P>
<P>
   Vote for Fernando Vina for National League MVP. Even if the
trophy has to be presented posthumously.
</P>
<P>
   Vina plays second base for the St. Louis Cardinals. He leads the
major leagues in being hit by pitched balls. Twenty-five.
</P>
<P>
   (Fernando has a long way to go to reach the major league record
of 50, set by Ron Hunt in 1971. But Hunt was different. If you get
hit 50 times in one season, you are not a ballplayer, you are a
carnival act.)
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Vina is the Baron of Bruise, the Sultan of Self
Sacrifice, the Human Pinata.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the pitch is up and in,'' a Cardinals' official explained
to me, ``Fernando doesn't flinch.''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with the world today is that there is too much
flinching.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Vina: Role model for us all.
</P>
<P>
   NOT THAT we're a nation of gutsy gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   I see a lot of Ford Explorers still equipped with their original
Fire-and-brimstone tires. These folks aren't afraid to play Decatur
Roulette.
</P>
<P>
   Replacement tires are hard to find, as name brands are selling
out fast.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Kerwin's wife went to replace her 'Stones before they
shredded and injured innocently &LR; -bystander squirrels and snakes.
</P>
<P>
   She rode home on four new Hankooks, made by a Korean firm.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, somebody is going to make a million bucks selling
this cheapie anti-car-theft item: The Firestone stencil.
</P>
<P>
   TINY WHINES: Just because a gripe is little doesn't mean it's
not valid. If you've got a mini-gripe, send it here so I can resin
up the bow of my teensy violin.
</P>
<P>
   Novato Steve is irked at the number of drivers he sees paying
their Golden Gate Bridge toll at the far left booth, then veering
across eight lanes of heavy traffic to take the 19th St. exit. You
folks better have a damn good excuse.
</P>
<P>
   John Eddy was e-nauseated when he heard a guy in an elevator say
``one giga dollars'' instead of one billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   And Peter Fortune is annoyed at the new love affair between
sports- &QL; 
people and the word ``situation.'' As in, ``We have a third-and-10
situation.'' Instead of, ``It's third-and-10.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter says he heard Barry Bonds on a postgame interview
explaining why Giants pitchers are pitching so well: ``They're not
letting the situation dictate the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE TO worry about: In the Honolulu Advertiser, arson
investigator Henry S.T. Kim says mynah birds building nests pick up
lit cigarette butts and wind up torching trees and houses.
</P>
<P>
   Even more annoying, I say, is when a mynah picks up a burning
roach and sits around spouting hipster philosophy and pecking on
unguarded Ding-Dongs.
</P>
<P>
   LURCHING ABOUT town in the back seat of a taxi, Aaron Licursi
was captivated by a tip in a San Francisco Taxi Information
pamphlet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to exiting the taxicab, please note the taxicab number.
Lost personal property can be recovered more easily if the vehicle
number is identified.''
</P>
<P>
   Licursi says, ``I can't help but think it's generally easier to
check for personal property than it is to note the taxicab number.
If I had the presence of mind to note the number of every cab I
ride in, then I doubt I'd leave behind personal items.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, but if Tony Bennett had jotted down his taxi number, he
wouldn't have to be moaning constantly about his heart.
</P>
<P>
   BEST PANHANDLER lines o' the week:
</P>
<P>
   ``Help me get my yacht out of dry dock?''
</P>
<P>
   Another guy, extending tin cup to a sharp-suited Richard Kales:
``Well, here comes Charles Schwab. Let's negotiate!''
</P>
<P>
   Seen on Market St. near the S.F. Centre: A homeless guy sitting
on a blanket on the sidewalk, tattered clothes, chatting on a cell
phone.
</P>
<P>
   And famed S.F. artist/photographer Ted Stefanski was walking out
of the Mitchell Brothers O'Farrell Theater when a down-'n'-out gent
inquired, ``Can you spare some change for the homeless?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry,'' Ted said, ``I just spent it all on the topless.''
</P>
<P>
   REDUNDANCIES redux: ``Honeymoon for two'' (from a radio
commercial, heard by Ruben Medina). ... ``Illegally parked vehicles
will be towed away.'' Galen Myers asks, ``Have you ever seen a
towed car that stayed where it was?'' ... And a headline spotted by
Will Gronlund: ``Disappointing pair of hip-hop movies.''
</P>
<P>
   BACK TO SCHOOL: A first-day report from my spy at Oakland's
Fremont High:
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 2,100 students in a school built for 1,300, a lot
of the teachers are new, the entire administration staff is new,
textbooks were in short supply, the computers were down and the
bathrooms didn't work. And it was one of the best opening days in
the history of the school. Everyone went about their business as if
everything was perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   How to explain?
</P>
<P>
   ``The unpredictable human spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   SPELLCHECK sometimes is useless.
</P>
<P>
   David Jensen sends a newspaper ad for a book-signing, sponsored
by Black Spring Books of Vallejo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Event will be held at Vallejo Navel &AMP; Historical Museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to check out the lint exhibit.
</P>
