<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMERICA GIVES ANGELS BIG ASSIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Tim Belcher found the perfect place to pitch for a
38-year-old returning from an elbow injury _ Comerica Park.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher might start referring to the Detroit Tigers' new
ballpark as ``Comerica the Beautiful'' after the expansive outfield
helped him pitch the Anaheim Angels to a 6-4 victory Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Several well-hit fly balls stayed in the park and allowed
Belcher to stick around for six innings in his first start since
July 2. And he wasn't about to apologize for his fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good and when I didn't feel good, I was glad to be
pitching in Comerica Park,'' Belcher (3-2) said. ``I got away with
a couple mistakes. When you're pitching in a park like that, your
main objective is to throw strikes and exercise damage control.
That's what I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put my feet to the fire the first couple of innings and made
it work. . . . Kudos to the architect of Comerica.''
</P>
<P>
   It's 420 feet to straight-away center field. The power alley in
left is 398, but the deepest part of the ballpark is at the
flagpole just slightly left of center field _ it's 435 feet from
home plate.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Mike Scioscia, though, said Belcher deserves some
of the credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't make that many mistakes,'' Scioscia said. ``There
were a couple balls hit hard to left field. But he made good
pitches in key situations and went six strong innings for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of start we saw when he came back the first
time and pitched two good ballgames. If he can maintain that, he's
going to give us a boost down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   While Comerica might have kept the Tigers in the park against
Belcher, it didn't keep the Angels' big hitters in. Troy Glaus (No.
41), Tim Salmon (No. 33) and Scott Spiezio (No. 15) each homered.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Troy Glaus, Tim Salmon and Scott Spiezio get ahold of
`em, they're going to go out anywhere,'' Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus and Spiezio hit their homers off Tigers starter Dave
Mlicki (4-11), who like Belcher was returning from an extended
absence. Mlicki hadn't pitched since July 22 because of a chronic
sinus infection that required surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The win was the Angels' second in a row, the first time they've
won two straight since beating the New York Yankees back-to-back
nights on Aug. 11 and 12. Because Seattle also won, the Angels
remained six games out in the American League West. With Cleveland
losing, the Angels moved to 6 games of the wild-card lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bengie Molina tied a career high with four hits, including a
double and a triple. But probably Molina's biggest hit of the game
was a two-out, opposite-field single to right that drove in two and
gave the Angels a 5-1 lead in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't try to hit the pitch somewhere,'' Molina said when
asked if he was trying to go the other way. ``I try to hit `em hard
and hope they fall for a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers narrowed their deficit to 5-4 on Wendell Magee's solo
homer in the seventh off Angels reliever Mark Petkovsek, but Salmon
made it 6-4 in the top of the eighth with his homer.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia went to Shigetoshi Hasegawa in the eighth and kept him
in to pitch the ninth for his ninth save. Troy Percival, who made
14 pitches to get his 26th save Wednesday, was available if needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be careful with how we use Percy down the
stretch,'' Scioscia said. ``He's coming off the situation with his
elbow (inflamed nerve) and we want to keep his command where he
needs it to be effective.''
</P>
<P>
   After struggling in the previous series against the White Sox,
Hasegawa returned to form, giving up only one single while striking
out three in his two innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was just mechanics,'' Hasegawa said of his recent
struggles. ``Maybe I was thinking too much about being a closer (in
place of the injured Percival). Now I'm just thinking about my
mechanics and making my pitches. That's it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
