<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5860 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-USOPEN-NYT &LR;      09-08 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECOVERY INCOMPLETE, BUT MARTIN GAINS SEMIS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the first two sets of their quarterfinal match of
the U.S. Open Thursday night, Todd Martin forgot his legs were
attached to cinderblocks, his broken-down body hastily repaired by
intravenous fluids and massages for the last 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 30, was no longer the folk hero inspired by his own
resuscitation just two nights before in an epic five-set comeback
victory over Carlos Moya.
</P>
<P>
   He was just the long-faced, gray-haired man from the Midwest
Thursday night, not flashy, but triumphant when it counted,
offering but few fist-pumps reminiscent of his battle cries in
Wednesday's magical morning hours. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Martin wanted a quick sequel in his quarterfinal against
unseeded Thomas Johansson, and for 1 hour 16 minutes he had it,
racing to a two-set lead. Then his legs slowed, and Johansson, who
had obviously cribbed a page in his opponent's two-sets-down
comeback chapter, rocked aces that shook Martin and threatened to
send the match into murky five-set territory.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Martin knew what he had to do. ``I understood that I
didn't need to play great tonight,'' he said. ``I just needed to
play the points at the right time better than Thomas did.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth set, Martin threw off his first-game service
break, and he recovered from a 4-2 deficit to win the final set by
cracking a crosscourt forehand winner, returning to his second
straight U.S. Open semifinal with a 6-4, 6-4, 3-6, 7-5 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in the semis of the Open was the greatest thing since
sliced bread,'' said Martin, who lost to Andre Agassi in the finals
last year. ``Cutters are still sharp. This is awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   He will face 20-year-old Marat Safin Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Safin, seeded sixth, defeated 14th-seeded Nicolas Kiefer, 7-5,
4-6, 7-6 (5), 6-3. Safin played both brilliant and head-scratching
tennis on the sun-bleached Arthur Ashe Stadium Court on Day 11 of
the U.S. Open to advance to his first semifinals of a Grand Slam
event.
</P>
<P>
   While Safin arrives on the adrenaline of youth, Martin advances
one more round with the veteran experience and the crowd behind
him. ``You do need to draw on energy that is there,'' he said.
``And then from there, their energy inspires more energy from
you.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Martin was not the only medical miracle out on the court
Thursday night. Last year, one week before the U.S. Open, doctors
diagnosed a viral infection around the lining of Johansson's heart.
Johansson, 25, who is from Sweden, had a rocky year, losing in the
first round at 10 of 15 tournaments before the Open. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He looked lost early. A break in the fifth game was all Martin
needed to win the first set. In the second set, again in the fifth
game, Martin earned the only break he needed. When he ripped a
crosscourt winner with an unforgiving angle, Martin pumped his fist
triumphantly. He had few of those moments Thursday night. ``It's
not supposed to happen every day of the year,'' he said of his
unusual show of emotion.
</P>
<P>
   But it would emerge more later. In the third set, Johansson got
his break in the fourth game, and he won the set on his 15th ace,
committing just three unforced errors. ``He was too good; he really
picked his serve up,'' Martin said. ``Walking back and forth to
receive his serves really took me out of my rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, Martin was showing signs of fatigue and was not able to
run to every drop shot. Johansson broke him in the first game of
the fifth set, when Martin's backhand half-volley landed
halfheartedly into the net. Johansson finished a love serving game
with his 20th ace, to take a 4-2 lead. But Martin held onto his
serve and carried the momentum. He broke Johansson on a forehand
that clipped the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally made it up in my mind to make him see me a little
more, just putting that extra pressure on him changed the rhythm of
the match and also took some of his ball striking away,'' Martin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin capitalized on the ugly points, and suddenly, they were
back on serve, and Johansson was serving to reach a tiebreaker when
Martin spoke to himself. ``I said some things to myself before the
points. `Do this, so even if you don't get through this game, he
knows what you're doing and you plant the seed for the
tiebreaker.'''
</P>
<P>
   But he did not need to do that. Martin had two match points when
he blasted a forehand cross court and Johansson's backhand return
fell into the net.
</P>
<P>
   A tired Martin, wearing heating pads on both of his knees and in
a subdued mood, was in contrast to the more playful Safin.
</P>
<P>
   A booming 6-foot-4-inch Russian baseliner with a bronze tan,
Safin boasted about not smashing his racquet for five straight
matches now, since way back in the first round of the U.S. Open,
last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I forgot about this already. I'm a new man,'' Safin said
Thursday, his devilish grin suggesting otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   If he can figure out who he is _ a 20-year-old boy with a
hiccuped attention span of a bored A-student, or one of the top
men's players _ his career could take another sharp turn. On
Thursday, his personalities swiveled back and forth, along with his
concentration.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still young, and if he believes in himself, he can be No.
1, if he becomes more concentrated on the court,'' his new coach,
the most current of four this year, Alexander Volkov said.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this swing Thursday: Kiefer held a 5-2 lead and was
serving for the set at 5-3. But Safin broke him and won four
straight games to take a 1-0 lead in the match. ``I knew I was very
close to losing this set, so I was a hundred percent
concentrated,'' Safin said.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage plummeted in the next set, as Safin responded in
reverse to momentum. Kiefer took advantage. ``When he loses his
serve, he gets better,'' Volkov explained.
</P>
<P>
   Kiefer saved three match points in the final set, but Safin
finished off the match on his serve, blasting a second serve 131
mph for a service winner. Safin had 16 aces, 47 winners and 42
unforced errors. Afterwards, Kiefer said that Safin has the tools
to win this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his confidence is getting much bigger and bigger,''
Kiefer said. ``I expected a hard fight against him because I saw
him playing many matches now. I knew that he goes for every shot.
He has a great serve.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
