<SLUG> BC-FBC-SCNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC SUSPENDS COUSINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC defensive end John Cousins has been suspended
indefinitely for a violation of team rules. He has not practiced
this week and will not suit up for Saturday's game against
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The transfer from West Los Angeles College enrolled at USC last
spring. He was switched from linebacker to defensive end during
training camp. Cousins has played football despite being deaf in
one ear and impaired in the other. He did not play in USC's
season-opener against Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   __ Grootegoed to redshirt: Although it's not official, strong
safety Matt Grootegoed is almost certain to redshirt after tests
revealed he has mononucleosis. USC coach Paul Hackett was
optimistic Grootegoed could return to practice within three to four
weeks, but that would probably be too late to salvage the true
freshman's season, since he would need to get in shape again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the card we've been dealt and will have to deal with,''
Hackett said. ``I don't know how long it will take, but we will let
it go very slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   Grootegoed has been playing on special teams and been the No. 3
strong safety behind sophomore Troy Polamalu and junior DeShaun
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   __ Wide right: USC practiced in the Coliseum on Thursday and it
was a rough workout for kicker David Newbury. He missed all three
attempts at the end of practice, with one ball glancing off the
pole that supports the net behind the goal post.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just really a confidence builder today,'' Hackett joked, then
added, ``We'll hope it doesn't come down to a field goal, but if it
does, he'll be the guy. That's why we came over here today, so we
could see what it was like.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Hackett was pleased that the team tested the Coliseum
out for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to get in our home. The turf looks great,''
Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   __ MacKenzie limited: With an ankle injury now added to his
hamstring problem, tailback Malaefou MacKenzie's status for the
game is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's ginger and very limited,'' Hackett said. ``I don't know
if I'll play him or not. I'm very concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Redshirt questions: While Grootegoed will now redshirt, there
is some debate whether several other freshmen will sit out the
season. Defensive tackle Kenechi Udeze will probably redshirt,
barring a major injury on the defensive line. Tailback Chris
Howard, who has not fully recovered from knee surgery last spring,
is another redshirt candidate. Howard's status will probably remain
uncertain, however, since MacKenzie has been injured and Petros
Papadakis is the only other backup to Sultan McCullough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys who are on the fence, and there's eight to 10, I'll
sit down with their families before the San Jose State game (on
Sept. 23),'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Matt Cassel of Chatsworth will not be officially
redshirted until after the season, because he is the No. 3
quarterback, and will make every road trip in case of injury to
Carson Palmer or Mike Van Raaphorst.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
