<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5871 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-ELVIS-N     09-08 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-ELVIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: TAKING THE TRAIN FROM MAINE TO MEMPHIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: please replace double parentheses (( )) with single
brackets)  
 By HOWELL RAINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the pleasures of an end-of-summer vacation is unessential
reading. I'm not talking about the melt-in-the-mind bonbons called
``beach books,'' but those more ambitious and alluring books that
linger on the shelf from year to year, only to be pushed aside
again and again by volumes that seem more essential to one's
workaday life.
</P>
<P>
   In my case, one of those I'll-get-around-to-it books has been
``Last Train to Memphis,'' Peter Guralnick's well-reviewed
biography of the young Elvis Presley. It has been on my shelf since
its publication in 1994, and a few weeks ago my musician son wanted
to borrow it for an upcoming road trip. Thus prodded, I bought him
a new copy and took my own long-neglected book along on a Maine
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   There was something oddly relaxing yet stimulating about
revisiting those steamy Memphis summers and long-ago Mississippi
River nights from the vantage point of an austere Northern coast.
The most sobering surprise for me, as a journalist, was that even
in the era of segregation, Southern newspaper writers exhibited a
surer grasp of what Presley was creating _ a new transracial
synthesis in American popular music _ than did the New York critics
quoted in the book. The latter concentrated on the sexual threat of
his hip movements, the hoodlum symbolism of his ducktail hairdo,
and the supposed limitations of one of the century's great vocal
instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, a number of writers had already observed with a
surprising lack of prejudice that ``our homegrown hillbilly
singer'' was fusing Nashville music with vocal and instrumental
licks picked up from B.B. King, Rufus Thomas, Arthur Crudup and
other black musicians. I was also struck by the fact that from the
first day of his national fame, Presley freely acknowledged his
musical debt. ``The colored folks been singing it and playing it
just like I'm doin' now, man, for more years than I know,'' he told
The Charlotte Observer in 1956. ``I got it from them.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Guralnick has something to teach about the biographer's
problem in writing about those American geniuses who burst upon us
with culture-changing force, then dissipate their gifts in lives of
self-parody. One thinks, in a literary context, of how Carlos
Baker's essential biography, ``Ernest Hemingway: A Life Story,'' is
distorted by the author's animosity toward the paranoid, posturing
Hemingway of the final years. Albert Goldman's ``Elvis,'' published
in 1981, exhibited a striking authorial condescension for its
subject.
</P>
<P>
   But Guralnick, by focusing on the early years of naive
brilliance, re-creates that period described with Fitzgeraldian
grace in Variety in 1957 by Hal Kanter, a screenwriter assigned to
hang out with Presley and help launch his movie career. The Presley
story, he said, is that of ``the young man with the ancient eyes
and the child's mouth . . . ((who)) awoke from the nightmare of
poverty to find the brilliant sun of Fame suddenly burst in his
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Another aspect of reading for pleasure rather than purpose is
that one encounters unexpected connections. The description of
Vernon Presley, the singer's father, as a ``taciturn, suspicious
man'' comfortable only in the family's ``private world'' rang a
couple of bells. I remembered the description of Albert Gore Sr. in
``The Prince of Tennessee,'' by David Maraniss and Ellen Nakashima,
as a man ``with that distant look in his eye.'' ``It's a mountain
thing,'' observed a family friend, who purported to see the same
Appalachian remoteness in Vice President Al Gore. What connections,
if any, I wondered, could be drawn between the hereditary political
prince and the self-invented king of rock 'n' roll, between a
sort-of Tennessee mountaineer and a deep-dyed son of the Southern
flatlands?
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the younger men lived in an era when the outsider
mentality that so powerfully shaped their Southern fathers _ both
the ne'er-do-well Vernon Presley and the relentlessly striving Al
Gore Sr. _ has been subjected to powerful forces of cultural
nationalization, including, as it happens, rock music. Yet a
literary visit to '50s Memphis _ to the white musicians in the Sun
Records studios and the black blues shouters along Beale Street _
carries a message that can also be gleaned from a week's sojourn
among the persistently laconic residents of modern-day Maine.
Distinctive regional differences do endure as factors in a nation
that may be getting smarter about celebrating and preserving them.
Those differences seem interwoven somehow with the quintessentially
American mystery of true genius emerging from as unlikely a place
as East Tupelo, Miss. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
