<HEADER>
A5873 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-DEGLIN-NYT &LR;      09-08 0195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DEGLIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
T.L. DEGLIN, 92, PUBLIC RELATIONS EXECUTIVE  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.H., Ariz., Conn.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Theodore L. Deglin, a longtime public relations
executive, died in Manhattan on Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   He was 92 and lived on the Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   Deglin, known as Ted, was Madison Square Garden's public
relations director from 1935 until he entered the Army in 1942. He
became a colonel and was awarded the Legion of Merit in 1945 for
his work as a public relations officer with Army forces in the
western Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, he became the president of a new, Manhattan-based
public relations firm, Deglin-Wood Inc., with clients including
Madison Square Garden Corp., ``21'' Brands, and Wine Producers of
California Ltd. The firm later became Ted Deglin &AMP; Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Deglin was born in Philadelphia and received a bachelor's degree
in 1930 from the University of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, the former Ann Reirden, whom he
married in 1961 after three early and brief marriages; twin
daughters, Dorian Scammon of Hopkinton, N.H., and Kane Peterson of
Westport, Conn.; and six grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
