<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WILSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
C. PHILIP WILSON, 79, EXPERT IN TREATMENT OF EATING DISORDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Conn.)   By ANAHAD O'CONNOR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dr. C. Philip Wilson, an expert in the treatment of
eating disorders and other severe psychosomatic problems, died Aug.
17 at his home in Manhattan. He was 79.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was heart disease, said his son Scott, a psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   While a resident in psychiatry at Columbia-Presbyterian Hospital
in New York, Wilson developed techniques for treating
gastrointestinal problems and anorexia nervosa, which was then
rarely diagnosed. Much of his treatment for anorexia and bulimia
focused on the earliest phases of childhood development and
mother-infant interaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the argument of nature versus nurture,'' Scott Wilson said,
``my father was very much a proponent of the nurture side and
emphasized that childhood developmental influences were crucial in
causing anorexia nervosa and other psychosomatic eating
disorders.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson wrote extensively for professional journals and reference
books. He was also an editor or co-editor of five books on eating
disorders. The best-known, ``The Fear of Being Fat,'' is widely
used in treating anorexia today.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, he received the Sigmund Freud Award of the American
Society of Psychoanalytic Physicians for distinguished service in
psychiatry and psychoanalysis.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Philip Wilson was born in Scarsdale, N.Y., graduated
from Yale and from the College of Physicians and Surgeons of
Columbia University, and began his medical career in the Navy in
World War II. While serving on a transport ship in the Pacific, he
became interested in the body's sensitivity to emotional changes,
having noticed that many enlisted men reported gastrointestinal
problems upon leaving home port.
</P>
<P>
   As a civilian he continued to explore the effects of emotional
stress on physical health, an interest that became a mainstay of
his private practice and his work at St. Luke's Hospital in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his son Scott, Wilson is survived by his wife,
Christine; his son Marc; his daughter, Cynthia; two brothers, H.
Donald and Stephen; and a grandson. All live in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
