<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSURE-MYANMAR-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYANMAR'S VICIOUS JUNTA DESERVES CENSURE, NOT COOPERATION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 775-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Few cities are as gloomy as Yangon, the rot-blackened capital of
Myanmar, known in better days as Rangoon and Burma respectively.
</P>
<P>
   By day, unemployed youths line the streets. By night, in the
deserted center, soldiers stand guard behind barbed-wire blockades.
</P>
<P>
   Under the grip of military rule, few people dare talk politics,
even in private. Beyond the capital, it is worse: in some parts
people must endure slavery, eviction from their villages,
destruction of their crops, murder and theft by the army.
</P>
<P>
   The one bright light amid the murk is Aung San Suu Kyi, the
leader of the National League for Democracy (NLD).
</P>
<P>
   Her nine-day protest, trapped in a car on the outskirts of
Yangon, and her subsequent detention under what amounts to house
arrest, remind her countrymen, and the wider world, both of the
intransigence of the military junta and of the fact that an
alternative still exists, despite years of oppression.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Suu Kyi's party won a general election, in 1990, by a
landslide, but the soldiers refused to move aside. Instead, they
dug in, occasionally making a few cosmetic changes to improve their
image: three years ago, for instance, they changed their name from
the State Law and Order Council to the State Peace and Development
Council.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays they claim to bring order and stability to a country
divided by ethnic rivalry, though in reality their intimidation
encourages rebellion, notably along Myanmar's borders, and
thousands have fled to Thailand in search of jobs and safety.
</P>
<P>
   They also claim that a new election will be held once a new
constitution has been written. In truth, the soldiers' intentions
remain unchanged, as they admit in their franker moments.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago they openly vowed to ``eliminate'' the NLD, and
they have recently been forcing members to leave the party in
droves.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Suu Kyi's protest was timed, in part, to show that the
party will not yield. It is welcome evidence of her continuing
readiness to defy the junta and fight for democracy.
</P>
<P>
   For two years, since a similar set of protests in 1998, she had
lain low, leading some of her countrymen to fear _ and the junta to
hope _ that the democrats were a spent force. They are not.
</P>
<P>
   Not much has been going their way, though. Although ritual
denunciations of Myanmar are still made in various world bodies,
and though Indonesia, the biggest country in Southeast Asia, has
junked its military autocrat in favor of a democratically chosen
president, Myanmar's junta has been all too successful at
ingratiating itself with its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   It enjoys cordial relations with China. And, more importantly,
it is looked on with an increasingly benign eye by most members of
ASEAN, the Association of South-East Asian Nations, which admitted
Myanmar to its ranks in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ASEAN argued then that ``constructive engagement'' would soften
the generals and that trade would bring liberalization, much as
Japan claimed when it tried to promote investment in Myanmar
earlier in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, other countries have also tried to engage the
junta. India has sent its army chief to discuss their common
border. Australia has offered to help set up a human-rights
commission in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
   Now even the European Union says it is ready to abandon its
previous standoffishness towards the regime and attend an ASEAN
meeting in Laos in December at which Myanmar will be represented.
</P>
<P>
   All bar Britain purport to believe that engagement, not
isolation, will bring a change for the better. They are wrong.
</P>
<P>
   As the continuing persecution of Miss Suu Kyi and her party
shows, ASEAN's policy has not achieved either its declared aim of
reforming the junta or the underlying strategic aim of many of the
region's diplomats: stopping Myanmar becoming a cockpit of
Chinese-Indian rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Like North Korea, Myanmar is a weak country run by vicious
people whose one diplomatic skill is an ability to play more
powerful countries off against one another.
</P>
<P>
   ASEAN should realize that any decent club, even one that admits
a communist country like Vietnam, lays down some basic standards
for its members' behavior.
</P>
<P>
   It should censure Myanmar in the strongest terms and make it
plain that its membership will be suspended if Miss Suu Kyi is not
released, her party allowed to organize freely and a realistic plan
put forward for a return to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Others should help ASEAN to that realization _ and prominent
among them should be the European Union, with a prompt announcement
that it won't go to the Laos meeting in December. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
