r k BC-GORE-ENERGIZER-BUNNY-     09-08 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ENERGIZER-BUNNY-ECONOMIST-375&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM SUNRISE TO SUNSET...GORE QUESTS, TESTS, NEVER RESTS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...NOTE 175-word trim; 1,150 uncut)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 975-word (trimmed) material from The
New York Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: 175-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 375; 1,150 WORDS UNCUT)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ It's six in the morning on Labor Day and Al Gore is
addressing an overflowing crowd at a fire station in Tampa, Fla. He
warms them up with a few firefighting anecdotes _ it turns out that
his uncle Everett was a fireman _ before reverting to his usual
catalogue of policies and promises.
</P>
<P>
   He will reduce prescription-drug prices for old folk (a forest
of crutches is raised aloft in approval), raise the minimum wage by
a dollar an hour (loud cheers), and provide tax credits for
university education (even louder cheers).
</P>
<P>
   By the time the first rays of dawn can be seen on the horizon,
he has promised something to almost everyone present (with the
notable exception of the man holding a huge sign demanding the
appointment of a special prosecutor), and the crowd marches off
happily into the sunrise.
</P>
<P>
   It is hardly surprising that a swot like Gore should want to get
an early start on Labor Day, the traditional kickoff point for the
home stretch of the campaign. But this is actually the fifth event
in what the Gore team is billing as a 28-hour workathon.
</P>
<P>
   So far the vice president's audiences have included building
workers in Philadelphia (at 6 p.m.), hospital workers in Flint,
Mich. (at close to midnight), shop-floor workers at a truck factory
(at just before 1 a.m.), and twelve customers at Pop and Son's Cafe
in Tampa (at 5 a.m.).
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Joe Lieberman, who tagged along as far as Tampa, jokes
that running mates should start demanding collective-bargaining
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Gore packed in two Labor Day rallies later that day _ a huge
event in Pittsburgh and a smaller one at a speedway in Louisville,
Ky. _ and even managed an unexpected visit to a high-tech factory
on his way to bed.
</P>
<P>
   America is the first society in the world that has tried to
organize itself on the assumption that human beings do not need to
sleep. There are 24-hour news channels, 24-hour wedding chapels,
and, of course, 24-hour lap-dancing emporiums.
</P>
<P>
   So it was only a matter of time before someone invented the
24-hour political campaign; and it is only right that that someone
should be Al Gore, the protege of the man who invented the
``permanent campaign.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (175-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 375) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Today's presidential campaigns are untrammeled by the
constraints of time and money that bring sanity to politics in
other countries. It is more than a year since the unofficial start
of the campaign _ the Iowa straw poll _ and there are still two
months to go.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush and Gore campaigns have already spent more than a
quarter of a billion dollars collectively, and this could well turn
out to be America's first billion-dollar presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to think of a better way to satirize all this excess
than for the world's best-known environmentalist to fly from
Pennsylvania to Florida and back again in the space of a few hours.
</P>
<P>
   Gore not only hurtles around in a giant Boeing 757, Airforce
Two. He has another giant aircraft full of journalists following
behind. (This week W. finally closed the ``jet gap'' by getting a
757 of his own, handing his old Boeing 727 to Dick Cheney.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,150) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Even the mundane business of eating is over the top. Gore
started his tour with a cheese-steak sandwich with the building
workers, followed shortly afterwards by pizza. He started the next
day with some country ham and biscuits at Pop's place at 5 a.m.
before eating a mushroom omelette with the local firefighters. On
the way to Louisville he stopped to pick up 20 boxes of pizza.
</P>
<P>
   There are two powerful defenses of this extraordinary way of
doing politics. The first is that the United States is a darn big
place. The only way to prevent politicians from becoming completely
cut off from the people is to force them to spend years on the
stump.
</P>
<P>
   America's way of democracy thus obliges politicians to spend
weeks hanging around diners in Iowa and New Hampshire (thanks to
the caucuses and primaries) and then later to get to know some of
the dullest parts of the Midwest (thanks to the concentration of
swing states in the Rust Belt).
</P>
<P>
   The second defense is that being president is a hard job, and
voters need to make sure that the candidates are up to it. How
better to test their ability to take the punishing pace of the 24x7
global economy than to force them to ricochet from coast to coast
and north to south?
</P>
<P>
   And how better to test their ability to stand up to tub-thumping
fanatics than to force them to discuss prescription-drug charges
with Florida pensioners?
</P>
<P>
   There is also a more subtle defense of the American political
system: the hazing defense.
</P>
<P>
   The electorate is bent on subjecting politicians to all sorts of
humiliating rituals before handing them power. Politicians not only
have to prove that they can stuff themselves all day long with junk
food while remaining telegenic. They have to prove that they can
endure in-your-face rudeness without batting an eyelid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Al Gore,'' the smiling vice president said to one man in a
Florida diner. ``When Clinton leaves,'' the man replied, ``why
don't you go with him.''
</P>
<P>
   There is even something to be said for this four-state,
five-city extravaganza. Gore and Lieberman made a great fuss about
the fact that, unlike W., they understand people who have to work
at odd hours of the day and night. (Gore's mother put herself
through college by waitressing in an all-night coffee shop;
Lieberman's father drove a bakery truck before dawn.)
</P>
<P>
   But the real point of the exercise is to raise doubts about
Bush's capacity for hard work.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore is the Energizer Bunny of this campaign, Bush is the
napster, taking his favorite feather pillow wherever he goes _ an
aide carries it in a special bag _ and pining if he has to spend
too many nights away from home.
</P>
<P>
   For all its symbolic virtues, however, Gore should hesitate
before organizing another workathon, if only to keep the press from
staging a revolt. Listening to one speech by Gore is hardly a
rousing experience. Listening to several speeches in a row,
including one just before dawn, verges on torture.
</P>
<P>
   Bush started the week with yet another faux pas: calling a New
York Times journalist a ``major-league (vulgarity)'' in the range
of a live microphone. (A hint: it's an anatomical part in the human
southern hemisphere; site of hemorrhoids.)
</P>
<P>
   That word was mild compared with the ones being bandied around
by some members of the press as they completed their 28th
consecutive hour of following the vice president. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
