<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 05:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5929 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-MEMORIAL-OVERKILL?-EC     09-08 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEMORIAL-OVERKILL?-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM HERE TO ETERNITY: WHO MERITS A MONUMENT _ SOLDIERS OR
SINATRA?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 625-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Who better deserves a prominent memorial: the
singer whose ``My Way'' launched a thousand karaoke bars, or his 16
million contemporaries who fought in the Second World War?
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, it looks as if New York City will erect a statue
of Frank Sinatra before Washington gets around to building a
tribute to the troops whose ranks Sinatra joined only on celluloid.
</P>
<P>
   But neither is proving particularly easy work. The Sinatra
statue would stand on a small pedestrian island in the heart of
Times Square (ironically, just a few feet from the city's most
prominent Army recruiting office, and close to the spot where
wartime sailors once pelted his image with tomatoes).
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say that the statue will only make the square's
appalling traffic problems worse; a few also gripe that Broadway is
an inappropriate spot for a memorial to a man who seldom trod the
boards, at least in a theatrical sense.
</P>
<P>
   Not for the first time, Sinatra might be saved by having friends
in the right places. The city's mayor, Rudy Giuliani, has vowed to
put up a memorial to the local hero.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that he actually came from New Jersey, a place with
nothing else to recommend it in New Yorkers' eyes. But Sinatra not
only sang ``New York, New York''; he was also one of the first
Italian-Americans to become a national idol.
</P>
<P>
   Turn now to Washington. The most bizarre thing about the
memorial to those who fought in the Second World War is that it
does not already exist.
</P>
<P>
   The capital is full of physical appreciations of one sort or
another (including one to Franklin Roosevelt's dog, Fala).
Memorials have already been built to those who fought in Vietnam
and Korea, and one has been eagerly proposed for Ronald Reagan,
even though he is still alive and therefore, by law, is not
eligible to get a Washington monument for at least 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Even more bizarrely, the campaign for the Second World War
memorial seems to have gotten off the ground only because of the
involvement of actor Tom Hanks (of ``Saving Private Ryan'' fame),
though it now enjoys wide political support.
</P>
<P>
   The monument will stand on the National Mall, the strip of
parkland between the Washington Monument and the Lincoln Memorial.
But before ground-breaking in November, two federal agencies must
make final reviews of the project.
</P>
<P>
   Critics complained that the first rather hulking design looked
inappropriately fascist.
</P>
<P>
   The revised seven-acre plaza, which would feature two massive
archways, 56 free-standing pillars, fountains and waterfalls,
several bronze eagles and a nine-foot wall emblazoned with over
4,000 gold stars, would still not shame ancient Rome.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial's chief architect, Friedrich St. Florian, says the
design celebrates America's ``unprecedented unity'' during the war.
The National Coalition to Save Our Mall bemoans the design's
``institutional and corporate abstraction and anonymity'' in
contrast to, for example, the Vietnam Memorial, which lists every
fallen soldier by name.
</P>
<P>
   And there is even dissent among ex-servicemen's groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing there that tells you anything about World War
11,'' says John Graves, an ex-serviceman who has starred in a
television spot opposing the current design. ``A memorial that
needs explaining is not a memorial.''
</P>
<P>
   These complaints have not gone unheard. This week, an
independent federal agency urged Bruce Babbitt, the secretary of
the interior, to reconsider the plans before approving them.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's report contends that, as proposed, the memorial
would clash with its subdued surroundings and ``intrude upon the
uncluttered historic vistas of the Mall.''
</P>
<P>
   That's always a problem with memorials: they tend to obscure as
much history as they commemorate. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
