<P>
   &UR; SINCERE APOLOGY OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret a private comment I made to the vice-presidential
candidate made it to the public airwaves. I regret everybody heard
what I said.'' (George W. Bush, after his salty remark about
reporter Adam Clymer of the New York Times was picked up by an open
microphone) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE SAD THAN ANGRY: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed in the governor's language.'' (Adam Clymer) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OPPORTUNISM OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``We hold the members of the Fourth Estate in the highest
regard. They should be treated with the respect they deserve.''
(Gore spokesman Chris Lehane, in response to Bush's vulgar comment.
When asked what respect the press deserved, Lehane responded,
``That's the beauty of the comment.'' Press pool, Sept. 4) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DEBATE DEBATE (1): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm showing up on Tuesday. I hope he shows up.'' (George W.
Bush, referring to a proposed debate with Al Gore on NBC moderated
by Tim Russert. Bush refused to take part in more than one debate
with his rival organized by the official body, the Commission on
Presidential Debates.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DEBATE DEBATE (2): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wrong with those Commission debates? Is it that too
many people will be watching?'' (Gore, in response to Bush.
Washington Post, Sept. 6) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SOUND BITE OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   At the West Indian Day parade in New York, a woman was arrested
and charged with assault after biting a Secret Service agent who
had stopped her from approaching Hillary Rodham Clinton, the
Democratic Senate candidate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ROCK-STAR FANTASY OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore and Joe Lieberman called their marathon Labor Day
campaigning, which covered five cities from Michigan to Florida in
28 hours, the ``Hard Day's Night'' tour. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NADER NADIR: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm running to win. You don't run to lose.'' (Ralph Nader, who
will probably get about 3 percent of the vote according to recent
polls. NBC ``Nightly News,'' Sept. 4) &QL;
</P>
