<HEADER>
A5933 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-LAOS-HMONG-MINN-ECONO     09-08 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAOS-HMONG-MINN-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FLOURISHING HMONG OF MINNESOTA  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minneapolis-St.Paul, MINN.)  (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 550-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ST. PAUL, MINN. _ Drive through Frogtown, a seedy bit of St
Paul, Minn., and the future of Laos is on display.
</P>
<P>
   On one side of University Avenue is Foodsmart, a supermarket
owned by a Hmong businessman. On the other is the office of the
Hmong Times, next door to the Asian-American press. Nearby are a
Hmong bookshop, a Hmong chemist and dozens of other Hmong-run
shops.
</P>
<P>
   Toua Xiong, who owns the supermarket, says he wants ``to turn
Frogtown into Hmongtown.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike their relations in Communist-run Laos, the Hmong of
Minnesota, some 70,000 of them, are evidently flourishing.
</P>
<P>
   The Hmong fought with America's CIA against North Vietnam during
the Vietnam War. Hmong fighter pilots and troops attacked the Ho
Chi Minh Trail, part of which wound through Laos. When the
Americans withdrew, thousands of Hmong fled to Thailand, and then
on to America.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 25 years on, the Hmong want to improve matters back home.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Hmong who remain in Laos, those in America are riven
between the militant-minded, who say the struggle against the
Communists should continue, and a larger group of moderates, who
would encourage trade, remittances and contact with their old
country.
</P>
<P>
   General Vang Pao, who once led the Hmong in battle, has stout
backing from the oldest support group for the Hmong in America, the
Lao Family of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Ying Vang, its boss, says he wants America to ``go and rescue
our people.'' He suggests that ``maybe we can do some economic
sanctions.'' He claims that agents sent by the Laotian government
have been creating splits among the Hmong in America.
</P>
<P>
   What of the recent bomb attacks in Laos, blamed on unnamed
dissidents? Vang does not support them. Nevertheless, he says,
something must be done to stop what he calls ethnic cleansing in
Laos.
</P>
<P>
   The moderate Hmong in St. Paul say that closer ties, not
sanctions, would improve the lot of their people.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Pao Xiong, a Hmong politician on a government committee for
Asian-American affairs, says that Hmong businessmen in St. Paul
would leap at the chance to invest back home.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to move some of Minnesota's wealth _ the state's
economy was worth $161 billion in 1998 _ to Laos, which earned $1.3
billion in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   As Laos's neighbor, Vietnam, has found, the diaspora can be a
major source of hard currency.
</P>
<P>
   A few former residents are now visiting Laos, says Fu Hang of
the Asian Development Corporation. His father has bought land
there. ``When Laos opens up, then we'll do business there,'' he
says. Others send money to build temples and to support families.
</P>
<P>
   The moderate Hmong seem to be winning the argument. The Laotian
royal family, which lives in France, visited Minnesota in June and
encouraged Lee's group. Members of the Laotian government have
visited the moderates in Minnesota, much to the outrage of the
militant Hmong.
</P>
<P>
   An article in the Hmong Times in June called the moderates reds
and collaborators. But Lee says, ``Everything depends on us. If we
succeed, we open up the door for future generations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hmong's dollars, if not their bullets, could yet change life
in Laos for the better. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
