A5934 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-SHREDDING-JAC-NASSER-     09-08 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHREDDING-JAC-NASSER-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIT THE ROAD, JAC?: FORD BOSS'S CAREER, AND CREDIBILITY,
DEAD-ENDS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 950-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ On Wednesday, Sept. 6 Jac Nasser, chief executive of
Ford Motor Company, appeared before a congressional subcommittee
investigating the recall of at least 6.5 million Firestone tires
fitted to Ford Explorer sport-utility vehicles (SUVs).
</P>
<P>
   Before he even took the stand, he was on the defensive.
Disintegration of the tires is already blamed for causing 89 deaths
in America and a further 46 in Venezuela, and both Firestone and
Ford have been accused of being, at the least, slow to react to
growing evidence that there was a dangerous problem.
</P>
<P>
   Nasser was up in front of the congressmen with Masatoshi Ono,
the boss of Firestone in America (Firestone is part of Japan's
Bridgestone Corporation).
</P>
<P>
   The contrast was sharp. Nasser was, as usual, the Australian
tough guy. Ono was all contrition. ``I come before you to apologize
to you, the American people, and especially to the families who
have lost loved ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Also giving evidence was Joan Claybrook, president of Public
Citizen, a consumer group, and a former National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration (NHTSA) official. She said that Ford and
Firestone officials should be charged with second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Nasser had tried to avoid giving evidence to Congress
at all, offering to send two technical people in his place, and
pleading that he needed to stay in Detroit to manage the company's
response to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Ono, meanwhile, had agreed readily to the request to appear,
despite having poor English and a harder case to plead.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone also had a huge tire recall in the late 1970s and was
reprieved only when the Reagan administration relaxed safety rules.
</P>
<P>
   Either Nasser was cowardly, or he was arrogantly jockeying to
get a more favorable slot before the committee, avoiding being
sandwiched between his critics from consumer and safety groups.
</P>
<P>
   Since nobody could accuse the engaging but pugnacious Nasser of
ducking a fight on his battle through the ranks to the top of the
world's second-biggest car company, ill-judged arrogance seems the
more likely answer.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, when the American press and broadcasters were on a
feeding frenzy over the recall of Firestone tires fitted to Ford
Explorers, Nasser appeared on prime-time television advertising
slots professing the company's commitment to customers and their
safety, and promising to do everything to replace suspect tires as
quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   But the great thing about going on TV ads is that nobody can
answer back _ unlike during a congressional hearing. Nasser must
have been made very quickly aware of what a mistake he had made in
at first refusing to appear.
</P>
<P>
   The tough-talking Australian is probably the most wired manager
in Detroit. His top-floor office has a dozen screens around its
high-tech walls, with CNBC murmuring in the background and
motor-industry Web sites flicking on and off all the time. He says
he needs all this to keep up-to-the-minute with information.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, his multi-screen office-cum-TV-studio must
have told him how far the value of his stock options had shrunk
when Ford's share price started diving as the crisis grew, and
management began to look like rabbits caught in the headlights of
an SUV.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the reaction to his planned no-show was coming across the
ether. The committee chairman, a Republican from Louisiana named
Billy Tauzin, promptly attacked Nasser's reluctance to appear.
</P>
<P>
   Here was a man whose vision of Ford's future success is to get
close to customers to satisfy their needs and sell them not just
cars but all sorts of other services as well, shrinking from a
public discussion of the biggest customer and safety problem to hit
Ford since the early 1970s (when its little Pinto cars started
bursting into flames in accidents because of a badly placed fuel
tank).
</P>
<P>
   Here, too, was a man who wants to create lifelong customer
relationships, holding back from the eyeball-to-eyeball exposure
that is what any worried Ford customer wants right now.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was cowardice or arrogance does not much matter. It
looked simply awful.
</P>
<P>
   The car industry in Detroit has an old saw about getting down to
basics, ``where the rubber meets the road.''
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of Nasser's ambitious attempt to transform Ford
from a low-rated car-making stock into a glamorous service and
consumer company, with a higher share price, along comes the most
basic problem _ literally where the rubber meets the road.
</P>
<P>
   Inquiries under way by the NHTSA and by Congress will attempt to
discover what went wrong with the tires and whether Ford and
Firestone were to blame for not responding more quickly. Some are
in no doubt already where the blame lies.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Claybrook of Public Citizen maintains that Ford and
Firestone knew about the tire problem with the Explorer (such
vehicles account for as much as 25 percent of Ford's profits) as
long ago as the early 1990s, as a result of lawsuits following
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   She alleges that there was a cover-up, with gagging orders
imposed as part of the settlements of these suits.
</P>
<P>
   Nasser is not responsible directly for what Ford was doing all
those years ago, but his initial response to the crisis brings
echoes of earlier complacency.
</P>
<P>
   If he continues to stumble, the most likely outcome is that his
chairman Bill Ford (an earnest environmentalist as well as a Ford
heir) will take over the front-line position of defending the
company, which is usually what chairmen of the board are for
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Unless somebody at Ford gets this consumer-safety issue under
control, it will not just be Firestone tires that are shredded _ it
could be Jac Nasser's career as well. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
