<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC VIRTUES, PRIVATE VICES IN CHILE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 450-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   SANTIAGO _ Earlier this year, MercadoLibre, a Miami-based online
auction company, found to its surprise that Santiago's underground
railway authority had vetoed part of its planned advertising
campaign in Chile.
</P>
<P>
   The state-run metro seems to have objected to a poster
proclaiming ``vendo mis pelotas,'' or ``I sell my balls.''
</P>
<P>
   The veto was predictable. When it comes to public morality,
Chile has long been more straitlaced than its neighbors. General
Augusto Pinochet's dictatorship, with its curfews and press
censorship, helped to keep it that way.
</P>
<P>
   But though a Chilean judge is due to question General Pinochet
next month on criminal charges, in moral matters the center-left
governments that have ruled since 1990 have done little to
challenge his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Divorce is still illegal, although polls show that most Chileans
think it should not be. The rich seek annulments, often paying
their lawyers to arrange false witnesses. Many poorer Chileans
simply avoid marriage: nearly half the country's children are born
out of wedlock.
</P>
<P>
   Discotheque owners feel unable to install contraceptive
machines. Abortion is illegal, even when a mother's life is at
risk.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the government reckons that one in four pregnancies
ends in abortion. The true figure is probably higher. Some
abortions take place discreetly at private hospitals, others
dangerously in backstreet clinics. All are expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Neither are Chileans especially faithful. In a recent survey of
sexual habits by Fundacion Futuro, a polling firm, the average
respondent guessed that two-thirds of men and almost half of women
would have at least one affair while married. But fewer than half
of the respondents admitted themselves to wanting to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Such hypocrisy may owe much to the influence of the Catholic
Church, stronger in Chile than in many other South American
countries. It runs many private schools and controls one of the two
main television channels.
</P>
<P>
   Many businessmen, including the owners of the main media groups,
are active Catholics. A locally-owned cable television firm
recently refused to carry the Playboy channel.
</P>
<P>
   The church also has influence with the government, especially
through Christian Democracy, the ruling coalition's largest party,
but also with the Socialists, who are grateful for its defense of
human rights during the dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Lagos, Chile's president since March, is a socialist
agnostic and in his second marriage. But as a candidate, he dodged
the issue of divorce as much as he could _ out of deference to
Christian Democracy, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   His government does plan to introduce a divorce law, though it
will face a struggle to gain congressional approval. Abortion,
though, is still taboo. Lagos says that legalising it, even for
mothers at risk, is not on his agenda. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
