r k BC-BULLDOZED-BEIJING-ECO     09-08 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLDOZED-BEIJING-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRECKING BALLS ARE DEMOLISHING OLD BEIJING  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 900-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   BEIJING _ On Sept. 7 they started knocking down the courtyard
house of Cao Xueqin, the 18th-century author of ``The Dream of the
Red Chamber,'' China's greatest novel and one that occupies a
bigger place in Chinese hearts than ``Madame Bovary'' or ``Anna
Karenina'' do in French or Russian ones.
</P>
<P>
   The house was in the way of yet another soulless road that
Beijing's municipal authorities want to drive through a
centuries-old neighborhood of narrow alleyways, called hutong in
the Beijing dialect, to the southeast of Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities argued, certainly disingenuously, that it was
not definitely Cao's house but that, if the scholars campaigning in
favor of its preservation could convince them otherwise, they would
put up a memorial to it after its destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Six-lane avenues impress the Communist Party authorities.
Developers from Hong Kong and elsewhere in China drool at the
commercial buildings that can be put up alongside the new roads.
</P>
<P>
   A stone's throw from Cao's house in Zhushikou is another old
neighborhood that suspects it is up for destruction in favor of a
blank expanse of grass that a Hong Kong tycoon thinks will afford a
better view of his new shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, the residents will be given as little notice as
those in Zhushikou. They had first read posters proclaiming that
their area was designated for destruction on July 18, and were told
to move out before Sept. 15. They were each offered compensation of
100,000 yuan ($12,000), with an extra 20,000 yuan if they left
early.
</P>
<P>
   Now one more swathe of the city, 2 km (just over a mile) long,
is a sea of rubble, a community scattered.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, much of what remained to make China's
capital an extraordinary city has been systematically destroyed in
favor of characterless boulevards and brutalist, bathroom-tile-clad
architecture, all choked by a cloud of traffic pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Communists came to power in 1949, travellers reported
an eighth wonder of the world: a green if dusty city, largely
unaltered from the medieval plan laid out under Kublai Khan and
built upon by the Ming (1368-1644) and Qing (1644-1912) dynasties.
</P>
<P>
   China's most famous architect of the 20th century, Liang
Sicheng, suggested that Mao Zedong should preserve the ancient,
imposing city walls as precincts for people to stroll along, and
turn the massive gatehouses into theatres, cafes and suchlike.
</P>
<P>
   He also begged the Communists to build their administrative
center to the west of the Imperial City. Mao, the newly-installed
emperor, took offense.
</P>
<P>
   The walls were torn down, Tiananmen Square (the symbol of
political power in China) was expanded into an immense space of
Communist bleakness, in the center of which, after Mao's death (and
admittedly against his orders), the Great Helmsman's corpse was put
in its hideous mausoleum.
</P>
<P>
   What survived this blitz (as well as the anarchy and destruction
of the Cultural Revolution) was the resilient vernacular life of
Beijing, typified by the hutongs.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing's planners say that the hutong neighborhoods are too
dilapidated to renew and too narrow to be modernized with gas,
water and sewerage systems. They get in the way of where cars want
to go.
</P>
<P>
   And besides, don't the residents happily take the big sweeteners
to live in grim new blocks on the edge of the city?
</P>
<P>
   As one middle-aged hutong resident put it this week, ``Stylish
new furniture doesn't sit well in these old-fashioned buildings.''
Better to get a new apartment than an old sofa.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to blame people for wanting to leave. Under
socialism, the hutongs are run down and overcrowded. Today, few
households have title to ownership, and frequently the several
households sharing one traditional courtyard bicker over their
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Yet equally, it is not hard to imagine that a clearer system of
property rights would render hutong houses valuable propositions
for private renovation.
</P>
<P>
   Garrison Keillor was not quite right when he said that only
Americans pulled down old houses because they were too difficult to
clean.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist Party sees itself in the vanguard of what it calls
China's ``spiritual civilization'' and ``socialist culture.''
President Jiang Zemin is in America this week, where a charm
offensive in the form of exhibitions, concerts, theme parks and
circuses is designed to enlighten Americans about Chinese tradition
and culture.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing, desperate to win the contest to hold the Olympic Games
in 2008, boasts about the ``greening'' and ``modernizing'' of the
capital. In reality, China's quest for modernity destroys much of
the old in favor of the ugly.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of Chinese who object to the destruction, led
by Liang Congjie, the architect's son, along with sentimental
foreigners, are usually branded as elitist.
</P>
<P>
   A more sophisticated response to the elite is to say that
China's cultural heritage is more in the mind _ in poetry and
imagined landscapes _ than in those old physical objects that
remind the Chinese of their backwardness.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the nature of Communism seems to be a more credible
explanation for what is going on. Liang laments the lack of
accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Two days before the destruction of Cao's house, ``Old Man'' Ma,
as he is known, whose family had lived there for six generations,
said in his courtyard: ``All it would take to stop this tragedy
would be one word from an official.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 0545EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
