<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 05:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5938 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-`LOOPY'-TECHNOLOGY-EC     09-08 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`LOOPY'-TECHNOLOGY-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING POWER LINES INTO DATA LINES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 575-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Everybody seems to love the ``local loop'' nowadays.
That is what the firms now battling for control of it call the
wires that connect telecommunications networks with homes and
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   It was not always thus, for the local loop has traditionally
been the low-margin bit of the business. But now, thanks chiefly to
the Internet, consumers everywhere are clamoring for ever-faster
ways to download ever-larger quantities of data, and are willing to
fork out tidy sums for the privilege.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious beneficiaries of such windfalls should be the local
telecoms firms that already have customers in the grip of their
copper tentacles.
</P>
<P>
   The snag is that these old telephone wires lack the carrying
capacity to do the job. Hence the Interest in using a second set of
cables that enter most buildings _ power lines _ as reserve
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Power-line technology (PLT), as it is known, is not a new idea.
Electricity companies have been using a primitive form of it for
years to check faults and to read meters on their networks.
</P>
<P>
   But to sate the demands of Internet users means boosting the
signal from a few hundred kHz to more than 1MHz, and that is more
easily said than done.
</P>
<P>
   Some firms, such as Siemens and Nortel, are experimenting with
``single-carrier'' technology, which transmits the signal on a
unique frequency using high power.
</P>
<P>
   This has the advantage of reaching distant consumers clearly.
However, it requires cranking up the juice so much that such
systems tend to emit a lot of radiation and thus create
interference with other telecommunications systems.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative, ``multi-carrier'' approach has been adopted by
Endesa, a Spanish utility, and Newbridge, a Canadian one. Here, the
signal is divided up between several frequencies.
</P>
<P>
   A similar amount of power is used, but because it is dispersed
over more bandwidth the peak power-level at any given frequency
(and thus the potential for generating interference) is lower than
with the single-carrier method.
</P>
<P>
   The snag is that multi-carrier signals do not travel as far as
single-carrier ones, so they require the construction of expensive
repeater stations.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot of these experiments, however, is that the technology
really does work _ at least according to a new report on the future
of PLT from the Smith Group, a technical consultancy, and UBS
Warburg, an investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   Power companies should not celebrate quite yet, however. Neither
of their approaches complies with existing regulations in the EU _
the area where PLT might be expected to be used most, since a
relatively large number of American Internet users already have
broadband connections.
</P>
<P>
   And although officials at the European Commission, as well as
those in some member countries, are plodding along to develop
standards that might allow PLT to flourish, their ideas of the word
``haste'' may not be compatible with the speed of change in matters
to do with the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The result, according to Nick Pink, one of the report's authors,
is that PLT is likely to be overtaken by other means of delivery,
such as cable modems and broadband wireless links, before it is
allowed to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Boring old utility companies that had been hoping to be re-rated
by the stock market as exciting, new Internet firms may have their
hopes dashed after all.
</P>
<P>
   The unusually pointed title of the report sums up the prospects:
``Warning: This bird may not fly.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
