<HEADER>
A5941 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-DIRECTOR-INTERVIEW-AZ     09-08 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIRECTOR-INTERVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-DIRECTOR-INTERVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    DIRECTOR NEIL LABUTE HOLDS BACK DARK SIDE IN `NURSE BETTY(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Director Neil LaBute admits he had to suppress his darker side
while making (beginitalic)Nurse Betty(enditalic), which stars Renee
Zellweger as a waitress who loses herself in a soap-opera fantasy
world.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute, who wrote and directed the unrepentantly malevolent
(beginitalic)In the Company of Men (enditalic)and (beginitalic)Your
Friends and Neighbors(enditalic), pulled his punches in
(beginitalic)Nurse Betty(enditalic), which leans more toward comedy
than drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``My tendency is always to go, `Oh, let's stick it to them a
little bit. Let's keep them on their toes,''' LaBute says.
</P>
<P>
   But in making (beginitalic)Nurse Betty(enditalic), LaBute
realized that ``the audience really wants to go on a roller coaster
ride, but not actually be thrown out of the car.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't mind going upside down a little bit, but they
really don't want to hit the pavement,'' he says. ``I've applied
pavement, concrete, on other outings, so I thought this time I
would let them remain seated.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBute even cut a graphic scene in which someone is shot in the
head, instead allowing the character to die offscreen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried it the other way and the audience literally just
turned off,'' LaBute says. ``They were like, `Omigod, I did not
just see that.''''
</P>
<P>
   The movie also stars Morgan Freeman and Chris Rock, who play hit
men who trail Betty across the country after she inadvertently
makes off with their drug stash.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute says the movie successfully walks the line between a
light comic story, which centers on Betty's fantasy about being
engaged to a soap character, and the evil mission of her two
pursuers. That was especially tough, because the actors were doing
other projects at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to know if you're getting that tone, that
strange mix of humor and violence,'' LaBute says. ``Are you kind of
keeping that ball up in the air, where there's a continuity, it's
just not wildly veering from one side of the road to the other?''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman is the biggest star to cross LaBute's path so far, and
the director says the veteran actor really brought a presence to
the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was fantastic from beginning to end,'' LaBute says. ``He's
just got such experience and such weight to him. There's a certain
dignity. You completely buy him as the president of the U.S. or a
hit man or whatever he is. And he brings a sort of grace to it.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBute says Rock joined the cast because it gave him an
opportunity to act, not just do his nightclub routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the page, it's not the kind of guy who would be ideal for
him to play,'' LaBute says, ``because he was really the quiet one,
kind of sullen, the first to grab his weapon rather than talk to
somebody. And it was only by his frustration that you brought any
of the humor out of him.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he adds, Rock had to be prepared to act with
the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a scary proposition, actually, to go into the
ring with Morgan Freeman,'' LaBute says. ``By doing what seems to
be nothing, by just being still and taking over the screen, he will
blow you away, you will disappear if you aren't up to the task. And
I think Chris really sort of took it as both an acting challenge
and an acting camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, LaBute says he was really attracted to the film because
it was a departure for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for something that would surprise people, and
have them say, `Gee, I didn't think he would go there,''' he says.
``While there is a certain darkness of character and tone splashed
throughout (beginitalic)Nurse Betty, (enditalic)I think the overall
sense of it is that it's a much lighter kind of picture.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Muller at bill.muller(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
</TEXT>
