<HEADLINE>
BOSTON TV CHANNEL DECIDES TO AIR `DR. LAURA' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After completing what it called ``a very serious review of her
plans'' for the program, WCVB-TV (Channel 5) in Boston announced
Thursday that it will air controversial talk host Dr. Laura
Schlessinger's new syndicated TV show beginning Monday at 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Although Channel 5 officials never received the full preview
tape they requested from the show's producer, Paramount, they
viewed excerpts they found reassuring. ``She steered far clear of
the subject matter that precipitated this controversy and I've been
assured by Paramount she'll remain far clear of it,'' said Channel
5 president and general manager Paul La Camera.
</P>
<P>
   Gay rights activists _ who accuse Schlessinger of anti-gay bias
_ were critical of WCVB, which many parties believed was the only
station still debating whether to air the show.
</P>
<P>
   The Gay &AMP; Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation ``is deeply
disappointed that WCVB has decided to air this program,
particularly given the open dialogue we've had with the station and
their obvious concern with the community in Boston,'' said GLAAD
spokeswoman Cathy Renna. Eric Marion, an organizer of a Monday
protest against Schlessinger in Boston, said ``WCVB can no longer
be considered a friend of the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Station officials says they will monitor the show carefully. And
director of programming Elizabeth Cheng asserted that the protest
campaign had already ``changed the way (Schlessinger) has talked
about'' homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hearst-Argyle buys Manchester's Ch. 9
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WMUR-TV (Channel 9), the Manchester, N.H. station that became
the dominant Granite State media outlet and a crucial player in the
quadrennial New Hampshire primary, has been purchased by
Hearst-Argyle Television Inc. in a $185 million cash transaction.
The sale, by the privately held Imes Communications company to the
same corporation that owns WCVB-TV (Channel 5) in Boston, was
announced Thursday. The deal is expected to be finalized early next
year.
</P>
<P>
   WMUR vice president and general manager Larry Gilpin called the
sale ``a personal triumph for all of us who have played a role in
the station's phenomenal growth.'' According to Nielsen statistics
cited by the station, its daily newscasts are seen by more than a
quarter million New Hamsphire viewers.
</P>
<P>
   While stating that ``we don't like to use the word `synergy,'
it's a forced word,'' Hearst-Argyle chief operating officer Tony
Vinciquerra said in an interview Thursday that the there were plans
to maximize the combined advertising clout of WMUR and WCVB. He
also indicated that WCVB president and general manager Paul La
Camera would help ``oversee the transfer of the station to
Hearst-Argyle.''
</P>
<P>
   WMUR ``has evolved in the past eight to 10 years in a very
positive way and is clearly the voice of New Hampshire,'' added
Vinciquerra. ``It is the station of record in New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda program wins Emmy
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Newton, Mass. producer Ben Loeterman's one-hour ``Frontline''
episode on the genocide in Rwanda has captured an Emmy Award for
outstanding investigative journalism program. The program, titled
``The Triumph of Evil,'' aired on PBS on Jan. 26 and was honored at
a Wednesday night ceremony in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very difficult film to watch,'' said Loeterman, of
``Triumph of Evil.'' ``It is gratifying to see the film has had as
much impact as it has, as exemplified by this award.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
