</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 09:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5950 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-USAID-$ADV10-C     09-08 2610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-USAID-$ADV10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE PRICE OF PEACE: DESPITE WEALTH, U.S. AID LIKELY TO CLIMB
WITH PEACE DEALS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With color graphic.
 &HT;    With ISRAEL-DEFENSE-$ADV10; ISRAEL-DATA-$ADV10.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Sept. 10 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV, Israel _ Three doors from the austere facade of the
U.S. Embassy is the ``Buzz Stop,'' a beachfront bar where the
American-Israeli relationship flows as smoothly as the draught on
tap.
</P>
<P>
   A miniature Statue of Liberty stands above the entrance and
Israeli owner Eli Barel holds court on the patio overlooking the
Mediterranean Sea. Behind him there's a booming city, where cranes
hover over new malls and skyscrapers, and sport utility vehicles
clog the highways.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the child of America. They have been with us from the
beginning. They raised us,'' Barel says in Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   But even Barel is not aware that the United States usually gives
his small country some $3 billion a year _ equaling about $500 for
each of the 6 million Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they give that much, then God bless America,'' says the
hefty 50-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   America's blessings are likely to increase. Israel is growing
wealthy and already draws one-fifth of all U.S. foreign aid, but it
will likely be getting more.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday is the deadline for a peace agreement between the
Palestinians and Israel _ and the Palestinians have threatened to
declare a state with, or without Israel's approval. After the
failure of July's Camp David peace talks, American mediators are
pressing for an agreement, which could cost more than $17 billion
in aid to Israel for upgrading its military over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   With a country smaller than Vermont, Israelis say they can only
offer land for peace if their army is stronger. And they want
America to help pay the bill.
</P>
<P>
   In July, President Clinton promised to pitch in, but a few
congressional leaders have blanched. First, they were upset at
Israeli plans, over U.S. objections, to sell an advanced radar
plane to China. Israel eventually cancelled the deal. Then, some in
Congress didn't like the price Israel placed on peace.
</P>
<P>
   Their sentiments echo a minority both inside and outside Israel
who say it's time for the country to get by with less help from
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do consider Israel a strategic ally and I want it to
succeed, but at the same time I don't want Israeli citizens to
assume this is an entitlement, like food stamps in the Middle
East,'' says Alabama Republican Rep. Sonny Callahan, who heads the
House subcommittee that writes the foreign aid budget.
</P>
<P>
   Says Callahan, who favors eliminating economic, though not
military, aid to Israel: ``The more money we give to Israel, the
less money we have for starving children in Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   Most, however, say aid to Israel is an investment that reaps
strategic dividends for America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (in the United States) know we can always rely on Israel in
any situation,'' says Ester Kurz, director of legislative strategy
for the American Israel Public Affairs Committee (AIPAC). ``If
Israel weren't there, if Israel were weakened, if Israel couldn't
stay strong against its enemies, we wouldn't have much of an
ally.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an ally that receives uniquely special treatment:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  According to the Congressional Research Service, a branch of
Congress, Israel has received more than $66 billion in grants and
$15 billion more in loans from the United States since 1949 _ far
more than any other country.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The aid continues as Israel grows wealthier and better able to
stand on its own. It's economy is in a hi-tech boom and, this
summer Israeli officials cut $300 million in taxes on stereos,
refrigerators and other electric appliances, in expectation of
budget surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Aid to Israel is given on freer terms than aid to any other
country. Israel is the only country that gets the money up front
each year. It can then invest it, or lend some of it back to the
United States in bonds, earning interest until it can spend it.
</P>
<P>
   Totals for the interest were not available, but based on
estimates from Israeli and U.S. officials, it likely topped $750
million during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Long relationship
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds of this year's regular U.S. assistance, $1.9
billion, is military aid . The other $949 million is economic aid.
It totals about $2.8 billion, more than what was given to Africa
and Latin America combined.
</P>
<P>
   The United States also authorized another $1.2 billion in
special military aid to be given over three years as Israel
implements the 1998 Wye River peace deal. Under the accords, Israel
agreed to hand over to the Palestinians land in the West Bank,
captured in the 1967 War.
</P>
<P>
   In all, it was one of the richest aid years in a solid
relationship that dates back more than half a century.
</P>
<P>
   President Harry Truman took a risk when the United States became
the first country to recognize Israel's statehood in 1948. The
surrounding Arab countries, then beginning their war against the
Jewish state, would count America among their enemies.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. aid to Israel began slowly. It rarely cracked $100
million a year _ and mostly then in loans _ through the 1950s and
1960s, even while the nation fought three wars. In the early 1970s,
the aid pace increased, especially after the surprise Arab attack
that started the 1973 Yom Kippur War.
</P>
<P>
   After the Rose Garden signing of an historic peace agreement
with Egypt in 1978, aid to Israel and Egypt rose sharply and
eventually settled to about $3 billion and $2 billion a year,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Israel's aid is required to go for purchasing military
equipment from American defense contractors. It makes for a $1.5
billion-a-year boon to federal lawmakers whose states _ including
Texas, Ohio, Florida and Georgia _ have factories with Israeli
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Even among Israelis, there has been growing recognition that aid
to Israel should eventually come down. Following a landmark speech
to Congress in 1996 by then-Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu,
Israeli and American officials agreed to reduce the overall aid 20
percent over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   It will drop gradually, but the reductions made so far in the
regular aid were offset this year when President Clinton and
Congress agreed to give the extra $1.2 billion for the Wye
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that what really makes the U.S. aid relationship
with Israel special is not only the volume of aid but the leeway
Israel has in spending it.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, they cite the annual economic aid. Other
countries get such aid with spending overseen locally by the U.S.
Agency for International Development (USAID).
</P>
<P>
   While officials say the aid to Israel is meant to help the
country pay off old debts to the U.S., the money goes into the
general Israeli budget where it can be spent on everything from
welfare to roads.
</P>
<P>
   Accrued Interest
</P>
<P>
   Also, both the economic and military aid come in lump-sum
payments within 30 days after the passage of the U.S. budget.
Israel can then deposit the money in interest-bearing accounts. It
also buys U.S. bonds, in effect lending the money back to the
United States for interest, until the Israeli government needs it.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Brig. Gen. Moti Besser estimates that the interest on
just the military aid has totaled more than $500 million since it
started coming in a lump sum in 1991. It could be much higher.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli Ministry of Finance says, for example, interest on
military aid reached $120 million last year alone.
</P>
<P>
   The lump-sum payments for economic aid started in the early
1980s at Israel's request.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to members of Congress and said, 'There is a way you
can help us without increasing the level of aid,' `` said Daniel
Halperin, former economic minister in the Israeli embassy to the
United States. ``The advantage was that it didn't show in the
budget.''
</P>
<P>
   But, economists and congressional staff contacted by Cox
Newspapers said the lump-sum payments cost American taxpayers
money. If the money stayed with the U.S. Treasury longer, under one
scenario, the U.S. government could use the money to pay off old
debt and save interest costs perhaps near what Israel earns.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan, the Alabama congressman, calls the lump-sum practice
``stupid, or at least unusual, foreign policy,'' but he has not
been able to change it.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Congress proposes letting Egypt earn interest on its
aid, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Aid reaps dividends
</P>
<P>
   Despite the perks in the U.S. aid package, Israel supporters say
it has been good for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   For Israel, they say, the military aid has kept the tiny state
several steps ahead of the Arab rivals who surround it. Israel's
army is small, but is recognized as the best-equipped and strongest
in the region.
</P>
<P>
   It is from this position of strength that the Israelis seek to
make peace with the Palestinians, and other Arab neighbors. Israeli
officials say that if they must risk giving up land, they want
extra assurances that Israel will keep a military edge.
</P>
<P>
   During peace talks with Syria last year, Israeli officials
floated the figure of $17 billion as what they would need to hand
over the strategic Golan Heights, captured from Syria during the
1967 War.
</P>
<P>
   Israel supporters argue that such requests are not out of line
because U.S. aid has paid off for America. First, many Americans
feel a sentimental bond to Israel, which they still see as an
underdog democracy.
</P>
<P>
   There were strategic gains. As Arab countries saw they could not
defeat Israel, they sought to make peace, helping calm a region
that sits on 60 percent of the world's crude oil reserves.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, they sought better ties with the United
States. The result: Both Israelis and Arabs were turning to America
for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best investment and cheapest investment the United
States has ever made,'' said Israeli Dan Schueftan, an occasional
advisor to the Israeli ministries of defense and foreign affairs.
``You (in the U.S.) end up in a situation where both sides are
indebted to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel's survival also provided a Cold War outpost for the
United States in a potentially explosive Middle East loaded with
Soviet clients. Israel did things, like destroy an Iraqi nuclear
reactor in 1981 that, in hindsight, also served American interests.
</P>
<P>
   Israel also gave equipment to the United States in the Persian
Gulf War in 1990, and works closely with U.S. intelligence
services.
</P>
<P>
   Other needs exist
</P>
<P>
   But, critics say at least some of the aid to Israel could do
more good in other places. There are a host of needs, from an
HIV/AIDS crisis in Africa that activists say requires $3.3
billion-a-year to a $500 million shortfall in U.S. embassy staff
and construction.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Israel's economy and army are strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are so vastly superior to any combination of Arab armies
it's ridiculous,'' said Stephen Zunes, a Middle East expert at the
University of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   As far as Israel's role as a Middle East outpost, the U.S. now
has other allies in the region _ including a Navy base in Bahrain
and troops in Saudi Arabia and Kuwait. On matters of peace, Zunes
says it's pressure, not aid, that leads Israel to make concessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would give money to where it is most needed, and Israel is
pretty far down the list,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of other types of aid, to Africa for example, note
that the U.S. devotes less than 1 percent of its budget to foreign
aid, low compared to other industrial nations. Many fear that it
would be even less if Israel, backed by AIPAC, was not the main
beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
   But even with overall increases, Colin Bradford, former chief
economist to USAID, thinks the Israel-Egypt share would be too big.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't doing enough in the broader global setting. We ought
to be doing more, but we also need to get the proportions right.
Israel and Egypt can both stand on their own feet more than they
used to,'' says Bradford, now at American University in Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Israel, meanwhile, is far richer than other U.S. aid recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Once a hard-scrabble Zionist frontier, Israel is now a regional
economic powerhouse. Western franchises, from Blockbuster Video and
Office Depot are common. American firms like Intel Corp. and Lucent
Technologies are buying technology start-ups for billions.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's gross domestic product (GDP) per capita was $18,300 in
1999, according to the on-line CIA World Factbook. By comparison,
Spain's was $17,300 and Greece's $13,900. The U.S. per capita GDP
was $33,900 and the United Kingdom's $21,800.
</P>
<P>
   The economy overall nearly doubled from $53 billion in 1990 to
$101 billion in 1999, according to the Israeli Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
   Economist Jimmy Weinblatt has written that the Israeli economy
has developed an ``addiction'' to the U.S. aid and that it stunts
economic growth. Israel could handle a cut, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the short run, it would cause some shortages but in the
long run it is the right thing to do,'' says Weinblatt, dean of
humanities and social studies at Israel's Ben Gurion University.
</P>
<P>
   Other Israelis offer different reasons for cutting the aid. Some
among Israel's political right-wing see it causing a political
addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is such a psychological dependence,'' says Israeli
member of parliament Uzi Landau. ``There is a notion that Israel
receives so much help from the United States . . . that we have to
listen and do what we are told.''
</P>
<P>
   Backing aid despite unsure public
</P>
<P>
   Among the American public, says Steven Kull, director of the
Program on International Policy Attitudes at the University of
Maryland, people tend to be skeptical of aid to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   He cites a 1999 Gallup Poll of 1,021 people, with a plus or
minus 3.5 percent margin for error, showed a plurality of more than
40 percent favoring a decrease in aid to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Kull says, though, that general public opinion does not
influence Washington as much as organized groups.
</P>
<P>
   And pro-Israel groups are well organized. They frequently
arrange to bring American politicians _ from Austin, Texas, Mayor
Kirk Watson to would-be President George W. Bush and Florida Sen.
Connie Mack _ on trips where they meet with Israeli officials.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan says there's a local pressure, too, because, ``the
Jewish community has been very generous with contributions'' to
political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   But Scott Lasensky, research fellow at the Brookings Institution
in Washington, says support for Israel is grass-roots and
broad-based. Especially active are evangelical Christian groups who
believe Israel must be strong before Jesus Christ can return.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wednesday's peace process deadline forces the region to
confront a potential new cycle of violence between Israelis and
Palestinians, even as they negotiate possible solutions that could
lead to an end to their 52-year conflict.
</P>
<P>
   With a dramatic breakthrough for peace, Lasensky says, Israel's
request for billions in new aid will likely be received well by
both Republicans and Democrats in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Momentum drives these aid packages,'' Lasensky said. ``It's
still Washington's best bipartisan consensus: Aid to Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For information on strategic issues facing Israel see the Jaffee
Center
</P>
<P>
   for Strategic Studies at Tel Aviv University:
</P>
<P>
   www.tau.ac.il/jcss
</P>
<P>
   For the American Israel Public Affairs Committee see:
</P>
<P>
   www.aipac.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
