<TEXT>
<P>
   TOP U.S. AID RECIPIENTS
</P>
<P>
   Israel receives far more U.S. foreign aid than any other
country. Following is how it compares to the other top 10 aid
recipients for this fiscal year:
</P>
<P>
   1.
Israel......................................................$4.13
billion
</P>
<P>
   2.
Egypt.......................................................$2.06
billion
</P>
<P>
   4. Colombia...............................................$1.36
billion
</P>
<P>
   5. Palestinian Territories..................$512 million
</P>
<P>
   6.
Jordan.....................................................$428
million
</P>
<P>
   7.
Kosovo....................................................$216
million
</P>
<P>
   8.
Russia.....................................................$209
million
</P>
<P>
   9.
Ukraine...................................................$202
million
</P>
<P>
   10. Georgia................................................$141
million
</P>
<P>
   Figures for Israel, Egypt, the Palestinian Territories and
Jordan includes money for implementing the Wye River peace accords
of $1.2 billion, $25 million, $400 million and $200 million
respectively. The money is dispensed over a three-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Figure for Colombia includes a $1.3 billion special allocation
to fight drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Except for Colombia, the list includes economic and
military aid in the main foreign aid bills passed for the current
fiscal year. Other aid may be given in other allocations.
</P>
<P>
   Source: U.S. Agency for International Development.
</P>
<P>
   BREAKDOWN ON AID TO ISRAEL: 2000 (Fiscal Year)
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Would work well as bar or pie chart, or something more
artsy like a tank barrel divided into the different sections:
</P>
<P>
   Total.....................................................$4.13
billion
</P>
<P>
   Military aid.....................................$1.92 billion
</P>
<P>
   Economic aid..................................$949.1 million
</P>
<P>
   Refugee aid.....................................$60 million
</P>
<P>
   Total includes $1.2 billion aid from implementing the Wye River
peace deal for modernizing the Israeli army.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: About 74 percent of military aid ($1.42 billion) must be
spent in U.S., and about 26 percent ($500 million) in Israel or
elsewhere; refugee aid to attract, resettle immigrants from other
countries, primarily the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Source: The Congressional Research Service.
</P>
<P>
   BREAKDOWN ON AID TO ISRAEL: 2001 (Proposed by U.S. House)
</P>
<P>
   Total......................................................$2.88
billion
</P>
<P>
   Military aid......................................$1.98 billion
</P>
<P>
   Economic aid...................................$840 million
</P>
<P>
   Refugee aid......................................$60 million
</P>
<P>
   Total does not include interest Israel raises on U.S. aid, or
aid for joint projects with the U.S. Department of Defense.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: About 74 percent of military aid ($1.47 billion) must be
spent in the U.S., and about 26 percent ($515 million) in Israel or
elsewhere; refugee aid to attract, resettle immigrants from other
countries, primarily the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Source: House Appropriations Subcommittee for Foreign
Operations, Export Financing and Related Programs.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL, EGYPT AID COMPARED TO TOTAL FOREIGN AID (Proposed by
U.S. House)
</P>
<P>
   Aid to Israel and Egypt increased in reward for signing an
historic peace deal in 1978. The two countries now receive more
than one-third of America's foreign aid, and would again in the
bill proposed for next year by the U.S. House.
</P>
<P>
   Total foreign aid (Fiscal Year 2001, Proposed): $13.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Israel and Egypt: $4.87 billion ($2.88 billion for Israel; $1.99
billion for Egypt.)
</P>
<P>
   Source: House Appropriations Subcommittee for Foreign
Operations, Export Financing and Related Programs.
</P>
<P>
   BUYING IN BULK
</P>
<P>
   The roughly $2 billion in annual U.S. military aid to Israel has
to be spent in America, with the U.S. Defense Department overseeing
the purchases. Here are some samples:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $2.5 billion for 50 F-16 fighter jets, built in Fort Worth,
Texas by Lockheed Martin Corp.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $415 million for 12 Apache Longbow ground attack helicopters
built in Arizona by Boeing Co.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $62 million for 241,000 high explosive 155mm artillery
projectiles from Iowa-based American Ordinance LLC.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $27 million for 57 advanced, so-called AMRAAM, air-to-air
missiles made in Tuscon, Ariz., by Raytheon Corp.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Purchases made during last two fiscal years.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Federation of American Scientists' Arms Sales Monitoring
Project.
</P>
