<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 09:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5955 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-MURRAY-COLUMN09-COX     09-08 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOEMURRAY-COLUMN
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Hard to get a cool haircut in hot
Texas
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ I had stopped by the barbershop, mainly to catch
up on the news. Not that I didn't already know what everybody's
talking about.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody's talking about the weather.
</P>
<P>
   My little hometown was made mention of on national TV for having
a record-breaking high temperature of 110 degrees this week, with
hardly any regular rain for as long as most anybody can remember.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't even have to go into the barbershop to get the news. It
was being talked on the sidewalk out front.
</P>
<P>
   The nice lady from the hardware store next door was checking
with other businesses to see if anybody else had received the phone
call that had come into the hardware store, something to the
effect:
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the fire emergency center. There is an out-of-control
fire dangerously close to your location. Evacuate immediately. This
is a recorded message.''
</P>
<P>
   She said a couple of the other stores in the vicinity had gotten
the same call. Then again, most had not.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do think we ought to do?'' she asked, understandably
nervous.
</P>
<P>
   I told her straight off what I was going to do
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get a haircut,'' I said. ``But I'd appreciate it
if you'd come get me if it looks like I need to move my car.''
</P>
<P>
   You could see smoke in the far distance to the south, but no big
surprise in that. Here lately, the pineywoods of East Texas being
the tinderbox that they are, you're likely to see smoke in most any
direction most any time.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, the barbershop had received the same recorded
message. No matter. The barbers were remaining at their post, good
barbers that they are. The customers weren't evacuating either, not
wanting to lose their seniority for the next vacant barber chair.
</P>
<P>
   When my time came, Nick the barber _ my barber for the past 40
years or so _ caught me up on the news.
</P>
<P>
   A customer earlier that day had been telling about his catfish
pond turning over, such was the heat. He lost some 100 fish, he
said, and nice-size ones at that, some as much as five pounds.
</P>
<P>
   I'd been worrying about the same problem, I told Nick. Not that
I have a catfish pond.
</P>
<P>
   What I have is a goldfish pond in the back yard, brick and
cement, about four feet across and maybe a foot deep. It's home for
six or eight koi, and nice-sized ones at that, some half as big as
a man's palm.
</P>
<P>
   I'd been doing what I could for them, most days bringing home a
bag or two of ice from the convenience store, dumping it in the
fish pond to help the koi to cool off.
</P>
<P>
   None has gone belly-up yet, though for a fact, I imagine they'd
like to evacuate if they could.
</P>
<P>
   While I was getting a haircut, the phone rang. One of the
barbers picked up the receiver, said hello and then after a moment
hung up without saying anything else.
</P>
<P>
   It had been another recorded message, he said, this one advising
that it was now safe to return to your place of business or
residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonder how they knew we were still here to answer the phone,''
he said. Everybody thought about that for awhile.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. When I left the barbershop, I was relieved to see my car
hadn't been burned up in the parking lot after all. Not that the
seats didn't feel like they were on fire.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; Website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
