<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 09:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5967 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-TIRE-LIABILITY-L     09-08 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-TIRE-LIABILITY-LEVY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFETY CAN COST TOO MUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Friday, Sept. 8, and thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By ROBERT A. LEVY    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After 88 deaths and who knows how many serious
injuries, the temptation is almost irresistible to bring the boot
of government down more heavily on the neck of Firestone and, by
extension, other tire makers and auto-related industries. But the
current environment _ perhaps best characterized as near-hysteria _
is precisely the wrong one in which to be formulating new
regulations. We need to step back and take a dispassionate look at
both the pluses and minuses of granting the federal government yet
more authority in this area.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that Firestone and Ford should escape
punishment if the evidence supports civil liability or even
criminal sanctions. The government regulations that are in place
must be enforced, along with common law and statutory remedies.
</P>
<P>
   The broader question, however, is what sort of regime should be
put in place for the next safety-related problem.
</P>
<P>
   Every year 40,000 Americans die in auto-related accidents. We
could eliminate that horrific cost overnight by banning
automobiles, or requiring every car to have the safety features of
a tank, or mandating that cars be designed to travel no faster than
five miles an hour. Of course, those remedies all sound silly. We
have decided that the benefits of driving today's cars at today's
speeds outweigh the costs _ enormous though they are _ of 40,000
annual deaths.
</P>
<P>
   That utilitarian calculus is applied every day in various
contexts. Sometimes we analyze the cost-benefit tradeoffs
explicitly; other times, as in the example of auto deaths, only
implicitly. Either way, there's nothing misguided or immoral about
it.
</P>
<P>
   In the Firestone case, there are two important guideposts.
</P>
<P>
   First, will any particular proposed new rule lead to unintended,
adverse consequences? Government regulation frequently imposes
hidden and substantial costs on industry and, indirectly, on
consumers. In part, that's because bureaucrats operate with
perverse incentives. If a product is not recalled and injuries
occur, government will inevitably be blamed. If there is a recall
when there was really little threat to safety, however, the
regulators are not likely to be criticized. The likely result is
more recalls and regulations than are justified by the facts _ and
greater costs in both higher prices and lost opportunities as good
products are kept off the market.
</P>
<P>
   Second, are there more cost-effective, less intrusive means of
attaining the desired objectives? Government regulation is not the
only safeguard for consumers against corporate negligence or
corruption. The market itself provides a protection: who will now
buy Firestone products, unless they can be proved safe? The courts
provide another. Not only Firestone, but its parent company and
Ford as well, can be sued for compensatory and maybe punitive
damages. Then there are private certifying organizations, like
Consumers Union and Underwriters Laboratory, which would
undoubtedly take on a greater role if government were not involved.
</P>
<P>
   In any situation where government is tempted to step in, there
is also the deeper question of whether federal intrusion is even
authorized by the Constitution. In the Firestone case, the answer
is clearly yes. Since tires are integrally related to maintaining
the free flow of commerce among the states, Congress can pass
appropriate legislation under the Commerce Clause _ though arguably
rules emanating from an administrative agency like the National
Highway Transportation Safety Administration are a usurpation of
Congress' legislative powers. Safety regulations applied to many
other products, however, like guns and drugs, are justified only by
a tortured reading of the Commerce Clause.
</P>
<P>
   In the Firestone case, as in every other, the reflexive lurch
toward more government as the solution might satisfy our desire to
do something, but we must also consider whether the action we
contemplate will be fair and will advance our larger goals.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Levy is senior fellow in constitutional studies at
the Cato Institute.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a `separate-buy' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
