<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 09:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5968 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-DEBATES-PLISSNER     09-08 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-DEBATES-PLISSNER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POINT ON THE DEBATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Friday, Sept. 8, and thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By MARTIN J. PLISSNER    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the current argument about sponsorship of this
year's presidential debates, too little attention has been paid to
the cramped schedule imposed by the fall calendar of televised
sports events. Nobody wants to force Americans to choose between
these valuable debates, on the one hand, and ``Monday Night
Football,'' the World Series or the Olympic Games on the other.
</P>
<P>
   To schedule around these events, as well as avoiding the final
week of the campaign, the Commission on Presidential Debates chose
four dates within a narrow two-week window in early and
mid-October. These dates were not, to be sure, necessarily set in
stone. In the past, the major party presidential candidates have
routinely played fast and loose with the original dates chosen by
the commission, as well as most other details of the debates, and
negotiated changes between themselves.
</P>
<P>
   While the motivation, timing and political wisdom of the
sweeping proposal by George W. Bush has been soundly attacked with
reason, he does have a point in trying to schedule a debate before
the Olympics start next Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The country is ready for debates now. The candidates should be,
too. For months, they have been talking past each other on the
stump and at their summer conventions, sending out unchallenged
promises and claims to a public that is for the most part
inattentive.
</P>
<P>
   Between now and Election Day, the candidates will hurl a couple
of hundred million dollars or so worth of 30-second spots at each
other. This will be harder for people to escape but won't be any
more enlightening. It would be good to have the candidates engage
each other directly and starting now, rather than three weeks from
now, so the country can watch and make some judgments.
</P>
<P>
   In his curt dismissal of Bush's proposal for a debate next week,
Al Gore (along with, naturally, the commission) has pointed out
that only NBC would carry it, while all the broadcast networks have
agreed to carry the prime-time debates proposed by the commission.
Those so-called prime-time ``roadblocks'' by the broadcast
networks, supposedly reserving uniform times for the commission's
debates, may turn out, however, to be a bit less than advertised.
Major League playoff games are scheduled on NBC during two of the
commission's debates, and on Fox on the other two nights.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is the commission's venue: confrontations in
public auditoriums at colleges. These schools (like convention
cities) have posted significant sums of money for the privilege of
playing host. The commission's commitments to them, and the
elaborate arrangements required for these live public events, were
set in place well before either nominee was picked. Now that there
are nominees who are entitled to a say in the matter, it is not
easy to make adjustments _ though, when pressed in the past, the
commission always has.
</P>
<P>
   NBC doesn't have these logistical problems. It can simply light
up a studio on Tuesday night, set up a table for the vice
president, the governor and Tim Russert _ and go. As it happens,
the commission itself did promise this sort of format (minus
Russert) for one of its own debates.
</P>
<P>
   In the NBC-sponsored debate, to be sure, the national television
audience in the many, many millions would not have the benefit of
two or three thousand on-site viewers supplied by the commission,
all of whom have to be shushed into behaving themselves, including
audience plants supplied by campaign tacticians. There would be
nothing to watch or listen to but the candidates and the moderator.
</P>
<P>
   The unadorned studio setting worked (with a few extra reporters)
for John Kennedy and Richard Nixon in what remains the gold
standard for presidential debates. Why not give it a try? It might
start a trend.
</P>
<P>
   (Martin J. Plissner is the former executive political director
of CBS News. He is the author of ``The Control Room: How Television
Calls the Shots in Presidential Elections.'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a `separate-buy' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
