<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GAY-SPEECH (San Francisco) _ Schoolteacher Robert Downs thinks
homosexuality is immoral, so he was unhappy when his district
declared a Gay and Lesbian Awareness Month each June, and even
unhappier when colleagues posted rainbow flags and gay pride
materials on school bulletin boards. Downs put up his own bulletin
board in a hallway near his classroom and posted pictures of a
traditional family, the text of a federal law against same-sex
marriage and the Supreme Court ruling against sodomy _ and a
biblical passage calling homosexuality ``detestable.'' The
principal ordered him to stop, saying he was violating not only the
district's policy but also its curriculum that promoted tolerance
and diversity. On Thursday, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
said the school hadn't violated Downs' freedom of speech. By BOB
EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-MARIJUANA (San Francisco) _ A federal judge says it's
none of the government's business if California doctors tell
seriously ill patients that marijuana might ease their pain. The
federal law that declares marijuana a dangerous drug, with no
accepted medical use, does not authorize the government to punish
doctors for ``voicing their professional opinions based on their
best medical judgment,'' U.S. District Judge William Alsup said. By
BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VIETNAM (San Francisco) _ President Clinton, who in July
signed a sweeping trade pact to normalize relations with Vietnam
for the first time since the fall of Saigon, has expressed interest
in visiting the communist country in mid-November. San Francisco
Mayor Willie Brown hopes to be invited on such a trip. By ILENE
LELCHUK.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SELENA (San Antonio) _ ``Selena Forever,'' the Broadway-style
musical whose national tour was canceled in May for financial
difficulties, is coming back to the stage. Producers say the
musical will relaunch Nov. 15 at Los Angeles' Doolittle Theater for
a six-week run. By RAMIRO BURR.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-NURSE (Undated) _ With ``Nurse Betty,'' director
Neil LaBute has made a film that treads a strange, looping path
between ruthlessness and hope: It's a fable, yes, but it's a fable
that invokes Doris Day while it's fixing to bump off a couple of
major characters. Innocence weds barbarity at one weird altar. By
AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-WATCHER (Undated) _ Hot off his stint as a
quarterback in the dismal ``The Replacements,'' Keanu Reeves suits
up for the somehow worse ``The Watcher,'' this time as a
lady-killer let loose on the streets of Chicago. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-SOLOMON (Undated) _ Did you hear the one about the
rabbi who told his flock that in order to really understand life in
1911 Wales its members should try reading Dickens? If that's not
funny, it at least reveals that the rabbi isn't watching the same
movie we are. Yes, Paul Morrison's ``Solomon and Gaenor,'' set in a
Welsh mining town, has the look of a Dickensian bowl of cold gruel.
But the film is in the key of ``Romeo and Juliet,'' and it's a
one-note tune. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-LOVE-SEX (Undated) _ Famke Janssen, who squeezed men
to death with her legs as a villain in the James Bond flick
``Goldeneye,'' merely talks them to death in ``Love &AMP; Sex.'' By G.
ALLEN JOHNSON.
</P>
<P>
   TV-REVIEW-GIRLFRIENDS (Undated) _ It's safe to assume that UPN's
surprisingly good new comedy, ``Girlfriends'' will be called ``the
black `Sex and the City.''' It's almost impossible to ignore the
similarities _ four women trying to get their love lives in order
while living in a big city, this time Los Angeles. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   DR.-LAURA (San Francisco) _ Protests are expected outside
television stations that are scheduled to carry the premier of
``Dr. Laura,'' the talk show hosted by Laura Schlessinger. Groups
opposed to the sharp-tongued, conservative counselor's anti-gay
rhetoric have been pressuring advertisers not to sponsor the
program, which is being distributed by Paramount Television. By
CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LIGHTNING-PROTECTION (Albany, N.Y.) _ Lightning strikes
somewhere on Earth every second and it can and does strike the same
place twice _ it hits the Empire State Building at least 25 times a
year. Lightning causes billions of dollars in property damage, but
state-of-the-art protection systems can help save lives and
property. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS. (For release Sunday, Sept.
10.)
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Houston) _ Questions and answers on a variety of
gardening topics. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ Each night Ivan Williams relaxes,
closes his eyes and dreams. He calls it visualization, but when
you're trying to visualize what he is, maybe dreaming is more
accurate. He is the kickoff returner for the University of Texas, a
team that hasn't returned a kickoff for a touchdown in 254 games,
the longest streak in the nation. By MARK WANGRIN.
</P>
