<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Landmark birthdays add up
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When my son turned nine this summer, it did not seem, at first
blush, like a landmark birthday.
</P>
<P>
   But one night, when he was shooting baskets on a Fisher-Price
hoop hiked to the highest notch, it struck me:
</P>
<P>
   He's halfway there.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway between crib and college.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway between Mom and Dad Are the Center of the Universe and
Mom and Dad Are a Pimple on my Social Universe.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway between ``I love you past Pluto'' and ``Give me my
space.''
</P>
<P>
   It also strikes me that I don't want him to be halfway there.
I'd like him to stick around the house for another 20 years or so.
</P>
<P>
   This is why God created adolescence, or so the theory goes, to
make that inevitable separation less painful.
</P>
<P>
   And for many parents, that's the way it works. Some parents
count the days until their children move out of the house and into
their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   For others, the empty nest feels only ... empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bittersweet,'' said our neighbor Jerry Shultz, whose
second-eldest, Addie, our babysitter and honorary daughter, is
entering Wright State University next week. ``It seems as if I
should still be carrying her on my shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   Shultz was 36 and ``completely undomesticated'' when he married,
only to become, in short order, the primary caretaker of four
children. ``They're my whole life now,'' Shultz marvels. ``I don't
know what I'd do without them.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, he has been wondering what he'll do without Addie, who
graduated in June as valedictorian at Colonel White High School:
``She laughs at my jokes.'' He wonders what happened to the
4-year-old who begged to enter preschool and ``who soaked
everything up like a sponge.''
</P>
<P>
   Catch Roberta Longfellow on a good day, and she won't get the
least bit weepy about the fact that her daughter, Jessica Larson,
started Miami University this fall.
</P>
<P>
   But the weekend after she dropped Jessie off in Oxford,
Longfellow confesses, ``I cried at the drop of a hat. Riding home
without her, I was sobbing.''
</P>
<P>
   Longfellow and her husband, David Larson, had raised Jessie, who
graduated as co-valedictorian at Stivers High School, to be a
``strong, independent female, able to make good decisions about her
life and to feel confident in her abilities,'' she said. ``Our
basic feeling is that we've done our job.''
</P>
<P>
   Longfellow will keep plenty busy with church, work, and raising
son Christian, a ninth-grader at Stivers. ``But I just miss her.
There's a big empty spot in our household. I hear cars driving down
our street, and I think it's Jessie coming home. Meals together are
important to us, and it's still very obvious she's missing.''
</P>
<P>
   As we rush our children out the door in the morning, we're
tempted to want to to rush them into young adulthood and
independence. What bliss to throw out the Rolodex file of
babysitters, to be able to watch a play without watching the clock.
What bliss, not to tell the tardy monitor why you're running late
this time.
</P>
<P>
   We find ourselves wishing our children were older, more
independent, without realizing that every day wished away brings us
closer to that inevitable day when they leave home.
</P>
<P>
   Ready or not, we're halfway there.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Mary McCarty by e-mail at marymccarty(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
