<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Globetrotting has a lot going for it
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since becoming a reluctant but seasoned tourist, I'm often
called on to advise friends, and even a few strangers, on the ins
and outs of international travel.
</P>
<P>
   One question I get is, ``How much will it cost?'' Since airlines
cut out food and started packing people like sardines in
wide-bodied jets, you can visit London and Paris for less than
you'd spend in a day at Six Flags or a night watching the Braves in
Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, who has never met a destination she didn't like, is
always finding bargain trips she can't afford to pass up. I'm
hard-pressed to argue. Two weeks halfway around the world can
actually be cheaper than staying home. If we're stuck on a
riverboat on the Nile, she can't go shopping at Lenox or Phipps, or
have her hair done at a pricey salon in Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't buy a lot of souvenirs, you can see a large part of
the world on a single Social Security check. Even souvenirs aren't
overly expensive unless you are married to a spouse who thinks you
can fit a large rug into an overhead bin that filled up 15 minutes
before your boarding call. In every country we've visited we've
found a good supply of reasonably priced native items made in
China.
</P>
<P>
   We meet interesting people. During a routine three-hour delay at
Kennedy Airport in New York when we were headed for China I got
into a conversation with a security officer from the Bronx. ``You
won't have a language problem in China,'' he informed me. ``They
all speak English over there.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a matter of fact,'' he said, ``everybody in the world
speaks English, because that's what God speaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Not knowing of anyone, including Billy Graham, who has had a
face-to-face conversation with God in recent times, I asked the
officer how he knew that English is God's chosen language.
</P>
<P>
   ``If God doesn't speak English,'' he answered, ``why did he
write the Bible in English?''
</P>
<P>
   While we were floating down the Yangtze River the tour guide
explained details of the big dam the Chinese are building. When he
told us the water level would rise something like 200 feet behind
the dam, a gentleman from New Jersey raised his hand. ``How much
will it rise in front of the dam?'' he asked. (How did we lose the
war?)
</P>
<P>
   One of my biggest challenges in international travel is trying
to persuade my wife not to stuff enough into her suitcase to stock
the third floor at Rich's. She has left a trail of ruptured
bellhops and porters all over Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   With the quality of deodorants on the market today, I don't see
any need to carry more than a couple of changes. But I never win
that battle, despite a chronically strained back that requires
regular chiropractic adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   My job is lift, tote and fetch. Find the ice machine, watch the
bags while she goes to the restroom, find whatever plug she needs
to work the hair dryer, carry the souvenirs she takes home to store
in the attic, make Persian rugs fit into overhead bins on
airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Except for all that, she says, I'd be welcome to stay home and
look after my garden. The only good news I have to pass on in this
area is a rumor that the Teamsters Union is seriously considering a
drive to organize elderly male tourists with chronically strained
backs.
</P>
<P>
   If you're planning an overseas trip with a tour group, I advise
practicing dinner converstion before departure. For example, if you
are talking with table companions about London, and you have been
there only once, be sure to say: ``The last time we were in London
....'' Or, ``The first time we were in London ....''
</P>
<P>
   If you've been to Paris only two times, say: ``We've only been
to Paris twice.'' Be careful to emphasize ``only,'' as if you've
been everywhere else in the world 10 or 12 times. By carefully
phrasing, you can be truthful and still pass yourself off as a
prolific world traveler, even if your only previous trip was a
two-night cruise to Nassau.
</P>
<P>
   A few simple preparations make international travel more
enjoyable. I advise losing at least 10 pounds before leaving home;
otherwise you won't be able to squeeze into the child-size airplane
seat for the trip home. Enroll in a weightlifting program designed
to strengthen back muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Either buy more deodorant or get a bigger suitcase. Practice
water discipline in case you get caught on a bus with a 26-year-old
tour director who never needs a pit stop. Caution yourself not to
order wine with a screw cap when you're in France. Unless you don't
mind people thinking you're from either Newark or Cleveland, don't
wear black wing-tip shoes with white socks and chartreuse walking
shorts.
</P>
<P>
   Despite obvious hazards, international travel has advantages.
You don't have to trim shrubbery or carry out garbage, and it's a
great way to avoid estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
