 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Saturday, September 9 and Sunday,
September 10, 2000 are moving today to clients of the New York
Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ I had stopped by the barbershop,
mainly to catch up on the news. Not that I didn't already know what
everybody's talking about. Everybody's talking about the weather.
(Murray, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ T.S. Eliot wrote that April was the cruelest
month. He never visited Texas in August. One joke going around is
that the devil was thinking about moving hell to Texas but decided
it was too hot. (Borders, Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel)
MOVEDLATHAM-COLUMN _ MARSHALL, Texas _ You hear a great deal about
global warming these days. Some people say it threatens life on
Earth, others say it is nothing but a myth. Me, I don't know
anything about that either way.
</P>
<P>
   What I do know about is global cooling. Now there is something
that has really changed our lives over the last 40 years. (Latham,
Longview News Journal)
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ Protection of minority views is essential to
our democracy. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ Since becoming a reluctant
but seasoned tourist, I'm often called on to advise friends, and
even a few strangers, on the ins and outs of international travel.
(Jim Minter is a former editor of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ When my son turned nine this summer, it did not
seem, at first blush, like a landmark birthday. But one night, when
he was shooting baskets on a Fisher-Price hoop hiked to the highest
notch, it struck me:He's halfway there. Halfway between crib and
college. Halfway between Mom and Dad Are the Center of the Universe
and Mom and Dad Are a Pimple on my Social Universe. (McCarty,
Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ George W. Bush is back in full-smirk mode now
that he's muddled the issue over presidential campaign debates. He
appears to think he has muddled it successfully, and perhaps he
has. Didn't Al Gore say he would debate Bush any time anywhere and
isn't he now, just as Bush charges, refusing to do just that?
Indeed. But Gore's rhetorical sally assumed Bush would first buy
into the debates that the presidential debate commission would set
up. After all, every candidate since 1988 had, including daddy
Bush. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.)
MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ All along I knew that Patty the Postal Lady
was not a latent killer. Patty delivers the mail to my house.
Often, we chat. Sometimes about the rock music she has bellowing
from the portable radio in her little truck, sometimes about other
things. But I never envisioned that one troubled day she would show
up back at the post office, automatic weapon in hand, and
rat-a-tat-tat a bunch of co-workers. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service.)
MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ There's bound to come a time, when modern
technology and ancient avarice converge to let the dot-coms into
the Games _ although, if the NBC brass has it way, that time may be
a long time in coming. (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox News
Service in the Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
