<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10-YEAR-OLD MACS AND OTHER ANTIQUES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I have been using a Macintosh SE/30 for the
past 10 years. My wife uses a PC with Windows 95. There are
important documents I would like to transfer to her PC. You
recently suggested inserting a PC floppy into the Mac to copy the
files. I get two choices when I try: eject or initialize.
</P>
<P>
   _ MacStuck
</P>
<P>
   DEAR MACSTUCK: You know, you might be able to sell a Mac that
old to an Apple collector and make enough to buy a new one. Anybody
want to buy my IIe? I could use some cash, too.
</P>
<P>
   The original SEs _ tiny little Macs with tiny little monitors _
had 800-megabyte floppy drives. If that's what you've got, forget
about flipping floppies with a PC: the hardware just won't do the
job. The SE/30s were supposed to come with Apple's Superdrive,
which could read 1.44-megabyte Mac and PC disks as well as the
older Mac floppies. If you didn't get the Superdrive, you should
take your Mac right back to the store and get your money back.
That's assuming your time machine is still in working order.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe your system files are too old to fully support the
Superdrive's capabilities. There's one other trick you might try,
though. Assuming you really are using high-density, 1.44MB disks on
the SE, you can get software that will let your PC read them. Just
go to some shareware site like www.hotfiles.com and search for
``Mac disk.''
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Is there any way I can have moving icons on my
desktop?
</P>
<P>
   _ Poetry in Motion
</P>
<P>
   DEAR POETRY: Yes. Drink heavily before using your computer.
You'd be surprised how much those little icons can move around.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I want to put my old PC up for sale. Microsoft
Word 97 shows my name as the licensee in the opening window. How
can I delete or change that? Also, is my name somewhere in Windows
95, and can I delete it?
</P>
<P>
   _ Anonymous
</P>
<P>
   DEAR ANON: The Microsoft Office products are tricky. When first
installed, they stash your name deep in the Windows Registry in
hexadecimal code, the language of geeks. Even if you find the right
Registry key, you have to figure out how to spell the name in hex,
plus leave a null character after each letter. More trouble than
it's worth.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you uninstall the program, the Registry key doesn't
always get deleted, and your name still winds up on the program
after reinstalling. Try this: After uninstalling, run Regedit, the
Registry editor. Look for a folder called ``Office,'' which is
probably in
HKEY(underscore)CURRENT(underscore)USER/Software/Microsoft, and
delete it. Now reinstall Word with the new name.
</P>
<P>
   It's easier to strip your name from Win95. While in Regedit, do
a search (Control-F) for your name, then edit any key where it
shows up.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I am greatly relieved to finally discover
through your sleuthing and insightful reporting that the first 23
years of my life were indeed a myth, and that the state of ``Ohio''
is just an urban legend. I am heartened that I did not grow up in
``the mistake on the lake'' and that Crosby, Stills and Nash sang
about ``four dead'' in ``Idaho.'' Many thanks for placing my mind
at ease.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nohio
</P>
<P>
   DEAR NO: Idaho? Hmmm. No ``Idaho'' on my map. Are you trying to
start another hoax?
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay welcomes questions from
all 42 states as well as the rest of the world. Write him at
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com (snail-mail: Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax: (817)
390-7257. In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst, editorial
systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
