<HEADER>
A6097 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     09-08 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS BUSH FEELING HEAT FROM GORE?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BILL THOMPSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It looked bad, I know. Just as George W. Bush's double-digit
leads in the public-opinion polls were going up in smoke, I went on
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Was I bailing out on my presidential candidate? Was I struck
speechless by Al Gore's sudden surge? Was I searching the planet
for some island paradise where the natives never heard of the
Gallup Poll?
</P>
<P>
   None of the above, actually.
</P>
<P>
   My visit to the sidelines at a moment when the quadrennial
political game was finally getting itself cranked up was prompted
not by the Gore heat _ as a Democratic friend suggested _ but by
the suffocating heat wave that parched the Lone Star landscape and
turned summer-sensitive Texans into withering idiots.
</P>
<P>
   Having made it almost to the end of August without indulging
myself in a column that whined about the heat, I decided to lay low
until the moderating breezes of September worked their magic on the
summer of 2000. Imagine my dismay when the second-to-last day of my
vacation _ Labor Day, Sept. 4 _ delivered a brain-scorching
temperature of 111 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   I probably deserved it, to be perfectly honest. I'd spent the
previous few weeks bragging about how well I'd withstood my 14th
Texas summer, rarely complaining out loud and never once calling a
travel agent to inquire about airfares to Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Which just goes to show: You don't want to get smug about
surviving a Texas summer until, oh, Thanksgiving or thereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Overconfidence can be hazardous to your health.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to Bush, Gore and the 2000 presidential
race that appears to be so close that most polls put the candidates
within a few percentage points of each other _ within the margin of
error, in other words.
</P>
<P>
   Most pundits _ and the candidates, for that matter _ had
cautioned all along that the race would tighten by Labor Day and
that summer polls showing Bush with a comfortable lead should be
viewed with considerable skepticism. Still, it was tempting for
Bush-backers to imagine their guy cruising to victory and maybe
even racking up landslide-like vote totals on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   It could still happen, of course. The Gore turnaround was so
abrupt, so startling; it seems reasonable to wonder if it's real.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's new-found momentum was produced in large part by a
51-minute speech and a three-second kiss at the Democratic National
Convention. Couldn't it ebb just as quickly?
</P>
<P>
   Gore is not the sort of candidate who is prone to
self-destruction, however. Bush must find a way to regain the
initiative. And he is entirely capable of doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats _ and certain Republicans, come to think of it _ seem
to be laboring under the impression that Bush is a one-dimensional
front-runner who can't handle adversity. Have they already
forgotten his spectacular comeback in the Republican primaries
after early losses to John McCain?
</P>
<P>
   Have they forgotten _ or maybe they never knew _ about his 1994
underdog campaign for governor of Texas? Bush trailed the
incumbent, Ann Richards, from the beginning until darn near the end
of that race, but he won the election by a comfortable margin.
</P>
<P>
   Bush can come from behind if he has to; he doesn't need the lead
to run his race.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Bush-haters who e-mails me incessantly compared this
presidential campaign to a horse race in which the front-runner
runs too fast, too early, and finds himself outfinished at the
wire.
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough. But as aficionados of the sport of kings can tell
you, a resourceful thoroughbred can surrender the lead briefly,
then surge back to the front and win going away.
</P>
<P>
   A pollster friend of mine warned me to ignore those summer polls
showing Bush in front by daylight _ and he's warning me now to
ignore the polls showing Bush behind. The best bet at this stage of
the race: The polls will fluctuate wildly, at least for a while.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, Bush will win. He's the best candidate. He
has the best vision for the nation's future. The voters are smart
enough to figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
