<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6114 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-DR.-LAURA-HNS &LR;      09-08 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DR.-LAURA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `DR. LAURA' TO GO ON THE AIR AMID PROTESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CAROL NESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Conservative radio host Laura Schlessinger makes
her television debut Monday in what easily could prove a test of
the premise that there is no such thing as bad publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Groups opposed to the sharp-tongued, conservative counselor's
anti-gay rhetoric have been pressuring advertisers not to sponsor
the program, which is being distributed by Paramount Television,
and urging viewers to boycott the program.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount has declined to divulge its corporate sponsors.
Several, including heavyweights Procter &AMP; Gamble, Sears and
American Express, have pulled out in a glare of unwanted consumer
pressure pumped up by the gay community.
</P>
<P>
   Other advertisers reportedly dropped Schlessinger's hugely
popular radio talk show.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the protest against the TV program is Stopdrlaura.com
(www.stopdrlaura.com). The site was started after the San
Francisco-based Horizons Foundation, which gives money to gay
causes, and allies launched a campaign to get Schlessinger to
moderate what she tells her 18 million listeners about
homosexuality and to try to press Paramount, TV stations and
corporate advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dr. Laura phenomenon is a milestone in terms of
publicizing disapproval of anti-gay bigotry,'' said Peter Teague,
executive director of the Horizons Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The publicity has not stopped the show from being snapped up by
stations covering almost 98 percent of U.S. viewers, according to
Daniella Cracknell, the publicist for the show.
</P>
<P>
   Among those are CBS affiliate KPIX-TV in San Francisco. Teague
and others plan to protest outside the station's studios on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to let KPIX know we are still really angry they
decided to run this show,'' said Ryan Clary, a protest organizer.
``We don't think they had to do it. We want to let them know we
intend to monitor the show.''
</P>
<P>
   KPIX station manager Jerry Eaton said he might not have chosen
the show if he had known beforehand about some of Schlessinger's
anti-gay comments.
</P>
<P>
   Schlessinger, 53, has called homosexuals ``biological errors''
and homosexuality a ``deviant sexual orientation,'' spoken
favorably of counseling that purports to ``cure'' gayness, and
inveighed against child-rearing and marriage by homosexuals and
lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   Since her move into the TV realm has stirred up so much
controversy, Schlessinger has defended her views as moral
statements of her beliefs as a convert to Orthodox Judaism and said
she never intended to hurt anyone.
</P>
<P>
   She said she is not anti-gay or a bigot, and that opposing equal
status for homosexuals is not homophobia.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount has assured its critics that Schlessinger's show will
feature people of all viewpoints on social issues.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco protest is one of more than two dozen
scheduled to take place around the country over the weekend and
Monday. The biggest is expected to be Monday outside the Paramount
studios in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney Mintz, the rabbi of Temple Emanu-El in San Francisco,
said she would be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to speak out as a Jew and to say as a rabbi that she
doesn't represent what all Jews think about homosexuality,'' Mintz
said. ``It's not all right to be homophobic, and it's not all right
for corporate sponsors to put their money into something that's
homophobic. We are asking people to pull their sponsorship and
Paramount not to sponsor the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Paramount has not released tapes of the show in advance, but
press materials show the first week's topics will cover classic Dr.
Laura ground: teens and drugs, affairs, working mothers,
pornography.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
