<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 12:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6116 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-LIGHTNING-PROTECTION-     09-08 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIGHTNING-PROTECTION-$ADV10-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PROTECT YOUR HOME AGAINST LIGHTNING STRIKES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Sept. 10)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A bolt of lightning packs a powerful wallop. It
can explode brick and concrete and surge through electrical
systems, damaging computer equipment, communication lines and
robotics. It can cause a fire in an instant.
</P>
<P>
   Lightning causes billions of dollars in property damage each
year.
</P>
<P>
   Lightning strikes somewhere on Earth every second, according to
the Lightning Protection Institute in Arlington Heights, Ill.
Although lightning is unpredictable, it can and does strike the
same place twice. It hits the Empire State Building at least 25
times a year.
</P>
<P>
   State-of-the-art lightning protection systems can help protect
lives and property.
</P>
<P>
   A lightning protection system is designed to control or redirect
a lightning strike on a specified path. Instead of attracting or
preventing a strike, it provides a path for the electrical current
to travel to the ground safely, and without returning up.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the size and construction of your home, lightning
protection installation costs approximately $1,200 to $6,000 or
more. A job may take one to two days.
</P>
<P>
   Systems should be installed by a lightning protection specialist
approved by the Lightning Protection Institute and Underwriters
Laboratories. Be sure to get a Master Label from your installer to
prove that the job meets code requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a one-time job,'' said Dennis Crowley, owner of
Crowley Lightning Protection in Auburn, N.Y. Air terminals (the
industry term for lightning rods) should be placed less than 20
feet apart and should be installed on the roof, chimneys and vents.
They should also be on dormers if they are not protected by a
higher ridge on the roof.
</P>
<P>
   Liz Cooper, owner of Associated Lightning Rod Co., in Millerton,
N.Y., said that the installation is also bonded to metallic objects
such as oil and gas lines, heating ducts, electric, water pipes,
steel I-beams in the basement, gutters and antennae.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should have your lightning protection system inspected
every five years, especially if you've had any work done on the
house,'' Cooper said. ``The inspection service is usually free.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6122 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ANTITRUST-$ADV10-1STL     09-08 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTITRUST-$ADV10-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AOL MERGER SCRUTINY HERALDS A NEW APPROACH TO ANTITRUST
 &HT;    Eds: Adjust 8th graf to fix syntax.
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, Sept. 17.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This month, antitrust regulators in the United
States and Europe are grilling executives of Time Warner Inc. and
America Online Inc. about their proposed merger.
</P>
<P>
   But the trust-busters' aggressive stance has left merger
supporters scratching their heads. They point out that AOL, an
online service provider, and Time Warner, a media company, aren't
even in the same business.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my view, I don't think there are any regulatory issues,''
Time Warner Chairman Gerald Levin said at a conference last month.
``There are no business overlaps'' between the companies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Given that regulators now routinely approve huge mergers among
nearly identical companies, such as Exxon and Mobil, why pick on
two corporations that operate in different industries?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because this isn't a classic antitrust case _ it's really a
New Economy issue,'' said Bill Whyman, president of The Precursor
Group Inc., a Washington-based firm that does research on Internet
companies and strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups and other merger opponents say that if
governments sit back now, large companies will rush forward to
seize control of both the Internet's content _ news, sports, music,
movies and the like _ and the means to deliver it, such as cable
wires.
</P>
<P>
   Their nightmare scenario: a decade from now, one or two global
behemoths will own the wires entering people's homes and use them
to shove proprietary content down consumers' throats at high
prices.
</P>
<P>
   These fears have led regulators to focus on preventing the
``leveraging'' of technologies that could inhibit competition on
the Internet, Whyman said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the European Commission, the regulatory body that
sets antitrust policy for 15 countries, took up the fight against
techno-leveraging when it summoned executives from AOL and Time
Warner to Brussels for closed-door hearings.
</P>
<P>
   A confidential report, written by the commission and leaked to
several U.S. reporters, was brutal in its assessment of the merger,
saying the companies would combine their strengths to harm
competition in the business of selling movies and music via the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, that business does not exist on any significant
scale.
</P>
<P>
   But ``the commission is of the opinion that there is an emerging
market'' for selling movies and music digitally, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the commissioners believe that soon, consumers
won't go to video-rental stores to obtain movies, they will
``download'' them directly into their television sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time Warner's vast array of video and film properties (e.g.,
CNN and Warner Bros. Film library) are ideally suited for
distribution via high-speed Internet connections.'' As a combined
company, AOL Time Warner ``could leverage Time Warner broadband
content ... to dominate the emerging high-speed Internet access
market in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Leverage, in this context, means the merged companies could
their technological advantages _ AOL's online service and Time
Warner's content _ to lift itself into a monopolistic position on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Is it fair for regulators to engage in prophylactic
trust-busting in industries not yet launched?
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Levin suggested it wasn't, but consumer groups
applaud the idea of preventing possible monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regulators' position is appropriate,'' said David Butler,
a Consumers Union spokesman in Washington. The new approach is
necessary because ``new ground is being plowed here that may very
well result in consumers receiving fewer choices and potentially
higher prices.''
</P>
<P>
   This preventive trust-busting is very different from the
traditional ways of regulating against monopolies: measuring market
share in an existing industry and discouraging companies from
growing ``horizontally'' by absorbing similar businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the classic antitrust case, Producer A has 20 percent of
the market and Producer B has 30 percent, and the regulators don't
want them to merge to get 50 percent,'' Whyman said.
</P>
<P>
   The AOL Time Warner deal does not fit that pattern. AOL provides
online services for about 24 million subscribers. Time Warner owns
cable TV systems, film companies, record companies, magazines,
Turner Broadcasting and many other media operations.
</P>
<P>
   If AOL were stretching horizontally, it would be buying another
Internet service provider, such as EarthLink Inc. But by joining
with Time Warner, it is creating a new kind of conglomerate. Levin
calls it ``the first Internet-powered media-communications company
of the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups call it scary. They want the Federal Trade
Commission (FTC) and the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) to
impose ``safeguards'' on it.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Chester, executive director of the Center for Media
Education, a nonprofit group, said regulators should insist that
AOL Time Warner offer its cable customers an unlimited number
choices among Internet service providers, provide a full array of
content without bias for its own material, and end all joint
ventures with AT&AMP;T Corp., the nation's largest cable operator, to
ensure tough competition.
</P>
<P>
   Since the deal was announced Jan. 10, executives of AOL and Time
Warner have been saying they will operate an ``open'' system that
allows competition, but consumer advocates say such assurances are
worthless without an enforceable consent decree that spells out the
three safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   European regulators are expected to issue their ruling in early
October, while U.S. regulators are not expected to rule until
November.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Federal Trade Commission, www.ftc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Federal Communications Commission, www.fcc.gov
</P>
<P>
   AOL, www.corp.aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner, www.timewarner.com
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
