<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6125 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-SELENA-HNS &LR;      09-08 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELENA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GROUP TO REVIVE CANCELED SELENA MUSICAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RAMIRO BURR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ ``Selena Forever,'' the Broadway-style musical
whose national tour was canceled in May for financial difficulties,
is coming back to the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Producers say the musical will relaunch Nov. 15 at the Doolittle
Theater in Los Angeles for a six-week run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all excited about this because we really believe in this
project,'' said Robert Trevino, one of the producers and vice
president of Promotional Management Group, which is handling
publicity and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The play tells a story that is really American. It is
wholesome, good, and it shows that hard work pays off,'' said Joe
Bradberry, chairman of the Coliseum Advisory Board. ```Selena' the
musical shows that someone who has a dream and follows that dream
can excel and achieve great things in life and can have a
tremendous influence on other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Quinn, one of the founding producers of the musical, also is
part of the new team that's relaunching the play.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, Ricardo Montalban's Nosotros Foundation has
closed on the purchase of the historic Doolittle Theater, a complex
that foundation board Chairman Jerry Velasco valued at $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're planning a grand opening gala in conjunction with the
new `Selena' musical opening, which will help raise funds for the
foundation,'' Velasco said.
</P>
<P>
   Producers said they hope to take the play to Las Vegas, San
Diego and other cities after the six-week Los Angeles run.
</P>
<P>
   Trevino said most of the cast, including Veronica Vazquez from
New York, who played the adult Selena; Danny Valdez, who played
Abraham; and Liza Ybarra from San Antonio, who played Suzette, are
returning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're negotiating with several of the other cast members and
we'll make an announcement on that soon,'' Trevino said.
</P>
<P>
   The play, which was developed and premiered at the San Antonio
Municipal Auditorium in March, toured Chicago and the Texas cities
of Corpus Christi, Dallas, El Paso and Houston before being
canceled in early May in Los Angeles. Universal Amphitheater
officials blamed sluggish ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   Producers then canceled subsequent tour dates, citing financial
setbacks as a result of the lost revenue.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Ramiro Burr's e-mail address is rburr(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
