<HEADLINE>
$ADV13 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Wednesday, Sept. 13, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard. 
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe now that the ``La Vida Loca'' craze has receded, we can
see more clearly how thoroughly our popular culture is influenced
by the Hispanic world. A snapshot will be on display tonight at 9
when CBS broadcasts ``The Latin Grammy Awards'' from the Staples
Center in Los Angeles _ an event highlighted by a tribute to the
late Tito Puente.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Estefan, Andy Garcia, Jimmy Smits and Jennifer Lopez
co-host the two-hour spectacular, and you can expect performances
by Estefan and Lopez as well as the ubiquitous Carlos Santana and
Marc Anthony. Christina Aguilera will be on hand, and 'N Sync is
set to perform a group duet with Son By Four. Keep an ear out for
Los Fabulosos Cadillacs and the Buena Vista Social Club as well.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Martin will also be in attendance, but we've heard a rumor
that his leather pants have canceled, claiming exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Olympic Soccer, local cable provider channels at 6:30: The
opening ceremony on NBC isn't until Friday, but if your local cable
company is hooked in, you can tune in to the U.S.-Czech match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' CBS at 8. I is for the Idiot housemates, who
turned down $50,000 cash last week to stay together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sole Survivor,'' Fox at 8: Part one. Billy Zane stars in this
adaptation of a Dean Koontz thriller, as a reporter who has lost
his wife and child in a plane crash. But then he meets a woman who
was on the plane, even though there were supposedly no survivors,
and we're off and running. Gloria Reuben of ``ER'' co-stars.
Conclusion airs Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Our Own Terms: Moyers on Dying,'' PBS at 9: Conclusion of
the four-part exploration of the way we die now focuses on a
hospice program.
</P>
<P>
   ``West Wing,'' NBC at 9: The president gets ready to face a
college audience, while the military searches the Iraqi desert for
a downed pilot. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopkins 24/7,'' ABC at 10: Part four of the surprisingly
successful documentary look inside a real hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law &AMP; Order,'' NBC at 10: McCoy gets involved in the case of a
political murder in Chile _ 27 years after the fact. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``AFI's 100 Years ... 100 Laughs,'' Fox Family Channel at 8:
Rerun of the three-hour American Film Institute extravaganza
honoring the funniest films ever. There may be a few occasions when
you'll have to cover the little ones' ears, but the family that
laughs together ...
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Election,'' Showtime at 8: Matthew Broderick and Reese
Witherspoon are great in this dark, R-rated 1999 comedy about a
teacher who'll go to any lengths to stop a demented overachiever
from winning a class election. Chris Klein also stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick Van Dyke Show,'' Nick at Night at 10: Mary Tyler Moore
picked her two favorite episodes _ ``My Blond-Haired Brunette'' and
``The Curious Thing About Women.'' If we remember correctly, that's
the one with the hair dye and the one with the inflatable raft.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Park,'' Comedy Central at 10: The boys cause trouble in
the schoolyard. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investigative Reports,'' A&AMP;E at 10: Host Bill Kurtis welcomes
the Olympics with a report on the use of performance-enhancing
drugs, which were already causing controversy last week at customs
down in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Corner,'' HBO at 11: Part two includes a life-changing
arrest in this graphic, compelling drama of drugs' effect on a
Baltimore family. Charles S. Dutton directed, and Khandi Alexander
tops a terrific cast. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATE NIGHT TALK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' CBS at 11:35: Sally Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight Show with Jay Leno,'' NBC at 11:35: Dennis Rodman and
movie-star-to-be Kate Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher,'' ABC at 12:05 a.m.:
Cranky old Rudy Boesch from ``Survivor'' and Billy Ray Cyrus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late, Late Show with Craig Kilborn,'' CBS at 12:35: TBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Night with Conan O'Brien,'' NBC at 12:35: TBA.
