<HEADER>
A6131 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-OPEN-WILLIAMS-BOS     09-08 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-OPEN-WILLIAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS SISTERS CHANGE THE PACE OF TENNIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Richard Williams, one daughter down and the other
facing Martina Hingis, sat on the top bench of a set of aluminum
bleachers next to a US Open practice court and uttered a tennis
truism.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't play at the same level you were at before against
the Williams sisters,'' he said. ``It's not good enough to win. I
think Lindsay (Davenport) definitely changed her level.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport stepped it up to bump last year's champion, Serena
Williams, from the tournament Wednesday night. Serena's big sister,
Venus, plays Hingis in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Understand, Richard Williams does not make himself the most
popular man in tennis with his predictions and proclamations
concerning his talented daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Holding up a sign stating, ``It's Venus' party and no one was
invited,'' during her triumphant Wimbledon final didn't go over
that well. Neither does the talk of all-Williams finals. Nor did
the talk years ago of Venus and Serena _ or would it be Serena and
Venus? _ becoming Nos. 1 and 2 in the land well before they had
done much of anything.
</P>
<P>
   Now they have done plenty.
</P>
<P>
   And no one would argue that the sisters and their powerful,
court-covering games have done just what their proud papa and
confident coach says: They have changed the way women's tennis is
played.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they raised the bar,'' said CBS analyst Mary Carillo.
``Athletically, they are such a physical presence on the court. In
order to combat that, you've got to get yourself fitter or try to
grow taller, which is hard to do. Or just understand how to break
down their game.''
</P>
<P>
   Carillo is far from alone in her assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Williamses are, especially in women's tennis, the
first players that are that aggressive, hit the ball hard, and are
such great movers,'' Davenport said. ``Everyone who is a big
hitter, like Mary (Pierce), myself, Monica, none of us can move
nearly as well as the Williamses.''
</P>
<P>
   So all have had to adjust their games. Martina Hingis is the No.
1 ranked player in the world, but she has not won a Grand Slam
event in nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
   She has to get past Venus Williams _ who took her out in three
sets in a Wimbledon quarterfinal _ to get a chance at a second US
Open title Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The power and aggressiveness of the Williams women have hurried
and harried their rivals, Hingis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, it was like everything was a little slower,'' Hingis
said. ``You had more time to prepare the shots, just mix it up
more, do this or that, slow it down, make it faster. Now you have
to hit every ball, you know, pretty hard as you can, and also in
practice you just always have to be aggressive. No more time to
play games. That's what changed the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   For the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competition's gotten higher in all aspects of the game,''
Davenport said. ``A couple of years ago Martina won, I think, like
11 tournaments and forced everybody else to get better. Now Venus,
by winning all these matches in a row, is forcing everyone to try
and beat her here. And Serena, the same last fall when she won the
Open. I think everybody's just doing a lot for women's tennis,
trying to get it better and better. And the better all the top
players can play, the closer the matches and the more the fans like
it and the better it is for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Which doesn't mean _ despite Davenport's success against Serena
Williams in the quarterfinals _ that it gets any easier when it's
time to go between the lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a number of levels, they've changed the face and the look
of women's tennis,'' Carillo said. ``You can't really compete with
them at their physical level, so somehow you have to drag them down
to your level or go up against them and what they have and figure
out a way to pick it apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Take Davenport as Exhibit A. ``Lindsay did a masterful job
against Serena,'' Carillo said. ``She took away Serena's running
game, which is exactly what you have to do. She centered the ball;
she kept hitting it right into the middle of the court and robbed
her of her running game. Serena and Venus are so dangerous on the
run. Don't let them run. You don't want to get into a track meet
with them, so make them hit and try to beat them from there.
Lindsay is capable of outhitting them.''
</P>
<P>
   Another key to Davenport's win was that she did it in two sets,
Carillo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it gets to three sets, it becomes a physical battle
again,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis is Exhibit B.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's playing much better,'' Carillo said. ``She looks
fitter and fresher mentally, I think. One year on, she understands
if she's going to beat back-to-back big babes, it's going to take
one big effort. She really has to try and husband her strength in
earlier rounds and really try to get things done in a quick and
very efficient manner, and she's done that here very quickly with a
minimum of fuss.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Hingis also met Venus Williams in the semifinals and
beat her in three sets, but then did not have enough left in the
finals for Serena.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the best thing of all for women's tennis is that not only
have the Williams sisters brought out the best in Davenport,
Hingis, and others, but the rivalries at the top _ with any luck _
should last a while.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport is 24, and Hingis turns 20 later this month. Venus is
20, and Serena's 19th birthday is this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many more years to come against the Williams
sisters,'' Hingis said after losing to Serena Williams last year at
the Open. ``It didn't happen today, but there are many more Grand
Slams and finals to come. Hopefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's match isn't a final. But it's the next best thing to
one. The winner of the Hingis-Williams match plays the winner of
the Davenport-Elena Dementieva semifinal for the title Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Carillo likes Hingis's chances against Venus.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Williams, as might be expected, thinks otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Venus comes out and plays the way Venus can play, and Venus
wants to play, no one can stop her,'' the coach/father said. ``No
one.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been correct before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1303EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6132 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-NURSE-HNS     09-08 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-NURSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `NURSE BETTY' OFFERS FOOD FOR THOUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Note cast box at end)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Greg Kinnear has found a sub-specialty in playing unctuous
louts, and in ``Nurse Betty'' he plays a beaut: the suave star of a
popular daytime soap opera who finds himself the object of a fan's
psychotic fugue. His response to this news, comical at first,
heartrending in the main, yields one of the most finely drawn
portraits of haute-dirtbag egotism to grace the screen all year.
He's a skin-crawling charm to watch.
</P>
<P>
   He's also a prime reason to view and scratch your head over
``Nurse Betty,'' as subversive and eccentric a film as mainstream
comedy ever gets. Put it in quotes: ``mainstream'' and ``comedy.''
For all its sleek marketing and blurb-ready premise, the film is
likely to madden moviegoers who expect the chuckles and pacing of a
laff-riot blockbuster, and it's just as likely to sicken anyone who
doesn't want ``Pulp Fiction''-y blood-and-guts thrown in with the
punch lines. It is beyond question a funny, thought-provoking and
skillfully made film. It is also somewhat deranged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nurse Betty'' was directed by Neil LaBute, the maestro of
verbal savagery who made ``In the Company of Men'' (cruel corporate
wonks toy with deaf woman) and ``Your Friends and Neighbors''
(cruel urban yuppies toy with each other). Both are fables of
dysfunction, exaggerated fantasies that offer long, dark gazes into
the human urge to manipulate. At best they're virtuosic; at worst
they're infuriatingly false. In real life, no one's that awful.
</P>
<P>
   And in ``Nurse Betty,'' no one is. Quite. Working from a
screenplay by short-story writer John C. Richards and music editor
James Flamberg, LaBute has made a film that treads a strange,
looping path between ruthlessness and hope: It's a fable, yes, but
it's a fable that invokes Doris Day while it's fixing to bump off a
couple of major characters. Innocence weds barbarity at one weird
altar.
</P>
<P>
   The bride in question is Betty Sizemore (played by a fittingly
ingenuous Renee Zellweger), a waitress with a boorish clod of a
husband (LaBute alumnus Aaron Eckhart, sporting a mullet) and a
serious crush on George McCord (Kinnear), who plays heart surgeon
Dr. David Ravell on a soupy daytime drama called ``A Reason to
Love.''
</P>
<P>
   When a pair of murderous reprobates scalp (yes, scalp) and
murder Betty's husband before Betty's startled eyes, she
disconnects from reality and retreats into the tidily plotted realm
of soapdom: She believes the show is real, and she believes she's
part of the action.
</P>
<P>
   To that end Betty writes a ``Dear Del'' letter to her dead
spouse (``You don't seem happy any more'') and resolves to cross
the country in search of her great soulmate, her ex-fiancee, her
one, true, virtuous and immortal love, Dr. David Ravell.
</P>
<P>
   The shady dealers, played by a never-more-elegant Morgan Freeman
and a never-more-lethal Chris Rock, track Betty in her deluded
quest and plan to kill her. What happens when they find her is less
interesting than what happens when she finds David (``Why did he
call you George?'') and even less interesting than the sly
observations on fiction, illusion and film that get spread like
bread crumbs along the way. Betty falls in love with a phantom; one
of her husband's killers falls in love with a phantom; the film
itself, a spectral medium, calls on ``Roman Holiday'' and a few
bars of ``Que Sera, Sera'' (sung not by Day but by Pink Martini) to
conjure figments of Hollywood's past.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Curtis once boasted that he knew Doris Day ``before she was
a virgin,'' and while Zellweger lacks Day's unfaltering pie-faced
perkiness, there's enough of the naif about her to give the climax
real pathos. You mourn for her loss of innocence.
</P>
<P>
   And while ``Nurse Betty'' fails to answer some of the very
questions it asks about myth and our ways of escape _ while a few
narrative gaps indicate overzealous editing _ the film does dish up
plentiful food for thought. It also dishes up Greg Kinnear as one
luscious skunk of an actor, a perfect reminder that sometimes,
reality just can't compete with our favorite mirage.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``NURSE BETTY''
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Renee Zellweger, Greg Kinnear, Chris Rock, Morgan
Freeman, Aaron Eckhart
</P>
<P>
   Director: Neil LaBute
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R, for strong language, violence, sexual situations
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 112 minutes
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
