<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIN HAS JETS UP AND RUNNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ One thing Bill Belichick and Bill Parcells
can agree on is their respect for Curtis Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Once a star in New England, Martin has spent the last three
seasons with the Jets after the Patriots made what may turn out to
be one of the worst decisions in team history _ not matching
Parcells's free agent offer to Martin after the 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   Martin signed a 6-year, $36 million deal that included a
``poison pill'' that would have exploded the Patriots' salary cap.
He received a $7.5 million bonus: a signing bonus of $4.2 million
and a $3.3 million roster bonus (the poison pill) received seven
days after signing. Nevertheless, Martin should have been wrapped
up long before he received the Jets' offer.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have never really replaced him, coming close with
Robert Edwards, who gained 1,150 yards in 1998. But they've had
nothing to compare with Martin, who has established himself as one
of the great threats in the game. He's the ingredient the Patriots
do not have to complement Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Curtis has 6,300 yards for his five-year career, so he has
averaged better than 1,200 yards per season,'' said Parcells, the
Jets director of football operations. ``I'm not saying he's the
best in the league, but I mean this with all my heart, I'll take
him over any back in the league, and you can have the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick shares that view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Curtis is a great back,'' said the Patriots coach. ``He's not
physically big but he's a strong player. Pound for pound he's
probably as strong a player as there was in '96 here and on the
Jets team the last three years. He's got great vision, good speed,
he's a very consistent player. You know he's going to give you his
absolute best every time he touches the ball. He's so tough to
bring down one on one. He can run with power and move the pile for
a couple of extra yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin has given the Jets a complete offense. ``He was a leader
by the first week he got there,'' said Belichick. ``Curtis is a
much more powerful inside runner than what we had in '97 (Adrian
Murrell). Curtis has great leadership, too. Everyone who comes into
contact with Curtis, players, coaches, fans, that guy commands a
lot of respect.
</P>
<P>
   After Martin's departure, those sentiments were expressed
throughout the Patriots' locker room. He was an inspirational
person who harbored strong religious convictions. ``I came into the
locker room one time and I swore and I found myself going up to
Curtis and apologizing,'' said former Patriots wide receiver Shawn
Jefferson. ``That's how much guys respected him.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick was part of the effort to take Martin away from the
Patriots. He feels the Jets were fortunate in taking advantage of a
salary cap maneuver that is no longer legal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the collective bargaining rules were, the restricted
free agents could get a contract and the team they were on couldn't
match,'' said Belichick. ``At that point in time you could put a
poisin pill in there. The NFL Players' Association and the
management council got together and eliminated the poison pill. Am
I surprised the Patriots couldn't match it? No, not at all. If that
contract were presented today it would have been easy to match.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick has seen both sides of Martin. He saw the Martin that
ran for 199 yards in Tuna Bowl I at Foxboro Stadium against the
Jets. His best effort against the Patriots came last Nov. 15 when
he ran for 149 yards on 31 carries. In three of his four games
against New England, he's carried for more than 100 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very creative in how they get him the ball,'' said
Patriots middle linebacker Ted Johnson, whose job it is to shut
Martin down. ``They do screens and draws. It's a conventional
offense, but they get creative with Curtis. We have to find a way
to shut him down.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick is aware of the creative ways Charlie Weis _ the
former Jets offensive coordinator _ used Martin. And under Dan
Henning, the Jets probably aren't going to be too much different.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick knows the Jets system so well he's made a point to
warn his team about becoming complacent because of his knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though there's a lot of familiarity in this game _
knowing their schemes and plays _ that goes both ways,'' said
Belichick. ``It's important we don't take things for granted. There
are going to be some curveballs and changeups thrown and we'll be
trying to caution the team on a comfort level because we run a lot
of the same plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick is worried about the volume of plays he has his team
preparing for. He says that if you prepare for 30 things, there are
still things left uncovered. ``And the volume is more than you can
cover during a week of practice,'' he said. ``The things we've run
with the Jets, you couldn't practice in a week. You have to ask
yourself, `What are you going to prepare for?' You have to select
the things you think they'll do against you. Inevitably, you're
going to miss something but hopefully you can recognize what it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' defense hopes to recognize what Martin will be
doing and try to stop a running back who never should have left New
England.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
