<HEADER>
A6139 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-MTV-AWARDS-BOS &LR;      09-08 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MTV-AWARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MTV ADS DULL THE EDGE BY SLOUCHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yes, the MTV Video Music Awards ceremony is supposed to be all
loosey goosey. It's one of the few remaining places where we can
expect insults and curses and skin (oh my!) to slip by the censors.
But still: If you were going to host MTV's signature event, the
live extravaganza that was the top-rated entertainment program in
cable history last year, the pop-cultural hotbed whose classic
moments _ Pee-wee Herman's return, Michael and Lisa Marie's kiss _
have become etched in our collective memory, wouldn't you at least
try to come up with some sharp material?
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Wayans brothers Marlon and Shawn were half-baked
hosts of the 17th annual Video Music Awards at Radio City Music
Hall. Their filmed skits were sloppy, their filler jokes were
awkward, and their introductory routine was very routine, from its
flat riffs on Firestone Tires and Juvenile's expensive teeth to the
melee at the Source Hip-Hop Music Awards, a subject they revisited
repeatedly despite the audience's indifference to it. And Marlon's
decision to take the baton from Prince and Howard Stern and become
a moon man _ and I'm not talking about MTV's astronaut statuettes _
was tragic.
</P>
<P>
   And so the evening evolved as a poorly hosted series of low
sparks and high-heeled fashion mistakes. Unexpectedly, MTV's Carson
Daly needed to step in midway to lend a firm hand and explain the
evening's most anarchic, rock 'n' roll moment: While Limp Bizkit
accepted the Best Rock Video award, the bass player for Rage
Against the Machine climbed onto a giant jungle-gym-like stage
ornament, rocked it back and forth, and refused to come down
despite urgent requests from the stage crew. It was spontaneous,
for sure, but not as cool and edgy as MTV and the Wayans wanted it
to seem.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, most of the telecast was not as edgy as MTV might have
wished, from Fred Durst's cameo onstage at the end of Christina
Aguilera's medley to what was going to be _ but then wasn't _
Christina Aguilera and Britney Spears presenting the Video of the
Year Award to their enemy, Eminem. (At the last minute, Whitney
Houston and Bobby Brown took the podium.)
</P>
<P>
   What moments helped make the show less of a bore?
</P>
<P>
   --Napster founder Sean Fanning nervously introduced Britney
Spears wearing a Metallica T-shit. Metallica, of course, is the
band leading the fight against Internet music ``pirates'' like
Napster. As Fanning spoke, the camera caught Metallica drummer Lars
Ulrich in the audience with his eyes closed, feigning sleep. Later,
a filmed Wayans sketch featured Ulrich pretending to borrow things
from the ``frat boy,'' noting, ``Sharing is only fun when its not
your stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   --The hyped GLAAD street protest of MTV's support of Eminem
exerted very little presence over the event. In fact, it was
Eminem's night, as he accepted a pair of awards, was the object of
many jokes about his hatred for teenybopper music, and delivered
the central musical performance. He began with ``The Real Slim
Shady'' on the street in front of the Radio City Music Hall with an
army of Eminem wannabes, and he ended on the stage rapping to his
critics, ``I am whatever you say I am.''
</P>
<P>
   --The lyrics to Britney Spears' hit ``Oops . . . I Did It
Again'' feature her adamently pronouncing ``I'm not that
innocent.'' thursday night, she underscored that point in a big way
during an ultra-flashy medley that found her stripping off a
pinstripe suit and dancing up a storm in a skimpy bikini top and
skin-tight peach pants.
</P>
<P>
   --Macy Gray added a new twist to her big little girl persona, as
she seemed to be a big little girl who stayed too long at the fair.
Her massive red 'fro couldn't hide the fact that she was stradling
another dimension, particularly as she presented best pop video
with LL Cool J and couldn't stop referring to a Wayans bit about
her private parts. ``I hate making videos,'' she said while
accepting Best New Artist in a Video. She's a trip.
</P>
<P>
   --Janet Jackson performed the show's opening number in a
feathery, blue-lit, ``Cats'' outfit that was as dated as her dance
moves. Jackson gets points, though, for looking head-scratchingly
and frighteningly like her brother Michael. Freakiness still rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Did someone ask who won? When it comes to the Video Music
Awards, that's far from the lead. Eminem won Best Male Video and
Video of the Year; 'N Sync won Best Pop Video, Viewer's Choice
Award; Aaliyah won Best Female Video; Blink 182 won Best Group
Video; Destiny's Child won Best R&AMP;B Video; Jennifer Lopez won Best
Dance Video; and Sisqo won Best Hip-Hop Video.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
