<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WATCHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE WATCHER' ISN'T EVEN WORTH A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE WATCHER 
Directed by: Joe Charbanic 
Screenplay by: David Elliott &AMP; Clay Ayers 
Starring: James Spader, Keanu Reeves, Marisa Tomei, Ernie Hudson,
Chris Ellis 
Running time: 93 minutes 
Rated: R (violence and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another week, another dumb serial killer movie. This one, ``The
Watcher,'' identifies Keanu Reeves's character pretty early as a
sadist who tortures women and then cuts their throats with piano
wire, but not before needling James Spader's FBI man by first
express-mailing him a glossy 8x10 of each victim. On the whole,
Reeves was more appealing as a scab quarterback in ``The
Replacements.'' The killings are his character's way of
perpetuating a homoerotic mind game with Spader's burned-out agent,
who, after having unsuccessfully pursued the killer for several
years in Los Angeles, has retreated to Chicago. There he hopes to
get over the post-traumatic stress syndrome that has turned him
into a pill-popping wreck kept from collapse by twice-weekly
sessions with shrink Marisa Tomei.
</P>
<P>
   To borrow a phrase from another Chicagoan, John Belushi, ``The
Watcher'' is a but nooooo movie. Spader's agent just wants to take
a much-needed break for a while, but nooooo. Reeves's psycho won't
leave him alone. When Spader comes out of his depression long
enough to notice that he's been sent photos of murdered Chicago
women, he realizes the killer has followed him and is up to his old
tricks. It's at this point that a merely gory and meretricious
movie turns stupid. Spader's lawman not only miraculously snaps out
of his depression once, but twice, as Tomei's therapist becomes
relegated to victim status.
</P>
<P>
   The cat-and-mouse turns into a personal duel, with stupid car
chases, an explosion, and Spader's character pointing a gun at
Reeves's killer, but behaving as if his trigger finger was
paralyzed and allowing the murderer to make a big speech. ``The
Watcher'' wastes some handsome night shots and views of Chicago.
The last time Reeves worked there, he had the great special effects
of ``The Matrix'' to fall back on. This time, the screenplay falls
on him. By the time his psycho fixes Spader's cop with his bright,
beady eyes and says, ``We're yin and yang,'' you're not at all
interested to learn who's which.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6145 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-COFFEY-BOS     09-08 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-COFFEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COFFEY PERKING UP FOR HIS 21ST SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When Paul Coffey sat home in the summer of 1999, he
made up his mind the upcoming NHL season, his 20th, would be his
last.
</P>
<P>
   He had gone through a hellish 1998-99 campaign, playing 10 games
with Chicago before being traded to Carolina, and injuries had
taken their toll.
</P>
<P>
   But Coffey's battered state took a big turn for the better last
season, and after finishing strong with the Hurricanes, the
defenseman decided to continue playing.
</P>
<P>
   He signed a two-year contract with the Bruins July 13, and the
club is hoping the 39-year-old can ignite an offensive spark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last July, I was going into that year as it being my last,''
said Coffey. ``I wasn't telling anybody, I was just going to play.
It had been too frustrating the previous year with injuries. I
wasn't able to play up to the level I like to play at. I knew
mentally what I wanted to do, what I could do. But I couldn't get
it done. My back was bugging me, I had weakness in my right leg.
But last year, when I did finally get a chance to play with
Carolina, it was a really enjoyable year.''
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of Coffey watchers in Boston before his
arrival. Coffey and former Bruins captain Ray Bourque have been
neck and neck in a number of career categories in the NHL record
book. Going into this year, Bourque is leading in goals scored by a
defenseman (403 to Coffey's 396). Coffey leads in most career
assists by a defenseman (1,131 to Bourque's 1,117) and most career
points by a defenseman (1,527 to Bourque's 1,520). In assists,
Coffey and Bourque are Nos. 2 and 3, respectively, in league
history.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Bourque closed the gap with 18 goals and 34 assists
for 52 points. Coffey, who wasn't playing at the start of the
season with the Hurricanes, ended with 11 goals and 29 assists for
40 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember a reporter said to me, some time in November, `What
do you think of the race?' '' said Coffey. ``I said, `What race?'
and he said, `Between you and Ray.' And I said, `Well, Ray is
sprinting, and I'm stuck in the mud. I ain't moving.' I wasn't
playing. It was great to see him doing well, but I was just biding
my time and hoping to get a chance to play. It turned out I did. I
just made the most of it, got myself in good shape, and things went
well.''
</P>
<P>
   When Coffey entered unrestricted free agency July 1, he
initially set his sights on a contract with the Maple Leafs. But a
chance in his hometown didn't work out, so he continued the search.
In the end, his new team turned out to be Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a total surprise,'' said Coffey. ``It threw me back in
a good way. All players say stuff, but I'm really honored to be a
member of the Bruins. An Original Six team _ Bobby Orr, Phil
Esposito _ I mean, c'mon, what do you need? It's incredible, and if
it doesn't make you feel a few years younger, nothing will.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are his eighth organization (Coffey has played for
one franchise in two different incarnations _ Hartford and
Carolina), and he said the move was a good one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tougher on my wife than it is me,'' he said. ``I come in
and all of a sudden, I've got 20 brand-new best friends. I promised
her when I was in Carolina, that was it. But she saw the fire in my
eye last year, the fun I had and the willingness to compete at the
top level and being able to do it. This opportunity came up, and I
just really enjoy the game.''
</P>
<P>
   President/general manager Harry Sinden said he wants the Bruins
to play a different style than they have in the past few years, and
he's hoping Coffey will help orchestrate a more uptempo game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty much going to play the way I play as long as it
fits in with the way Pat Burns wants me to play,'' Coffey said
Thursday during practice in Wilmington. ``He's the coach, and he
makes the decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Coffey does agree that the NHL hasn't been as exciting as it
could have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game on the whole _ never mind the Boston Bruins, the last
few years _ lacks some entertainment,'' he said. ``I'm talking from
a fan's point of view. I know there is a lot of pressure on wins
and losses, but if you're going to charge $50 or $100 a seat,
you're obligated to go out and entertain. I'm speaking as a fan. I
think the game on the whole the last few years got a little too
much, `Wait and see and let's try to win or lose this thing in the
last five minutes.' ''
</P>
<P>
   New NHL director of officiating Andy Van Hellemond has promised
a tightening of the way games are called, and Coffey said he
welcomes that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame the officials; the officials are doing a great
job,'' said Coffey. ``It's a tough job to have to do, but I think
from the players' perspective, all they want is consistency. Night
in and night on, a hold is a hold. Obstruction is obstruction. All
of a sudden, because a game is 2-0 and there's five minutes to go,
you're allowed to get away with that stuff. I don't agree with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coffey said he is raring to go and has as much fire as ever. If
he didn't, he said he wouldn't be out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money's not the motivation,'' said Coffey. ``It's just still
being able to compete, especially with the young guys, showing you
can still do it. I'm not good at anything else. You can't come off
the ice dead tired or get a punch in the head fishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing better than being elbowed in the head. At
least you know you're alive, you feel it. Or an ice bag on your
knee because you got hit with a puck. That's the mentality of us, I
guess. I'm not going to miss it when it's over, but it's kind of
nice. It lets you know why you're doing it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
