<HEADLINE>
`MNF' TALK IS MUSIC TO OHLMEYER'S EARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don Ohlmeyer, executive producer of ``Monday Night Football,''
has heard all the criticisms about the addition of Dennis Miller to
the booth. He has read all the stuff about production snafus and
on-air confusion.
</P>
<P>
   You know what? He loves it. Every single word. Oh, he doesn't
like mistakes and he readily admits his new show is still ``a work
in progress.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is proud for one simple reason: ``When was the last time
you heard anyone talk about `Monday Night Football'? '' Ohlmeyer
asked. ``When was the last time anyone quoted something from
`Monday Night' the following day?''
</P>
<P>
   If that's the barometer _ and it surely is the one Ohlmeyer is
using _ then ``Monday Night Football'' is doing just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miller is a lightning rod,'' Ohlmeyer said, likening the
comedian to the legendary Howard Cosell. ``They both generate a
visceral response from viewers. Cosell was once voted the most
popular and hated in the same poll.''
</P>
<P>
   While most attention is focused on the commentating, Ohlmeyer
said the production still needs some tinkering.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's game between St. Louis and Denver provided several
examples. Talking over a referee's call on the field is
inexcusable. Having Melissa Stark's audio problem in the middle of
a report is one of those technical glitches that shouldn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   The replay of the Rams' Az-Zahir Hakim's punt return in the
first quarter should have been shown instantly, but wasn't. To his
credit, Ohlmeyer said that as a viewer, he wants replays of great
plays shown right away. He even admits screaming at his television
when they are not.
</P>
<P>
   But he explained that in addition to the game, he has five
commercials to air each quarter as well as network promos. Ohlmeyer
also had to make the choice of showing the home crowd going crazy
over the return or a replay, which could be shown later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in television for over 30 years,'' he said. ``There
are maybe three or four shows that I have done that I don't think
needed any improvement. I'm a very tough grader.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cross fire
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CBS studio analyst Randy Cross has been following the escalating
hype generated by the Patriots-Jets game Monday night. ``If the
players get half as excited as the fans and the sportswriters, then
the game will be a struggle of Titanic proportions.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow CBS analyst Phil Simms said the Patriots are hurting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team is not as talented as it was three years ago or even
last year,'' Simms said. ``They have Bruce Armstrong coming off
major surgery and Ben Coates is gone. They lost a lot of depth,
including wide receiver Shawn Jefferson, who had a great opening
week in Atlanta. And they still have no running back. It's a team
that missed their chance at a good run and now they have to
reshuffle and reload and see if they can do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's the ideal situation there but (Bill)
Belichick liked that he was in control of personnel and not in
trouble with the salary cap. He will have some freedom in the
future to make moves and get players.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Buck's take
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joe Buck calls Saturday's 1 p.m. Yankees-Red Sox game on Fox and
readily admits he doesn't know what to make of either team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to get a handle on the Red Sox,'' Buck said.
``Outside of Pedro Martinez pitching every five days, everything
else is a crapshoot. They still have the ability to beat teams but
there has been no consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   Buck did give credit to general manager Dan Duquette and manager
Jimy Williams. ``You can't blame all of the woes on Duquette,''
Buck said. ``He has tried to bring in players. Some of them just
haven't worked out. And give credit to Williams. I know he's taken
his hits but he is one those managers that is able to get the most
out of the talent that he has. He's done a fantastic job.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are another story. ``They're beatable,'' Buck said.
``They are a much different team that bounced the Red Sox from the
playoffs last year. Who would have believed three months ago that
Roger Clemens would be their best pitcher?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sticky wickets
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a recent piece called ``Just Trying To Make A Buck-ner,'' Jim
Rome blasted Bill Buckner haters on Fox Sports Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some chowderheads are bitter that former Red Sox first baseman
Bill Buckner has a deal to sign pictures of himself letting that
ball go through his wickets in the 1986 World Series against the
Mets,'' Rome said. ``Bad enough that he cost you a World Series,
chowds. Even worse that he's going to profit from it, right? Wrong.
As if Buckner cares about you Red Sox fans. You're the ones who ran
him out of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're the ones who ruined his life. The guy had 2,715 base
hits, and all he is remembered for is not making that play. It's
his way of killing the pain and dealing with the hurt. Leave the
guy alone. Let him sign a few pics, make a few bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
