<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CMGI LOOKS TO BECOME GE OF THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are these guys management material?
</P>
<P>
   CMGI Inc., the Andover, Mass. company that became famous as a
nurturing investor of Net start-ups, took another step Thursday in
its transformation into a long-term manager of operating companies.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI unveiled plans to consolidate its 17 majority-owned
businesses around five segments of the Internet, eventually leaving
one or two companies in each of those areas, such as interactive
marketing, infrastructure, and e-business. Venture capital
investing, the company's original claim to fame, simply becomes a
sixth operating division.
</P>
<P>
   Those changes are expected to take a couple of years. The
process will involve merging businesses and selling off those that
don't mesh.
</P>
<P>
   The company's current group of 17 operating companies includes
some higher-profile names like search site AltaVista, hosting
company Navisite Inc., and Engage Inc., an online marketing
services company. It also includes many lesser-known companies like
SalesLink, AdForce, and 1stUp.com.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI has investments in dozens of other Internet companies,
which remain in the company's venture portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts universally applaud CMGI's focus on operating
companies, which it first discussed publicly in August. CMGI will
publish the financial details of each operating business line for
the first time when it announces the results of its fiscal fourth
quarter this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a logical progression,'' said Steven Frankel of Adams,
Harkness &AMP; Hill in Boston. ``If you want to be perceived as an
operating company, you must have metrics investors can understand
and measure you by.''
</P>
<P>
   CMGI executives describe the shift toward an operating mentality
as a corporate evolution that has been underway for some time. In
reality, it is a change of focus demanded by a stock market that
once drove CMGI shares to the stars and has since slammed them back
to earth with stunning force.
</P>
<P>
   The value of CMGI shares ballooned by an amazing 800-fold in
their first six years, by the end of 1999, but have lost 69 percent
so far this year. The stock slipped $3.50 to $43.19 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Making big money as an incubator of dozens of Net start-ups
requires a receptive market for new public stock offerings. Once
that door closed, there was no choice but to hunker down and focus
on running businesses for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   Chief executive David Wetherell and his top managers may have
bottom-line religion today, but those same executives were playing
up their venture investing expertise as recently as early this
year.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed that each time a hot new Net area captured the
attention of investors, CMGI announced a new $1 billion venture
firm targeted at it. Business to business? Start a $1 billion
venture fund. Infrastructure? Set up another.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI had a habit of putting its venture reputation behind the
Internet investment wave of the moment. Would those billions really
be put to work? It was hard to imagine, but since CMGI stood as the
sole limited partner, plans could eventually be scaled back.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually came Thursday. CMGI said both those new $1 billion
funds were being ``integrated'' with another outstanding venture
pool, CMGI (at)venture IV. Nobody was talking about billions. The
dollar targets are now ``open-ended.'' CMGI also said it would
forgo plans to start a big international venture fund with Hicks,
Muse, Tate &AMP; Furst, a Dallas buyout firm, and Pacific Century
Cyberworks Ltd. of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Sound abrupt? Some analysts such as Ullas Naik of First Albany
Corp. think CMGI was just doing what a Net company has to do,
adapting its talents to a market that continues to change very
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got a bad rap on the Street for being way too malleable
when it comes to their positioning, but I don't fault them at all
for that,'' said Naik. ``I can change my model as often as I want
as long as I'm doing the very best I can to maximize shareholder
value. They have to do these things.''
</P>
<P>
   Now CMGI executives will have to answer two basic questions:
What exactly do they have to manage and are they up for it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think overnight investors will become convinced this
is a successful operating company, but this was a necessary first
step,'' said analyst Safa Rashtchy of US Bancorp Piper Jaffray.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, it was difficult to determine the rate of growth
and profitability of CMGI operating companies in any detail. This
will begin to change when deeper financial disclosure becomes the
new standard.
</P>
<P>
   The CMGI goal is to be thought of as the General Electric of the
Internet, managing many different business lines to their full
potential. CMGI will find that credibility as a manager of
operating companies comes one quarter at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Welch didn't become famous overnight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
