<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S RENEWAL TIME FOR THEIR UNIFORM RIVALRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ His childhood rivalry was Dodgers-Giants, and if you
knew him you never had to guess which side he was on. He hated the
Giants. He hated them so much that, as much as he dreamed of
playing in the majors, he was willing to be a selective dream
catcher: He wanted to be drafted, but he didn't want those bums
from northern California, the Giants, to draft him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they didn't,'' Rod Beck said Thursday. ``The A's did. But
after a couple of years, the A's traded me to the Giants. Then I
was thinking, ``Oh, (expletive).' ''
</P>
<P>
   Beck understands how you might be feeling this morning, even if
some of your friends don't. You feel this way because the Yankees
are in town. Yankees-Red Sox was here before both World Wars,
before the Depression, before baseball at night, and before
``Baseball Tonight.'' It was here before instant replays and
Instant Messenger. There have been nearly 2,000 of these games _
1,845 after the teams play their next four games _ and, in most
cases, the sentiments remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   That is, after so many games in so many weeks, months, and
decades, you still can't stand them. There can never be enough
``Yankees suck'' taunts from Sox fans. There can never be enough
1918 reminders from Yankees fans. On and on it goes. It is one of
the rare debates/rivalries that never gets old. You can still get a
rise out of a Beatles fan by mentioning Yoko Ono. A Police fan will
tell you that Sting should have never left. For some, Lionel
Ritchie was never the same after leaving the Commodores. And if you
are a Yankee lover who wants to open an argument with a verbal
haymaker, you mention the Babe who left the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who commute between New York and Boston daily.
There are Bostonians living in Manhattan and New Yorkers going to
school on Commonwealth Avenue. But there are thousands of fans who
aren't interested in crossing over. They don't want to know that
Bernie Williams is a thoughtful man, a jazz head (he plays guitar)
who once performed in Greenwich Village. They don't want to know
that Darren Lewis is a thoughtful man who has attended classes in
the offseason and loves reading and talking about books.
</P>
<P>
   They don't want to know because they might like them. You can't
have that in a series like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the fans are going to be rowdy and, as a player, you
love being in games like this,'' Beck said. ``But I hope people
understand that we don't actually hate the dudes on the other team
just because they are wearing uniforms with pinstripes. We don't
generally hate the guys; we just don't like their uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think before, when you had the same guys on the same teams
every year, it was easier to develop a rivalry. Then, before free
agency, you really didn't like the other guys. It was personal.''
</P>
<P>
   Sox fans have no problem with that. They will take care of Luis
Polonia, Jose Canseco, and Roger Clemens. All they expect from Beck
and his teammates is a series split. Well, maybe three of four. OK,
let's be honest: Most folks are thinking sweep, even if the Yankees
have been playing spectacularly since July 1.
</P>
<P>
   It has been more than two months since these teams last played.
That's a lot of time for one-liner lovers to come up with material.
You will hear New Yorkers heckling Manny Alexander, a light-hitting
utilityman whose alleged ownership of steroids has left many fans
confused. You will hear Bostonians heckling David Justice, whose
long-ago divorce from the stunning Halle Berry still confuses many
of her suitors.
</P>
<P>
   Fans will practically cart the series history with them to
Fenway this weekend. Some of them will take it to New York on
Monday, when the Sox play the Yankees again in a makeup game.
Generally, Sox-Yankees would be enough entertainment for four days.
But Sox-Yankees in a pennant race is a bonus. At this time last
year, Pedro Martinez went to Yankee Stadium and threw a one-hitter,
which led to a weekend sweep of the Yankees. Now, realistically,
the Sox know they need a repeat if they want to win the American
League East.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the numbers,'' Derek Lowe said. ``If we split with
them, we're back at square one. If we want to make a move, we're
going to have to take three out of four. I'm not saying we can't do
it, but being down six games with about 20 to play means you have
to go on a 16-4, 17-3 run to have a chance to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox haven't had that type of consistency since May, when
they took over first place on Mother's Day. For most of the summer,
they have been as fluid as Boston traffic. There have been lots of
stops and starts. And whenever there has been movement in the form
of a mild win streak, the Sox have found themselves sounding like
kids in the back seat, forever asking ``are we there yet?'' and
thinking that the next win will spark The Big One.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, they began to look like the Sox you loved in May. Jose
Offerman hit two home runs, and the team scored 11 runs against the
Twins. That means there were two double-digit-run games in the same
week, following a 40 games/40 nights plague in which the Sox
couldn't reach double figures.
</P>
<P>
   It's good that they were able to do it, but they did it against
the A's and Twins. If the playoffs began today, neither of those
teams would be participating. This weekend is different. They will
have to play well against the Yankees. The well-bankrolled,
well-covered, well-despised, in-first-place Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere I've played, I've been part of some big
rivalries,'' Beck said. ``With the Giants it was the Dodgers. With
the Cubs it was the Cardinals. Now it's the Yankees. Baseball needs
these rivalries.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck, a former Giants closer, says he now roots for the team he
hated as a kid. In many ways the Us vs. Them games have similar
themes. But this is where Sox-Yankees is different: If Beck had
grown up as a Sox lover in Boston, pitched for the Yankees, and
then said he rooted for them, he would never be forgiven. It's been
like this since the days of FDR and JFK. In Sox-Yankees, you pick a
side and you keep it for life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Holley is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at holley(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
