<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6154 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-REEBOK-TURNAROUND-ART     09-08 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REEBOK-TURNAROUND-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 REBUILDING REEBOK IS GOING WELL, COMPANY CHIEF SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, Mass. _ Reebok International Ltd. may have some snazzy
sneaker lines in the pipeline and an eye-popping new headquarters
here, but after five years of disappointment, is the company's long
overdue comeback finally for real?
</P>
<P>
   Executive vice president Angel R. Martinez thinks so.
</P>
<P>
   During a headquarters event Thursday at which reporters were
given a preview of upcoming Reebok fashions in both footwear and
apparel, Martinez said, ``2001 is going to be a breakthrough year
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some outside observers also see signs for optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reebok is gaining momentum,'' said John J. Shanley, an analyst
at First Security Van Kasper.
</P>
<P>
   After downsizing and cost-cutting, after taking steps to unify
its management team and its marketing vision, there is evidence
that a company long stalled is at last moving forward.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Reebok reported that second-quarter earnings had more
than doubled. Its stock price hovers near a 52-week high, closing
Thursday at $20.75, up 19 cents. And a marketing tie-in with the
phenomenal TV show ``Survivor'' has targeted plenty of attention on
the Reebok brand the company wants to revitalize.
</P>
<P>
   According to Martinez, the latest effort to re-energize Reebok
started late last year, shortly after chairman Paul B. Fireman
stepped forward to take an expanded role at the company.
</P>
<P>
   The move came after Reebok's second-ranking executive, Carl
Yankowski, abruptly left in December to take a job elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the long lead times in the athletic footwear
industry, strategy changes decided upon today can take 12 months or
more to fully implement. So the jury is still out on Reebok's
latest turnaround effort.
</P>
<P>
   Attempting turnarounds is nothing new for Fireman, though
earlier efforts have yielded mixed results.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, for example, Fireman vowed to right Reebok within two
years. But annual profits sagged, going from $135.1 million in 1997
to $11.04 million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Annual sales also have been in a mostly downward trajectory,
sinking to $2.9 billion in 1999. At one point during this decline,
Adidas-Salomon AG eclipsed Reebok as the number two player in an
industry still dominated by Nike Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, there are signs that negative trends at Reebok are
reversing. While recent second-quarter sales fell slightly,
footwear back orders from US retailers rose 6.2 percent, a good
omen for future sales. The numbers are encouraging, said Lehman
Brothers analyst Robert Drbul.
</P>
<P>
   There's more good news.
</P>
<P>
   After some doldrums, fashion cycles now seem to be breaking
again in the direction of the sneaker companies.
</P>
<P>
   According to editor Bob McGee of the trade publication Sporting
Goods Intelligence, khaki ruled youthful fashions for much of the
late 1990s. After young consumers outfitted themselves at stores
operated by Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch Co. and Gap Inc., they wanted brown
shoes _ industry lingo for hiking boots and other casual lines _ to
match their khaki duds.
</P>
<P>
   As these all-important young consumers opted for brown shoes,
many sneakers from Nike, Reebok, and Fila Holdings SpA languished
on store shelves, according to published reports. To clear out
slow-moving merchandise, retailers offered discounts, and such
promotions helped melt away Reebok's profits.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the fashion cycle has turned again. With the Gap and
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch seemingly in less favor, there may be an
opportunity for sneaker companies to win back young customers.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok has sometimes been criticized for a less-than-sure
fashion sense. No one, however, can accuse some of next year's
lines of lacking boldness. Drawing inspiration from the Sydney
Opera House in Australia and the architecture of such cities as
Boston and Vienna, some new shoe lines feature a ``faceted'' look.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound strange _ shoes inspired by the curve, color, and
texture of buildings _ but retailers have responded positively, in
part, perhaps, because Reebok consults with them early in the
design process, something it hadn't done before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their quality and styling have improved dramatically,'' said
analyst Shanley of Reebok's new fashions.
</P>
<P>
   This new fashion sense expresses itself in collections that
incorporate a theme running through both shoes and apparel.
</P>
<P>
   If some of the footwear has a new exterior look, the inside
continues to build on Reebok's DMX cushioning technology, which
seems to have struck a chord with consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful of becoming overly dependent on Nike, many retailers may
be rooting for a Reebok comeback. Support from retailers can
translate into better displays for Reebok merchandise in stores,
and that in turn can help drive sales.
</P>
<P>
   Once, Reebok relied on legions of athletes to promote its brand,
and it was famous for changing ad agencies frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it uses only a handful of ``icon'' athletes, such as
basketball's Alan Iverson and tennis star Venus Williams. And its
presence at the upcoming Olympics will be far less than in previous
years.
</P>
<P>
   On the ad agency front, Reebok has stayed with Berlin Cameron &AMP;
Partners of New York for three years.
</P>
<P>
   A consistent marketing campaign, new well-received styles,
fashion trends that look more kindly on athletic footwear _ all
could help propel Reebok back toward the profit levels it enjoyed
in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, there may be one potential obstacle on the comeback trail:
foreign currency issues. Reebok earns a big chunk of its sales
overseas, where results can be vulnerable to the declining euro and
the British pound.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Martinez was upbeat Thursday, comparing the
progress of Reebok's comeback to the midpoint of a marathon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mile 13 in the marathon; you're feeling really good, and
you know you're going to finish the race,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
