<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EYES HAVE IT _ BUT LINE JUDGE WON'T BUDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Someday Russell Seeney can tell his grandchildren his
journey from Australia to the US Open in 2000 was worthwhile beyond
any man's most fantastic dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``There I was, kids, just me and her _ Anna Kournikova _ the
most famous tennis player, possibly the most famous woman in the
world at the time,'' he will relate. ``Just peering into each
other's eyes. It was, uh, electrifying.''
</P>
<P>
   More like electrocuting, if you want the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Seeney, an Aussie from a tennis family, was sitting there in
Arthur Ashe Stadium minding his own business when this fabulous eye
contact occurred Thursday. His business, as it happens, was keeping
his eyes on the south baseline, a judicial role, during the mixed
doubles championship match.
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova, standing at that white stripe, was serving at 3-4 in
the second set, and matters were getting tight. Arantxa Sanchez
Vicario and Jared Palmer were ahead of Kournikova and another
Russian, Max Mirnyi, two games from capturing the title, which they
eventually won, 6-4, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   So the serve went to Sanchez Vicario, who slapped a forehand
return toward the baseline, a ball too well struck for Kournikova
to reach. The ball landed . . . where?
</P>
<P>
   ``Out! It's out!'' yipped Kournikova, who expected Judge Seeney
to utter ``Out!'' as well, and extend his right arm southward. He
was mute, possibly stunned, as so many men have been by her charms.
She heard the umpire intone, ``Love-15,'' meaning point to the
Spanish-American coalition of Sanchez Vicario and Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no,'' Kournikova sternly informed the umpire. ``The
ball was out. Our point.'' She began tapping her racket on the
alleged spot, an inch behind the line, but she got no help from the
hard-faced asphalt. No tell-tale mark appeared, as it might on
clay.
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova pouted. Guys kind of like her pouty, sultry looks in
the photos that have graced every possible magazine but Field and
Stream and Soldier of Fortune. She pouted some more, then turned
her attention toward the culprit: Seeney.
</P>
<P>
   She began to stare at him, her hazel eyes blazing. He stared
back, transfixed. For a long minute, he was the envy of every male
in the congregation of 15,000. Eyeball to eyeball with Anna. What
man wouldn't melt? What hockey team wouldn't grovel and chorus,
``Out! A thousand times out! Anything you want, Anna.''
</P>
<P>
   Could Seeney deny her? Would he be so mean as to deprive her of
one teeny-weeny, itsy-bitsy point in this hour of her need?
Everybody in the joint could sense this paltry point was pretty
big, and would probably lead to her and Mirnyi losing the title.
They didn't want her to vanish so soon, after only 73 minutes on
view. Why else were so many people watching a mixed doubles match
if not magnetized by Kournikova?
</P>
<P>
   The ball did seem out from where I was sitting, and people were
booing the umpire. But Judge Seeney had the best seat in the house
to rule in such matters. He was stonily silent. Only three little
letters (O-U-T), but he refused to utter them. As Tammy Wynette
stood by her man, Seeney stood by his call.
</P>
<P>
   That is pressure. Umpires may be assailed by such as Jimy
Williams of our Olde Towne Team, but how hard can it be to turn
down an appeal by craggy old Jimy? Here was Kournikova, the siren
in the kind of pistachio shift that drives men nuts, pleading for a
smidgen of kindness and consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Seeney didn't flinch. Brave, righteous man, or ogre? Take your
pick. Nevertheless, he wouldn't budge even for the lass who bends
men around her little finger as her countrywoman Catherine the
Great used to do.
</P>
<P>
   He undoubtedly will cherish the memory of their brief,
tantalizing encounter, perhaps dining out on it when he returns to
Australia. One simple word might have changed their relationship _
but maybe her gaze struck him dumb.
</P>
<P>
   At last Kournikova stopped tapping her racket disapprovingly.
She went back to work after losing that critical point and lost her
vital service game to 3-5. She and the gangling 6-foot-5-inch
Mirnyi lost the next game, and the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Poor little rich girl, who wins hearts and endorsements,
headlines and commercials _ but not titles. She might have won this
one if only Russell Seeney had seen it her way and muttered
``Out!'' Hers was a disappointing Open. She was upset by another
teenager, Justine Henin, in the third round, and collected merely
$74,000 ($31,500 alongside Mirnyi).
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova departed immediately with nothing to say. Mirnyi,
definitely a ladies man, who won the Wimbledon and US mixed doubles
two years ago with Serena Williams, is also in the men's doubles
final, accompanied by the Boy Bomb, Lleyton Hewitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Mirnyi said, intending no slight to Hewitt, ``the best
part has been spending two weeks with Anna.'' Though it was no more
than cohabitating a tennis court, what guy wouldn't have wanted to
trade places with him?
</P>
<P>
   The teammates kissed after their last point.
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova did not blow a kiss to the mesmerized but tongue-tied
Judge Seeney.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
