<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY POLLS A SHOT IN THE DARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trouble with preseason polls is that they are voted on in
the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   You can study all the magazines, depth charts, and scouting
reports you want and you don't really know how good a team really
is or can be.
</P>
<P>
   College football is not like the National Football League where
there is generally a reasonable amount of stability from season to
season.
</P>
<P>
   A top 5 team at the end of one year might not necessarily be one
at the start of the next. Some picks _ Florida State, Nebraska _
are safe in any season.
</P>
<P>
   Take this year, for example. Alabama, Virginia Tech, and Penn
State.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama started the year third in the Associated Press preseason
poll, receiving three first-place votes. Virginia Tech was 11th.
Penn State was 22d.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Alabama began its season with a 35-24 loss to UCLA in a
game that was not a fluke. The Tide was outhit, outhustled, and
outplayed.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State has yet to hit anything other than the skids as it
has dropped back-to-back games to Southern California and Toledo.
The Lions play Louisiana Tech Saturday, attempting to avoid the
first 0-3 start since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech _ which was picked behind Miami in the Big East
preseason polls, although the Hokies have not lost to the
Hurricanes (who were fifth in the polls) since 1994 _ opened its
season with a romp over Akron.
</P>
<P>
   On a local level, go to the Big East opener between Boston
College and West Virginia. The Eagles were picked either third or
fourth, behind Miami, Virginia Tech, and Syracuse. West Virginia
was a spot back.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, West Virginia romped to a 34-14 victory. Is West Virginia
better than people thought? Is BC worse?
</P>
<P>
   Who knows.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the point. No one really knows, yet we make judgments
and predictions that create rankings.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, this was no big deal. The polls were fun to
argue about, nothing more. The decisions about final rankings were
played out during the course of the season with the bowl
representatives making their own selections.
</P>
<P>
   The new-age technology is different. We have the Bowl
Championship Series rankings based on computer printouts that
determine strength of schedule and the value of margin of
victories.
</P>
<P>
   Those rankings determine who will play for the national
championship game _ which happens to be in the Orange Bowl this
season.
</P>
<P>
   In an ideal world of college football, the teams would play a
month's worth of games before we would have the first poll of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not going to happen. We are obsessed with the Who's
No. 1 mentality from start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   So be it. But when you look at the results each week in
September, be careful before you call any game an upset.
</P>
<P>
   A team like UCLA, or even Toledo, who almost no one had in any
Top 25 in the preseason, might emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are Florida State and Nebraska will be in their usual
top spots by the time October arrives and that will be fine. They
will have earned their spots.
</P>
<P>
   But until then, don't pay too much attention to the Top 10.
Everybody is just guessing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Raising the bar &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rarely do you see a Notre Dame team as a decisive home underdog,
but that is the case for Saturday's game against No. 1 Nebraska.
``If we want to set our sights high, that's a good place to
start,'' said Notre Dame coach Bob Davie when asked about comparing
the Irish with the Huskers. ``If you want to raise the bar of your
footbal team, you raise that bar comparing yourself to Nebraska.''
</P>
<P>
   Think about that for a minute. This is Notre Dame we're talking
about, not Virginia Tech or Marshall or some other rising program.
</P>
<P>
   How times have changed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Airing Lion laundry &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It has been an interesting week at Penn State as coach Joe
Paterno tries to recover from the 0-2 start and the public airing
of laundry that was created when running back Larry Johnson Jr.
took a verbal blast at the system. To make matters worse, Johnson
is the son of defensive line coach Larry Johnson Sr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope we keep our dirty laundry to ourselves,'' said
Paterno. ``We're all frustrated. That's why I kept my mouth shut,
so I didn't say anything I'd be sorry about.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lions' problem is not difficult to see. They can't score or
move the ball. They have gained 308 yards in total offense in two
games, which isn't even a good half for a team like Nebraska early
in the season. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the shoe fits . . . &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin coach Barry Alvarez has had to do some major league
scrambling early in the season after the NCAA ruled 26 of his
players would face suspensions ranging from one to three games for
accepting extra benefits from a Madison-area discount shoe store.
Alvarez's only advantage? He can stagger the suspensions and
doesn't have to announce them until game time. The Badgers barely
survived with a 19-7 win over Western Michigan Saturday, but they
will be hard pressed to overcome a tougher Oregon team Saturday . .
. The heat wave that continues in the Southwest is becoming a
health concern. Usually, the spate of 100 degree days is gone by
Sept. 1, but SMU opened its season Saturday night and the game-time
temperature was 109 . . . Michigan got its season off to a nice
start with a 42-7 romp over Bowling Green last week, but the cost
was considerable. The Wolverines lost tight end Shawn Thompston
with a knee injury and defensive end Jake Frysinger with a foot
injury. And that's in addition to the injuries to quarterback Drew
Henson (foot), who will miss at least two more games, and safety
Cato June and wide receiver Tyrece Butler, who are out for the
season with knee injuries . . . Although Texas coach Mack Brown
said he will use both Major Applewhite and Chris Simms as his
quarterbacks this season, starting with Saturday's opener against
Louisiana-Lafayette, Simms doesn't think it will work on a
long-range basis. ``I can't see it throughout the season,'' he
said. ``I don't think it could work. It's too much turmoil for a
team. It just never works.'' . . . Toledo took care of one Big Ten
``power'' in Penn State last week. This week it could be Michigan
State's turn when it faces Marshall. Marshall comes into the game
with the longest winning streak in the country (17 games) and a
63-7 win over Southwest Missouri State. ``It's quite obvious from
the way they've dominated the Mid-American Conference the past
three years they have far superior talent than the rest of the
league,'' said Michigan State's Bobby Williams . . . The trouble
with polls is already obvious this season. In the Associated Press
writer's poll, Alabama remained ahead of UCLA, despite what
happened Saturday and in the coaches poll _ Penn State still
received votes despite its 0-2 start. Speculation is that Larry
Johnson Sr. voted for Penn State this week in an act of contrition
for what his son said . . . Call them the road warriors. Only five
Division 1A teams will open their seasons with three consecutive
road games. Southern Miss, Tulane, BYU, Miami (Ohio), and
Mississippi State are the hearty bunch. BYU has already made two
cross-country trips, losing to Florida State in Jacksonville, Fla.,
two weeks ago and coming back to beat Virginia in Charlottesville
last week. The Cougars have a relatively short trip Saturday with a
visit to the Air Force Academy in Colorado Springs, Colo. . . .
Boston College, which could use some good luck after last week's
embarrassing debut against West Virginia, catches a little break
when it travels to Army Saturday. The Cadets are coming off a short
workweek of preparation since they opened the season Monday
afternoon at Cincinnati with a 23-17 loss to the Bearcats . . . If
you want a sleeper team coming out of the Big East it could be
Temple. Don't laugh. The Owls have gotten more competitive each
year under coach Bobby Wallace _ they have a win over Virginia Tech
at Blacksburg, which is something Miami doesn't have.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
