<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6161 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-REVIEW-GIRLFRIEND-     09-08 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEW-GIRLFRIEND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `GIRLFRIENDS' WE CAN ALL LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TIM GOODMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is the burden of television history that unless you create
something stunningly original, a series will find itself
pigeonholed and compared to others that have come before it.
</P>
<P>
   And so it's safe to assume that UPN's surprisingly good new
comedy, ``Girlfriends'' (9:30 p.m. Monday, check local listings)
will be called ``the black 'Sex and the City.''' It's almost
impossible to ignore the similarities _ four women trying to get
their love lives in order while living in a big city, this time Los
Angeles. They are all perfectly diverse in their personal styles
and approaches to life, a la ``Sex and the City.''
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Girlfriends'' will have a difficult time distancing
itself from the HBO hit, the series is markedly different on many
levels and deserves its own credit for being funny. In fact, what
separates this show from ``Sex and the City'' most glaringly is the
heavier emphasis on one-liners. Where ``Sex and the City'' tends to
dabble in drama and subtlety, ``Girlfriends'' _ while no stranger
to feelings _ prefers punch lines over angst.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat surprisingly for an all-black comedy, Kelsey Grammer is
the executive producer. But the voice behind the series is Mara
Brock Akil, who helped shepherd ``Moesha'' and ``The Jamie Foxx
Show.'' Clearly this black-women-turning-30 thing is ripe material
for her, as she gives us four powerful personalities and one of
UPN's brightest shows in years.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the way is Joan (Tracee Ellis Ross), the anchor of the
foursome. She's a successful attorney with her own house and
fabulous furniture, sparkling morals (no sex until three months
with a nice guy) and a bright personality. But she's lousy with
men. Much like Carrie in ``Sex and the City,'' she's the lead
voice, addressing the camera directly (instead of Carrie's
voice-overs) in a variety of funny revelations.
</P>
<P>
   Her secretary and good friend is Maya (Golden Brooks), who still
has a fighting amount of street left in her (which comes in handy
when she verbally defends Joan, which is regularly). Maya is
married with a kid and is working to succeed in the business world
with Joan as her lead.
</P>
<P>
   Toni (Jill Marie Jones) is a successful real estate agent but
makes no bones about looking for a very, very rich man with great
taste in clothes who will take care of her for the rest of her
life. She spars frequently with Maya as the two riff on social
class. She's one of Joan's closest friends.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn (Persia White) rounds out the group and also stands out the
most. She's part earthy-crunchy, part punk, part social activist.
She went to college with Joan but is now in her eighth year of
graduate school, preferring the mental approach to actually joining
the working world.
</P>
<P>
   The wild card here is William (Reggie Hayes), a kind of nerdy
but funny social loser who works with Joan at the law firm. His
dumb-droll asides are a nice change of pace from the sass of Maya
and Toni.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girlfriends'' does not break a lot of new ground. The women
have the same obsession with men and appearances that plague the
foursome on ``Sex and the City.'' But the jokes are funny, sharp
and consistent, making this _ easily _ UPN's best chance at a major
sitcom hit.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Girlfriends'' is another so-called ``urban comedy''
that UPN has found success with (``The Parkers'' is a big hit in
African-American households), this one has a better chance at
crossing over racial lines.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it will have to survive the ``Sex and the City''
knock-off tag. And, more dangerously, survive the fate of UPN,
which remains unknown. The network is in danger of folding _
possibly in the middle of this season.
</P>
<P>
   But right now, ``Girlfriends'' is the first show of the new fall
season and, given that most of the offerings across the dial will
be dismal, is a nice way to start things off.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
