<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6163 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OUTDOORS-MOUNTAINBOAR     09-08 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-MOUNTAINBOARDING-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 MOUNTAINBOARDING TAKES OFF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BARTLETT, N.H. _ The 12-year-old from Florida showed off a
slightly bruised knee and deemed his latest endeavor and the newest
toy to hit New England's mountains ``pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   The mother of a young Rhode Island teenager came by and asked if
she could take a picture to make a point: ``to prove to my son that
we do so have fun,'' she said. Seems he had opted for the nearest
skateboard park with his aunt and uncle and missed his chance to
try mountainboarding.
</P>
<P>
   It was a drizzly late Sunday afternoon, and a mountain bike race
was taking place at the other base lodge. There were more watchers
than doers on the dirt track Attitash/Bear Peak Ski Resort uses for
its mountainboarders.
</P>
<P>
   One father said he was sure mountainboarding was going to take
off, though. He longed to try it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the big boss said no,'' he lamented. ``I've had back
surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   A young mountainboarder headed up the path. He carefully climbed
onto the board with the fat, inflatable tires _ almost a snowboard,
almost a skateboard. He pointed it down the hill and took off.
Bending his knees, he carved a couple of gentle turns, used the
hand brake to control his speed, and dipped and rolled over the
mounds of dirt in his path.
</P>
<P>
   Think road bike turned mountain bike.
</P>
<P>
   The mountainboard is ``like a big skateboard with pneumatic
wheels and inflatable tires holding you down with bindings,'' said
Paul Spacht of Sunday River, Maine. ``Like a skateboard where you
beef things up and make it stronger for off-road use. It basically
really is like a large skateboard with air tires and a rear
brake.''
</P>
<P>
   Think snowboarders looking for something to do in the summer.
Think skateboarders looking to take their wheels and tricks to new
terrain.
</P>
<P>
   And think ski and snowboard resorts looking for ways to make use
of their hills and mountains in the summer. It certainly won't hurt
if they can introduce new folks to their ski areas and mountain
sports.
</P>
<P>
   Flash back to eight years ago in Lake Tahoe. Snowboarding
buddies Paul McConnell and Jason Lee were sitting on a chairlift.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were real hard-core into snowboarding,'' McConnell said.
``We were riding in the winter of 1992-93 and talking about what we
were going to be riding in the summertime. We thought someone must
be making this thing. We even thought it would be called a
mountainboard.''
</P>
<P>
   They looked around, but couldn't find any.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first few we made out of necessity, for ourselves,''
McConnell said. ``Our friends saw them, and we thought of
modifications we could do with the next batch. We took their money
and made another batch and just kept going. We went through several
revisions and then it really started to get out of control, so many
of our friends wanted them.''
</P>
<P>
   A business _ and a sport _ were born.
</P>
<P>
   Mountainboard Sports _ a couple of its mottos are ``Some of Us
Can't Wait for Snow'' and ``After a Few Months Without Snow
Desperation Overrides Common Sense'' _ has its gear at several New
England ski areas this summer. Sunday River, Attitash/Bear Peak,
and Killington in Vermont, all American Skiing Company resorts,
offer mountainboarding, as does Gunstock in Gilford, N.H. Smugglers
Notch in Vermont has used mountainboards for five years as part of
its summer camp programs.
</P>
<P>
   The mountainboard business is booming. And it's only just begun,
McConnell figures.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have come on board, and all signs are good.
Mountainboard Sports has sold 16,000 boards since it started in
1996, and McConnell is looking to sell 16,000 more this year.
</P>
<P>
   He is living in Vermont this summer, pushing the sport and
trying to line up more ski areas for next summer. He has a couple
of commitments already, and he would love to get another 20 resorts
by next year and then keep doubling the total.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like snowboarding, I think it could take off in the Northeast
first and then hit the rest of the country,'' McConnell said.
``They're not ski resorts with huge rock mountains. Some of them
are midsized mountains, and their terrain is ideal. They have a lot
of grass and dirt. On Gunstock's downhill boarder-cross, all the
features are made out of dirt. It's like a golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   Killington has a 3.6-mile trail serviced by a gondola. Sunday
River takes its beginners to a parking lot for some basic
instruction and then shows them how to get on and off a chairlift.
Then they hit the slopes.
</P>
<P>
   The ground can be unforgiving for falls, so speeds are slower
than they are for snowboarders.
</P>
<P>
   ``A normal recreational speed is about 10 miles an hour,''
McConnell said. ``Fast enough to have fun, slow enough to be in
total control all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Renters are outfitted with helmets, and wrist, knee, and elbow
pads. Most riders he knows, Spacht said, stick with the hand
brakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a lot simpler than it appears to be _
snowboarding, skateboarding with a little BMX thrown in,'' Spacht
said. ``It's easier than snowboarding. It's got the wheels and
tracks itself where a snowboard slips and slides. And skateboarding
is much harder than snowboarding.''
</P>
<P>
   Count Bryan Mahn, 29, of South Boston, as a believer.
</P>
<P>
   A chef in Cambridge, he saw a brochure for mountainboarding at
Sunday River in late April and, like McConnell and Lee before him,
wasn't ready to have his snowboarding season end.
</P>
<P>
   He called the toll-free number for Mountainboard Sports and
found the nearest retailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy at the store let me try it, so I was riding down a
hill in Fitchburg,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He bought one on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more of a risk, obviously. It's not snow you're
falling on, it's gravel and rock and dirt,'' Mahn said. ``But it's
exhilarating. You still feel the same carving, and you don't need
snow to do it, and you can do it anywhere. On the street, down a
hill in the park. You can go anywhere with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahn races, and he carries brochures in his backpack for anyone
who asks about mountainboarding. He's not even paid to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hand them out and figure the more people who get
involved, the easier it will be to get parts and stuff like that
and the more areas that will get involved,'' Mahn said.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what McConnell is hoping.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
