<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSBORNE IS BACK AND BETTER THAN EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So you wanna be a rock star? Good luck. One minute you're up,
the next minute you don't even have a record deal, as singer Joan
Osborne can tell you.
</P>
<P>
   Her debut album, ``Relish,'' in 1995, went multiplatinum and had
the megahit ``One of Us,'' a mildly provocative tune in which she
wondered if God might be ``just a slob like one of us, just a
stranger on the bus trying to make his way home.'' The song angered
a few far-right religious types, but helped her gain five Grammy
nominations and tour the world.
</P>
<P>
   Logic would suggest that she earned some artistic autonomy for
her next record, right? Well, wrong. She was dropped by Mercury
Records _ she still doesn't understand why _ but has landed on her
feet with the new ``Righteous Love,'' which comes out Tuesday on
Interscope Records.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird. Music is an even more precarious career than it
used to be, so I definitely feel lucky to put another album out and
go on another tour. You can't take it for granted,'' says Osborne,
a Kentucky native now based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think record companies have this idea that audiences are
very fickle, so there's not nearly as much emphasis any more on
building a lengthy career over several albums. They pretty much
only want to put out a record that they think is going to sell 10
million copies. That's the sort of corporate bind they've gotten
themselves into, after all these megamergers and stuff,'' Osborne
adds. ``I certainly was not part of the decision to drop me from
Mercury. I don't really know what went on in that room at that
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, here's a memo to Mercury's short-sighted executives: you
blew it, because Osborne's new record is one of the finest of the
year. It furthers the erotic soul-rock of her first CD, while
broadening her horizon from Irma Thomas-like grit to
Pretenders-like heaviness, along with some shimmering, George
Harrison-sounding guitar and adding some mystical drone singing in
the qawwali tradition of Pakistan's Nusrat Ali Fateh Khan, with
whom Osborne studied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through a phase of listening to Harrison's `All Things
Must Pass' over and over,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   It's a deeper, more mature, but still rocking album that
reflects the growth that Osborne has made in recent years. She used
her success as a springboard to sing with Luciano Pavarotti in
Italy for a Bosnian relief benefit, to record a duet with Bob
Dylan, to record with the Chieftains, to write with Cuban artists
and play the Karl Marx Theater in Havana, and to make two trips to
India to study voice _ one of which resulted in her performing for
the Dalai Lama.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt comfortable drawing from a lot of disparate sources
this time,'' she says of her latest music. ``I don't sit down and
draw maps for myself or anything like that. I just try to spend
time with the music that I love and hopefully that forms what I
create myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Her emotions run the gamut on the new songs, from the
romantically hopeful title track, to the breakup tune, ``Poisoned
Apples,'' to a stunning cover of Dylan's ``To Make You Feel My
Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Osborne sees the record as being ``more straightforward than the
last one _ and that had much to do with my state of mind when I was
in the studio. I didn't have a label at the time, and there
certainly was no guarantee that I was going to find another one, so
I guess I felt like I had to sort of fish or cut bait. It was time
to really just do it and be straightforward about my approaches to
singing and music.''
</P>
<P>
   Osborne is now ready to go back on tour _ her Avalon show will
feature a new band, save for returning guitarist Jack Petruzelli.
She also is about to launch a new online publication, Heroine
Magazine (www.heroinemag.com), on Sept. 12. The focus is on ``women
who are doing inspiring and interesting things,'' she says, adding
that the first issue will include a discussion between Susan
Sarandon and the Indigo Girls about their political activism and
how they mix that with their creative work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been coming up with a lot of the article ideas and it's
definitely been fun,'' says Osborne. ``If it overwhelms me, then
I'll let it go, but it's been exciting so far.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New U2 single: The advance buzz had U2 going back to its rock
roots for its next album, but the new single, ``Beautiful Day,''
shoots down that theory. It's a fairly lame, synthetic-sounding
stab at the dance-lite market, complete with gooey lyrics about how
``it's a beautiful day . . . you got no destination.'' There's a
chiming guitar line from The Edge, but the rest of it is schmaltz.
Hopefully, U2's CD (``All That You Can't Leave Behind,'' due next
month) will be better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
