<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ROSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW EIGHT WOMEN ROWING A BOAT TURNED THE TIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN CLEGG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE RED ROSE CREW 
A True Story of Women, Winning, and the Water 
By Daniel J. Boyne 
Hyperion, 206 pp., illustrated, $23.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Oct. 21, thousands of rowers will gather for the Boston's
Head of Charles Regatta, the 35-year-old tradition that is half
athletic contest and half beer garden. Any number of those boats
will be rowed by women. This fact seems unremarkable in an era when
the Williams sisters match up at Wimbledon and the WNBA stages
down-to-the-wire playoffs and television covers it all. But it
wasn't always so.
</P>
<P>
   Change came slowly in the world of rowing, one of the oldest and
most elite intercollegiate sports. Harvard and Yale have had an
annual race since 1857, but until rowers Chris Ernst and Anne
Warner launched a protest in 1976, women were not even allowed to
shower at the Yale boathouse. The Head of the Charles had no events
for women until Gail Pierson, an MIT professor, forced the issue in
1969 and became the first woman to race a single.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Red Rose Crew,'' these athletes get their due. Author
Daniel J. Boyne, director of recreational rowing at Harvard
University, looks at the wild passion and ragged strength that
stoked a winning boat and helped usher in a new era for women's
sports.
</P>
<P>
   The eight women rowers who won the silver medal in the 1975
World Rowing Championship weren't exactly a consciousness-raising
group. They were in it to play hard and whip some Russian butt.
``For most of the women in `The Red Rose Crew,' rowing was simply a
way to explore and express a part of themselves that had been
largely suppressed by American society, not to make a political
statement,'' Boyne writes. ``And yet in pursuing their passion in
the sport they indeed acted heroically, in the truest sense,
without any thought about fame or profit. Ironically, it is only
now, more than two decades later, that the full significance of
their actions can be truly appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyne's story is launched in 1972, the year that Congress passed
Title IX, the law requiring universities to give equal funding to
men's and women's sports teams. It was also the year that the
decision was made to include women's crew in the 1976 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   First, however, there were tryouts for US Women's Rowing Camp.
``Those who made the first cut would be invited to Boston, where
the appointed coach would make further selections. In the end,
eight rowers, a coxswain, and two spares would travel to
Nottingham, England, and row at the World Championships.''
</P>
<P>
   And here, finally, is where untamed drive meets legend. Harry
Parker, Harvard's taciturn, courtly rowing coach, agreed to take on
the women's crew. Parker has been the subject of elegiac
sportswriting before, of course, most notably in ``The Amateurs,''
by David Halberstam. And though Boyne prunes where Halberstam
inflates, Parker comes off none the worse.
</P>
<P>
   Parker, Boyne writes, ``was a different kind of coach than most
sports fans were used to, as different as the sport he coached.
Behind the studied, silent air was an intelligent, piercing look
that the press, for lack of a better word, called patrician. His
coaching style was minimalist. He had no need to yell to get people
to do what he wished.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyne, author of a spare and useful rowing text called
``Essential Sculling,'' documents the emotionally wrought process
of picking an eight-woman crew. It eventually includes Carie
Graves, the intense ``stroke'' who sets the pace; Pierson, the
reformed single sculler who understands the politics of the rowing
world; and Lynn Silliman, the coxswain who steers the boat and the
psyches of her crew.
</P>
<P>
   With supple prose and pinpoint anecdotes, Boyne tells a story of
transformation. For the Red Rose crew, who found singular grace and
purpose on the water. And for those of us who watch rowing, or any
other sport, in hopes of adding a little loft to everyday life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6179 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-HENDRIX-BOS &LR;      09-08 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-HENDRIX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ULTIMATE `EXPERIENCE' OF JIMI HENDRIX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the 30th anniversary of Jimi Hendrix's death, which means
an all-out campaign to memorialize him. Leading the way is a
four-CD box set, ``The Jimi Hendrix Experience,'' due in stores
Tuesday, the same day the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in Cleveland
opens a major exhibit on him.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Sept. 17 _ the day before the anniversary of his death _
the Showtime channel airs the biopic ``Hendrix,'' starring Wood
Harris of ``Remember the Titans'' fame. It retraces the
singer-guitarist's rise from a Seattle childhood to life in
Greenwich Village and London, and historic performances at the
Woodstock and Monterey Pop Festivals.
</P>
<P>
   For serious Hendrix fans, though, the show piece is the
spectacularly designed, no-expense-spared box set, with a cover of
purple velvet imported from France. It has a suggested retail price
of $69.99 for the CDs, or $59.99 for eight vinyl albums, and the
set boasts the most previously unreleased music ever bunched into a
Hendrix package.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, it was made under the auspices of Hendrix's family,
which won a court case not long ago to finally regain control of
Hendrix's archives. Thus, we can bid goodbye to some of the bogus
Hendrix packages of past years. Some were good, but many were
wretchedly inconsistent and even filled with intrusive,
uncalled-for overdubbing.
</P>
<P>
   The new set is ``not just a pretty box with a lot of the same
stuff that you've heard before,'' says John McDermott, a Newton
resident who coproduced it with Hendrix's family and with longtime
Hendrix engineer Eddie Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, nearly every track is an alternate take (Hendrix
sometimes made 20 to 30 takes of a single song), an alternate mix
(with a few new mixes by Kramer), or previously unreleased live
tracks from shows in Stockholm, London, Paris, the Isle of Wight,
Monterey, San Diego, Berkeley, and even Maui, where Hendrix did an
impromptu gig in a meadow on a mountainside, attended by just a few
hundred people who saw leaflets handed out that day.
</P>
<P>
   Great pains are taken to show Hendrix's incendiary live style _
long jams are recorded, as are blazing covers of the Beatles's
``Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band,'' Howling Wolf's ``Killing
Floor,'' Bob Dylan's ``Like a Rolling Stone,'' plus Chuck Berry's
``Johnny B. Goode'' and Carl Perkins's ``Blue Suede Shoes.''
Hendrix's fundamental blues root is also shown by a live version of
B.B. King's ``Rock Me Baby'' and by ``Catfish Blues,'' inspired by
Muddy Waters's ``Still a Fool.''
</P>
<P>
   The set is generally chronological, starting with a 1966 studio
take of ``Purple Haze,'' where the vocal is more prominent and the
guitar playing actually more psychedelic than the toned-down
version that came out on record. Other songs were slowed down, too,
as they progressed, notably ``Little Wing.'' The faster-tempoed
version is included here, before Hendrix producer Chas Chandler
(who was also bassist with the Animals) persuaded Hendrix to rein
it in.
</P>
<P>
   One problem for a listener to this box, however, is the rapid
jumping between studio and live cuts. For that reason, nothing
reaches the same incendiary level as the ``Live At Winterland''
album that Rykodisc put out during the '80s. There are only two or
three live cuts in succession here, before studio takes _ often
more careful and plodding _ are interspersed.
</P>
<P>
   Another key element is that this box set, as coproducer
McDermott says, is meant as a companion to the four records that
Hendrix made in his lifetime. To fully appreciate it, one needs to
have heard those records, thus this is not designed as a Hendrix
primer. If you're new to Hendrix, get those other records first
(especially ``Are You Experienced?'' and ``Axis: Bold as Love'')
before you delve into this set.
</P>
<P>
   But for connoisseurs, this box is a treasure. Hendrix's
improvisational nature is demonstrated throughout, whether it's a
previously unreleased stoned rap on ``Third Stone from the Sun,''
or when he starts recording the spacy ``Burning of the Midnight
Lamp'' on harpsicord in the studio, only to later play it on guitar
in a concert in Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
   Extensive written comments are provided on each song by
McDermott, who has penned two books on Hendrix (titled ``Hendrix:
Setting the Record Straight'' and ``The Jimi Hendrix Sessions''),
plus worked on box sets by Cream, Eric Clapton, and on an upcoming
double-CD by Blind Faith.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott also explains the growing tension between Hendrix and
bassist Noel Redding, who wanted more arranged music and less
jamming and eventually left the group and was replaced by Billy
Cox. Original drummer Mitch Mitchell was later replaced by Buddy
Miles (when Hendrix's group became known as the Band of Gypsys),
but Miles grew ``cocky,'' says McDermott, and Mitchell was invited
back, though Redding never returned.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining Hendrix family _ notably his sister, Janie _
formed a company, Experience Hendrix, which put out this box and
also an official bootleg, ``Live at Clark University,'' taped at
that Worcester college in 1968 and available only through
www.jimi-hendrix.com. Future projects may include a live Hendrix
album from Royal Albert Hall. For now, though, it's time to
celebrate his 30th anniversary and hopefully entice collectors to
this attractive, if sometimes unwieldy, new box. But, again, get
his original albums first if you're not already a diehard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6181 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-BOCELLI-BOS &LR;      09-08 1407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BOCELLI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDREA BOCELLI'S LATEST CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andrea Bocelli's new CD of Verdi arias arrives in the stores on
Tuesday, which is another way of saying it will start flying out of
the stores and straight to the top of the charts.
</P>
<P>
   The record is a little disappointing but it is still a very good
thing because it will introduce this music to thousands of people
who haven't heard it in performances that are genuinely musical and
stylistically authentic, even if the voice isn't invariably up to
every challenge Verdi sets.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian superstar recorded his new album in sessions with
Zubin Mehta and the Israel Philharmonic last December and January
in Tel Aviv. The ambitious program includes 15 arias or cabalettas
from 10 operas, some of which Bocelli would hardly dare to sing in
an unamplified live operatic performance _ but he is hardly the
first tenor to record arias from operas he couldn't sing onstage.
Fifty years ago some 78s by Ferruccio Tagliavini created a great
stir; it sounded as if a great new dramatic tenor had emerged. In
person, Tagliavini had a beautiful light, lyric voice, which he
proceeded to damage permanently by trying to sound in a live,
unamplified performance the way he sounded electronically. That
doesn't change the fact that some of Tagliavini's early recordings
sounded great, and still do.
</P>
<P>
   Bocelli did sing three of these arias during his heavily miked
concert at the Worcester Centrum Centre in April. All the work
preparing the recording benefited the audience: he sang these arias
considerably better in the Centrum than he does on the recording.
Also, during his spring American tour, Bocelli encountered a new
voice teacher; even in a few weeks of work, Bocelli made some
substantial technical advances _ one wishes the record had been
made after the tour rather than before.
</P>
<P>
   There's no getting around the bad news, which is that a
principal element of Bocelli's appeal is in short supply on this
album, and that is the intrinsic beauty of his timbre, which the
microphone adores. There has always been an element of strain in
his singing; like his predecessor Giuseppe di Stefano, Bocelli has
figured out how to use that effort for artistic effect _ strain
makes him sound earnest and sincere. But here he goes beyond sounds
distinctly stretched uncomfortable a good bit of the time, and the
consequence is that clouds pass over some of the sunlight in his
voice.
</P>
<P>
   Those who heard the unamplified Bocelli sing Massenet's
``Werther'' in Detroit know that nature has given him a very light
tenor voice. Verdi wrote several roles that can be effectively sung
by such an instrument. Bocelli sings arias from two of them, the
Duke in ``Rigoletto'' and Alfredo in ``La Traviata.'' He delivers
them attractively, with a good flourish in the cadenza in ``La
donna e mobile,'' and a vastly prolonged high D at the end of
``Possente amor.'' Is this the highest note Bocelli has recorded?
</P>
<P>
   One wishes he had sung more arias conceived for this weight of
voice. Most of his other choices from ``Ernani,'' ``Don Carlo,''
``Luisa Miller,'' and ``La Forza del Destino'' are associated with
greater heft; the microphone has to supply it rather than the
tenor. The results are only intermittently convincing, although
Bocelli's delivery of the sound and intent of his own language is
always remarkable. There are a few surprises _ ``Di quella pira''
has a fair amount of punch and panache, and it is very unsual to
hear it sung this accurately, and in the original key. (An
unidentified soprano supplies some phrases for Leonora that are
invariably cut from theater performances.) In a press kit
interview, Bocelli confesses that this piece was a challenge for
him from the start, ``an aria that requires `agilita' (agility) and
`forza' (force) and that I always carefully avoided singing, but
which was more or less a must for this album. Consequently I had to
study it, and I worked very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Bocelli must have worked very hard on ``Celeste Aida'' as well.
This aria rides over some rough patches in virtually every tenor's
voice. Bocelli sings the aria as a love song, not a showstopper,
and emerges honorably from the contest, crowning the final phrase
with a spectacular diminuendo on the final high B-flat _ an effect
favored by his teacher and mentor, Franco Corelli, and that others
seldom attempt. (On a Met broadcast, Carlo Bergonzi tried it and
cracked wide open). Bocelli does join the majority of tenordom by
skipping the trills in ``Ah si, ben mio'' from ``Il Trovatore,''
but otherwise he isn't a shirker _ he takes the big jumps in the
barcarolle from ``Un Ballo in Maschera'' that other tenors
sometimes rewrite, although one wishes he wouldn't sound so careful
about them. The purpose of those jumps is to bring out the
daredevil in the singer.
</P>
<P>
   All but one of the arias are performed as complete scenes, with
introductory recitative, aria, and, where one exists, rousing
concluding cabaletta; if Verdi calls for the chorus, the forces of
the Maggio Musicale Fiorentino chime in. For some reason _ the
length of the CD? _ Bocelli does omit the dramatic recitative that
precedes Riccardo's last-act aria from ``Un Ballo in Maschera'' _
but that choice is better than singing the recitative and omitting
the aria, which is what Jussi Bjoerling used to do.
</P>
<P>
   One artistic flaw of the recording is that it is programmed like
a pop album; mood flow takes precedence over other musical and
historical considerations. Carlo Bergonzi made one of the great
Verdi albums when he sang all the principal arias from all of the
operas, in chronological order; most tenor recitals at least group
arias from the same opera together, and in the order in which they
appear. Not Bocelli, who leads off with the rousing ``Di quella
pira'' from ``Il Trovatore'' and follows it by ``Ah, si ben mio''
from the same opera that immediately precedes it _ directly
reversing the order Verdi intended. He sings an aria from the end
of ``Rigoletto,'' then two arias from ``Un Ballo in Maschera''
before returning for an aria and cabaletta from an earlier act of
``Rigoletto.''
</P>
<P>
   This album gives some reason for worry _ as does the
announcement that Bocelli plans to sing ``Aida'' on stage, which he
shouldn't try, along with ``Tosca'' and ``L'Amico Fritz,'' which
might work. A recording of ``La Boheme'' is scheduled for release
next month, and he is supposed to record the Verdi Requiem with
Renee Fleming, Olga Borodina, Ildebrando d'Archangelo, and
conductor Valery Gergiev this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Bocelli has assets he shouldn't squander the way di Stefano did;
Alfredo Kraus and Tito Schipa stayed within their voices and both
were still singing successfully at 70. Too often, Bocelli is
singing well beyond his voice, even with the help of the
microphone. He hasn't done himself permanent damage _ he sounded
better in Worcester and in Paris (where I heard him both
unamplified in the rehearsal room and in the amplified concert)
than he does on this new record. But there is still reason to
worry.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, this writer stands firmly in Bocelli's corner. One
reason lies in conversations within the last couple of years with
Luciano Pavarotti, Placido Domingo, and Jose Carreras. The three
tenors really don't have that much in common, and the only thing
all three of them said is that they would never have pursued a
career in singing and in opera if it hadn't been for Mario Lanza _
who sang in only two operatic productions onstage, but whose films
and recordings reached people in a way that no mainstream opera
singer of his era ever did. Bocelli isn't like Lanza at all, but he
has the same kind of mass appeal. We can only hope that his
recordings, concerts, and videos will attract three tenor teenagers
as talented as Pavarotti, Domingo, and Carreras to the world of
opera.
</P>
<P>
   While Bocelli may not be in the class of the Big Three or
several others, he is nevertheless a more honest, pleasing,
stylish, and musical singer than many colleagues active on the
operatic stage and in the recording studio; last spring, in Paris,
even Seiji Ozawa was impressed with the elegance and style of
Bocelli's phrasing.
</P>
<P>
   Bocelli is also living a fantasy of every opera lover, including
himself; against every expectation, he has awakened the tenor
within.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
