<HEADER>
A6186 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RWANDA-PEACEMAKER-BOS     09-08 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RWANDA-PEACEMAKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER BURYING RWANDA DEAD, PEACEKEEPER COMFORTS KILLERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Her first job was to bury corpses, tens of
thousands of them.
</P>
<P>
   Her next job is to prepare Rwanda for the release of thousands
of the killers.
</P>
<P>
   Aloisea Inyumba, executive secretary of Rwanda's National Unity
and Reconciliation Commission, is at the vortex of a risky
experiment designed to help her nation move forward from its 100
days of genocide in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly anonymous in the swirl of activity at the United Nations
Millennium Summit this week, Inyumba is part of the small Rwandan
delegation. She is held up by the government as a bright light at a
time of persistent international criticism over Rwanda's part in
escalating the multi-nation war in the Democratic Republic of
Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Inyumba, 34, a Tutsi party loyalist, also belongs to a second,
more loosely formed group, both global and gender-specific: an
initiative called Women Waging Peace, launched last year at Harvard
University's Kennedy School of Government by Swanee Hunt, the
former US ambassador to Austria.
</P>
<P>
   ``She,'' said Hunt, nodding to Inyumba over a table at the Four
Seasons Hotel in Manhattan, ``has a hell of a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunt, director of the Kennedy School's Women and Public Policy
Program, founded Women Waging Peace to recognize and publicize the
roles of women engaged in preventing conflicts and sustaining
peace. But she also wanted to help women leaders find other women
like them around the world in order to build a support network and
exchange ideas.
</P>
<P>
   The Rwandan woman, she believes, is one of her stars. ``Spend an
hour with Aloisea and you walk away a changed person,'' Hunt said.
</P>
<P>
   Inyumba, who lived in exile in Uganda until the end of the
genocide, lost two brothers in the fighting, in which an estimated
800,000 Tutsis and moderate Hutus lost their lives in a spasm of
Hutu-led killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems I am selfish talking about my family, when other
people lost everybody,'' she said, adding that in her family, ``I
still have four people alive.''
</P>
<P>
   When she returned as part of the Tutsi government, she oversaw
much of the burials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just removed people from the hills and buried them with
some dignity. You know, we haven't yet finished burying the dead.
Some are in bad shape, in swamps. One of the issues we have now is
how do we ask these victims to forgive the killers when the bodies
haven't all been taken care of.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a system called the gacaca (pronounced GA-cha-cha), named
after traditional village courts, Rwanda's justice ministry and
Inyumba's commission hope to begin releasing almost all of the
estimated 150,000 prisoners to thousands of local _ and mostly
untrained _ judges. The prisoners, who have been held in what human
rights groups call inhumane conditions, will return to the sites of
their alleged crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Rwandan authorities, who hope to complete the details of the
judicial plan in two months, have devised a four-tier system of
punishment, dividing the groups into the masterminds; the people
who killed in the hundreds; those who slayed tens of people; and
those who told the killers where to find hiding Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
   While the sentencing guidelines haven't been finalized, Inyumba
said that some people who killed a dozen or fewer people could be
sentenced to community service.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you say that someone who killed 10 people is not very
bad?'' Inyumba asked. ``You say, `Well, others killed 300.' At
least they will have served seven years in jail and we will put
them to work to do some good.
</P>
<P>
   ``And in the previous regime, if you killed, you were glorified.
The culture of hate has been so institutionalized in our system.
That will end,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt called the planned program a ``very imperfect system to
deal with an impossible situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This effort is as big as South Africa's Truth and
Reconciliation Commission. It's going to be terribly uneven. But
now you have all those thousands of people languishing in prison,''
Hunt said.
</P>
<P>
   Alison Des Forges, a consultant to Human Rights Watch who has
studied the Great Lakes region of Africa for 30 years, agreed that
Rwanda had to act to end the prison logjam. At the time of the
genocide, Inyumba noted, Rwanda had only 50 lawyers in the country.
There was no way, she said, that enough lawyers could be trained to
deal with the backlog of cases.
</P>
<P>
   But Des Forges found fault in the lack of representation for the
accused. ``All the weight of the state is added to the prosection,
while the person accused is denied any help,'' she said. ``That
seems to us to possibly result in a whole series of unfair
judgments.''
</P>
<P>
   She also questioned the human rights commission's role in
setting up so-called solidarity camps, in which she said some
participants are given weapons training. And Des Forges, like many
others, criticized Rwanda's continued role in the Congo war.
</P>
<P>
   Inyumba said the government was fighting in the Congo to uproot
those who led the genocide campaign. ``What happens in the Congo
has a direct effect on us,'' she said. ``Those people moved just a
few miles from our border.''
</P>
<P>
   The continued militarization of Rwanda adds yet another
complication for someone preaching reconcilation in the years
following the worst episode of genocide since the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   But Inyumba holds onto hope. She mentioned the closing of 70
orphanages after hundreds of families adopted children. ``We had
children who were Tutsi adopted by Hutu families,'' she said. ``I
said to myself, `Oh my God, am I doing the right thing?' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine?'' said Hunt, leaning close to Inyumba. ``That
is like asking Jews to adopt German babies after the Holocaust.''
</P>
<P>
   Inyumba continued: ``When people talk about success, they
usually talk about political participation. But I talk about
children as a way of becoming successful. So look at the children
who were adopted. That is success.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, she said, she has heard of no problems with the Tutsi
children in the Hutu families.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
