<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GUN' DRAWS A BEAD ON TARANTINO AND SCORES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE WAY OF THE GUN 
Written and directed by: Christopher McQuarrie 
Starring: Ryan Philippe, Benicio Del Toro, Juliette Lewis, Taye
Diggs, Nicky Katt, Scott Wilson, James Caan, Dylan Kussman, Kristin
Lehman 
Running time: 119 minutes 
Rated: R (strong violence/gore, language and some sexuality) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having written the screenplay for ``The Usual Suspects,''
Christopher McQuarrie takes his place behind the camera as well as
behind the word processor for ``The Way of the Gun'' and doesn't
quite out-Tarantino Quentin Tarantino, but does stay with him most
of the way. Despite an ending that gets away from him, McQuarrie's
``The Way of the Gun'' is the best Tarantino spinoff yet. The
reason is that no matter how violent things get _ and the air gets
pretty thick with bullets _ his thugs and grifters never lose sight
of the main thing, which is their exuberant delight in playing to
the most appreciative audiences they could have, namely one
another.
</P>
<P>
   For all its flying ammo, ``The Way of the Gun'' is the sum total
of its nonstop stylizations. Never deluding itself into thinking
it's naturalistic, the film is flamboyantly operatic, with big
arias and set pieces for its various lowlifes. It revels in its
written quality, with each character getting plenty of juicy
pronouncements as its outrageous crimes escalate. It's not so much
pulp fiction as it is pulp Verdi for the eyes, riding a highly
theatrical fatalism best embodied by Benicio Del Toro and Ryan
Philippe, as a pair of murderous drifters. Stumbling into a piece
of unanticipated information while visiting a sperm bank to earn
some quick money, they improvise a scheme to kidnap and hold for
ransom the pregnant mom-for-hire in the employ of an aging mobster
whose young blonde second wife wants a baby without the
inconvenience of pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Punchy as a lot of the dialogue is, the film is at its best in
the glances of complicity exchanged by Del Toro and Philippe as
they move in on what they anticipate will be a big payoff. This
involves keeping Juliette Lewis's pregnant surrogate mom intact
until they can collect their money and live to spend it. They are
not naive about the risk. They're more unnerved than they care to
admit at the aplomb displayed by James Caan's bagman, who cuts
through his usual fatalistic-shrug-ridden gangster shtick to remind
them that while he may appear to be an old man, he obviously is a
survivor. Nor is Scott Wilson's boss mobster the kind of man to
hold still for a shakedown. He gives his own hired heavies a chance
to redeem themselves from the disgrace of allowing the pregnant
woman to have been snatched away from them in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   McQuarrie's feel for the diverting tangent keeps the film from
lapsing into dumb linearity. Part of the fun arises from the fact
that nobody's hands are clean here, and that all sorts of
deviousness are afoot. There's quirky humor, too, ranging from
running jokes about cell-phone reception along the Mexican border
to the moment when Caan gets on the phone to a hired gun and the
guy on the other end is prevented by the phone call from pulling
the trigger on his own suicide. Little things _ the throb of an
idling semi, Del Toro yanking Philippe back from a tender impulse
felt for the pregnant captive _ count for a lot here. ``The Way of
the Gun'' sometimes trips over its own contrivance, especially at
the ammo-ridden end. But most of the time McQuarrie and his cast _
especially Del Toro, Philippe, and Lewis delivering her best,
grittiest work in years _ make it crackle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
