</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-HEART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AUTUMN HEART' LETS ITS EMOTIONS GET IN THE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE AUTUMN HEART 
Directed by: Steven Maler 
Screenplay by: Davidlee Willson 
Starring: Ally Sheedy, Tyne Daly, Willson, Jack Davidson, Marceline
Hugot, Marla Sucharetza 
Running time: 109 minutes 
Rated: unrated 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The big thing that ``The Autumn Heart'' has going for it is the
raw urgency of its intense emotions. The big thing that ``The
Autumn Heart'' has working against it is the raw urgency of its
intense emotions _ or, rather, that the film finds no way to keep
them from seeming blatantly contrived. Too bad, because it's a
fundamentally sympathetic study of a split family trying to come
together 20 years after a bitter divorce and it has some affecting
performances, especially from its women. They're the ones left
behind in a blue-collar part of the North Shore and would have
remained walled off by their anger and hurt feelings. But when the
family's school bus-driving matriarch has a heart attack, she asks
her three grown daughters to find their father and the now-grown
son he took with him.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that while they're only several miles apart
geographically, they're a world or two apart on the socioeconomic
ladder. Pushing on, although they're taking a risk by venturing
beyond their longstanding enmity, they discover that their father
has prospered and is a computer millionaire, while their grown-up
little brother is going to Harvard and is engaged to a moneyed
fiancee. Let it be said that the acting is terrific, particularly
when Ally Sheedy makes us feel how hard she has to fight to keep
her sustaining anger intact, and how conflicted she feels when she
discovers that her father not only isn't a monster, but stayed away
in part because he was told to.
</P>
<P>
   If Sheedy does the job with cold fury and hot eruptiveness, Tyne
Daly skirts some awfully melodramatic writing as the mom in her bed
in the cardiac unit, reminding us how much emotion can be conveyed
by making us feel, behind her tight-lipped stolidity, the effort it
takes to keep it inside. As the well-intentioned brother,
scriptwriter Davidlee Willson is rather eclipsed by the trio of
sisters, played by Sheedy, Marceline Hugot, a pillar of
working-class endurance, and Marla Sucharetza, who won my sympathy
for her ability to cope with being the character most heavily laden
with blue-collar cliches.
</P>
<P>
   What ``The Autumn Heart'' desperately needs is some shadings and
nuances to leaven the simplistic dimensions of its primal
outpourings. Sucharetza makes the youngest sister, with her
conciliatory nature, much more interesting and faceted than the
writing and costuming. They relegate her to a stereotype who
guzzles beer at her natural habitat, a bowling alley, and shows up
at a shower for her brother's snooty fiancee wearing teased hair
and a faux leopard-skin-patterened miniskirt. It would have been
more believable if the rich people were the ones who behaved
crassly and the working-class women, made to feel out of place, had
been on their best and most muted behavior. In ``The Autumn
Heart,'' a crude delivery system isn't up to what it's asked to
deliver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
