<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VIETNAM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAN FRANCISCO SEEKS ROLE IN POSSIBLE VIETNAM TRADE MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ILENE LELCHUK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ President Clinton, who in July signed a sweeping
trade pact to normalize relations with Vietnam for the first time
since the fall of Saigon, has expressed interest in visiting the
communist country in mid-November.
</P>
<P>
   The White House is not announcing any official travel plans but
San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown, a Democrat who has been a strong
Clinton supporter, said he would like to be included on a trade
mission if the president goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a close working relationship with Vietnam,'' Brown
said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20,000 Vietnamese-American live in San Francisco and
its sister city is Ho Chi Minh City (formerly Saigon). Vietnam
selected San Francisco for its first American consulate in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton makes the trip, another symbol of good faith and
reconciliation, he would be the first president since Richard Nixon
to set foot in Vietnam since the war ended 25 years ago. Clinton's
own history with the country has been widely publicized and
debated. He opposed the U.S. involvement in the Vietnam conflict as
a youth and used student deferments to avoid the draft.
</P>
<P>
   This would be Brown's second trip to Vietnam on behalf of the
city. He first traveled there as part of an Asian goodwill visit in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco doesn't have California's largest
Vietnamese-American community _ about 300,000 live in Orange County
and 120,000 live in San Jose _ but San Francisco has been on the
forefront of forging a relationship with post-war Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Vietnamese-Americans here soared between 1975 and
1992 when refugees, the so-called boat people, fled the communist
regime. Many settled in the Tenderloin neighborhood of downtown San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees' ties to their homeland remain strong, because of
families and memories left behind, which makes the issue of
normalizing U.S-Vietnamese trade relations an emotional subject.
Not everyone is happy about the president's possible trip while
others welcome it.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Nguyen, executive director of the Southeast Asian
Community Center in San Francisco, said the trade accord is a vital
economic tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the development of trade between the two cities, this is
a necessary step toward democracy in Vietnam,'' Nguyen said.
``Otherwise, they would close their doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen, 55, lived in Saigon until 1984, when he, his wife and
two sons escaped on a 30-foot-long boat with about 80 other people
seeking political freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Yen Nguyenle, who works with Nguyen at the community center and
is a member of the Ho Chi Minh Sister City Committee, left the
country in 1979 when she was 15. Her father, who was held in a
re-education camp there until 1983, didn't join the family in the
United States until 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyenle, 36, said she is excited about Clinton's trade mission.
She hopes Brown and members of the sister city committee, which
takes annual trips there already, will be invited.
</P>
<P>
   For U.S. businesses, a new trade agreement opens a market of
almost 80 million Vietnamese consumers who can buy U.S. goods and
services, especially in the telecommunication, banking and
high-tech fields.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam trade has been heavily taxed, with tariffs averaging 40
percent on goods exported to the United States. With normalized
trade relations, tariffs could drop as low as 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The trade pact signed by Clinton in July is still awaiting
congressional approval.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
