<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6197 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-KID-TECH-LADN &LR;      09-08 1343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KID-TECH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GIFT THAT KEEPS GIVING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You feel it. You know you do. You're a parent of a child under
the age of about 10, and school has just started.
</P>
<P>
   Face it: while you're glad they have classwork to occupy him or
her for the next nine months, you have this sneaking suspicion that
you've banished your baby to a lifetime as a washed-out, alcoholic
barback in a semi-successful biker bar in Sandusky, Ohio, all
because you haven't gone out and bought a) a computer for your
beloved and b) all the newest and coolest educational software to
make learning fun.
</P>
<P>
   As for computers, Moore's Law continues to work its magic,
blessing anxious parents with the ability to buy powerful, cheap
machines that can do most things a little one would want, short of
calculating nuclear- weapons blast effects (for that, you'll need
Deep Blue's latest supercomputing successor).
</P>
<P>
   But short of those particular needs, Apple Computers just
released the newest family of its iMac computers, which make
wonderful machines for students, while taking up relatively little
room on their no-doubt cluttered bedroom desks.
</P>
<P>
   At $799 for the cheapest current model, the iMacs are powerful,
easy to use and stylish machines that are hard to resist for those
who want to choose a machine for their child that is similar to
what they are most likely using at schools.
</P>
<P>
   As wonderful as are the iMacs and their more powerful and
expensive big brothers, the G4 line of Power Macs, there are good
reasons to buy Windows-based PCs instead, especially if you're
using the machine too.
</P>
<P>
   If, for instance, the adults in the house want to run many
specialized kinds of business software (other than art and other
creative programs), they'll need a machine that runs some flavor of
Microsoft's Windows operating system. Despite the many excellent
qualities of the iMac and Apple's resurgent fortunes, many of those
programs just aren't available in Mac format.
</P>
<P>
   If that's what you need, Dell's Dimension L series of computers
offer a nice package of features and power that should be
sufficient for most family needs at an attractive $899 price.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to buy from a company that actually has a store you
can visit (Dell sells only online and over the phone), anything
with a 500-megahertz Intel Celeron processor (or the equivalent and
somewhat cheaper AMD K6-2 chip) should be more than enough
horsepower. Intel's Pentium III and AMD's Athlon computer brains
provide a step up in power and are increasingly showing up in
extremely affordable mid-range systems such as the Dell.
</P>
<P>
   With all PCs, make sure you get at least 64 megabytes of RAM, or
memory, and make sure that you have a good-sized hard drive to
store all your stuff (6 to 10 gigabytes should be ample if you're
not too much of a digital packrat). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But what about software for the new machine? A raft of new
titles has just hit the market, in anticipation of the return to
school. Unlike other kinds of software, most children's titles are
hybrid discs, with versions that run on Windows-based PCs and on
Apple Power Macs and iMacs. Generally, they all come with
technologies that seamlessly modulate the difficulty of problems
with the child's progress, easing the problems where a child has
trouble and stepping up the challenge when he or she has mastered a
level.
</P>
<P>
   Another trend seems to be the inclusion of various throw-in
older educational titles or other goodies, such as videos, that are
included in the box as an added incentive.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly as well, these titles come with Internet
components, like Scholastic's I Spy Online, or even entire for-pay
services, such as the Blaster's Virtual Classroom disc that comes
the Math Blaster and Reading Blaster titles of Knowledge Adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, these titles are designed to make sure children have
a good time playing what seem to be games, even as they are
learning about language, math, problem-solving skills or other
challenges. Here then, with some help from my own two Personal
Entertainment Testing System units, Morningstar and Dakota, are
some titles of recent vintage worth checking out:
</P>
<P>
   Mia 2: Romaine's New Hat is the newest, science-oriented title
from Kutoka Kids, whose first Mia was such a lovely charmer. Again,
we have terrific 3-D graphics far better than are seen in most
children's titles (or any other software, for that matter), with
the sweet-natured mouse Mia once again needing help from the player
to navigate her way home through a challenging world.
</P>
<P>
   Kutoka thoughtfully includes directions for ``big kids'' to make
sure the little ones don't get frustrated at certain key points,
and there's a nice array of activities that teach children in the
early grades of school about various science issues. My two love
it, and it's easy to see why. It's a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Knowledge Adventure has long put out well-regarded educational
software that focuses on either specific subjects or grade levels.
</P>
<P>
   Its Math Blaster and Reading Blaster titles continue to impress,
each loaded with 300 lessons covering a wide range of reading or
math issues, and targeted to age spreads of a couple of years each.
</P>
<P>
   The company also is behind the seemingly omnipresent JumpStart
educational series, which now features titles for children as young
as 18 months up to sixth graders. The two-disc JumpStart First
Grade Deluxe covers a wide array of subjects, including music and
art, and comes with a separate videotape.
</P>
<P>
   (Another word to tech-anxious parents: there's little evidence
that your child will be forever stunted if she isn't working the
computer by her 19th month. (Her 19th (BEGIN ITAL)year(END ITAL)
might be another situation, but hey, Luddites need love, too.)
Particularly for the youngest children, (BEGIN ITAL)any(END ITAL)
computer interaction should be when they get interested, not when
you get anxious. They'll get interested soon enough just watching
you use the machine.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the toddler titles from both JumpStart and Disney
Interactive are nicely done, with lots of brightly illustrated,
simple activities for children who don't yet read but are starting
to get familiar with their ABCs, numbers, music and more.
</P>
<P>
   Disney relies on its stable of beloved characters to enliven
titles such as Mickey Mouse Preschool and Buzz Lightyear's Second
Grade. The characters provide familiar faces as students work
through math, reading, art and other activities.
</P>
<P>
   Familiar characters also grace two new titles from Infogrames:
Blue's Art Time Activities and Blue's Reading Time Activities. Like
the hit Nickelodeon program ``Blue's Clues'' upon which they are
based, the titles are designed for children between the ages of 3
and 6. They feature Blue the cartoon dog and the genial human host,
Steve, gently walking players through graphically simple but
engaging activities.
</P>
<P>
   Scholastic has updated its terrific but somewhat aging I Spy
title with I Spy School Days, which significantly expands the range
of problems children aged 5 to 9 must solve as they gather clues
that in turn can be used to solve other brain teasers. The puzzles
and other ``brain-building games'' are clever in their
construction, subtly teaching children surprisingly sophisticated
logic skills, among much else.
</P>
<P>
   Scholastic also just released I Spy Junior Puppet Playhouse,
which targets children between the ages of 3 and 5 with on-screen
puppeteering activities and a variety of other rhyming, sorting and
math problems. A playfully primitive graphic look will appeal.
</P>
<P>
   One last note: while all these programs promise to improve a
child's learning and comfort with computers, the best thing you can
do to encourage both is practice ``shoulder-to-shoulder'' learning
with them. Sit down next to your children as they work through the
titles; you'll be amazed what a difference it can make.
</P>
<P>
   _ Morningstar and Dakota Bloom contributed to this article. &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
