<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASTAWAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL `CAST AWAY' BE A SURVIVOR?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use om or after Sept. 10, 2000, by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
 
 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Note to anyone running into director Robert Zemeckis in the next
couple of months: Don't ask him about ``Survivor.'' He's a little
touchy about the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you would be, too, if you had spent two years of your life
on a movie project called ``Cast Away,'' a realistic drama about a
workaholic (Tom Hanks) who winds up marooned on a desert island and
must cope with problems that go beyond the trifling troubles that
Rich and Rudy and the other ``Survivor'' contestants faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie is about one man's spiritual and psychological
journey,'' Zemeckis says. ``There are no tiki torches here, no
radios made from coconut shells.''
</P>
<P>
   Zemeckis shut down production of the film for nearly a year so
Hanks could lose weight and add a beard. In the interim, Zemeckis
and the ``Cast Away'' crew made ``What Lies Beneath,'' a decision
that the director calls an ``exaggerated Roger Corman thing, making
two movies for the price of one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was damn hard,'' Zemeckis says.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks had difficulties of his own losing 50 pounds after beefing
up to the play a prison guard in ``The Green Mile.'' (``In all
honesty, I was as big as a house there for a while,'' Hanks says.)
But worse than the diet, worse than the bushy beard (``It horrifies
people,'' Hanks says, ``and everybody hates it, including me'') was
acting in so many scenes by himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard and pretty lonely sometimes,'' Hanks says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing is,'' he adds, laughing, ``is that you don't
have to memorize so many lines because you're not talking to
anybody.'' (Dec. 22) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6202 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-ARMY-JOURNALIST10-COX     09-08 1468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-JOURNALIST10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One soldier's story
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a party for his Sunday school class, Jim McLaughlin decided
to play a trivia game, asking his two dozen guests to jot down
something the others didn't know about them.
</P>
<P>
   On his own slip of paper, McLaughlin wrote: ``I did what Gore
did in Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was stumped.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Al Gore's campaign publicizing his Vietnam service,
the group would probably be able to guess what McLaughlin meant:
He, like Gore, served as an enlisted Army journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most people would probably not be able to come up with a
job description for a such a position. The Army had reporters in
Vietnam? What for?
</P>
<P>
   Was that some kind of special post for the privileged?
</P>
<P>
   Not so, McLaughlin says. His Vietnam job had its perks, he says,
but it was far from cushy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt very fortunate to come back in good shape, in one
piece,'' says McLaughlin. ``I was around an awful lot of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true, he says, that he and the thousands of other military
reporters and photographers were more fortunate than combat
soldiers. Much of McLaughlin's work consisted of covering ``grip
and grin'' awards ceremonies, held in secure areas. He wrote a lot
of articles about generals pinning Purple Hearts on wounded GIs.
</P>
<P>
   He ate hot meals, enjoyed hot showers, clean
</P>
<P>
   sheets and cold beer. He had women and men who'd clean his
quarters, clothes, offices and shoes for $20 a month.
</P>
<P>
   But he adds that he spent a lot of time traveling around the
country. Many journalists encountered land mines, snipers, even
full-blown firefights. More than 70 civilian reporters and
photographers were killed; no one has a count of casualties among
military journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody over there, if you got off base, you were never
completely safe,'' McLaughlin says.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin rode in truck convoys that came under sniper fire
several times and often hitched rides on helicopters. ``And a lot
of helicopters got shot down,'' McLaughlin says.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin didn't know Al Gore, so he can't directly compare his
war stint with the vice president's. But McLaughlin's tour was
typical what many Army journalists experienced in Vietnam _ a lot
of montony interspersed with serious work, danger and occasional
horror. Their service won the admiration of other vets.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta businessman Duke Doubleday, 57, was a combat officer who
was in the thick of many firefights. He lauds the service of
military journalists, including _ even though he staunchly opposes
Gore politically _ the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reporters I knew, military and civilian, begged to jump on
a helicopter and go with us,'' he says. ``They too were under fire
in countless instances, just doing the jobs they were sent to do.
Rockets, mortars and sapper attacks were not exclusively designed
for designated combat-trained individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Sherman, 58, an Atlanta commercial photographer who ran an
Army photo lab in Vietnam, recalls one journalism assignment, which
seemed safe at the outset. ``Once we went up with a general to
shoot some pictures,'' he says, ``and we found some snipers.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Sherman: ``Just being in-country could limit your life real
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin was drafted in June 1967, only weeks after earning an
advertising degree from Southern Illinois University. ``It was
pretty shocking, even though I'd expected it,'' he says. He was
engaged to his college girlfriend at the time. (The couple waited
until his return in 1969 to marry. He and his wife, Jane, now have
a college-age son.)
</P>
<P>
   He was sent to clerk-typist school, but the Army changed his
military-occupational speciality to ``information specialist''
after he arrived in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fluke ... I guess because I had a background in
journalism. Nobody ever said.'' But McLaughlin was delighted. ``I
was actually doing something of substance, as opposed to just
typing out orders or commendation awards.''
</P>
<P>
   The job involved filing stories, often about awards or the
heroism of individual soldiers, for use by hometown newspapers. So
military journalists were popular among grunts, even though they
were sometimes derided for being able to return to the safety of
their bases.
</P>
<P>
   They also kept tabs on the brass. ``If I was going to go out
with a general,'' McLaughlin recalls, ``we'd call his driver and
ask, where is he going today? We'd drive behind his jeep in a press
truck.''
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, the Army reporters would get stories in the
official newspaper Stars &AMP; Stripes. ``Getting in Stars &AMP; Stripes
was like hitting a home run,'' says McLaughlin, showing off a few
clips at his upscale home near Walton High School.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to writing, Army journalists had to take regular
turns manning guard towers with M-16 carbines. One night, that duty
got McLaughlin caught in a firefight. About 1 a.m., the Viet Cong
attacked a nearby mountain, and McLaughlin, along with other
guards, was ordered aboard a chopper that took him to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get thrown into a situation like that, it gets really
kind of scary,'' he says. ``You're trying to think, but there's so
much going on around you. You've got our jets coming in shooting
tracers, and that lights up the sky. You can't see very well.
You're scrambling around to get someplace where you've got some
protection.''
</P>
<P>
   The VC, as was their practice, fled at dawn. When the fight
ended, McLaughlin found that a fellow GI had faked his death so
well that an enemy soldier had stolen his wristwatch.
</P>
<P>
   That indicent proved to be an aberration for McLaughlin. Though
he pulled occasional guard duty, he was never in combat again.
``Let's say the firefight wasn't the highlight of my tour,'' he
says. ``But that's what you do if you're an enlisted guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the time, the journalists stayed in their compounds, as
depicted in the Stanley Kubrick movie ``Full Metal Jacket.'' The
days passed slowly, and were often monotonous.
</P>
<P>
   Days began with breakfast at 6 a.m., and journalists were on
duty from 7 a.m. to 7 p.m. He lived in a barracks with about 10
other men, but was allowed to wall off his own bedroom. ``The
lifers, the career guys, stayed at one end. We stayed toward the
other. You put up your mosquito netting and that was that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some days, nothing happened, but American headquarters in Saigon
demanded at least one story a day from his group, no matter how
trivial.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, life on base was ``pretty comfortable,'' McLaughlin
says. ``Most of the time I could go to the rec room and drink a
beer. We had an air-conditioned photo lab with a refrigerator for
cold beer, and basically since we had film to trade, we could get
things like fresh lobster, bread, clothing. The bathroom had
running water, showers, but no flush toilets.''
</P>
<P>
   There was even a beach nearby, but it was too polluted to enjoy
very much. McLaughlin wrote to his fiancee in Illinois almost every
day. There was a Red Cross library at the base, and he read all he
could.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin says he often volunteered to jump on a truck or
chopper _ ``just to get out and see things so you wouldn't be wired
to a desk all day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out on the road more than some of the others, not
because I was out to earn some Silver Star or Purple Heart, but I
just enjoyed being out and about,'' McLaughlin says. ``I liked the
airplanes, the choppers, getting the human-interest stories, seeing
what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Military journalists carried .45-caliber pistols and, but toted
M-16 carbines like the grunts when pulling guard duty. McLaughlin
can't remember whether he fired his M-16 that dark morning on the
mountain, but adds: ``I don't think I ever fired my .45. Not
once.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he did experience the horrors of war, and not just during
his night in combat. Pointing out a photo taken by his partner of
dead enemy soldiers, McLaughlin says he remembers vividly being
sickened at the scene. The Viet Cong, he adds, had been ``gunned
down in cold blood'' by South Korean allies of the South
Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impression that's stayed with me was all of the Vietnamese
people surrounding the bodies, oohing and aahing.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses: ``It's funny that until you got close to coming home,
you didn't worry too much about the danger. However, essentially,
it was around you most every day if you went off post to do a
story.''
</P>
<P>
   JIM McLAUGHLIN FILE
</P>
<P>
   Age: 55
</P>
<P>
   Family: Married to college sweetheart Jane Hughson. One son,
David, 21.
</P>
<P>
   Residence: East Cobb County, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Military service: Drafted 1967. Served as Army reporter in
Vietnam. Honorably discharged 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Occupation: Sales executive, Owens-Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
