<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEXAS REMAINS RESILIENT ABOUT BREAKING RETURN RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK WANGRIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Each night Ivan Williams relaxes, closes his
eyes and dreams.
</P>
<P>
   He calls it visualization, but when you're trying to visualize
what he is, maybe dreaming is more accurate. That or hallucinating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play the game in my head,'' the University of Texas kickoff
returner says, momentarily putting himself in character. ``I see
the opening kickoff. I see the ball in the air. I see myself
catching it. Everything that can possibly happen.''
</P>
<P>
   His eyes pop open and he frowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lately,'' he said sheepishly, ``I've been visualizing getting
tripped up by the kicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the lot of a UT kick returner, burdened not just with
weaving his way through 10 kamikaze pilots in cleats but by the
nation's longest streak without a return score _ 254 games and
counting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been too long,'' Williams said of the streak, which
measures 674 attempts. ``Now is the time. Twenty-two years is a
long time. Most of us weren't even born.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, only 12 scholarship Longhorns were alive when
Johnny ``Lam'' Jones went 99 yards for a score against Southern
Methodist on Oct. 23, 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The Horns call their return team ``Quick Six,'' and they break
the pre-kickoff huddle with the chant, ``Take it to the house.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Quick six _ that's what it is,'' Williams said. ``It can
happen in 13 seconds, 15 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Or it can not happen in 693,792,000 seconds, give or take a
couple hundred thousand.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of such abject frustration, the Horns are nothing if
not resilient.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, speedy Montrell Flowers vowed to take one back for a
touchdown on opening night against North Carolina State. He wound
up returning two all year _ for a total of 31 yards.
</P>
<P>
   This year, speedy Victor Ike will be the main returner. Asked if
he learned anything from Flowers' boasts a year ago, Ike said, ``If
we do what we can do, what ability is, we'll take one to the
house.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he added: ``We have a whole season.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, returning kickoffs has rarely been easier.
Last year in NCAA Division I-A, 90.1 percent of all kickoffs were
returned, the highest figure since 1956. Of those 4,554 returns, 40
went for touchdowns. The average return was 20.3 yards,
fourth-highest since the NCAA began keeping the statistic in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   Texas tight ends coach Tim Brewster, who doubles as kickoff
return coach, is well aware of the streak. He doesn't emphasize it,
knowing that each failed attempt would only add to the pressure.
All he stresses is that his charges average the 30-yard-line per
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think it's incredible at the University of Texas to
have a streak that long, with all the great returners we've had. ''
Brewster said. ``Everybody understands it doesn't happen often. If
you have one or two (a year), you've done real well.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the two deep backs, the 240-pound Williams is supposed to
lead the 200-pound Ike into the wedge and, hopefully, a seam.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we're looking for is a crease,'' Brewster said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brewster said the Horns have gone with bigger returners this
year because on every return they'll have to break at least one
tackle. ``In Ivan Williams and Victor Ike we've got two strong
backs,'' he said. ``You can't block everybody on a kickoff return,
so you've got to have guys who can run through an arm tackle and
then run away from everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Return teams have to be at once optimistic and prepared for
disappointment. Williams is perhaps better suited for it than most,
having returned five kickoffs for touchdowns in high school.
</P>
<P>
   Four of which were called back.
</P>
<P>
   Patience will, like glaciers, eventually prevail. Entering their
1987 game against Georgia Tech, the Clemson Tigers hadn't taken a
punt back for a score in 17 years; a kickoff return in 25.
</P>
<P>
   The streak stood at 999 combined returns when Joe Henderson took
a Tech kickoff 95 yards for a score. Minutes later, teammate
Donnell Woolford took a punt back 78 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he also visualizes the day the Horns take one back
(though it might not come this week _ Louisiana-Lafayette hasn't
allowed a TD return since 1989).
</P>
<P>
   When it does happen, the party on the sideline will be grand,
Williams promised. But on the field, it will be like any other
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hand the ball to the ref, let it be known I'd been there
before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He paused.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, it's been a while,'' he said. ``But we HAVE been there
before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
