<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLASTIC-SURGERY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECK OUT PLASTIC SURGERY CREDENTIALS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use after Mon., Sept. 11, 2000, by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
 
 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a good idea to check the professional and educational
background of any doctor you plan to consult or hire. Especially in
plastic surgery, where the person charging you thousands of dollars
to fix your appearance may have had the bulk of his or her training
in gynecology or even dentistry.
</P>
<P>
   In the state of California, any doctor licensed as a physician
and surgeon can legally perform any surgical procedure on an
outpatient basis, says Dr. Thomas R. Stevenson, president of the
California Society of Plastic Surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real bellwether is if the doctor has hospital
privileges,'' says Stevenson, professor and chief of plastic
surgery at UC Davis. ``Hospitals have much more stringent criteria
for privileges. They wouldn't let me do neurosurgery at this or any
other hospital unless I proved I was qualified.''
</P>
<P>
   If a plastic surgeon claims to be board certified, patients
should ask his field of certification, say officials from the
American Society of Plastic Surgeons _ the educational branch of
the American Board of Plastic Surgery (ABPS). The answer will
determine how much and what type of training the doctor has
received.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people deserve to understand that there are
boards that are legitimate and real and others that are sort of
contrived,'' says Dr. C. Lin Puckett, president of the American
Board of Plastic Surgeons and professor of plastic surgery at the
University of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``American people who are seeking cosmetic surgery or any other
kind of plastic surgery are probably sophisticated enough to ask if
someone is board certified. They are not necessarily sophisticated
enough to differentiate when that individual says, `Yes, I'm
certified by the Two-Step Board of Plastic Surgery.'''
</P>
<P>
   In order to receive certification in plastic surgery from the
ABPS, members must have graduated from an accredited medical school
and completed at least five years of additional training: three in
general surgery, two in plastic surgery. They have practiced
plastic surgery for an additional two years and passed
comprehensive written and oral exams. Certification must be renewed
every seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Both medical doctors (MDs) and doctors of osteopathy (DOs) can
earn board certification from the ABPS. Osteopathy is a system of
healing that emphasizes manipulation (as of joints) but does not
exclude other uses of medicine or surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Osteopaths can also gain certification in plastic surgery
through the American Osteopathic Association (AOA) by undergoing
two years of training in plastic and reconstructive surgery
following three years of training in surgery or an AOA-approved and
completed residency program in orthopedic surgery or an
AOA-approved and completed residency in otolaryngology/facial
plastic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   In order to be certified through the American Board of Facial
Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery, a doctor has to have previous
certification from the ABPS or the American Board of
Otolaryngology. The doctor will have graduated from a residency
approved by the Accreditation Council for Graduate Medical
Education (ACGME), been in private practice for two years in facial
plastic surgery, and have passed written and oral exams. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1404EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6219 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-SOLOMON-H     09-08 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-SOLOMON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ROMEO, JULIET WITH A WELSH TWIST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Note cast box below)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paul Morrison's ``Solomon and Gaenor,'' set in a Welsh mining
town, has the look of a Dickensian bowl of cold gruel. But the film
is in the key of ``Romeo and Juliet,'' and it's a one-note tune.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon (Ioan Gruffudd) is a door-to-door fabric salesman.
Gaenor (Nia Roberts) is the penniless girl on the other side of one
of those doors. He offers her a swatch, she declines, he shows up
the next day with a dress, which he pulled an all-nighter to
finish. Innocuously batted eyelashes give way to heavy petting
which turns into a roll in the hay which results in a pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   The skies are permanently gray so the forecast calls for
drizzles of tragedy. Wait _ Solomon hasn't told Gaenor he is the
son of an Orthodox Jew? Make that a downpour. He hasn't even told
her his name is Solomon, instead slipping her the gentile pseudonym
Sam Livingston.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Morrison has the broken hearts in the right
places and the secrets percolating on the stove. But the film,
while socially progressive (she is quick to give it up, while he
seems to have no intention of asking for her hand), is crippled by
us-against-the-world deck-stacking. Gruffudd, who played Horatio
Hornblower for the BBC, and Roberts, in her first film, spark
intensity and can usually be seen alluding to a third dimension for
their ill-drawn characters. However, the folks around Solomon and
Gaenor (parents, siblings, a reverend, etc.) are of brittle,
villainous stock. Their vocation is to tip the sympathy scales in
favor of our young sweethearts through their contempt.
</P>
<P>
   And it works. But is this really how we want to root for a pair
of lovers: in response to how much the people around them detest
their love?
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the affair is nicely, if not redeemingly, situated
around a miners' strike that results in anti-Semitic vandalism, one
of whose targets is Solomon's father's pawnshop. Of all the
occasions here to use a heavy hand (there are enough to leave us
feeling morally spanked), Morrison chooses to push the gloomy
romance. Mechanical storytelling and scandal-mongering are
preferred over intimacy, but you can see Morrison reaching beyond
Shakespeare for Thomas Hardy-caliber disaster.
</P>
<P>
   He is a traditionalist, though, with overly familiar ideas about
how to keep people apart, sexually, familially, geographically. He
even throws in an inexplicably dopey finale that barely fulfills
the portended doom. You wish the film had a trace of rebellion,
spontaneity or anger. Otherwise, it's not clear whether people
start dying out of love or obligation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Solomon and Gaenor''
</P>
<P>
   CAST Ioan Gruffudd, Nia Roberts
</P>
<P>
   WRITER-DIRECTOR Paul Morrison
</P>
<P>
   RATED R
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
