   TIRE-RECALL (Washington) _ Developments in the recall of
Bridgestone/Firestone tires. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-MICROPHONES (Tula, Russia) _ Most Soviet-era enterprises
in Russia are struggling to shed outdated equipment and oversized
workforces. They cannot hope to compete on the global market
because their products are of poor quality. But the Oktava company
has used Soviet-era expertise to become a thriving producer of
microphones. Since it began exporting in 1994, its revenue has more
than doubled and U.S. and British rock musicians prize the
microphones, praising their quality even if they are ugly. By
Sabrina Tavernise.
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLERCHRYSLER-MITSUBISHI (Tokyo) _ DaimlerChrysler moves to
tighten its control over Mitsubishi Motors, the troubled automaker
that is reeling from last month's disclosure that it concealed
customer complaints and auto defects for more than two decades,
DaimlerChrysler says it will pay 10 percent less for its 34 percent
stake in Mitsubishi. Mitsubishi Motors' president steps down, as
expected. As Renault did with Nissan, DaimlerChrysler, installs its
rail unit chief as Mitsubishi's chief operating officer and sends
other managers to Tokyo. By Miki Tanikawa.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-WALMART (Frankfurt) _ German regulators have ordered
Wal-Mart to raise prices, blaming the retailer for a price war.
Germany's cartel office has found that Wal-Mart and two smaller
retailers were selling some food products at below cost. By Edmund
L. Andrews.
</P>
