<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6264 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-ANNIVE     09-08 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-ANNIVERSARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A YEAR AFTER TRAGEDY AT WEDGWOOD BAPTIST, THE PAIN REMAINS FRESH
FOR SOME
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JIM JONES 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ It has been a painful and exciting year for
the Rev. Al Meredith and his congregation at Wedgwood Baptist
Church.
</P>
<P>
   Meredith, his congregation and a nation have mourned the deaths
of eight people and the wounding of seven others in the Sept. 15,
1999, shooting at the Fort Worth church.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past year, the church has flourished, and Meredith
has taken the message of faith during life's darkest hours to
secular and religious groups nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   As compelled as Meredith is to extend that message, he also
looks forward to spending more time shepherding his flock after the
first anniversary of the shootings. Some Wedgwood members have
mixed feelings about the approaching anniversary and memorials
planned for next week, church administrator Mike Holton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a milestone we will be glad to get past,'' said Holton,
who survived because a bullet fired by gunman Larry Gene Ashbrook
hit a metal door facing during the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some of us,'' Meredith said, ``it is as fresh as the day
it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Meredith's face and words of faith were flashed on TV screens
across America in the days after the shooting spree in a sanctuary
full of youth celebrating See You at the Pole, an annual observance
at schools during which young people publicly display their
Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hearts are broken but not crushed,'' Meredith declared at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   Holton said, ``People have discovered Al all over the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In his message at conventions and other gatherings, Meredith has
emphasized that even horrific times can't quash the human spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has bowled me over is the requests I have to speak from
nonchurch organizations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meredith flew to Detroit recently and spoke to 240 salespeople
employed by a phone company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave them my sales pitch, too,'' he said. ``I share the
Gospel. A lot of those salespeople don't go to church anywhere. I
tell them about my faith. If they don't like that, I tell them
don't ask me to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   Meredith recently took a weeklong vacation at a friend's
oceanfront condo in Florida, where he played tennis and golf every
day. Even then, he made time to speak at two churches about the
lessons of Wedgwood.
</P>
<P>
   His many speaking engagements have stolen time from his church,
Meredith lamented.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been as good a pastor to the folks here, and I hate
that,'' he said. ``I'm not here to go to hospitals, counsel with
individuals. Others have had to take up the slack.''
</P>
<P>
   He plans to cut back on his speaking, but he doesn't regret the
opportunity to extend his message beyond Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to share the story of God's grace that we
experienced,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Average attendance at Wedgwood's Sunday services has grown from
800 to more than 1,200. And, many new converts are now a part of
the 2,000-member church.
</P>
<P>
   ``A man came forward for conversion this month who had been
resisting faith, and his life had fallen apart,'' Meredith related.
``A week before the shootings he had been visited by Shawn Brown,
one of the people who were killed.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the kind of story he shares on the road and will impart
during anniversary appearances in the coming week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an example of good coming out of evil,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wedgwood church members have had a variety of responses since
the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody grieves in their own way,'' Meredith said.
``Everybody's pain is unique. Some of our kids won't talk about it
at all. Others will talk about it with anyone who will listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Counselors have talked to the congregation, and members have
been encouraged to reach out to those who grieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church is the body of Christ and the family of God,''
Meredith said. ``We minister to each other. You just love folks,
hold onto each other without trying to offer any words of advice or
counsel. We let them know we share their grief.''
</P>
<P>
   Some church members have recovered from the shock, but the
anniversary will trigger traumatic memories. Many want to put the
traumatic events behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some think we might be fixating on it,'' Meredith said. ``So
you try to find a balance.''
</P>
<P>
   The anniversary ``can be a real opportunity for healing, or it
can be a real opportunity for opening an old wound and letting it
fester some more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a real tender, sensitive time for those whose
family members were killed,'' he said. ``And yet, the Lord can use
that as a real time of healing. If you stuff your grief, it festers
on you. If you can deal with it, embrace it, then God can make it
good grief.''
</P>
<P>
   Meredith said the tragedy has deepened the church's resolve to
take the message of Christian hope to more people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are thinking of a new senior adult ministry,'' he said.
``The neighborhood we live in has more people over 65 than just
about any area. The average age of our members is 27 or 28. We are
such a young church we could use some more gray heads.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the shooting, other Wedgwood members have ministered
beyond the church walls.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Galey, a Wedgwood counselor who was severely wounded, went
to Thailand to speak to a group of churches. Jay Fannin, the
church's youth minister, has spoken at rallies for young people
across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five of our girls were invited to go to Australia to help
prepare churches to witness during the upcoming Olympics,''
Meredith said. ``On the way back, they stopped in Hawaii and led a
youth rally. That's positive. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``If God can use your tragedy to help other people, it gives
some sense of purpose about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some have called Wedgwood a ``miracle church'' because it
emerged so rapidly from its loss. Ashbrook fired hundreds of rounds
and had ammunition left when he took his own life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of the miracle is that we didn't have 50 funerals,''
Meredith said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, during the church's 40th anniversary celebration, the
congregation dedicated a $3.2 million building project that was
begun before the shooting. The expansion will include a community
life center with a full-size gymnasium, walking track, banquet area
and more classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Meredith said his wife, Kay, often says that he and church
members should guard against any impression that they are boasting
about Wedgwood Baptist's quick rise out of the catastrophic event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not that Wedgwood is such a great church,'' he said.
``It is that God is such a great God. God can give grace in the
midst of the darkest tragedy _ the most unthinkable things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of that awful evil, God is still doing much good. That's
the true miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
