<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6277 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-LOVE-SEX-     09-08 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-LOVE-SEX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `LOVE &AMP; SEX' REVEALS SOME TRUTHS ABOUT RELATIONSHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. ALLEN JOHNSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Famke Janssen, who squeezed men to death with her legs as a
villain in the James Bond flick ``Goldeneye,'' merely talks them to
death in ``Love &AMP; Sex.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Love is a minefield,'' Kate Welles (Janssen) tells us in the
opening narration of writer-director Valerie Breiman's sharply
written reverse-image of Woody Allen's ``Annie Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You take a step, get blown to pieces, put yourself back
together again and stupidly take another step. I guess that's human
nature. It hurts so much to be alone we'd rather get blown up than
remain single.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, we need the eggs, and that's not the only
``Annie Hall'' reminder. Kate, like Alvy Singer, is a writer, and
relates her sexual history in a loose flashback structure.
``Nosferatu,'' the original German Expressionist silent, obsesses
her as ``The Sorrow and the Pity'' torments Alvy. There's even a
memorable scene in a yellow Volkswagen recalling Annie's bad
driving.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Love &AMP; Sex'' finds its own way to deliver some truths
about relationships. Kate is moody, brash and hilarious _ she
describes herself as knowing more about oral sex than
relationships. But she's not an over-the-top, in-your-face Angelina
Jolie-esque creation. She's a normal, young, single woman who
happens to be attractive, living in Los Angeles, and looking for
the right guy.
</P>
<P>
   Janssen, the talented Dutch-born actress, neurotically powers
her way through a performance that displays keen intelligence,
wicked wit and a weakness for kittens. In so doing, she has pulled
off a unique double: She's in the summer's best Hollywood action
film, ``X-Men,'' and now she charges ahead in one of the best
independent movies.
</P>
<P>
   Kate meets an artist, Adam (Jon Favreau), who is so struck by
her at his own exhibition that he literally wills her to be his
girlfriend. Soon, they cohabit, and his insecurities begin to wear
on Kate. In trading information, Adam says he has slept with two
girls previously, while Kate causes his jaw drop by admitting she
has slept with a baker's dozen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirteen!'' Adam exclaims. ``You're like a whore!''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's how guys think.
</P>
<P>
   The on-again, off-again relationship allows Breiman (who
presumably didn't get the leeway to flesh out deep issues in her
fleshy first two films, ``Going Overboard'' _ Adam Sandler's first
film in 1989 _ and ``Bikini Squad,'' in 1993) to explore the
ever-present fear of being alone and her central theme: How do you
know when you're in the ``forever'' relationship?
</P>
<P>
   Favreau and Janssen don't look like a couple, but their precise
comic timing and enthusiasm are believable, and they develop real
chemistry (so much so that Favreau cast Janssen in his directorial
debut, ``Made,'' to be released in 2001). It helps that the
dialogue is hip, natural and observational, elements that allow
Favreau to excel.
</P>
<P>
   The plot conventions, which include an unwanted pregnancy, and
the initial cause of her flashbacks (some nonsense about Kate being
fired by her editor unless she writes a story about love that she
really believes, yeah right) _ are mere window dressing for what we
already know: These two belong together, and we want them to be
together.
</P>
<P>
   Relationships are indeed confusing, and ``Love &AMP; Sex'' does a
great job in showing how we tend to make them more complicated than
they really are. In simple truth, the right relationship is someone
you are able to ``feel normal around,'' as Adam says at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Question is, just what is normal?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Love &AMP; Sex''
</P>
<P>
   CAST Famke Janssen, Jon Favreau
</P>
<P>
   WRITER-DIRECTOR Valerie Breiman
</P>
<P>
   RATED R
</P>
</TEXT>
