<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6285 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS &LR;      09-08 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NOBODY'S HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HELEN THOMAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There's nobody at home at the White House these
days. Lame duckism is setting in. The White House, so often
described by former occupants as the loneliest place in the world,
has certainly taken on that aura.
</P>
<P>
   Except for their personal belongings, the Clintons seem to have
already moved out of the Executive Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady has been AWOL for several months as she pursues
her campaign for a Senate seat from New York. She has established a
residence in posh Westchester County, north of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   She drops in at the White House every once in a while, mainly to
be on hand for official state functions. She is expected to be
hostess at the Sept. 17 state dinner in honor of Indian President
Atal Vajpaya. It's payback time for the royal treatment she
received on two trips to the subcontinent.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, meantime, is keeping up his heavy fundraising
and travel schedule, making him an absentee chief executive much of
the time. He appears a bit forlorn to be on the bench while Vice
President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush are playing
starring roles in a high-stakes struggle to succeed him. He
wistfully told friends recently that this was the first Labor Day
in 26 years that he did not march in a parade.
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea, daughter of the first couple, also is generally absent
from 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue, even though she took a sabbatical
from Stanford University this semester to savor the family's last
days in the White House, as press secretary Joe Lockhart put it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she is spending the fall helping her mother campaign or
she's sitting in as her father's guest at high-powered meetings
with foreign leaders both abroad and at home, more recently at the
millenium summit in New York.
</P>
<P>
   When told that Chelsea's presence at some of the private meeting
was annoying to some foreign delegations, Lockhart shrugged and
said: ``So what?''
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea's new boyfriend, Jeremy Kane, also a senior at Stanford,
has been traveling with the family as an intern with the
speechwriting staff.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is giving Clinton a wide berth. In fact, the Gore team
frankly wants the president to ``butt out'' and not become a
Republican target in the election campaign. Whenever Bush talks
about the need ``to restore honor'' to the White House, he is
hoping voters will remember that Gore was Clinton's enthusiastic
supporter during the impeachment controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton still has some legislative clout in his final months in
office. He mustered enough Democratic votes to sustain his veto of
the repeal of the estate tax and is likely to win other veto
showdowns in the next month.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and the Republican-controlled Congress will likely agree
on appropriations bills to avoid any government shutdown like that
of 1995-1996. And there are indications Congress may give in to the
president's appeal for an $1 increase in the minimum wage,
currently at $5.15, over two years. To that, I say: Better late
than never. Passage of ``hate crimes'' legislation still may be
possible.
</P>
<P>
   On the foreign policy front, Clinton seems to have struck out in
his drive for a final Middle East peace settlement. Time is running
out on all fronts for the president.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons, who have lived most of their married lives in what
they facetiously call ``public housing,'' were fearful when they
moved into the White House that they would lose their privacy.
``I'm not going to live in a bubble,'' the president said as he
left Little Rock after his 1992 election. Well, he was sure wrong
about that.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Centre College in Danville, Ky. is still hoping to host a debate
between the vice presidential candidates, Democrat Joe Lieberman
and Republican Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   The college is the site designated by the unofficial Commission
on Presidential Debates for an Oct. 5 faceoff between the two
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman as accepted but no word so far from Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Patsi Trollinger, spokesman for the college, said the small town
has spent $700,000 to prepare for the big event. Centre College's
great claim to fame is that its football team beat Harvard, 6 to 0,
in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lady Bird Johnson will be showing up in Virginia pretty soon to
help her son-in-law Sen. Charles Robb, who is married to her
daughter Lynda Bird, in his tough reelection campaign. The
87-year-old former first lady became a political pro in 1964 when
she undertook a 4-day whistlestop train tour through the South
during Lyndon B. Johnson's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The former first lady has created a wildflower center, just
outside of Austin. A group of schoolchildren recently visited the
center and were shown a portrait of Mrs. Johnson. ``That's Mother
Nature,'' piped up one little boy. It was a fitting tribute for the
woman who made national beautification her major project in the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helen Thomas can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address helent &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1512EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6288 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBA-OLYMPICS-0909-CO     09-08 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-OLYMPICS-0909-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DESPITE HARDSHIPS, CUBANS DREAMS OF OLYMPIC GOLD - BEATING THE
U.S.
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMONAR, Cuba _ The old men sit on chairs under the awning of
the gas station, swapping lies and looking for all the world like
characters straight off the ``Andy Griffith Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Except they're speaking Spanish, and they aren't talking about
fishing or hunting or the latest misadventures of the sheriff's
loopy sidekick.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, their main topic is the same thing that's dominating
Cuba's airwaves, not to mention the non-stop dialogue that hums on
street corners, under shade trees and any place else that a handful
of this talk-happy island's residents gather.
</P>
<P>
   The old men, in this small town about 100 miles east of Havana,
are talking about the upcoming Sydney Olympics. And like any
die-hard Georgia Bulldog or Texas Longhorns or Florida Gator
football fan, they are firmly convinced their team is going to win,
and win big.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuba has great athletes and the Olympics are our chance to
show the world,'' said Miguel Alvarez, who sees more customers come
to the gas station to air up bicycle tires than to buy gasoline.
``The world already knows that we love sports, and now we will get
to prove it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even for those Cubans who don't love sports, it appears
impossible to avoid the growing Olympic fever.
</P>
<P>
   The nightly news program on Cuban State television is filled
with long blocks of reporting on past Olympic glory and the status
of the current team. A banner hung outside the National Sports City
complex in Havana urges the team ``To Sydney for the glory of the
Motherland.''
</P>
<P>
   Cubans have always been sports fanatics, with a near-legendary
love for baseball. But ever since Fidel Castro's 1959 revolution,
they've had the active encouragement of their government, which
early on identified sports as a key element in its vision for an
egalitarian, socialist society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sport is the right of the people,'' Castro declared shortly
after the revolution, a quotation that now graces the walls of many
of Cuba's local stadiums. ``We must inundate every corner of the
island with sports equipment. We should strive to improve our
athletes rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort has been successful.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the performance of Cuban athletes has been
remarkable, especially in the Olympic Games. Despite being one of
the world's smaller countries, with a population of only 11
million, Cuban athletes took home 31 Olympic medals in 1992's
Barcelona games, placing fifth among all nations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 in Atlanta, Cuba won 25 medals, placing eighth in the
world rankings.
</P>
<P>
   But like everything else in Cuba, sport is tinged with politics.
</P>
<P>
   Castro touts his teams' successes, partly out of rightful pride,
but also likely as a way to pump up his citizens _ and divert their
attention _ as the nation struggles toward recovering from the 1991
collapse of its long-time communist sponsor, the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the continuing saga of Cuban athletes who defect
to the U.S. or other nations, hoping to cash in their talents for
the big riches other Western athletes enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Ever wary of the negative propaganda impact of such defections,
Cuban officials warned their departing 240-member Olympic team to
guard against the ``blackmail, bribery and harassment'' they might
face in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuba will continue to battle to restore the true principles of
the Olympic spirit, will continue to denounce corruption and to
attack the mercantilism which is currently defiling and curtailing
the full development of sports as an expression of friendship and
relations between nations,'' Cuba's Foreign Minister Felipe Perez
Roque told the Olympic team at their send-off.
</P>
<P>
   No one questions that Cuban athletes make peanuts compared to
stars in many other nations. Top Cuban athletes are paid US$25 per
month. That's more than double the average Cuban's monthly wage of
US$10, but far short of the millions many professional American
athletes earn.
</P>
<P>
   And the Cubans train just as hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secret of our success is that we start with the very young
and we work very hard,'' said Augustin Avila, a former player for
the Cuban national baseball team and now coach of a squad of 15- to
16-year-olds in Havana. ``We practice every day, two to three
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Cuban system of sports development is something akin
to the scouting and minor-league system employed by American Major
League Baseball teams. Perhaps that's because Castro himself was a
promising baseball pitcher who was voted ``Athlete of the Year'' in
1944 at his university.
</P>
<P>
   Just as in the U.S., teams of scouts work the circuit throughout
Cuba, going to elementary schools to identify youngsters with
above-average potential. But not just in baseball. The most
talented kids in basketball, volleyball, track, gymnastics and
other sports are tapped to apply for a School for Sports
Initiation, where they attend regular academic classes but also get
advanced coaching.
</P>
<P>
   The best from that level graduate to one of the nation's Schools
of Higher Athletic Performance, another setting for intensive
training. From there, ambitious kids hope to catch the eye of a
coach or scout from one of the major city teams or a national team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone here wants to play for the Cuban Olympic team,'' said
14-year-old Antonio Ciscard of Havana, who plays on Avila's team.
``It's our dream _ that, and to beat the Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   The enthusiasm seems just as strong in Cuba's rural towns like
this one, where some people plan on crowding into the homes of
friends or neighbors who have televisions in order to watch the
games.
</P>
<P>
   In Limonar, the men at the gas station are certain that one of
the Cubans who will bring home a gold medal will be record-holding
high-jumper Javier Sotomayor, who grew up in their tiny town and
whose mother lives in a neat, two-story home across the street.
</P>
<P>
   They dismiss Sotomayor's alleged positive results on a drug test
last year, focussing instead on the fact that international
officials have cleared him to compete in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a regular guy,'' Miguel Alvarez said. ``We know him
here because he comes home all the time to visit his mother. We're
going to watch the Olympics on television, and we're sure he will
win again.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams' E-mail address is: mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
