 ATTN: Style and Leisure Editors:  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, April 16, and thereafter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BURNING-MAN (Black Rock Desert, Nev.) _ There aren't many rules
at Burning Man _ the weeklong cyberhippie carnival in the middle of
the Nevada desert that ended on Labor Day. Burning Man, as you may
or may not know, is devoted to ``radical self-expression.'' In 1986
its founder, Larry Harvey, burned a stick-man effigy on a Bay Area
beach after breaking up with his girlfriend. As the pyrocentric
event grew into an annual rite, authorities told Harvey to take his
followers elsewhere. Now, 25,000 of them make the pilgrimage to the
Black Rock Desert, a vast dry lake bed 120 miles north of Reno.
Artists. Performers. College kids. Partyers. Techno-geeks. Ravers.
Neo-paganists. Dot-com yuppies. Professional and amateur nudists.
The effigy has grown to a 40-foot neon skeleton stuffed with wood
and fireworks, whose spectacular torching is the event's
ritualistic climax. By Rick Marin.
</P>
<P>
   LA-CARAVELLE (New York) _ La Caravelle, which opened with a
$5.50 prix fixe lunch and $7.50 dinner, celebrates its 40th
anniversary this month. A New York institution, it has stood as a
marker of a bygone era of glamour. But rather than settling into
dinosaur status, it has actually hung around long enough to be back
in style again. By Alex Witchel.
</P>
<P>
   UPSCALE-TEEN-FASHION (New York) _ Armed with unprecedented
personal incomes and a precocious knowledge of what women a decade
older consider chic, the upward-striving teen-ager is the newest
target of luxury marketers who once focused strictly on adults.
Chanel, Ralph Lauren, Lancome and Versace are all making a play for
the teen-age market, as is Bobbi Brown, the makeup artist behind an
upscale department store line, whose recent volume of makeup tips,
``Bobbi Brown Teen-age Beauty'' is on The New York Times list of
best-selling children's books. By Ruth LaFerla.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GIRDLE-GIRLS (New York) _ As unlikely as it may seem, the
celebrated life of the Park Avenue princess has infiltrated the
bohemian Brooklyn enclave of Williamsburg, in the form of the
Girdle Girls, a club of women living it up in ladylike high style.
By Heather Chaplin.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ In September, the sunlit garden blazes
with strong colors: dark red dahlias, deep plum-colored gladioli,
brilliant yellow rudbeckias towering over orange canna flowers. But
the real star of autumn doesn't start shining until dusk, when the
nicotianas pick up their drooping heads, open their white throats
and pour perfume into the darkening air. By Leslie Land.
</P>
