<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6297 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MTV-AWARDS09-COX     09-08 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTV-AWARDS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Skin, slams and protests: MTV
 &HT;    By Chris Riemenschneider
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It had more lip-synching than ``Solid Gold,'' more flesh-baring
than ``Sex and the City,'' more backstabbing than ``Survivor,'' and
enough Eminem to put the PTA on red-alert.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 MTV Music Video Awards _ shown live Thursday from New
York's Radio City Music Hall, and bound to rerun as often as the
Backstreet Boys'' Burger King commercials _ as usual met the cable
station's quota for fast, bleeped and out-of-control entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesome, the three-hour event was not. Aerosmith's Steven
Tyler explicitly addressed the sex life of MTV personality Carson
Daly; Sisqo performed his over-worn underwear hit ``Thong Song.''
Even teenyboppers Britney Spears and Christina Aguilera showed
their wild sides in separate, feisty performances (Spears also
displayed her back-side).
</P>
<P>
   It was fitting, then, that shady rapper Eminem got the most
attention from the show. The real-life Marshall Mathers won for
video of the year and best male video for his dis-'em-all hit ``The
Real Slim Shady.'' He also provided the show's most entertaining
performance, coming in off the street with a fleet of a hundred or
so lookalikes following him.
</P>
<P>
   A hundred or so gay rights activists also followed Eminem to the
show in protest. His lyrics have been denounced by the Gay and
Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation as homophobic, and MTV made
concessions to the group by airing a commercial discouraging
violence against gays after Em's appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The rapper still got in the last word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time a relative tries to sue me or a critic tries to
slam me ... I sell more records,'' he said when accepting his last
award, ``So, I gotta thank them, too.''
</P>
<P>
   MTV tried to fly its rainbow colors by booking the world's most
famous gay man (for another 14 1/2 minutes, anyway). ``Survivor''
winner Richard Hatch was part of a forgettable skit with WWF star
Chyna _ something about finding out who was tougher. The audience
won, for sitting through the debacle.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn and Marlon Wayans, the show's first-time hosts, weren't
much funnier. Most of their monologue was met with meager laughs,
particularly a line about Firestone tires (``Some of you all aren't
laughing because you gotta drive home on them,'' they lamely tried
to cover up).
</P>
<P>
   Musically, other highlights included Rage Against the Machine's
straight-ahead blast through ``Testify,'' Blink-182's use of
high-flying midgets for its version of ``All The Small Things,''
and especially Nelly's live TV debut of ``Southern Grammar.''
Because Nelly recruited a half-dozen other rappers for his set,
though, the overnight chart-topper is still a faceless wonder.
</P>
<P>
   This MTV Awards had its own version of the ``Soy Bomb'' dancer,
from the 1998 Grammys: Someone climbed a giant, metallic prop 10
feet above the stage and sat there shaking it as the members of
Limp Bizkit were accepting the rock video award. That someone
turned out to be Rage Against the Machine bassist Tim Commerford,
who was arrested after the incident (and whose group lost the
award).
</P>
<P>
   ``That guy should be getting this award,'' Durst said watching
him, ``that's rock 'n' roll.''
</P>
<P>
   Protests, arrests, disses and cusses. The entire show turned out
to be quite rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Chris Riemenschneider at
criemenschneider(at)statesman.com or 445-3607.
</P>
<P>
   Most quotable
</P>
<P>
   O
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Wayans: ``We got Eve here ... oh, my bad, that's Sisqo'.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Wayans, on Britney Spears' risque performance: ``The girl
went from the Mickey Mouse Club to the strip club.''
</P>
<P>
   Kid Rock, on Rage Against the Machine bassist Tim Commerford's
dare-devil protest: ``Is it for world peace? Is it for world
poverty? What are we fighting for?''
</P>
<P>
   Moby, presenting the rap video award (which Juvenile was up
for): ``Nothing is more exciting in a hip-hop artist's career than
when he gets his first platinum tooth.''
</P>
<P>
   Eminem, on Britney Spears and Christina Aguilera: ``I don't have
any differences. I just don't like them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Carrey, on Eminem: ``His lyrics are totally, socially
unacceptable, but I think we'll all be OK if we just spend more
time with our kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Continued from D1
</P>
<P>
   O
</P>
<P>
   See Eminem, D7
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
