<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6313 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-CORPORATE-APOLOGY-NNS     09-08 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORPORATE-APOLOGY-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CORPORATE OFFICIALS, STONEWALLING DOESN'T WORK ANYMORE 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
FRIDAY, Sept. 8, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: Embargoed against use before Sunday. 
 By TERENCE J. KIVLAN  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Playing a soon-to-be-retired cavalry captain in the 1949 western
``She Wore a Yellow Ribbon,'' John Wayne chides his young,
eager-to-please replacement: ``Never apologize, Cahill. It's a sign
of weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   But unlike today's captains of industry, Wayne's frontier Army
officer of the 1870s didn't have overnight groundswells of hostile
public opinion and plummeting stock prices to worry about. In the
age of instant mass communication and lawsuits, sackcloth and ashes
have become the uniform of the day for corporate officials trying
to live down a product safety or service fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   The trend was dramatically illustrated during a one-week period
last month when three of America's largest and proudest companies
aired network television ads begging pardon for various
transgressions _ United Airlines for a summer of flight foul-ups,
Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. for its shredding tires and the Ford
Motor Co. for using the tires on its Explorer sport-utility
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apologies have become part of the cost of doing business,''
said the University of Florida's Jim Twitchwell in an interview.
``You make a faulty product, you know you are going to end up in
court, and you realize that you have to be seen as someone who just
made a mistake, not as someone who has made a calculated business
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But as perhaps the basic reason for the outbreak in corporate
repentance, Twitchwell cites an ethos that now pervades much of our
popular television entertainment, especially the confessional
variety. ``It's the era of Oprah Winfrey,'' said Twitchwell, an
English professor who is doing research for a book on what he views
as the modern obsession with apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no formal, scripted apology until the 20th
century,'' he said. ``I mean, Napoleon didn't apologize. ... Now we
have the culture of emotion, in which you want to feel good about
what you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Business pundits prefer the hard-nosed explanation for the wave
of corporate atonement: Stonewalling just doesn't work anymore.
``You just can't hide things the way you used to,'' said Walter
Bennis of the University of California Business School. ``Consumers
find out about it on the Internet. ... And then it's breaking news
on CNN. You can't cover up anymore due to the cascade of
information.''
</P>
<P>
   As the main precursor and model for today's approach to crisis
management in the business world, Bennis and other experts point to
Johnson and Johnson CEO James Burke's tour-de-force handling of the
1982 Tylenol tampering episode. ``Right away, Jim Burke went on `60
Minutes' to say, `We screwed up,''' said Bennis, referring to
Burke's appearance on the CBS newsmagazine show.
</P>
<P>
   But the immediate inspiration for the apologies from United,
Bridgestone/Firestone and Ford may have been the negative example
of former Coca-Cola CEO M. Douglas Ivester's stumbling performance
during last year's contamination scare in Belgium, according to
Bennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was slow getting over to Europe and getting on
television,'' said Bennis. ``That really backfired. ... I am
convinced that was what led to his being forced out.''
</P>
<P>
   Corporations have also been coming under pressure from within to
'fess up for alleged wrongdoing _ in the form of activist investors
who pool their money in mutual and pension funds that offer
``social screening'' information on the policies of various
companies toward the environment, racial and gender diversity and
other issues.
</P>
<P>
   The stage was set for the rise of the movement in the 1970s when
institutional investors became dominant in the stock market, said
Ritchie Lowrey, a sociology professor at Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the day of the individual investor, a Ford Moter Co. could
say to me, `You own 1,000 shares in Ford? We could care less,'''
said Lowrey, author of ``Good Money: A Guide to Profitable Social
Investing.'' ``But now if I get together with an institutional
investor and union pension fund and we threaten to pull our
holdings, it's not just 1,000 shares.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowrey said these investor groups will often reward companies
with a ``progressive'' posture by aggressively buying their stock.
``Or they will be pro-active,'' he explained. ``They will acquire a
company with a bad record ... and float shareholder proxies at
shareholder meetings to force change.''
</P>
<P>
   Some investor rebellions have been organized and coordinated
through outside groups like the Interfaith Center for Corporate
Responsibility in Manhattan, which was formed in the mid-1970s to
prod U.S. companies into pulling out of South Africa during the
days of apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   The center's membership now includes 275 religious groups and
commands holdings of over $100 billion in a broad range of
corporate portfolios, according to director Tim Smith. While
eschewing ``direct credit'' for the spate of corporate apologies in
recent years, he added in an interview, ``If the question is, `Are
we one of the groups that helped create a culture where companies
feel more accountable to the public?' the answer to that is
absolutely yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith is convinced that while apologies make sense as a
damage-control strategy, they are sincere in many cases. ``There is
self-interest involved as well as very real remorse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have worked with the Ford Motor Co. over the years and I
know something like this is very worrisome to them,'' Smith said of
the tire problem. ``They really value their brand name and
credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Other experts see another motivation for corporate contrition:
terror. ``Companies have to handle their public relations
differently because they know they have an angry public out
there,'' said Nancy Snow, a political science professor at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   When confronted with a debacle like the tire scandal, ``They
have to show they are doing something now, or they could be out of
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Snow argues that public antagonism toward big companies is being
fueled at least partially by the perception that they have used
loopholes in campaign finance laws to become the chief bankrollers
of a political system that favors the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, legal liability also contributes to the fright
factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are facing strong liability and are trying to affect the
jury pool,'' charged Trial Lawyer Association leader Doug Sheff of
the recent apology blitz on the part of Firestone and Ford. ``The
idea is you get your message out before (the juries) even get in
the box.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Sheff, an attorney in Boston, said he believes corporate America
has been spooked by the multibillion-dollar damage awards voted by
juries against the tobacco companies in the past half-decade,
ending their long winning streak in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impenetrable wall of corporate silence has been broken,''
said Sheff. ``There are a lot more people, including ex-employees,
who are willing to speak up and talk about things like documents
that are embarrassing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1535EDT &QL; 
