A6322 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-MEDICAL-MARIJUANA-HNS     09-08 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-MARIJUANA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RULING SHIELDS DOCTORS WHO DISCUSS MARIJUANA WITH PATIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A federal judge said the law that declares
marijuana a dangerous drug does not authorize the government to
punish doctors who tell seriously ill patients that marijuana might
ease their pain.
</P>
<P>
   The rebuff of federal drug policy chief Barry McCaffrey, who
sought to strip marijuana-recommending doctors of their authority
to prescribe legal medicines, was a setback for the Clinton
administration in its relentless battle against California's
medical marijuana law.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has had more success in going after local
organizations that supply pot to patients.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the Supreme Court stopped the Oakland Cannabis Buyers'
Cooperative from distributing marijuana to its members while the
courts ponder whether evidence of dire medical need justifies an
exemption from federal drug laws.
</P>
<P>
   In short, under the latest court decisions, a doctor can
recommend marijuana legally but a cooperative cannot supply it
legally.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's ruling by U.S. District Judge William Alsup
``demonstrates the legal, medical and philosophical bankruptcy of
the government's position with respect to medical cannabis,'' said
Robert Raich, a lawyer for the Oakland cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Graham Boyd, an American Civil Liberties Union lawyer
representing doctors and patients who sued McCaffrey, was more
upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that this strong opinion signals that the war on
doctors has come to an end,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Weiner, a spokesman for McCaffrey's Office of National Drug
Control Policy, said the agency had no immediate comment.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 215, a ballot initiative approved by California
voters, lets patients use marijuana, based on a doctor's
recommendation, without risking prosecution under state drug laws.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates say it often is the only effective medication to
combat nausea and other side effects of treatments for the acquired
immune deficiency syndrome (AIDS) and cancer. Seven other states
have similar laws.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two months after voters approved the measure in
November 1996, McCaffrey announced that doctors who recommended
marijuana would lose their registration with the Drug Enforcement
Administration, which they need to prescribe legal drugs, and could
face criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The government issued a clarifying statement two months later,
saying doctors were free to discuss the pros and cons of marijuana
as long as they stopped short of recommending the drug.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. District Judge Fern Smith ruled that doctors still
faced an unacceptable risk of punishment for speaking freely, and
issued a preliminary injunction in April 1997 protecting
physicians, unless they did something to help patients get
marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd argued that doctors remained fearful of even discussing
marijuana and sought a broader injunction from Alsup, who was
assigned the case when Smith moved to another job.
</P>
<P>
   Alsup refused Boyd's request to restrict criminal prosecutions
of doctors, saying it was speculative because the government had
not tried to prosecute anyone.
</P>
<P>
   But he went a step beyond Smith by ruling that doctors could
issue oral or written recommendations for marijuana _ short of a
formal prescription _ even if they knew a patient might obtain the
drug illegally.
</P>
<P>
   ``A sincere recommendation alone is not a federal crime, even if
the doctor foresees it could be used to facilitate a federal
crime,'' Alsup wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He said doctors, if asked, must tell patients that marijuana is
illegal. But Alsup rejected the government's distinction between
discussing and recommending marijuana and said patients are
entitled to hear a doctor's opinion that marijuana is the best
available therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If such recommendations could not be communicated, then the
physician-patient relationship would be seriously impaired,'' the
judge said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
