<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESIDENTIALGAFFES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO ERR IS PRESIDENTIAL: WE SALUTE THE HIGH PRIESTS OF MALAPROP
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's no secret. I know they curse. I know they say things they
don't mean and mean things they don't say. I know they blurt out
goofy comments in moments of unintended honesty or become so
tongue-tied that their comments make no sense at all. And their
jokes can have a cruel edge.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, I was bugged for hours when a National Public Radio
reporter last weekend announced that Texas Gov. George W. Bush used
``earthy language'' in describing a New York Times reporter.
</P>
<P>
   What specifically was this ``earthy language''? I had to know.
</P>
<P>
   I listened to and watched news until I finally got the full
curse down. At first blush my thought was: ``A major-league what?
That's not presidential!''
</P>
<P>
   Then I recalled that this comment would pale compared to some of
those spewed by LBJ or Richard Nixon. It would falter alongside
more serious bloopers. And it reminded me of Sen. Eugene McCarthy,
who in his 1968 campaign announced: ``It is dangerous for a
national candidate to say things people might remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every blunder by politicians is like the George W. Bush
comment _ unintentionally picked up by a live mike, a comment for
which he, as of press time, has offered no apology.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, history is full of goofy remarks that fall into the
category of Things a Presidential-Type Person Said And May Later
Regret.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   A WAR DID NOT RESULT: Joking around before a news conference in
1984, President Ronald Reagan announced into a microphone: ``I have
just signed legislation outlawing the Soviet Union; bombing begins
in five minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FORD FREES POLAND: ``There is no Soviet domination of Eastern
Europe, and there never will be under a Ford administration.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Gerald Ford, U.S. president, 1976
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   COMPLAINTS ABOUT REPORTERS: ``I always said than when we don't
have to go through you b-------, we can really get our story over
to the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   _ President John F. Kennedy, 1962
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BRILLIANT INSIGHT I: ``When a great many people are unable to
find work, unemployment results.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Calvin Coolidge, 1930, the same president who said, ``I think
the American people want a solemn ass as a president, and I think
I'll go along with them.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ELEGANT CURSE: ``McKinley shows all the backbone of a chocolate
eclair.''
</P>
<P>
   _ President Theodore Roosevelt on his predecessor, William
McKinley
</P>
<P>
   ELEGANT SLAM: ``Ronald Reagan doesn't dye his hair, he is just
prematurely orange.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Gerald Ford, 1974
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   INELEGANT SLAM: ``You know when you're milking a cow and you
have all that foamy white milk in the bucket and you're just about
through when all of a sudden the cow switches her tail through a
pile of manure and slaps it into that foamy white milk? Well that's
Bill Fulbright.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lyndon B. Johnson, on Sen. William Fulbright, 1967
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   READ HIS MIND: ``I have opinions of my own _ strong opinions _
but I don't always agree with them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ George H.W. Bush
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   UNTIE HIS TONGUE: ``I know how hard it is for you to put food on
your family.''
</P>
<P>
   _ George W. Bush, at the Greater Nashua, N.H., Chamber of
Commerce, January 2000
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   UNINTENDED TRUTH I: ``I urge the Congress to join me in mounting
a major new effort to replace the discredited president.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Richard Nixon, committing a Freudian slip in his State of the
Union speech, 1974
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   UNINTENDED TRUTH II: ``People will say a spot announcement does
not give the audience a chance to get to know the candidate.
Sometimes that is a good thing for the candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Richard Nixon as vice president, addressing the Radio and TV
Executives Society, 1955
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   TOO MUCH HONESTY I: ``I've looked on a lot of women with lust.
I've committed adultery in my heart many times. This is something
God recognizes I will do _ and I have done it _ and God forgives me
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jimmy Carter, 1976 interview in Playboy magazine. Also by
Carter during that campaign year: ``I am convinced that UFOs exist,
because I have seen one.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   UNCOMFORTABLE WIGGLING: ``It depends upon what the meaning of
the word `is' means.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Clinton, grand jury testimony, 1998
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PROVED WRONG: ``When the president does it, that means that it's
not illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Richard Nixon
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BRILLIANT INSIGHT II: ``Killing, rioting and looting are
contrary to the best traditions of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lyndon B. Johnson, 1965
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BRILLIANT INSIGHT III: ``Things are more like they are now than
they ever were before.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Dwight D. Eisenhower, 1955
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   WHERE JIMMY CARTER GOT HIS HONESTY: ``Sometimes when I look at
my children I say to myself, `Lillian, you should have stayed a
virgin.'''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lillian Carter, mother of Jimmy and Billy
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   WHO SAYS THEY REGRET THESE REMARKS?: ``I stand by all the
misstatements that I've made.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Vice President Dan Quayle, August 1989
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SOURCES: ``1,911 Best Things Anybody Ever Said, The Book of
Political Quotes, The Guinness Book of Poisonous Quotes,''
www.slate.com, www.britannica.com
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
