<HEADER>
A6339 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-GREIG-COLUMN09-COX     09-08 1484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREIG-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't you just love receiving an invitation?
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Austin's social season is in full swing. What
kicks it off for you? The Admiral's Ball? Back-to-school night? A
Longhorn tailgate party? The Woman's Symphony League's Jewel Ball?
The Austin Assembly brunch? Come autumn, mail boxes (e- and
otherwise) explode with invitations _ weddings, dinner parties,
birthdays, showers and anniversary celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   They arrive heart-felt and often hand-written. I open each one,
fingering the heft of the paper, noting the ingenuity of the host
and feeling slightly heady at having been included at all.
Sometimes I have made the cut because it's a phone book occasion
(everyone in it was invited), but even then I experience an almost
girlish response to have been chosen.
</P>
<P>
   As a tyke, my birthday parties were announced by a packet of
preprinted, fill-in-the-blank, simple invitations carefully
selected from the racks of the five-and-dime. OK, so Winn's is long
gone and so are most of these invitations. But the spirit lives.
Filling in those blanks made me feel like Caroline Astor (the Mrs.
Astor, creator of the first American social register, ``The 400'')
if only for a few minutes. While Austinites do not usually
entertain in locales as grand as The Astor's Rhode Island digs,
invitations announce all sorts of events.
</P>
<P>
   Ever wonder what to wear when the dress is Texas tux? Do
nonprofits spend a bankroll on invitations to lure you to an
occasion? Who is crazy enough to write out wedding invitations by
hand? Do e-mail addresses on response cards work? Is R.S.V.P. a
cognac? Is there a silver lining to traditional wording? Before you
open your next invitation or plan a soiree, peruse this edition of
the Greig Files. So it is not a guaranteed spot on every invitation
A-list invitation, but it is a fun, informative read.
</P>
<P>
   What's special about an invitation?
</P>
<P>
   ``It sets the tone of the party,'' says Claire Saunders of the
Party Cat. Always send the invitation that packs the biggest wallop
_ you won't regret it. After all, invitations are a small item on
party budgets. And remember, says Saunders, ``To invitees that
can't come to the party, the invitation is their only impression of
the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Do people really mail invitations?
</P>
<P>
   More than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate events, anniversary parties, dinner parties, showers,
rehearsal dinners. Sending a printed invitation with all the
information _ dress to locale _ helps both the hostess and the
guest. Slap a colorful invitation on the bathroom mirrors or
refrigerator. Saves confusion. Saves time. With the quick
turnarounds from stationers and ability to print your own, the cost
of an invitation has plummeted in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't they name it Zenas?
</P>
<P>
   Because they used the founder's last, not first, name _ Crane.
</P>
<P>
   The company founded in 1801 supplies currency paper, cotton
papers for business correspondence as well as stationery for
invitations. Zenas' father sold Paul Revere paper in 1775 for the
cColonies' paper currency. Crane supplies the paper for most
official state events as well as a few minor blips on the social
scene screen _ the dedication of the Statue of Liberty and the
opening of the Golden Gate Bridge to name two.
</P>
<P>
   What do custom invitations cost?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the customer wants to spend, says Paper Place's Molly
Smith. You can use printer compatible stock and do it yourself, or
have a calligrapher pen them on Crane's finest gold bevel-edged
stock.
</P>
<P>
   This veteran Austin stationer has fashioned custom labels as the
invitation affixed to a bottle of wine for a Napa Valley party
($2.50 per label plus wine) and tied layers of ribbon on nail
polish bottles nested in confetti and mailed to guests to a
teen-ager's day-of-beauty party ($5 each). Need a family crest
engraving die? No problem if you have $1,700 for the multi-layered
hand-cut copper die.
</P>
<P>
   Having helped pen everything from the invitations for a wedding
at Deep Eddy (``so and so take the plunge'') to a hHarlequin
romance-theme wedding, Smith is ready to word anything _
Thank-Goodness-I-am-divorced parties to Fido-turns-5 fetesparties.
</P>
<P>
   Her most unusual request? To print a single wedding invitation
to a mythical marriage in Cancun for a student to present as
``evidence'' to professor. Cutting class used to be easier.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely leave the keyboard but want to Friday night?
</P>
<P>
   Then Evite.com is the site for you _ create lists, discuss a
rendezvous with friends online, send and receive electronic
invitations. No muss. No fuss. No postage. Perfect for popular
techies who have no magnets, much less refrigerators, and a hard
time keeping IPO celebration dinner party dates straight. Millions
use this service and find it the Filofax of the century.
</P>
<P>
   What is the too-too and much-much of wedding invitations?
</P>
<P>
   Those created by the hand calligraphers at Pendragon Ink. The
entire invitation (not just the envelopes and reply cards) are
calligraphied and may be adorned with a hand-painted flower (how
about a bluebonnet?). Pendragon Ink creations are a hot item,
reports Nancy Owen of Alegra's Discount Bridal and Invitations. She
would know. Her shop handles the invitations for about 1,000
weddings a year.
</P>
<P>
   Other changes on the wedding invitation scene?
</P>
<P>
   Colored inks and a return to very traditional wedding
invitations. ``People are realizing a wedding is an adult event and
have ceased creating cutesy invitations that read like a pPrecious
mMoments card,'' says Owen. Many weddings are taking place abroad
with large receptions given in Austin after the honeymoon.
</P>
<P>
   Maps and stamped reply cards are standard enclosures, although
Owen refuses to include registry information in wedding
invitations. Amen!
</P>
<P>
   What would Emily say?
</P>
<P>
   A good rhetorical to have ready when facing relatives (current
and soon-to-be) who question the phrasing on a wedding invitation.
If you stick with traditional wording, you always have a plausible
defense for not including your step-father'sstepfather's third wife
in the invitation text.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the traditional wording stangleholdstrangleholds on
wedding invitations has loosened in recent years. Couples who are
footfooting the tab want (and deserve) top billing, and often both
sets of parents issue the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   A note of caution. Think twice before going over-the-top cute
(``We were friends, We were lovers, Come to the Wedding, But bring
no others''). Consider how your grandchildren will react to it 40
years from now!
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line? An invitation reflects the sentiments of the couple
_ conventional or current.
</P>
<P>
   Received a ``Save the Date'' card?
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't yet, you will soon. In the hectic schedules of
working and travelling families, hostesses have begun sending such
notices (e.g. _ Save the date: March 17, Erin &AMP; Jake's wedding in
Maine) so an event can be placed on a calender calendar well in
advance. Four to six weeks notice for a wedding or family reunion
is not enough time to schedule vacations, day care, cash-in
frequent-fliyer miles or snag boffo prices on airline tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy, can you spare $2.50?
</P>
<P>
   That is what the average invitation to a non-profit fund-raiser
costs, estimates Junior League's ``A Christmas Affair'' chair Lisa
Rodman. Besides chairing this four-day event (Nov. 15-19) expected
to raise more than $800,000, Rodman has worked on other major
events such as the opening of the Austin Children's' Museum.: ``The
invitations to such events sends a message to those who may not
attend the event and honors sponsors,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   This year the Lleague will send these invitations to
approximately 9,000 on a carefully culled list. Overwhelmed by some
gala invitations? Remember, most costs are covered by in-kind
donations of service, and labor (assembly, addressing, bulk mail
preparation, etc.) is courtesy of volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   What's with the buttons and bows?
</P>
<P>
   Embellishments, they are called embellishments _, are a very
popular addition to invitations, notes Smith. Vellum overlays
(those see-through sheets with a pattern or the party info) are
often added with a hand-tied ribbon or raffia bow.
</P>
<P>
   Inventive invitation types see possibilities everywhere. For
example, extra large playing cards hole-punched and tied to a
vellum overlay to announce a Cassinocasino party. Embellishments
can mean nights at the kitchen table or an extra fee for stationers
staff who are paid to create the look. Worth it to show a guest
your taste.
</P>
<P>
   Jane S. Greig constantly trolls for consumer questions, answers,
tips, good deals and discounts. Contact her at P.O. Box 670, Austin
78767, 445-3697, 445-3968 (fax) or jgreig(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
