<HEADER>
A6384 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV1     09-08 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV10-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKE MORE WELLS TO DRAIN DRIVEWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, September   10, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. We have the mother of all driveways, 8,000 square feet, with
a well 7 feet deep and 3 feet in diameter, in the middle. When it
rains, the well fills up and water covers the lot. Is there any way
to make the water drain away?
</P>
<P>
   ALICE LEUNG, Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I suggest you contact the driveway builder to see if he could
add more wells, or make the single well drain better. The single
well is not big enough to accommodate all the water, and the water
table may be too high for it to be effective in the first place.
Ask the public works department if there's a sewer to link into.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I tried your trick of injecting talcum powder between the
boards of my floor where I have squeaks. I also tried driving
tapered shingles between the floorboards and joists below; it
helped some but not completely. My fiberglass tub is still
squeaking when I stand or sit in it. Is there anything else I can
do? Could I put Great Stuff in the cavity under the tub?
</P>
<P>
   IRMINE FARMERIE, Shrewsbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Aha! And all this time we thought it was the floor that
squeaked. The tub is squeaking because its bottom is hollow, and
the fiberglass bottom is not strong enough to keep from flexing
under the weight of a bather or showerer. More modern fiberglass
tubs have a honeycombed bottom to prevent this.
</P>
<P>
   I gave the opinion that pumping Great Stuff, the expanding
urethane foam, into the cavity is not practicable, but thinking
twice about it, it might work, because in the cavity, the Great
Stuff is dense enough to prevent flexing. Drill holes in the floor
below and insert the Great Stuff through those holes. You will need
a good amount. You have to be very careful that you don't overfill
the cavity because the stuff doubles its volume as it sets, or at
least increases a lot. I have seen it distort window frames.
Overfilled, it could distort the fiberglass.
</P>
<P>
   The same flexing happened to the handyman with his over-sized
fiberglass shower stall floor, and he took the precaution of
inserting wood supports under the stall floor before it was
installed. The supports must have shifted, or shrunk enough when
they dried out to allow the flexing to occur. He lives with it, and
considers the squeak an accompaniment to his shower tenor.
</P>
<P>
   How about inserting wood supports in the cavity from below?
That's unlikely because the floor (probably a double floor) would
have to be cut to receive the supports, which would be inserted
blindly. So if the Great Stuff doesn't work, the only recourse is a
new tub.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I thought I had a good roof when a second layer of asphalt
shingles was installed. Now the shingles show rust stains around
the metal chimney. The roofer said it was the chimney, and put in
new flashing. The shingles showed rust again around the pipe. What
can I do? There is a cap on top of the metal chimney.
</P>
<P>
   FRUSTRATED, Duxbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It certainly is frustrating, especially since there may be
more than one cause. But don't be too quick to blame the roofer.
First, make sure the metal chimney is stainless steel or aluminum,
not galvanized, which could rust and cause the stains on the roof.
I can't imagine the chimney being anything but stainless or
aluminum, and insulated, to boot. An ordinary galvanized chimney
would rust out in months. If it is galvanized, I suggest installing
a stainless steel one from below the roofline to the top.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure the flashing is aluminum or copper. Lead flashing is
good, but it can rust.
</P>
<P>
   A final cause might be the chimney cap. If you burn oil or gas,
you are creating a lot of water vapor that goes up the chimney,
hits the cool cap, and condenses into water, which runs down the
chimney and stains the shingles. A different kind of cap might
reduce this condensation; a simple wire mesh secured to the top of
the chimney to keep out vermin and debris might be enough.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Overgrown plants shaded my house and the bottom of the
vertical T-1-11 plywood panel siding is rotting away. How can I fix
that? Can I patch it? The panels are quite high, with a sort of
trim at the top, separating them from the siding above.
</P>
<P>
   VICTORIA JOHNSON, North Easton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. First, cut back the plants so the siding can get some air to
dry out. Take off each 4-by-8-foot panel and replace it with a new
one. If you try cutting off a couple of feet where it is rotted,
and put in short pieces, you will get horizontal joints where the
old meets the new. This would look funny and also be difficult to
prevent water from getting behind them. So, replace the entire
panel, where it will end at the top in a natural position. This
will not be much more expensive than if you tried patching with
short panels.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail
hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
