<HEADER>
A6399 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV10-     09-08 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAYTIME'S FOR DROWSING, SO BRING ON THE NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
 By LESLIE LAND    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In September, the sunlit garden blazes with strong colors: Dark
red dahlias, deep plum-colored gladioli, brilliant yellow
rudbeckias towering over orange canna flowers. But the real star of
autumn doesn't start shining until dusk, when the nicotianas pick
up their drooping heads, open their white throats and pour perfume
into the darkening air.
</P>
<P>
   Nicotiana alata, also known as N. affinis, gives no hint of
splendor during the day. The plants are rangy and tall, the
half-closed flowers a washed-out chartreuse, lightly veined in pale
maroon. Stems and leaves are covered with small, sticky hairs,
guaranteeing that by summer's end the plant will look as if it
needs dusting. (It does, but you can't: Nothing but a real downpour
really cleans it off.)
</P>
<P>
   When night falls, however, the flowers glow. Leaves and stems
fade into darkness. You know why N. alata used to be called jasmine
tobacco, and all its faults fall away.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the virtues list is a long one, including far more than
scent.
</P>
<P>
   Those hairs keep predators away, and as long as the plants
aren't overfed, they seldom become diseased. They thrive in full
sun or light shade, tolerate both drought and sog, and grow in
almost any soil but tightly packed clay.
</P>
<P>
   They are powerhouse flower-producers, too. Keep them deadheaded,
cut them back when they get leggy and they will keep producing
until killed by hard frost.
</P>
<P>
   Each flower makes buckets of seeds, which self-sow readily. As
long as you remember not to deadhead everything, one planting will
provide a lifetime supply of volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny, gray-green seedlings don't appear until well after the
weather has warmed, but once they do show up, they're patient. You
can move them to new spots whenever you get around to it, even when
they are quite large, a trait that comes in handy as earlier
annuals fade away.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, for instance, the 30-foot swath of shirley poppies
that borders our central path gives up the ghost in late July. No
problem. I just shop around where I haven't weeded and before long
have a 30-foot swath of undernourished nicotianas. (Life is tough
under a squash plant.) With sunlight and a dose of fertilizer,
fill-out is swift. Two or three weeks later, we have a full sweep
of night fragrance that lasts well into fall.
</P>
<P>
   Nicotiana alata is a tender perennial, usually sold as an annual
because it's killed by strong frost. Gardeners in Zones 8 and
warmer can keep it going simply by cutting it back. (Cover with a
dry mulch if your climate is borderline.)
</P>
<P>
   You can also dig it up and put it in a pot. It will continue to
flower in a sunny window until Thanksgiving or so. Cut it back when
it quits and let it rest through the winter (no fertilizer). Feed
it in spring and it will start blossoming again.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to alata, there are about 70 other species of
nicotiana. Most are more or less scentless, but the statuesque
N.sylvestris is a happy exception. Though far larger than alata, it
has a more delicate scent, less heavily tropical, with shadings of
rose and lilac.
</P>
<P>
   Given room to grow, N. sylvestris makes a yard-wide rosette of
enormous leaves while sending up six-foot blooming stems, and its
starry clusters of narrow flowers erupt from their stalks like
fireworks. On the downside, the lower leaves start to look ratty
well before blooming ends. Clearly a case for Dr. Alata: Transplant
a few into sylvestris' skirts and the new growth will hide bare
spots while giving another layer to the fragrance.
</P>
<P>
   N. sylvestris is sometimes marketed as Only the Lonely, a
reminder that the whole group has severe nomenclature problems.
Other old-fashioned flowers have poetic common names: Cupid's dart
for Catanache, love-in-a-mist for Nigella, dame's violet for
Hesperis. But nicotianas can't seem to do any better than flowering
tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps there's some justice involved. The flowering types do
contain nicotine, and Nicotiana glauca, or tree tobacco, a
perennial type with smooth, blue-green leaves and scentless but
charming small yellow flowers, is so toxic that eating even a
little will kill you.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't keep me from cherishing my N. glauca plant, which
has been going back and forth between basement and garden for eight
years. I just dig it up in the fall, whack it back so it will fit
under the beams and put the roots in a plastic bag. The following
spring, outside it goes. By fall it will be a 10-foot tree
festooned with narrow yellow bells.
</P>
<P>
   The nicotianas' rightful colors are yellow, white and, in N.
langsdorffii and N. Lime Green, a lovely though not particularly
limey green. To get reds and pinks you must plant one of the modern
hybrids, ideally either Daylight Sensation or Heaven Scent. Though
their colors are somewhat muddy, they still have strong fragrance
and blend well with other plants. That's more than can be said for
the Domino group, and much more than can be said for the ubiquitous
Nicki series.
</P>
<P>
   Squat, sticky, dull-colored, open all day, the utterly scentless
Nickis threw out the baby and kept the bath water, but because they
bloom while still very small, they are the only nicotiana plants
sold in most garden centers. If they're the only nicotianas you
know, a world of wonders awaits.
</P>
<P>
   N. alata and N. sylvestris are sold by Perennial Pleasures
Nursery, P.O. Box 147, East Hardwick, VT 05836; (802) 472-5104;
www.antiqueplants.com; catalog $3.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven Scent is sold by Harris Seeds, P.O. Box 22960, Rochester,
NY 14692; (800) 514-4441; www.harrisseeds.com; free catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Daylight Sensation is sold by Ed Hume Seeds, P.O. Box 1450,
Kent, WA 98035; www.humeseeds.com; price list free.
</P>
<P>
   N. glauca and N. langsdorffii are sold by J.L. Hudson, Star
Route 2, Box 337, La Honda, CA 94020; no telephone; catalog $1.
</P>
</TEXT>
