<P>
   WARSH-COLUMN (Undated) _ In a roomful of profesionals, Eric
Maskin would not stand out except perhaps for the mildness of his
mein. He is 49, somewhat formal, wears eyeglasses. He plays
classical clarinet well enough to have though of trying to make his
living as a concert musician, but that is true of any number of
professional scientists. Yet it is the economist Maskin who this
autumn is moving into the house at the Institute for Advanced Study
in Princeton, N.J. that once belonged to Albert Einstein. And as
you would expect, there is a story in that. By David Warsh. 1000
words.
</P>
