<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6422 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WTIMOR-U.N.-KILLINGS-     09-08 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTIMOR-U.N.-KILLINGS-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIAN LEADER APOLOGIZES FOR U.N. DEATHS IN WEST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Two days after three U.N. refugee workers were
murdered in their office in West Timor, Indonesia's president
Abdurrahman Wahid on Friday formally conveyed his nation's ``very
deep sorrow'' for their ``horrific death'' and promised to
prosecute the killers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in disbelief and outraged that such unspeakable crimes
were committed against the good people of the UNHCR,'' Wahid said
in a letter to Secretary-General Kofi Annan, using the acronym for
the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees. ``The people of Indonesia
mourn with the families of those who were brutally murdered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We condemn the perpetrators of this criminal act, who appear
to be disguising themselves as pro-integrationist East Timorese, ``
Wahid said, ``and we vow to bring them to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier on Friday, in a news conference on information
technology sponsored by the Economic and Social Council, Wahid
responded to questions about the killings. He suggested that
``criminals'' in one of the self-styled militia groups opposed to
East Timor's independence from Indonesia were responsible for the
deaths of Carlos Caceres, a 33-year-old American from Puerto Rico;
Samson Aregehegn, 44, an Ethiopian, and Pero Simundsa, 29, a Croat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many criminals join the integrationist forces, and we have to
look into that,'' Wahid said, referring to the self-styled militia
gangs that violently oppose independence for East Timor on the
divided island.
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesian president insisted that calm had been restored in
Atambua, the town where rioters with firearms and machetes
ransacked an office run by the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees,
clubbing and hacking the three workers to death and slashing at
others as they escaped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that now everything is, in the military parlance,
under control,'' Wahid said. ``I think now the situation is very
good there. That is according to the full report I got this
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   His assurance came as news agencies circulated reports of a
fresh killing by militiamen of 11 to 20 Timorese, including elderly
people and children, at Betun, a town about 40 miles from Atambua,
on Wednesday night and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid said that two military battalions had been sent to Atambua
and that Indonesian authorities had detained 19 people there in
connection with the ransacking of the U.N. office.
</P>
<P>
   Another man, he said, had been detained in connection with the
killing of a militia leader, Olivio Mendonca, also known as Moruk.
Wahid said initially that grief at the discovery of Mendonca's
decapitated corpse on Tuesday prompted supporters to attack the
office, though there was no apparent connection between his death
and the agency.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. refugee workers were killed on Indonesian soil while
Wahid was attending a summit meeting of world leaders here. When
his turn came on Friday to address the meeting, Wahid barely
referred to the incident beyond noting the minute of silence that
Annan arranged on Wednesday to honor the three dead workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council, which was briefed on the killings on
Wednesday, scheduled consultations on the incident for later Friday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The attack in Atambua, which followed other incidents of
intimidation and harassment by the criminal gangs, has forced the
United Nations to pull its staff members out of West Timor. They
had been helping to care for and repatriate refugees who a year ago
fled similar attacks in East Timor, after its residents voted for
independence.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   About 100,000 refugees remain in camps in West Timor.
</P>
<P>
   The last of more than 400 employees of the United Nations and
other aid organizations in West Timor left on Friday, with no
immediate plans for their return.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more a question of if rather than when,'' said Ron
Redmond, a spokesman for the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees.
``We have been asking for assurances and guarantees for the overall
security of the humanitarian staff who have been trying to work
with the refugees for the last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Redmond said in a telephone interview from Geneva on Friday that
the Indonesian authorities had been asked repeatedly to separate
``these militia thugs'' from the population of the refugee camps.
Many refugees wanted to go home to East Timor, he said, but had
been terrorized for months, despite Indonesian assurance that
security would be provided.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far as we're concerned, the time for words has passed, and
we want to see some action on the ground,'' Redmond said.
</P>
<P>
   The attack in Atambua took place on Wednesday when 30 to 50
armed men split off from a funeral procession for the slain militia
leader and stormed the refugee office.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. workers, concerned about the potentially incendiary
funeral, had contacted the Indonesian police and army officers at a
military base several hundred yards from the compound to ask for
protection beforehand. Indonesian authorities said the mourners
were not dangerous, there was no problem and the refugee workers
should remain where they were, Redmond said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously that was deadly wrong,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1611EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
