<HEADER>
A6447 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-GIRDLE-GIRLS-ART-$ADV     09-08 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRDLE-GIRLS-ART-$ADV10-1,070(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PARK AVENUE PRINCESSES OF BROOKLYN 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By HEATHER CHAPLIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Autumn Lucas was the picture of leisure, sitting in a
courtyard cafe under the spreading branches of a dogwood tree,
sipping a soy latte. Though it was midmorning on a Wednesday, when
most people are bustling about their offices, she was chatting with
a friend about Shu Uemura face cleanser and a play she had seen the
night before. The wind made the silk scarf on her head flutter
prettily behind her. Only the drumming of her manicured hand gave
away a strain of impatience, as she was expected in a few minutes
for a luncheon to plan a charity event.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, 29, is not a postdeb from Greenwich, nor even a junior
jet set wannabe. Her scarf is from the Salvation Army, and her
turquoise feather necklace, which made the saleswomen at Barneys
buzz, is from a Midtown vendor. Lucas, who makes her living as a
caterer, is a socialite of her own making. She is a member of the
Girdle Girls, a club of women living it up in ladylike high style
in Williamsburg, Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Unlikely as it may seem, the celebrated life of the Park Avenue
princess has infiltrated the bohemian enclave of Williamsburg. Its
ladies are even lunching, setting out to prove that free time,
beautiful clothes and the satisfaction of giving back to the
community are not the exclusive right of the Upper East Side. Of
course, adopting the swell life without the backing of big bucks or
family names takes creative finagling. So the Girdle Girls do their
own offbeat version of high society, Brooklyn style.
</P>
<P>
   The place to see and be seen if you are a bright young thing in
Williamsburg is the Girdle Factory. It isn't Swifty's or Chow's.
It's only a little shop for vintage clothes on Bedford Avenue, but
the parade of stylish women across its concrete floors would give
the buyers at Jeffrey pause. Artists, producers, editors, actors
and bartenders meander through during the day to try on Pucci
dresses and Tony &AMP; Tina eye liner. They wear parachute-fabric pants
from H&AMP;M, secondhand Agnes B., vintage Dior heels, maybe a Katayone
Adeli trench coat bought on a splurge. The store's manager, Lulu
Ramirez, founded the club last winter, inviting customers whose
style caught her eye to be members.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these women were coming into the store, and we'd have
these great rich conversations,'' explained Ramirez, who has smoky,
black-rimmed eyes and wears vintage dresses with knee-high black
boots. ``I wanted people to start meeting each other. The only
requirement is that you have an original style. It's cool girls
supporting cool girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, 37, called the first meeting in January, and more than
40 women showed up. Many drinks and a lot of bonding later, a
social club was born. Still invitation-only, the Girdle Girls meet
monthly at local bars, where they socialize and network, and the
local men tend to gawk. ``We have to keep our locations pretty
hush-hush,'' said Kettie North, 30, who owns the Girdle Factory,
``or else all the guys are already there when we come in, and it
ruins the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In May, following the example of their Silk Stocking District
sisters, they decided to give back to the community. A series of
bake sales ensued, with members dressed to the nines, vintage
aprons round their waists and trays of Rice Krispies treats in
their hands. They raised $260 for the Brooklyn Animal Resource
Coalition, which may not seem much compared with the take at the
Lenox Hill Hospital Winter Ball, but the Girdle Girls generally do
not have grandfathers who founded steel mills or cosmetics empires.
</P>
<P>
   Their meetings are part fashion support group, part postfeminist
rap session, with a dose of front-stoop gossip thrown in. At one
meeting held at Yabby, a former garage renovated into a slick
lounge on Bedford Avenue, local guys in tattoos and grungy T-shirts
lurked at the pool table as the Girdle Girls settled into the deep
red couches. Over chardonnay and single malt scotch, they discussed
topics like the feminist underpinnings of their all-women social
club and a spa in the unlikely environs of Greenpoint that gives
great facials and manicures.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first heard about the Girdle Girls, I thought it would
be stupid,'' Ruthie Lee, 25, said at Yabby. She is an aspiring
fashion stylist with bee-stung red lips, wearing slinky black
mules. ``But then I broke up with my boyfriend, and all these girls
totally pulled me through it. I honestly don't know what I would
have done without them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting nearby, Lisa Craegh, who immigrated to Williamsburg from
London about three years ago, balanced a cracker with Brie in one
hand and a glass of wine in the other. To a chorus of groans, she
announced that she had to leave the meeting early.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her boyfriend is flying in tonight,'' a woman in a white
shirtdress offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last time he was here, she lost 7 pounds in like a day,''
another woman whispered. ``They never left her apartment.''
</P>
<P>
   Craegh, 28, leads the model Girdle Girl existence. She wakes up
around 11 a.m., goes to a yoga class or takes a swim, makes a pot
of tea at home, writes in her journal, paints or works at one of
her three jobs and visits friends in the evening. She wears Mario
Badescu skin care, blue tinted sun glasses and talks knowingly
about Fashion Week. Not bad, considering that Craegh is a painter
who earns about $20,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other Girdle Girls, she has learned that the key to
self-pampering is resourcefulness. The skin products are from a
friend who works for Mario Badescu, and she is familiar with
Fashion Week because she helped an up-and-coming designer build a
set for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may not have financial security right now, but my life is
based on a sense that I have what it takes to make it in the
future,'' Craegh said. ``The good life here is based on a sense of
self-worth, that we deserve it right now and don't have to wait for
it or be born into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Craegh acknowledges that this is not always the most pragmatic
or financially responsible approach to life. ``It's fairy talish,
it's magic,'' she said. ``It's a Cinderella thing. We believe in
our own inner princesses, or whatever.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Girdle Girls are not the slackers of the early 1990s,
spending their days sipping beer and waxing ironic. They work, but
in jobs with flexible schedules that allow for lattes in the
afternoon and cosmopolitans at midnight. They want to be painters,
actresses, fashion designers and writers, but see no reason to
clump about in unfashionable clothes and bad haircuts along the
way. Artistic ideals are important, but so are good shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be an actor, and I want to make a good income doing
it,'' Lucas said. ``I want to travel and wear beautiful clothes and
not have to count my pennies. But the key is to have the confidence
it will come and not just wait until after it happens to live the
good life.''
</P>
<P>
   While these Williamsburg princesses may not yet share space with
the Lauder sisters in the party pages of Vogue and Harper's Bazaar,
around their own neighborhood the Girdle Girls are becoming social
stars. ``They're getting to be a known thing,'' said Lawrence
Elliott, 35, who owns the Read Cafe on Bedford Avenue, ``We see
crews of them going by the window. They're trouble, but in a good
way.''
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon at the Gray Parrot Cafe, Lee, wearing a skin-tight
denim skirt and red mohair cowl-neck tank, said: ``It's like being
a celebrity. I've heard us called the Williamsburg socialites.''
</P>
<P>
   But being a self-made socialite, often without means, does have
its awkward moments. Walking through the meatpacking district one
day last season, Lucas was mesmerized by a pair of azure suede Jil
Sander platform heels at Jeffrey. ``If they're less than $300,
they're mine,'' she promised herself. Though the shoes cost
$563.57, she left the store with an olive version of the shoe
charged to her credit card and a second pair, the azure ones, on
order. Panic struck on 14th Street.
</P>
<P>
   It's just this kind of dilemma that tests a Girdle Girl's
mettle, a particular brand of grace laced with chutzpah. Two days
later, Lucas headed back to the store with her best-looking guy
friend by her side for added confidence and requested a refund.
When the clerk skeptically asked why she was returning them, Lucas
waved her hand in the air. ``Oh, I'm just really over the whole
platform thing,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
