<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LOCKHART LEAVING AS WHITE HOUSE PRESS SECRETARY
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ White House press secretary Joe Lockhart, the
pugnaciously partisan spokesman hired to defend President Clinton
during the height of his impeachment struggle, said Friday he would
leave the administration by Oct. 1 to seek a job in the private
sector.
</P>
<P>
   No decision was announced on Lockhart's successor, but he is
expected to be replaced by his deputy, Jake Siewert, who has been
with the Clinton administration since the president took office in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart, who served as deputy to White House spokesman Michael
McCurry for two and a half years before taking over the spokesman's
slot in October 1998, has said quietly for months that he was ready
to leave to spend more time with his wife and their young daughter.
</P>
<P>
   He said he plans to spend the fall giving speeches and looking
for a job that would build on his 20 years working in politics and
the media.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said he had not discussed his departure with Clinton,
but has had conversations about it with White House chief of staff
John Podesta.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart, known for a barbed wit and an equally cutting partisan
edge, became Clinton's chief spokesman just before the House
impeachment of Clinton in December 1998 on charges stemming from
his relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky,
and the president's subsequent acquittal by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   He dealt with aggressive press inquiries with a combative
combination of counterjabs, bristling sarcasm and a lightning
recall of domestic policy detail and specifics meant to cast
Clinton's political foes in a poor light.
</P>
<P>
   Siewert, 36, is a graduate of Yale University and the University
of California at Berkeley law school.
</P>
<P>
   He met Clinton in 1991, when the future president was governor
of Arkansas and Siewert was working for the Democratic Governors
Association in Washington. After Clinton took office, Siewert spent
nearly three years working in the White House communications
office.
</P>
<P>
   He directed press operations in New Hampshire for Clinton's
re-election campaign in 1996, and returned to the White House the
following year to run the press office for Clinton's National
Economic Council.
</P>
<P>
   He became deputy White House press secretary in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans's e-mail address is bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
