   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP (Undated) _ The Republican Party rides to the
aid of embattled GOP nominee George W. Bush with a blistering
televised attack on Democrat Al Gore that uses the Democrat's 1996
fund-raising scandal to question his credibility in promising to
strengthen public education. On the campaign trail, Bush picks up
the endorsement of the National Fraternal Order of Police while
Gore touts a 10-year, $36 billion tax break for college tuition.
Democratic vice presidential candidate Joe Lieberman and Bush
campaign aides disagree over Bush's record in Texas on providing
health insurance to children. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-BUSH (Warrendale, Pa.) _ Republican presidential candidate
George W. Bush unveils his new campaign slogan, a new townhall
rally format and a new party attack ad in his effort to counteract
Al Gore's rise in the polls. By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-OIL (New Orleans) _ In this oil-industry state, Vice
President Al Gore walks a careful line _ calling for measures to
lower gasoline prices without bashing one of the state's big
industries. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN (Houston) _ Sen. Joseph Liberman pushes the Democratic
ticket's health care plan here, but the hand-picked audience got a
little off-message by offering some praise for Gov. George W. Bush,
the Republican presidential candidate. By ALAN BERNSTEIN.
</P>
