<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, Ext. 218.
WASHINGTON, Sept. 8 -- The following chart shows how senators and
representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the last
week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   THERE ARE NO SENATE VOTES THIS WEEK.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: ESTATE
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday sustained the President's veto of a bill
to repeal the estate tax. Voting 274-157, the House failed to reach
the two-thirds majority necessary to override a veto. Supporters of
the override said ending the tax on inherited properties would
reduce administrative costs for businesses and allow more Americans
to pass their estates to their children. Opponents said repealing
the tax would benefit only the wealthy and would prevent spending
down the debt and strengthening Social Security. A ``yes'' vote
supports the tax repeal.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: CHILDREN
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday passed, 405-18, a bill to provide more
child support to families leaving welfare. Supporters said the bill
would simplify child support payments and give mothers leaving
welfare all the child support collected for them, instead of
returning half to the state. Some opponents said the bill would
place state functions under federal control. Others objected to
provisions that could allow funding social service programs run by
religious institutions, saying the bill would sanction
discriminatory hiring practices. A ``yes'' supports the child
support bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2
</P>
<P>
   --- ---
</P>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The attendance record is not part of the
current vote chart because the company that supplied us with the
information is no longer in service. We are looking for a new
source.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
<P>
   keyword(s) state(s)ny
</P>
