<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-5-QUESTIONS-OLYMPICS-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOB WRIGHT ON GETTING HIS $705 MILLION WORTH FROM THE OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 10)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bob Wright, the president of NBC, is wrapping up a few
last-minute details stateside this week before he heads off with
about 800 of NBC's biggest advertising clients for Sydney,
Australia _ and his network's biggest production of 2000, the
Summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   With agreements to broadcast the games in the U.S. for every
Olympiad through 2008 _ a total of five _ NBC has become the
network of the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Wright said he will be spending a chunk of his time in Sydney
Harbor, aboard the same ocean liner the network took to Barcelona
in 1992 to wine and dine the biggest commercial spenders.
</P>
<P>
   Wright said he is increasingly confident that the 2000 games,
even at a fee of $705 million for the American television rights,
will prove to be an unqualified success, at least in terms of
programming if not quite in profits. Following are excepts from a
telephone conversation on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How did the advertising industry respond for this Olympics,
in light of the bribery scandals at the International Olympic
Committee?
</P>
<P>
   A. That was certainly a concern to us, but it does not seem to
have affected any business issues. The IOC handled it as best they
could. They made a conscientious effort to clean things up and get
the bad guys out. We hit our target in advertising sales of $900
million. This was a situation, when we went into those Olympic
deals, where we hoped to enhance NBC's reputation and not lose too
much money. We hit very good economic circumstances, which we were
counting on. So this is not a money-losing situation for us this
year. But it's not going to be much of a profit center.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Will this year's coverage differ much from previous Olympics?
</P>
<P>
   A. The biggest programming difference is 279 hours of Olympic
programming on our cable networks CNBC and MSNBC. There will be a
total of 70 hours on the network. The cable exposure presents
opportunities for other sports, especially for a lot of team sports
that have never been seen, like soccer and softball. We're also
going to have a full program of boxing on CNBC, starting every
night at 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You were able to use the Olympic coverage on cable in
negotiations to extend your agreements with cable operators for
your cable channels. How significant are these new deals?
</P>
<P>
   A. We have been very interested in extending our carriage
agreements with cable operators and the Olympics were certainly an
important part of that. We've used everything to gain the
extensions, including retransmission consent agreements and some
opportunities for improvements on the digital side when we reach
that stage. Many cable operators were interested in extending
through the end of our Olympic commitments in 2008 and some of them
even went beyond that to 2012. It means that CNBC and MSNBC are
guaranteed carriage in the U.S. to a point as far off as 2012.
That's enormously significant for us.
</P>
<P>
   And by the time we get to the Salt Lake City games in 2002, the
distribution for MSNBC will expand from 62 million homes to about
70 million, another very significant advance. The biggest
television stations we own have always taken great advantage of
Olympics years. Between the Olympics and the political advertising
this year, it will be the biggest financial year ever for the
stations we own.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You have committed almost $3 billion more for the rights to
the games in 2002, 2004, 2006 and 2008. Given that, how crucial is
it that you perform well in terms of ratings from Sydney?
</P>
<P>
   A. Our performance in Sydney is very crucial. If some tragedy
were to strike and we put up terrible numbers it would certainly
impact up negatively. But having said that, the reality is that
Salt Lake City, as a domestic Olympics, stands on its own, has a
cachet all its own. The impact of whatever happens in Sydney will
be felt on Athens in 2004. But I'm confident we're going to do very
well.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Much has been made of how big events, like ``Survivor'' on
CBS, have helped bring viewers back to the networks. Does having
the guarantee of an Olympics every two years provide NBC with a
built-in advantage?
</P>
<P>
   A. It's important that we are able to say that we are the
Olympic network, and we can keep on displaying those rings as part
of our identity. Those rings have great recognition. That was a
really important factor in helping us decide to take on this
economic obligation. There is a debate about how valuable events
like this are as promotional vehicles for future programming. It is
hard to assess their promotional value, especially in the fall when
the baseball playoffs will cause a lot of disruption of schedules.
But the ability to have the most-watched programming to display
your new shows is clearly a benefit. And we're already setting up
for Salt Lake City. Those games start only 13 months after we leave
Sydney.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
