<P>
   EU-AUSTRIA (Paris) _ A panel of experts assessing the status of
democracy and human rights in Austria has recommended that the
sanctions imposed last year because members of a far right party
had been included in the ruling government should be lifted. The
experts, appointed by the European Union, gave high marks to the
new government, concluding that minorities, refugees and immigrants
enjoyed the same if not greater legal rights and protections in
Austria as in the other countries in the Union. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-MILLENNIUM-SUMMIT (United Nations) _ The first working
summit meeting of nearly 150 world leaders ended Friday with an
ambitious set of goals for the new millenium that tried to mesh the
demands of the rich and poor nations _ calling for democratic
rights, female equality and better environmental protection on one
hand and the a less lopsided balance in the world's economy on the
other. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-CLINTON (United Nations) _ President Clinton on Friday
urged China's president, Jiang Zemin, to open a dialogue with the
new government of Taiwan and put a stop to its missile exports to
Pakistan, but received little from Jiang except for cordial good
wishes for his retirement in four months time and congratulations
for helping usher China into the World Trade Organization. By David
E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CUBA-CASTRO (New York) _ Fidel Castro, in New York for the
summit meeting, speaks at the Riverside Church on Friday night. By
Chris Hedges.
