   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PREGNANCY-RIGHTS (Washington) _ When does a pregnant woman _ or
even a potentially pregnant woman, given increasing medical
knowledge about reproductive health _ cross the line between
autonomy and obligation? In an age of reproductive freedom, when no
woman can be forced to carry a pregnancy to term, when if ever
should society intervene to protect the future interests of a child
whom a woman has chosen to bear? If fetal health is the issue, what
about a pregnant woman who uses illegal drugs or who smokes two
packs of cigarettes a day, or who abuses alcohol, given that the
American Medical Association has identified fetal alcohol syndrome
as ``the leading cause of mental retardation in the western
world''? And fundamentally, whose interest is it, anyway? By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
