<HEADER>
A6526 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-STOBART09-COX     09-08 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-STOBART09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stobart on the other side
 &HT;    By Doug Harris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Chuck Stobart knows that most college football
coaches travel more than a circus act. But he was certain the
vagabond life was over when he joined Arizona's staff 14 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to Arizona to retire,'' he said. ``We
re-did a house and six months later we moved.''
</P>
<P>
   Stobart followed head coach Larry Smith to Southern Cal, then
went to Memphis to be a head coach himself. He hooked on at Ohio
State in 1994 and was promoted to offensive coordinator this
season.
</P>
<P>
   His shining moment with the Wildcats came against current boss
John Cooper, Arizona State's coach then. Arizona pulled the upset,
but Cooper's team already had clinched the PAC-10 and had the last
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to Pasadena,'' he said, ``and they went to El Paso or
someplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Stobart is back in Arizona, but he will be on the other sideline
with the 18th-ranked Buckeyes tonight.
</P>
<P>
   They will have to contend with the Desert Swarm, the decade-old
nickname for the Wildcats' roving defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``That name is very apropos,'' Stobart said. ``They bring people
from all over the place, and it looks like a storm coming across
the desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a defense like that, two things can happen _ the offense
can have bad plays, but you also give up big plays. You have to
have patience on offense and understand you might not block all
their people sometimes. What you don't want is to have a play where
you give the ball over to the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a job for a poised, veteran quarterback. And Stobart
is convinced the Buckeyes have one in Steve Bellisari, who had an
unspectacular but relatively mistake-free performance in the
opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than two quick passes (that were misfires), which can
happen to anybody, I thought he was very good,'' Stobart said. ``He
had no interceptions _ he wasn't even close to having one. We had
the one bad center-snap exchange, but other things he handled very,
very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes and Wildcats have been on eerily similar paths.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State went 11-1 in '98, Arizona 12-1.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State went 6-6 in '99, Arizona 6-6.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State finished with three straight losses last season, same
as Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Each is eager to bounce back and has its defense to thank for
season-opening wins. The Buckeyes foiled Fresno State with four
defensive touchdowns, while the Wildcats scored one in a 17-3 win
at Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dick Tomey's team has one of the country's better
quarterbacks in senior Ortege Jenkins, but he went a mere 3-of-15
passing for 11 yards against the Utes, who missed three field goals
inside 35 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just had a bad night,'' OSU defensive coordinator Jon
Tenuta said. ``He just wasn't on. He's been around since '97. He's
a good football player.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got great skill,'' middle linebacker Matt Wilhelm
said. ``Their receivers can jump and catch the ball, and Ortege has
a gun. It's going to be rough. It will be like going against a Big
Ten team.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ortege &AMP; Co. shouldn't expect help from its defense this
week, according to the Buckeyes.
</P>
<P>
   The Desert Swarm?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard of it, but I'm not impressed,'' center LeCharles
Bentley said. ``We'll show 'em what the Buckeyes can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Contact Doug Harris at dougharris(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
