<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6533 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-AGGIES09-COX     09-08 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AGGIES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Do-over time for A&AMP;M veterans
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Mark Farris expects to see some roles
reversed tonight.
</P>
<P>
   When Texas A&AMP;M plays host to Wyoming, the Aggies quarterback
doesn't anticipate seeing what he saw a week ago from certain
veteran players. Mostly, it's precisely because they are veterans.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M's 24-10 loss last Saturday at Notre Dame was noteworthy
because several inexperienced Aggies played with poise and
confidence, while several elder statesmen stumbled and bumbled. But
Farris, who falls into the former category along with tailback
Richard Whitaker and wide receiver Robert Ferguson, said he
believes those in the latter category _ namely receiver Chris
Taylor, cornerback Jay Brooks and tight end RoDerrick Broughton _
should recuperate quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the same things would have happened to young guys that
happened to them, it might be hard for the young guys to bounce
back,'' Farris said. ``But these are older guys who know what it
takes to bounce back. They know how to put it behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   They might know, but that doesn't make it easy.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, a steady senior and a team leader, was still in shock
this week after two major gaffes against the Irish. First, he
allowed a third-quarter punt to sail over his head, and the ball
rolled dead at the Aggies' 4-yard line. Then three plays later he
dropped a gorgeous pass from Farris that would have either gone for
a 92-yard touchdown to give A&AMP;M a 17-7 lead, or gotten the Ags out
of a deep hole.
</P>
<P>
   It was the drop Taylor found difficult to forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to come back from it in a positive way,'' he said,
``but it's hard to deal with something of that magnitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor has made some huge plays during his Aggies career. He
caught a school-record 96-yard pass against Tulsa last year and
snared an 81-yarder in a huge victory over Nebraska as a sophomore
in 1998. But that was of little solace in the aftermath of the
dropped pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I remember the big catches,'' Taylor said. ``But the
drop is more vivid in my mind. That play could have been one to add
to that list (of big catches).''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't escape the notice of any Aggie that in Sunday night's
NFL game between Tennessee and Buffalo, Titans Eddie George and
Frank Wycheck dropped passes in the open. But A&AMP;M receivers coach
Larry Kirksey said that didn't ease the pain for Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He beat himself up so much that I didn't have to do it to
him,'' Kirksey said. ``He's human. Things are going to happen. But
I expect him to make that play and I expect him to make it the next
time the opportunity presents itself. He'll come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on offense, Broughton made a critical mistake. The senior
was penalized for moving early on a fourth-and-goal play inches
from the end zone on the opening drive of the second half. The
penalty forced A&AMP;M to settle for a field goal for a 10-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the ball, Brooks is a full-time starter for
the first time. But the junior has played extensively and has a
history of making big plays _ in his career he's returned a fumble,
interception and blocked punt for touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   At Notre Dame, however, he was victimized on both Irish
touchdown passes, which came in one-on-one coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let my team down,'' Brooks said after the game.
</P>
<P>
   But free safety Michael Jameson said he expects his childhood
friend and former teammate at Killeen Ellison High to bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tough-minded guy,'' said Jameson, unlikely to play
tonight because of sprains to both ankles. ``You can't come back
and show a lack of confidence because that might rub off on the
younger guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jay's hurt by what happened. People have been getting on him
and that doesn't make him feel good,'' Jameson added. ``But he's
got the short-term memory that you need to play defensive back.
You've got to put it behind you and make the next play.''
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected miscues by the veterans and the polished play of
the newcomers at Notre Dame are what have helped to turn R.C.
Slocum's a distinguished shade of gray.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mistakes kill you as a coach,'' he said. ``They just drive
you nuts. But at least when older guys make them, they have an edge
in bouncing back quicker than the younger guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning, the Aggies hope, tonight.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Randy Riggs at rriggs(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
