<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6543 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-HIGHTECH-VISAS-NNS &LR;      09-08 1388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHTECH-VISAS-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-TECH EMPLOYERS PUSH FOR MORE VISAS 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
FRIDAY, Sept. 8, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: Substitute the plus symbols for the words
(plus)(plus) in 2nd graf. 
 By ALEX PULASKI And JIM BARNETT  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sanjit Tamhane paved his road from India to Oregon with layers
of language.
</P>
<P>
   Not the Marathi he grew up speaking in Bombay, nor English in
and of itself. Those came before his fluency in ASP, C(plus)(plus),
Visual Basic, Java and HTML.
</P>
<P>
   In short, he is a software whiz in a world hungry for those
whose precisely ordered keystrokes push electrons through copper
and aluminum, squeezing big ideas past transistors smaller than
bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   American industry lured him and thousands more to this country.
Stories like Tamhane's unfold each year as the high-tech economy
booms and firms search the globe for talent to feed their growth.
</P>
<P>
   But unprecedented demand for technically skilled labor is
bumping against questions of public policy. High-tech companies
must secure visas for foreign workers, but their numbers are
limited by law.
</P>
<P>
   Now, high-tech companies want to lift restrictions on the H-1B
visa program that already has brought a half-million people to this
country. The visas allow companies and institutions to hire skilled
foreign workers for as long as six years and can ultimately lead to
permanent residency.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation is pending in Washington, D.C., and the industry
hopes to get results before Congress adjourns Oct. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main concern is to get the bill passed,'' said Daven
Oswalt, a spokesman at the Semiconductor Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
   An industry-backed measure that would nearly double the number
of H-1B visas available to people such as Tamhane is threatened by
election-year politics. Each party is blaming the other for delays.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, high-tech employers say they can't thrive without a
larger immigrant pool. Computer engineers and others warn of
oversupply and worry about diluted salaries.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Tamhane makes more every month than he did in a year in India.
But coming to America is not solely following a dollar-strewn path;
it constitutes an intellectual challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``An engineer with two years' experience has to go to the
U.S.,'' said Tamhane, who lives in Corvallis, Ore. ``If he doesn't
go, it means there's something wrong with his skills. You're either
stuck or you're dumb.''
</P>
<P>
   Being neither, Tamhane finds himself addicted to junk food, DVD
movies and negotiating Interstate 5 in his 1998 Toyota Avalon.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   U.S. history is full of cyclical lessons on the importation of
labor.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Carnegie, who needed cheap steelworkers to combat unions
in the 1880s, called foreign immigration ``a golden stream which
flows into the country each year.''
</P>
<P>
   But Congress has turned off the spigot every time the economy
ran cold and racial tensions turned hot. The Chinese Exclusion Act
was passed in 1882, and demands for a Japan Exclusion Act in the
early part of this century were dropped only after Japan agreed to
stop exporting male workers.
</P>
<P>
   Congress eliminated Asian immigration in 1924 except from the
Philippines, then a U.S. territory.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, when American farmers needed pickers in the job-rich
years after World War II, the Bracero Program was enacted. It
allowed 4.5 million Mexican laborers to legally pick U.S. crops
from 1942 to 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Now the high-tech industry, the newfound engine of the U.S.
economy, is before Congress arguing that foreign workers are the
oil that keeps that motor humming.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech won a big victory in Congress two years ago, achieving
a 77 percent increase in the number of H-1B visas processed each
year. But after peaking this year at 115,000, the number of visas
allowed is scheduled to decrease to 65,000 by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The industry has pinned its hopes to a bill that would raise the
cap to 200,000. Without some kind of legislative relief, industry
officials think the new year's allocation of visas likely will run
dry in January.
</P>
<P>
   This year's cap was reached in March, halfway through the
federal fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   While both parties are eager to help the industry, some
Republicans say the visa program limits opportunity for U.S.
citizens. Some Democrats, meanwhile, charge that imported labor,
even in the high-tech sector, depresses wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had to go into the free market and bid without the
advantage of H-1B, the price of high-tech workers would go up, and
I bet you six times more people would decide not to become gourmet
chefs, but they would learn to become chemists instead,'' said Rep.
Pete Stark, D-Calif. ``It's all supply and demand.''
</P>
<P>
   High-tech companies argue that they are unable to fill hundreds
of positions at a time because demand far exceeds supply.
</P>
<P>
   They sometimes point to a 1997 Commerce Department study
indicating that more than 1 million high-tech jobs would surface by
2005, but U.S. colleges and universities were producing only 25,000
graduates a year with degrees in computer-related fields.
</P>
<P>
   A General Accounting Office assessment of that study, however,
concluded that it was flawed by ``serious analytical and
methodological weaknesses that undermine the credibility of its
conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   The GAO did not determine whether the high-tech shortage was
real.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Norman Matloff, a computer science professor at the
University of California at Davis, has concluded that the
programmer shortage is an industry fiction to depress wages by
continued hiring of cheap foreign help.
</P>
<P>
   His studies indicate that high-tech companies hire only 2
percent of the applicants they see.
</P>
<P>
   Organizations representing high-tech workers, such as the
Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers, are urging
Congress to keep the visa cap where it stands until further study
establishes a need for expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Koon, Intel's director of corporate affairs, said the
chip-maker, based in Santa Clara, Calif., in fiscal 1998-99
directly hired 455 employees, about 7 percent of all U.S. hires, on
H-1B visas.
</P>
<P>
   She said Intel views those workers as neither cheap nor
short-term.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to pay prevailing wage,'' she said. ``The people
we're looking at are people with all kinds of experience and
degrees where they can work almost anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some scenarios and clearly for some companies, they are
temporary workers in a sense,'' she said. ``We intend when we hire
them that we'll eventually get them a green card.''
</P>
<P>
   For many workers that's the ultimate payoff of the H-1B visa,
which by itself is good for six years. Employers can petition the
government to grant permanent U.S. residency in place of the
temporary visa.
</P>
<P>
   Julian Emmerson, who works for Northwest Software in Beaverton,
Ore., moved from England in 1994 on an H-1B visa. He, his wife and
two daughters became permanent residents this year. They just
bought a house on six acres.
</P>
<P>
   But Tamhane isn't sure whether he will stay here or return to
India.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   His journey reminds him of an Indian proverb about the big fish
that left a small river destined for the sea. Riding a current of
high-tech immigration, Tamhane is curious to know whether he is a
big fish after all.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies, such as SEH America, a silicon wafer
manufacturer with a plant in Vancouver, Wash., have employed few
H-1B workers because of costs associated with hiring. Fewer than 10
of the SEH plant's 1,700 workers hold the visa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very expensive to hire people and pay for the visas and
we'd rather hire Americans if we can,'' said Julie Branford, an SEH
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ____-
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Pulaski is a reporter for The Oregonian of Portland, Ore.
Jim Barnett is The Oregonian's Washington bureau reporter.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1654EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
