   US-SUGAR _ U.S. Sugar is laying off 300 people; not sure what
kind of workers. Company recently got a new CEO who had said
reorganization was likely. (Rush, Owers, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   CNN-FYI _ CNN predicts it will turn a profit on a new Web site
aimed at teachers and the millions of school children who go online
for homework help. CNN executives say the site doesn't have ads,
but they have signed on three companies that are paying to have
their logos, names and links appear on the site. The Web site,
CNNfyi.com, officially launches Monday. (Kempner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FLA-FLIGHTS _ A Florida-based carrier called Southeast Airlines
plans to begin service in Atlanta next month, flying to Charlotte
and two Florida cities at cheapo fares. (Fonti, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PEST-INDUSTRY _ Complaints about termite inspections resound
nationwide. Accusations about various firms regularly failing to
perform adequate inspections _ even forging customer signatures on
reinspection tickets _ have cropped up in Florida, Alabama and
other states. As such charges of misbehavior persist the
pest-control industry battles a chronic credibility problem. Other
improprieties, regulators and consumers say, include applying
insufficient amounts of chemicals in termite treatments and
misleading customers on warranties. (Miller, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   PEST-GREEN _ The hot new weapon in the battle against America's
termites looks low-tech, resembling a footlong plastic screw.
Inside its hollow cylinder is placed a bait _ pieces of pine or
other wood. A dozen or more of these bait stations are planted in
the ground around a house. If termites start to nibble on the pine,
a chemical is put in the cavity, and the termites carry this poison
back to the colony. The death spiral begins. (Miller, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   PEST-TIPS _ Consumer tips on pest control. (Miller, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
