u i BC-FRANCE-FUEL-NYT &LR;      09-08 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-FUEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARGE FRENCH UNION URGES END TO FUEL PROTESTS, BUT MANY IGNORE
CALL 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A truckers' strike protesting the rising cost of fuel,
which had begun to cripple supplies around the country, seemed to
lose some of its momentum on Friday as the leader of France's
largest trucker's group urged its members to lift their blockades
at more than 90 of the country's major fuel depots.
</P>
<P>
   But many truckers _ perhaps encouraged by a poll that suggested
that more than 80 percent of the country supported them _ appeared
to defy their leader. And a smaller union said that its members
would continue the protest as well.
</P>
<P>
   The truckers want a 20 percent cut in diesel fuel taxes for
freight trucks and have been joined by workers from many other
sectors of the economy who have been squeezed by the spiraling cost
of fuel in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   The strike has presented Prime Minister Lionel Jospin with a
difficult political problem. On Wednesday he cut off negotiations
with the unions when his offer of a 15 percent cut in taxes was
rejected. Late Friday, he met with several of his Cabinet ministers
to discuss the next steps to take in the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a booming economy, France has a huge budget surplus,
so Jospin may be able to reduce the high taxes on fuel. But
environmentalists who form part of the prime minister's ruling
coalition are fiercely opposed to any further concessions and have
already criticized the 15 percent cut he offered.
</P>
<P>
   The truckers began their protest in earnest on Monday as a
followup to a strike by fishermen, who had blocked the country's
ports last month to protest fuel costs and eventually won financial
concessions from the government. Soon after the truckers began
their blockades, they were joined by farmers, airline workers, bus
drivers, taxi drivers and even the owners of river barges and
sightseeing boats that cruise the Seine. They all found ways to
block traffic and disrupt train and air services in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   The country's largest farming union said on Friday that it, too,
would keep up the protests that have cause varying hardships
throughout the country and gas shortages at up to 80 percent of gas
stations.
</P>
<P>
   But some strikers were reported to be ending their protests,
especially in the northern regions of the country. And one
particular flash point, the Channel Tunnel in Calais, was clear of
protesters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
