<HEADER>
A6605 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-IDOLATRY0909-COX     09-08 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IDOLATRY0909-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Neither candidate gets God's endorsement? Sorry, that's idolatry
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Enlisting God to hype a political candidate
is the worst kind of blasphemy.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are good at it. Democrats are getting better. But
both parties are dabbling in idolatry.
</P>
<P>
   Vice presidential candidate Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn.,
often prays to God as part of his canned ``stump'' speech. His
prayer is appropriate at home or in synagogue but not while
publicly running for office.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, prayers appear to be addressed to an
audience other than God. And they seem designed more to impress the
electorate and win votes than be an act of worship.
</P>
<P>
   As an observant Orthodox Jew, Lieberman should rigorously avoid
even the appearance of that kind of blunder.
</P>
<P>
   His faith is, no doubt, genuine, but his public piety looks
suspiciously like he is using God to promote his own agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush does the same thing. Bush uses God as an
interchangeable campaign device to be bent to the needs of his
audience.
</P>
<P>
   He went to Bob Jones University this spring to speak to
conservative Protestant students and faculty who routinely spew
venom toward Catholics. Then he apologized profusely to the Roman
Catholic community for doing so.
</P>
<P>
   He insists Jesus is his favorite philosopher, as if the
Christian Messiah were a member of his campaign staff.
</P>
<P>
   Every candidate has the right to practice the faith of his
choosing. But both Christianity and Judaism condemn those who
manipulate God to conform to their will. That's idolatry.
</P>
<P>
   Putting something, anything _ money, sex, power, one's own will
or political office _ before God is idolatry.
</P>
<P>
   Many scholars suggest that idolatry is the sad foundation of
absolutely every sin condemned in the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   And the most prominent politicians of both parties wallow in it
daily. They try ludicrously to register God as a member of their
faithful followers.
</P>
<P>
   God is obviously not a Republican or a Democrat. He is a
reformer, but he would not be a member of the Reform party no
matter who heads that ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Televangelist Pat Robertson makes God appear to be a fascist.
But God is more likely to be a libertarian.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no label can contain the Father of Abraham, Jesus and
Mohammed. And even that image falls short of the glory of the God
politicians bandy about with such cavalier ease.
</P>
<P>
   God is both liberal and conservative, so neither side of that
debate can claim him. God's spirit blows where it will, making all
things new, according to the New Testament. No one can be more
liberal than the Holy Spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, God is the same yesterday, today and forever, a rock of
unwavering stability with whom all can find solace, Scripture tells
us.
</P>
<P>
   Despite campaign rhetoric, God is quintessentially independent
and stands in judgment of the idolatry of all politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
