<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Sept. 10, will move Saturday (in the `a' category
unless otherwise noted.)
</P>
<P>
   _ On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE-POLITICS-REVIEW (Washington) _ The consensus of
politicians, economists and the public generally on health policy
has shifted since the 1992 election. Then, the prevailing view was
that the failure of many Americans to have medical insurance posed
a serious national problem. There was widespread disagreement over
how to solve the problem but not over whether it could and should
be addressed. Now, the politicians and economists have come to
believe _ and the public has become convinced _ that the problem is
simply too difficult to solve in one giant stroke. By David E.
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-INSULT-REVIEW (Undated) _ I am used to being around big
news. But observing the story is different than being it. And last
week I seemed to be the story. Gov. George W. Bush spotted me at a
rally in Naperville, Ill. Not realizing the microphones were
working, he told his running mate, Dick Cheney, that I was a
``major league (expletive).'' This was hardly the first time I have
been attacked, though it was the first time the attack accorded me
``major league'' status. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inside:
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-WARMING-REVIEW (Undated) _ Past climate ups and downs
mostly mesh well with simultaneous natural variations in the
brightness of the sun or the cooling effect of parasol-like plumes
of particles spewed by big volcanoes. But the recent warming,
according to several recent studies, only correlates well with one
thing: the buildup of carbon dioxide, methane, and the other
greenhouse gases. The lesson in all of this, according to many
climate scientists, is that no one should expect some alarm bell to
start ringing _ some disquieting image of a melted pole, say _ to
conveniently summon societies to take action to forestall a
hot-house future. By Andrea C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-POLITICS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The disagreement over the
proper place of religion in politics summons us once again to the
works of those ever-useful observers of American life, Alexis de
Tocqueville of France and James Bryce of Britain. Both of their
classic studies, Tocqueville's ``Democracy in America'' (1835) and
Bryce's ``The American Commonwealth'' (1888), attend the matter in
a spirit that should elicit an amen from Sen. Joseph Lieberman, who
has rekindled the issue by saying that religion supports a moral
foundation for public policy. By Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   NAPSTER-MP3COM-REVIEW (Undated) _ It seems ironic that MP3.com
is being punished even though it was the online music service that
was trying to ensure that people have legitimate copies of the
works _ properly paid for _ before letting people listen to the
music, says Pamela Samuelson, co-director of the UC-Berkeley Center
for Law and Technology. By contrast, Napster, another high-profile
Internet music company being sued by the major record labels, has
so far eluded any legal backlash, though that it aims to help
people copy and share music without paying for it. Yet Samuelson
predicts ``Napster has a much better chance on appeal than
MP3.com.'' By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   BANNED-APPAREL-REVIEW (Undated) _ Why do politicians focus on
certain types of clothing. And how does a brief bit of fabric cause
so much consternation? Several nations have banned or actively
discouraged miniskirts. France requires male bathers to wear
skintight Speedos rather than trunks, on the ground that trunks
could pass for shorts and be worn in potentially unsanitary areas.
And in America, Chief Justice William Rehnquist has suggested that
women in provocative clothing may be inadvertently inviting sexual
harassment. By Jenny Lyn Bader.
</P>
<P>
   CIA-POLITICS-REVIEW (Washington) _ The CIA has been struggling
for its footing since the end of the Cold War robbed it of a raison
d'etre. But under the Clinton administration, it has suffered from
two worsening trends: a skittishness about politically sensitive
intelligence and an aversion to risky espionage operations. This
spring CIA analysts were ordered that there were to be no surprises
and no intelligence fiascos that could cause headaches in November.
By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   DORMS-BELONGINGS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The days when students would
show up at the end of summer with a trunk and a suitcase are long
gone, say college administrators. Today, students have become
hermit crabs and simply take everything with them when they move
into the dorms. The ideal seems to be as much stuff as it is
possible to cram into their rooms. By Jayson Blair.
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPIC-FORECAST-REVIEW (Undated) _ Two Yale business school
professors have developed a formula they say enables them to
predict exactly how many gold medals each country will win at the
Sydney Olympics. The formula posits that just two factors account
for 95 percent of a nation's predicted medal count: the number of
medals it won at a previous Olympics, and the size of its economy.
By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-ELECTION-REVIEW (Belgrade) _ Democracy is about choice, but
in the Yugoslav version, now playing itself out with Slobodan
Milosevic's future at stake, there are likely to be more choices
than usual. But with a strong opposition candidate doing better
than Milosevic in the opinion polls, Milosevic also gets to make a
choice: whether to accept the choice of the people _ if it goes
against him _ or to manipulate the totals and declare victory
regardless. By Steven Erlanger. (Moving in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
