<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6620 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-SMITH-COLUMN09-COX     09-08 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLessons about work, dignity and fairness.c. 2000 Cox News
<TEXT>
Service
<P>
   My father's family leased land to sharecroppers _ ironic for a
family that descended from chattel slaves to turn other people into
wage slaves.
</P>
<P>
   Sharecroppers worked the land, never owning it and never getting
out of debt. They made money for someone else, but rarely knew what
it was like to have money in their pockets. Recalling those days
when workers picked the cotton on his daddy's land in Burleson
County, my father said, ``It wasn't fair.'' His words are a lesson
for me about work, dignity and fairness.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the custodians, clerks, librarians and others at the
University of Texas who keep the campus running receive few
benefits and low pay. That isn't fair, either, especially at one of
the largest universities in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   This week's ``burnt orange flu,'' organized by members of the
University of Texas Staff Association, didn't become an epidemic.
But the issues behind the sickout are real to anyone who has worked
hard and never been able to make ends meet. They are real to people
who have had two jobs. They are real to child-care workers and
teachers, who are paid so little for shaping our future.
</P>
<P>
   They are real enough for a city commission to study how to
address Austin's growing wage divide. And they are real enough for
the Travis County commissioners to approve an $8.50 minimum wage
for county employees this week.
</P>
<P>
   A full-time job ought to pay for the basics of living. But
that's not the case in Texas, a right- to- work state with one of
the highest percentages of working poor people in the nation. We
don't bat an eye when people work 40 hours a week and still need
food stamps or government-subsidized healthcare.
</P>
<P>
   Austin is among the most expensive cities in the state. And the
wage gap on the UT campus mirrors the divide in Austin. The average
pay for support staff at UT has increased by 15 percent in three
years, but it still lags behind other local salaries.
</P>
<P>
   But university and staff association officials use conflicting
pay figures. The minimum wage at the university, effective this
month, is $7.61, university officials say. The staff association
says the minimum wage, according to a UT pay plan, is only $6.73 an
hour. The staff association is calling for a minimum wage of $9.16
an hour. Other demands include no increase in out-of-pocket health
insurance premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Pay and benefits aren't the only problems, according to the
staff association. Working conditions for some custodians is
unsafe, the workers alleged in an unsigned letter. The custodians
say they are forced to work with hazardous chemicals, which cause
their eyes to burn, carry 20- pound vacuum cleaner bags, and get a
doctor's note if they're out sick for four hours. Some of the
complaints are being investigated, say university officials.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' flagship university needs to adjust its priorities. You
don't create a great university by breaking the backs of the
workers who run it.
</P>
<P>
   The staff issues at UT are not unlike those facing the
sharecroppers who worked for my grandfather: a decent wage, a
little dignity, fairness. That's not too much to ask for.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact susan Smith at ssmith(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
