<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Sept. 9, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Humid air streaming north from the Gulf of Mexico will fuel
showers and thunderstorms across the Southeast and lower
Mississippi Valley on Saturday. A few storms will produce more than
an inch of rain. The precipitation will slightly reduce the
regional rainfall deficit, but the drought-plagued areas of Central
Texas and Oklahoma will stay dry.
</P>
<P>
   A weakening front will bring broken clouds and isolated showers
to the interior Northeast, though most of the region will stay dry
and warm with intervals of clouds and sun. Farther south, drier air
circulating around high pressure near the Carolina coast will bring
considerable sunshine to the Middle Atlantic and Southeast Coasts.
</P>
<P>
   The West will be mainly sunny, though onshore breezes will cause
cool, showery weather near the Northwest coast. Isolated strong
afternoon storms will erupt in the northern Plains as an
approaching jet stream disturbance intercepts humid air.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: HURRICANE HUNTERS
</P>
<P>
   A cluster of thunderstorms over the Gulf of Mexico caught the
attention of forecasters at the National Hurricane Center on
Friday. So, Saturday, an Air Force hurricane-hunter aircraft is
scheduled to investigate the possibility that the thunderstorms
could organize into a tropical storm. Because tropical systems
often form over remote areas that have few weather observations,
forecasters must rely on aircraft reconnaissance to gauge the vital
signs of these potentially dangerous systems. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
