<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6649 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0909-COX     09-08 2049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0909-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Gore promotes tuition tax breaks
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore, at a community college in New Orleans, pushed a tuition
tax break to ease college expenses, as well as other efforts to
bolster worker training. A key element of Gore's spending package
is an effort to upgrade education and training programs that Gore
argues are key to worker survival in an economy increasingly
dominated by burgeoning information technology. He has proposed a
10-year, $36 billion package that would make college tuition
payments tax deductible. The package includes an option to make the
tuition expense deduction a tax credit as well, which would ensure
the same kind of tax break for people with lower incomes.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN STYLE MAKEOVER FOR BUSH
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush put his campaign's new closer-to-the-people style
into practice by sharing coffee and answering questions from
high-tech factory workers as he campaigned in Pennsylvania with a
new theme: ``Real Plans for Real People.'' He said he's ready to
talk to voters _ lots of them _ and visit in their homes. ``I've
got to get out and talk to people, and I'm going to do a lot of
it,'' he told workers at a Marconi Communications factory cafeteria
in Warrendale. Bush also said he would continue to speak plainly,
regardless of poll numbers: ``I'm going to tell you what I think
and let the political chips fall where they may.'' Bush told
reporters that the National Fraternal Order of Police has endorsed
him.
</P>
<P>
   SEPARATE BUT EQUAL WITH HALLIBURTON
</P>
<P>
   Citing ``cultural differences,'' the company that Dick Cheney
headed for the past five years maintains separate restrooms
overseas for its American and foreign employees. Halliburton Co.
said Cheney was unaware of the segregated restroom policy in effect
during his five years as chairman. The oil services giant, a major
federal contractor operating worldwide, said the policy was ``not
an attempt to demean any employee'' and was ``no different than
Eastern countries that often designate facilities for use by
Westerners.'' But a State Department official, Bill Wanlund, said
he had never seen a similar policy in trips and assignments to four
continents. And a leading public health professional, Richard
Levinson, said, absent evidence of unsanitary practices, he could
see no justification for the policy.
</P>
<P>
   NEW AD HITS GORE ON CREDIBILITY
</P>
<P>
   Trying to help George W. Bush regain his footing, the Republican
Party plans to air a new TV ad questioning Al Gore's credibility.
``Can I believe him?'' asks a female narrator in the ad that raises
the vice president's fund-raising troubles in 1996 and criticizes
his education proposals. GOP officials said today the new ad will
air in Michigan and Pennsylvania, two of the most competitive
states. Over the last week, the Republican National Committee has
aired an ad in 16 states that questions Gore's credibility on
campaign finance reform and claims of a key role in developing the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   WILLINGNESS TO MOVE ON DEBATE ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   Amid Republican concerns that he needs to end the debate over
debates, George W. Bush and several of his advisers have sent
signals that they were willing to be flexible about the original
position that they had outlined and that Al Gore had rejected. Bush
had been seeking to cast that rejection as a referendum on Gore's
credibility, asserting that the vice president was breaking a
promise to debate anytime and anywhere. But a few of Bush's
advisers conceded that Bush had not made significant inroads with
that argument, which the campaign had made the centerpiece of a TV
spot.
</P>
<P>
   DEBATE REHEARSALS HAVE THEIR STAND-INS
</P>
<P>
   Even while largely rejecting a bipartisan commission's plan for
presidential debates, George W. Bush has been preparing privately
for months for his square-off with Al Gore. The Bush campaign early
on tapped wonkish Sen. Judd Gregg of New Hampshire to play Gore in
practice sessions with Bush, and the two have been rehearsing since
at least June. Gregg also played Gore in 1996 for GOP vice
presidential nominee Jack Kemp. Asked by the Washington Post what
made Gregg a good Gore, GOP officials described Gregg as ``smart,''
``stiff'' and ``dour.'' Playing a similar role for Gore has been
lobbyist Tom Downey, a former congressman who played Kemp for
Gore's 1996 preps and Bill Bradley during the primaries this year.
</P>
<P>
   IN TEXAS, LIEBERMAN SPOTLIGHTS BUSH'S RECORD
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lieberman, surrounded by families who have been unable to
get health care for sick children, said today in George W. Bush's
home state that the governor ``has just not made children's health
coverage and care a priority. In this campaign, Governor Bush may
say that he has a plan to improve children's health across America,
but I think we have a right to ask why hasn't he done it in
Texas,'' Lieberman said in Houston. Later today, Lieberman and his
wife, Hadassah, will rally supporters at an evening event in Miami
Beach and stay overnight.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY SKIPPED MOST TEXAS ELECTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney skipped 14 of 16 elections since registering to vote
in Dallas County, Texas, in late 1995 after moving there as the new
head of Halliburton Co., an oil services company. The missed votes
included the Texas primary in March in which Cheney could have cast
his ballot for his future running mate, George W. Bush. That
2-for-16 voting history compares with the 5-for-6 election
participation rate of his Democratic counterpart, Joe Lieberman,
over the same period. Cheney, campaigning today in Vermont,
acknowledged that he didn't vote in this year's Texas primary, but
said he's voted ``in every federal primary and general election in
the last 20-some years.'' He said extensive travel has kept him
from becoming involved in state or local politics.
</P>
<P>
   JUST DO THE MATH, BUSH URGED
</P>
<P>
   Three prominent Social Security experts have asked George W.
Bush to explain how he would protect the system while diverting
huge sums of money into private investments. ``The arithmetic is
simple,'' they warned in a letter to Bush, arguing that his Bush's
proposal would drain $1 trillion from Social Security and threaten
benefits for millions nearing retirement. The three signatories:
Henry Aaron, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution; Bob
Ball, Social Security commissioner from 1962 to 1973 under three
different presidents of both parties; and Alicia Munnell, a
professor at the Boston College School of Management and a former
assistant secretary of the Treasury. A copy of the letter was
obtained by the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   GORE TAX BREAKS CALLED TOO VAGUE
</P>
<P>
   A non-partisan congressional panel found that 19 of Al Gore's
proposed tax breaks are too vague for an official estimate, leading
to Republican charges that Gore isn't living up to his call for
specifics on campaign issues. The Joint Committee on Taxation,
which estimates all tax legislation on Capitol Hill for Democrats
and Republicans, released documents today showing that such Gore
proposals as a health insurance tax credit, cuts in the estate tax
and education tax breaks ``require additional specification'' in
order to be estimated.
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN CLOSER TO SOME FUNDS
</P>
<P>
   Federal elections officials have determined that Pat Buchanan is
eligible to receive at least some of the $12.6 million in federal
campaign funds earmarked for the Reform Party's presidential
candidate. Staff members have recommended to the Federal Election
Commission that Buchanan be preliminarily certified for the funds,
but at least one commissioner opposed the proposal, expressing a
desire to discuss the matter in public. Buchanan rival John Hagelin
also is seeking the federal funding. A public hearing on the issue
is scheduled for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   OPRAH'S VOTE CLUB
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore and George W. Bush have been engaged in a tug of war for
women voters, mostly middle- and lower-income white women, for much
of the year. And now they hope their pilgrimage for a sit-down with
Oprah Winfrey will do for their presidential campaigns what her
book club routinely does for writers: propel them to the top of the
best-seller list. Gore is scheduled to appear on Monday, with Bush
following up on Sept. 18. Both candidates will appear for the full
hour. The show's theme is ``Why should I vote for you?''
</P>
<P>
   BLACK BAPTISTS ADDRESSED FROM AFAR
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore was warmly received and George W. Bush was met mostly
with silence as both courted the black vote in satellite television
speeches to the National Baptist Convention, USA Inc. in Los
Angeles. Both candidates, however, were sharply criticized by
convention leaders for failing to show up in person. Gore sent his
daughter Kristin to introduce him, and received frequent applause
during a 15-minute speech that stressed black issues and family
values. But there was mostly silence until polite applause at the
end of Bush's five-minute speech. ``He didn't say anything. He did
not explain anything. . . . It was a little five-minute, `Glad you
invited me. Sorry I can't be there. God bless you. That's it,' ``
said Geraldine Martin, a convention-goer from North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS OF OIL SEEPS BACK INTO CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   Many of the nation's most keenly contested states in the
presidential election are also wintry states, where voters could
well feel the double sting of high fuel prices at the pump and in
their homes. And as furnaces fire up against the chill winds of
autumn, the blaming started anew. Republicans, responding to the
10-year high in oil prices, accused the Clinton-Gore administration
of squandering U.S. influence with oil-producing nations and
standing helpless to protect consumers now. Al Gore's campaign shot
back that George W. Bush has no energy policy at all, other than
``to let his friends in the oil industry drill our wilderness
areas,'' as spokesman Doug Hattaway put it.
</P>
<P>
   VOTER PRESSES CHENEY TO GET TOUGHER
</P>
<P>
   The Republican campaign is too soft on Al Gore. That was the
assessment by a voter during Dick Cheney's campaign swing through
Maine and New Hampshire. ``I'd like to see you and Governor Bush be
more aggressive in challenging Al Gore,'' Steve Caminiti, a Bush
supporter, told Cheney in Portland, Maine. The 35-year-old
financial planner said he's frustrated that Cheney and George W.
Bush haven't taken on Gore more stridently on the issue of tax
cuts. The GOP ticket is letting Gore get away ``with lying on a
regular basis,'' Caminiti told Cheney during a question-and-answer
session after Cheney's speech.
</P>
<P>
   NO POLE FOR FIREMAN JOE
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lieberman stopped by Fire Station No. 2 in Little Rock,
Ark., just as the firefighters were washing one of their big red
trucks. Lieberman talked with them for a while about the election,
then decided to help them wash the truck, taking a few swipes at it
from the side. Then one of the firefighters suggested he go down
the firepole, and while others urged him on, Lieberman's aides
immediately advised against it. The day before, while visiting a
Harley-Davidson factory in Kansas City, Mo., he got on the back of
a bike, also against the wishes of his aides.
</P>
<P>
   NO GIULIANI, MUCH CLINTON, AT LATE PARADE
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of this year's Labor Day parade up Fifth Avenue in
New York, to be held Saturday, are planning to turn the march into
a major platform for Hillary Clinton's Senate campaign. To
highlight her, the parade's organizers have taken the unusual step
of not inviting Mayor Rudy Giuliani, who was briefly Clinton's
opponent. Nor have they invited the Republican who is running
against her, Rep. Rick Lazio. In recent years, the parade has been
scheduled for the Saturday after Labor Day, because many union
members don't want their three-day holiday weekends cut short for
the march. Union leaders also wanted to hold it on a day when more
people would be in Manhattan to see it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
