<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-TXINS.908-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  INS COMMISSIONER DORIS MEISSNER'S LEGACY
</P>
<P>
   By Alison Vekshin
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Sept. 8 -- In her first days as the head of the
Immigration and Naturalization Service, Doris Meissner was
surprised when someone passing in the hall surprised her by calling
her ``commissioner.'' She quickly turned to see who was being
addressed.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, the significance of her position as head of the
country's largest federal law enforcement agency instantly set in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commissioner was always somebody else and suddenly it was
me,'' said Meissner, who had served in senior-level positions in
the agency. ``It sunk in that people were really looking to me to
set the course.''
</P>
<P>
   Meissner, 58, was sworn in on October 18, 1993, after the U.S.
Senate unanimously confirmed her nomination. She has managed the
agency for almost the entire term of President Clinton's
administration.
</P>
<P>
   She came on at a time when the organization was largely
under-funded and looked upon as a backward bureaucracy. The
commissioner post was not exactly sought after.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been somewhat traditional in previous administrations
that the head of the INS is a political appointment for a supporter
-- a backwater for political appointees,'' said Frank Sharry,
executive director at the National Immigration Forum, a
pro-immigrant advocacy organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doris doesn't come from that school,'' Sharry said, adding
that President Clinton actively courted her for the post. ``She was
the best person for the job and was reluctantly recruited to sign
on. It's an impossible job.''
</P>
<P>
   A daughter of German immigrants, Meissner was born and raised in
Milwaukee and attended the University of Wisconsin at Madison. She
enrolled in the Integrated Liberal Studies program, where she met
fellow freshman Charles Meissner. They married in 1963, a few days
before graduating. She majored in history with a minor in French.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Meissner postponed her post-graduate studies to work as
assistant director of student financial aid at the university while
Charles completed his doctorate. Then, in 1969, she got her
graduate degree at Madison in political science and education
policy.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled the turbulence of the 1960s in Madison. As a
teaching assistant in graduate school, her classes were cancelled
for weeks at a time because of anti-war demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Meissner did not get involved in the student activism on campus.
``I never was a take-to-the-streets person,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the experience of seeing the protests and the violence led
her to become involved in politics. She wanted to effect change
constructively.
</P>
<P>
   She worked on the successful 1970 campaign to elect Democrat
Midge Miller as one of the first women to the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The Meissners moved in 1971 to Washington D.C., where Doris
Meissner became the first executive director at the National
Women's Political Caucus, a bipartisan organization committed to
getting women elected to public office.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, she became a special assistant to the U.S. attorney
general through the White House Fellows program. Under the highly
selective program created in 1964, 11 to 19 people work full time
for a year as a special assistant to a Cabinet member or a senior
presidential advisor.
</P>
<P>
   She remained at the Justice Department as an assistant director
of the Office of Policy and Planning, executive director of the
Cabinet Committee on Illegal Aliens and a deputy associate attorney
general.
</P>
<P>
   While her German background gave her an inherent appreciation
for the immigrant experience, she admitted to getting into
immigration by happenstance.
</P>
<P>
   As a staff aide on the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, her
husband was responsible for overseeing issues related to Vietnam.
After Saigon fell in 1975, the Meissners agreed to sponsor a
refugee family.
</P>
<P>
   When her colleagues learned that a Vietnamese family was living
wth her, they assumed that she was dedicated to the immigration
cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it never left me from then on,'' she said. ``One thing or
another just kept arising and I became more and more deeply
involved in immigration issues in the Justice Department.''
</P>
<P>
   She served as acting INS commissioner in 1981 and then as
executive associate commissioner until 1986. She left the Justice
Department to become a senior associate and director of the
Immigration Policy Project at the Carnegie Endowment for
International Peace, a nonprofit organization that focuses on
international affairs and U.S. foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   She returned to the department in her current post at a
politically charged time. One of the biggest immigration surges in
U.S. history sparked an anti-immigrant sentiment during the 1990s.
More than 10 million people have immigrated to the United States
since 1990, up from 7,338,062 in the 1980s. Lawmakers pushed
legislation to limit the influx and some attempted to dismantle the
INS.
</P>
<P>
   Meissner led the agency through an overhaul. The INS budget has
grown from $1.6 billion in 1993 to $4.3 billion this year - with
$4.8 billion proposed for the 2001 fiscal year - to support
increased enforcement efforts and to modernize antiquated systems.
</P>
<P>
   The INS work force has gone from 17,000 to more than 32,000
employees. And the agency has developed a new system for handling a
backlog of citizenship applications. When she leaves office at the
end of the Clinton administration, her agency will have processed
more naturalization applications in the last five years than it had
in the last 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   But reforming the INS has not been easy. Meissner's Citizenship
USA program, designed to overcome a three-year backlog by quickly
approving naturalization applications for about 1.3 million people,
was met with Republican opposition. They accused the agency of a
politically motivated effort to pad voter rolls before the 1996
election.
</P>
<P>
   Also, under the hastily implemented program, about 300 people
with criminal backgrounds were naturalized, because FBI fingerprint
reports were not obtained in time.
</P>
<P>
   That year, Meissner also faced a personal tragedy. On April 3,
1996, Charles Meissner, a senior official at the Commerce
Department, died in the plane crash in Croatia that also killed
Commerce Secretary Ron Brown. The Meissners have two grown
children.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Meissner faced perhaps the highest-profile
case of her tenure.
</P>
<P>
   The INS commissioner played a central role in the Elian Gonzalez
controversy, ruling in January that, since the Cuban boy's mother
died while trying to reach the United States, his father back in
Cuba should speak on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   To Meissner, the case was simple, with the bond between the
parent and child at the heart of it. The hardest part was reuniting
Elian with his father, against the wishes of the Miami relatives
who had taken in the boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously what was hard about it was the emotion and
controversy surrounding it,'' Meissner said. ``It affected me in
that it took a tremendous amount of effort and perseverance.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian aside, she said the INS has faced a huge challenge in
trying to reduce illegal immigration from Mexico, citing several
Border Patrol successes in closing some major smuggling corridors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you tighten up the more aggressive and expensive the
smuggling becomes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Border Patrol, one of INS' law enforcement units, has grown
from 3,900 in 1993 to more than 8,000 agents today. All but 700 are
at the Southwest border to combat the shift in illegal immigration
from urban to more remote regions. The agency apprehended 1,537,000
illegal aliens along the borderin fiscal 1999.
</P>
<P>
   INS uses a combination of border patrol agents, camera systems
and air surveillance, and performs hundreds of rescues each year at
the border.
</P>
<P>
   In a nation of immigrants, Meissner said, a central concern for
INS today is the public's attitude toward immigration.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very high levels of immigration,'' she said. ``But
there is not really a national consensus on how much immigration,
what kinds of immigrants ought to be coming into the country, what
numbers of immigrants ought to be coming and how best to integrate
the people from very far-flung parts of the world into the life of
our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act
of 1996, a major piece of legislation, reflected a growing push in
Congress to reduce immigration.
</P>
<P>
   The law stiffened criminal penalties for immigration-related
offenses and imposed restrictions on the eligibility of aliens for
public benefits. It created new requirements on sponsors of alien
relatives for immigration and overhauled the removal process of
inadmissible and deportable aliens, including creating an
``expedited removal'' process.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with immigration issues has been a challenge, admitted
Meissner, who plans to take time off when her term ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many things that I have to deal with are really difficult and
it's hard to know what the best decision is,'' she said. ``An awful
lot of what I do falls into the areas of gray.''
</P>
<P>
   But those who have worked with Meissner consider her a firm and
fair commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is someone who doesn't get flustered,'' White House Deputy
Chief of Staff Maria Echaveste said. ``She just comes up with a
strategy to achieve her goals. Others who have gone through the
gauntlet like she has in the last eight years would have moved
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharry, who has known Meissner since 1984, sees her as firmly
committed to good government and professionalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been in a number of meetings with her where a
politically expedient decision was right there for the taking, but
that's not what moves her,'' Sharry said. ``She brought in some
real top people and is credited for bringing a real enlightened
approach to the management of the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``She inspires respect,'' he said. ``Whenever Doris walks into a
setting with immigration advocates, they treat her like a visiting
dignitary.''
</P>
<P>
   While her leadership has had a lasting impact on the INS,
Meissner said the agency ``is not yet where it needs to be in order
to be a service organization as well as a true professional law
enforcement organization.''
</P>
<P>
   And immigration will remain a touchy and divisive subject long
after she leaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We deal with some of the most fundamental instincts that we as
human beings have: A desire to improve our lives, provide for our
families, allow our children have a better future, and live in a
system that respects rights and fundamental freedoms,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the immigration issues really do go to the heart of
who we are as a nation,'' Meissner said. ``And I think I've been
able to play a part in preserving and strengthening our immigration
tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Meissner Graphic 1
</P>
