<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6685 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-UN-0909-COX     09-08 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-UN-0909-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON LEAVES UN SUMMIT WITH UNFINISHED BUSINESS
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ President Clinton wrapped up three days of intensive
diplomacy here Friday amid an air of diminishing expectations, as
the weight of unfinished business began to settle on the shoulders
of a leader who's era is about to close.
</P>
<P>
   With four months left in office, Clinton used this week's
Millennium Summit at the United Nations to begin bidding farewell
to the community of global leaders he's engaged with and, in many
cases, befriended over the past eight years.
</P>
<P>
   At almost every turn, though, there were signs that key pieces
of the vast global agenda Clinton has crafted and pursued aren't
likely to fall into place before he leaves office in January.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Russian President Vladimir Putin clashed publicly
over nuclear arms controls, in an unsettling reminder that, a
decade after the end of the Cold War, the transformation in
U.S.-Russian relations Clinton sought to forge remains dangerously
incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   An awkward chance meeting between Clinton and Cuban dictator
Fidel Castro carried similar irony. Clinton had hoped, and sought
early on, to end four decades of estrangement between the two
neighbors, but the thaw was thwarted after Castro's MIGs shot down
two Miami-based Cessnas flying near Havana to protest his regime in
1996, killing four unarmed civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's Friday meeting with Chinese President Jiang Zemin
underscored the continuing friction in Sino-American relations over
Beijing's enduring political repression and human rights abuses,
seven years after Clinton began pushing a policy of engagement,
saying increased U.S. trade and investment would help promote
reform in the world's most populous nation.
</P>
<P>
   Surely most disappointing of all, with no visible progress in
his meetings with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat, hopes were fading, though not completely
abandoned, for the Mideast peace accord Clinton has labored
tirelessly to secure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to keep pressing here,'' Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright told reporters Thursday. ``But the truth is,
just look at the calendar, and there is not a lot of time.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Clinton can claim success on a host of his foreign
policy priorities. Returning democratic rule to Haiti, ending
ethnic bloodshed in Bosnia, winning Congressional passage of the
North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) and heading off a
financial debacle in Mexico are among the big games in his win
column. Critics may debate the effectiveness of each of those
initiatives, but Clinton, for better or worse, got each done.
</P>
<P>
   It's too early to rule out additional victories, as well,
including the possibility, however remote, that Clinton might yet
be able to pull a rabbit out of the diplomatic hat and bring Arafat
and Barak to a Mideast peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   There comes a point in the life of an administration, however,
when the thrust shifts from generating lofty long-term objectives
to the more mundane exercise of plotting life after government.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, Deputy National Security Adviser Jim Steinberg
left the White House to take a job at a philanthropic institution,
part of the normal shift from public to private sector as any
administration winds to a close.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone can read a calendar,'' said Walter Kansteiner, who
served as an NSC official under President George Bush. As the clock
winds down, he said, ``there is a realization that they're some
things you're just not going to get done.''
</P>
<P>
   The crafting and pursuit of U.S. foreign policy is always a work
in progress. International diplomacy is as much a management
challenge as a set of tasks to be checked off when complete.
</P>
<P>
   Where domestic policy often revolves around specific benchmarks
_ legislation gets passed, programs get implemented, institutions
take on a life of their own _ foreign affairs is a bit more messy,
complicated as it is by the actions and motives of U.S. allies,
partners and foes abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some end marks, but more often than not it is a
process,'' said Kansteiner, a partner with The Scowcroft Group, a
Washington D.C. consulting firm. ``There's the peace process that
doesn't get finalized, or the bilateral relationship that gets over
one hurdle but then faces other problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Often an outgoing president's problems get kicked down the road
to its successor.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton inherited from Bush, for example, difficulties in
Somalia _ where Bush sent 30,000 troops two weeks after losing to
Clinton in 1992 _ and in Iraq, where U.S. pilots continue to fly
combat air patrol missions almost daily, precisely as they did when
Clinton took office.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever replaces Clinton in January _ Democrat Al Gore or
Republican George W. Bush _ will doubtless inherit a range of
global challenges just as Clinton did.
</P>
<P>
   He will also inherit opportunities, however, to build on
progress Clinton has made.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have learned the lessons of the past,'' Clinton said in
his final address as president before the United Nations, ``we can
leave a very different legacy for our children.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
