<HEADER>
A6704 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GRANDPARENTS-$ADV10-C     09-08 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRANDPARENTS-$ADV10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BOOMER GRANDPARENTS ARE CHANGING THE STEREOTYPE
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Sept. 10.
 &HT;    By MEGAN K. DOYLE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Remember gray-haired Grandma in her checkered
apron, baking perfect cookies? Today, Grandma's wearing a business
suit and behind the wheel of a sport utility vehicle, talking on a
cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   On this Sunday, as the nation celebrates National Grandparents
Day, ``grandparents are a new breed of people,'' said Dr. Arthur
Kornhaber, the founder and president of the Foundation for
Grandparenting and author of ``Contemporary Grandparenting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The old stereotypes of aging _ being aged as a grandparent _
don't hold right now. The boomer generation are people who changed
the world. They're used to doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 74 percent of Americans over 50 are grandparents,
according to a study by Age Wave, LLC and Cologne Life
Reinsurance(cq).
</P>
<P>
   Steven Barsch, chief executive officer of igrandparents.com, a
Web site devoted to enhancing the lives of grandparents and their
grandchildren, agreed that baby boomers are creating a new image of
grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's grandparent is younger, wealthier, has much more time
and is much more active,'' Barsch said. ``Today's grandparents are
not sitting back in a rocking chair waiting for death to take
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Wilson, 57, of West Palm Beach, Fla., is a prime
example. An avid golfer and very active church member, Wilson _ a
grandfather of two _ travels all over the country to race cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider myself an average grandparent,'' Wilson said.
``I focus more on investments on my grandchildren's behalf, stocks
and bonds. I let their parents focus on their everyday
bringing-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson isn't the only one. Fifty-six percent of grandparents
agreed that contributions to a college fund are and easier choice
than traditional presents, according to a 1995 survey by Maturity
Mark Services.
</P>
<P>
   New image or not, today's grandparents face a difficult role,
according to Susan V. Bosak, author of ``How to Build the Grandma
Connection.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Modern grandparents face many challenges,'' said Bosak.
</P>
<P>
   Divorce, physical distance and an age-segregated society are
reasons today's grandparents to feel hesitant about getting
involved in grandchildren's lives, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many boomer grandparents are turning to new methods such as the
Internet and e-mail to face these challenges. Adults 50 and over
are just as likely as young adults to use e-mail on a daily basis,
according to a 1996 study in American Demographics magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody spends more time or money on line than the 50-plus
demographic,'' Barsch said. ``It puts them on an even keel with
their grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   Kornhaber who also founded the Web site grandparenting.org,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very strongly that every grandparent today has to be
computer-literate if they want to live in their child's world.''
</P>
<P>
   With more grandparents still actively involved with their
careers, relationships with grandchildren can suffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have busy, hectic schedules,'' Bosak said. ``And the
key to bonding is frequent, consistent contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Christine Howard, 53, of West Palm Beach, a grandmother of five,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself a very busy person,'' says Howard. ``I
assist my husband in the office and cook three meals a day. I'm an
active person with no time at all, but I still manage to find time
for my grandkids.''
</P>
<P>
   Bosak and other authorities said that a strong
grandparent-grandchild relationship is important to both lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk about how important parents are in children's lives,
even how important peers are in children's lives, and somehow
grandparents get forgotten,'' she said. ``Research shows that
children need as much as four to six active adults in their
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Grandparents Day provides an opportunity for many grandparents
to be a part of their grandchildren's lives. The day began as the
idea of West Virginia housewife Marian McQuade in 1970, and was
officially declared National Grandparents Day by President Carter
in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   While some grandparents may indeed mark the day by baking
cookies with their grandchildren, others may be sharing activities
such as hiking, sailing, traveling, or gardening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's grandparents are not grammies and grandpas whittling
around the house,'' Kornhaber said. ``Those days are gone. It's a
whole new ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   igrandparents.com: www.igrandparents.com
</P>
<P>
   Foundation for Grandparenting: www.grandparenting.org
</P>
<P>
   Megan K. Doyle's e-mail address is MeganD(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
