<HEADER>
A6712 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LOSTDOG-CHIP-NYTR &LR;      09-08 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOSTDOG-CHIP-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROCHIP REUNITES OWNERS WITH MISSING DOG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ga.)   By JULIA FERRANTE   The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ A dog named Jack showed up at an animal shelter
here this week. He wasn't talking, but a microchip implanted under
his skin told a surprising story.
</P>
<P>
   Jack, a Labrador mix, traveled a long way to get to Central
Florida. His owners, Luann and Allen Lane of Marietta, Ga., hadn't
seen the pup since late March, when, at 8 weeks old, he followed
their beagle, Barney, under the fence in their yard and disappeared
from the Atlanta suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Barney returned that day, but Jack never came back, Allen Lane
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How he got here we can only imagine,'' said Debbie Taylor,
director of operations in Lakeland for the Society for the
Prevention of Cruelty to Animals.
</P>
<P>
   A couple who live in Mulberry found Jack about two weeks ago and
searched for his owner, but brought him to the SPCA when they came
up dry, Taylor said. Taylor said she routinely scans pets brought
into the shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've reunited pets with their owners before, but never across
state lines,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Luann Lane speculated that a truck driver or someone who was
moving to Florida picked up Jack and kept him.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said that since Jack left the Lanes, he had been neutered
and gained about 45 pounds. She thought it likely someone took him
in, brought him to a veterinarian and drove him to Florida. He
probably escaped again and was lost until the Mulberry couple found
him two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Lanes paid $4.95 to have the identifying chip implanted in
Jack when they adopted him from an Atlanta area animal shelter,
Luann Lane said. Animals adopted from shelters there are required
to have the implants in case they are lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was a good idea, and as it turns out, it was a
great idea,'' Allen Lane said.
</P>
<P>
   When Jack disappeared, she reported the loss to the animal
shelter and the information was put out on a national network.
</P>
<P>
   When Taylor scanned Jack, the Lanes' information came up.
Although Jack had apparently been to a vet to be neutered,
veterinarians don't routinely scan pets brought in for treatment,
Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who lost him may still be looking for him, but he's
registered to this couple in Georgia, so that's where he's going,''
Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Jack is traveling back to Georgia with Luann's ex-husband, Steve
Engstrom, a computer salesman who happened to be in Florida doing
business in Tampa and Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``He travels quite a bit, and Florida is part of his
territory,'' Allen Lane said. ``We called him and said, `You're
never going to believe what happened.'''
</P>
<P>
   Barney the beagle died about two weeks ago. He dug out of the
yard again and was hit by a car, Allen Lane said. The Lanes adopted
another dog, a cocker spaniel mix named Buddy, during their search.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they get along,'' Luann Allen said. ``I think they
will. Jack won't know us, of course, but I'm really excited.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is a member of The New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
