<HEADER>
A6725 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-AARP09-COX     09-08 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AARP09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AARP SAYS BUSH, GORE MEDICARE PLANS BOTH UNDERFUNDED
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Both presidential candidates will need to put more
money into their proposed Medicare prescription drug plans before
they will satisfy the nation's largest elderly association, its
director said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a National Press Club luncheon, Horace B. Deets,
executive director of AARP, said passage of a Medicare prescription
drug benefit will be the organization's top legislative priority
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be aggressive. We will be forceful. And we will not
rest until all Medicare beneficiaries have access to adequate and
affordable prescription drug coverage as part of Medicare,'' Deets
said.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly the American Association of Retired Persons, AARP has
34 million members aged 50 and older and is considered one of the
most powerful lobbying organizations in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Although the non-partisan association has not endorsed the
prescription drug plan or the Social Security reform plan of either
Vice President Al Gore or Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, its
principles are closer to those expressed by Gore on both key
issues.
</P>
<P>
   AARP wants a voluntary prescription drug benefit that is a part
of Medicare, similar to the Part B program covering doctor bills in
which more than 95 percent of Medicare beneficiaries are enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan does that. He proposes to create a voluntary
Medicare program paid for with a separate drug premium. When fully
implemented in 2008, it would cover half the cost of prescription
drugs up to $5,000 and all out-of-pocket prescription expenses
above $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of his prescription premium are about $25 a month.
That would be in addition to the Part B premium which is now $45.50
a month.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan would provide Medicare subsidies to enable
individuals to purchase competing private insurance plans. The
amount of the government subsidy would vary according to a
beneficiary's income. Benefits and costs would vary according to
the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Both plans would provide free benefits to low-income elderly.
Gore's plan would cost about $253 billion over 10 years; Bush's
plan would cost about $158 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Deets said AARP has not determined how much more money would be
needed to meet its goals, but it would be more than the amount
proposed by Gore. He said AARP would like to see combined premiums
for Part B and the new drug benefit in the $30 to $50 range.
</P>
<P>
   On Social Security, Deets said AARP has a set of six principles
it would like to see incorporated into any reform. Among them, the
association prefers that individual savings accounts be established
as an addition to _ rather than a replacement of _ benefits
generated by the current system.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan would earmark a portion of the 12.4 percent payroll
tax used to finance Social Security to create individual investment
accounts. Those benefits would replace a portion of the guaranteed
Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Gore would use the projected federal surplus to reduce the
federal debt and pledge that money toward future Social Security
reserves after 2037.
</P>
<P>
   While AARP does not endorse candidates, it has launched a major
effort to inform voters about candidate positions and urge them to
vote. Deets said about 70 percent of the association's 34 million
members are expected to vote this fall.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   AARP: www.aarp.org
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
