<HEADER>
A6742 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-HONGKONG-ELECT-NYT &LR;      09-08 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG ELECTIONS FOCUS ON CITY ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Law Hing shifted restlessly from one foot to the
other as he listened to the candidates trade accusations in a
debate at a housing project here this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are without integrity,'' he said, shaking his head
at the litany of supposed wrongdoing and chicanery.
</P>
<P>
   Well over 1 million people are expected to turn out for
legislative elections on Sunday, the second since Hong Kong
reverted to Chinese sovereignty in 1997. Many, like Law, 73, regard
voting as a civic duty and a hard-won privilege. But even though
this is the largest exercise in multiparty politics under Chinese
rule, Beijing has barely a walk-on role.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than seizing the election as an opportunity to stand up
to China, most people here regard it as a chance to register their
dissatisfaction with the Hong Kong establishment. Hong Kong
politics, which in previous years throbbed with debates about
freedom and law, now revolve around seamier issues, like a party
boss who failed to disclose his business interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Beijing factor is no longer important,'' said Lau Siu-kai,
a professor at the Chinese University here. ``China is perceived as
having withdrawn from local politics. But there is still a lot of
voter discontent.''
</P>
<P>
   People here blame the government for failing to lift Hong Kong
out of the Asian economic crisis more quickly. They say it has
careened from scandal to scandal under the hapless leadership of
Tung Chee-hwa, a shipping magnate installed by Beijing as Hong
Kong's chief executive. The Legislature is seen as an ineffectual
body that carps about Tung, but offers no solutions of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Tung's ties to Beijing, dissatisfaction with him has not
translated into unhappiness with China. In a new survey by Hong
Kong Baptist University, 63 percent of those polled approved of the
performance of the Chinese president, Jiang Zemin, while only 32
percent approved of Tung.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a decline in optimism,'' said Michael DeGolyer, who
conducted the survey. ``But it seems to have more to do with how
Hong Kong's leaders are performing than with any supposed
interference from Beijing.''
</P>
<P>
   The ebbing of China as a hot issue has scrambled Hong Kong's
political landscape. In 1998, when fears about Beijing were still
running high, the Democratic Party scored a resounding victory,
winning nearly half the directly elected seats in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   But in district elections last year, the Democrats lost ground
to the main pro-Beijing party, the Democratic Alliance for the
Betterment of Hong Kong. Its emphasis on the economy was more
appealing to voters in recession-ravaged Hong Kong than appeals to
democracy or civil liberties.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, analysts predict that the Democratic Party
will hold on to its position _ but only because the pro-Beijing
party has been tarred by a scandal involving one of its founders.
</P>
<P>
   The party may also be hurt because of its coziness with Tung's
government. This week, Tung was on the defensive again after an
investigation concluded that one of his advisers had met with
officials at Hong Kong University to suppress opinion surveys
critical of the government.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say this aggressively local election is a sign of
Hong Kong's political maturity. Left alone by Beijing, the former
British colony is behaving like any big city during campaign season
_ consumed by local disputes.
</P>
<P>
   But other commentators say the nasty tone in campaigning
reflects Hong Kong's stunted political culture, where only 24 of
the 60 members of the Legislature are directly elected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1757EDT &QL; 
