</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: CENSORSHIP EASED
</P>
<P>
   With a general election due next month, the government has
temporarily eased some of its restrictions on the news media and
the holding of public meetings. Only war news will still face the
heavy censorship put in place by President Chandrika Kumaratunga.
Under those rules, virtually any criticism of the government was
illegal.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: OIL PRICE REBATE
</P>
<P>
   With oil prices at their highest levels in a decade, Ralph
Klein, premier of Alberta, Canada's largest oil-producing province,
has announced that his government will mail each taxpayer two
rebate checks for $100, one in November and one in April. Noting
that his province is to take in a record $5.7 billion from oil and
gas royalties, Klein challenged other oil-rich jurisdictions in
North America, like Texas, to follow his lead.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: FREEDOM FOR 11,000
</P>
<P>
   In a move to reduce overcrowding in the country's prisons, the
ministry of corrections plans to release about 11,000 people
accused of petty crimes who have been unable to make bail while
awaiting trial. The prison system, which has been plagued by
escapes and mismanagement, has a capacity of about 100,000 inmates
but has been holding as many as 170,000 in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: TROOP CUT PROPOSED
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev said a high-level decision had
been made to reduce the size of the armed forces by about 30
percent, or 350,000 troops, in the next three years. ``Decisions to
that effect have been made and proposals on how to proceed are
being drafted for the president,'' Sergeyev said, according to the
Interfax news agency. Last month President Vladimir Putin pressed
his commanders for a major restructuring of the 1.2 million-member
armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: BASQUE CRACKDOWN PLANNED
</P>
<P>
   The cabinet approved measures to crack down on separatist
violence in the Basque region. Under the proposed laws, which
require parliament's approval, youths engaged in separatist street
violence would be tried as adults and subject to longer sentences.
In addition, trials of terrorist suspects would be held in Madrid
instead of in the Basque region.
</P>
</TEXT>
