<HEADER>
A6760 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CAR-NASCAR-NYTR &LR;      09-08 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DEVICE MAY PUT BRAKES ON ACCIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK ZIER  
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nervous NASCAR drivers, contemplating their return to New
Hampshire next week, hope to have a new safety device in place when
they get back to the track where two competitors died this year.
</P>
<P>
   The device, developed by Roush Racing, is a sensor that monitors
heat given off by the brakes. When the brakes are applied hard, the
sensor automatically kills the engine.
</P>
<P>
   It was tested before Darlington's Southern 500 by Jeff Burton,
one of five Roush Winston Cup drivers, and has generated a lot of
enthusiasm among those concerned about lessening the impact of a
car going into a wall because of a stuck throttle.
</P>
<P>
   Stuck throttles were blamed for crashes at New Hampshire
International Speedway that killed Winston Cup driver Kenny Irwin
July 7, and Busch driver Adam Petty May 12.
</P>
<P>
   After Irwin's wreck, NASCAR mandated engine kill buttons on the
steering wheel, hoping drivers could manually shut off the engine
when needed, and throttle stops to prevent the metal piece that
opens to allow fuel out of the carburetor from sticking in that
position.
</P>
<P>
   Neither worked last week at Darlington, S.C., when Bobby
Labonte's throttle stuck during practice.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin, another Roush driver who is a strong proponent of
the brake sensor, said drivers don't have time to push a kill
button when the car is out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you that the driver can't be responsible for
shutting it off when it sticks wide open,'' Martin said, referring
to the engine.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Helton, NASCAR's chief operating officer, said the
sanctioning body had no objection to teams using the Roush sensor
on their cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may see some of them voluntarily used in some of the races
soon,'' Helton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't stop someone from putting it in the cars right
now,'' he said. ``What you have, though, is a new element that has
to be thought through. And a competitor generally doesn't want to
put something brand new in a race car in a points battle.''
</P>
<P>
   After his wreck at Darlington, Labonte said he might not have
walked away uninjured if the accident had happened at New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important ... that we make sure that we're as safe as we
can be and feel as safe as we can,'' Labonte said. ``I can honestly
say that if this would have happened at New Hampshire, I don't
believe it would have turned out as good, just the way the track is
configured.''
</P>
<P>
   While most drivers endorsed the brake sensor, Rusty Wallace had
some reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``For it to work, you have to apply a whole lot of pressure to
the brakes, you've got to lock up all four tires,'' Wallace said.
``You have to mash the brake so hard you might blow out a tire. I
don't know if I want that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, though, seems to represent the thinking of most drivers
who, at the very least, feel the Roush brake sensor can't hurt
anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a real answer to the stuck throttles,'' Martin said.
``It still doesn't mean you won't wreck, but at least you won't
have the rear wheels pushing you into the wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
