<P>
   CUBA-OLYMPICS HAVANA _ With the Sydney Olympics set to begin in
September, Cuba is gearing up for another bout of sports-mania. The
tiny island nation has produced staggering numbers of medal winners
in past Olympics, and the games provide a rallying point for a
people shackled by a struggling economy and tight government
controls. We visit local ballfields and playgrounds to get a
grass-roots view of just what the Olympics and athletics mean to
everyday Cubans. (Williams, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-UN _ NEW YORK _ President Clinton wrapped up three days
of intensive diplomacy here Friday amid an air of diminishing
expectations, as the weight of unfinished business began to settle
on the shoulders of a world leader who's era is about to close.
With four months left in office, Clinton used this week's Millenium
Summit at the United Nations to begin bidding farewell to the
community of global leaders he's engaged with and, in many cases,
befriended over the past eight years. At almost every turn, though,
there were signs that key pieces of the vast global agenda Clinton
has crafted and pursued aren't likely to fal into place before he
leaves office in January. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
