<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   SMITH-COLUMN _ My father's family leased land to sharecroppers _
ironic for a family that descended from chattel slaves to turn
other people into wage slaves. Sharecroppers worked the land, never
owning it and never getting out of debt. They made money for
someone else, but rarely knew what it was like to have money in
their pockets. Recalling those days when workers picked the cotton
on his daddy's land in Burleson County, my father said, ``It wasn't
fair.'' His words are a lesson for me about work, dignity and
fairness. Today, the custodians, clerks, librarians and others at
the University of Texas who keep the campus running receive few
benefits and low pay. That isn't fair, either, especially at one of
the largest universities in the nation. (Smith, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ I had stopped by the barbershop,
mainly to catch up on the news. Not that I didn't already know what
everybody's talking about. Everybody's talking about the weather.
(Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ T.S. Eliot wrote that April was the cruelest
month. He never visited Texas in August. One joke going around is
that the devil was thinking about moving hell to Texas but decided
it was too hot. (Borders, Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel)
MOVEDLATHAM-COLUMN _ MARSHALL, Texas _ You hear a great deal about
global warming these days. Some people say it threatens life on
Earth, others say it is nothing but a myth. Me, I don't know
anything about that either way. What I do know about is global
cooling. Now there is something that has really changed our lives
over the last 40 years. (Latham, Longview News Journal) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ Protection of minority views is essential to
our democracy. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
