percent of athletes in some Olympic sports use drugs and blames the
IOC for not doing enough to wipe out doping, The New York Times
reported today. (Fish, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   OLY-DRUG _ Edwin Moses, the hurdling icon, looks out on the
Olympic playing field with disgust, suspecting the drug problem in
sports hasn't changed a bit. All the clues are still there. Some
more so than ever. The sudden, drastic change in body shape. The
sculpted appearance. Out-of-this-world performances. Even the need
for braces at a ripe old age, which insiders link to skeletal
changes brought on by the use of drugs like human growth hormone
HGH. (Fish, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 35''
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   OLY-DRUGBAR _ At first glance, Olympic officials appear to have
taken strides to clean up the Sydney Games by wheeling out a test
to detect the use of the banned synthetic hormone erythropoietin
(EPO), considered the drug of choice for endurance athletes. But
some medical experts suggest it's just the latest ploy by the
International Olympic Committee to cleanse its image and some
athletes have moved on to a new drug, anyway. (Fish, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 15''
</P>
<P>
   OLY-COLD-BAND _ The Fayette County, Ga., High marching band
