<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE YEAR LATER, SEE YOU AT THE POLE HAS RENEWED MEANING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JIM JONES 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Some might expect members of Wedgwood
Baptist Church to cancel a See You at the Pole rally at their
church this year.
</P>
<P>
   After all, last year's rally at the Fort Worth church _ attended
by teens from many churches who had prayed at their schools'
flagpoles earlier in the day _ turned into a ghoulish catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   While 400 young people were singing and praising God last Sept.
15, a gunman carrying numerous rounds of ammunition walked into the
church _ and no one knows why he chose that church on that day.
</P>
<P>
   He first shot people who greeted him. Then he went into the
sanctuary and began firing. Some said he cursed Christianity. He
hurled a pipe bomb that exploded without hurting anyone at the
front of the church.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen people were wounded, seven of them fatally, before the
gunman, Larry Gene Ashbrook, for reasons unexplained, ended his
attack. He sat down in a back pew and shot himself to death.
</P>
<P>
   Despite last year's tragedy and lingering memories, church
leaders never considered calling off this year's event to culminate
the See You at the Pole observances at schools. The gathering is
scheduled for 6:30 p.m. Sept. 20 in the church sanctuary, and it
will be bigger than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not afraid,'' said Wedgwood youth minister Jay Fannin,
who led the 1999 rally. ``We believe God was in control last year,
and we believe he still is in control. We are going to trust God.''
</P>
<P>
   The same band that played last year _ Forty Days _ will perform
Sept. 20, even though some band members have memories of bullets
whizzing past them at last year's rally.
</P>
<P>
   Extra security will be in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police have been very cooperative, and we've told them about
the rally,'' Fannin said. ``Also, we have four or five police
officers who are members of our church.''
</P>
<P>
   See You at the Pole is a student-led, before-school prayer begun
in 1990 in nearby Burleson, Texas. Youths in all 50 states and more
than 20 countries on six continents participated in the prayer
event last year.
</P>
<P>
   See You at the Pole is more popular than ever, national
organizers say, thanks in part to the shootings at Wedgwood last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Fannin has received inquiries about Wedgwood's rally from youth
ministers of many churches. Some plan to bring their entire youth
groups to the Wedgwood rally, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our kids are very excited about coming,'' Fannin said. ``They
are anxious to get their friends here.''
</P>
<P>
   Many survivors of the shootings will also attend, but the focus
will be on the young people who will talk about prayer experiences
at their schools.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Noland, the See You at the Pole coordinator for
Discipleship Ministries in Burleson, said more people than ever are
calling and asking for T-shirts and other items his company
provides to promote the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really do believe the tragedy at Wedgwood has turned into a
positive impact for See You at the Pole,'' Noland said. ``It has
shown more evidence for the need for prayer in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the U.S. Supreme Court ruling outlawing public prayers
at football games has caused some confusion this year, Noland said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some principals call and say they cannot participate
because of the football prayer ruling,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the before-school prayers are legal if they are
student-initiated, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Americans United for Separation of Church and State, which
campaigns against prayer in public schools, also believes that See
You at the Pole is a legal activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law protects students who want to go to school early and
pray,'' said Steve Benen, an Americans United spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   As thousands of students around the nation gather around
flagpoles on Sept. 20 to pray for the country, many will also lift
up prayers for those young martyrs for the faith who were shot at
Wedgwood.
</P>
<P>
   And many of us far past school age with lingering memories of
that peaceful summer night that turned into a nightmare will join
in those same prayers.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
