<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6776 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CARS-COLLECTING-ART-N     09-08 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-COLLECTING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD CARS IN MAGAZINE'S PAGES ARE ALSO IN THE PARKING LOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT9 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CHARLES McEWEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BENNINGTON, Vt. _ Old cars are an integral part of the landscape
at Hemmings Motor News.
</P>
<P>
   Hemmings, a monthly magazine chock-full of advertisements for
collectible cars, parts and related services, also owns a
collection of 78 old cars and trucks, a handful of them quite rare.
Of these, about 45 are registered, insured and capable of being
used on public roads.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the pampered cars in many collections, the
Hemmings fleet is actually driven _ in parades, for movie shoots
and, each summer, by journalists who come here for a day of deja vu
on the roads around Hemmings offices in what was once a schoolhouse
west of town.
</P>
<P>
   The collection is the pride of Terry Ehrich, 59, the publisher
and editor in chief of Hemmings and a major shareholder in its
parent company, Watering Inc. He and his brother, Perez, the vice
president for business operations, publish Hemmings and two other
car-related magazines, Special Interest Autos and the new Hemmings
Rods &AMP; Performance, along with an almanac, a host of car calendars
and related books. The company is branching out into Internet and
television ventures.
</P>
<P>
   The circulation of Hemmings, which looks like an 800-page phone
book, is about 260,000 copies a month. Special Interest Autos,
published six times a year, has a circulation of about 30,000,
Terry Ehrich said, and some 50,000 copies of Rods &AMP; Performance,
just out with its second issue, are being distributed, many of them
at car shows.
</P>
<P>
   In building the collection over the last two decades, Ehrich
said he had sought two basic types of cars: ``icons'' and ``the
unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Icons, he said, are ``cars that people are going to drive by and
say, `My mom had a car just like that.''' So the collection has its
Mustang, a dark blue '66 convertible, and its Malibu, a red '69
convertible with a 396-cubic-inch V-8. The other category, ``the
unusual,'' also includes the ``small and cute.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most unusual car in the collection is a
teardrop-shaped two-door sedan, a 1934 McQuay-Norris. It is one of
two survivors of the six that were made and is the only one in
running condition, Ehrich said. Using Ford engines and drivetrains,
the cars were made as publicity vehicles for the McQuay-Norris
Manufacturing Co., an automotive parts maker. Hemmings shows it off
with the collection's most recent acquisition, a similarly shaped
aluminum camping trailer from the late 1940s, unrestored but in
reasonable condition.
</P>
<P>
   Fitting the ``small and cute'' bill are a 1938 American Bantam
roadster; a 1950 Crosley Gasporter, a tiny tanker built for use at
small airports; and two minicars, a 1960 BMW Isetta and a 1966 King
Midget.
</P>
<P>
   The collection has several purposes, including advertising and
public relations. ``The first use of these vehicles is
visibility,'' Ehrich said, ``here at home at the office and
especially at our filling station, on the road and at car shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the cars are displayed at an old-time filling station
that the company operates next to its headquarters in town. Several
cars and trucks are always on display at the station, and the two
service bays have become a sales floor for Hemmings publications,
model cars and clothing items. Out front, young attendants actually
pump gas, clean windshields and check the oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a leader in so many areas of this American life, Vermont
has outlawed billboards since sometime back in the '50s,'' Ehrich
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vehicles make good billboards.''
</P>
<P>
   They also send a message that cuts to the heart of what Hemmings
is all about _ preserving pieces of auto history. ``One of my
favorites, just in terms of putting our name out in a visible way,
is the 1934 Ford wrecker,'' Ehrich said. ``I just love to drive
that in a parade towing a slightly ratty Model A Ford.''
</P>
<P>
   Another purpose of the collection, Ehrich said, ``is to show
that Hemmings is an active participant in the hobby, not just a
publishing company making a living on the hobby.''
</P>
<P>
   The collection is cared for by two consultants to Hemmings,
Justus Taylor and Jim Howe. Taylor, a tall and trim 60, is a former
leather craftsman, cinematographer and motorcycle racer for BMW who
now flies a vintage sailplane. Howe, a young-looking 53, lives near
Bennington on 20 acres that he calls However Wild Farm. He once
worked in a machine shop in Bennington and for a while repaired and
restored Volkswagen Beetles for resale.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor is the collection's troubleshooter. He said: ``The thing
that I do best is to be able to analyze a problem _ `What is that
noise? Where is it coming from?' _ and to come up with a solution.
Then Jim and I get together, and the two of us equal three.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Howe's specialties is scouting prospective additions for
the collection. ``Quite a few people approach Hemmings about buying
their vehicles,'' he said. ``Selling it to Hemmings is sort of like
sending it to heaven. And if it's something that Terry decides he's
interested in, then I check it out. What I look for is what was it
like before it was restored. The first thing I do is slide under
the vehicle. I don't really care what the top looks like.''
</P>
<P>
   To make repairs, he often hunts for parts by telephone or
computer, as was the case with an ailing starter on a '58 Volvo 445
wagon. ``Today I learned that the starter's Bendix gear doesn't
exist in the U.S.,'' he said. ``So I've got to get on the Internet
and wade through some Swedish.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the public-relations and advertising functions.
``I also spend a fair amount of time helping Hemmings decide where
and when to use their vehicles,'' Howe said. That comes to some 50
to 75 events a year, he estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, when dealing with old cars and trucks, a little
detective work is called for, along with mechanical skills. ``One
night I got a call from the Hemmings filling station that the tow
truck wouldn't start,'' Howe said. ``I got them to describe the
problem, and it sounded to me like it was out of gas. They said,
`No, we filled it.'''
</P>
<P>
   When he got to the station, Howe checked the gas tank, which is
under the passenger seat, and it was empty. But again, the
attendants insisted that they had filled the tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Well, how much did it take?''' Howe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they said, `Oh, not much _ a couple of quarts.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And I said, `Show me where you put it.' Know where they had
put it? In the radiator.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1806EDT &QL; 
