<SLUG> BC-OLYMPIC-BUDGET-NYT- </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times will publish a 14-page Olympic preview
section on Monday, Sept. 11. Stories for that section will move
Friday thru Monday from The New York Times News Service, in the
``s'' file.:
</P>
<P>
   OLY-RUN-JONES (Undated) _ As Marion Jones tells the story, she
was an 8-year-old in Southern California when the Olympics first
entered her head like a song that would not leave. Her family drove
to see the Olympic torch as the relay made its way to the 1984
Summer Games in Los Angeles. Back at home that same night, she went
into her room and wrote on a chalkboard, ``I want to be an Olympic
champion.'' Sixteen years later, at the 2000 Summer Games in
Sydney, Australia, Jones is attempting to become the first woman to
win five gold medals in track and field at the same Olympics. By
Jere Longman. 3,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic on the components of the long jump is being
sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN (Sydney, Australia) &UR;  &LR; _ &UR;  &LR; This is an awesome
task for the athletes. They must save the Olympic movement. They
must also wrest the focus back from the sleaze merchants who
connived under the cover of the five rings. They must leap over
time zones, break down the artificiality of the taped television
broadcasts, get past the greed and the stuffiness of the
International Olympic Committee. The next weeks belong to the
athletes, now arriving in Australia from all over the world. By
George Vecsey. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SWM-THORPE (Sydney, Australia) &UR;  &LR; _ &UR;  &LR; In a country where
swimming is the most popular Olympic sport, where important meets
draw prime-time television exposure and exorbitant ratings, it is a
17-year-old named Ian Thorpe who has Australia entranced. The very
first evening of the Sydney Olympics, the whole of Australia will
be captivated by this 6-foot-5 inch, 210-pound teen-ager with size
17 feet, who will swim the 400-meter freestyle to win a gold medal,
and perhaps to lower his own world record of 3 minutes 41.33
seconds. The Thorpedo, as he is known, is also favored in the 200
freestyle _ his world record is 1:45.41 _ and he will swim for a
third gold in the 800-meter freestyle relay. By Jere Longman. 1,700
words.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OLY-GYM-KAROLYI (Undated) _ Normally, the effusive Bela Karolyi
rambles on in glorious hyperbole but in such a thick Transylvanian
accent, a toy decoder ring is required to untangle his words. But
after watching Shannon Miller's comeback end at the Olympic Trials
last month with an inglorious fall, and witnessing three other top
gymnasts take spills on the balance beam, Karolyi was short on
words in Boston. The finish to the trials in mid-August seemed to
unnerve Karolyi. Once the national team coordinator announced the
Olympic team _ which included two former members of the 1996 gold
medal team, Amy Chow and Dominique Dawes _ he quickly discussed the
difficult subjective selection process and exited the room. ``We
can contend for a medal,'' said Karolyi as he departed. ``We have
to work.'' By Selena Roberts. 900 words.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BKW-EDWARDS (Undated) _ At age 36, Teresa Edwards, the
veteran point guard of Team USA, is tired. But Edwards is also
unbent. ``At this point, I can ride the boat or drive it,'' she
said. ``It doesn't matter. I just want to win.'' By Mike Wise.
1,400 words.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OLY-RUN-FREEMAN (Sydney, Australia) _ Cathy Freeman, Australia's
most prominent athlete and most prominent Aborigine has been
running fast enough to win medals and generate headlines since she
was 11 and newspaper reporters in her hometown of Mackay dubbed her
``wonder girl.'' On the evening of Sept. 25, the date of the 400
final in Sydney, she will be _ barring injury _ the favorite: both
on paper and in the hearts and minds of the Australian fans whose
interest in and connection with Freeman made this the first session
of track and field to sell out. By Christopher Clarey. 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-TV-COLUMN (Undated) _ NBC will tape every minute of the
Sydney Games and package the best for a five-hour prime-time show.
All of NBC's morning and late-night coverage will be taped, as will
everything on CNBC and MSNBC. In essence, NBC will show you what it
believes you want to see. NBC even has minute-by-minute surveys
that prove what you want and that you surf away when you're shown
what you don't want. So if you don't like what you see at 10:45
p.m., you must not be in the majority or maybe nobody surveyed you.
By Richard Sandomir. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of television schedule for every day of Games
on NBC, MSNBC and CNBC is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
