<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BIZ-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD BUSINESS NEWS IN BRIEF  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   CONCESSIONS FOR MERGER
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the European Commission said Friday that America
Online Inc. and Time Warner Inc. have proposed concessions in their
attempt to overcome European antitrust objections to their merger.
``There have been undertakings,'' said Amelia Torres, a spokeswoman
for Mario Monti, Europe's commissioner in charge of competition
affairs. European officials refused to say what the proposed
concessions were or whether they would be sufficient, but industry
executives think AOL may have offered to strengthen its earlier
proposal to limit its ties to Bertelsmann AG, the German media
conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   INVESTING IN TURKEY
</P>
<P>
   Financial institutions from Greece, Turkey and the United States
have joined to form a private equity fund that will invest in
Turkey. Bosphorous Capital Partners was created by J.P. Morgan
Capital Corp., a subsidiary of J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co.; the National Bank
of Greece and Garaniti Securities, a leading Turkish securities
firm. The limited partnership will start with capital of $45
million, and it intends to raise an additional $55 million by fall
2001. The fund anticipates investing in small and medium-sized
businesses in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADIAN JOBLESS INCREASE
</P>
<P>
   Canada's unemployment rate jumped to 7.1 percent in August from
6.8 percent in July and 6.6 percent in June, a surprising trend
that has raised concerns about the strength of the economy. An
estimated 27,000 jobs were added in August, but more than three
times as many people joined the workforce. The influx of
job-seekers is a sign of confidence, economists said. But they
noted that the number of new jobs in August did not make up for the
31,000 lost in June and July _ and that last month's additions were
mostly part-time positions. The gain in full-time work during the
past six months has been 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ANGLO AMERICAN PROFIT IS UP
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by increased platinum prices and growing demand for
diamonds, Anglo American PLC, the world's biggest mining company,
said its first-half profit rose by 77 percent to $951 million. The
increase outstripped both analysts' forecasts and the performance
of British-base rivals Billiton PLC and Rio Tinto PLC. Analysts
attributed the demand for Anglo's mining products and for the
diamonds mined by De Beers, in which Anglo holds about one-third of
the stock to booming economic conditions in the United States.
Anglo shares rose three percent to 4,117 pence. The company is in
the throes of an overhaul, selling off non-core businesses while
expanding its mining and forest products divisions.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE BOND DOWNGRADE
</P>
<P>
   Moody's downgraded yen-denominated Japanese government bond to
Aa2 from Aa1. The rating agency cited the government's highest
ratio of debt as a percentage of gross domestic product among the
leading economies and uncertainty over Japan's economic recovery.
The rating announcement caused a sell-off of stocks and bonds for a
brief period, but they recovered.
</P>
</TEXT>
