 For Release SATURDAY AMs, September 9, 2000  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
budgeted graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or
 &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   UN-AFRICA (New York) _ It wasn't the plan, but perhaps the most
significant result of the UN summit was the platform it gave some
African leaders to tell the developed world's chiefs that Africa is
being exploited anew under the guise of globalization. Typical was
Gambia's president, who rages about the ``new slavery'' of
globalization _ another way, he says, that the North takes his
nation's raw materials at bargain prices and seeks to sway the
minds of his people. By John Donnelly. 1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-GENDER (Washington) _ An astonishing gender chasm has
opened between the presidential candidates, the greatest in memory.
Many forces are at play, especially on whether the stresses of the
modern family have added a new dynamic. By Mary Leonard. 1000
words.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BUSH (Westland, Pa.) _ The Republican nominee switches
gears to counter a spate of troubling poll numbers and growing
concern his campaign is a mess. By Anne E. Kornblut. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-GORE (New Orleans) _ What a week it's been for Al Gore
_ from his 27-hour campaign-a-thon to releasing his economic plan
to winding up in New Orleans outlining his plan to make college
tuition tax deductible and to increase college attendance and
graduation rates. By Glen Johnson. 1200 worsd.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-SECRETS (Boston) _ A federal judge strikes down
Massachusetts' first-in-the-nation law requiring tobacco companies
to reveal the ingredients in cigarettes and smokeless tobacco,
agreeing with the tobacco companies' arguments that to do so would
reveal trade secrets. By Shelley Murphy. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY-ROMNEY (Belmont, Mass.) _ Looking to bury the hatchet
after their bitter 1994 US Senate race, Mitt Romney hosts Ted
Kennedy on a tour of the new Mormon Temple in Belmont. By Brian
MacQuarrie. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TKT-AMGEN (Boston) _ Lawyers for Transkaryotic Therapies and
Amgen present closing arguments in US District Court in their
closely watched lawsuit over Amgen's patents for its popular
anemia-fighting drug, Epogen. By Ronald Rosenberg. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBC-NEB-ND (South Bend, Ind.) _ Yes, no question about it.
Today's meeting between No. 1 Nebraska and Notre Dame is a marquee
game in a weekend that has a few of them. By Mark Blaudschun. 700
words.
</P>
<P>
   MCDONOUGH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Jimy Williams will be the manager
of the Red Sox next year, if he chooses to be. By Will McDonough.
1800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
