<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6802 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP-HNS &LR;      09-08 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GOP LAUNCHES TV ATTACK ON GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Republican Party rallied to help GOP nominee George W. Bush
on Friday with a blistering televised attack on Democrat Al Gore
that said the vice president cannot be trusted to strengthen public
schools because of his role in the Clinton-Gore fund raising
scandal in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Republican chairman Jim Nicholson said the GOP advertisement _
to be broadcast in Pennsylvania and Michigan _ cites Gore's role in
a fund-raising scheme that led to the indictment of 22 people and
Gore's new emphasis on campaign finance reform. The combination is
evidence that the vice president can't be trusted when he talks
about education, according to Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   ``For eight years now, Al Gore has shown that he's a man whose
words must be questioned _ no matter what the topic is,'' Nicholson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The narrator of the 30-second spot says: ``Now Al Gore's
promising more accountability in our schools. And that sounds good.
Until you find out he doesn't require any testing. And no testing
means no accountability. Just more politics from Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign spokesman Doug Hattaway said the GOP ad on behalf
of Bush was a ``desperate'' personal attack that showed that when
Bush has his back ``against the wall, he'll do anything to get
elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and Gore have offered plans to strengthen
locally-supervised public education with federal assistance and use
testing to hold local authorities' accountable for students'
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Hattaway challenged GOP efforts to raise questions about Gore's
fund-raising activities, insisting that the vice president had
``never been found to have done anything illegal'' during $50
million worth of taxpayer-financed investigations into the
Clinton-Gore fund-raising effort in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who now trails Gore in the latest national surveys, had
vetoed an earlier GOP ad that challenged Gore's ethics. The latest
ad is similar to another ad raising questions about Gore's
credibility; that ad is being broadcast in seven other states.
</P>
<P>
   The new GOP campaign ad hit the television airwaves as Bush
overhauled campaign tactics to allow greater direct contact with
voters in line with a new slogan, ``real plans for real people.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the prospects for Gore-Bush debates appeared brighter
after representatives of the two candidates announced plans to meet
with the unofficial Commission on Presidential Debates to work out
details for debates. The commission has proposed three presidential
debates in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``We turn on a dime,'' Bush boasted, adding that meeting with
voters was ``what I'm good at ... I like interfacing with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spent more than an hour politicking face-to-face with
Marconi Communications workers at a factory cafeteria in
Warrendale, Pa. ``When you get in that (voting) booth, remember who
came by,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, flanked by several dozen motorcycle police officers who
had escorted his motorcade, thanked the 290,000-member Fraternal
Order of Police for endorsing his White House bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll have a friend in the White House,'' Bush said of an
organization that backed Clinton-Gore re-election in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the incumbent vice president, continued his efforts to
seize the role as the candidate of change. The 24-year veteran of
Washington told students at Delgado Community College in New
Orleans that his proposed 10-year, $36 billion tax break for
college tuition showed ``the right set of priorities'' to enable 75
percent of America's high school graduates to pursue higher
education.
</P>
<P>
   Gore left it to Democratic vice presidential candidate Joe
Lieberman to go after Bush with some of the harshest criticism of
the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, a 12-year veteran of the Senate, accused the two-term
governor of Texas of leaving 1.2 million children without health
insurance and fighting state legislation that would have extended
health coverage to 220,000 children last year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush ``may say that he has a plan to improve children's health
across America,'' Lieberman said, adding: ``Why hasn't he done it
in Texas?''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said a Gore-Lieberman administration would fight to
guarantee access to health care coverage to all children by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett said Lieberman was ``distorting and
misrepresenting'' Bush's record as the state's two-term governor,
adding: Lieberman had become ``the attack dog surrogate for Al
Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett said that Bush had expanded health care coverage for
children in Texas at a time when the Clinton-Gore administration
had allowed 2.4 million more children to join the ranks of the
uninsured since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   GOP vice presidential candidate Dick Cheney, campaigning in New
England in a bid to raise questions about the Gore-Lieberman team
in and around Lieberman's native Connecticut, got sidetracked into
answering questions about failing to vote in 14 of the 16 elections
that took place in Texas since he registered to vote in Dallas in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Among the elections that Cheney missed was the Texas
presidential primary in March in which he could have voted for
Bush, his future running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, a former defense secretary and 10-year member of
Congress from Wyoming, said that extensive business travel as chief
executive of the oil services firm Halliburton Corp., had prevented
him from voting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I traveled a great deal,'' Cheney explained. ``Dallas was my
base. That's where I lived or was headquartered, but I was not
involved in community affairs very extensively in Dallas. My focus
was on global concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic party spokeswoman Jennifer Backus seized upon the
revelation of Cheney's voting record that first appeared in the
Dallas Morning News to wonder: ``If Cheney didn't vote for Bush,
why should the rest of America?''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The GOP ad joins two other television commercials being aired in
Florida, Iowa, Kentucky, Maine, New Mexico, Oregon and West
Virginia that cite Gore's fund raising at a Buddhist temple in
California in 1996 and his claim that he had created the Internet
to question his credibility.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wire service reports contributed.
</P>
