<HEADER>
A6807 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-LA-CARAVELLE-$ADV10-N     09-08 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-CARAVELLE-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT DOESN'T LOOK A DAY OVER 30 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 10)  
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When I invited friends to dinner recently at La
Caravelle, one asked plaintively: Was she allowed to wear pants?
</P>
<P>
   I laughed, until I spent a morning with the scrapbooks the
restaurant's original owners, Robert L. Meyzen and Fred Decre, had
kept since its debut on Sept. 21, 1960. I realized then that my
friend has a long memory. An article in The New York Times dated
Oct. 7, 1968, titled ``Even the Restaurateurs Concede That Pants
Are Fashionable,'' read in part: ``Robert Meyzen of La Caravelle,
who has long frowned on pants `because very few women wear them
handsomely,' said with resignation: ``This is going to be the
fashion this winter. You can't avoid it. If the woman is young,
elegant and well-groomed, personally, I don't feel there's anything
wrong with it.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later Meyzen officially surrendered on the issue of
pants, telling The Times, ``At first we didn't allow them, but we
are here to serve food, not to buck the trend of fashion.'' Though
he added sternly, ``We don't allow turtlenecks.''
</P>
<P>
   That contretemps was second only to another revolutionary
moment, in 1963, when The New York Journal-American published an
article called ``Missing Millinery,'' which recorded sightings of
Pauline Trigere and Elizabeth Arden daring to go hatless at
Pavillon, while at La Caravelle, ``the same hatlessness prevailed''
among editors from Harper's Bazaar and Vogue. Mon Dieu!
</P>
<P>
   La Caravelle, which opened with a $5.50 prix fixe lunch and
$7.50 dinner, celebrates its 40th anniversary this month. A New
York institution, it has stood as a marker of a bygone era of
glamour. But rather than settling into dinosaur status, it has
actually hung around long enough to be back in style again. While
the older crowd continues its patronage (Brooke Astor, Geoffrey
Beene and Oscar de la Renta among them), the next generations are
booking tables, too. In a fashion season smitten with the trappings
of uptown chic, the younger set is seeing La Caravelle not as stiff
but as Old World charming. They are happy to dress up and play
Paris for an evening out.
</P>
<P>
   Or an afternoon. Last week at lunch, I watched Alexandra Lind, a
30-year-old fashion designer whose cocktail dresses sell at Searle
and whose bridal gowns sell at Bergdorf Goodman's, with three other
women, bringing the median age in the room down by half. Honoring
the tradition of the fashionable women who have always frequented
La Caravelle _ Babe Paley and the Duchess of Windsor among them _
they were dressed to the teeth, complete with the new bowling-ball
bags, barely in stores yet. It was the first time Lind had been
back since she was 15. ``I was pleasantly surprised,'' she said.
``It was a really warm atmosphere and felt very youthful, not
overly formal at all. I liked the intimacy of it. You can really
talk to people. And hear them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rita Jammet, who with her husband, Andre, became owners of La
Caravelle in 1988, says they have attracted younger diners by
steering away from stuffiness with an attitude they call ``friendly
formality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were out of favor at some point, but the pendulum swings
again and the next generation is attracted to us,'' Jammet
(pronounced jah-MAY) said. ``We are trying to bring back the idea
of hospitality, not give the feeling, `Are you good enough to come
in here?'''
</P>
<P>
   Though the phrase friendly formality sounds lifted from a
marketing textbook, I did see it in practice at two meals last
week. Women were stylishly dressed (even in pants), with the
exception of one who dashed in at lunch wearing khakis and a black
tank top, took one look around her and seemed sorry she did.
Jackets are required for men, though ties are optional, and also
required is a decorum that disqualifies the packs of marauding
traders who seem to frequent steakhouses _ at least every time I'm
eating at one. As Jammet put it, ``We try to maintain a civility
here. Yes, it's wonderful to be young and social and up-and-coming,
but you still have to maintain a certain gentleness with
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Friday night of Labor Day weekend, the restaurant was
surprisingly full, with a wine-tasting dinner under way in a
private room. The few cell phone users didn't shout; a man
escorting a Catherine Zeta-Jones look-alike looked askance at
something on his plate, and it was immediately whisked away; and if
I ever raised my glance, a waiter was instantly at my side. I admit
it. I liked being taken care of. My oysters came accompanied by
small pieces of bread that had already been buttered. I started to
feel my shoulders come down from around my ears and settle back
where they belong.
</P>
<P>
   That the restaurant looks good helps. It is lauded for its
pastoral murals, painted by Jean Pages, a student of Raoul Dufy;
the Jammets replaced the original red velvet banquettes with peach,
to highlight them further. This ensures that what Holiday magazine
wrote in 1964 still holds: La Caravelle ``is so flatteringly lit
that it turns aunts into nieces and sugar daddies into gigolos.''
Certainly, by the time our dinner ended, we felt as if we had been
on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that feeling comes from the sense of time travel. The
Jammets have divided the menu between classic (quenelles, Dover
sole) and contemporary (tuna carpaccio), and it's a flashback to
childhood (the good parts) watching someone carving a roast duck
tableside.
</P>
<P>
   The other lift is dining surrounded by history. For starters,
the bar, tucked away in the back, heralds the room's early days as
a speak-easy. Then there are the ghosts of diners past. For its
inaugural year alone, the restaurant's reservation book included
Ambassador Joseph Kennedy, Cecil Beaton, Mainbocher, Otto Preminger
and Harry Winston. When President Kennedy was elected, the White
House chef, Rene Verdon, was selected and trained by La Caravelle's
chef, Roger Fessaguet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But there were bad times, too. The recession of the early 1970s
hurt the restaurant, as did the switch in Broadway curtain times
from 8:30 to 8:00, cutting into the traditional dinner hour. By
1978, Mimi Sheraton demoted La Caravelle to two stars in The New
York Times, down from Craig Claiborne's four.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a period before Andre and Rita took over where you
didn't know if the restaurant would survive,'' said Tim Zagat,
publisher of the Zagat Surveys. ``Our survey has measured that the
demographic is younger than it used to be and the restaurant is
definitely more popular.'' (The chef, Cyril Renaud earned three
stars from The Times in 1998. He left in April; his sous-chef, Eric
Di Domenico, who trained at Taillevent, has taken over.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the food is still wonderful, customers, young and old,
rave about the Jammets' particular brand of hospitality. His father
founded the Bristol Hotel in Paris, and he worked here as an
assistant manager at the Regency; Jammet was at the French Embassy.
They bought La Caravelle just as a recession hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk about our bubble bursting,'' Jammet said. They hired a
public relations firm that mandated modernization, designing a
(short-lived) corporate-looking logo. ``It took away all the
charm,'' Jammet said. The changes they did make included hiring the
Japanese chef Tadashi Ono. ``Even though he had French training,
that was considered revolutionary,'' Jammet said. He is now at Sono
on East 57th Street, which the Jammets own with Larry Goldenberg of
Gramercy Tavern.
</P>
<P>
   So, they know what modern is. But when it comes to La Caravelle,
they still will go only so far in forsaking anything that might be
considered old-fashioned. ``If we decide tomorrow to be hip and
downtown,'' Jammet said, ``the new people wouldn't know us. And the
older ones wouldn't want to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1815EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
