<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6819 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-CASTAWAYS-REVIEW-L     09-08 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CASTAWAYS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW MEET THE REAL SURVIVORS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use on or after Mon., Sept. 11, 2000, by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With all due respect to Rudy Boesch, Sue Hawk and the other
``Survivors,'' you guys are wimps. ``Castaway 2000,'' an ongoing
series from the British Broadcasting Corp. debuting today on BBC
America, plunked 36 men, women and children on a remote, gorgeous
island off the coast of Scotland that, due to its severe
conditions, has been deserted since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   These intrepid souls (or crazies, depending on your point of
view) are spending a full year on Taransay. No one gets voted off.
Jeff Probst and his tiki torches are a hemisphere away (thank
heaven!). And, most shocking of all, !ital!no one's doing it for a
big cash prize or, to look at all but one of them, a potential
media career when it's over.
</P>
<P>
   Were it on a network, ``Castaway 2000'' would become as big a
sensation as ``Survivor.'' Even on BBC America, it has a chance of
winning more converts than ``Big Brother.'' These first four
episodes being unveiled this week scarcely make it to the official
beginning of the great experiment, and yet each of them has more
conflict and intrigue than ``Big Brother'' looks to muster in its
entire run. Think Leonardo Di Caprio's vehicle ``The Beach,'' only
with bad teeth and worse weather.
</P>
<P>
   This first week of episodes seems, in a way, more a tease than
actual programming, especially since there's very little material
based on the island, but the material still manages to impress.
We're shown the grueling, ``Survivor''-style auditions of some 50
or so finalists (out of more than 4,000 applicants) to pare the
cast down to a small society, filled with leaders and followers,
nice guys and arrogant jerks, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the claims aren't too earth-shattering: The castaways
will get very depressed, stressed and put out with one another,
we're told. (And that's different from regular real life in
!ital!what way?) But at least the sundry experts on hand here _ a
psychologist and a survival trainer named (no joke!) Lofty Wiseman
(he looks like the sort of guy sea chanteys are written about _
again, no joke) _ offer fairly honest and unflattering assessments
of those trying out, not the sort of timid, meaningless drivel that
Dr. Drew and that freaky Internet lady routinely disgorge on ``Big
Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the first three episodes is given over to the
competitions used to weed out the weaklings or the simply
unpalatable applicants _ obstacle courses, animal wrangling (and
neck-wringing), hut-building _ and the incessant bickering that
results when the alpha males throw their weight around.
</P>
<P>
   Here we see folks shoveling a mountain of excrement (no, not
``Big Brother'' episodes on tape) simply to see if they can stomach
it _ the rationale given is that the island's septic system is
likely to be faulty. Applicants are asked if they're squeamish
about killing animals. One seems to have bloodlust in his eyes;
another replies, ``Is that after I've had sex with it?''
</P>
<P>
   CBS this isn't.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth episode offers different sorts of tensions, as
castaways gripe about their contracts, the deadline to complete
some of the living quarters on the island is blown and a few crates
of the participants' belongings are accidentally destroyed,
inspiring rebellion (including from the island's lone doctor)
before the show's premise even kicks off.
</P>
<P>
   But as opposed to ``Big Brother,'' whose decision-makers seem
shockingly resolute to keep anything of interest off the air _ for
one thing, those airplane banners tormenting houseguests, or the
participants' near mass-walkout after being forced to perform a
``roast'' _ ``Castaway'' almost relishes airing its dirty laundry,
and in wicked winds that reach up to 140 miles per hour on the
island.
</P>
<P>
   Already, a heartthrob has been born: Ben Fogle (who now receives
sacks full of fan mail while still residing on the island), a hunky
photo editor who is that rarity _ a sensitive yet heroic leader
with a kind sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   More favorites are sure to follow. Like other ``reality'' shows,
``Castaway 2000'' has a kitschy feel to it at times, and some of
the TV producers' bad luck streak has a ``Big Brother'' vibe to it.
But given the stakes _ many in England don't expect these survivors
to endure the entire stretch, even without goofy tribal banishment
ceremonies _ it'll be a microcosm of society worth keeping an eye
on. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``Castaway 2000.'' &QL; 
What: Reality series about 36 men, women and children set on a
deserted island. &QL; 
Where: BBC America. &QL; 
When: 5 and 6 p.m. tonight; 5 p.m. Tuesday through Thursday; 10
a.m. to 8 p.m. and 10 p.m. to 2 a.m. Saturday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1818EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
