<HEADER>
A6823 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      09-08 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Saturday, Sept. 9 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-CLINTON (United Nations) _ President Clinton on Friday
urged China's president, Jiang Zemin, to open a dialogue with the
new government of Taiwan and put a stop to its missile exports to
Pakistan, but received little from Jiang except for cordial good
wishes for his retirement in four months time and congratulations
for helping usher China into the World Trade Organization. By David
E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CUBA-CASTRO (New York) _ Fidel Castro, in New York for the
summit meeting, speaks at the Riverside Church on Friday night. By
Chris Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-SUPPORT (Washington) _ Less than a month after he faced
open criticism among many core Democrats about his centrist message
and running mate, Vice President Al Gore has moved swiftly to
consolidate his support among progressive Democrats and energize
once disaffected party activists, political analysts and Democratic
officials say. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   VOTER-DATABASE (San Francisco) _ At the end of an alley on a
nondescript street, a political consulting firm with the unusual
name of Aristotle International has compiled the nation's largest
voter data-bank _ the names of 150 million Americans who registered
to vote. And it is selling them to politicians like George W. Bush,
Joe Lieberman and John McCain. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   EU-AUSTRIA (Paris) _ A panel of experts assessing the status of
democracy and human rights in Austria has recommended that the
sanctions imposed last year because members of a far right party
had been included in the ruling government should be lifted. The
experts, appointed by the European Union, gave high marks to the
new government, concluding that minorities, refugees and immigrants
enjoyed the same if not greater legal rights and protections in
Austria as in the other countries in the Union. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BRICK-ATTACK (New York) _ A look at the lives of the five
teenagers ages 14 to 17, each from relatively stable middle-class
families, none with a criminal record, charged with bludgeoning a
Chinese restaurant owner to death with a brick during a bungled
ambush to steal their $60 order of food. By David Barstow and Sarah
Kershaw.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
