<HEADER>
A6824 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-CORREIA-PREVIEW-LADN &LR;      09-08 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORREIA-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT JUST ONE OF THE GIRLS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By SANDRA BARRERA 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amy Correia got a thumbs-up as one-fourth of the Girls Room
tour.
</P>
<P>
   A full U.S. tour, the free show was a way to introduce
up-and-coming artists such as Correia.
</P>
<P>
   Now the singer with the bittersweet voice and well-spun tunes to
match is setting out on her own with a tour in support of her debut
album, ``Carnival Love,'' set for release Sept. 26 on Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every song on the record reads like a brief moment taken
from Correia's experience as a small town girl living in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   Born in a small town in southeastern Massachusetts, Correia
dreamed of living in New York like her cousins who came to visit
every summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started talking to me like, `God doesn't exist,' '' she
says. ``And I think they really sparked my interest in seeing what
was outside of my town.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from high school, Correia left for college in
New York City. But a back injury a couple of years later got her
sent home.
</P>
<P>
   Bedridden for two months, she used the time to write songs on a
guitar she bought her last year in high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used a how-to-play-guitar book to remind myself how these
chords went and to learn things like `Leaving on a Jet Plane,' ''
she says with a laugh. ``You know, all the big hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Correia is making her own hits.
</P>
<P>
   And she does it with a voice reminiscent of Rickie Lee Jones,
although she says she stumbled upon her sound by mimicking a number
of voices.
</P>
<P>
   Correia learned to sing by listening to records by singers such
as Ray Charles, Billie Holiday and Mick Jagger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny because I don't think I write songs like the
Stones, but I love the Stones,'' she says. ``I love the Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   And because she loved singing, Correia began writing songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think going to college, I didn't realize how it was going to
come in handy,'' Correia says. ``I didn't know until I was halfway
through it that I was going to do music and songwriting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing they teach you in a writing class is, you're
not supposed to tell, you're supposed to show something,'' she
says. ``And I think my songs do that, for the most part.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``Chinatown,'' Correia's girlish voice sings about how all
there is to do is ``... watch the vegetables rot, the monkfish
flop.'' She goes ``sailing through the (New York) street on a sea
of faces'' in ``Life Is Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Correia even zooms across the city on ``The Bike'' left to her
by her late great-uncle Pat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally I'm not that biographical,'' she says. ``I really go
out of my way to change details because I don't want to get in
trouble or hurt anybody's feelings or get sued. But with that song,
I just couldn't resist.''
</P>
<P>
   Correia brings these and other songs from her album to Luna
Park. She will be playing with Gerri Sutyak, a cellist who
accompanied Correia on the Girls Room tour. (Eventually she plans
to add a full band.)
</P>
<P>
   ``For now it's kind of nice because it's pretty raw, but there's
a sophistication about it, too,'' she says. ``Gerri really lends
the sophistication. I have to play the rawness. But it seems to be
going over pretty well.'' &QL; 
---The show: ``Amy Correia.'' &QL; 
Where: Luna Park, 665 N. Robertson Blvd., West Hollywood. &QL; 
When: 9:45 p.m. Tuesday and 9:45 p.m. Sept. 19. &QL; 
Tickets: All shows are free, but there is a two-drink minimum. Call
(310) 652-0611 for more information. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
