<SLUG> BC-OLY-BAD-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: BADMINTON  
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Monday, Sept. 11.) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
  Major in Asia, minor throughout most of Europe and virtually
invisible in the United States, badminton is a fast-twitch indoor
feast of lunging gets and leaping smashes that bears only a vague
resemblance to the diletante's diversion.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE SETUP
</P>
<P>
   The game was developed in England in the 1860s by daughters of
the Duke of Beaufort at his country seat, Badminton House, whence
it spread to the colonies, but it took well over a century for the
quickest of all racket sports to reach the Olympics in 1992.
Competition is single-elimination and held in men's and women's
singles, men's and women's doubles and, unlike in Olympic tennis,
mixed doubles, too. Avoid calling the fine, feathered object
hissing through the air a birdie. It is a shuttlecock. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE SCORING
</P>
<P>
   Two of three games in all events. In men's singles and all
doubles events, games are played to 15 points. In women's singles,
games are played to 11. In all cases, points can be scored only
while serving. It gets tricky in the tiebreakers. If the score is
13-13 in a game (9-9 in women's singles), the player who reached
that total first can choose to extend the game by calling ``five,''
which means the first one to 18 or 14 wins. If the score is 14-14
(10-10 for those women's singles iconoclasts), the one who got
there first can extend the game by calling ``three,'' which means
exactly what you think it means.
</P>
<P>
   THE STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   Shuttlers spend much of their time airborne in order to improve
their hitting angles and generate leverage, but what makes
badminton intriguing and an aesthetic delight are the rapid rhythm
shifts: explosive smash and then silken drop shot.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE NAMES
</P>
<P>
   The badminton strongholds are Indonesia, Malaysia, China, South
Korea and Denmark, which has produced the only two non-Asian
Olympic medalists. Denmark's Peter Gade Christensen is a slight
favorite in the men's singles in Sydney, but his countrywoman
Camilla Martin should have a harder time with the Chinese women,
led by Gong Zichao. Indonesia's Candra Wijaya and Tony Gunawan are
an exceptional men's doubles team, while China's Gu Jun and Ge Fei
are likely to defend their Olympic title in women's doubles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6851 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-PRISONER-445&AMP;A     09-08 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-PRISONER-445&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT AGREES TO RULE ON ISSUE OF PRIOR CONVICTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an early first act to its new term that begins
next month, the Supreme Court agreed Friday to resolve a growing
dispute over federal court review of state criminal convictions.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether federal prisoners can seek federal court
review when the prior convictions are the reason the prisoner has
been sentenced to extra time as a repeat offender.
</P>
<P>
   Although the question seems technical and arcane, it has grown
in importance as federal sentencing has increasingly taken into
account an offender's criminal past. There has been a recent spate
of divergent federal appeals court rulings on whether the validity
of earlier state court convictions can be challenged in federal
court once the enhanced federal sentence has been imposed.
</P>
<P>
   Appeals from two of those opposite rulings were awaiting Supreme
Court action, and the Justice Department told the justices that a
prompt resolution was ``important to the stability of federal
sentences.''
</P>
<P>
   The court on Friday accepted an appeal by a California man who
was convicted of violating a federal law that makes it a crime for
a felon to possess a gun. He was then sentenced under a separate
federal statute, the Armed Career Criminal Act, which imposes a
minimum 15-year sentence for the gun violation on anyone who has
three previous, serious felony convictions. The effect was a
doubling of the sentence for the defendant, Earthy D. Daniels Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels had four previous convictions in the California courts
that met the definition. After his federal sentencing, he filed a
motion in federal court to vacate his sentence on the ground that
two of the earlier convictions, both for robbery, were
constitutionally invalid because of improperly obtained guilty
pleas and inadequate legal advice. He made his motion under a
federal law, Section 2255, which authorizes federal inmates to seek
correction of erroneous sentences.
</P>
<P>
   The federal district court in Los Angeles denied the motion, as
did the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in San Francisco. Both
acted on the basis of their interpretation of a 1994 Supreme Court
decision, Custis v. United States, which held that federal
defendants could not challenge the validity of prior state
convictions at their federal sentencing hearing. The 9th Circuit
went further and held that challenges also could not be brought
after the sentence was final.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Custis decision was limited to the sentencing
proceeding, or acted as a complete bar to later review of state
court convictions, is the issue that has divided the federal
circuits, because the Supreme Court in the 1994 case did not
address the further issue.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Almost simultaneously with the 9th Circuit's decision in
Daniels' case, Daniels v. United States, No. 99-9136, the 5th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals, in New Orleans, read the earlier decision
differently to permit a challenge under Section 2255 of a federal
inmate's three 10-year-old drug convictions. The Justice Department
has appealed that ruling, United States v. Clark, No. 00-122.
</P>
<P>
   The court gave no indication on Friday of why it acted before
its usual starting date to add the Daniels case.
</P>
<P>
   There had been some speculation that the justices might act
Friday in the Microsoft antitrust case, in which the court must
decide whether to hear the company's appeal or let the case be
heard first by the federal appeals court here. But there was no
word Friday. Since all the initial briefs in the appeal have been
filed, the case is ready for the justices' action. The next
possible date for an order in the Microsoft case is Sept. 26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1831EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6853 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUTCARS-VW-4MOTION-     09-08 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUTCARS-VW-4MOTION-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SAME MEAL, WITH BIGGER PORTIONS, FOR LESS MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, September 10)  
 By BOB KNOLL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By now, the auto-buying public largely understands that few
makes and models are unique, but that they are assemblages of parts
shared with other products from the same manufacturer. What may be
surprising is the extent to which different cars use the same
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the car-designing process as a giant buffet. In
planning its LeSabre, Buick filled its plate with various General
Motors components, ultimately ending up with the same platform,
engine, transmission and brakes that Pontiac scooped up for its
Bonneville. The garnishes and side dishes were different, and the
LeSabre got some extra whipped topping for dessert, but the meals
were much the same.
</P>
<P>
   The platform _ the basic architecture of a car's unit-body
construction _ is the crucial ingredient. If an automaker has an
exceptional platform, it can mix and match components to create a
variety of cars that look different, have distinct images and
appeal to different buyers. This approach runs counter to
cookie-cutter lineups like Chrysler's K-cars, which looked and
performed much the same regardless of size or price.
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen and Audi, both part of Volkswagen AG, have often
shared platforms successfully, enabling them to share the huge
costs of developing designs. When VW needed an attention-getter, it
looked no further than the platform of its Golf and Jetta. It added
a new body with a characteristic shape, and the New Beetle was
born. When Audi wanted to make a statement with a high-style sporty
car, the same platform was waiting. The TT coupe was born, followed
by a TT roadster.
</P>
<P>
   For 1996, Audi introduced the very successful A4 compact sedan.
As with other Audis, it had an engine mounted longitudinally _ that
is, from front to back, not from side to side as it is in the VW
Golf and Jetta _ and was available with Audi's highly regarded
quattro all-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the VW Passat, which had been imported since 1990,
languished. Then in 1998, it was completely redesigned on a
slightly stretched version of the Audi A4 platform. The midsize VW
ended up with a wheelbase almost as long as the one on Audi's
upscale A6. This Passat cost less than the A4 but had slightly more
room inside and a better ride, too. Sales took off.
</P>
<P>
   Audi's big remaining edge was the fact that it could be ordered
with quattro all-wheel drive, a reassuring feature in bad-weather
driving. But now VW has leveled the field with the addition this
year of the Passat 4motion, its version of quattro.
</P>
<P>
   The 4motion system is a $1,650 option on GLS and GLX sedans and
wagons, but only in combination with a 2.8-liter V-6 engine _ the
same one used in Audis _ and an automatic transmission. Thus,
Volkswagen has upped the ante by offering Audi's main attractions
at VW prices. Some fraternal cannibalism seems unavoidable, with VW
taking a bite of Audi's market.
</P>
<P>
   I have just finished driving one of the most sought-after
Passats, the top-line GLX 4motion wagon. Although the A4 and Passat
wagons look similar and share engines, transmissions and
accessories, there are differences. One is that the Passat's longer
wheelbase adds almost 2 inches of rear-seat legroom to the wagon
and sedan, and several inches to the wagon's cargo area. VW's own
figures show the Passat wagon has 36 cubic feet behind the second
seat, compared with the A4's 31.3 cubic feet. With the rear seats
down, the VW has 74 cubic feet versus the Audi's 63.7. Among
all-wheel-drive station wagons, the Passat's cargo volume is
greater than all but the Mercedes E320 wagon, even beating the new
Volvo V70.
</P>
<P>
   Another difference is price. The GLX wagon that I tested has a
list price of $31,705, including the destination, or delivery,
charge. Its only options were 4motion and the required automatic
transmission. An Audi A4 quattro 2.8 wagon, with the same engine
and similar equipment, is $34,420, a difference of $2,715.
Comparably equipped, a four-cylinder version of the Audi A4, the
1.8 Turbo, is $29,980 with quattro and automatic transmission. But
a Passat GLS 4motion is even less, starting at about $28,000, and
comes with a V-6.
</P>
<P>
   With the introduction of the 4motion system, the Passat has made
a giant step toward parity with the A4. In today's market, customer
preference seems to be for some sort of a sport utility, but not
one that's too trucklike, and an all-wheel or four-wheel-drive
system that is not cumbersome or awkward to use. Subaru has had
great success with its all-wheel-drive sedans and wagons, and
others are following. But Audi's quattro remains the gold standard
of road-going all-wheel-drive systems.
</P>
<P>
   The specifications make it clear that 4motion and quattro are
one and the same. Both are designed to work with a longitudinal
engine. Both have an automatic-locking center differential that
distributes engine torque to the front and rear axles in a 50/50
split so that all four wheels equally divide the torque. Under
conditions when slippage occurs with either a front or a rear
wheel, the differential can send up to two-thirds of the torque to
the wheels that have the best grip. Both have an electronic locking
differential in front and rear axles that limit how much each wheel
can spin, sending more torque to a wheel on the other side that has
traction.
</P>
<P>
   The quattro and 4motion systems operate seamlessly and
transparently. Other manufacturers claim seamless operation, but in
my experience only Subaru's system is equivalent to Audi's, and now
VW's. Most others operate either the front or rear wheels all the
time unless a loss of traction occurs, at which time the center
differential diverts power to the wheels with traction.
Unfortunately, this diversion of torque is often noticeable and
sometimes annoying.
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage of the VW-Audi systems is that with the
combination of a locking center differential and torque-splitting
axle differentials, an Audi or VW can drive away even if only one
wheel has traction. Many four-wheel-drive systems do not have this
capability; in some, the vehicle cannot move if only one wheel
lacks traction.
</P>
<P>
   Will this updated Passat take sales from the Audi A4?
</P>
<P>
   That seems likely. There remain only a few reasons to choose the
Audi: Its name is more prestigious; its styling may be more
appealing to some, and it comes with a warranty and free service
for 3 years or 50,000 miles, compared with 2 years or 24,000 miles
for VW.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
