<HEADLINE>
SPORTS CAPSULE: TAE KWON DO 
(FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
  This sport originated as a self-defense art in Korea, where its
name means ``the way of kicking and punching.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike the non-Olympic sport of karate, which involves the hands
80 percent of the time, tae kwon do is 80 percent feet. This is its
first appearance as an Olympic medal sport after demonstration
status in 1988 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
   THE SETUP
</P>
<P>
   The 100 athletes from 48 nations will compete in four weight
classes for men and four for women (normally in world
championships, there are eight classes for each). A loss before the
finals eliminates chances for a gold or silver, but anyone who
loses to a finalist returns in a repechage, or second chance,
tournament for a bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCORING
</P>
<P>
   Each match can last three rounds of three minutes each and ends
in a knockout or decision. Points are scored with a kick or a punch
to the colored portion of a padded chest protector or a kick to the
helmet. Three judges score the match electronically. If the judges
tie, the referee decides the winner.
</P>
<P>
   THE STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   As in chess matches, many competitors think defense first and
pick moments to try to score. As a result, scores are often low,
like 2-1 or 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   THE NAMES
</P>
<P>
   The only countries to qualify the maximum of two men and two
women are Korea, Chinese Taipei, the United States, the
Philippines, Spain and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest favorite is Victor Estrada Garibay of Mexico in
men's welterweight. Kay Poe, 18, of Houston is favored in women's
flyweight, and medals seem likely from Juan Moreno of Miami in
men's flyweight and Steven Lopez of Sugarland, Texas, in men's
featherweight.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
