<HEADLINE>
FROM CRUEL SUMMER TO KINDER FALL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use after Sun., Sept. 10, 2000, by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS AND GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, it's fall. The leaves are turning, the days are shortening,
and the movies are supposed to be getting better, right? Right?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. This is traditionally the time when studios roll out
their serious fare for Oscar consideration, but a cursory look at
the schedule seems to indicate that the majors are interested more
in box-office gold than Oscar gold. Just look at November: It
starts with a ``Charlie's Angels'' update and another Mars movie,
segues to Adam Sandler playing Satan's slacker son and goes out
barking with ``102 Dalmatians.'' It's not exactly a schedule that's
going to make anyone forget this summer's miserable movies.
</P>
<P>
   But there is hope. We've already seen some of the movies and can
tell you that Cameron Crowe's sentimental rock `n' roll
remembrance, ``Almost Famous,'' and Ang Lee's gorgeous martial arts
drama, ``Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon,'' are among the year's
best. October brings a dozen different films each weekend, and
we're betting that there will be a surprise buried somewhere in
there. After all, who knew about ``Being John Malkovich'' this time
last year?
</P>
<P>
   Nobody did. And that's the beauty of the season. Somewhere
between Schwarzenegger and Stallone (don't these guys belong in the
summer?), there will be small pleasures like ``Shadow of the
Vampire'' and David Mamet's ``State and Main,'' movies that remind
us that intelligence and fun can indeed go hand in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, of course, that this is a tentative list. Dates and
titles can and will change. (In fact, you can pretty much bet that
the ``Rugrats'' movie and Robert Redford's ``The Legend of Bagger
Vance'' will find a different opening weekend.)
</P>
<P>
   Here is what's in store: &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`HOW THE GRINCH STOLE CHRISTMAS' &QL; 
The haps in Whoville &QL; 
By Glenn Whipp &QL; 
Turning Dr. Seuss' thinly sketched children's classic ``How the
Grinch Stole Christmas'' into a full-length feature turned out to
be less of a problem for Ron Howard than he thought it might.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened pretty organically,'' Howard says. ``You realize
early that the Whos are out of their mind for Christmas. And what
one of us grown-ups hasn't at one time or another shook their head
and said, 'Christmas is getting out of control'? Well in Whoville,
it's really out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   And the only person not included in the mania is the Mean One,
Mr. Grinch, the man with the brain full of spiders and the
garlic-filled soul. Makeup genius Rick Baker spent five hours each
day turning Jim Carrey into the Man Who Stole Christmas, and the
process drove Carrey so batty that Howard brought in a former Navy
SEAL to help him cope with the claustrophobia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was more or less a mummy, but that's what he wanted,''
Howard says. ``He wanted to be the Grinch, not Jim Carrey in green
face paint.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was Carrey's love for Seuss' tale and vision for the
character that convinced Howard to tackle the adaptation in the
first place. Because, to quote the song, originally he didn't think
he would touch it _ even with a 39-and-a-half-foot pole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a tremendous trepidation going into this because people
really love this story, and you don't want to do anything to screw
it up,'' Howard says. ``But after talking to Jim, I got caught up
in his enthusiasm and thought, 'Why not?' And it turned out to be
one of the coolest things I've ever done in my career.'' (Set for
release Nov. 17.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`CROUCHING TIGER, HIDDEN DRAGON' &QL; 
East meets East &QL; 
By Glenn Whipp &QL; 
When Taiwanese director Ang Lee (``The Ice Storm,'' ``Sense and
Sensibility'') was trying to raise $15 million to make his latest
film, he'd pitch it to investors as a ``Sense and Sensibility''
with martial arts. It proved to be an intriguing enough idea to
secure financing. Then Lee had to go out and actually make the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the hard part,'' Lee says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   He more than succeeded. ``Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon''
floored audiences at Cannes with its poetic mixture of romance,
Taoism and ballet-like martial arts action. It's Lee's dream movie,
the film he has wanted to make ever since watching martial arts
movies as a child.
</P>
<P>
   But with its strong emotionalism and prominent female
characters, ``Crouching Tiger'' differs strongly from traditional
martial arts films. The story: Chow Yun-Fat plays Li Mu Bai, a
weary warrior who turns in his ancient sword so he can lead a life
of contemplation. When an aristocratic young woman (amazing
newcomer Zhang Ziyi) steals the sword, Li Mu Bai joins with an old
friend, Shu Lien (Michelle Yeoh from ``Tomorrow Never Dies''), to
retrieve it and settle an old score.
</P>
<P>
   That description only scratches the surface of the film's
abundant pleasures. Filmed throughout China, ``Crouching Tiger,
Hidden Dragon'' is also an epic love story featuring some of the
most jaw-dropping martial arts choreography in film history. That
should come as no surprise, given the presence of the legendary
Yuen Wo-Ping, the man who made the fight scenes in ``The Matrix''
such a kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an almost impossible task we set before us, trying to
make an artistic, human drama along with a modern martial arts
film,'' Lee says. ``They're two different animals. We're asking the
audience to believe the real emotions we're presenting and then
accept people flying through the air, performing abstract feats of
skill. It will be new for most people.
</P>
<P>
   And it will be imitated by a lot of filmmakers. But it won't
likely ever be done quite as well. (Set for release Dec. 15) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`WHAT WOMEN WANT' &QL; 
A way with 'Women' &QL; 
By Glenn Whipp &QL; 
What do women want? Don't ask Mel Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Figure it this way,'' Gibson begins rather glumly. ``Freud
spent almost his entire working career trying to figure that out,
and he died without the answer. Not that I put much stock in Freud,
but at least he was trying to find the answer. And he didn't come
any closer than the rest of us. Well, he thought he did, but really
he was just chasing his tail around.''
</P>
<P>
   So ... that's it?
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' Gibson says, ``here's what I really think. The answer
lies somewhere between chocolate and conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   See's Candies ought to like that. In ``What Women Want,'' Gibson
plays a self-absorbed ad executive who, after getting electrocuted
in the bathtub, discovers he has the ability to read women's minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, he's appalled by it because there's a lot of stuff
he doesn't want to hear,'' Gibson says. ``And then he starts to use
it and becomes a complete pig. And then he discovers a whole side
of him that he never knew was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Nancy Meyers (``Parent Trap'') says Gibson
doesn't need much help when it comes to women, especially when it
concerns directors of the fairer sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows how to talk to women and be with women and he really
listens,'' Meyers says. ``He's about the furthest thing from macho
you could find.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell that to Gibson. When asked what women would hear if
they could read men's thoughts, he says, ``The sound of crickets
chirping and a lot of knuckle-dragging. And maybe an episode or two
of the Three Stooges.''
</P>
<P>
   Nyuk, nyuk, nyuk. (Set for release Dec. 15) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`TRAFFIC' &QL; 
Soderbergh yearned to direct 'Traffic' &QL; 
By Glenn Whipp &QL; 
Director Steven Soderbergh was coming off two critical successes
(``Out of Sight'' and ``The Limey''), a flat-out hit (``Erin
Brockovich'') and a casting call for a remake of ``Ocean's 11''
that had every top-name actor in Hollywood clamoring for a part.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that seemed to matter for Soderbergh when it came to
getting his latest project, ``Traffic,'' off the ground. The movie
is a series of intertwined dramas revolving around the
international drug trade. People loved the screenplay, but the
enthusiasm was tempered by the bleakness of the subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it,'' Soderbergh says matter-of-factly, `'drug
movies don't have a storied history when it comes to making
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox put the film in turnaround last winter, only to pick it up
again when Harrison Ford expressed interest in playing the lead
character: a drug czar who most cope with his junkie daughter. Ford
ultimately passed (``Coming off of 'Random Hearts,' the material
was just too dark,'' he says) and Fox did, too. Soderbergh ended up
spending his own money to fund pre-production while he looked for
another studio. (USA Films stepped up.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been an interesting, harrowing experience,'' Soderbergh
says. ``I wouldn't wish it on anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Douglas ended up taking the lead, and his new wife,
Catherine Zeta-Jones, joined the cast as well, playing a drug
dealer's wife. Among the other featured players: Dennis Quaid,
Benjamin Bratt, Albert Finney, Benicio Del Toro and Don Cheadle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of stories, and hopefully we've found a thread
to make them work together,'' Soderbergh says. ``If it works, it
could play like 'The French Connection' crossed with 'Nashville.'
'' (Set for release Dec. 22.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
