<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-ART-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL COMMENTARY: OIL-FUELED INFLATION CATCHING UP WITH WAGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hardly any description of the booming economy fails to include
this upbeat observation: Wages have been rising faster than
inflation for most workers since January 1996. The boom has lifted
all boats, and that is its great social gift.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, hardly noticed until now, the lifting stopped.
Wages are still rising, but no longer faster than inflation.
</P>
<P>
   That is a troubling development. Nothing has seemed more
important in the economic boom than the wage gains it has
conferred. High-end workers, those earning more than $80,000 a
year, always gain ground. But the pay of nearly everyone else went
nowhere for a quarter-century, until the rising prosperity of the
1990s _ and a falling unemployment rate _ finally brought relief.
</P>
<P>
   Wages have risen 3 percent to 5 percent a year since 1996, with
the precise figure depending on the measure used _ average wages,
median wages, hourly wages _ and the particular group of workers
measured. The $7-an-hour worker has done as well as those earning
$18 or $25. And even now, these ``nominal'' wages, unadjusted for
inflation, continue to rise at a fairly steady pace, according to
Labor Department data tabulated by the Economic Policy Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is inflation. A dollar's worth of nominal wages does
not buy as much when prices rise. Inflation must be subtracted to
know the ``real'' rate of wage growth. A 4 percent nominal raise
becomes no raise at all if inflation is also 4 percent. And that is
roughly what has happened. The Consumer Price Index, which rose
less than 2 percent a year in 1997 and 1998, is now climbing at an
annual rate of more than 3.5 percent, nullifying all or most of
this year's wage gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that you have had constant nominal wage
growth, yet slowing real wage growth, which over the last two
quarters has been just about flat,'' said Jared Bernstein, an
economist at the Economic Policy Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The oil shock is the culprit, and there is hope that it will end
soon, with OPEC increasing production enough to bring down the
prices of heating oil, gasoline and aviation fuel, and with them
the inflation rate. The decision to step up output could even come
this weekend at a conference in Vienna. But the oil crisis is in
its second year, and an earlier production increase didn't pull
prices down.
</P>
<P>
   If inflation keeps up at its present pace, American workers will
be in a bind. Either they must agitate for bigger nominal wage
increases _ making better use of the leverage they have from a very
low unemployment rate _ or they will have to accept that the
longest economic expansion in American history has lost its lifting
power for them. ``We are at a moment of testing,'' said Peter
Hooper, chief domestic economist for Deutsche Bank North America.
</P>
<P>
   Many forecasters and Wall Street economists argue that the
necessary bargaining power is still there. If the inflation rate
stays up, workers will indeed wake up and fight for raises large
enough to keep ahead of inflation or, failing that, jump to jobs
that pay more. That has not happened yet, this argument goes,
because most people believe that inflation in the longer run will
be less than 3 percent, and nominal wage gains will turn back into
real ones.
</P>
<P>
   Such thinking ignores accumulating evidence that American
workers are more passive than in the past, and much less able, when
inflation erodes their wages, to take advantage of market demand
for their services. A host of reasons are cited: Globalization, job
insecurity, the decline in union membership, mass extinctions of
higher-paying factory jobs, an influx of low-wage immigrants,
companies that are quick to relocate to lower-wage regions, the
disappearance of cost-of-living adjustments. The list continues,
with two new observations.
</P>
<P>
   The 86,000 workers who struck Verizon so effectively last month
settled for a 12.5 percent wage increase over three years, plus
less tangible stock options and profit sharing. Many nonunion
workers have been getting similar wage increases since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   And the old corporate practice of splitting productivity gains
with employees _ often at the insistence of unions _ is fading.
Labor productivity has been rising more rapidly over the last two
years, meaning that workers generate more revenue and income for
their companies. But the fruits have gone mainly into profits, not
wages. Corporate profits rose in the second quarter to 9.7 percent
of gross domestic product, from 9.34 percent in the fourth quarter
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Workers have not yet recognized the extent to which their
rising productivity has not yet been matched by increases in
nominal wages,'' Hooper said.
</P>
<P>
   The great concern, in sum, is that the lift for wage earners
from the booming economy is fading, and in danger of disappearing
entirely if the oil shock lasts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1838EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
