<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6861 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-GARDENCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-08 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC-GARDENCOLUMN 
WHITEFLIES AND OTHER PESTS CAN BE CONTROLLED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
(c) 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
Q: What is the best way to stop a whitefly epidemic? We have had a
terrible problem with these pests this summer._ L.D.R., Spring,
Texas
<TEXT>
<P>
   A: Whiteflies drain the sap from foliage and, given a heavy
infestation, can weaken a plant and stunt growth. Damaged leaves
may be stippled yellow, and many curl and turn brown.
</P>
<P>
   Adults and nymphs excrete honeydew, a sticky substance that, in
turn, promotes sooty mold on the leaves, a fungus that turns the
leaves a sticky black. This mold, however, is not really harmful
and can be gently washed off the leaves.
</P>
<P>
   The whiteflies, however, should be controlled. Persistent,
strong sprays of water from the garden hose, aimed at the
undersides and tops of the leaves, help break up the problem. This
may sound silly, but daily or every-other-day treatments will help
you rid the plants of the pests.
</P>
<P>
   You also could try an insecticidal soap. Yellow sticky traps and
pesticides containing pyrethrum, rotenone or neem also can help
fight these pests. Malathion can be used, too, but be sure to read
and follow the directions carefully. Do not use malathion on
hibiscus. Whatever your means of attack, persistence is the answer
until you get matters under control.
</P>
<P>
   The following recipe for combating whiteflies, spider mites,
scales, chinch bugs and other pests is from Mark Bowen, who owns
Living Art Landscapes and is president of the board of directors
for Urban Harvest, a Houstoncommunity garden organization:
</P>
<P>
   Place 1 cayenne pepper, 1 whole lemon (cut up), 1 garlic bulb, 3
tablespoons of soybean oil and 2 tablespoons of seaweed extract
(kelp) into a blender and mix. Strain through pantyhose.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the concentrate into a pump sprayer, dilute with water to
make either a strong 1-gallon or a weaker 2-gallon solution.
</P>
<P>
   Water plants, wait a day or two, then apply the spray in the
morning. Bowen recommends the weaker solution for drought-stressed
plants. To be safe, test-treat a few leaves before spraying the
entire plant. Avoid spraying delicate plants such as African
violets and ferns.
</P>
<P>
   Toss strained solids into the compost.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Recently while visiting in Fredericksburg, Texas, I
discovered a tree in a residential area that was bearing fruit. The
homeowner said it was a type of apple. The fruit is red, 1 to 2
inches in size, and tastes like a sweet apple. Have you ever heard
of this type of apple? _ R.F.N., Bellaire, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Crabapples are 1 to 2 inches, and some types are red, but the
fruit not eaten by the birds is usually used for jellies since they
are not sweet. I don't know of a sweet apple that small, so I asked
fruit tree expert Bill Rohde for help. It's possible that the apple
you saw was one grown from seed, or the tree is not being thinned,
or both. Thinning young fruit enables a tree to put more energy
into fewer apples, and the result is larger fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for a ground cover that will survive our heat
and seemingly constant drought. It would be planted in full sun.
Any suggestions? _ A.M.W., Bellaire, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Barring many repeats of record-shattering heat and severe
drought, there are plants that tolerate sun and drier conditions _
lantanas, for example. And rosemary has held up well this summer in
our garden. I have given it a little water, however, to avoid
dusty, bone-dry conditions.
</P>
<P>
   I would vote for ornamental grasses. You could mass one type,
mix those of varying heights or mix the grasses with lantana,
Rudbeckia `Goldsturm' and/or purple coneflowers.
</P>
<P>
   The wispy, pinkish plumes of the native ornamental grass Gulf
muhly (Muhlenbergia capilleris) are spectacular in late summer and
early fall. Height is 2{ to 3 feet. The maiden grass Miscanthus
sinensis `Gracillimus' has slender, weeping foliage with white
midribs and coppery plumes. Height is 5-6 feet. Dwarf selections
include Pennisetum alopecuriodes `Little Bunny,' a charmer that
produces creamy, puffed flowers in fall.
</P>
<P>
   Just keep in mind that any of these plants will take some water
until established.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Huber is the Houston Chronicle's garden editor.
</P>
<P>
   XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
