<P>
   LOYALTY (Mesa, Ariz.) - Mesa Community College's student body
vice president, who said he's a member of the Communist Party, has
refused to sign a loyalty oath required of all community college
student officers and employees. Because of his refusal, college
officials won't let him take office and won't pay him his salary.
The oath, which makes it a felony to be a Communist, has been
illegal since 1966 when the Supreme Court declared such loyalty
oaths unconstitutional, after a Tucson teacher challenged them,
according to the ACLU. The ACLU has taken the student officer's
case and has preliminary assurances that the college district will
change its oath policy. (Arizona State University also requires a
loyalty oath, but it's generic and constitutional, according to the
ACLU). By EDYTHE JENSEN. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
