<HEADLINE>
HOW AN UNPRETENTIOUS FAMILY CAR, THE PASSAT, GOT SO HOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
(ART ADV: NYT Photos 21,22,23 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHELINE MAYNARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Family sedans generate big sales, but seldom do they
create a buzz. The Volkswagen Passat, however, has gained
most-wanted status, thanks to glowing reviews from automotive
writers, high ratings from consumer publications and positive
word-of-mouth among owners.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, Consumer Reports has given high ratings to the
Passat. In its July issue, the magazine rated the Passat GLS V-6
first among midsized sedans, over the Toyota Camry, Nissan Maxima
and Honda Accord. The magazine had previously ranked the
four-cylinder Passat above comparable models.
</P>
<P>
   A top ranking from Consumer Reports, or even its more common
``recommended'' rating, is coveted, given that many car shoppers
come to dealerships clutching copies of the magazine's reports,
which some regard as gospel; some auto marketing executives have
estimated that its recommendation can result in 25,000 added sales.
</P>
<P>
   The Passat has also received uniformly favorable notices in
enthusiast magazines and newspaper reviews, and it has won industry
awards. This summer, for instance, J.D. Power &AMP; Associates named it
the ``most appealing family car.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Passat sales are soaring, setting records for much
of the year. And if sales continue at the torrid first-half pace,
VW is likely to sell nearly 90,000 Passats in 2000, well above last
year's sales record of 68,151, said Tony Fouladpour, a spokesman
for VW. The Northeast is a particularly hot market, accounting for
15 percent of Passat sales nationwide, Fouladpour said.
</P>
<P>
   The car is attracting interest among consumers who might never
have considered VW's lineup before. In Grand Rapids, Mich., buyers
often arrive at Betten Imports with copies of Consumer Reports in
hand, said the sales manager, Jeff Leckta. Used to selling
Volkswagens to repeat customers, ``I'm seeing people in here that
I've never seen before,'' he said. Several recent buyers traded
Camrys for Passats.
</P>
<P>
   He and other salespeople complain about a lack of cars to sell.
As early as May, some dealers were telling customers that if they
wanted a Passat, they would have to order a 2001 model, due out in
October.
</P>
<P>
   The car's popularity means VW has not offered special lease
deals, discount financing or rebates, even though the Passat is
priced above its rivals. The base GLS is $21,200, compared with
$18,600 for a Honda Accord LX and $20,388 for a Toyota Camry LE.
The Passat GLS V-6 starts at $23,800 versus the Honda Accord LX V-6
at $21,950 and the Toyota Camry LE V-6 at $22,358.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the Passat, a descendant of past VW models like
the Quantum and Dasher, is quite recent. The previous-generation
car suffered from quality problems and boxy styling. ``You had to
have a real appreciation for Teutonic German design,'' Fouladpour
said of the 1990-97 model. Sales slipped as low as 11,021 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Everything changed with the redesigned 1998 model, whose
roofline is a graceful arc that mimics the look of the New Beetle.
The restyled Passat won praise for its interior comfort, adept
handling and responsive engine. Many of its parts are shared with
the more expensive Audi A4 and A6.
</P>
<P>
   Fans include Ron Pinelli, the founder of Autodata Corp., a
statistics and marketing firm in Woodcliff Lake, N.J. This year, he
bought a silver Passat GLS with a turbocharged four-cylinder
engine. He promptly added another $3,000 in custom wheels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Accord and Camry are wonderful products, but the Passat has
more passion behind it,'' Pinelli said. He said the Passat's
popularity was a symbol of VW's sales comeback in the United
States. ``It wasn't many years ago that VW was basically out of
business in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Passat has brought Volkswagen a sought-after group of buyers.
Their average age is 38, compared with 43 for the last Passat. More
are women: 43 percent, compared with 38 percent previously. And
their household income tops $83,000, up $13,000. Three-quarters are
college-educated, compared with two-thirds for the previous car.
</P>
<P>
   Many auto companies would put on a full press to attract
additional buyers, but VW's goal is to eventually sell 100,000
Passats a year in the United States. Fouladpour said VW could not
hope to steal more business from the Accord and Camry, which each
sell more than 350,000 cars a year, because of production
constraints and a relatively small network of dealers.
</P>
<P>
   And VW insists that the Passat, with its decidedly German ride
and handling characteristics, was never intended to appeal to the
mass American market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still not a car for everybody,'' Fouladpour said. ``It
has a personality that attracts a certain type of buyer. Toyota and
Honda do vanilla and bland better than everyone else. We intend to
be a wakeup call.''
</P>
</TEXT>
