<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF THE SHELF: `WHEN GENIUS FAILED' 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Aug. 21, 1998, a little-known investment partnership in
Greenwich, Conn., lost $553 million. The loss on that single sunny
Friday left the behemoth fund with $2.9 billion in capital, down
from $4.67 billion just months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The fund, of course, was Long-Term Capital Management, which was
born in the brain of an enigmatic Wall Street bond trader named
John Meriwether. By September 1998, with world markets already
roiled by a Russian bond default, the enormous fund was teetering
at the edge of failure, with many of the world's biggest banks and
brokerage houses shackled to it by countless links of leverage.
</P>
<P>
   If the hedge fund failed, who else would be pulled down with it?
And how would a market already nearing the thin edge of panic
react? Faced with those questions _ and with the impossibility of
receiving reliable answers in the time available _ the head of the
Federal Reserve Bank of New York called the fund's top creditors,
the chieftains of Wall Street, to an emergency meeting at which
they ultimately agreed to bail out the fund with fresh capital.
</P>
<P>
   That dramatic and still controversial rescue, and the events
that let up to it, are the threads that Roger Lowenstein weaves
into ``When Genius Failed: The Rise and Fall of Long-Term Capital
Management'' (Random House, $26.95). This richly textured and lucid
account is not the first book to try to parse the secrecy that
shrouded those events. ``Inventing Money: The Story of Long-Term
Capital and the Legends Behind It,'' by Nicholas Dunbar (Wiley &AMP;
Sons), added a wealth of financial history and market theory to the
core story.
</P>
<P>
   But Lowenstein, a former Wall Street Journal reporter, has taken
a completely different path, examining the events primarily through
the prism of human nature. The results are a riveting account that
reaches beyond the market landscape to say something universal
about risk and triumph, about hubris and failure.
</P>
<P>
   Central to the story is Meriwether himself, an accountant's son
who grew up in a close-knit neighborhood in Chicago. An honor
student with a mathematical bent, he parlayed his passion for golf
into a college scholarship. Even as a teen-ager, he was an avid but
cautious gambler, holding his cards _ and his ambitions _ close to
his chest.
</P>
<P>
   After college, he taught high school mathematics for a year,
then enrolled in the University of Chicago's business school,
working his way through as an analyst for a large insurer. In 1974,
at 27, he was hired by Salomon Brothers, one of the leading
bond-trading houses on the Street. Three years later, after making
millions for the firm speculating on government and municipal
bonds, he formed the arbitrage group, which used Salomon's own
capital to exploit tiny disparities in bond prices.
</P>
<P>
   To help him find these opportunities, he recruited a band of
mathematical scholars, young academics whose awesome intelligence
gave Meriwether the edge he sought in the increasingly competitive
markets. The group was remarkably isolated from the rest of Salomon
Brothers, and Meriwether protected them from even the normal human
interaction of the workplace. ``The professors were brilliant at
reducing a trade to pluses and minuses; they could strip a ham
sandwich to its component risks; but they could barely carry on a
normal conversation,'' Lowenstein says.
</P>
<P>
   They were a remarkable band, and most of them became permanent
acolytes at Meriwether's altar, following him at every step of his
career: Eric Rosenfeld, an MIT-trained assistant professor at the
Harvard Business School; Victor Haghani, a graduate of the London
School of Economics; and the rigidly rational Lawrence Hilibrand,
who has two degrees from MIT. Meriwether left Salomon Brothers
after a brush with scandal _ he was the supervisor of a trader
caught manipulating Treasury securities. He then started his own
hedge-fund replica of the arbitrage group, adding three high
priests of finance: Robert Merton and Myron Scholes, Nobel
laureates for work relating to options pricing, and David W.
Mullins Jr., who had been vice chairman of the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   These men all possessed an unswerving faith in the notion that
markets are fundamentally rational and efficient, and that every
price generated in that marketplace is the correct one. Among
economists, this so-called efficient market theory is just that, a
theory, reflecting a Platonic ideal of the marketplace. Moreover,
the theory assumes that trading in any market is more or less
continuous and that prices move smoothly from one level to the next
nearest level, giving everyone a chance to adjust portfolios
rationally to reflect the changes.
</P>
<P>
   Through Lowenstein's compassionate eye, we watch as these
fascinating coddled geniuses discover what any dedicated
flea-market shopper already knows: In real life, people buy and
sell things for reasons entirely unconnected to rationality. As he
notes, the mathematical laws governing a coin toss rest on the fact
that ``the coin doesn't remember that it landed on tails three
times in a row; the odds on the fourth flip are still 50-50.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But markets have memories,'' he says. ``Sometimes a trend will
continue just because traders expect (or fear) that it will.''
</P>
<P>
   He adds: ``After three bad `flips' in the market, the fourth
flip may no longer be completely random. Some traders may have
taken losses and be forced to sell; other investors, looking over
their shoulders, may panic and decide to beat them to it.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is pretty much what happened in the galloping climax to
the Long-Term Capital story. ``The partners believed that, over
time, investors would become more rational, more steady, more
efficient _ more like  &UR; they &LR;  were,'' Lowenstein concludes. Instead,
as the story unfolds, Meriwether's brilliant followers became more
irrational, greedier, more oblivious to their own flaws _ in short,
more like the rest of us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
