<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6868 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CANCER-DRUGS-(TRIMS)-     09-08 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-DRUGS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. RETREATS FROM PLAN TO LOWER MEDICARE PAYMENTS FOR CANCER
DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Under withering criticism from doctors, patients
and Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican presidential nominee, the
Clinton administration backed away Friday from a plan to cut
Medicare payments for cancer drugs given to hundreds of thousands
of patients each year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said the cuts, which were to
have taken effect on Oct. 1, had been deferred indefinitely.
Federal officials said they needed to study the whole process by
which Medicare pays for cancer chemotherapy, including not only
drugs, but also the services of doctors and nurses.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy-Ann Min DeParle, who supervises Medicare as administrator
of the federal Health Care Financing Administration, said she still
believed that Medicare paid too much for cancer drugs. But, she
said, the government will not make any immediate cuts in payments
for the drugs because officials now recognize that payments to
doctors for chemotherapy services are inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, doctors use the overpayments to help subsidize the
cost of delivering the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare officials said they would not lower payment for cancer
drugs until they increased payments for administering the drugs.
Next year, DeParle said, the government will propose regulations or
legislation to increase payments for the services.
</P>
<P>
   Donna E. Shalala, the secretary of health and human services,
announced the plan to reduce ``excessive Medicare payments'' in
May. Medicare officials said today that they did not realize the
cuts could have disrupted the nation's entire system of cancer
care.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors, led by the American Society of Clinical Oncology, said
they would have had to send many cancer patients to hospitals for
treatment, causing inconvenience to patients while increasing costs
to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare now pays for a very limited number of outpatient drugs,
including cancer drugs provided in doctors' offices.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they worried that the cuts would
become a political fiasco, undermining Democratic efforts to secure
broad Medicare coverage for all medically necessary prescription
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Bush cited the planned cuts to support his argument
that the Medicare agency was ``rigid and sluggish and slow to
change'' and posed ``a hazard to your health.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio, the Republican candidate for Senate in New
York, said last month, ``In light of its oft-proclaimed intention
of saving Medicare, it's highly ironic that the Clinton
administration would propose a policy that would sabotage the
ability of seniors to obtain cancer therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nita M. Lowey, D-N.Y., said that if the cuts had occurred,
many doctors would have found it ``financially impossible to
provide chemotherapy services in their offices.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At least 121 members of Congress _ 70 Republicans and 51
Democrats _ signed letters to Shalala expressing alarm at the
planned cuts.
</P>
<P>
   A 1987 law directed the Medicare agency to study the adequacy of
Medicare payments for chemotherapy services in doctors' offices.
The study, due on April 1, 1989, was never done.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, Medicare officials said Friday, they will now do the
study that Congress ordered 13 years ago. The study could take many
months, and it will not be easy to change the Medicare payment
formula so it accurately reflects the special costs incurred in
outpatient cancer care.
</P>
<P>
   Terry S. Coleman, former chief counsel of the Medicare program,
said: ``The reimbursement methodology is so complicated, you can't
just go in and adjust a few billing codes. The same methodology is
used for all physician specialties, not just oncology.''
</P>
<P>
   While putting off cuts in payment for cancer drugs, Medicare
officials said they would cut payments for drugs used at kidney
dialysis centers and in the treatment of emphysema and other lung
diseases, starting Jan. 1.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   People with irreversible kidney failure typically go to a
dialysis center three times a week to have waste cleaned from the
blood. They receive drugs to treat bone disease and anemia.
</P>
<P>
   Dolph Chianchiano, director of public policy at the National
Kidney Foundation, said: ``As a result of the cuts being made by
the government, Medicare patients may be unable to obtain the drugs
they need, or they may have to make a special visit to a hospital
each week to get the drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   One example illustrates how the cuts could have affected cancer
care.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dean H. Gesme, president of the National Coalition for
Cancer Survivorship, an advocacy group for patients, works with
four other doctors at a clinic with 4,000 to 5,000 patients in
Cedar Rapids, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Gesme said Friday that the cuts would have cost his clinic
$300,000 to $500,000 a year. Currently, he said, the clinic,
Oncology Associates, receives $2 million to $2.5 million a year in
payments from Medicare for drugs and $400,000 for the services of
doctors and nurses who administer the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Gesme said the clinic did not make any money on its Medicare
chemotherapy business, but derived all its profits from privately
insured patients.
</P>
<P>
   The changes planned by the Clinton administration would have
directly affected only Medicare reimbursement. But Gesme said,
``When Medicare makes sweeping cuts, private insurers often follow
suit, assuming that the government must be right.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa T. Skolfield, a spokeswoman for the Department of Health
and Human Services, said, ``The oncologists raised some legitimate
concerns.'' Skolfield said Shalala was not aware that Medicare was
underpaying for such services when she announced the cuts in May.
</P>
<P>
   However, Medicare officials have long been aware of the problem.
An official notice published in the Federal Register in 1988
acknowledged that Medicare ``may fail to compensate adequately for
the services'' of doctors and nurses providing chemotherapy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
