<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURNING-MAN-$ADV10-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LEAST LIKELY BURNING MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 10)  
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACK ROCK DESERT, Nev. _ There aren't many rules at Burning Man
_ the weeklong cyberhippie carnival in the middle of the Nevada
desert that ended on Labor Day. But one of them is ``No logos.'' I
was warned about this before I went. Unfortunately, I don't own any
clothing without logos. Who does? So as an anti-anticommercial
statement on my first morning there, I wore an old Creative Artists
Agency T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``CAA!'' a female voice shouted as I biked past her encampment.
``Burn in hell!''
</P>
<P>
   I turned the shirt inside out. After four days in this
brand-free zone, I would come to see her point.
</P>
<P>
   Burning Man, as you may or may not know, is devoted to ``radical
self-expression.'' In 1986 its founder, Larry Harvey, burned a
stick-man effigy on a Bay Area beach after breaking up with his
girlfriend. As the pyrocentric event grew into an annual rite,
authorities told Harvey to take his followers elsewhere. Now,
25,000 of them make the pilgrimage to the Black Rock Desert, a vast
dry lake bed 120 miles north of Reno. Artists. Performers. College
kids. Partyers. Techno-geeks. Ravers. Neo-paganists. Dot-com
yuppies. Professional and amateur nudists. The effigy has grown to
a 40-foot neon skeleton stuffed with wood and fireworks, whose
spectacular torching is the event's ritualistic climax.
</P>
<P>
   A small temporary city springs up on this lifeless playa, so
flat and desolate it can be used only for land speed tests and
fashion shoots. Imagine a hallucinogenic state fair that combines
elements of Woodstock, Mardi Gras, ``Alice in Wonderland'' and
Cirque du Soleil. In short: not my scene, in the extreme.
</P>
<P>
   Years of professionally mandated cynicism have shut off whatever
synapses are required to participate in a drum circle. I'm not a
hugger. I hate camping. But a couple of San Francisco friends who
had gone last year persuaded me I could enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, I figured. As long as I got the big bed in a
state-of-the-art recreational vehicle and would never be forced to
use a Porta-John.
</P>
<P>
   I was curious. Another friend was so affected by his Burning Man
experience last year that it inspired him to take an unscheduled
sabbatical from his New York television production business and
embark on a three-month ``tour of the planet.'' And elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   So I found myself way out of cell phone range, spending almost
12 hours setting up a Moroccan tent. I had never set up a tent,
much less an 18-by-30-foot canvas Ali Baba number. My friends John
and Ted (who made a quiet killing as an Internet entrepreneur) sent
a woman to Morocco to buy it for the occasion _ an order that
included pillows, ottomans and a few caftans. These guys, along
with John's brother, David, and I were the core team, as they say
in Silicon Valley, of a group that would swell to two more RVs and
a Chevy Suburban. It was a sprawling frat party free of the
civilizing influences of wives or girlfriends.
</P>
<P>
   We camped on Anal Avenue. I hasten to explain that Black Rock
City is laid out like a clock face, with some streets fanning
straight out from 2 to 10 o'clock, at half-hour intervals, and
other curved concentric ones named for parts of the body. We were
between Knee Lane and Sex Drive. Look, it was the best parking spot
we could find in the middle of the night. Last year, the street
theme was the solar system, and my friends wound up on Uranus.
</P>
<P>
   John, who works for a health care start-up, and his brother, a
composer, filled our pseudo-souk with world-music instruments.
There were Indian and African drums, flutes, a zither, not one but
two didgeridoos, which by some standards is two didgeridoos too
many.
</P>
<P>
   Once the logistical nightmare of erecting the tent was over, it
was a hit. People kept stopping to admire it. A young woman on a
bicycle promised to come back later to belly-dance. The people
across the street _ who spent their entire time drinking, grilling
and shouting obscenities _ hated us for it. When one of our
happy-face pinatas went missing, they offered unconvincing denials.
</P>
<P>
   That night, we started our wanderings with a round of minigolf
on a clothing-optional course at the bottom of our street. Our day
had already featured a conversation with the owner of a pair of
pierced nipples. So we were becoming inured to all the female
nudity, partial and full. (Not really, but we were getting better
at not staring.)
</P>
<P>
   Spectators are the only kind of people Burning Man doesn't want
_ yahoos and squares like me in jeans and black windbreakers and
orange ``Lake Tahoe'' baseball caps. I could see that I was seen as
a nonparticipant who didn't contribute to the madness, but only
gawked at it. Twice I was described as ``funny looking.'' It was
getting to me.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone had a gimmick, some bit of personal performance
art _ a pope costume, a fur-covered bicycle, a tricked-out ``Mad
Max'' car. At night, they turned themselves into walking light
installations, festooned with fluorescent glow sticks, neon
headgear sculptured into a fish shape (there was a whole school of
them swimming around), or flashing red LED displays tracing
arteries and a beating heart.
</P>
<P>
   The more ambitious revelers ran moving sideshows. A perennial
favorite was a physicist who calls himself Megavolt. This mad
scientist stands on top of a truck rigged with two huge tesla coils
shooting deafening bolts of man-made lightning through his metal
suit. Perfectly safe, he says. But you couldn't help wondering if
the doc's brain hadn't accidentally been switched,
Frankenstein-style, with some stoner in the crowd gaping slackjawed
at his act.
</P>
<P>
   The air was cold and clear, but bad weather was coming. The next
day, Ted and I rode bikes out to ``the Man'' himself, the towering
effigy at the end of a promenade of monumental sculptures.
Suddenly, a dust storm rolled over us, filling the air with choking
white dust loaded with alkali from the lake bed. With no more than
five feet of visibility, we pedaled in the general direction of our
camp. I felt like T.E. Lawrence, my CAA T-shirt tied over my mouth
and nose to keep out the cancer dust.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Others who have seen the pictures thought it looked more like a
scene out of ``Ishtar.''
</P>
<P>
   At least now I'd participated. I'd have a tale to tell at the
Center Camp cafe, a tented 24-hour freak show that made the bar in
``Star Wars'' look like a TGI Fridays. An image from the cafe that
will haunt my dreams is the old man I saw walking out of it one
afternoon, shaking and stark naked, like somebody's lost
grandfather or the ghost of Timothy Leary back for one last crazy
trip.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   The drug component of Burning Man cannot be denied. A bulletin
board in Center Camp posted results of a survey taken at last
year's festival. About half the respondents said they had indulged
in illicit substances. Half of them cited marijuana, and 20 percent
Ecstasy. The Pershing County Police patrolled the streets, always
in cars and trucks, some marked ``K-9 Unit.'' Drug-taking appeared
to be clandestine, not brazen. Black Rock Rangers, volunteers in
overalls with no official authority or status, ran interference
between the ``citizens'' and the law, discouraging blatant drug
consumption or other illegal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   One Black Rock Ranger told us he had stopped a bout of domestic
violence in a tent and been punched by a drunk the night before. We
asked if either he or the police ever stopped any public nudity.
``Are you kidding?'' he said. ``If ain't too cold and I ain't
working, I'm naked.'' The Ranger then informed us that his nickname
was Nude Marty.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't about to get naked, but by the second and third nights,
I did have a nighttime get-up that I hoped would at least shield me
from public ridicule. I took an orange-and-black wool poncho that
John had brought and tied red glow sticks to the fringe. A
half-baked effort compared with the simple but powerful dreadlock
effect Ted's younger brother Mark (a sculptor) created by
safety-pinning dozens of glow sticks to his fishing hat. The fuzzy
yellow bunny suit and happy-face head that Roland, one of our other
camp mates, had on outdid us all. I looked like a chili-pepper
promotion at Taco Bell. Still, the poncho got me my first hug, from
a slightly plump young woman outside one of the miniraves on the
playa. She must have been on drugs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
