<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6872 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-BURNING-MAN-$ADV10-2N     09-08 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURNING-MAN-$ADV10-2NDTAKE(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
 
BLACK ROCK DESERT, Nev.: been on drugs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   To escape a flash rainstorm, we ducked into Space Cowboy, a
tented theme rave populated almost entirely by men and women in
Western gear. Until then, I'd never really understood the appeal of
raves and the poundingly repetitive techno beat that drives them. I
remember my niece telling me she felt old at raves when she was 23.
How in tarnation do these kids move like that? I used to think I
had rhythm. At 150 beats a minute, all I could do was try to blind
people with my flashing red New York Taxi Wand (a gift!) to
distract them from the geezer in their midst. At Space Cowboy, in
my dusty jeans and Day-Glo poncho, I felt like I'd finally found my
tribe.
</P>
<P>
   The rain turned the ground into mud that locked bicycle wheels
and turned shoes into platforms. Shades of Woodstock. I hated
Woodstock, all three of them _ not that I ever went. The whole
hippie commune ideal it conjures, the woolly politics turn me off.
There are no politics at Burning Man, except a practical
environmental commandment _ ``Leave no trace!'' _ that keeps the
peace with the Bureau of Land Management, and a libertarian social
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do anything you want as long as it doesn't interfere with
anyone else's good time,'' as I read in the daily alternative
paper; there is also an official daily paper, which is already
pretty alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Smith could have lived with that. So could a Deadhead or
any Silicon Valley chief executive in our camp.
</P>
<P>
   For all the tribal drum beating, what really drives Burning Man
is individualism. In the 1960s, hippies young and old basically
wore the same pair of bell-bottoms. Here, the point is not to wear
the same thing as anyone else. ``I just want to be different like
all the other different people'' was Ted's joke about all the
nonconformist conformism around us. But it was energizing. What we
labeled the ``obnoxious friendliness'' of most of the Burners was
infectious. Before long, you stop fighting it.
</P>
<P>
   I went soft. I drummed _ once. For my last night, I asked Tracy,
our resident face-paint artist, to give me a couple of red-glitter
tears. When the Man burned, the sad chili-pepper salesman would
bear witness! I hugged that chubby chick back.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Besides the nudity, the allure of Burning Man is aesthetic.
Aesthetic escapism from Disney and MTV and Old Navy and Starbucks.
I understood why people covered up the sign on their Ryder rental
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Even for a hard-core free-market capitalist like me, branding is
starting to seem like a plague, turning cities into billboards,
foreign countries into fast-food courts. In his book on globalism,
``The Lexus and the Olive Tree,'' Thomas L. Friedman argues that no
two countries with McDonald's franchises have ever gone to war. The
price of this supersized Pax Romana is, well, a McDonald's in every
country.
</P>
<P>
   Driving back into civilization _ or, rather, Reno _ I looked at
the Emporio Armani logo on my sunglasses case. I'd never given it a
second thought. It looked kind of stupid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
