<HEADER>
A6874 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-OILPRICES-TEX     09-08 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OILPRICES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL PRICES ON VERGE OF A FALL, EXPERTS SAY
</HEADLINE>
  DUPLICATION WARNING: Story is being double filed in ``a'' general
news and ``f'' financial categories. 
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
 By DAN PILLER 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As President Clinton and other world leaders wring their hands
about a 10-year high in crude oil prices, some energy traders are
putting out the word that oil prices could tumble _ and soon.
</P>
<P>
   They say that, contrary to recent reports, there is no shortage
of crude oil. Rather, they say, the recent run-up of crude prices
above $30 per barrel reflects artificial trading conditions. Thus,
the expected increase in production by members of the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries this weekend could trigger a
sudden fall in crude oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   A drop in crude oil prices would be a mixed blessing in Texas.
Although motorists would get some relief from pump prices that are
50 percent higher than last September, the state's oil producers
could be thrown into the pit of low prices they endured two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that when oil prices start down, the correction
could be anything but mild,'' said energy analyst Frederick Leuffer
of the Bear Stearns investment firm in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Houston oil analyst Ken Miller of Purvin &AMP; Gertz said on
Thursday that if OPEC countries decide to increase production in
order to stabilize prices, ``they very well could cause prices to
crash.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Houston consulting firm, Groppe, Long &AMP; Littell, said
Thursday that ``missing barrels'' of crude aren't being counted in
the international energy statistics that show tight worldwide crude
inventories.
</P>
<P>
   George Littell of the firm said that if OPEC ministers add to
their daily production when they meet this weekend, as expected,
``it is very possible for them to cause another period of low
prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Texans in the energy business know how quickly things can
change. Three years ago, the industry was enjoying stable prices
ranging between $20 and $22 per barrel, well above the $15 price
considered the profit level for producers.
</P>
<P>
   Then OPEC, which controls prices by virtue of having 70 percent
of the world's crude oil supplies, decided to loosen the production
spigots. The result was a plunge in prices to as low as $10 per
barrel by early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The results were dramatic. Fort Worth's biggest oil company,
Union Pacific Resources Group, laid off 400 workers. UPR moved its
remaining 800 Fort Worth jobs to Houston after being acquired this
year by Anadarko Petroleum.
</P>
<P>
   Oil giants Exxon and Mobil merged, as did British Petroleum and
Amoco. Oryx Energy of Dallas was bought by Kerr-McGee of Oklahoma
and, like Union Pacific Resources, saw its jobs moved out of town.
On the service side, Halliburton and Dresser Industries did a
crosstown merger in Dallas. In the process, Halliburton eliminated
the 400 jobs at its Fort Worth production facility.
</P>
<P>
   The low prices were reversed beginning in the spring when OPEC
was able to impose production quotas on its members. As a result,
motorists have paid around $1.50 for regular self-serve gasoline
this summer, and prices reached $2 a gallon in California and parts
of the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Miller says the crude oil market could be on the precipice of a
sudden drop because of a phenomenon in futures trading called
``backwardation.''
</P>
<P>
   With backwardation, prices for a commodity such as crude oil are
lower in future months than they are at present. In the case of
crude, the $35 per barrel price this week for October delivery
slides to $30 for April and $28.45 for September 2001.
</P>
<P>
   This phenomenon causes the big oil companies, which do the bulk
of energy futures trading, to buy the bare minimum of crude for
their refineries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to pay $34 for crude today when the price may be
$4 to $6 per barrel less in a few months,'' said Miller. The
refining companies themselves don't comment on their futures
trading strategies.
</P>
<P>
   But with an increase in OPEC production, the reverse could set
in, Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Saudis might have to let the price of oil drop down to as
low as $20 per barrel in order to stabilize the market,'' he said,
reflecting the widespread belief that the equilibrium price _ where
demand meets supply _ is the same $20-$24 per barrel level where it
traded before its plunge, beginning in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   If the drop happens, he said, oil companies would quickly buy
more crude and thus produce more gasoline and other distillates,
driving down retail prices for motorists and users of home heating
oil.
</P>
<P>
   That would be, in traders' terms, a ``contango,'' a situation in
which futures prices are higher than the current price. That would
cause oil companies to buy crude furiously to lock in the lower
prices, thus duplicating the trading environment that caused crude
prices to plunge two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The crude is there for the buying, according to Bear Stearns'
Leuffer, who says there are about 250 million barrels of crude oil
that are ``missing'' from international reports. Those barrels are
in tankers at sea and sitting in various pipelines and storage
facilities in OPEC nations, going unsold because of backwardation,
he contends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there is a lot of oil in Asia and on the water, and
it's coming here next,'' Leuffer said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that international energy statistics that traders have
been using to justify shortages and higher prices are ``notoriously
unreliable.'' Instead, Leuffer contends, higher tanker rates this
year show that plenty of oil is moving around but that it hasn't
yet been directed to refineries in the U.S. and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that oil is headed for a tumble,'' Leuffer said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
