<HEADER>
A6875 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-08 1773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS DESERVES TO RETURN IN 2001 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jimy Williams will be the manager of the Red Sox next year, if
he chooses to be. Williams has a year left on his contract. The Red
Sox feel he has done a solid job managing the team since he started
in 1997 and that he is one of the best managers in the game.
</P>
<P>
   We bring this up because there seems to be a growing rumor that
general manager Dan Duquette is ready to get rid of Williams and
bring in Felipe Alou, his old friend from Montreal. Alou was the
manager of the Expos when Duquette was their GM, before coming to
Boston in January 1994. Reportedly, even though Alou has another
year left on his contract, he will finish as manager this season,
setting up a conspiracy theory with Duquette dumping Williams and
bringing in Alou.
</P>
<P>
   It says here that would be a lousy thing to do because, even
though Williams is quirky, he has been the best manager this team
has had since Dick Williams. The job he and pitching coach Joe
Kerrigan have done with that staff this season is remarkable. The
Red Sox have gotten nothing out of second and third base this year,
and are still hanging in the playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tapegate: The Jets think they know who sent a coaching tape to
one sportswriter in the Boston area and another in New York, in an
effort to belittle Bill Parcells. The No. 1 suspect is current
Patriots head coach Bill Belichick. No. 2 is former Jets offensive
coordinator Charlie Weis, now the Patriots' offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets say the tapes are coaching tapes, which would only be
available to the coaches. The video did not come from national
televison or NFL Films. This particular version could only come
from coaching tapes belonging to the New York Jets, because they
show Parcells and Belichick on the sideline during the closing
minutes of the Patriots' 30-28 win at the Meadowlands last Sept.
12. The Jets believe that when Belichick's group of former New York
employees came to Foxborough, they took some of the tapes with
them. Then, 10 days ago, they sent them out of the Patriots office
in Foxborough to the sportswriters with a note saying they show
that Parcells was confused at the end of the game and didn't know
the score. The stories written off the tapes by these writers say
that because Parcells didn't know the score, he mismanaged the
game's final six minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story is a lie,'' said Parcells. ``I knew the score. I
knew we were ahead. When the Patriots made a first down deep in our
end on a pass to Troy Brown with two minutes to go, I felt the game
was over for us. We only had one timeout left. They could run the
clock down and kick an easy field goal to beat us, which they did.
During that final two minutes, I didn't pay attention to what was
going on with the time. My mind was on what I was going to say to
the team about all of the injuries we had that day and losing such
a tough game. It was a very unusual set of circumstances and I was
trying to sort out what I was going to say to my team in the locker
room. This thing is so stupid, it's funny.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets think Belichick was trying to counter the criticism of
him in Parcells's new book, ``The Final Season,'' (written with
yours truly) which went on sale this week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was 40 years ago today that their paths crossed for the
second time, and together Gino Cappelletti and Frank Tripucka made
history. Cappelletti scored the first points in the history of the
American Football League with a 35-yard field goal in the first
period of the Patriots' opening 13-10 upset loss to the Denver
Broncos. Tripucka threw the first touchdown pass in the new league,
a 59-yarder to Al Carmichael in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny thing about that game,'' said Tripucka, an All-American
at Notre Dame in the late 1940s, and a star in Canada before being
called back to the AFL. ``I had met Gino years before in
Saskatchewan. He was just out of college and he came to Canada
looking to play ball. But we could keep only eight Americans in
those days, and only one quarterback. I already had the job. I
didn't know he could kick until he kicked the field goal. He never
tried that with us. I didn't know he could catch until he became
one of the best receivers in the AFL, because he didn't try that
with us. Our coach, Frank Filchock, never tried him at any other
position other than quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   On the night of the AFL opener, Cappelletti, who went on to
become the all-time leading scorer in AFL history, was not a pass
catcher. He was a safety. Later in the year, he established a club
record with three interceptions in a game against Babe Parilli,
then the Oakland quarterback, who would join the Patriots and
Cappelletti in '61.
</P>
<P>
   ``We killed Denver three weeks before that (43-6) in a preseason
game in Providence,'' said Cappelletti. ``We had a great preseason
(4-1). They didn't win a game. They were on the road for three
weeks and should have been washed out. Then they came in and
knocked us over. We were stunned.'' But Cappelletti found out years
later there was a good reason for the sudden Denver turnaround. ``I
bumped into Filchock (the same coach who cut him in Canada and was
the Broncos' first head coach) and he told me what happened.
(Denver) had practiced at BU the evening before the opener. We came
in to practice at night, because our coach (Lou Saban) wanted to
practice under the lights, at the same time of the game the next
night. Filchock told me when he was leaving practice, walking up
the street, he looked down on the field and saw us practicing.
There was a gate open so he walked in and stood up at the back of
the stands. He watched the whole practice. Normally, the practice
before a game wouldn't show much, but Saban kept us out there for a
couple of hours, ran everything we had on offense and defense. So
by the time practice was all over, Filchock knew everything we were
going to do. They stopped our offense cold the next night.''
</P>
<P>
   Tripucka remembers the game this way: ``I threw a touchdown pass
to Carmichael, then in the second half, our kicker, Gene Mingo, ran
back a punt for a touchdown. That's the only time he ever did it.
He really wasn't a kick returner, but in those days players had to
do more than one job, so they used him as a returner. In those days
in the AFL, it was a league of haves and have-nots. The rich owners
had the good teams because they could afford to pay the better
players. Denver had the poorest team in the league. We couldn't
even afford sweatsuits to have for cold weather. We didn't have
playbooks. We never had a game plan. Filchock was a different kind
of coach. The players never watched films of the other team, or the
game they played the week before. He didn't believe in a lot of
practice. In fact, he didn't like to practice. The night before a
game, when he got the team together to watch a film, it wasn't
football. He showed Mickey Mouse cartoons. He thought they were
funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played for four years and had to retire because I was 38 and
couldn't do it anymore. They've retired my number (18) in Denver.
There are only three numbers retired. Mine, Floyd Little's 44, and
John Elway's 7. I'm proud of that. I think I'm up there for
surviving four years,'' he said with a laugh. Meanwhile, the
league, now folded into the NFL, has survived 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Antoine Walker is right. The Celtics aren't going anywhere until
they get a center. You can't play defense at a high level in the
NBA unless you have a center who can intimidate the opposition with
his rebounding and shot-blocking ability . . . There are some bad
vibes on one of the local professional teams. The ex-wife of one of
the players has been blowing the whistle to wives of others
players, saying their hubbies have been cheating on them on the
road. This has been causing problems on the team, very similar to
the situation Wade Boggs and Margo Adams triggered on the Red Sox
years ago . . . Here is the latest line on the Boston teams from
the Mirage Sports Book in Las Vegas: The over/under on the Patriots
is 7 1/2, meaning the oddsmakers don't think they will win eight
games this year. They are 40-1 to win the AFC and 75-1 to win the
Super Bowl. The Celtics are the longest shots of the locals, 125-1
to win the NBA title. The Bruins check in at 55-1 to win the
Stanley Cup. The Sox are 7-1 to win the American League pennant and
14-1 to win the World Series. The Yankees are 12-5 favorites to win
the division.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is the assessment of one NFL general manager who watched
the films of the Patriots' loss to Tampa Bay last Sunday: ``It is
the worst performance I have ever seen by an offensive line. They
got slaughtered. Not on any single play did they block all four
Tampa defensive linemen. Not once. If you graded out every Tampa
linemen, all of them would have been 90-plus, they were that
dominant. On one play, (Warren) Sapp took the guard in front of
him, ran him down the line 7 yards, and threw him into the
ballcarrier, knocking them both down. I've never seen anything like
that before in this league'' . . . The sale talks on Suffolk Downs
are ongoing. The owners of Suffolk have come back with a
counteroffer. If the buyers take the deal on the table, they can
take over the East Boston track . . . The word is that the Seattle
defensive back the Dolphins torched consistently last Sunday in
their 23-0 victory was former Patriot Chris Canty . . . Don't think
they aren't a little upset in Pawtucket that the Red Sox called up
some of their best players heading into the final weekend, after
which the PawSox lost their final four games to fall out of the
playoff picture. The Red Sox should have left them on the farm
until Pawtucket clinched before bringing them to the big club,
especially if they were going to come to Boston and sit on the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are going to support defenseman Marty McSorley at his
trial in Vancouver later this month. Charges have been brought
against McSorley for using his stick to hit rugged Donald Brashear
in the head in the closing seconds of a game in Vancouver earlier
this year. ``We're going to back him up as much as we can,'' said
Bruins president Harry Sinden. ``We feel the entire story should be
told. There were things that happened in that game before the final
minute that played into what happened.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Will McDonough is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at mcdonough(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
