<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6878 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-U.S.-PIETY-WHEAT     09-08 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-U.S.-PIETY-WHEATCROFT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN EUROPE, POLITICS WITHOUT PIETY 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Saturday, Sept. 9, and thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By GEOFFREY WHEATCROFT    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATH, England _ Across the Atlantic, the role of religion in the
American presidential race has been followed with a mixture of
interest and polite puzzlement. What Europeans find so striking is
not that there is a Jewish vice presidential candidate, but that
Joseph Lieberman wears his piety on his sleeve, just like other
American politicians of recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing so vividly illustrates the gulf between America and
Europe. After all, a Jewish leader is not new for Europe. France
had a Jewish prime minister in 1936, England in 1868, and Spain, of
all countries, in 1835, but none of them _ Leon Blum, Benjamin
Disraeli or Juan Alvarez Mendizabal _ were devoutly observant, as
Lieberman is. Indeed, Disraeli had been baptized as an
Episcopalian, just like Barry Goldwater.
</P>
<P>
   Europe is the cradle of institutional Christianity, but today,
institutional religion in Europe is on the point of collapse. Fewer
than one French person in 10 goes to church even once a year, and
the Roman Catholic church has never been less influential in the
life of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In my country, we have a Church of England ``by law
established,'' with the queen as its supreme governor. And its
services are now regularly attended by a mere 2 percent of the
population. So it goes across Europe; the collapse of organized
Christianity, for better or worse, can be seen from Ireland to
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Of the advanced industrial world, only in the United States does
religion thrive. Polls have shown that a remarkable 40 percent of
Americans claim to worship in various churches, synagogues and
mosques.
</P>
<P>
   This gulf is reflected in politics on either side of the
Atlantic. European politicians invoke God rarely if at all, and not
many of them even pretend to be personally devout. Tony Blair is a
High Episcopalian who often goes to Mass with his Catholic wife,
but he is an exception. Indeed, only a minority of British prime
ministers in the 20th century could be called Christians in any
serious sense. Winston Churchill, for example, went to church on
formal occasions, but was privately agnostic.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the days when European statesmen were more often
privately inspired by faith, as Gladstone and Bismarck were in
their different ways, they did not parade their religious devotion,
as this year's presidential candidates have all felt obliged to do.
The only one who didn't was Bill Bradley, and look where it got
him.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when an American politician could have publicly
echoed the Italian nationalist Cavour's phrase about ``a free
church in a free state.'' He might even have privately agreed with
H.L. Mencken that you respect the other guy's religious faith in
the way you respect his belief that his wife is beautiful and his
kids are smart.
</P>
<P>
   No longer. Today, Lieberman continually calls on the Almighty
and asserts that religion is the only true basis for morality, a
claim that makes us very uneasy here. George W. Bush, in his guise
as a born-again Christian, excites derision among English
commentators, and so does Al Gore when he says he asks himself,
``What would Jesus do?''
</P>
<P>
   What indeed? What would Jesus do about the budget surplus, China
trade or Sierra Leone? The gospels provide remarkably little
guidance about practical conduct, certainly not in military or
economic matters.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt European bafflement at American religiosity has
overtones of condescension toward American cultural
``backwardness,'' a condescension that often thinly conceals envy
and resentment. But in this case, the cynical Old World may have a
point.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of preaching, Lieberman could simply say, ``I take my
religion from the Torah and my politics from America.'' He could
recognize that plenty of unbelievers lead highly moral lives and
that some religious people don't. He might reflect on what his
people went through in vehemently religious societies. He might
note that his political career, like those of Disraeli and Blum,
has benefited from the defeat of political sectarianism.
</P>
<P>
   And instead of saying that he is going to keep doing what he
does because he believes it's the American way, he could
acknowledge that the free exercise of religion is truly part of
American way _ and one of the blessings of a free, open and secular
society.
</P>
<P>
   (Geoffrey Wheatcroft is the author of ``The Controversy of Zion:
Jewish Nationalism, the Jewish State, and the Unresolved Jewish
Dilemma.'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
