A6881 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-NIXON-BIOGRAPHY-ADVIS     09-08 0348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIXON-BIOGRAPHY-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: ``The Arrogance of Power: The Secret World
of Richard Nixon,'' written by former BBC journalist Anthony
Summers with Robbyn Swan, is an exhaustive investigation of the
life and career of the 37th president of the United States. In
researching the book, Summers conducted more than a thousand
inteviews and drew on hundreds of thousands of documents. The New
York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer three excerpts from the
biography, each about 1,100 words in length. NORTH AMERICAN RIGHTS
ONLY. For purchase information, please contact DEBRA WEYDERT in New
Jersey at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)
</P>
<P>
   NIXON-BIOGRAPHY-EXCERPT1 _ Outwardly Pat Nixon gave every
indication that she was the perfect politician's wife. Inwardly,
however, she was miserable: she hated public life and campaigning.
Richard Nixon was cold and dismissive toward her, and associates
never saw any signs of affection. This excerpt describes their
troubled relationship, punctuated by accounts of abuse, on occasion
allegedly physical. 1,100 words. NORTH AMERICAN RIGHTS ONLY.
</P>
<P>
   NIXON-BIOGRAPHY-EXCERPT2 _ This excerpt describes how winning
the preidency changed Richard Nixon. He lavishly redecorated the
White House living quarters, and set up nine separate offices, all
with expensive communication systems, yet kept a very leisurely
work schedule. As former Republican Party chairman Len Hall put it,
Nixon became ``regal, kinglike. ... He loved power, power to sit in
the Oval Office and just issue orders. ...'' 1,100 words. NORTH
AMERICAN RIGHTS ONLY.
</P>
<P>
   NIXON-BIOGRAPHY-EXCERPT3 _ This excerpt describes how, in 1968,
the founder of the Dreyfus Fund gave Richard Nixon a large quantity
of the prescription drug Dilantin, which Nixon began taking without
a doctor's supervision. In 1974, as his presidencey deteriorated,
Mr. Summers recounts how Nixon's aides and advisers took steps to
ensure that an increasingly erratic president didn't compromise
national security. 1,100 words. NORTH AMERICAN RIGHTS ONLY.
</P>
