<HEADER>
A6888 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-08 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGION COLUMN: SECULAR HUMANISTS OFFER ALTERNATIVE TO
NON-BELIEVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Health care, education and the military have all been
_ not surprisingly _ major topics in the current presidential
campaign. But then so, too, has personal religious belief.
Certainly, a series of declarations by major candidates have made
it seem so, as when Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican
presidential nominee, said that belief in Christ had changed his
life and when Sen. Joseph Lieberman, the Democratic vice
presidential nominee, delivered a speech about the value of
religious belief in public life.
</P>
<P>
   It has made some defenders of church-state separation uneasy.
And a couple have even worried that all this talk of faith leaves
non-believers feeling like outsiders. According to polls, this is
not a small group in a nation of more than 270 million people. At
least 5 percent of Americans claim no belief in a deity; nearly
three times that number say they have no religious preference or
affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   But their presence is not always obvious _ unless, that is, an
organized group shows up, like several hundred secular humanists
who have come to New York this weekend for a conference declaring
that one can affirm values and culture that originated in a
particular religious faith, in this case, Judaism, without having a
need to believe in God.
</P>
<P>
   The conference is the International Federation of Secular
Humanistic Jews, an association of organizations in Europe, Israel,
North and South America and Australia. It recently established a
small headquarters in New York, but its previous meetings have been
held overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The New York event began Friday night at Cooper Union, with
speakers ranging from the poet laureate Robert Pinsky to the film
director Lawrence Kasdan. But in an interview beforehand, two of
the federation's leaders voiced concern that some who might want to
belong to a community of secularists (just as religious believers
might want to join a church or synagogue) may be unaware that such
opportunities exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think many people don't know that there's a place to go,''
said Myrna Baron, the federation's newly appointed executive
director and also founder of the City Congregation, a humanistic
Jewish group in New York. The word ``humanism,'' she said, does not
translate into all languages (modern Hebrew being one of them) but,
in her experience, those who wear the label of humanistic Jews
share an interest in human dignity, human rights and the study of a
Jewish heritage that emphasizes its human contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Baron was accompanied by Felix Posen, a co-chairman of the
federation who lives in Great Britain. ``What we're interested in
is to give the extra option,'' he said. By that, he said, he meant
a Jewish identity distinct from that offered by religious
organizations. The constituency of the secular communities, he
said, would be those who agreed with a phrase he attributed to the
philosopher Sir Isaiah Berlin: ``I'm tone-deaf as far as God is
concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Baron brought along a copy of ``Sh'ma,'' an independent journal
of Jewish opinion, which devoted its June issue to the subject,
with articles by Rabbi Sherwin T. Wine, founder of both the
federation and the humanistic Jewish movement in the United States,
and Yehuda Bauer, an Israeli scholar of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our movement is secular because its focus is on the pleasures
and pains of this world,'' Wine wrote. ``It is humanistic because
it finds the source of power for solving problems in human beings
and because it sees the meaning of Jewish history in the Jewish
defiance of an unjust world.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer wrote that for him, God's existence after the Holocaust,
in which 1.5 million children were killed, was ``impossible from a
moral point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   The journal provided space, too, for theological replies. Rabbi
Marcia Prager, an official of a Jewish renewal organization, wrote
that one can draw a lesson from the mystical teachings of Jewish
Cabala: ``It is perhaps the ultimate testimony to the magnificence
of the Divine love that God is willing to create and sustain a
universe in which God's own Presence is hidden, in which God's own
existence can be denied, in which God can be abandoned.'' And Rabbi
David A. Teutsch, president of the Reconstructionist Rabbinical
College, wrote: ``When we do not feel the presence of the Divine,
living Torah keeps God present nonetheless.''
</P>
<P>
   Posen said that he and others in the federation hope to develop
educational materials for children and adults who want to study
Judaism as culture, rather than religion. ``I'm starting a huge
literary project of cultural Judaism,'' Posen said, citing one such
project. He said the work already had scholarly advisors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will divide history into seven or eight periods, starting
with the Torah,'' he said. The project will range well into the
modern era, so that much of its attention will be on recent Jewish
cultural contributions. Placing his palms about two feet apart to
indicate several volumes of books, Posen said, ``If it is this
size, more than half of it will be the last 150 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
