<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6889 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-END-LETTING-GO0910-CO     09-08 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-END-LETTING-GO0910-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    When faced with a loved-one's death, resources may help
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Talking about death and dying with a parent or
other loved one can be frightening for even the closest of
families. But the subject must be broached if the needs and wants
of the dying person are to be met, and to give them peace of mind.
</P>
<P>
   The best time, of course, to talk about end-of-life issues is
before a crisis occurs, when heads are clear and there is still
time to plan.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing what your family member wants ahead of time can prepare
you to be an advocate for their wishes at the end of life.
</P>
<P>
   Key topics for families to discuss include:
</P>
<P>
   _ When would you want medical treatment to offer comfort rather
than prolong life?
</P>
<P>
   _ Who would you want to make your health-care decisions if you
could not speak for yourself?
</P>
<P>
   _ What are your religious, cultural or philosophical beliefs
about death and dying?
</P>
<P>
   _ How do you want to live at the end of your life?
</P>
<P>
   To help guide your family discussion, Sacramento Healthcare
Decisions, (916) 484-2485, has published a booklet called ``Finding
Your Way: A Guide for End-of-Life Medical Decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the topic has been aired, families need to act.
</P>
<P>
   _ Draw up a living will or an advance directive. Discuss this
with the family member's doctor or other advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Gundersen Lutheran's Programs for Improving End-of-Life Care,
(800) 362-9567 ext. 5279, offer an information packet called
``Respecting Your Choices'' that includes tools for completing
advance directives. For state-specific advance directive forms,
contact Partnership for Caring: America's Voices for the Dying at
(800) 989-9455, or www.choices.org.
</P>
<P>
   _ Before it's too late, ask a family member or friend to tell
you about memorable events in his or her life. Retelling life
stories and documenting them in writing or on tape can ease the
dying process and leave a lasting treasure for loved ones. The
Hospice Foundation of America, (800) 854-3402, offers a publication
called ``A Guide for Recalling and Telling Your Life Story.''
</P>
<P>
   _Visit a sick or dying friend, offer to give a family caregiver
some time to rest, or volunteer to spend an hour or two each week
helping a seriously ill person. To learn more about volunteer
opportunities, call Hospice of Dayton at 256-4490, or visit
www.hospicedayton.org, or contact any of the other hospice
organizations listed below.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seek help if you are grieving or bereaved. Hospice
organizations can help. So can your church or other faith
community. Some funeral homes, including Tobias, also offer grief
counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1929EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6890 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-END-OF-LIFE0910-COX     09-08 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-END-OF-LIFE0910-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    PBS series raises awareness of end-of-life issues
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Dying is not an option, eventually, but to those
of us who don't go quickly, the Grim Reaper does offer some
choices.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital, home or hospice? Resuscitate or terminate? Seek out
new experimental therapies or old friends? Painful alertness or
comfortable sedation? Acceptance or defiance?
</P>
<P>
   Relatively few Americans are aware of those and other choices
they can make as their lives or the lives of loved ones wind down.
More of us are willing to discuss safe sex and unsafe drugs with
our children than to talk with our terminally ill parents about how
they want to be cared for in those last weeks and days, according
to a National Hospice Foundation survey last year of Americans 45
and older.
</P>
<P>
   Only 22 percent of those who lost loved ones to terminal illness
used hospice services in 1998. Physicians often are clumsy or
dumbstruck about end-of-life topics, but research shows that's fine
with most terminal patients and their families. They don't want to
have that conversation either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to create higher expectations in the community when it
comes to care for the dying,'' said Victoria Weisfeld, senior
communications officer of the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation
(RWJF). To that end, the RWJF has been at the forefront of both
researching and raising awareness of the many issues involving
death and dying.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation is a principal sponsor of a six-hour PBS series
running tonight through Wednesday, ``On Our Own Terms: Moyers on
Dying,'' to air from 9 to 10:30 p.m. each night. Bill and Judith
Davidson Moyers follow more than a dozen dying patients and their
families to address options available for the terminally ill, and
the obstacles to making those choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of the series is to make an impact on the way that
we all think about death, and how we can all die better in
America,'' said Dr. Jules Sherman, medical director of Hospice of
Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   There is broad consensus that American medicine is far better at
curing than it is at comforting, whether from physical, spiritual
or emotional pain. The health-care industry should be more
sensitive to the dying, few would argue, and should give more
encouragement to those who want to reconcile old rifts and regrets,
and to stipulate whether doctors should try to restart their hearts
again.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, there are concerns that the growing
``good death'' movement is deceptively glorifying something that is
inherently bad. Or that it is driven as much by saving money as by
relieving pain. Or that there is frightfully little ground between
the right to die and the duty to die. Or that physicians should no
more embrace death than policemen should embrace crime.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton Daily News talked with dozens of local physicians,
nurses, counselors, ethicists, patients and their families about
these end-of-life issues for a series that will run concurrently
with the PBS series. The newspaper series also will look at hospice
care and similar programs based in hospitals or geared for the
indigent.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, we will raise more questions than answers, if
only because many answers are as individual as fingerprints. For
some people, dying on our own terms means fighting all the way.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of local health-care organizations plans to turn the
PBS series into the beginning of a community conversation, said
Sister Carol Bauer, Good Samaritan Hospital's vice president of
mission effectiveness and the chair of the fledgling Greater Dayton
Healthcare Ethics Consortium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to tell the people what they need to be
educated about,'' she said. ``We're hoping this will raise clarity
about what are the key issues that the community wants to talk
about.''
</P>
<P>
   WORDS TO TRY
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the right phrasing can make all the difference in
talking with a sick person.
</P>
<P>
   _ Instead of: ``Dad, you are going to be just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Try: ``Dad, are there some things that worry you?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Instead of: ``Don't talk like that! You can beat this!''
</P>
<P>
   Try: ``It must be hard to come to terms with all this.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Instead of: ``I can't see how anyone can help.''
</P>
<P>
   Try: ``We will be there for you, always.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Instead of: ``I just can't talk about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Try: ``I am feeling a little overwhelmed now. Can we take this
up later tonight?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Instead of: ``What do the doctors know? You might live
forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Try: ``Do you think the doctors are right? How does it seem to
you?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Instead of: ``Please don't give up. I need you here.''
</P>
<P>
   Try: ``I need you here. I will miss you terribly. But we will
get through somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Instead of: ``There has to be something more to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Try: ``Let's be sure we get the best of medical treatments, but
let's be together when we have done all we can.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Instead of: ``Don't be glum. You will get well.''
</P>
<P>
   Try: ``It must be hard. Can I just sit with you for a while?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Source: ``Handbook for Mortals'' by Joanne Lynn, M.D., and
Joan Harrold, M.D. (Oxford University Press, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
