<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NEB-ND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEBRASKA-NOTRE DAME AT THE TOP OF EVERYONE'S GAME DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ You can feel it in the air. You can almost
smell it. You certainly can see it with all the RV's in the parking
lots. And you can certainly see in in the sea of red that has
invaded the Notre Dame campus, reportedly close to 20,000 of them,
most of them without tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, no question about it. Saturday's meeting between No. 1
Nebraska and Notre Dame is a marquee game in a weekend that has a
few of them.
</P>
<P>
   But look around more closely. Listen to the words and the
atmosphere is far different than it was back in 1993 when No. 1
Florida State came to town.
</P>
<P>
   Back then it was a battle of equals, in which Notre Dame was
more equal for a week.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time. And that's what's strange. Notre Dame is an
underdog. A big one and the Irish are saying the things that
underdogs stay, starting with Irish coach Bob Davie, who earlier
this week talked about Notre Dame aspiring to get to the level of
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Davie was speaking the truth, of course. Notre Dame wants to be
like Nebraska, like Florida State. Like the big boys.
</P>
<P>
   Now just think about that for a minute. This is Notre Dame.
Rockne and Leahy and Parseghian. The Gipper. The Golden Dome.
</P>
<P>
   But people don't think Notre Dame can win. Just make it
respectable is the hope of even the most devout Subway Alumni.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish players _ fed by Davie who fired them up at a pep
rally in Notre Dame Stadium Friday night _ are taking strength the
underdog role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a respect game,'' said Notre Dame linebacker Anthony
Denman. ``People across the country are writing us off, saying that
we're going to get blasted. They're basing that on last year. They
don't know what we have inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Or outside, which is the problem. On paper, it does look like a
mismatch in a lot of areas. Nebraska, which is making its first
regular season appearance against the Irish in 52 years, looks
stronger in a lot of areas. Along both lines of scrimmages. At
quarterback where Eric Crouch has Heisman potential, while Notre
Dame's Arnaz Battle has only potential, with one game experience as
a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska also has talented I-back in Dan Alexander and a
dangerous wide receiver in Bobby Newcombe, the former Husker signal
caller until Crouch supplanted him.
</P>
<P>
   In last week's 49-13 romp past San Jose State, which was nothing
more than a glorified controlled scrimmage for the Huskers, Crouch
ran for three touchdowns and passed for another.
</P>
<P>
   But San Jose State is not Notre Dame. And Nebraska is not Texas
A&AMP;M, which bowed to Notre Dame, 24-10, last week.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska may very well be the best team this season. The Huskers
make a strong statement of being the best team of the last decade
with three national championships and an 82-8 record in eight
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The X factor is the Notre Dame mystique, especially at Notre
Dame Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska fans as well as Notre Dame fans were informed _ if they
didn't already know _ that No. 1 Miami came here ranked No. 1 in
1988 and left with a 31-30 loss; and Florida State invaded Notre
Dame Stadiuim ranked No. 1 in 1993 and were hit with a 31-24 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Logic says that Nebraska is better and will survive this weekend
of early September madness.
</P>
<P>
   Tradition and the mystique that surrounds this place _ even when
the spiral is downward as last year's 5-7 record indicated _ says
something strange might happen this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why this game is so intriguing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1932EDT &QL; 
