<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TORONTO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD INVADES TORONTO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ERIC HARRISON 
C. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
TORONTO _ Movies stars. Paparazzi. Why, we could almost be in
Hollywood.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every September for 10 days, Toronto turns into Los Angeles
without the ... well, without a lot of things _ killer smog,
massive traffic jams, a debilitating fear of downtown and of
walking. OK, so there's no comparison. Still, while the annual
Toronto International Film Festival is going on, some call this
city Hollywood North. And, at times, it's almost possible to
believe it.
</P>
<P>
   Times like now.
</P>
<P>
   It's the festival's opening night, and the waterfront teems with
beautiful people, almost 4,000 by some counts. A massive line of
Canadians has formed to get into the gala outdoor party. At least,
it's assumed they're Canadians and not Californians, since none of
them seems to know that nobody who's anybody (begin ital) ever (end
ital) waits in line.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the fence, past security, a rhythm and blues band is
playing, though few people are paying attention. They're lining up
for food and drinks, or else they're gawking. Or, more precisely,
they're looking for someone to gawk at.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Gere, Gwyneth Paltrow, Robert De Niro, Al Pacino, Alec
Baldwin and Sarah Jessica Parker are among the stars said to be in
town. But except for a stray Canadian movie director or an actress
few people south of the border have heard of, the big names are
partying in the VIP tent, shielded from the little people. Maybe
this (begin ital) is (end ital) like Los Angeles after all.
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto festival, which kicked off Thursday, is celebrating
its 25th year. Started in 1976 by a real estate lawyer and local
impresario with nine filmmakers and actors in attendance and 127
films from 30 countries, it now has grown to the second most
important international festival behind Cannes. Nearly 2,500 film
industry representatives are here this year; 329 movies will be
shown from 56 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Like all of the big film festivals, it pretty much reflects what
the film industry is all about _ commerce, glitter and art.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto is considered by many who work in Hollywood, at least
among those who actually (begin ital) like (end ital) movies, to be
the best festival to go to because of the balance it has struck.
Films are shown here from around the world _ Europe, Latin America,
Asia, Africa _ and there is an emphasis on film as art. But at the
same time, it's a congenial place to do business.
</P>
<P>
   The trade publication Variety blew an ill wind in this direction
with a story on the eve of the event bemoaning the earnings
fall-off for ``specialty films,'' the kind of small movies that
tend to dominate festivals. But Hollywood interest in Toronto has
never been higher _ especially since so many movies in recent years
(including ``American Beauty,'' ``The Red Violin,'' ``To Die For''
and ``Shine'') have gone on to acclaim and commercial success. The
presence of all the stars is one indication of that.
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate its silver anniversary, festival organizers have
commissioned 10 short films inspired by the festival. It also is
showing movies from the festival's inaugural year, including
``Cousin, Cousine;'' ``Dersu Uzala;'' ``Harlan County, U.S.A.;''
and ``Grey Gardens.'' The anniversary also seems to have inspired
an inward gaze on the part of festival organizers; a number of the
most visible films being showcased reflect on the industry itself
and on the nature of celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stardom,'' the opening-night movie, is about a teen-age
fashion model who zooms to spectacular international success but
who, in the glare of the spotlight, loses her identity in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   One of the movies receiving a warm critical reception is ``State
and Main,'' David Mamet's story of a film crew that plops down in a
small Vermont town and turns life around for the inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duets,'' starring Paltrow, is about nobodies in the Midwest
who find fulfillment on the karaoke stage, where for the length of
a three-minute song, they become stars.
</P>
<P>
   At a private party before the opening-night gala for his movie,
Denys Arcand, the director of ``Stardom,'' noted the irony _ his
movie was about the very phenomenon he was experiencing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media, the cameras, the stars. The people here will not be
disoriented when they see (the movie),'' he told reporters. ``It's
the same subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Mamet's movie, which stars Baldwin, Parker, William Macy and
Philip Seymour Hoffman, steps away from the seriousness of his
recent stage and film work. It pokes fun at the insincerity and
foibles of movie people confronting crisis after crisis in a remote
village where even old farmers know the current market share of
Warner Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to see the characters spout venom and slurs through
their fake smiles and witness their oily machinations without being
reminded of another movie showing at the festival, ``The
Contender,'' starring Jeff Bridges, Joan Allen, Christian Slater
and Gary Oldman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Contender'' is about politics _ not show business _ but as
``Wag the Dog'' showed, there doesn't seem to be much difference.
Allen plays a woman tapped to replace the sitting vice president,
who has died in office. But her nomination is threatened when
photos that possibly show her engaged in a college orgy come to
light.
</P>
<P>
   The politicians in the movie spin fictions and alter truth in
much the same way the moviemakers in ``State and Main'' do.
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto festival was started in 1976, at a time when the
American film industry was undergoing fundamental and cataclysmic
change. For a brief period in the 1970s, then-young film auteurs
such as Martin Scorsese, Altman, Francis Ford Coppola and Peter
Bogdanovich used film in much the way a writer would use a pen, to
make personal statements. But then Hollywood caught blockbuster
fever after the success of ``Jaws'' and ``Star Wars'' in rapid
succession in 1975 and 1977.
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto festival, and the films it discovered and promoted,
ran counter to the big-budget-blockbuster trend. In recent years,
with the new emphasis in Hollywood on independently financed and
produced movies, the festivals have risen in importance.
</P>
<P>
   This summer's drop in box office for specialty films
notwithstanding, the Toronto festival is secure. Since 1976, 291
movies screened in Toronto have won Oscar nominations, and each
year Hollywood comes calling.
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to pass up the opportunity to snatch up the next
``Blair Witch Project'' or ``Life Is Beautiful,'' both of which
came out of the festival circuit. No one can resist the call of
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   XXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
