<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6899 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-PRIMARY-ART-NYT &LR;      09-08 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PRIMARY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCUSATIONS OVERSHADOW ISSUES IN DIVISIVE BRONX CONTEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT24 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ First came the tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   In just one afternoon in a week that he will not soon forget,
Larry B. Seabrook saw his race for Congress rocked by a tabloid
revelation that he had filed joint tax returns even after he and
his wife were divorced. There was the added tidbit that both
Seabrook, a state senator from the Bronx, and his former wife
maintained that they were unaware of their divorce until years
after it became official. The day wasn't done yet, and neither was
his opponent, who accused the senator of breaking the law and
called for a criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In that same tumultuous week that Seabrook went on to accuse his
opponent, U.S. Rep. Eliot L. Engel, of being so conniving and
desperate to win re-election that he had illegally obtained the
information from sealed divorce records and leaked it to the news
media.
</P>
<P>
   Seabrook then took his complaints to the doorstep of Engel's
office, holding a news conference to accuse his opponent of a list
of misdeeds. But Seabrook was ultimately upstaged by a woman who
brought the news conference to a screeching halt by falling to the
ground and screaming incoherently about being Seabrook's wife. That
sent a frightened Seabrook dashing from the scene, fearful, he
said, that the woman might have been carrying a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this primary battle in the 17th Congressional
District, which includes parts of the Bronx and some of Westchester
County, is not your typical political contest. With a seemingly
endless stream of vitriol, the campaign has provided voters with a
box-seat view of charges of racism, anti-Semitism, sabotage,
malfeasance and political betrayal, not to mention enough
revelations about Seabrook's marital woes to provide a season's
worth of soap opera scripts.
</P>
<P>
   Engel, a 53-year-old white incumbent, is working feverishly to
get re-elected in a district whose demographics have shifted
dramatically, from the mostly white electorate that first sent him
to Congress 12 years ago to its current overwhelmingly black and
brown majority.
</P>
<P>
   Seabrook, 49, a black state senator, has invoked the theme of
black political empowerment in a campaign that has been marred by a
string of embarrassing revelations that have portrayed him as
acting injudiciously at best _ and illegally at worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a pretty thing to watch,'' said J. Philip Thompson,
a professor of political science at Columbia University. ``The
effect of all this activity has been to push issues completely out
of the campaign.'' When Engel first won the seat in 1988, the 17th
Congressional District was about 60 percent white; now it is only
about 22 percent white, with the balance being mostly black and
Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Seabrook has criticized Engel as an inattentive
incumbent who spends far more time at his home in Maryland than in
the district. If elected, Seabrook would be the first black
congressman to represent the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   As Seabrook was busy putting together his campaign, Engel's
aides were busy collecting damaging information on Seabrook. They
chronicled, for example, Seabrook's poor attendance record in the
State Senate and gathered records indicating that Seabrook sought
reimbursement for travel expenses to Albany for more days than the
Senate was in session.
</P>
<P>
   Engel and some of his supporters also suggested that, in
appealing to black pride, Seabrook had injected race into the
campaign in a bold and racist appeal to black voters.
</P>
<P>
   The next shoe to drop came when Seabrook, who has long had an
arm's-length relationship with the party, was suddenly endorsed by
its chairman, Assemblyman Roberto Ramirez, a move that some Engel
supporters charged was anti-Jewish. Engel lent his own voice to
that view, even suggesting that Hillary Rodham Clinton was harming
her standing with Jewish voters by not supporting him ( Clinton has
refused to take sides in contested Democratic primary races).
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the race has split Democrats in the district
and beyond. Engel has been endorsed by former Mayor Ed Koch, as
well as the Democratic Party organization of Westchester County.
Seabrook has been endorsed by the Rev. Al Sharpton, as well as most
Democratic officials in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eliot Engel offers nothing to the people of this district,''
Seabrook said. ``To those of us who live here, he is a ghost.''
</P>
<P>
   Engel has a ready retort. ``Larry Seabrook is the biggest
scofflaw in the New York State Legislature,'' the congressman said
this week. ``He is the one going around saying that he should be
elected because he is black. He started this campaign on a negative
note.'' ''
</P>
<P>
   Engel has denied having any responsibility for disseminating
information about Seabrook's taxes or his divorce. Still, it is
clear that many voters, particularly black and Hispanic ones in the
district, find that difficult to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Many other voters, particularly white ones, see Seabrook as a
divisive figure, more inclined to rely on race than merit in
presenting himself to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people in this area believe he is running for the wrong
reason,'' said Assemblyman Jeffrey Dinowitz ``And that reason is
simply demographics.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this has made this peculiar campaign something that many
politicians and voters are already lamenting, despite the
uncertainty of its outcome. ``This race has been mostly about mud
slinging,'' said the Rev. Hillary Gaston, the pastor of the
Parkchester Baptist Church. ``Neither one of them has put forth a
meaningful agenda that would excite anyone. People want to know,
`What are you doing for our community?'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
