<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6900 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-TOBACCO-SECRETS-BOS &LR;      09-08 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SECRETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SAYS TOBACCO DISCLOSURE LAW GIVES AWAY SECRETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A federal judge has struck down the state's
first-in-the-nation tobacco disclosure law, ruling that it forces
tobacco companies to give away valuable ``trade secrets'' by
ordering them to reveal the ingredients in cigarettes and other
tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
   In a 40-page decision dated Thursday and released Friday, US
District Judge George A. O'Toole Jr. wrote that ingredients added
to cigarettes, snuff, and chewing tobacco ``produce distinctive
flavors, tastes, and aromas which vary from brand to brand and are
a reason why consumers choose one brand over another.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Toole concluded that the 1996 Disclosure Act violates the
constitutional rights of tobacco companies because it would force
them to reveal ingredient formulas that cost millions of dollars to
develop and have been kept secret.
</P>
<P>
   The law, which requires companies to identify the ingredients in
each brand ranked ``in descending order according to weight,
measure or numerical count,'' would make it easier for competitors
to duplicate another company's popular brand and steal business
from them, O'Toole concluded.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that the state was aiming to promote public
health by advising consumers of the contents of cigarettes, O'Toole
concluded it was impossible to predict how much protection the
disclosures would provide to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is good reason to think that much, if not all, of the
hoped for benefit could be achieved by disclosure requirements
tailored to avoid the loss of trade secrets . . .,'' O'Toole wrote,
noting that federal law calls for general disclosure of the
contents of tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
   The decision drew sharp criticism from antismoking advocates who
have made Massachusetts a national leader in tobacco education and
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on this decision, we know much more about what's in a
box of cereal than in a package of cigarettes,'' said Dr. Howard
Kho, commissioner of the Massachusetts Department of Public Health.
``We're talking about a product that causes over 10,000 deaths a
year in Massachusetts and it's astonishing that we are trying to
protect any secrets about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers should have a right to know what's in a product that
causes so much suffering and death.''
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure law has been on hold since it was passed in 1996
after all of the major tobacco companies filed suit against the
state's attorney general and public health department. The
plaintiffs in the case include Philip Morris, R.J. Reynolds, Brown
&AMP; Williamson, Tobacco Corp., Lorillard, and US Tobacco Co.
</P>
<P>
   Brendan McCormick, a spokesman for Philip Morris, said, ``We are
certainly pleased that the judge agreed we should be able to
protect propriety brand recipes. We are not opposed to disclosing
ingredients, we are opposed to turning over our propriety brand
recipes.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1986 federal law requires tobacco companies to provide lists
of ingredients in their products to the US Department of Health and
Human Services, but the information isn't made public and doesn't
include a brand-by-brand breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, tobacco companies are required to disclose information
about the ingredients in their products, but the information isn't
shared publicly. And Minnesota has an even narrower law, requiring
tobacco companies to disclose only certain compounds and additives.
</P>
<P>
   McCormick said Philip Morris currently provides information
about the ingredients in each of its brands on its website,
www.philipmorrisusa.com, but protects the secrecy of its recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Tolman, the former state senator who wrote the disclosure
law, said, ``I don't see why the ingredients in cigarettes should
be any more protected than the ingredients in Coca Cola. I'm not
looking for the recipe or the amounts, just the ingredients, like
we know in every food and every drug made in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   While disappointed in the judge's ruling, Tolman noted that the
disclosure law raised public awareness about what is in cigarettes
and prompted one company, Liggett, to voluntarily release a list of
the ingredients in its cigarettes: sugar, menthol, valerian root
etract, cedarwood oil, and more.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Bilafer, a spokesman for Attorney General Thomas Reilly,
said the state hasn't decided yet whether to appeal the decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
