<HEADLINE>
GORE WIDENING LEAD OVER BUSH AMONG WOMEN VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Fixes time reference.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Married, working, and with young children at home,
the Pennsylvania woman who took part in a focus group earlier this
week seemed to sum up George W. Bush's problem with female voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so classic male,'' she told Democratic pollster Celinda
Lake, referring to the Texas governor's proposal to privatize a
portion of Social Security. ``He wants to take your savings and
risk it.''
</P>
<P>
   The most stunning development in the latest, post-Labor Day
round of national polls is Al Gore's grip on women voters.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president not only has erased the advantage Bush held
earlier with women. But with an appeal centered on social and
economic security for working families, Gore also has opened up a
gender gap _ call it a chasm _ that appears to be the biggest since
pollsters first noted this Mars-and-Venus disparity in voting
behavior in the 1980 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   A CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll released Friday shows Gore leading
Bush 57 to 33 percent among female voters, Bush ahead among men 55
to 37 percent, and Gore with a slim overall lead of 47 percent to
Bush's 44 percent. A Reuters/Zogby poll, out Thursday, had Gore
with a 53.6 to 33 percent advantage among women and leading Bush by
5.4 percent overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen anything like it. You have to wonder if it
is going to continue,'' pollster John Zogby said. ``Bush was doing
well among women, even Democratic women, and we have watched that
support dissipate. Bush is not going to get it back unless he
starts talking about issues women care about _ education and health
care.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican pollster Linda DiVall says her newest survey,
completed Thursday night, shows only a 5 percent Gore lead among
women. ``Bush's rating with women is fine,'' DiVall said. However,
she added that to regain the advantage, ``he needs to become more
aggressive and energetic and enthusiastic, and do a better job
contrasting his issues with Gore and exploiting his own ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts agree that Gore has gained the upper hand among women
with both image and issues. First, he largely has neutralized the
so-called character question by declaring his independence from
President Clinton, and indirectly the scandals of his
administration, by picking Senator Joseph I. Lieberman as his
running mate and by dramatizing his strong family values and loving
relationships with his wife, daughters, and mother at the
Democratic National Convention in August.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Gore has made it a point to address women's anxieties
about the fragility of the nation's prosperity with detailed plans
to guard the budget surplus and target tax credits for college
tuition, child care, and long-term care for elderly parents. When
he is not touting his own fiscal prudence, Gore accuses Bush of
wanting to take risks privatizing Social Security and Medicare,
federal programs that disproportionately benefit women.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it is the young, middle-class mother in Pennsylvania, or
the senior citizens she surveys, economist Heidi Hartmann says
women have reason to be risk-adverse: Over their lifetime they
typically earn less than men, have been the first to be laid off,
less likely to receive private pensions, and have not accumulated
savings to invest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Bush has to promise that nobody who is retired,
or near retirement, will have any reduction in Social Security
benefits under his plan creates the concern for many women that
maybe he won't be able to keep his promise,'' said Hartmann,
president of the Institute for Women's Policy Research, a nonprofit
think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Lake says the presidential race could come down to the fight to
capture two key female groups: elderly women, who went Republican
in the 1998 congressional elections and were particularly disgusted
by Clinton's extramarital affair, and so-called ``waitress moms'' _
working mothers, married and single, with some or no college
education _ who now make up 60 percent of the undecided vote.
``Waitress moms are back in charge of the election,'' Lake said.
</P>
<P>
   They are one reason Gore refers so often to ``working families''
in his speeches and has made their concerns central to his
campaign. Gore's proposals for universal preschool, pay equity,
raising the minimum wage, expanding the federal Family and Medical
Leave Act, and giving a five-year Social Security credit to women
who leave jobs to raise children are aimed directly at middle-class
mothers juggling work and family.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the economy is booming, the demands of balancing work and
family gets a little more intense,'' said Dianne Bystrom, director
of the Carrie Chapman Catt Center for Women and Politics at Iowa
State University. ``And women, who tend to be the family
caretakers, turn to government programs when they need a life
preserver.''
</P>
<P>
   In focus groups, women say they expected the economic boom would
allow them to work fewer hours and spend more time with their
children. Instead, a tight labor market, global competition, and
mobile technology are making employers demand more of them and
their spouses. Two recent strikes _ by Verizon Communications
workers in the Northeast and nurses at St. Vincent Hospital in
Worcester _ were fought over the issue of mandatory overtime.
</P>
<P>
   A report titled ``The State of Working America'' released on
Labor Day by the Economic Policy Institute, a liberal think tank,
showed that between 1979 and 1998, the average number of hours
worked by middle-income women, married and with children, increased
from 884 hours to 1,360 hours annually, up roughly 12 weeks a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need to spend money on polls to find out that women,
as well as men, feel they are stretched too thin,'' said Ellen
Bravo, co-director of 9to5, an Milwaukee-based advocacy group for
working women. ``I would be happy to hear what Gore and Bush say
they will do about it. It is a real issue, and it hasn't been taken
up enough, it hasn't been addressed enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday Bush began fulfilling his promise to get closer to ``real
people'' and their issues when he spent more than a hour chatting
and taking questions at a telecommunications-equipment plant near
Pittsburgh. ``This is what I am good at,'' he said. Aides to the
GOP candidate said they expect him to visit with families and
explain how his proposals would benefit them.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is also expected to put renewed emphasis on education, an
issue that won him support from women, and on some of the other
``compassionate conservative'' themes that he stressed at the GOP
convention in Philadelphia _ an event whose program and symbolism
were designed, in part, to broaden the party's appeal among women.
Whether he can regain the lead among women is uncertain. No
Republican presidential candidate has held the advantage with women
voters since 1988, when Bush's father got 50 percent of the female
vote to 49 percent for former Massachusetts Governor Michael
Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, both Bush and Gore have agreed to answer the
question, ``Why should I vote for you?'' when they make separate,
hourlong appearances on the Oprah Winfrey show. Gore will face the
TV show's largely female audience of 22 million on Monday. Bush is
scheduled to appear Sept. 18.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
