<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DEBATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS HE'LL TALK ABOUT DEBATES SCHEDULE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ George W. Bush, less than a week after rejecting
two out of three proposed 90-minute debates in favor of shorter
television talk show face-offs, agreed Friday to renegotiate the
debate schedule as it became clear he and Vice President Gore were
at an impasse on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Gore had said he would debate Bush ``anytime, anywhere'' _ as
long as his opponent also agreed to three 90-minute debates,
including one set for Boston, sponsored by the Commission on
Presidential Debates. Those debates, the standard for the last
three election cycles, are traditionally broadcast on all three
major television networks, guaranteeing the largest possible
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Bush proposed bypassing the first two commission debates in
favor of 60-minute appearances on CNN and NBC. When Gore refused,
Bush accused him of breaking his word, touching off a bitter round
of attacks that culminated in a negative ad questioning Gore's
credibility on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, however, as concerns about the direction of the Bush
campaign mounted in Republican circles, the Texas governor backed
away from his original stance. Without conceding they had
miscalculated in assuming they could cast Gore as a hypocrite, Bush
campaign officials said they were no longer committed to their
original plan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush communications director Karen Hughes even tried to turn the
about-face to Bush's advantage, saying that campaign chairman Don
Evans would call the commission to ``offer to meet with them
anywhere, anytime to discuss with them and the Gore campaign a way
to work out a plan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush is taking the initiative to break this impasse
and make sure the American people will have debates,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came after NBC executives canceled a proposed
debate on a special edition of ``Meet the Press'' next Tuesday
night. Bush had said he would appear solo if Gore did not accept,
but network executives refused to invite him, saying both
candidates would have to be present.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has already agreed to one commission debate, but rejected
two others, the first of which was scheduled to occur in Boston on
Oct. 3. Despite his sudden change of heart, the Boston event
remains unlikely, given Bush's lack of interest in visiting
Massachusetts and his view that the site, because it is adjacent to
the John F. Kennedy Library, has partisan associations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bush's willingness to compromise left both sides hopeful
the two candidates were closer than before to reaching an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we will come to a comfortable and satisfying
compromise, and the debate on the debates will be a non-issue
shortly,'' said Pennsylvania Governor Tom Ridge, who campaigned
with Bush Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Commission on Presidential Debates issued this statement:
``The Bush campaign has accepted the CPD's invitation to meet. We
are working to schedule a meeting with Bush and Gore campaigns
representatives next week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1939EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
