<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MP3?-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERKILL ON MP3 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 10, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judge Jed S. Rakoff went too far last week when he clobbered
MP3.com for allowing owners of compact discs to access their music
on the Internet. The fines he will levy could destroy the company
even though the plaintiff, Universal Music, produced no evidence
that it suffered harm.
</P>
<P>
   Rakoff, sitting in New York federal district court, was acting
on Universal's complaint that MP3 was violating copyright law when
it put Universal's music in a vast database on the MP3.com Web
site. Anyone in possession of a CD could listen to music from that
recording via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com ought to have obtained permission beforehand, and Rakoff
correctly noted that the company was aware of the treacherous legal
ground it was occupying. But the company's intent was not to cut
into sales of CDs, but to enhance its standing among CD owners. The
database was only accessible from January to April, when Rakoff
ordered it taken off the Internet. Since then MP3.com has reached
settlement with four other music companies. Only Universal kept
fighting in court.
</P>
<P>
   Rakoff decided that MP3 should pay $25,000 for each Universal
disc it had copied into the database. Depending on how many this
was, the fine could be as high as $250 million. Rakoff said in his
decision: ``The potential for huge profits in the rapidly expanding
world of the Internet is the lure that tempted an otherwise
generally responsible company like MP3.com to break the law and
that will also tempt others to do so if too low a level is set for
the statutory damages in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com, like many Internet companies, has yet to make any
money. Its stock plunged more than 75 percent in a year and stands
at $6.25 a share. Its settlement with the four other companies will
cost at least $80 million (more depending on how much Universal
gets). The company has set aside $150 million, but if it has to pay
more than that, it may go out of business. By putting the company
at risk, Rakoff does more than deter; he discourages any innovation
that might prompt a lawsuit over copyright.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Napster Web site, where songs are freely traded
without payment, MP3.com is trying to establish a middle ground
that recognizes the popularity of listening to music on line while
acknowledging the property rights of the recording industry.
Universal should be trying to enhance this plan, not cripple the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Universal and other recording companies are experimenting with
online sales, but they remain tethered to a retailing model in
which people physically buy a CD instead of downloading music.
Rakoff, in the guise of protecting a copyright holder, is actually
sustaining an industry. MP3.com will appeal, and Rakoff will hold
another hearing in November. In the meantime, Universal ought to
settle with MP3.com so that the company can continue to innovate.
MP3.com deserved to be slapped down, not threatened with
extinction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1940EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6907 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-MISSILE-BOS     09-08 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MISSILE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DEBATE ON MISSILE DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 10, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that President Clinton has bowed to necessity by postponing
any decision to begin construction on a national missile defense
system, his would-be successors owe the American public an honest
debate about missile defense. To clarify crucial security decisions
looming before the nation, Texas Governor George W. Bush and Vice
President Al Gore have an obligation to demystify an issue that has
been too often obscured by misleading slogans and disingenuous
political motives.
</P>
<P>
   On both sides of the dispute about a system that relies on
intercepting warheads outside the earth's atmosphere, politicians
have exhibited a misplaced insouciance toward technical problems
that knowledgeable scientists say are insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Postol, an MIT physicist and missile specialist, has written
a letter to the White House, informing the Clinton administration
that his analysis of test flights shows that the sensors meant to
guide ``exo-atmospheric kill vehicles'' to incoming warheads cannot
discriminate between simple decoys such as Mylar balloons and a
live warhead. Postol also charged that the Pentagon juggled test
data to hide the failure, perpetrating scientific fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Nyra Schwartz, a whistle-blower who supervised testing of the
system at TRW, told the Globe last spring that the technology of
the sensors ``does not work, will not work, cannot work.''
</P>
<P>
   The gist of White House and Pentagon responses to such warnings
has been to say that even if sensors cannot now locate a warhead
among balloons, sooner or later some technological breakthrough
will correct the problem. This amounts to blind faith in the
strategy of muddling through. A similar heedlessness led to the
waste of $60 billion in the futile pursuit of the space-based Star
Wars system that Ronald Reagan propounded.
</P>
<P>
   If Democrats and Republicans alike have been barking up the
wrong tree in the search for a shield against strategic missiles
from Iraq, Iran, or North Korea, their indifference to the laws of
physics may be traceable to their political habits of thought. Some
things, however, may not be spun.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton originally acceded to the Republican clamor for a
national missile defense as a political ploy, proceeding with a
limited system so that Republicans would find it harder to accuse
candidate Gore of being soft on defense. For their part, certain
conservative senators have battened on the public's psychological
craving for absolute security to flog an issue that pollsters
describe as a no-lose proposition.
</P>
<P>
   But science adheres to principles of proof and disproof that
politics cannot bend to its purposes. While partisan politicians
ignore the warnings of independent scientists, the country risks
provoking a new nuclear arms race encompassing China, India, and
Pakistan. In their debates, Bush and Gore should stop acting like
enthusiasts who have not heard the bad news and start discussing
the real advantages and disadvantages of disparate missile defense
approaches, including those that rely on lasers and boost-phase
interception.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 1941EDT &QL; 
