<SLUG> BC-ALLTEL-$ADV10-ART-940&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NOT-SO-LITTLE PHONE COMPANY FROM LITTLE ROCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 10)  
(EDS: In 9th and 10th grafs the words `degree symbol' are
substituted for the superscript circle symbol for the company name
`360(degree symbol) Communications') 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEVE BARNES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ A favorite story of Joe Ford, chairman and
chief executive of the Alltel Corp., involves a real yet proverbial
little old lady. He tells it to every new group of employees.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1948, Alltel, then known as Allied Telephone, bought a
group of tiny independent phone companies in southwest Arkansas,
including one in the hamlet of Amity. ``It had 200, maybe 250
customers,'' Ford recalled. It also had an employee named Edna
Nunn, who, despite being restricted to a wheelchair by childhood
polio, operated the company's manual switchboard, collected all its
bills and handled customer complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Ford became vice president and treasurer of Allied
in 1963, he noticed something odd about the Amity operation.
``Every single bill was paid on time,'' he said. ``Same thing the
second month. Now, that just doesn't happen.'' But it did happen
again the month after that, so Ford drove out to Amity to get an
firsthand explanation from Nunn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' she said bashfully, ``they'll all pay me back.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford uses the story to drive home a central tenet in his
strategy _ that customer service translates into customer loyalty.
From a small regional base, he has built a communications empire
around the idea, one whose modest national profile belies its size
and reach. And if the concept is not necessarily original to Ford,
well, ``I still want to convey that attitude,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Friday, however, Ford seemed equally eager to be
conveyed to Scotland, to start a vacation with his wife after 14
breakneck months of acquisition and expansion at Alltel. The
company now has 10 million communications customers in 24 states,
making it the sixth-largest land-line phone company in the country
and the fifth-largest wireless provider; nearly a million of those
customers have been added since Ford's last vacation in June 1999
(golf in Pebble Beach, Calif.)
</P>
<P>
   Growth by accretion has been the rule since Ford married the
founder's daughter, Jo Ellen Wilbourn, and joined the company as an
advertising salesman in 1959. That year, Allied Telephone reported
a whopping $12,000 in profit.
</P>
<P>
   Through the 1960s and 1970s, most of the company's acquisitions
were of small, independent operators in Arkansas and nearby states
_ like the one that brought Edna Nunn onto the payroll. But that
all changed in 1983 when Ford, by then a senior executive, helped
engineer a transforming merger in which Allied effectively
swallowed Mid-Continent Telephone of Canton, Ohio, a company four
times its size, to form Alltel. Ford became president and chief
executive in 1987 and chairman in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   More big deals followed, culminating in the $6 billion
acquisition in 1998 of 360(degree symbol) Communications, a
wireless operator based in Chicago with 2.6 million subscribers. A
smaller deal last year _ $1.8 billion for Aliant Communications of
Lincoln, Neb. _ brought the total number since Ford joined the
company to more than 250.
</P>
<P>
   Other independent phone companies have also expanded by gobbling
up their peers, large and small, but few have transformed their
businesses quite as sweepingly. The 360(degree symbol)
Communications deal was ``the seminal event for the company,'' said
Eric Strumingher, a telecommunications analyst at PaineWebber,
because it made Alltel as much a wireless company as a land-line
phone utility; last year, wireless operations provided 42 percent
of Alltel's $6.3 billion in revenue and 52 percent of its $1.62
billion in operating income.
</P>
<P>
   The two businesses are closely integrated. ``While others are
talking about bundling of services and being a company that
provides one-stop shopping, Alltel is, of all the large companies,
the only one executing that strategy well,'' Strumingher said.
``There's no other company I know of at its size or larger that has
completely torn down the structural barriers that exist between
wireless and hard-line business.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's growth has not come cheaply. In some deals, Ford
said in an interview, he has agreed to pay as much as $1,100 a
customer _ a price that he regards as a sharp premium, but one that
market conditions forced on him. ``Everything I've ever bought, I
always thought I paid too much for,'' he said with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   But the math has always turned out all right, he quickly added:
``We've worked through everything we've paid.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to giant rivals like the former Bell companies,
which usually turn for capital to the big financial center banks
and Wall Street houses, Alltel has financed much of its growth
through a Little Rock neighbor that shares its tendency to fly
under the radar of its rivals: Stephens Inc., the brokerage and
investment banking firm. The Stephens Group, the family-owned
parent holding company of Stephens, is also Alltel's largest
shareholder, with a stake valued at about $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's personal ties to the Stephens family are three decades
old; he and his wife are close friends of Jackson Stephens,
chairman of Stephens, and Ford's youngest son, Scott, 38, worked
for Stephens for a decade before becoming an executive at Alltel.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The changing industry landscape has helped open the way for
Alltel. ``Deregulation changed it all,'' Ford said. ``Competition
replaces regulation.'' But he wondered whether the government's
grip has relaxed enough. ``The FCC, to my mind, is still too much
of a regulator,'' he said. ``They've been doing too much `social'
regulation as opposed to economic regulation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford's other main public policy concern is education. ``I think
it's pretty serious when some youngster comes out of high school
and really can't read or write,'' said Ford, whose father was a
state education commissioner for many years. Without adequate
schooling, he said, people cannot take full advantage of Internet
access, a market he has positioned Alltel to penetrate,
particularly through wireless services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the thing that's out there,'' Ford said. ``I'm convinced
people are going to be more on the go in the future than they have
been in the past. They want access to information and we want to
give it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Alltel took a big step toward that goal with a deal
it struck earlier this year with Verizon Communications, swapping
$600 million in cash and some of Alltel's wireless properties in
the Midwest and Northeast for Verizon's in Ohio and in Sun Belt
states from Arizona to Florida. Alltel gained 700,000 customers in
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Colette Fleming, an analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in New
York, said the deal was shrewd for the company, even though by
widening its service area it is increasing the proportion of its
calling volume that will not generate roaming charges, the fees
that callers pay when using their phones outside their own
company's territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any short-term hit they're taking in earnings due to reduced
roaming revenues is necessary to position them for the long term,''
Fleming said.
</P>
<P>
   The company told analysts last Thursday that 2001 earnings would
indeed fall short of the $3.26 a share that they had been
expecting, and that $3 to $3.10 was more likely. But Bruce Behrens,
who manages the Flag Investors Communication fund, said Alltel
stock ``ought to be worth a lot more'' than the $50.88 it fetched
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ford will turn 65 in 2002, and expects to retire then. His son
Scott, now chief operating officer, is widely seen as his heir
apparent, but Ford deflects questions about succession, saying
only, ``It's up to the board of directors.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, he is enjoying Alltel's success as much as ever. ``I
think we've hit a stride,'' he said. ``I think it's just a matter
of `keep expanding, keep growing.' I get up every day looking
forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
