<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV10-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVING INTO EINSTEIN'S HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, September 10, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a roomful of profesionals, Eric Maskin would not stand out
except perhaps for his gravity and the the mildness of his mien. He
is 49, somewhat formal. He plays classical clarinet well enough to
have once thought of trying to make his living as a concert
musician, but that is true of any number of professional
scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is the economist Maskin who this autumn is moving into
the house at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, N.J.,
that once belonged to Albert Einstein. And as you would expect,
there is a story in that.
</P>
<P>
   Maskin's appointment was the climax to a long search to replace
Albert Hirschman as the only economist on the faculty of the
storied Institute. Founded in 1930 as a research center where great
minds could pursue their studies without the burden of teaching,
the Institute became a haven to Einstein, mathematicians John von
Neumann and Kurt Goedel, as well as any number of humanists of
similiar seniority in their fields. Promising young scholars visit
for a year at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschman himself is, at least in certain precincts, only
somewhat hard an act to follow than is Einstein. As a Jewish
refugee from Nazi Germany in the 1930s, he spent most of a decade
battling fascism in Italy, Spain, and France, then fled to the
United States and became an influential development adviser to
third world nations for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   After his appointment to the Institute in 1974, he wrote a
series of perceptive and original books which stretched the
conventional boundaries of economics. He is the living symbol of
the humanist approach to the discipline, an action intellectual who
throughout his career rejected the modern tendency to formalism,
politely but firmly.
</P>
<P>
   Maskin is just the opposite. A highly-regarded theorist who
played a key part in the integration of game theory into economics
in the 1970s and 1980s, he continues to use entirely mathematical
tools in his investigations into learning, bargaining and other
topics. So his selection is important for what it says about the
changing place of economic thought in American culture.
Traditionally the Institute's mathematicians and physicists have
disdained economists; humanists have mistrusted them. Hirschman
held his ground with moral authority.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his temperament, Maskin may be the ideal person to
mediate in the little inderdisciplinary hothouse, says a colleague.
The house? It was no part of the recruting bargain, says Maskin.
The home of Einstein's sister-in-law until the mid-'80s, and a
physicist after that, it just happened to be empty when the time
came to move. Maskin had other motives. ``Even at a university as
good as Harvard, you never see the people in the building next door
to your own. The demands of a department are just too great.''
</P>
<P>
   That Princeton was to lure Maskin away from Cambridge -- a
Harvard professor, he had been visiting the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology last year -- reflects the continuing improvement in
the fortunes of economics at that very wealthy university. The
department has recruited several top economists in recent years:
Jose Scheinkman from Chicago, Christopher Sims from Yale, Paul
Krugman from MIT. With Maskin also planning to teach, Princeton
surely now must be considered among the top centers of American
economics, along with MIT, Harvard, Stanford and the University of
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone will applaud the institute's choice. The scene in
France has been enlived this summer by the appearance of a
newsletter of Post-Autistic Economics, aiming to ``link people
wishing to bring sanity, humanity and science back to economics.''
(A translation can be had for the price of a blank e-mail to
pae(long dash)news(at)hotmail.com.) The first issue reported, ``The
French economics mainstream is in a state of shock and apprehension
following dramatic and unexpected events in June.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Ecole Normale Superieure, a leading university, students
had circulated a petition complaining of excessive mathematical
formalization. Le Monde, the Paris daily, took up the cudgel on
their behalf. Some well-known economists _ Daniel Cohen, Jean-Paul
Fitoussi, Michel Vernieres -- expressed sympathy and support.
Education minister Jack Lang promised an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   More indicative of the drift in France, however, may be the fact
that mathematical economists at the Institut Universitaire de
France (who are among the leaders in the world) have begun teaching
their courses in Toulouse in English in order to attract higher
quality international students. Mathematics has become the standard
language of written economics; perhaps the conversion to a verbal
English standard is next.
</P>
<P>
   At the Eighth World Congress of the Econometric Society in
Seattle last month, Maskin gave the first of five featured
lectures. His topic was auctions: the growing excitement among
theorists as economists learn to design auctions which take effect
of the interdependence of values, instead of pretending (as in the
past) that no buyer's private information affects any others'
valuations.
</P>
<P>
   Governments have been conducting such auctions for years, of
course, especially of the rights to the electromagnetic spectrum
for television and radio broadcasts and cell phones. They had been
alerted to the possibilities by theorists such as William Vickrey
and Ronald Coase. Robert Wilson, the Stanford University professor
who introduced Maskin, is a principal in a firm that has made a
fortune serving as consultant on spectrum auctions. But greater
realism in theory means better results in practice, as economists
home in on a better understanding of the intricacies of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Other plenary lectures at the Seattle meetings included Torsten
Persson of Stockholm's Institute for International Economics,
surveying extensive new work on how political institutions shape
market outcomes; James Heckman of the University of Chicago on
various grounds for evaluating the effects of policies; Thomas
Sargent of Stanford University on the difficulty of anticipating
all possible outcomes of events; and Elhanan Helpman of Tel-Aviv
University and Harvard University on the nature of lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   Economics is becoming harder, as physics is hard. But this is as
far from autism _ the disregard of external reality _ as you can
get. Economics itself is moving into Einstein's house.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
