<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-ROMNEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD FOES MEET IN A MORMON NEUTRAL GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELMONT, Mass. -- Politics is a Massachusetts blood sport, but
its wounds can heal with time.
</P>
<P>
   That message was reaffirmed Friday at the gleaming Mormon temple
on a Belmont mount, where church activist Mitt Romney led US
Senator Edward M. Kennedy on a tour of the controversial, nearly
completed structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not bad blood; there has not been bad blood,'' Romney
said of his relationship with Kennedy since their bruising US
Senate campaign in 1994. ``We have differing views on a number of
issues, for sure. But as individuals, we certainly respect each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Romney's prominent role in the Mormon Church played a part in
the Senate race. Kennedy and his nephew, then-US Representative
Joseph P. Kennedy II, said then that Romney should be questioned
about the Church's exclusion of women from the clergy and its ban
before 1978 against black clergy.
</P>
<P>
   A quick, negative backlash stung the Kennedys, and Joseph
Kennedy apologized for saying, incorrectly, that Mormons continued
to ban blacks from the clergy. The role of religion in the
remainder of the campaign was put to rest -- publicly, at least.
</P>
<P>
   Friday afternoon, any lingering aftertaste from that delicate
but explosive issue appeared to have been long washed away, with
Kennedy praising the ``magnificent'' architecture of the temple and
the zeal of its missionaries. The senator even said he believes the
temple should be allowed to build a 139-foot spire that neighbors
have blocked in Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``If other churches are going to have their expressions in terms
of spires, this one should as well. What's fair is fair,'' Kennedy
said. The Belmont temple has brought its case to the state Appeals
Court.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting of the former rivals, only their second since the
campaign, may have further undercut the sputtering, renegade bid by
Jack E. Robinson to unseat Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Romney Friday declined to endorse Robinson, a fellow Republican
who has been unable to secure any backing from the state's GOP
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know him. I haven't met him, haven't heard from him.
I'm living in Utah now,'' said Romney, who was summoned after a
corruption scandal to be chief executive of the 2002 Winter
Olympics, which is planned for Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, too, shied away from giving Robinson any recognition.
When asked if he would debate his challenger, Kennedy answered
instead by thanking Romney profusely for inviting him to the
temple.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the tour, Kennedy listened respectfully as Romney and
church elders guided the senator through various rooms where
Mormons will reflect, pray and marry after the temple's dedication
on Oct. 1. He also asked many questions, particularly about the
church's aggressive missionary program in which 60,000 young people
are spreading the faith worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1994 campaign, Romney had been president of the 14
Mormon churches in the Boston area. At the time, he said that an
elected official could be a devout Mormon and also protect the
beliefs of others.
</P>
<P>
   Some voters remained unconvinced. Romney said after the race
that his religion may have contributed to a sense that he was
culturally alienated from the largely Catholic electorate in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Romney also was hurt by the Kennedy's efforts to portray him as
a heartless corporate raider, linking him to the layoffs of 266
union workers in Indiana. Some of the striking workers traveled to
Massachusetts to blast Romney, whose venture capital firm had
acquired the company that laid off the employees.
</P>
<P>
   Romney had not been directly involved in the layoffs, having
taken a leave of absence as chairman of Bain Capital in order to
campaign. But he was slow to respond to the Kennedy attacks, and he
further hurt himself by describing the layoffs as justified
economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Romney reiterated his stance that Mormons can separate
religion and politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally keep three things completely separate: sport,
politics and religion,'' Romney said. ``I have strong faith, but I
don't mix my faith and my sport, or my politics. Instead, I try to
keep those in separate dimensions.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator echoed that sentiment. ``I think President Kennedy
probably said it best: that he wanted to be evaluated as an
American who was Catholic and not as a Catholic president,''
Kennedy added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
