</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-END-OF-LIFE-MAIN0910-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Leaving life gracefully
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANDALIA, Ohio _ The morning after Chuck Gross's 90th birthday
bash, he woke up in severe pain from a fracture in his spine. His
doctor guessed it had been caused by the spread of his prostate
cancer, first diagnosed eight years before. But Gross declined to
be treated or even tested for metastatic disease. He felt the time
had come to leave this life gracefully, and on his own terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't interested in any heroic measures _ no chemotherapy
or anything like that,'' Gross said. ``I figure I'd lived my
lifespan _ over my lifespan. I was on borrowed time.''
</P>
<P>
   Just days before his birthday last December, Gross had been
cooking, cleaning, even driving. So his doctor assumed that his
refusal of treatment meant that he was depressed and prescribed a
mood-enhancing medication. Gross told his family to flush the pills
down the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I've ever been depressed,'' he said. ``I just
knew I didn't want to set any records for longevity.''
</P>
<P>
   Until two generations ago, Americans usually died suddenly after
an acute illness or an accident. But infections and fevers that
once ran their deadly course in a matter of days have been replaced
by chronic illnesses, such as cancer, heart disease and
Alzheimer's, that take months and even years to kill while doctors
and patients fight back with an array of modern medical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, dying for most people has become a process, one that
requires more care and more forethought than ever before. Every
family faces a different set of challenges, and every death has its
own course.
</P>
<P>
   In the mornings when he rises, Gross sits a moment on the edge
of his bed and musters his strength to meet the day. In silhouette,
his curved back and bone-thin legs form a human question mark.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his cancer, Gross also suffers from emphysema, the
result of 65 years of smoking. Just reaching for the phone now can
leave him gasping. At his family's insistence, Chuck quit smoking
four years ago when he first moved into the Vandalia home of his
oldest son, Charlie, and his wife, Susie.
</P>
<P>
   In May, after Gross had grown so thin and weak he needed a
wheelchair, he talked with his three grown sons about his decision
to let go. They agreed to share in his care and promised to keep
him comfortable. In June, they called on Hospice of Dayton, a
nonprofit agency that neither hastens nor postpones death. Its
mission is to keep patients free of pain and their quality of life
as high as possible, to the very end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew he was on the last furlong, and we talked about it
with him,'' said Charlie, 54. ``We knew nothing about hospice,
except that they help people through the death process. And we had
heard nothing but good things about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospices here and around the country began as a volunteer
movement 25 years ago that believed in providing services to ease
the pain and fear at the end of life rather than therapies that
hook patients to machines and isolate them from loved ones. Hospice
founders set out to give dying patients and their families choices,
and to help them face life's inevitable end with dignity, comfort
and hope. Hospice services include patient and family counseling,
specialized nursing care and drugs and supplies for pain relief.
</P>
<P>
   Since the mid-1990s, the hospice industry, which gets nearly $2
billion a year from Medicare, has been forced to operate
increasingly like a business because of government and insurance
constraints. In the past five years, the average number of Hospice
of Dayton patients served in the Miami Valley dropped by a third,
from 324 per day in 1996 to 221 in 1998. Currently, Hospice of
Dayton cares for about 240 patients per day in its inpatient and
home-care programs. While the organization continues to break even,
it drew on $2.8 million in community donations last year to cover
the cost of uncompensated care.
</P>
<P>
   FACING THE INEVITABLE WITH A CLEAR VISION
</P>
<P>
   Steve Gross, Chuck's 51-year-old middle son, said their father
made it easy to get hospice involved early on, before Chuck was in
crisis and while heads in the family were still clear. ``He said
that sounded like a good idea. . . . He knows he only has so much
time left. He's never tried to put a phony face on things.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospice nurse Donna Sweeney, who visits Gross once a week to
check on his symptoms and his medications, said Chuck's
straightforward approach to death, and his sons' forethought in
granting his wishes, aren't typical of American families.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never talk about (death and dying) until it's too late,''
she said. ``We reached some turning point in the 20th century where
we thought, once we were born, we would live forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Gross had been prescribed morphine pills by his physician to
control his pain, but his stomach couldn't tolerate them. Instead,
he was switched to a slow-release Duragesic patch, which lasts
three days. The patch, along with regular doses of the milder
pain-killer Darvocet, have eliminated his pain with few side
effects.
</P>
<P>
   When hospice staff took over Chuck's pain management, Charlie
noted, they were more flexible in their approach. ``The nurse told
us you could put on two patches at once if you needed to . . . and
there's no rigid rule that you have to wait 72 hours to change his
patch,'' he said. ``These hospice nurses really know more about
pain control than the doctors because they deal with it all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Chuck receives visits from a hospice social worker,
a hospice chaplain and a hospice volunteer, all of whom help attend
to his emotional and spiritual needs.
</P>
<P>
   `I'M GOING TO A FAR BETTER PLACE'
</P>
<P>
   End-of-life experts would agree that the Gross family is doing
nearly everything right in supporting Chuck in his decision, but
family stresses and strain are inevitable. In early June, when
Charlie was convinced that he was ``shutting down,'' Charlie and
his brothers spent a 12-hour vigil in Chuck's room until the
feeling passed.
</P>
<P>
   And there have been nights when Chuck has woken in a panic,
overwhelmed with an indescribable dread, a feeling he compares to a
visit from ``the Angel of Death.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He just had a feeling he was going to die and he couldn't
explain it,'' Charlie said. ``Of course, maybe the Angel of Death
was there. Who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   On those nights, Chuck called out for Charlie and asked him to
stay with him and rub his back. On several nights, he asked if
Charlie would sleep in his room.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always says, `Apologize to Susie that I asked you to stay
here,' '' Charlie said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though hospice works to educate families on the warning
signs of impending death, emotions can take over. Charlie and his
brothers twice have called Sweeney when they were convinced their
father was near death. ``The sons went into panic mode. But you can
expect that: They haven't dealt with this before,'' Sweeney said.
She noted that Chuck cared for his wife, Ruth, almost exclusively
during the last two years of her life, shielding his sons from the
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Gross said he is comfortable now and ready to accept the
inevitable. He neither looks forward to nor fears death, he said,
believing ``that when I die I'm going to a far better place than I
am now.'' A Lutheran by faith, he believes in the Resurrection and
looks forward to meeting his past friends and loved ones in the
next life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a place of great peace and joy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck has given power of attorney for medical decisions to
Charlie. His advance directive asks that there be no tube feeding
and no resuscitation efforts and that he be permitted to die at
home _ hopefully, surrounded by his three sons _ rather than in a
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Although he's had good days when he can walk behind his
wheelchair from kitchen to bedroom, Chuck mostly sits and conserves
his strength. His small sitting room has been dubbed ``the Ferndale
room,'' since it is furnished with a well-worn recliner, an old
clock and other beloved items from the family's Ferndale Avenue
home, where Chuck lived for 46 years. The room has a window that
looks out to a neighbor's gazebo and a small wooded lot. He likes
to watch the treetops swaying in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think I'd get bored sitting here and doing nothing, but
I really don't,'' he said, his hands clasped behind his head. ``The
Lord made me a good sitter. There's an art to good sitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember that cartoon guy, the one that always said, `What, me
worry?' I guess that's it. I don't worry about anything. There's
very little in the world you can change, so why not accept it and
not worry. I guess that's my philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING BACK ON LESSONS LEARNED
</P>
<P>
   Gross credits a strong religious faith for his belief in death
as a transition, but he says he's still left wondering about the
meaning of his long life when so many of his friends and family
members have passed, including his wife of 43 years, Ruth Louise,
who died in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why am I still here? I'm pretty much to the useless point now,
yet I know I'm here for a purpose. I just can't see any. But the
Lord must have some reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Gross quotes a snippet of poetry long ago committed to memory,
some lines he saw on a now-forgotten wall plaque. ``I would not sit
in the scorner's seat, nor hurl the cynic's ban. But let me live in
a house by the side of the road, and be a friend of man. . .''
</P>
<P>
   His sons say their father, a retired accountant who once headed
Dayton's tax division, is facing death with the same grace and
equanimity that he brought to his life. ``Not that he never gets
rattled or doesn't have a bad day, but he doesn't stay there,''
Steve said.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck wasn't always so even-tempered. He remembered a day during
the Great Depression when he discovered the boss's son had gotten a
pay raise while he had taken a cut. ``I was sitting in my boss's
chair, my feet up on his desk, yelling my head off when I fell back
flat on the floor. I was still yelling, with my finger in the air,
when it suddenly dawned on me: Here I was, making all this fuss,
and it won't accomplish a damn thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I try to be more selective in my anger. In fact, I don't
have much anger in me anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Gross says he has no major regrets in his life, although he
never took that ocean cruise he promised himself after spending the
war in an accounting office in East Africa, working for an aircraft
maintenance center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a happy marriage, a good home. I enjoyed my family. I
was basically a happy man at heart,'' he said. ``I guess if I knew
then what I know now I would have gotten more education. But I grew
up at a time when you didn't need a (college) degree to be an
accounting clerk.'' He was among the first graduates from Dayton's
Roosevelt High School in 1928.
</P>
<P>
   `THERE'S NOTHING UNDONE, NOTHING UNSAID'
</P>
<P>
   Charlie and his two brothers say the talks with their father,
and with the hospice staff, have prepared them for their father's
death. ``When he goes, it's going to be OK. We've given him
permission to die,'' Charlie said. ``There's nothing undone,
nothing unsaid.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Gross family has come to accept Chuck's dying so matter
of factly, it may be because they have lived so closely together as
a family.
</P>
<P>
   On Labor Day weekend, the three sons and their children gathered
at Charlie's home in Vandalia, as they do for nearly every holiday.
They fired up the grill for hamburgers and then did what the Gross
family has done at every gathering since the boys were big enough
to bounce a basketball _ played hoops in the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck watches from his wheelchair as his own sons take on the
grandkids _ Kevin, 24; Nate, 22 and Jonathan, 16 _ in what the
youngest son Dave calls a ``grudge match'' between the two
generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've beaten us the last two times, but we still hold the
overall title,'' said Dave, 43. ``And we always will, because we'll
quit before we let them take over.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie compared his childhood memories on Ferndale Avenue to
episodes of ``Leave it to Beaver.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our life was like what so many people make fun of today. We
didn't have much, but we ate well. Our mother was a professional
homemaker. We were a close family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just being together as a family _ that was fun, and still
is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing end-of-life issues with their father is easier, too,
because ``he's still sharp,'' Steve said. ``He's still like he's
always been: he's just Dad. You can be like two adults (with him),
or if you want to talk about something, you can get advice _ like a
son to a father.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck reads mysteries and historical novels, devours crossword
puzzles and can still play a mean game of Trivial Pursuit. ``He's
one of the smartest men I've ever met,'' Charlie said. ``He has a
vast array of what he calls useless knowledge. . . . He still beats
everyone who's on 'Jeopardy ' and 'Wheel of Fortune.''''
</P>
<P>
   TELLING THE TRUTH WITH COMPASSION
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said that Chuck's vital signs have been strong enough
lately that, if he continues to stabilize over the next few months,
he might be discharged from the hospice program. Patients must have
a life expectancy of six months or less to qualify for hospice
services.
</P>
<P>
   But predicting longevity is as much an art as a science, she
said. ``One time it will turn out exactly the way you tell the
family, and the next three times it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Every person reacts differently to their approaching death,
Sweeney said, and in her 8 1/2 years as a hospice nurse, she's seen
the full range, from a 57-year-old woman who made all of her own
funeral arrangements before deciding to end her kidney dialysis and
her life, to a real estate woman in her 50s with end-stage lung
cancer who begged Sweeney ``to help me get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Telling patients the truth in such cases is the only option, she
said, but it has to be done with care. ``Those are the ones where
you take a deep breath and hope you're saying the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, not everything that comes out of our mouth is always
from us. For those who believe it's from God, it's from God,'' she
said. ``You just know when you go off on this progression of words.
You ask yourself, where did that come from? I'm not that clever.
I'm not that smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Gross says the day his brothers and father met with the
hospice team for the first time in June, ``It was strange _ just
the fact that you're sitting down and you're talking about someone
in your midst who is probably going to die in the foreseeable
future. But it was actually a good meeting. We actually laughed a
lot, and once it was over, (Chuck) said he felt really good about
things.''
</P>
<P>
   It was after one of his father's Angel of Death experiences that
Charlie started getting Chuck up in the mornings before going off
to his job as a salesman for RIS Paper in Dayton. Charlie helps his
father dress, brings him a wet rag for washing and combs his hair.
Then he wheels him out to the kitchen, where Chuck usually has a
frozen waffle and tea as he reads the morning paper.
</P>
<P>
   After breakfast on a recent morning, Charlie wheeled Chuck back
to the Ferndale room, watched as he settled into his recliner and
then stooped to give him a big parting hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``See you tonight,'' Charlie said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll miss you,'' said his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay out of the liquor cabinet,'' Charlie teased.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you sell a lot of paper today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd better, or they'll fire me,'' Charlie said.
</P>
<P>
   On his way back to the kitchen, Charlie said, ``When he's having
a tough time, he doesn't want to be alone. You might have to sit
with him more, and he wants to know where you are. You'll ask him,
'Are you hurting?' He'll say no, but he'll say, `My mind is racing
and I'm fidgeting. Just sit with me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he wants to die alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Illich, a hospice volunteer, visits with Gross just to talk,
or not to talk, whichever seems more comfortable at the time. ``He
needs company. So he has a big family? That doesn't mean
anything,'' Illich said. ``You can feel isolated at times even with
a big family.''
</P>
<P>
   The first time he visited Gross, Illich said, ``I thought I had
to talk. I thought Chuck would be upset with me if I didn't say
anything. But the second time I just sat there. I felt comfortable,
and I think Chuck did, too.''
</P>
<P>
   THE AGE-OLD CYCLE COMES AROUND AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   Steve, who helps shower his father and cuts his hair, said Chuck
has made it easier on his sons by accepting their care.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not embarrassed at all by what we do for him,'' Steve
said. ``I told him, `You know you took care of us when we were
little. We'll never be able to return the favor.' And he said, `But
that was different.' I said, `No, it is isn't. It's the same
thing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Dave agreed with his brother. ``It's almost a privilege to be
able to care for him now. It's a way of completing the whole
cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie refuses to use the word ``tied down'' in relation to his
father's care, but he and his wife Susie can't leave him by himself
for long periods. And Chuck needs Charlie's help getting up in the
mornings and going to bed at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's a bit like having a child again,'' Charlie said.
``He told me one night, `Our roles are reversed now.' I told him,
`That may be true, but we'll never catch up. We'll never get even
for all the things you did for us.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's the age-old cycle, Dave said, of love begetting love from
one generation to the next. ``We're all pretty much convinced that
love isn't what you feel, it's what you do,'' he said. ``Our
parents taught us that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
