<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors at publications outside the United States may find the
following stories from the New York Times News Service that are
scheduled for release on  &UR; SUNDAY, &LR;   &UR; Sept. 10, &LR;  of particular
interest. We plan to move these stories by 2 p.m. EDT on Saturday,
Sept. 9.
</P>
<P>
   This budget is prepared from preliminary schedules, and some
stories may later be eliminated or altered; please check the
following budgets for additional information: REVIEW-BUDGET,
SUNDAY-BUDGET, SUNBIZ-FINAL-BUDGET and STYLE-BUDGET.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONEY AND BUSINESS (Will move in ``f'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MITSUBISHI (Normal, Ill.) _ For a short but trying time a few
years ago, this small town made national headlines. Horrifying
stories had emerged about the Mitsubishi auto assembly plant here.
Its factory floor, some workers charged, was one where some men
felt free to grope female workers, to ask them to bare their
breasts or to aim air guns between their legs. The company, while
vehemently denying the charges, nevertheless agreed in June 1998 to
pay a record $34 million to settle the largest federal lawsuit over
sexual harassment. In reality, however, while the headlines have
faded, the problems have not. By Reed Abelson. (With photo and
graphic)
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-BHAMAN-OPPENHEIMER (Undated) _ Ajeev Bhaman was born in
Bombay, has lived in England and was educated in the United States.
As a teen-ager, he traveled the world with his father, the captain
of a cargo ship. So he is not fazed by the travel required in his
job, running the $170.8 million Oppenheimer Developing Markets
fund. His travels have paid off. The fund returned 12.7 percent a
year, on average, for the three years through Sept. 1, putting it
in first place among diversified emerging-markets funds. By Carole
Gould. (With graphic)
</P>
<P>
   OFFICE-POLITICS (Undated) _ With the post-Labor Day political
campaign season now gathering speed, many politically active
workers in corporate America find themselves trying to low-key
their activism on the job _ or at least keep their politicking
below the radar of frowning managers. By Melinda Ligos.
</P>
<P>
   MY-MONEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Finding the job of your dreams _
with the compensation to match _ is not too difficult in the new
economy. Being certain that you will still have it six weeks later
is a different matter. By Catherine Bergart.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEK IN REVIEW (Will move in `a' or `i' categories, as noted) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE-POLITICS-REVIEW (Washington) _ The consensus of
politicians, economists and the public on health policy has shifted
since the 1992 election. Then, the prevailing view was that the
failure of many Americans to have medical insurance posed a serious
national problem. Now, the politicians and economists have come to
believe _ and the public has become convinced _ that the problem is
simply too difficult to solve in one giant stroke. By David E.
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-INSULT-REVIEW (Undated) _ I am used to being around big
news. But observing the story is different than being it. And last
week I seemed to be the story. Gov. George W. Bush spotted me at a
rally in Naperville, Ill. Not realizing the microphones were
working, he told his running mate, Dick Cheney, that I was a
``major league (expletive).'' This was hardly the first time I have
been attacked, though it was the first time the attack accorded me
``major league'' status. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-WARMING-REVIEW (Undated) _ Past climate ups and downs
mostly mesh well with simultaneous natural variations in the
brightness of the sun or the cooling effect of parasol-like plumes
of particles spewed by big volcanoes. But the recent warming,
according to several recent studies, only correlates well with one
thing: the buildup of carbon dioxide, methane and the other
greenhouse gases. The lesson in all of this, according to many
climate scientists, is that no one should expect some alarm bell to
start ringing to conveniently summon societies to take action to
forestall a hot-house future. By Andrea C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-POLITICS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The disagreement over the
proper place of religion in politics summons us once again to the
works of those ever-useful observers of American life, Alexis de
Tocqueville of France and James Bryce of Britain. Both of their
classic studies, Tocqueville's ``Democracy in America'' (1835) and
Bryce's ``The American Commonwealth'' (1888), attend the matter in
a spirit that should elicit an amen from Sen. Joseph Lieberman, who
has rekindled the issue by saying that religion supports a moral
foundation for public policy. By Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   BANNED-APPAREL-REVIEW (Undated) _ Why do politicians focus on
certain types of clothing. And how does a brief bit of fabric cause
so much consternation? Several nations have banned or actively
discouraged miniskirts. France requires male bathers to wear
skintight Speedos rather than trunks, on the ground that trunks
could pass for shorts and be worn in potentially unsanitary areas.
And in America, Chief Justice William Rehnquist has suggested that
women in provocative clothing may be inadvertently inviting sexual
harassment. By Jenny Lyn Bader.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   CIA-POLITICS-REVIEW (Washington) _ The CIA has been struggling
for its footing since the end of the Cold War robbed it of a raison
d'etre. But under the Clinton administration, it has suffered from
two worsening trends: a skittishness about politically sensitive
intelligence and an aversion to risky espionage operations. This
spring CIA analysts were ordered that there were to be no surprises
and no intelligence fiascos that could cause headaches in November.
By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPIC-FORECAST-REVIEW (Undated) _ Two Yale business school
professors have developed a formula they say enables them to
predict exactly how many gold medals each country will win at the
Sydney Olympics. The formula posits that just two factors account
for 95 percent of a nation's predicted medal count: the number of
medals it won at a previous Olympics, and the size of its economy.
By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-ELECTION-REVIEW (Belgrade) _ Democracy is about choice, but
in the Yugoslav version, now playing itself out with Slobodan
Milosevic's future at stake, there are likely to be more choices
than usual. But with a strong opposition candidate doing better
than Milosevic in the opinion polls, Milosevic also gets to make a
choice: whether to accept the choice of the people _ if it goes
against him _ or to manipulate the totals and declare victory
regardless. By Steven Erlanger. (Moving in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Will move in `e' category or as noted) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-NEW-SEASON (New York) _ Ben Brantley surveys the
upcoming Broadway season, which includes the return of Edward
Albee, one of the handful of working American playwrights to whom
the word ``great'' adheres easily and a dramatist who rarely fails
to exasperate and never fails to intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   DEVIL-FILM (Los Angeles) _ Lately, and almost unnoticed, the
Devil has been getting his due on the silver screen. For the new
season, ``Bedazzled'' stars Brendan Fraser as a nerdy young man who
surrenders his soul to a very seductive Devil played by Elizabeth
Hurley. ``Little Nicky'' stars Adam Sandler as Satan's good son,
Harvey Keitel as Satan and Rodney Dangerfield as Satan's father. In
``Lost Souls,'' a thriller, Winona Ryder plays a devout
schoolteacher who becomes aware of a Satanic conspiracy. And the
granddaddy of them all, ``The Exorcist,'' will be re-released with
additional material never shown before. By Jamie Malanowski.
</P>
<P>
   VAMPIRE-FILM (Undated) _ When E. Elias Merhige's ``Shadow of the
Vampire,'' with its attention-snagging stars John Malkovich and
Willem Dafoe, opens on Dec. 29, it will mark at least the fourth
time that filmmakers have resuscitated this particular version of
the vampire: Nosferatu, that disturbingly peculiar and apparently
iconic figure created by an odd little group of Germans 79 years
ago. By Jim Shepard.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-SEASON (Undated) _ The cleft dividing the composers of the
19th century from those of the 20th is arguably the most prominent
geographical feature of our musical landscape. Two attitudes _ on
how music should sound, how it should feel and what its purpose
should be _ have split audiences, musicians and commentators so
decisively that in still a third century, the 21st, the gap is only
marginally narrower than it was 100 years ago. On consecutive days,
March 2, 3 and 4, 2001, at Carnegie Hall, the sides will face each
other in a format of rare concentration and potency. The Vienna
Philharmonic plays; Pierre Boulez conducts. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   POP-MUSIC (Undated) _ The paradox of pop is that intentions
rarely correspond to results. The most carefully thought out,
elaborately realized musical opus may well be ignored or
repudiated, while a casually tossed off ditty can turn out to be
timeless. Listeners, not musicians, will make the final decisions
about what is worth saving. And in the meantime, fleeting pleasures
will do just fine. By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   PIERRE-GILLES-ART (Paris) _ When Claudia Schiffer posed for
them, she became ``Venus,'' framed by sparkling plastic flowers,
two lovely tears running down her porcelain cheeks. The pop singer
Nina Hagen metamorphosed, improbably, into a beatific Virgin Mary
and, in another image, into a bondage victim, dressed in latex and
roped to a kitchen chair. Catherine Deneuve turned into the ``White
Queen,'' floating among clouds in a gown and tiara. This is the
pop-culture paradise of the French artists Pierre and Gilles, who
use fashion, religion and the star system to create an idealized
universe of their own. Over the next year, that universe is coming
to the United States. By Amy Serafin.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-DANCE (New York) _ Diversity, thy name is individuality.
That may well be the message of ``France Moves,'' a major festival
of French contemporary dance that will spread some 10 experimental
troupes in New York. By Anna Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES-SEASON (New York) _ In the year ahead there will be an
amazing variety of private art collections starring in exhibitions
at museums across the country. Three in New York illustrate why
private art collections are formed, why museums exhibit them _ and
in some cases acquire them _ and why museumgoers find them
irresistible. One such show, ``The Embodied Image: Chinese
Calligraphy From the John B. Elliott Collection,'' opens September
15 at the Metropolitan Museum of Art. By Rita Reif.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (Will move in `t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-FRANCE (Undated) _ In Normandy's heartland in mellow
autumn, a traveler fills up with the hearty food and spirit of a
robust area. By Frederick Turner.
</P>
<P>
   CYBER-TRAVEL (Undated) _ Click for a safari in Africa or
spelunking in Arizona. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Lead item: A King Arthur tour of England.
By Eric P. Nash.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STYLES (Will move in `l' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LA-CARAVELLE (New York) _ La Caravelle, which opened with a
$5.50 prix fixe lunch and $7.50 dinner, celebrates its 40th
anniversary this month. A New York institution, it has stood as a
marker of a bygone era of glamour. But rather than settling into
dinosaur status, it has actually hung around long enough to be back
in style again. By Alex Witchel.
</P>
<P>
   UPSCALE-TEEN-FASHION (New York) _ Armed with unprecedented
personal incomes and a precocious knowledge of what women a decade
older consider chic, the upward-striving teen-ager is the newest
target of luxury marketers who once focused strictly on adults.
Chanel, Ralph Lauren, Lancome and Versace are all making a play for
the teen-age market, as is Bobbi Brown, the makeup artist behind an
upscale department store line, whose recent volume of makeup tips,
``Bobbi Brown Teen-age Beauty'' is on The New York Times list of
best-selling children's books. By Ruth LaFerla.
</P>
