<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6924 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-JANELY-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-08 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JANELY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ADVANCE FOR SUNDAY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    LITTLE TREAD LEFT ON OLD POLITICAL WHEEL
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JANE ELY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those who practice, report or pontificate about politics long
have had a tendency to reinvent the proverbial wheel.
</P>
<P>
   This election, however, seems to have offered far more
reinvention cliches than any in modern times. At least, this seems
true to one old, tried _ and, admittedly, pretty tired _ political
memory.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, this ragtag political writer finds herself
particularly resenting some of the conclusions this new generation
of political reinventors have attached to many of their varied new
views of old political ploys and personal acts.
</P>
<P>
   One activity that has presented a special opportunity for goofy
deductions has to do with political husbands and wives and the
exchanges of kisses _ and adoring looks _ between various pairs,
notably Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore and his wife,
Tipper, and former Republican President Ronald Reagan and his wife,
Nancy.
</P>
<P>
   Some actually maintain that a strong contributor to Gore's
recent attraction for women voters can be directly attributed to
the passion demonstrated in the onstage embrace between Gore and
his wife at the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITAL) The kiss, (END ITAL) a prolonged and rather
provocative act in political circles, actually has been cited as
the reason Gore finally has attracted the usually Democratic women
to his camp.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us more than resent this dopey conclusion, a conclusion,
by the way, most often reached _ and announced _ by men. Perhaps we
can take some heart that many of the guys hung up on the (BEGIN
ITAL) kiss, (END ITAL) at last, have suggested a reason for Gore's
belated political capture of many female voters might have more to
do with his positions on so-called women's issues than with how he
greeted his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Along these lines, no matter how incredible it may seem to many
of us, there actually is a new bunch of folk which has decided the
adoring looks Nancy Reagan so often cast at her husband may have
been genuine. This not-exactly-profound conclusion comes from those
who have seen the recently published ``I Love You, Ronnie,'' a
collection of letters written by Ronald Reagan to his wife, whom he
married in 1952, and her commentary.
</P>
<P>
   While admittedly the Reagans were not inclined to express their
more passionate feelings in such a forum as a national convention,
anyone who ever saw them really embrace can tell you their kisses
were scorchers, especially compared to the Gores' last month. Once,
a photographer who had fired his camera at a kiss of the Reagans
after they had been apart a few days swore the scene burned up his
film and he was unable to salvage any pictures.
</P>
<P>
   None who had seen that _ or any other semi-private Reagan _
embrace ever bothered to demand to see the reportedly burned-up
film.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most reinvented of all political wheels this year is
the one turning around the debate over the fairly traditional
presidential debates.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Republican George W. Bush has managed to sound pretty
silly in his gamesmanship over where and when he'll debate Gore.
The candidate who balks the most at accepting the design of the
so-called official debate commission always does.
</P>
<P>
   But, the claim of many _ so-called independent observers as well
as a lot in the Gore camp _ that Bush wants to be seen in debate by
as few Americans as possible is downright insulting to the American
people as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   To contend, as the anti-Bushers do, that, ideally, the debates
should have no television competition is beyond silly. Their
premise that the more television channels carrying a debate, the
larger the audience, hardly compliments the American public.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, if a debate were broadcast only on, say, NBC, what
is there to keep everyone in America with a television set from
watching it? To suggest, as this bunch does, that the more
opportunities the public has to watch something other than a
debate, the smaller the debate audience will be, is one thing.
</P>
<P>
   To suggest, as this bunch does, that every effort should be made
to give the public no alternative to watching a debate is awfully
offensive to one old ragtagger.
</P>
<P>
   Good grief. This goes beyond Big Government to Big Brother and
that's flat damn terrifying.
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, there are all those who think every political
action they haven't seen personally must be new.
</P>
<P>
   But ... enough.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many reinventions and interpretations on the old
political wheel, it soon may not be able to turn at all. Let us
hope it doesn't go completely flat before Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   But, then, let us also hope it doesn't get so filled with hot
air by then that it bursts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ely is a Houston Chronicle columnist. (jane.elychron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
