<HEADER>
A6926 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-MEXICO-FIREFIGHTERS-H     09-08 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FIREFIGHTERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MEXICAN FIRE CREW PITCHES IN NORTH OF BORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ZEKE MacCORMACK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KERRVILLE, Texas _ Gerardo Ureste wore a serene expression
Friday as he toppled charred trees and churned up embers from a
brush fire that had scorched the scenic highlands overlooking this
Hill Country city.
</P>
<P>
   For the 39-year-old Mexican firefighter, working here for $9.75
per hour offers the chance to earn in two weeks what could take
five years or more in his impoverished northern Mexican village,
Boquillas del Carmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no work there,'' said Ureste, noting that most
neighbors cater to tourists to get by.
</P>
<P>
   He was among 23 Mexicans recruited in 1990 and trained by the
U.S. National Park Service to fight fires in the 800,000-acre Big
Bend National Park, just across the Rio Grande from his village.
</P>
<P>
   The squad known as ``Diablos'' has since expanded to 43 members,
and the cross-border partnership has proven so successful that last
fall the Immigration and Naturalization Service cleared them to
fight fires across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The timing couldn't have been better, with hundreds of blazes in
the West and South straining American resources. The Diablos have
seen action this year in Arizona, Colorado and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a hard-working group,'' said John Zubia, a National
Park Service supervisor who traveled with the 20-man team who made
the trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Diablos use shovels, chainsaws and ax-like tools called
Pulaskis to fight fires.
</P>
<P>
   The fire near Kerrville, some 40 miles northwest of San Antonio,
broke out Sunday and came perilously close to neighborhoods west of
town, where homes sell for $700,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Such a lifestyle is a world away from the Diablos' simple homes,
which have no electricity and running water.
</P>
<P>
   The team has been living in relative luxury at a resort hotel
and has enjoyed ready supplies of food and drink donated to
firefighters by local businesses and charities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work and vacation, too,'' Ureste said with a smile Friday,
the Diablos' last day in Kerrville.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Forest Service plans to pack up Saturday and let the
Kerrville Fire Department finish extinguishing the few remaining
hotspots in the 1,300-acre fire zone.
</P>
<P>
   Only 11 of the original Diablos remained when John Morelock,
program supervisor for the Park Service at Big Bend, arrived at the
park in 1997. He organized new training sessions and revived the
corps, which is made up largely of men in their 30s and 40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told them to think long and hard before accepting this
position because this job is one of the most dangerous jobs they
can have,'' he said. ``And we told them to consider their family
situation, and the possibility they would have to go away at a
moment's notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the Park Service and INS expanded the Diablos' domain last
September, each crewmember worked only about two weeks a year.
</P>
<P>
   If the current program continues to be a success, Morelock said
the Diablos ranks may be expanded again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nationally, some of the people at high levels are excited
about the potential for Mexico to help with fire-fighting
shortages,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a firefighter shortage, but this has been a
record breaking year.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Diablos' pact was arranged, the United States and
Mexico already had a mutual aid agreement regarding fires within 10
miles of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Canada and Australia also have provided fire-fighting crews to
help in the United States this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
