<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6928 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-BUSH-BOS &LR;      09-08 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BUSH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TURNS FOLKSY TO REVAMP CAMPAIGN IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARRENDALE, Pa. _ The interior of the Marconi manufacturing
plant seemed ill-suited for a rousing campaign event: vast and
grey, filled with work cubicles, lit by fluorescent lights.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was it really ready to host George W. Bush Friday. His
microphone kept popping. Then a generator kicked in, drowning out
his voice.
</P>
<P>
   Aesthetically speaking, it was a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   But for Bush, this telecommunications equipment company, and the
last-minute visit here, marked an intentional change of course.
Gone were the confetti machines, the upbeat music, the cheering
crowds. In their place were people _ ``real people,'' Bush said _
and a string of serious policy remarks, as the Republican nominee
abruptly switched gears to counter a spate of troubling poll
numbers and growing concern his campaign is a mess.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign proudly noted the overnight metamorphosis, saying
they had ``turned on a dime.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you notice? I hope you noticed,'' communications director
Karen Hughes said. ``We're very quick, a very nimble campaign. I
want you to report: a very nimble and agile campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The sudden shift toward a more intimate campaign style _
reminiscent of the town hall meetings made famous by Senator John
S. McCain during the GOP primaries and relied on by Vice President
Al Gore _ felt familiar to longtime observers of the Bush campaign,
which underwent a similar transformation in the week after losing
the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, Bush waited less than a day after getting
the bad polling news to unveil a new slogan _ ``Real plans for real
people'' _ and admit he had been off course.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike his about-face last February, when he introduced new
themes, the changes Friday were cosmetic, leaving unaddressed
concerns expressed by some Republicans that his $1.3 trillion tax
cut is failing to resonate with the public. Bush campaign officials
explained that they had not conveyed his message effectively, and
would spend the weekend at his ranch in Crawford, Texas, continuing
to ``retool.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the campaign shifted direction on another
matter: the presidential debates. For the first time, Bush aides
said they were willing to negotiate with the Commission on
Presidential Debates, rather than demand the debates be held on
their terms.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush did not mention the issue Friday. He stuck mostly to
policy matters in the visit to the communications firm outside
Pittsburgh, then focused on Social Security privatization during a
rally in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush met with supporters in several roundtable settings
after the primaries, aides said he would place a greater emphasis
on one-on-one events from now on. He may also visit the homes of
some middle-income supporters who would benefit from his tax cut
proposal _ the ``tax families,'' who feature prominently at his
events _ to put a ``human face'' on his policies, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, at least, the personalized format seemed to put Bush at
ease.
</P>
<P>
   Unscheduled and unscripted, the Texas governor arrived at the
warehouse shortly after 8:30 a.m., dropping into the office
cafeteria to chat with employees. A cup of coffee in one hand, he
spoke to the group about the new economy, explaining that, as
president, he would limit the role of government to ensure further
entrepreneurial growth.
</P>
<P>
   Later, giving an address twice as long as his normal stump
speech, Bush described his proposal for Social Security, saying he
would set aside $2.3 trillion of the federal budget surplus to
overhaul the system and reiterating his belief that younger workers
should be allowed to invest some of their Social Security funds in
the markets themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a move that had been decided upon only a day earlier,
Bush opened the floor for questions and addressed each question at
length. It made for an unusually long event; the session lasted
more than 45 minutes, as opposed to his usual 8-minute stump
speech.
</P>
<P>
   At least one employee helped him along, asking: ``How can the
campaign overcome the clearly one-sided media coverage that so
severely restricts the Republican message getting to the people?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, chuckling, started to repeat the question to the rest of
the crowd, who had been unable to hear. ``The question was about
the media,'' he said, then stopped, saying he didn't want any
reporters to take offense.
</P>
<P>
   It was a delicate topic; just four days earlier, Bush had
accidentally uttered a vulgar insult about a New York Times
reporter over a public address system, causing a daylong uproar.
But even that didn't ruffle him Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect the media. Of course _ I've got 60 days before the
election,'' Bush said. ``There's an interesting relationship
between me and the media. One, I need them to get my message out.
And sometimes it comes out fairly, and sometimes, frankly, I don't
care for the coverage. . . . And they need me to make news.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said that dynamic was about to change. ``The best way for
me to get my message out is to speak directly to the people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 2004EDT &QL; 
