<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6929 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-08 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ADVANCE FOR SUNDAY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    DEBATE ABOUT DEBATES JUST PART OF ELECTION RITUAL
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CLAY ROBISON
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ As has been observed before, political campaigns are
not designed to improve government or to help voters make the best
choice on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Political campaigns are designed for one reason and one reason
only _ to get specific candidates elected to office.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates may have a host of reasons _ some of them even
high-minded _ for wanting to get elected, but they won't have a
chance to realize any of them if they first don't get more votes
than their &QL; 
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   That's why even church-going, family-loving candidates sometimes
hedge the truth, outright lie or trash their opponents with
negative advertising.
</P>
<P>
   And that's why the major presidential candidates have been
treating us to the quadrennial ritual of feinting and posturing
over how and when they should debate.
</P>
<P>
   It's a pretty safe bet that George W. Bush and Al Gore will face
off in formal debate at least once _ and probably twice _ before
Election Day. A deal may even be worked out by the time you read
this.
</P>
<P>
   But the pre-debate debate alone has told us something about what
the two candidates and their handlers think of their respective
strengths and weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   Gore didn't offer to debate Bush ``anytime, anywhere'' because
he wanted voters to view himself and his Republican opponent
performing on a level playing field. Gore issued the challenge
because it made him sound like a confident, in-control candidate,
and he believes _ probably correctly _ that he would have an edge
over Bush in most debate formats.
</P>
<P>
   For the same reasons, it also was no surprise that Gore would
readily agree to the three debates proposed by the bipartisan
Commission on Presidential Debates, which has been sponsoring
debates between White House nominees since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Gore nor Bush would be mistaken for a golden-throated
orator, but past performances indicate Gore is a stronger debater.
Bush never embarrassed himself during a string of Republican
primary debates last winter and seemed to become more confident
with each effort, but debating is not what he does best.
</P>
<P>
   So, it was equally no surprise that the Texas governor was
reluctant to agree to all three debates proposed by the commission,
since they would promise the largest potential television audiences
for a face-off between him and his Democratic opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bush proposed substituting two of the commission's
debates with joint appearances on network news or talk shows. He
doubtlessly would prefer their less restrictive, more informal
atmospheres, and he was able to catch Gore in a bit of a bluff. It
seems the vice president's ``anytime, anywhere'' challenge had
conditions attached.
</P>
<P>
   But, more importantly, the debate venues that Bush advocated
would offer much smaller audiences in the event that the governor
were to commit a major gaffe or turn in a lackluster performance.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, though, Bush may have been feeling more
pressure to reach a compromise with Gore because of the governor's
recent slippage in the polls and struggle to regain the momentum in
the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also may have had another goal in all the pre-debate
rhetoric _ to lower public expectations of his performance.
According to that theory, he could declare victory or at least a
tie with Gore if he didn't stumble while walking across the stage
and didn't botch the name of more than one Third World dictator.
</P>
<P>
   If the debates between Bush and Gore are true to recent form,
however, neither candidate will commit a major gaffe nor deliver a
knockout punch _ although both possibilities, particularly the
former, will loom.
</P>
<P>
   But, more importantly, maybe some undecided voters will actually
hear or see something that will help them choose between the two
major candidates _ or send them off in search of a third-party
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Robison is chief of the Chronicle's Austin Bureau.
(clay.robisonchron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
