   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-TRAINER (Washington) _ It was originally billed by the
Pentagon as a low-risk, relatively low-cost program to equip the
armed forces with a simple training aircraft for novice pilots. But
now the project is expected to significantly exceed cost estimates
_ by as much as $750 million with taxpayers footing most of the
bill. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HINES-COLUMN (New York) _ President Clinton brought his extended
farewell tour to the periphery of Broadway last week and indulged
in a variety of his favorite roles _ Daddy Warbucks, Peter Pan,
Tiny Tim. His star turn was a brief, largely anodyne speech at the
beginning of the U.N. Millennium Summit in which even the few
zingers took no particular courage for the leader of the last
remaining superpower. By CRAGG HINES. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ELY-COLUMN (Houston) _ Wrangles over presidential debates hardly
are new. But to suggest that not very many people will watch one
that would be broadcast only on NBC is pretty offensive to me and
quite arrogant of those doing the suggesting, the very ones who
contend George W. Bush is arrogant to play the usual debate game of
trying to get your way. By JANE ELY. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ Political campaigns are not
conducted to enlighten voters or improve government, but merely to
get someone elected. Hence, both George W. Bush and Al Gore are
playing games over when and how to debate. Each is trying to play
up his own strengths and emphasize his opponent's weaknesses. By
CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ While Al Gore and George W. Bush
zoom from state to state searching for votes, Bill Clinton blithely
circumnavigates the globe doing his own thing in his own way. With
less than five months left in his presidency, Clinton has
intensified his efforts to leave his mark on world and national
affairs. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
