<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: FIELD HOCKEY  
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
  The game is ``hockey'' to aficionados, who defensively insist on
calling the version played on skates with a puck ``ice hockey.''
But the aficionados should feel appreciated at these Olympics,
where field hockey will be more visible than ever because of
Australia's affection for and proficiency at this hard-running,
low-scoring game.
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE SETUP
</P>
<P>
   There will be 12 men's teams and 10 women's teams in Sydney, and
the only Americans on the artificial turf will be officials.
Neither the U.S. men nor, more surprisingly, the U.S. women
qualified. The semifinalists are determined by pool play, with the
top two teams in each pool going to the medal round.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCORING
</P>
<P>
   Halves are 35 minutes long, and if that does not produce a
winner, two sudden-death overtime periods (each seven-plus minutes
long) are played. If that still does not work, the medals will come
down to penalty strokes in which players take turns shooting on
goal. As in ice hockey _ let us give the aficionados what they want
_ players can be forced to leave the game for short periods to
serve penalties for fouls.
</P>
<P>
   THE NAMES
</P>
<P>
   The Australian women, known rather unimaginatively as the
Hockeyroos, have had a mediocre season, finishing third in this
year's prestigious Champions Trophy tournament behind Germany and
the Netherlands. But the now-chastened Hockeyroos remain the
favorites to defend the Olympic title they won in Atlanta (they
also won in Seoul, South Korea, in 1988). South Korea could also be
a factor. In the men's event, the Australian men, known not much
more imaginatively as the Kookaburras, are also medal contenders
but have a reputation for succumbing to pressure (they have never
won an Olympic gold medal).
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch, who won in 1996, and the Germans, who won in 1992, do
not have such skeletons rattling around in their closets. The
Indian men, incidentally, are considered to have an outside chance
for a medal after 20 years of frustration in a game they once
utterly dominated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
