<SLUG> BC-U.N.-CLINTON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE GAIN SEEN AS CLINTON MEETS CHINA'S PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ President Clinton on Friday urged China's
president, Jiang Zemin, to open a dialogue with the new government
of Taiwan and put a stop to its missile exports to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   But in what had already been a week of diplomatic frustration
for Clinton, Jiang offered little more than cordial good wishes for
the president's retirement in four months and thanks for supporting
China's bid to join the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton's aides described the session as ``cordial,'' the
lack of progress on some of the major issues still dividing the
United States and China finished off a week in which the president
had tried _ and failed _ to win one or two major foreign policy
accomplishments as he enters his final months in office.
</P>
<P>
   His efforts to restart the peace talks between Israel and the
Palestinians that broke down at Camp David in July made such little
headway that Clinton was overheard by photographers on Friday
telling the Irish prime minister, Bertie Ahearn, ``This Middle East
thing _ it's maddening.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not the only leader unhappy at the diplomatic gridlock. A
senior Japanese official said Israel's prime minister, Ehud Barak,
vented his unhappiness to his Japanese counterpart, Yoshiro Mori.
At a meeting on Friday, he complained that the Palestinian leader,
Yasser Arafat, ``has not responded'' to several new proposals on
the status of Jerusalem, and questioned whether ``Arafat has the
political courage to make the move.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides had played down the prospect of any major
progress on Chinese missile exports, Tibet or Taiwan in the days
leading up to the meeting with Jiang. But they had hoped that the
expected passage by the Senate this month of permanent normal trade
relations with China _ a prerequisite for the country's admission
to the World Trade Organization _ would be rewarded with some
political progress on issues that have bedeviled Washington's
relations with Beijing since the two leaders first met in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In a measure of their communications problems after seven years
of interchanges, a senior administration official said on Friday
that the meeting was ``designed to get these two men on the same
wavelength a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   Another official noted that Clinton's hopes of using the WTO
vote as leverage in his talks with Jiang had yet to pay off,
saying: ``We look to use the WTO entry to deepen political
cooperation. But they view Taiwan and issues like it as purely
internal issues. They don't connect the two the way we do.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jiang was eager to show his American hosts that he could
talk the talk of a high-tech nation, even while offering up
familiar lectures about respecting China's sovereignty. Immediately
after his hour-and-a-half meeting with Clinton, he used a luncheon
meeting of America's top business executives to declare that China
is plugging into the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have over 16 million netizens,'' he said in a speech
delivered entirely in English, ``more than 27,000 World Wide Web
sites, over 70,000 Chinese domain names and 61 million mobile
phones in China.''
</P>
<P>
   But he did not mention China's recent efforts to crack down on
the use of the Internet for the spread of dissenting opinions in
China, and Clinton, aides said, never broached the subject in their
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   When he was done reciting China's technological advances to the
executives, though, Jiang wove back to familiar territory. He
argued that China was a place of religious tolerance, saying: ``The
languages, religions and customs of ethnic minorities in China,
including the Tibetans, are protected and respected, and their
cultural traditions have been carried forward and developed.''
Pro-Tibet groups argue that China has done whatever it could to
stamp out the Tibetan culture, and they succeeded in killing a
World Bank project this summer that some feared would relocate
ethnic Tibetan farmers and further dilute the culture.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang also called the Falun Gong religious group, whose members
have been arrested in large numbers in recent months, a `cult'' and
said any government would crack down on ``those who have done
severe harm to the people.'' As he spoke, members of the group
performed silent exercises across Park Avenue, under the watchful
eye of the police.
</P>
<P>
   James Lilley, a former American ambassador to Beijing and a
guest at the lunch, said Jiang's arguments amounted to ``an effort
to grab the religious issues by the throat and say we have
religious tolerance, but not your kind,'' adding: ``He just wants
to sail right by the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The conversation on China's missile exports to Pakistan came
after Clinton, earlier this summer, sent a delegation to China to
try to cut off the supply. The administration worries that any new
missile technology would heighten Pakistan's ability to strike
India.
</P>
<P>
   But Jiang, by all accounts, has paid little attention to the
issue. ``This is going to take a while,'' one of Clinton's aides
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the Chinese leader indicate that he was ready to open
talks with Taiwan's newly elected leader, Chen Shui-bian. ``They
spent a long time on Taiwan, but Jiang took much of that describing
China's historical claims'' to the island. That also seemed out of
place for what will likely be the second to last meeting between he
two leaders; Clinton, by now, has heard China's claims to Taiwan
many, many times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
