<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers)  
 SOUTHERN LAWMAKERS DRIVING FIRESTONE/FORD PROBE 
 &HT;    
 By CARL HULSE  
NYT Regional Newspapers  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   WASHINGTON _ Southern lawmakers
<TEXT>
were in the driver's seat as Congress turned the high beams on
Bridgestone/Firestone and Ford Motor Co. and their corporate
culpability in tire failures that have claimed dozens of lives and
prompted a massive recall.
<P>
   Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., opened the congressional review of
the ongoing consumer controversy Wednesday morning as chairman of
the Transportation Appropriations Subcommittee. Rep. Billy Tauzin,
R-La., followed up as chairman of a hard-hitting House Commerce
Committee hearing that ran into the night.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawmakers from the region where sport utility vehicles are
a way of life were quick to weigh in as well on the human side of
not moving fast enough in the face of evidence of problems with
tires mounted on Ford Explorers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida is fourth in the number of crashes resulting from
these tire failures and accounts for the most fatalities,'' Rep.
Cliff Stearns, R-Fla., declared at the House hearing. ``Although
this is a national and international problem, these accidents have
been a great source of tragedy in my home state.''
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin, who acknowledged he had Firestone tires on his own
vehicle and has since parked it, said the hearings were not an
attempt to fix legal blame but were ``to ask ourselves why we're in
this mess and what we can do as a panel representing the Congress
here to make sure this never happens again.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Shelby: ``Ford and Firestone had at a minimum a moral
obligation to make sure that the products they sell to the American
public and other people in other countries are safe.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a distinct change in tone for a Congress that has been
generally friendly to the auto industry given its importance to the
U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   Both Tauzin and Shelby, for instance, received campaign
contributions from Ford's political action committee. And Shelby's
panel has been cited by auto safety advocates as a potential
roadblock to new federal Internet posting of potential roll-over
rates of some vehicles. Shelby has been credited, however, with
backing a tougher drunken driving standard.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates said the congressional attention to the tire
recall could have broad implications, shaking loose some safety
standards they say have been ``stuck in neutral'' for years due to
industry resistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you buy a brand-new car you expect to have a
state-of-the-art stereo in there, but you have a car that is
subject to safety standards issued in the late 1960s and 70s,''
said Jackie Gillan, vice president of the Advocates for Highway and
Auto Safety.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTA QUESTION
</P>
<P>
   Congress is still wrestling with whether to extend a ban on new
commercial fishing quota programs sought by some in the Gulf of
Mexico and elsewhere but must act by Oct. 1 or the prohibition will
expire on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Gulf fishing interests say current short seasons for such valued
species as red snapper force captains to sail in bad weather and
lead to wasted fish caught out of season and discarded. They want
the ability to enact new annual individual catch limits, a move now
backed by a group of Democratic senators.
</P>
<P>
   But other lawmakers and environmental groups want to extend the
moratorium another year to work out an acceptable system. They hope
to attach their plan to one of the giant spending measures expected
to move through Congress in the next month.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL REPAIRS
</P>
<P>
   Southern lawmakers are banding together to push legislation that
would provide seven historic women's colleges in the South with up
to $70 million over five years to restore landmark buildings on
their campuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't lose these historic campuses to age and neglect,''
said Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala., a chief sponsor of the aid to
colleges that date back 120 years and gave women their first
opportunity for higher vocational and industrial education.
</P>
<P>
   Schools that would receive aid if Congress agrees are:
University of Montevallo in Alabama; Mississippi University for
Women; Georgia College and State University; University of North
Carolina at Greensboro; Winthrop University in South Carolina;
Texas Woman's University, and the University of Science and Arts of
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   COASTAL CONTROVERSY
</P>
<P>
   A $3 billion conservation measure that would provide a windfall
to coastal states remains hung up in the Senate and Majority Leader
Trent Lott isn't sure he can move it through this year despite his
own support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the one bill that would be very helpful for beach
erosion and preservation of important areas, the CARA bill,'' said
Lott as he listed the Conservation and Reinvestment Act among his
priorities for the remainder of Congress. ``But we may not get to
all of those.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief of the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
