<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: EQUESTRIAN  
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once, these were tests for military men on horseback. Now, the
riders are usually civilians and often women, and age is no
barrier. The four riders on the U.S. jumping team are women, ages
42, 40, 34 and 23. The U.S. eventing team includes David and Karen
O'Connor, husband and wife from The Plains, Va., who won team
silver medals in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   THE SETUP
</P>
<P>
   The three disciplines _ jumping, dressage and eventing _ award
individual and team medals. In jumping, horse and rider race one by
one over a stadium course of 15 to 18 jumps, with fastest time
(combined with fewest faults) deciding. Dressage is seven minutes
of ballet on horseback, with the horse doing required moves in
response to invisible commands from the rider. Eventing combines
separate days of cross-country riding over 35 to 40 jumps, dressage
and show jumping.
</P>
<P>
   THE STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   Especially tricky in eventing because the horse would be worn
out if it always took the shortest route over the jumps, which may
be higher in the middle. So beforehand, coaches and riders walk the
course over and over, trying to determine the smartest line.
</P>
<P>
   THE NAMES
</P>
<P>
   Gold-medal favorites are Rodrigo Pessoa of Brazil in jumping,
Isabell Werth of Germany in dressage and Blyth Tait of New Zealand
in eventing. The best teams are Brazil and Germany in jumping,
Germany and the Netherlands in dressage and the Netherlands and the
United States in eventing. The Americans have good shots at one or
two medals in eventing and a medal in jumping from Margie
Goldstein-Engle of Wellington, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
