<SLUG> BC-BALLET-CLEVELAND-400&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDGET TURMOIL AT SAN JOSE CLEVELAND BALLET 
</HEADLINE>
   By OCTAVIO ROCA  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The San Jose Cleveland Ballet suspended all operations in
Cleveland on Thursday night, laid off all the dancers and canceled
its 25th anniversary season in that city.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Ballet School, which was to open its doors Monday
to 300 students for the new school year, also closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are deeply saddened,'' said board president Robert Jones,
``but we simply do not have the resources to continue to operate.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the company could not ask the dancers to continue
working ``when it finally became apparent that there was no
reasonable expectation'' that they would be paid. As of Friday
afternoon, the dancers were owed 3 1/2 weeks salary.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the board of directors in Cleveland caught the
San Jose board by surprise. And it placed in jeopardy the season in
San Jose that is scheduled to open Oct. 12 at the San Jose Center
for the Performing Arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working desperately with the people in San Jose to do
anything we can to make the season there happen,'' Jones said.
``But we know it is not going to be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   San Jose Cleveland Ballet is unique, belonging to two cities
thousands of miles apart. Each city has its own budget and is
responsible for its own fund-raising, but they share productions
and dancers. The Cleveland company, with an annual budget of $6.5
million, has been running at a deficit for a decade and has come up
short in its fund-raising projections.
</P>
<P>
   The San Jose side of the ballet company operates in the black,
with an annual budget of $4.5 million that is not directly affected
by Thursday's decision.
</P>
<P>
   For all its financial good health in San Jose, however, the
company's shutdown in Cleveland has unsettling repercussions for
dance in the Bay Area: The San Jose Cleveland Ballet dancers make
Cleveland their home. They take daily classes and rehearse every
ballet in the Cleveland studios, flying in and out of San Jose only
to perform. Relocating 40 dancers is a costly and time-consuming
proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the dancers, set builders, costume makers and all the
other workers who put together a dance season were laid off in
Cleveland. The company has no costume shop in San Jose. Real estate
and commercial rental space are considerably more expensive in San
Jose than in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The San Jose ballet board lent the Cleveland board $1 million
last year. So far this year, donors in San Jose have contributed
more than $500,000 for the new production of ``Don Quixote,'' but
now it is not known where or even whether those sets will be built.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In contrast, the Bay Area's other major ballet companies are
thriving. Oakland Ballet, streamlined but in solid financial
footing, opens Friday at the Paramount Theatre. ``We are in the
black,'' said Oakland executive director Ren &LR; e &LR; e Heider.
``Subscriptions are up 23 percent, and we are looking forward to a
great season.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Ballet, America's oldest ballet company, plans to
announce next week that it is in the black for the ninth
consecutive year. ``Our endowment over the last eight years has
grown from $3 million to $36 million,'' executive director Arthur
Jacobus said, ``and I am confident that support from the community
will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very fortunate to be living in San Francisco,'' Jacobus
said, ``a community with a real, strong commitment to the arts.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
