<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6946 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-CNN-FYI0909-COX     09-08 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-FYI0909-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN Web site aimed at teachers, studying students
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ CNN says it won't allow advertisements on a new Web
site aimed at teachers and at children who go online for homework
help.
</P>
<P>
   But CNN says it expects the site to become profitable. How?
Three education-related companies are paying to have their logos,
names and links appear on the site.
</P>
<P>
   The companies, described as ``education partners,'' also are
supplying some of the site's content. CNN officials say they
eventually will add two more companies as partners.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site, CNNfyi.com, launches Monday at fyi.cnn.com/fyi/.
It will have news written with students and teachers in mind,
sometimes by students themselves. It also will have suggested
lesson plans tied to news events, listings of homework resources,
message boards and information on a variety of subjects such as how
to prepare for college.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors include Riverdeep Interactive Learning, a provider of
educational material online; Harcourt, a major publisher of
textbooks and school materials; and HighWired.com, a company with a
Web site for information on specific schools and news from school
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The new Web site targets middle and high school students, as
well as teachers. It's a big market. An estimated 25 million people
under 18 go online.
</P>
<P>
   But there's also competition for the study time of youth. The
New York Times' Learning Network is a similar offering
(www.nytimes.com/learning/www). And America Online, which is
planning to merge with CNN's parent Time Warner, has launched its
own AOL(at)School (www.school.aol.com/). The new AOL service, which
schools sign up for, overlaps with some CNNfyi.com areas, but it
also includes a link to the new CNN Web site.
</P>
<P>
   CNN Interactive President Scott Woelfel says the AOL and CNN
sites won't be competitors, but he adds, ``We have yet to know
exactly how we fit around that.''
</P>
<P>
   Woelfel said CNNfyi.com will be expected to make a profit
eventually, but he said ``there is a bit of an altruistic
motivation behind it.''
</P>
<P>
   With prodding from founder Ted Turner, the company has since
1989 provided commercial-free half-hour daily news shows produced
for classroom learning.
</P>
<P>
   More than 15,000 schools have signed up for the service,
according to John Richards, Turner Learning's senior vice president
and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   CNNfyi.com is being run in conjunction with Turner Learning, the
educational division of Time Warner's Turner Broadcasting System.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
