<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6964 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v BC-SUNDAY-FINAL-BUDGET-2     09-08 1611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-FINAL-BUDGET-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service has moved the following
entertainment/arts, travel, business and style articles. If you
have questions about stories, call 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (moving in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-NEW-SEASON (New York) _ Ben Brantley surveys the
upcoming Broadway season, which includes the return of Edward
Albee, one of the handful of working American playwrights to whom
the word ``great'' adheres easily and a dramatist who rarely fails
to exasperate and never fails to intrigue, as well as the return of
Alan Bates in ``The Unexpected Man.''
</P>
<P>
   SEUSSICAL-THEATER (New York) _ Broadway is becoming more
preoccupied with the needs of an age group that in the past it
rarely catered to _ children _ while holding on for dear life to
the adult audience that has sustained it. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SEASON (Undated) _ Elvis Mitchell surveys the upcoming film
season, which he says will be a season of radical departures, with
an astonishing number of musicals from directors new to the genre
and an action film from a director who made his name with finely
tuned pictures based in the comedy of manners.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-LEAN-SEASON (Undated) _ The film industry's autumnal hopes
seem to be pinned, for the moment, on a live-action adaptation,
``Dr. Seuss' How the Grinch Stole Christmas'' and an updating of
the '70s television show ``Charlie's Angels,'' which not even those
of us who decorated our bedrooms with pictures of its
crime-fighting stars ever considered a work of art. And there are
further signs that cinematic seriousness has fallen on hard times.
By A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-ZELLWEGER (Los Angeles) _ Renee Zellweger has all the
trappings of a rising Hollywood starlet: the blond hair, the thin
frame, the bee-stung lips, the homespun childhood in Texas, no
formal acting training and a boyfriend who gets $20 million per
picture. But Zellweger is not simply another actress who has
succeeded by perfecting the art of playing herself. By Dana
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   AFFLECK-FILM (Hollywood) _ Since wafting into the public
consciousness three years ago in ``Good Will Hunting'' _ a film for
which he shared a screenwriting Oscar with his co-star and Little
League teammate, Matt Damon _ Ben Affleck has emerged as one of
Hollywood's major heart flutters. When his new romantic drama,
``Bounce,'' is released on Oct. 13, cardiologists across the
country will be on call. By Franz Lidz.
</P>
<P>
   BLAIRWITCH-FILM (Los Angeles) _ No matter who does it, making a
sequel to a hit film is one thing; making a sequel to a phenomenon
is another. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   DEVIL-FILM (Los Angeles) _ Lately, and almost unnoticed the
Devil has been getting his due on the silver screen. By Jamie
Malanowski.
</P>
<P>
   VAMPIRE-FILM (Undated) _ When E. Elias Merhige's ``Shadow of the
Vampire,'' with its attention-snagging stars John Malkovich and
Willem Dafoe, opens Dec. 29, it will mark at least the fourth time
that filmmakers have resuscitated this particular version of the
vampire: Nosferatu, that disturbingly peculiar and apparently
iconic figure created by an odd little group of Germans 79 years
ago. By Jim Shepard.
</P>
<P>
   CROWE-FILM (Santa Monica, Calif.) _ For Cameron Crowe, it has
always been about rock 'n' roll. That has been the story of his
life and work, starting with his precocious stint as a teenage
journalist with Rolling Stone magazine in the '70s, right on
through his current filmmaking career as a writer and director. By
Bill Desowitz.
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS-FILM (Undated) _ Presumably, with the blurring of
once-rigid boundaries between male and female roles, the action
heroine is no longer the anomaly who has to be softened, made
acceptable, by precisely those ``feminizing'' qualities that
undermine her plausibility, threaten to turn her into a harmless
joke. ``Charlie's Angels,'' the movie, will no doubt give us the
real thing: powerful, enterprising women who haven't got time to
look perfect, whose fingernails crack and whose roots grow out, who
give their Bosley (Bill Murray) not girlish giggles but power-grrrl
guff. By Molly Haskell.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-HENRY-JAMES-(Undated) _ Transferring Henry James to the
screen has never been easy. Still, Hollywood keeps trying. By Lisa
Zeidner.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-FOOD-FEASTS (Undated) _ In the scentless, flavorless
language of film, the dinner table is often used as an excuse to
assemble the cast: It becomes the stage for spilling secrets, for
acting out ancient dramas and measuring loyalties by shifts in
appetite. By Kristin Hohenadel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-SEASON (Undated) _ The cleft dividing the composers of the
19th century from those of the 20th is arguably the most prominent
geographical feature of our musical landscape. Two attitudes _ on
how music should sound, how it should feel and what its purpose
should be _ have split audiences, musicians and commentators so
decisively that in still a third century, the 21st, the gap is only
marginally narrower than it was 100 years ago. On consecutive days,
March 2, 3 and 4, 2001, at Carnegie Hall, the sides face each other
in a format of rare concentration and potency. The Vienna
Philharmonic plays; Pierre Boulez conducts. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   SERKIN-MUSIC (New York) _ Peter Serkin has never been an
ordinary virtuoso. His deep concern with the music of living
composers has brought him to work more than most solo pianists in
collaborative contexts and encouraged him to be unconventional in
his programming. By Paul Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   POP-MUSIC (Undated) _ The paradox of pop is that intentions
rarely correspond to results. The most carefully thought out,
elaborately realized musical opus may well be ignored or
repudiated, while a casually tossed off ditty can turn out to be
timeless. Listeners, not musicians, will make the final decisions
about what's worth saving. And in the meantime, fleeting pleasures
will do just fine. By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   JOAN-OSBORNE-MUSIC (New York) _ The music business has a long
tradition of making over its female artists, whether it's the
Supremes in finishing school or just the latest battery of stylists
dispatched to a video shoot. What's odd about Joan Osborne's
situation is that she seems to have forced this transformation upon
herself. By Karen Schoemer.
</P>
