<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: GYMNASTICS  
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: ``Andreea'' in 1st graf of ``THE NAMES'' is cq.)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a different look to these Olympics. The compulsories
have been eliminated, and the so-called 6-5-4 rule (six gymnasts
are on a team, five compete on each apparatus and the four highest
scores count) means event specialists are much more important.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Romanian women and the Chinese men enter as the
favorites for the gold medals, the new scoring method makes
determining the winners difficult. Now, strategy is more important,
and a poor routine is more costly.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Magnificent Seven surprised the world and won the
first team gold for the United States. But with weaknesses on the
vault and on the balance beam, Bela Karolyi's troops could have
difficulty trying to defend their title.
</P>
<P>
   THE SETUP
</P>
<P>
   The women compete on four apparatus: vault, uneven bars, floor
exercise and balance beam. If there are two apparatus that send
shivers down the spine of gymnasts, they are the balance beam and
the uneven bars. For 70 to 90 seconds on a 4-inch-wide beam, using
forward and backward tumbling passes, a gymnast has to have equal
levels of courage and concentration. The uneven bars are made more
difficult because of the precision it takes to execute transitions
from bar to bar and to execute release moves.
</P>
<P>
   The men perform on six apparatus: floor exercise, pommel horse,
still rings, vault, high bar and parallel bars. The one event that
does not allow for a pause or a hiccup in the routine is the pommel
horse, which is considered the most difficult. To most, the pommel
horse requires twice as long to master. The brute strength of the
men will also be judged on the still rings. No matter how talented
a gymnast is, if he does not have the physical might to perform in
this event, his chance for placing in the all-around competition is
remote.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCORING
</P>
<P>
   During team competition preliminaries, gymnasts perform an
optional exercise _ compulsories were eliminated after 1996 _ on
each apparatus. The scores are used to advance individuals to the
all-around finals and the apparatus finals, and to place entire
teams in the team final competition. This puts on the pressure from
Day 1.
</P>
<P>
   Six gymnasts from each of the 12 top nations at the world
championships are entitled to participate in the team finals for
the men's and women's titles. But this year, no more than five
gymnasts (which are selected by the national coaches) may compete
on a single apparatus, and the four highest scores count toward the
6-5-4 team total. The working order of the team is decided by each
country. Once qualifying ends, the team competition begins with the
previous scores discarded.
</P>
<P>
   The top 36 gymnasts from the team competition, with a maximum of
three per nation, qualify to compete in the all-around finals. With
numbers restrictions, this allows isolated gymnasts from nations
that have underdeveloped programs to show their talents. During the
men's and women's all-around finals, each gymnast performs an
optional routine on each apparatus. The male and female gymnasts
with the highest cumulative score win the gold medal and will hold
the sport's most prestigious title as the all-around champion.
</P>
<P>
   On the last day of competition, the apparatus finals takes
place. The top eight gymnasts on each apparatus from the team
competition, with a maximum of two per country, qualify. A gymnast
who competes in only one apparatus in team competition is still
eligible to participate in the finals. As in the all-around and the
team finals, the scoring begins anew. Gold medals are awarded for
each apparatus.
</P>
<P>
   THE STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   There was a lot of hand-wringing over the subjective selection
process for the U.S. women's team. The reason for the procedure
came down to strategy. Until recently, every athlete that made the
team competed on every apparatus, and the lowest score was dropped.
But in 1997, the 6-5-4 format was adopted for men's and women's
international competition. Teams are allowed to use all six team
members in any lineup for the most advantageous team position. A
gymnast does not have to compete on every apparatus to contribute.
For example, a gymnast may be weak on one event but be a specialist
on another.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, coaches will play a shell game with their
lineups from apparatus to apparatus in order to maximizing their
gymnasts' strengths.
</P>
<P>
   A perfect score in gymnastics is still 10.0, but there are start
values for each routine. A difficult routine is worth 10.0, but a
less complex one might be worth only 9.75. However, numbers do not
always add up in judging. In the past, judges tended to score
gymnasts who competed early in the lineup much harder, leaving
themselves room to give higher scores to later competitors. A
typical coaching strategy is to start each apparatus with a gymnast
who is likely to complete a routine flawlessly. As a result, the
gymnast can set the table for less-talented teammates.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a flip side to this, too; often the leadoff
performer cannot gain the top marks and ends up as the sacrificial
lamb for the team.
</P>
<P>
   THE NAMES
</P>
<P>
   If the two remaining members of the Magnificent Seven _ Amy Chow
and Dominique Dawes _ are going to recapture the glory from 1996,
they will have to lead the U.S. team past the strong Romanians,
Russians and Chinese. Romania is the reigning world champion and is
led by the disciplined and spectacular Simona Amanar, Maria Olaru
and Andreea Raducan. The Russians feature the vault champion Yelena
Zamolodchikova, while the Chinese are anchored by Jie Ling on the
balance beam.
</P>
<P>
   To help boost a &UR;  &LR; U.S. team that bottomed out with a poor showing
at the 1999 world championships, Bela Karolyi returned as national
coordinator and began camps to rebuild the team's confidence and
improve the difficulty levels on the gymnasts' routines. Chow and
Dawes, along with the budding Elise Ray and Kristen Maloney, hope
to make Karolyi's return a success by putting the United States in
medal contention.
</P>
<P>
   The men's team from China has been in the position as favorite
before at the Olympics. Four years ago, the Chinese arrived as
world champions but faltered in Atlanta and finished with a silver
behind Russia. China is led by Zhen Dong on the still rings and Wei
Yang on the horizontal bar, while Russia will return with Nikolai
Kryukov and Alexei Nemov from the country's 1996 gold medal team.
Belarus could also be a threat if Ivan Ivankov (Achilles' tendon
injury) is fit to perform. The Americans have a long way to go
before finding themselves among the elite.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
