 UNDATED: the elite.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RHYTHMIC GYMNASTICS
</P>
<P>
   Judging in this female-only event often seems to be based more
on how eye-pleasing each competitor is rather than on how well she
executes sometimes suggestive routines with five apparatus: rope,
hoop, ball, ribbon and clubs. In the individual competition,
gymnasts perform with four of the five apparatus. In the team
competition, five gymnasts work together as one unit. The favorites
for the all-around title in this sport are from Ukraine: the 1997
world champion, Yelena Vitrichenko, and the 1996 gold medal winner
in Atlanta, Ekaterina Serebrianskaya. Also pushing Ukraine will be
Russia, Bulgaria, Spain and Belarus.
</P>
<P>
   TRAMPOLINE
</P>
<P>
   In the sport's Olympic debut, the men's and women's trampoline
competitions will be judged based on two routines: compulsory and
voluntary. Jennifer Parilla is the only American to qualify for the
Olympics. Russia, France and Belarus all have strong teams in men's
and women's trampoline.
</P>
</TEXT>
