<HEADER>
A6970 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-DEBATE-1998-610&AMP;     09-08 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DEBATE-1998-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SHOWED RELUCTANCE TO DEBATE IN 1998 TEXAS RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ His Democratic opponent needled George W. Bush for
months about being ``afraid'' to debate. The opponent said he would
debate the Texas governor anytime, anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Bush hemmed and hawed. When the governor finally offered to
debate, his opponent accused him of trying to dictate terms that
would reduce the size of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   If the plot sounds as if it had been lifted from the debate
squabbles between Bush and Vice President Al Gore, think again.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic opponent in question was Garry Mauro, and the
election was the 1998 governor's race in Texas. ``Bush's position
was he'd do it when the time was right,'' recalled Mauro. ``And the
time was never right.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides now say that the governor always intended to debate
_ a point that seemed less clear at the time _ and agreed to a
single event late in the race when voters would be paying
attention.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush did so only after his campaign was allowed to control
when, where and how it was conducted, choosing the most remote city
in the state on a night when many people were attending high school
football games.
</P>
<P>
   His staff also dictated the format, choosing to have a single
moderator rather than taking questions from an audience or the
capital press corps, and rejecting a large auditorium in favor of a
small television studio.
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, Bush was simply playing the role of a popular
incumbent reluctant to share a stage with a long-shot challenger.
Despite leading in some polls by over 50 percentage points, Bush
showed the same cautiousness toward debating that he does today, an
approach that some now regard as a missed opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Before the presidential campaign, Bush had participated in only
two major debates, against Mauro in 1998 and against Gov. Ann
Richards in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was curious that he didn't take advantage of this
to prepare for the presidential race,'' said Richard Murray, a
University of Houston political science professor, of the 1998
race. ``Mauro would have been a good sparring partner.''
</P>
<P>
   Few people believed that Mauro, a former Texas land commissioner
who became the Democratic nominee for governor, had any chance of
winning. Bush was extremely popular and had raised nearly 10 times
more money. Mauro could afford little campaign advertising and
pushed for debates, even accepting an invitation to meet the
governor inside the ball park of the Texas Rangers, the baseball
team once run by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush rejected invitations from every major media outlet in the
state, leaving doubts about whether a debate would even occur. Five
weeks before Election Day, he agreed to an hourlong debate in El
Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Moore, managing editor of The El Paso Times, said Bush
accepted the newspaper's invitation only after it had held months
of meetings with the governor's top political adviser, Karl Rove.
</P>
<P>
   ``The argument that we pushed was that if the governor planned
to run for president, it would benefit him to have more than one
debate under his belt,'' Moore said, referring to Bush's 1994
debate with Richards.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro accused Bush of trying to orchestrate a debate that no one
would watch. El Paso, he noted, was the only city in Texas in the
Mountain Time zone. And by picking a Friday night roughly three
weeks before Election Day, Bush had chosen a time that conflicted
with high school football, an ardent passion across Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Bartlett, a spokesman for Bush, said the governor chose El
Paso because it had never hosted a debate, and he wanted to
emphasize the importance of voters in West Texas. Bush also was
aggressively courting Hispanic voters in El Paso.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Moore said the Bush campaign made several demands. First, he
said, they rejected the format used in the lieutenant governor's
debate in which the candidates were asked questions by members of
the audience, by a panel of journalists and then by each other.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Bush campaign insisted on a single moderator and
asked Moore to fill that role. Moore said the campaign also
insisted that the two candidates be seated at an oval table with
Moore in the middle. ``They wanted a very controlled environment
for the debate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro said the Bush campaign also required that the cameras only
be allowed to focus on the moderator and whichever candidate was
speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett said any prohibition on the cameras ``doesn't ring a
bell with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the debate itself was considered something of a dud.
Few people watched. Some political scientists, including Murray,
considered Mauro the winner. Nearly everyone agreed it did not
matter, and that, Mauro contended, is what Bush wanted all along.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
