<HEADER>
A6971 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BRAZIL-CLASSICAL-MUSI     09-08 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-CLASSICAL-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZILIAN CLASSICAL MUSIC HAS LIVELINESS OF POP 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As anyone who has spent time in Brazil can attest,
Brazilian celebrations don't usually require elaborate
justifications. Still, several were offered as reasons for the
concert of Brazilian orchestral music that the consulate general of
Brazil sponsored at Alice Tully Hall on Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Most immediately, Thursday was Brazil's Independence Day. The
concert also honored the 500th anniversary of the country's
discovery in 1500. The Millennium Summit meeting at the United
Nations was also cited.
</P>
<P>
   In more purely musical terms, the concert was a way to put the
spotlight on a side of Brazil's culture that is generally
overshadowed by its success in the world of global pop.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, the program was slightly disappointing. Although
it included U.S. premieres of a 1934 work by Francisco Mignone and
a 1959 score by Heitor Villa-Lobos, the Villa-Lobos was the most
recent work on the program. There were no works by living
composers, nothing to show what Brazilian composers have been up to
for the last 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Nirenberg, a Brazilian who divides his time between Rio
de Janeiro and Montclair, N.J., conducted the New York Chamber
Symphony. He opened the program with the Sinfonia from ``Fosca,''
an opera by Antonio Carlos Gomes.
</P>
<P>
   Gomes, a contemporary of Verdi, was in vogue in Italy in the
late 19th century. He assimilated the Italian opera style
completely, and this overture has it all: gracefully winding
woodwind themes, big ominous brass chords, a section given to
quietly haunting string writing that bowed to ``La Traviata,'' and
tub-thumping bombast in the final pages.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the short first half was devoted to Mignone's
``Fantasia Brasileira'' No. 3, a compact, sparkling work for piano
and orchestra. Unlike the Gomes, which is a thoroughly European
work, the Mignone draws on quintessentially Brazilian elements _
the same ones, in fact, that continue to make Brazilian popular
music and jazz so lively and so easily placed.
</P>
<P>
   Syncopated rhythms and playfully dissonant harmonies drive the
piano part, and the orchestral fabric has the kind of distinctive
coloration that Copland and Bernstein borrowed when they wanted to
evoke a Latin American atmosphere. Not quite a piano concerto, it
nevertheless offers some dazzling moments, and Linda Bustani, the
soloist, made the most of them.
</P>
<P>
   Nirenberg closed the concert with two works by Villa-Lobos. The
Preludio from the ``Bachianas Brasileiras'' No. 4 is steeped in
rich, deep string sonorities that evoke a 1940s vintage view of
Bach.
</P>
<P>
   The belated premiere was the Suite No. 2, a five-movement work
composed a few months before Villa-Lobos' death in 1959. It has its
dark moments, not least in the opening ``Lamento.'' But this is
hardly a deathbed rumination: The Scherzo is bright and
cosmopolitan, and the ``Macumba,'' with its sweeping strings, vivid
brass writing and insistent percussion, closes with a grandly
cinematic flourish.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra was in fine shape for much of the program. Moments
of ragged ensemble and strident string tone marred parts of the
Villa-Lobos Suite, but in the work's finale the orchestra's playing
was bright and energetic, and it brought an appealing warmth and
suppleness to the Gomes and the Villa-Lobos Preludio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 2031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
