<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6972 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-TELECOM-$ADV10     09-08 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-TELECOM-$ADV10-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGING THE ODDS ON THOSE BATTERED PHONE STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JANE TANNER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Death warmed over: That is how one analyst has described the
battered long-distance and local telephone sector of the
telecommunications industry. In a sharp reversal, the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 communications services index, which rose 18.2 percent
last year, has dropped 28.9 percent from a mid-December high to
173.55.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone stocks climbed last year, and a bit this spring, on
excitement about mergers and the entry of local carriers into
long-distance service. But Wall Street has done an about-face on
the sector, focusing on the dilution caused by acquisitions, on
higher-than-expected capital needs and on fear that competition
will put pressure on profits.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, many analysts say, the sector's hammering has been overdone
and indiscriminate. ``Investors tend to machine-gun the whole
group,'' said Drake Johnstone of Davenport &AMP; Co. That means that
there may be good buys among the injured. And for those who already
own some of these stocks, it may be wise to hold on.
</P>
<P>
   The ever-changing playing field can be difficult to follow.
Qwest absorbed U S West, a Baby Bell, this summer, but not before U
S West's cable arm, the MediaOne Group, was bought by AT&AMP;T, which
shed the Baby Bells in 1984. AT&AMP;T, now the long-distance giant, has
moved heavily into cable, while would-be competitors are forming
joint ventures. BellSouth and SBC Communications, meanwhile, are
combining wireless operations in a new stock.
</P>
<P>
   Investors can no longer distinguish companies by services _
long-distance and local telephone, wireless service and land lines,
digital data and video. Each company wants to provide the whole
package. ``These folks are trying to hang onto as much of the old
business as they can and get as much of the new,'' said Thomas
Wolzien, who follows the cable industry for Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP;
Co. ``Everyone is trying to eat everyone else's lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will end up with big lunches? Bruce Behrens, co-manager of
the $2.3-billion Flag Investors Communication fund, favors
companies that were traditionally in local service. ``The idea of
long-distance versus local is an artifact of regulation,'' Behrens
said. With fiber optics, phone companies pay little more to carry
calls for long distances than short, he added, and local carriers
are better positioned to woo new customers.
</P>
<P>
   He and his co-manager, Liam Burke, along with other analysts,
like SBC. In the first six weeks that the company offered
long-distance service in Texas, it signed up a half-million
customers, and it may hit a million by the end of the year. The
company is aggressively rolling out digital subscriber line
technology, or DSL, to transmit high-speed Internet data over phone
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Burke likes SBC's strategy of using joint ventures to get into
cellular and long-distance services. ``It shows sensitivity to
capital expenditures,'' Burke said. SBC is trading at $45.06, 18.8
percent off its 52-week high of $55.50, and at 17.3 times next
year's projected earnings of $2.60 a share. That compares with a
price-to-earnings ratio of 29.9 for the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth, meanwhile, has generally retained analysts'
confidence, but it has raised some concerns, with a failed bid for
the Sprint Corp. last fall, for example. And the company's slow
rollout of DSL has troubled analysts, too. Johnstone advises
holding BellSouth, to see if it can accelerate DSL installations.
The stock is trading at $40.
</P>
<P>
   He also advises holding Verizon Communications, although some
fund managers call it an attractive buy. Verizon, the combination
of Bell Atlantic and GTE, is also slow in rolling out DSL, he said.
``Part of the game is how quickly you can provide these services,''
he said. When consumers have no DSL alternative, cable companies
jump in to offer cable modem Internet service along with video and
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon is under attack from competitors in its business-laden
territories in New York, Washington and Baltimore. It recently
raised its expected capital needs for this year and next to $18
billion, from $13 billion. The stock, which traded at $66 in April,
is now at $44.31.
</P>
<P>
   Behrens and Burke say the big long-distance players _ AT&AMP;T,
Sprint and WorldCom _ face fundamental problems as boundaries
disappear between long-distance and local calling. But they are
worth more than their current severely depressed stock prices,
Behrens added. ``All these companies do have assets that can work
for them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's residential long-distance revenue was down last quarter,
and revenue from its business segment was also weak. Standard &AMP;
Poor's warned last month that it might cut the company's gilt-edged
credit and debt ratings because of ``concerns regarding AT&AMP;T's
cable television strategy, long-term prospects for AT&AMP;T's core
long-distance business, a more aggressive wireless expansion plan,
and its overall strategic direction.'' AT&AMP;T recently began offering
five months of free cable service to meet year-end goals for new
customers, but the question is whether those customers will stay
after the free period, Johnstone said. He recommends a wait-and-see
approach.
</P>
<P>
   However, David Goldsmith at the Buckingham Research Group said
investors should be focusing on AT&AMP;T's long-term picture. ``The
company is undervalued because people are focusing on the short
term,'' Goldsmith said.
</P>
<P>
   The shares closed Friday at $30.25, down 39.8 percent for the
year. AT&AMP;T Wireless, which trades as a separate stock, has been
strong.
</P>
<P>
   Worldcom, thwarted in its attempt to acquire Sprint, wants to
turn its focus to business customers. The company, aiming to expand
into Web hosting _ services and infrastructure to support Web sites
_ said last week that it had agreed to buy Intermedia
Communications, which holds a majority of Digex Inc., a Web hosting
company.
</P>
<P>
   Also last week, WorldCom executives warned that revenue for the
next few years would drop below forecasts. In light of the
announcements, Johnstone changed his recommendation from buy to
hold. He favors Qwest among long-distance carriers.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom hit a 52-week low of $32.56 in August and now trades at
$29.94, 16.1 times projected earnings for next year.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts favor challengers like Global Crossing _ but
expect the entire sector to pick up soon. ``I can't imagine it
going much lower,'' Burke said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
