<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6976 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-NITEOUT-MTVAWARDS-$AD     09-08 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-MTVAWARDS-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VIDEO SO GRAINY: CELEBSPOTTING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, Calif.)   (For release Sunday, Sept. 10)  
 By GUY TREBAY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Britney Spears owes Joey Heatherton a big one, and
let's not forget the unpaid image debt incurred by Christina
Aguilera and Mandy Moore. Heatherton, the older reader may recall,
was a Long Island-born nymphet who parlayed her hooded eyes, blond
shag and husky alto into a long career as a cut-rate Lolita,
playing Las Vegas lounges, episodes of ``Laverne &AMP; Shirley'' and
many seasons of Serta Perfect Sleeper mattress ads.
</P>
<P>
   As sex kittens go, Heatherton was no Sue Lyon. But then Lyon
never had Heatherton's staying power as a demicelebrity and sultry
permateen. That, after all, is the hold Spears, Moore and Aguilera
have on the popular imagination, as anyone who saw the MTV Video
Music Awards on Thursday night can verify. As did Heatherton before
them, these women look as if they could get you arrested. Unlike
her, however, they've used that appeal to build major recording
careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recording'' may be the wrong word in that sentence. That these
women (Aguilera in particular) can sing is not in question. That
they do sing is probably moot. Their real appeal is probably closer
to that of calendar models. These just happen to move. Anyway,
music of all sorts was weirdly secondary on Thursday to the more
central experience of watching the celebrity machine grind away.
</P>
<P>
   For six hours or so, the Avenue of the Americas became a
red-carpeted conveyor belt on which singing starlets were cranked
past banks of cameras, followed by gangsta rappers and dimpled boy
bands and superannuated rockers who had apparently lost the
directions to the Aged Rock Star Country Home. (Memo to Steve
Tyler: Have you considered a Roth IRA?)
</P>
<P>
   It was a night of limos more extended than some careers.
(Remember Ricky Martin? So hot eight months ago, yet no one seemed
too excited about his shaking bonbon now.) It was a night of cheap
fur, do-rags, statement eyeglasses, fake Gucci, real Gucci,
jailhouse denims, wonderfully bad rock fashions (the rock singer
Pink dressed as if she were the offspring of Sid icious and Poison
Ivy of the Cramps), crimped blond tresses, bleached Afros, platform
boots and compulsory Wonderbras.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm standing looking down at bald spots and cleavage,'' said a
V.J. posted on the balcony inside Radio City Music Hall. Some of
them were on the same people, as he went on to say.
</P>
<P>
   It was a night of journalists' reporting on events by watching
television in Rockefeller Plaza tents, and of fans crammed behind
police barricades a block from the Music Hall, idly hoping to catch
a glimpse of someone, anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trapped, basically,'' said Felicia Buchert, who had
come from Florida just for the show. ``Maybe we'll see Madonna. Who
knows?''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen. Madonna was in Morocco plucking her eyebrows
and changing diapers for her infant son, Rocco, as she explained by
satellite phone to MTV's Serena Altschul. Most of the other
notables were sequestered in nearby hotel rooms, their limo
arrivals timed with air-traffic-control precision, their
appearances calculated exclusively in terms of television time.
</P>
<P>
   Even the 100 guys who had been hired to walk behind Eminem
dressed like him in white T-shirts as he sang ``The Real Slim
Shady,'' winner of the Best Male Video award, barely saw the
singer. Parked in the solarium of the Women's National Republican
Club on 51st Street until showtime, they missed most of the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically got told some lies,' said Joseph Brugess, 20, of
Queens, who got the job after answering a Web site ad asking for
Eminem look-alikes with bleached blond hair. ``They led us to
believe we were going to be on stage,'' he said. Instead, ``we're
stuck here 8 hours yesterday, 11 hours today, and all we're getting
paid is 80 beans.''
</P>
<P>
   For those lucky few granted media access to a corridor around
Radio City, a few quiet hours at the Calvin Coolidge Library in the
Women's National Republican Club started to seem appealing. There
are limited returns on a middle distance sighting of, say, the
rapper Sisqo, who would be easy to miss even at close range.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he 5 feet, even?'' asked Delores McFadden, a tourist who
had miraculously finagled her way past the New York Police
Department, MTV security and the Music Hall guards to find a spot
near the theater entrance. ``I mean, you can barely see the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars tend to be like that, McFadden noted, zeppelin egos in
Napoleonic bodies. ``Well, you could see eye to eye with Sting, at
least,'' she told a bystander who had momentarily mistaken the
wizened singer for the venerable actor Richard Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Even fragments of Sisqo and Sting were more than Javier Perez
got. After waiting since 4 a.m. for a chance to see the celebrity
arrivals, Perez, 17, wound up squeezed into a patch of sidewalk
across the Avenue of the Americas. Standing on tiptoe, he did
briefly catch a glimpse of a mohawk belonging to the Red Hot Chili
Peppers bass player, Flea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was a really cool memory,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even this fleeting apparition was more than Christina Peterson
and Stacey Sawaya, of California and Ohio respectively, got as they
sat by a truck bay from which, someone had told them, 'N Sync might
make its escape.
</P>
<P>
   As for this reporter, he finally fetched up outside the defunct
Fashion Cafe, where some of the 26 little people hired to add a
frisson to the evening's Blink 182 finale were hanging out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I almost didn't come,'' said Niki Botelho-Pabros, a
3-foot-6-inch performer who was dressed for the night in a
leopard-print bikini top with leather dominatrix armbands and
combat boots. Dragging on a Marlboro Light, Botelho-Pabros said:
``I thought it would be exploitative, and I tend to stay away from
that stigma type of elf and clown job.''
</P>
<P>
   She decided to stick around, however, when it became clear that
to exploit a bunch of dwarfs and midgets for shock appeal would be
difficult to accomplish on an awards show where Howard Stern once
flew from the rafters baring his behind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
