<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6979 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-LORETTA-LYNN10-COX     09-08 2206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LORETTA-LYNN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At 66, Loretta Lynn remains a `Honky Tonk Girl' in a Nashville
gone uptown
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 10.
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HURRICANE MILLS, Tenn. _ About 65 miles west of Nashville, not
far off an interstate exit distinguished only by a truck plaza and
a diner with a winking catfish on the roof, country music legend
Loretta Lynn is light-years away from the glass-and-steel office
temples that now line Music Row.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a booth on her purple tour bus, which is parked just
down the road from her home, she looks more like a housewife than a
star, her face dusted slightly with makeup, cotton shirttails
hanging over a pair of jeans tucked into the only accessory that
smacks of show business: a pair of bright blue cowboy boots.
</P>
<P>
   ``They was made by, oh ... you know ... oh, what's his name ...
uh ... Nudie! That's it. They was made by Nudie,'' she says,
sticking a foot out from under the table to show off the work of
the flashy Nudie Cohen, the late costume designer who pasted
Nashville in rhinestones in the 1940s and '50s. Pointing to a black
heel that juts forward at a cocky 45-degree angle, she wisecracks,
``The only thing is, this darn thing makes me feel like I'm walkin'
on the middle of my foot.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn's idea of being a country star doesn't have much to do with
designer clothes, laminated backstage passes or exclusivity. Hers
is the old-school, approachable kind of country music, the one
where working-class people weep over a beer to your lyrics, then
stand in line for hours to get your autograph or have you kiss
their twitching kids.
</P>
<P>
   Her fans have gathered this evening to catch Lynn in a rare
concert appearance at her sprawling, river-bottom homestead. The
100-acre-plus compound, which she turned into a tourist attraction
in the early 1970s, contains her white-columned plantation house
(immortalized in the 1980 bio-pic ``Coal Miner's Daughter''), a
replica of the ramshackle Kentucky cabin she grew up in, an RV
park, a dirt-bike course, riding trails, a giant statue of a carved
wooden Indian, a hayride wagon, a souvenir shop and the open-air
concert hall where her bus is parked.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's been more than 20 years since Lynn's string of hit
records (``You're Looking at Country,'' ``One's on the Way,''
``Fist City''), her fans sit crowded on bleachers under a sweaty
outdoor pavilion that's not likely to show up on any Ticketmaster
seating chart. They're a blue-collar crowd _ mostly older folks in
shirtsleeves, T-shirts, baseball caps and sneakers, the kind of
people who're more likely to buy their country music at the counter
of a truck stop than at Tower.
</P>
<P>
   You get the feeling that if she didn't have to perform her
homecoming show tonight, Lynn would probably shuck off her shoes
and go barefoot across the sawdust floor. Instead, she's angling
for a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   At 66, four decades into a career that has made her not just a
country superstar but an American icon, Lynn is releasing a new
album _ her first set of original tunes in 12 years. ``Still
Country,'' which hits stores Tuesday, not only has her making some
of her richest music in decades _ songs that sound much like the
hits of her heyday _ but contains older-skewing lyrics about being
``On My Own.''
</P>
<P>
   The CD, which will sit in Wal-Mart racks next to discs from much
younger, pop-oriented acts such as Faith Hill and Shania Twain, is
packaged to make a bit of a political statement as well: On the
cover, the word ``Still'' is italicized.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're almost sticking it in people's noses and going
nyahhhhhh,'' says Nick Hunter, the Nashville record executive who
was thrilled to be able to sign Lynn to his upstart independent
label, Audium Records, last year. (For 35 years, she had been on
Decca/MCA.) ``As times change, some people don't think Loretta is
the image they want country to be anymore. But I'm not sure that
people running record companies care about the tradition and image
of country music.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;  Lynn's tin-roof twang may be the stuff of legend, but it's
not exactly the kind of music today's polished country radio
stations want to play. The 12 tracks on the new album don't deviate
one note from the backwoods style Lynn established on her first
record, ``Honky Tonk Girl,'' in thick, mountain dialect in which
``bare'' becomes ``bar'' (as in ``bar-footed''), fingers are
``fangers'' and wash is ``warsh.'' The new single ``Country in My
Genes,'' released last month, delivers fiddle and thick steel
guitar. It is not on the playlists of either of Atlanta's country
superstations, Kicks 101.5 and Eagle 106.7.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a place for Loretta Lynn, but it's not in mainstream
country now,'' says Kicks music director Johnny Gray. ``We have for
years played her music on our `Country Gold Saturday Night'
segments, because we respect her and what she's meant to country
music. But she's still very traditional in her approach to music,
which is fine but certainly doesn't fit country radio now, which is
targeted to people 25 to 54.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn thinks he has it backward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never left country music, everybody else did,'' she says,
taking a swipe at the current state of Nashville. ``It's made me a
good livin'. Why should I go in another direction?''
</P>
<P>
   The course that she's taking at this point in her famous life is
one that not many established or wealthy music stars travel. With
six children, 29 grandchildren, money in the bank from a jukebox
full of hit records and even a plaque in the Country Music Hall of
Fame, Lynn could easily settle into comfortable retirement on her
spread near the banks of the Duck River, making guest appearances
at awards shows or in younger artists' music videos. The 1980 movie
about her life, ``Coal Miner's Daughter'' (which seems to air
virtually every week on TBS), based on her autobiographical book of
the same name, secured her fame. She's even working on a sequel,
due for publication next spring. But the spunky mannerisms that
actress Sissy Spacek turned into Oscar gold still define the star
from Butcher Holler, Ky.: oblivious determination, a stunning
bluntness, and confidence that she's still a vital star.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people her age are checking out, and here she is checking
in once again,'' says Grand Ole Opry President Pete Fisher. ``Great
country music is, oftentimes, about consistent imperfection, that
artist who presents themselves honestly _ `take me as I am.' You
know once she gets up there and sings those songs, that's who she
is. She's not part of the mass-media machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn's producer, Nashville instrumental whiz Randy Scrugg,
agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't believe she's an artist of the past,'' Scrugg
says. ``She thinks she has something to say now. ... She's so real,
the true essence of the type of artist I've always wanted to work
with. And there aren't many of them left.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;  Lynn was publicly silent throughout much of the '90s, when
she retreated into her white-columned mansion to care for her
ailing husband, Oliver _ better known as ``Mooney'' or
``Doolittle.'' The roughneck Kentucky coal miner who married her
when she was just 13 (Tommy Lee Jones made a sexier version of him
famous on film) battled diabetes, eventually losing both legs, his
eyesight and his hearing. In 1996, the man who helped Lynn climb
out of the harsh mining life of Appalachia, bought her her first
guitar and pounded on the door of every country disc jockey to play
her records died.
</P>
<P>
   She had never lived alone in her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember nothin','' Lynn says. ``That first year, I
just don't remember. You know one day you're gonna lose 'em, but
you're never ready for it. ... I lost 12 people in four years: two
brothers, Conway (Twitty), two aunts, four uncles, Tammy (Wynette),
cousins. I just was in denial that anything had happened. I had the
house completely rebuilt, 'cause I could not live there the way it
was. Too many memories.''
</P>
<P>
   About a year later, she was walking in front of a Nashville
department store when she felt herself come back to life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw this mink coat in the window, and I said, `I'm gonna get
that. I don't care if it fits me or not. So I went in there and
bought me a full-length mink coat,'' she laughs. ``What did I need
it for? Where have I been that's that cold? But I'd never bought
one. I never went noplace. And haven't got to wear it. We've got it
in storage. I don't need it really. I just bought it.''
</P>
<P>
   That act of impulse shopping was, perhaps, the beginning of
Lynn's personal and professional resurgence.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;  In the decade she spent in virtual isolation caring for
``Doo,'' Nashville _ both the music scene and the city itself _ had
become virtually unrecognizable. The funky old houses that once
held Music Row publishing companies, where Lynn had knocked on
doors in the early '60s, had been torn down, replaced by high-rise
buildings filled with offices headed by young executives wearing
Armani suits. Without hits on the charts, Lynn's 35-year
association with MCA/Decca Records came to an end. Her longtime
producer, the legendary Owen Bradley, died in January 1998. And,
for the first time in her life, there was no Mooney to manage her
career.
</P>
<P>
   The husband-wife team were a notorious duo, fighting and making
up with the over-the-top emotions mirrored in Lynn's scorchingly
literal songs: ``Don't Come Home a-Drinkin' (With Loving on Your
Mind)'' or ``Your Squaw Is on the Warpath Tonight.'' While Mooney
did much to encourage his wife's career, the resulting riches and
public spotlight were often too much for a man who perceived
himself as more good ol' boy than grandstander. When Loretta drove
120 miles per hour in her big Cadillac (``Shoot, it said it could
go that fast, so that must mean I can drive it that fast''), Mooney
took away the car keys. He also liked his whiskey (hence his
nickname), resulting in an ongoing cat-and-mouse game of
``gotcha!'' with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to her rural mansion after the purging renovations
following Mooney's death, Lynn finally came to terms with the loss
of her powerful husband. Recently, she was even able to laugh about
their life together.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're never gonna believe what I found today,'' she says,
slapping her hands on the Formica table in front of her. ``I found
the last pint of whiskey I hid from Doolittle! I'd hid it behind
all the pots and pans and stuff that I didn't use unless it was a
holiday. I got down there in all them drawers this week and I found
it. And I said, `This is going in my museum!'''
</P>
<P>
   Just over the hill from the concert pavilion, across the street
from her stately home, Lynn is building a museum, to open next
spring, to house the memories of her life _ that speeding Cadillac,
her first stage dress (a homemade cowgirl suit) and props from
``Coal Miner's Daughter,'' a movie she says she ``hates'' to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many places where I just have to turn my head, it
hurts so much. A lot of stuff went much deeper than what people
know. Some of the bad things in there went much deeper.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mooney's last pint of whiskey will be on display.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect Lynn to become a curator. With the new album's
release, she's scheduled to make the rounds of late-night talk
shows, and she'll commence a book tour when the new autobiography,
``Still Woman Enough,'' is released by Hyperion next spring. It
picks up where ``Coal Miner's Daughter,'' published in 1976, left
off. She even has a boyfriend, an Arkansas ``Bible teacher'' whom
she met after listening to his inspirational tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lost his wife about the same time I lost Doo. ... He sent
me a picture of him on the back of an old mule named Pearl. I
laughed and said, `He's gotta be country'.''
</P>
<P>
   She says they see each other ``about every six months.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;  As for recording success, Lynn's new label plans to market
her new single and album to small country stations rather than the
big guys. While Kicks 101.5 and Eagle 106.7 may not be playing the
new tune, it has made the air on small-market stations such as
WCON/99.3 FM in Cornelia, where general manager Bobbie Foster says
she's playing ``Country in My Genes'' ``about twice a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Audium will also pitch the new record to the growing
``Americana'' radio market of alternative country music, where Lynn
is an icon. But she's somewhat oblivious to the marketing machine,
saying simply, ``What does `alternative' mean? Don't ask me.''
</P>
<P>
   As the sun goes down over hazy river-bottom fields planted with
corn and soybeans, Lynn takes the stage as she has a thousand times
before, her hand grasping the cord of a microphone as she belts out
her hits. The plain stage is decorated with red, white and blue
flags that look like they were borrowed from a parade float. The
audience swishes cardboard church fans in time to the music.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in the distance, kids are shooting off fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at all you folks out there, my gosh,'' Lynn says,
welcoming her fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure do love sangin' for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
