<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6981 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-SOC-$ADV11-NYT &LR;      09-08 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SOC-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: SOCCER  
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the grand and sometimes hoary traditions of soccer is
that every tournament no matter how big or small, must have a Group
of Death. That is to say, one bracket is inevitably stronger than
the others.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the Grupo de Muerte is a cliche, but at these Summer
Games it is a fact. The defending women's Olympic and World Cup
champions _ one and the same _ from the United States have been
placed in the brutal half of the draw.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans _ heroes of Atlanta, the stars of Pasadena _ must
play Norway first, then China and then Nigeria, with only two of
those four teams going to the semifinals. The lopsided draw came
about because the host team, Australia _ perhaps the weakest team
in the Olympic tournament _ was automatically seeded first, somehow
winding up in a group with Germany, Sweden and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   This arrangement is serious business.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the Women's World Cup, now a legitimate worldwide
attraction because of U.S. marketing in 1999, the Olympics are the
biggest event for female players. Failing to get to the semifinals
would be a jolt to China or Norway or the United States, and that
is precisely what is going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   THE WOMEN
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women are now coached by April Heinrichs, a former
star. They are sending 14 of the 18 players who won the 1999 World
Cup _ Mia Hamm, Kristine Lilly, et al.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been considerable retooling, with Michelle Akers
announcing her retirement. Siri Mullinix may have supplanted Briana
Scurry in goal, and the veteran defender Carla Overbeck will be
more marginal this time around.
</P>
<P>
   THE MEN
</P>
<P>
   The men's tournament is the usual hybrid Olympic affair,
essentially a 23-and-under championship spiced with a maximum of
three older players per team.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil declined to bolster its squad after a team psychologist
deduced that the younger players' egos would be hurt by the
inclusion of older players. The Americans did not publicly voice
such touchy-feely sentiments. Coach Clive Charles picked up Jeff
Agoos, 32; Frankie Hejduk, 26; and Brad Friedel, 29.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the squad consists of decent younger players from
Major League Soccer and European teams, plus one college player.
The Yanks will play the Czech Republic, Cameroon and Kuwait, hoping
to be one of two teams from the group to advance to the
quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   They will surely insist that they, too, have been placed in the
Gruppo di Morte. Just about everybody claims that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
