<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spotlight on color
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 10.
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This fall, fashion's mood has shifted from minimalism to
opulence, and makeup's following suit.
</P>
<P>
   The newest cosmetic colors ooze with an attitude of indulgence
and confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women should have fun with makeup this fall. It's very
retro,'' says Iris Ingram-Hopgood, a Stone Mountain, Ga.,-based
makeup artist.
</P>
<P>
   For fall, the focus is on lips and eyes, but never both at the
same time. Like having two divas in the same room, something's
bound to clash.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the intensity is going to be the lip, go lighter on the
eye, or vice versa. You really want to draw the attention to one
area,'' advises Faith Edwards, an Atlanta makeup artist.
</P>
<P>
   Reds take center stage for nails and lips in a variety of ripe
berry hues. For new lip shades check out ``Lady Danger,'' a
blackened red by M.A.C., ``Chili Thrill,'' a spicy red by Revlon;
and ``Profond Sommeil,'' a blood-red by Lancome.
</P>
<P>
   Deep reds go with all the colors that are happening this season.
</P>
<P>
   Brown earth tones are also hot for lips and nails. Most
cosmetics lines have something enticing to offer, from Maybelline's
``Barely Beige'' nail enamel and gloss, to Clinique's ``Pink
Chocolate'' and cocoa-toned ``Sugar Bean'' lipstick, to Estee
Lauder's ``Cinnamon Stick,'' ``Nutty Brown'' and ``Fiery Russet''
lip colors.
</P>
<P>
   Practically anyone can wear brown, but a lip liner in, say, a
red or contrasting brown is essential to make it blend with your
skin tone and provide a hint of color. Deep browns don't do justice
to fairer skin tones, unless you're going for a very dramatic
evening look, says Edwards. Darker skins can wear richer, more
intense browns, especially when a dab of sheer gloss is added to
the center of the lip.
</P>
<P>
   The eyes have it when it comes to dramatic color. See
Maybelline's ``Green Glam'' and ``Berry Chic,'' M.A.C.'s
``Infamous'' deep purple and ``Flammable'' crimson, and Estee
Lauder's ``High Pearl in Khaki Summer.'' Blend shadow lightly with
a professional brush or applicator, to avoid smudging.
</P>
<P>
   Blushes are soft and rosy this fall. Get the look with
``L'Oreal's ``Mocha Rose'' and ``Plume.'' For something more
intense, try Maybelline's pinkish-red ``Wild Fire,'' M.A.C.'s
goldish-yellow ``Honour'' and Lancome's deep red ``Potion
Magique.''
</P>
<P>
   A little blush goes a long way, and blending is key, unless you
want Betty Boop cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When applying blush, start in the apple of the cheek and blend
back. You just want a hint of color,'' says Edwards. ``At night,
it's OK to go heavier, but again, go with balance. Adding a little
silver or gold (powder or blush) on top makes it kind of funky for
evening.''
</P>
<P>
   Beauty online
</P>
<P>
   For the hot fall beauty collections, check out these Web sites:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.marykay.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.lorealparis.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.clinique.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.revlon.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.esteelauder.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.maccosmetics.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.avon.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.fashionfaircosmetics.com
</P>
