<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6982 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SABBATH09-COX     09-08 1486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SABBATH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holding fast to the _ and reaping its rewards
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You didn't see anchorwoman Brenda Wood on WXIA's 11 p.m.
newscast last night.
</P>
<P>
   Wood insists on a provision in her contract that guarantees
Friday nights off.
</P>
<P>
   But you probably didn't see her at the mall, the grocery store
or latest trendy nightspot, either.
</P>
<P>
   Wood, a lifelong Seventh-day Adventist, observes the Sabbath
from sundown Friday until sundown Saturday with her husband and two
teenage daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful thing to be able to put everything down and
just rest _ to put away the things of your secular world, all your
worries and responsibilities outside of the home, and really have
time to reflect, spend time with your family and worship God,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Chicken sandwich king Truett Cathy says amen.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy, founder of Chick-fil-A and a faithful member of First
Baptist Church in Jonesboro, has closed his restaurants on Sundays
for 53 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``All our leases in shopping malls are written that we close on
Sunday,'' Cathy said. ``To me, Sunday has always been a very
special day. As a kid, I didn't have to go to school, I didn't have
to do much work around the house, and I got to go to Sunday school
and church.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Cathy teaches a Sunday school class of 13-year-old boys
and includes an occasional lesson on keeping the Sabbath, or as
many Christians call Sunday, the Lord's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to have the reputation of being a hypocrite,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   When Sen. Joe Lieberman of Connecticut, an Orthodox Jew, joined
the Democratic ticket as the vice presidential nominee last month,
he made it clear that he does not intend to campaign on the Jewish
Sabbath. Lieberman's public acknowledgment of his tradition serves
as a stark contrast to the bustling commercialism that has engulfed
many other professing Jews and Christians, who seem to overlook the
commandment to ``remember the Sabbath day, and keep it holy,''
although they wouldn't think of violating the ones against stealing
or killing.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans are not worried about Lieberman neglecting his
job one day a week if elected, however. Asked by an ABC News poll
whether they were ``concerned his religious practices would
interfere with his duties as vice president,'' 89 percent of those
questioned said no.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Bible, the idea of keeping a Sabbath dates back
to the beginning of time _ or at least the first week. The book of
Genesis says, ``And on the seventh day God finished the work that
he had done, and he rested on the seventh day. ... So God blessed
the seventh day and hallowed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Baby boomers and their parents can remember a time when,
especially in the traditionally Christian Bible Belt, there was not
much choice of activity on Sunday. Stores were closed. Athletic
leagues wouldn't think of scheduling games. And a neighbor caught
doing yardwork was the subject of whispered gossip.
</P>
<P>
   The tradition was firmly established in North America in the
17th century when Puritans wrote Sunday observance into law. The
blue binding of their legal code may have given the restrictions
the nickname ``blue laws.'' The laws lasted in many places until
the second half of the 20th century, when state legislatures,
bowing to business pressures, began repealing them or making them
local options.
</P>
<P>
   For many people, Sunday became just another day for running
errands, finishing up work, or getting a head start on the next
week. But now, with Sunday commerce fully entrenched, some people
are mourning the passing of an enforced day of rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American culture has clearly made so much of business
success and making money that the whole Sabbath concept has gotten
lost,'' said Tim Norton of Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   As executive director of the Atlanta-based Lord's Day Alliance
of the United States, Norton now makes his living promoting Sabbath
observance. Since April, when he took the job as head of the
national, interdenominational organization, he has been practicing
what he's preaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a crazy working kind of person,'' Norton said.
``Practicing the Sabbath concept has made an unbelievable
difference in my life. I do rest. I use the day I worship, Sunday,
to be renewed and refreshed. The whole week is a different week for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Norton attends church and spends time with his wife and son.
Sometimes they entertain friends for meals.
</P>
<P>
   For much of its 112-year history, the alliance fought in
legislatures and courts for laws that ensured the right of workers
to a Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   Although the organization still supports some legislation,
Norton said, the focus is evolving into convincing people of the
need to observe a day of rest and worship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to turn our organization to focus on the Sabbath as
a gift of God,'' he said. ``When he created the world in a six-day
frame, whatever those units mean, then he took a day of rest for
himself. He was refreshed spiritually. We are trying to reclaim
that concept.''
</P>
<P>
   So are a couple of Protestant denominations.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 300 regional and national staff members of the 1.5
million-member American Baptist Churches in the U.S.A., the
so-called northern Baptists, gathered in March for a five-day event
called ``God's Servants Together: Keeping Sabbath.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. David Wheeler, senior minister of First Baptist Church
in Los Angeles, set the tone by telling the group that Sabbath ``is
part of the very nature of God ... the renewal and restoration of
original creation, part of the original rhythm ... part of the very
nature of time.''
</P>
<P>
   At its annual meeting in Long Beach, Calif., this summer, the
General Assembly of the 2.6 million-member Presbyterian Church
(U.S.A.) adopted a document called ``An Invitation to Sabbath:
Rediscovering a Gift,'' which will be sent to all the
denomination's congregations and seminaries.
</P>
<P>
   Kristine Haig, the Louisville-based church's coordinator for
spiritual formation, said the document was the result of a two-year
study.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more people are recognizing that we cannot continue
to live as we're living, that we're exhausted, we're burned out, we
have lost joy in our lives, and we feel driven,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even before its official distribution, the document is receiving
overwhelming response. Haig's workshops on Sabbath observance fill
to overflowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally try to take as many Sabbath moments as I can, and
if I'm working on Sunday, I take another day during the week as my
Sabbath,'' she said. ``The sense that we are only entitled to be
breathing air if we're producing something that somebody else says
is worth it, that's demonic. It's evil. It's contrary to what the
Bible teaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, clergy may be among the least likely people to
observe a Sabbath. With services to conduct, they often are their
busiest on their faith's established day of rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunday is the one day a week we work in the minds of most of
our members,'' said the Rev. Bob Setzer, a Southern Baptist
minister in Macon.
</P>
<P>
   Psychotherapist Wayne Muller, who lives in Northern California,
came to Sabbath-keeping when he was hospitalized near death with
the same bacterial infection that killed Muppeteer Jim Henson.
</P>
<P>
   During the long, slow recovery process, Muller, ordained as a
Congregational minister, said he considered the ``power of
dormancy'' for plants, soil and human souls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tides rise and fall, seasons go from spring and summer to fall
and winter, the heart expands and contracts,'' said Muller, author
of ``Sabbath'' (Bantam, $14.95). ``Everything in life moves in
rhythm, but we've convinced ourselves we can go in only one
direction _ forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Marva Dawn, a Lutheran theologian living in Vancouver, Wash.,
came to Sabbath observance less dramatically in 1983 as a doctoral
student at Notre Dame. ``I discovered Sabbath-keeping was a
wonderful way not to go insane,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn, author of ``Keeping the Sabbath Wholly'' (William B.
Eerdmans Publishing Co., $15), incorporates both Jewish and
Christian elements, beginning her Sabbath _ which she starts at
bedtime on Saturday _ by lighting candles and praying.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, she enjoys using her grandmother's china, cooking
special foods and having quiet time with her husband or
entertaining friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason for the day is to recapture our relationship
with God,'' said Dawn. ``My love for God deepens when I experience
the grace of God in other people.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a world of cellular telephones, fax machines and the
Internet, people rarely spend time just reveling in relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in the habit of taking naps, either,'' she said.
``That's a very good thing to do on the Sabbath.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
