<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6983 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS10-COX     09-08 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Adviser Gergen sees four presidents in the round, warts and all
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 10.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Richard Nixon died in 1994, many Americans mourned the dark
prince of a president whose disgrace was without parallel, while
others bit their tongues out of courtesy. President Clinton did not
know how closely his own fate would flirt with Nixon's when he said
in his eulogy, ``Today is a day for his family, his friends and his
nation to remember President Nixon's life in totality. To them, let
us say, may the day of judging President Nixon on anything less
than his entire career come to a close.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, David Gergen believes, one of Clinton's finest moments,
and one whose irony should be lost on no one. Americans have made a
parlor game of ranking their presidents, one reputation rising
while another slips. The Big Three _ Washington, Lincoln and
Franklin Delano Roosevelt _ are secure in the pantheon. A handful
compete for near-greatness, while most have settled into the
posthumous mediocrity that requires no monuments. Only a few are
judged outright failures, and Nixon was sui generis even in
failure.
</P>
<P>
   But with Nixon as with Clinton _ indeed with most of our
presidents _ there is more than what meets the eye, Gergen
believes, and few have seen so many so closely. He served as
speechwriter and policy adviser for three Republican presidents _
Nixon, Gerald Ford and Ronald Reagan _ and crossed party lines when
President Clinton sought his counsel early in his first term. As a
Republican serving a Democratic White House, he raised eyebrows,
but Gergen's interest has always been the effective exercise of
power. In the modern presidency, that might call for the honorable
art of persuasion or it might call for the newer, hardly venerable
technique of damage control.
</P>
<P>
   Gergen's new book, ``Eyewitness to Power: The Essence of
Leadership _ Nixon to Clinton'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $26), is not
quite a primer on the presidency, not entirely a leadership manual,
but very much the memoir of an insider. Gergen saw power exercised
close up, and came away with an appreciation for the complexity of
the men who exercised it. He is not uncritical _ far from it _ but
he sees his subjects in the round. ``Our culture,'' he writes, ``is
too quick to tear down our presidents once they are in office. All
of the six men I have known in office _ from Nixon to Clinton _
have been patriots who cared deeply about the fate of the country.
Several of them made terrible blunders, but they all struggled and
fought to create a better world.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Richard Nixon, who betrayed Gergen's loyalty in the end,
elicits sympathy: ``If Lincoln was justified in suspending habeas
corpus during the Civil War, as many historians believe he was, why
was Nixon _ as commander in chief _ not justified in bending lesser
laws to protect the country's security during the Vietnam War?''
</P>
<P>
   The sufficiently obvious answer is that a civil war was not in
progress, although Gergen believes it was at hand.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point here is his portrayal of four very different
men. Nixon was brilliant, paranoid, self-pitying, socially awkward
and the most intellectually serious student of leadership Gergen
has known. ``The tragedy of Nixon's life,'' he writes, ``is that he
could not live up to his own standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Ford was the necessary contrast, a ``safe'' rather than
exceptional man and yet one underestimated even by those closest to
him: ``I have always thought him the most decent man I have known
in the presidency. But there was something else that mattered even
more. Emotionally, he was the healthiest president we have had
since Eisenhower and Truman. He knew who he was, was at peace with
life, and liked people.''
</P>
<P>
   Words so deceptively simple almost leap off the page. Of how
many accomplished people _ to say nothing of presidents _ can the
same be said? And yet Ford was not, in these respects, terribly
different from Ronald Reagan _ ``in my view, the best leader in the
White House since Franklin Roosevelt.'' Reagan, Gergen writes,
``was not just comfortable in his own skin. He was serene.'' At the
same time, he ``had less curiosity about public policy than any
president since perhaps the 1920s,'' and was ``so dreamy and
inattentive to detail that he allowed dramatic mistakes to occur.''
But no one was so clear about what he wanted to do, and no one so
much enjoyed coming to work. His buoyance reassured Americans at a
time when they had been browbeaten by worriers.
</P>
<P>
   To come, then, to President Clinton is to return to the enigma
of intellectual gifts yoked to self-destructive impulses. Clinton's
presidency will not end in ruins like Nixon's, but he can only hope
that it will be seen in its totality. ``When he decamps and the
dust settles,'' Gergen writes, ``we will look back and see that
despite the scandals, he left the country far better off than he
found it.''
</P>
<P>
   But he will never be a model of leadership. He didn't want so
much to lead as to share power _ with his wife, with his vice
president _ and it cost him almost as much as his problems with
women and truth. The real troubles of his two terms, Gergen
surmises, have not been the ones in the headlines, but ``other,
more fundamental problems he brought to the presidency.'' Where
Nixon knew right from wrong, and chose wrong, Clinton ``has
360-degree vision but no true north.'' Few presidents have been his
intellectual equal, but most had a working compass.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
