r e BC-WEBRADIO10-COX     09-08 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBRADIO10-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Interactivity: Hear it loud and clear
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 10.
</P>
<P>
   By Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   Radio is radio, whether it's on the Web, in your car or pumping
from your home stereo. It's just an avenue for entertainment or
edification. But there are things that set the Web variety apart.
Aside from the lack of geographical constraints, Web radio has at
least one other advantage: immediate interactivity.
</P>
<P>
   Some Internet-only radio outlets have found ways to use the
medium and its immediacy to greater advantage. Many exclusively
online stations are DJ-less musical advertisements, streaming tunes
while the title and artist are displayed on your player along with
a link to order the CDs online.
</P>
<P>
   Sites such as iTurf (www.iturf
</P>
<P>
   .com) and Soundbreak.com (www.soundbreak.com) are taking things
to a higher frequency. Soundbreak.com launched earlier this year,
targeting listeners ages 15 to 35. The playlist leans toward the
alternative/modern rock format, with a more wide-ranging sound than
most non-Web modern-rock stations.
</P>
<P>
   Among Soundbreak's executives is former MTV VJ Mark Goodman, who
is vice president of music programming. ``We're not another Web
radio station; we're a forward-thinking Internet music destination
with live round-the-clock DJs,'' Goodman declares. ``We're all
committed to exposing new artists and being the signpost for new
directions in music.''
</P>
<P>
   Soundbreak listeners can be viewers, too. A camera is positioned
in the studio, sending out video of the DJs, and the chat feature
allows users to interact with the people in the studio and other
listeners 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   The interactive element really comes in handy when celebrities
visit the Soundbreak studios. To celebrate the site's launching,
the five original MTV VJs reunited for a chat with netizens in
February. Since then, the site has hosted chats with Ice-T, Fatboy
Slim, Linda Blair and former Guns N' Roses guitarist Slash, to name
a few.
</P>
<P>
   Soundbreak's site is graphics-intensive, so a high-speed
connection and a computer of recent vintage make a visit much more
pleasurable. One hint for slower connections: Get rid of the main
window and just keep the pop-up with video and audio feed on your
desktop.
</P>
<P>
   Another interactive radio site, iTurf, targets teenagers. It
recently entered the Web radio fray on a more limited basis than
Soundbreak. The site is the home of a network of teen-centric
ventures, including gURL.com, the Spark and Droog, all accessible
via the main iTurf site.
</P>
<P>
   ITurf's radio station is live from 1 p.m. to 1 a.m. weekdays,
with an all-request format and a chat feature that serves as the
conduit to the DJs for song requests. Like Soundbreak, iTurf offers
a video feed for higher-speer connections. You can choose from
three connection speeds, or just listen to one of four non-live
music streams.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Harrison writes for the Atlanta Journal-Consitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
