<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6985 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-CROWE10-COX     09-08 1378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROWE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Almost Famous' relives heady days of rock
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 10.
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can blame Cameron Crowe for kicking off the teen-movie trend
when his book ``Fast Times at Ridgemont High'' was filmed in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   You can blame him, in 1996, for sticking us with several
maddeningly persistent catch phrases (``Show me the money,'' ``You
complete me,'' ``You had me at hello'') from ``Jerry Maguire.''
</P>
<P>
   But you can't blame Crowe for loving rock 'n' roll. It's a love
that started when he was a teenager in San Diego, turned on to the
music by his older sister. Befriended by rock critic Lester Bangs,
Crowe wrote his first cover story for Rolling Stone magazine at age
15, traveling around the country with Led Zeppelin, the Allman
Brothers, the Who and other bands as both fan and chronicler of the
1970s music scene.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Almost Famous,'' which opens Friday, Crowe puts a fictional
spin on his own story. It's the cinematic coming-of-age of
15-year-old alter ego William Miller (Patrick Fugit), who gets on
board the bus of a band called Stillwater, fronted by singer Jeff
Bebe (Jason Lee) and brooding guitarist Russell Hammond (Billy
Crudup).
</P>
<P>
   Just as important to the story are the nonstars, the teenage
muses of the band who reject the term ``groupies'' and call
themselves the Band Aids, led by a child vixen with the adopted
name Penny Lane (Kate Hudson).
</P>
<P>
   The movie's rock credentials are solid. Seventies teen king
Peter Frampton, a longtime friend of Crowe's, served as technical
consultant for the concert scenes and plays a bit role. Crowe's
wife, Nancy Wilson, half of the '70s sister band Heart, wrote the
score and penned, with Crowe, the songs that Stillwater sings. And
Bangs, now deceased, turns up in the movie, played by Philip
Seymour Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent promotional tour, Crowe talked about his love of
music, fond memories of Atlanta, the real ``Penny Lane'' and the
hair-raising experience of screening ``Almost Famous'' for Robert
Plant and Jimmy Page of Led Zeppelin to get their approval to use
the band's music.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you notice that DreamWorks is positioning your movie the
same way it did ``American Beauty'' last year?
</P>
<P>
   A: Really? That's cool. I'm just glad we got to come here and
talk about it. I always loved Atlanta. In 1973, the first day of
the Who's Quadrophenia tour was Atlanta. So I got to come. Lynyrd
Skynyrd were opening at the Omni, and it was an amazing night. I
was covering the Who, and I'd just had my first cover story come
out. Ronnie Van Zant sought me out to say he'd read my story on the
Allman Brothers Band. He just said, ``Man, you're a good writer,
and I wanted to introduce myself, and I hope one day we'll be
honored by you writing something about us.'' That was an amazing
thing to me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And you were what _ 15, 16?
</P>
<P>
   A: I was 16. I had long hair and I'd always let it hang in my
face, because it would keep people from seeing how young I really
was. I sort of fit in because (the musicians) all had long hair in
their face, so I could walk through lobbies with them and feel like
I belonged, much more than in high school.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Maybe it's a stretch, but I found a common theme between this
movie and ``Jerry Maguire.'' In this case the setting is music; in
that one it was sports. But both are about talent having to battle
the corporate marketing-packaging mind-set. Is that intentional?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah. (Laughs.) Yeah, it's a very similar theme, I guess, and
where humanity winds its way through that story is pretty
interesting to me. I love the effect of fandom, what happens when
you love something, and you follow it through its stages of growth.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You just screened this for Robert Plant and Jimmy Page. What
was that like?
</P>
<P>
   A: Nerve-racking. Elton John (whose song ``Tiny Dancer'' plays
in one scene) never seemed as long as when you're showing the movie
to Led Zeppelin. Their music seemed real skimpily used, suddenly.
We didn't want to overdo it, because we didn't think we had
approval. But they gave us the approval and encouraged us to use
more of it. Which for me was ``the victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the movie, William's sister turns him on to rock 'n' roll.
Did your sister do that in real life?
</P>
<P>
   A: She absolutely did. ``Cheap Thrills'' was one of the pivotal
albums that didn't make it into the montage of album covers (seen
in the film). But, yeah, it's about 95 percent true.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why did it take so long to settle on a title?
</P>
<P>
   A: The truth is that I was very decisive about the title. I
wanted to call it ``Untitled.'' But after about a year and a half
of trying to convince the studio that it was cool to have a movie
without a title, I finally lost that battle. (He laughs.) Then we
went with the final title, named after the band's tour name. And it
fits because the movie is also about the people on the side of the
stage, outside the spotlight. When you're watching a band, you see
these people that are the guests, and you think, ``Who are those
people?''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was there a real Penny Lane, or was she a composite?
</P>
<P>
   A: Both. I always loved her name, and I loved her spirit. She
was a real muse girl, the real Penny Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Q: She used the name ``Penny Lane''?
</P>
<P>
   A: She did. Her real name was Penny Trumble. We named one of the
songs on the soundtrack after her, ``Lucky Trumble.'' We wanted to
pay tribute to her. She lives in Oregon. She never wrote a tell-all
book. She had a name for her crew _ it wasn't the Band Aids, it was
the Garter Girls. She's great. She actually could be the third
Wilson sister. She has similar qualities.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has she seen the movie?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah, she wrote me a letter. She said, ``If I die, I know
this thing has been left behind that explained with a certain
amount of nobility what I was like when I was younger.'' It was a
great letter.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You're riding the line between fiction and fact, revisiting
your teen self, and incorporating a real figure like your mentor,
Lester Bangs. Did it ever seem overwhelming, trying to keep that
all balanced?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's funny you should say that, ``overwhelming.'' When Philip
Seymour Hoffman first showed up and we started doing his sequences
_ ``overwhelming'' is the word. ... I felt a pressure to get Lester
right. And I still do. That was a tough one. I did think of
changing his name to ``Roger Banks'' or something.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Your movie touches on the tricky relationship between a
journalist and his subject. When is writing about someone a
betrayal? And you have Lester's advice, ``Be honest, but
unmerciful.''
</P>
<P>
   A: I've now learned what it's like to have that fed back to me.
One of the first times I showed the movie to the studio, they
called me back and they were like, ``Lester Bangs says to be honest
and unmerciful. Can we be honest and unmerciful with you?'' And I
thought, great. This is not how I wanted Lester to be quoted. It
gives people license to be needlessly brutal sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have a take on the music scene now vs. when you
started out in the '70s?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's so much more accessible now. One of my first concerts
was going to see the Who. I still love the Who. I stick them into
every movie. So I go to see the show in '71, I had the cheap seats
and I was milling around by the floor. The lights went down, the
crowd smashed us all right against the stage, and the Who came on.
I couldn't breathe. I was right against this wooden barricade. Pete
Townshend came onstage. He had some kind of English crown, and they
started playing ``I Can't Explain.'' He looked 30 feet tall. They
all looked huge. If anybody had told me on that night that soon all
of these people were going to be reduced to television size, I
would have said no way. But now they are. Everybody is accessible,
everybody is a TV star. The thing that movie stars always tell you,
which I never knew, is that you're untouchable until you go on TV.
When you're on TV, people on the street feel like they know you.
The mystique takes a hit. And the mystique of rock has taken a hit,
for better or worse.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
