<HEADER>
A6986 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-CRUISE-EXPERT10-COX     09-08 1481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUISE-EXPERT10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Set sail with travel agents' expertise
 &HT;    Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 10.
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A cruise can be like your favorite TV show _ it can carry you
away to a ``Fantasy Island,'' introduce you to new ``Friends'' and,
just maybe, help you find someone who's ``Mad About You.''
</P>
<P>
   But a cruise can also be a comedy of errors if you don't do your
homework _ choose one that's not your style and you might feel
you've set sail with a bunch of ``Freaks and Geeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, an experienced travel agent can help you tune in to the
right cruise for your needs. We asked three local agents, who
collectively have sailed on more than 150 cruises, to pick the top
trips for different types of travelers. Follow their advice and
your next cruise should bring you ``Good Times.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Heinrich
</P>
<P>
   Elite Cruise Service
</P>
<P>
   Roswell, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   770-552-7809,
</P>
<P>
   www.elitecruise.com
</P>
<P>
   The owner of Elite Cruise Service (founded in 1992), Heinrich
has sailed on more than 50 cruises on every major line. Her agency
is featured on the online travel network vacation.com.
</P>
<P>
   Howard S. Moses
</P>
<P>
   The Cruise Authority
</P>
<P>
   Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   1-800-326-4971
</P>
<P>
   www.the-cruise-authority
</P>
<P>
   .com
</P>
<P>
   Moses founded the Cruise Authority in 1988. He has sailed on 88
cruises and has appeared on CNN news segments and ``CNN Travel
Now,'' talking about cruising issues.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Alan Reinke
</P>
<P>
   Peachtree Travel
</P>
<P>
   Management
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   404-872-8747
</P>
<P>
   www.carlsontravel.com
</P>
<P>
   /agence/ga/trips
</P>
<P>
   Reinke opened his agency 20 years ago in Atlanta, catering to
intown residents. Today he manages a staff of vacation consultants
for seven metro Carlson Wagonlit locations.
</P>
<P>
   ALL IN THE FAMILY
</P>
<P>
   Heinrich: Although most major cruise lines offer children's
programs, Royal Caribbean is the best. Its ``Adventure Ocean''
program, combined with large youth facilities, large suites, a
baby-sitting service and exciting ports, makes it a winning family
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Moses: For three-, four- and now seven-night family cruises,
Disney Cruise Line's well-planned vessels allow children and adults
to have uncrowded vacation experiences each will enjoy. For seven
nights or longer, Carnival, Holland America Line, Princess and
Royal Caribbean all offer wonderful kids' programs, especially
during family travel periods (holidays, summer, spring break).
</P>
<P>
   Reinke: Carnival and Disney remain the frontrunners in onboard
activities for children. While both now offer three-, four- and
seven-night cruises, Carnival's much larger fleet encompasses a far
greater variety of itineraries. Each vessel is equipped with a
``Camp Carnival,'' providing all-day activities for kids. Disney's
spacious family staterooms are very popular, so expect few
discounts in the peak vacation months.
</P>
<P>
   THE LOVE BOAT
</P>
<P>
   Heinrich: What's more romantic than getting engaged or married
on a cruise? Royal Caribbean and Princess have wedding chapels on
some of their ships. For ladies traveling alone, Crystal and
Holland America offer the companionship of gentleman hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Moses: For couples, few experiences duplicate sailing aboard the
vessels of WindStar or Star Clippers. Billowing sails, exotic ports
of call and intimate vessels combine to make these ``can't miss''
romantic vacations. For singles, we advise sticking with larger
vessels, which may offer singles programs and active nightlife.
</P>
<P>
   Reinke: If a first or second honeymoon is in your future,
consider booking one of the luxurious 300-square-foot suites with
private verandah on Radisson Sevens Seas' Paul Gaugin. Its romantic
seven-night itinerary in French Polynesia includes two days in Bora
Bora and Moorea _ ahh, paradise found. If you're single and
searching for a little romance afloat, you will probably appreciate
the nonstop activities onboard Carnival's Fun Ships.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDEN GIRLS _ AND GUYS
</P>
<P>
   Heinrich: Cruising offers seniors the opportunity to enjoy the
amenities of a luxury vacation and exciting ports of call at
whatever level of activity the individual chooses. Most ships have
numerous elevators and ramps for ease of movement onboard, some
staterooms are equipped for the disabled, and special-diet menus
are available. Best of all, there are discount rates for seniors on
many Celebrity, Royal Caribbean and Carnival sailings.
</P>
<P>
   Moses: Most seniors typically enjoy the luxury of traveling
either on short notice or for extended periods. With this in mind
we like to recommend some of the more interesting itineraries
(South America, Africa, Australia/New Zealand, etc.). The ships
that sail these itineraries tend to be somewhat older and a bit
smaller, which provides for great value. Orient Lines, Holland
America Line, Crystal Cruises and Princess Cruises should be
considered.
</P>
<P>
   Reinke: I find that seniors are more drawn to the Old World
decor of Holland America's fleet than any other age group. With
greater flexibility in their vacation schedules, this group of
travelers should never want for a good value. Seniors with greater
than average disposable income will appreciate the pampering and
unique itineraries available on Radisson Seven Seas and Crystal
Cruises.
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVORS AND OTHER ADVENTURERS
</P>
<P>
   Heinrich: Royal Caribbean's Voyager and Explorer boast
rock-climbing walls, ice skating and in-line skating onboard, along
with numerous other activities. The line's warm-water cruises offer
snorkeling and diving excursions. Trips to Alaska on Royal
Caribbean, Princess, Crystal, Holland America and Norwegian Cruise
Lines may include glacier hiking, dog sledding and whitewater
rafting.
</P>
<P>
   Moses: In addition to offering adventurous itineraries (Costa
Rica, Africa, Australia/New Zealand, Amazon River), several lines
now offer pre- and post-cruise packages and shore excursions
incorporating adventure travel. Examples include African safaris as
part of cruises offered by Crystal and Silversea Cruises. Shore
excursions offered on many cruise lines include America's Cup
sailing, mountain biking, hiking and whitewater rafting.
</P>
<P>
   Reinke: If your idea of adventure includes a rain-forest hike in
the morning and scuba diving in the afternoon, I recommend the
100-passenger Temptress Explorer, offering seven-night itineraries
along Costa Rica's Pacific shore. Onboard naturalists offer evening
briefings detailing the following day's activities. For a less
strenuous taste of jungle adventure, the new Carnival Spirit will
offer eight-night cruises out of Miami that call at Belize, Costa
Rica and Panama beginning in November.
</P>
<P>
   THE PRICE IS RIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Heinrich: Carnival and Costa cruise lines offer the
budget-minded traveler good value without sacrificing the basics.
But don't forget that you get what you pay for. Small price
variations can mean the difference between a great vacation and a
not-so-great one.
</P>
<P>
   Moses: Perhaps one of the best values in cruising is Regal
Cruises' Regal Empress. It does some excellent itineraries and
offers a warm crew and very comfortable accommodations. Another way
to save money is to look for off-season time periods _ usually
between Labor Day and Christmas and April through May.
</P>
<P>
   Reinke: The fF
</P>
<P>
   Fall 2000 may well be remembered as the season of unprecedented
cruise bargains. Ships fleeing the onset of cool weather in Europe
and Alaska will be competing with the burgeoning fleet in the
Caribbean to push seven-day cruises down to prices as low as $499
to $549 per person. Carnival, Holland America, Norwegian Cruise
Lines, Princess and Royal Caribbean all share one thing in common:
bargains galore.
</P>
<P>
   DIFF'RENT STROKES (specialty cruises)
</P>
<P>
   Heinrich: Specialty cruises featuring music, sports, personal
finance, food, wine and other special interests are available in
the midprice range on Holland America and Norwegian Cruise Line, as
well as on the upcale Crystal and Radisson Seven Seas.
</P>
<P>
   Moses: Theme cruises are best located via a related magazine or
through an organization. Perhaps the best part of these cruises is
traveling with like-minded individuals who share your enthusiasm
for a given topic or activity. Many cruise lines, including
Crystal, Norwegian Cruise Lines and Cunard feature general theme
cruises on cooking, sports, art and history.
</P>
<P>
   Reinke: Bird watching, dogsledding, swing dancing, rock
climbing, ice skating, you name it _ it's available while afloat,
on ships big and small. Always the innovator, Carnival will offer
an itinerary tailor-made for island addicts starting in May 2001.
Starting in San Juan, Puerto Rico, the refurbished Holiday will
visit seven islands in seven days, including unspoiled St. Kitts,
St. Barts and Tortola.
</P>
<P>
   _Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlatnta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
