<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Book a barge to see fall in France
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 10.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now's the time to snap up a late-season deal on barge cruises in
France.
</P>
<P>
   French Country Waterways is offering value season discounts of
$400 per person on five luxury barges. All-inclusive rates Oct.
22-Nov. 4 start at $2,995 per person. The eight- to 18-passenger
hotel barges sail six-night cruises in Burgundy, the Upper Loire,
Champagne, Alsace-Lorraine and the Moselle Valley. Information:
1-800-222-1236; www.fcwl.com.
</P>
<P>
   Continental Waterways' 50-passenger, all-suite river barge
Chardonnay will offer six-night itineraries in Provence in the
south of France in late October through November and March and
April at value season rates starting at $1,990 per person double
($1,690 single). Book through Abercrombie &AMP; Kent (1-800-323-7308),
the Barge Broker (1-800-275-9794) or Premier Selections Inc.
(1-800-234-4000).
</P>
<P>
   Peter Deilmann Cruises offers weekly sailings on the Rhone and
Saone rivers in France aboard the newly refurbished 100-passenger
Cezanne and the 148-passenger Princesse de Provence. The two deluxe
vessels sail the French waterways through the Burgundy and Provence
regions from Lyon or Avignon through Nov. 4. Seven-night cruises on
the Cezanne are $1,430-$2,450 per person; on the Princesse,
$1,470-$2,285. Information: 1-800-348-8287;
www.deilmann-cruises.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Over there: Cruising in Paradise is offering two World War
II-themed nostalgia cruises next year aboard the 68-passenger Sea
Cloud and the 99-passenger River Cloud. The Sea Cloud sails the
Caribbean March 17-24 from Antigua. The July 7-14 River Cloud
cruise plies the Rhine from Nuremburg, Germany, to Arnhem,
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Guest speaker on both cruises will be best-selling author
Timothy B. Benford, who has written five nonfiction works on World
War II, plus two novels with WWII themes.
</P>
<P>
   The Sea Cloud, which served as an armed weather ship during
WWII, was built in 1931 as a private yacht by Wall Street
investment broker E.F. Hutton for his wife, Marjorie Merriweather
Post. Rates are $4,240-$8,540 per person.
</P>
<P>
   Rates for the River Cloud are $3,300-$4,800.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 1-800-874-2584; www.cruisinginparadise.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  And speaking of the Sea Cloud: Post's ol' ship sure does get
around. The ritzy, 350-foot yacht will sail with
hostess-with-the-mostess Anniemarie Victory (of Discovery Channel's
``World Class Cuisine'') three times next year. In February, it's
``Broadway Goes Caribbean''; in July, the Turkish coast and the
Greek Islands; and in September, Provence, France, and the Spanish
coast with guests Peter Mayle, author of ``A Year in Provence,''
and celebrated TV journalist Walter Cronkite.
</P>
<P>
   Costs: Caribbean cruise $6,900-$8,900 per person; Turkey/Greece
and France/Spain, $7,900-$12,500. Information: 212-486-0353.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Less is more: If you prefer intimacy over size, check out
www.smallshipcruises.com for information on adventure cruises,
wildlife cruises, luxury yachts, barges, sailing ships and dive
boats accommodating five to 500 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
