<HEADER>
A6988 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-FAT-CRUISE10-COX     09-08 2186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAT-CRUISE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Survival at sea, in an ocean of calories
 &HT;    By Amanda Miller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Take two pairs of pants,'' friends who are cruise veterans
advised when they found out about my plans for a seven-day
Caribbean voyage. A pair you can wear now and one the next size up
for after you cross the sea of indulgence, they said.
</P>
<P>
   No way, I replied. Weigh, they said. Weigh before you go. Weigh
after you come back. You'll be 5 pounds heavier.
</P>
<P>
   And I thought you were supposed to leave your cares behind on a
cruise. Would this be the diary of a disaster at sea?
</P>
<P>
   Day 1
</P>
<P>
   Barely aboard the MS Veendam, a modern and elegant Holland
America ship, not even out of port in Fort Lauderdale, and already
I am gazing longingly at a friend's two extra-large scoops of
chocolate ice cream. They are floating in hot fudge sauce, nestled
in a valley of chocolate chip cookies. I don't even like ice cream,
and rarely eat dessert. What's going on here, some sort of
cruise-induced trance?
</P>
<P>
   There are six of us traveling together, all two-time cruisers
except for the ice cream mogul and moi, the Miss Piggy wannabe. Two
have Veendam experience. ``Wait'll she sees the Midnight Chocolate
Extravaganza,'' one says with a knowing smirk.
</P>
<P>
   They've taken bets, it turns out, on how soon I'll break. The
most cynical of the group gives me four hours; another guesses a
day.
</P>
<P>
   After a sensible lunch _ a spoonful of shrimp salad, a spoonful
of cabbage salad, broccoli soup, a roll, iced tea _ I go for a
scoop of the vanilla bean ice cream with strawberries and
blueberries (250 calories). The first hour aboard ship. The first
meal. Everybody loses their bet. The battle of the bulge has begun
in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   I take eight brisk turns around the deck _ two miles _ to
contemplate my possibly flawed theory: With enough exercise and
portion control, I'd told the doubters, you don't have to come back
blown up like an inflatable raft. It seemed so plausible on land.
</P>
<P>
   Up ahead is Cheryl McKenzie, one of the ship's two fitness
instructors, out looking for walkers and handing out ``fitness
passports'' to encourage them. She's 25 _ slender, of course _ and
enthusiastic about the ship's efforts to keep people active.
</P>
<P>
   Passports are stamped each time a passenger completes an
activity _ walking around the deck, shuffleboard, line-dance
classes, using the weight room _ and can be redeemed for ship's
merchandise at the end of the cruise. About half of all passengers
get a passport, and about half of those redeem it, McKenzie says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a big eater,'' she confides, maybe because she's from
Yorkshire, England, not particularly noteworthy for culinary
delights. ``But some of the staff puts on weight during the cruise.
It's that chocolate buffet and all the other stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, I stick to my plan for dinner: an appetizer of
mussels, some vegetable soup, baked melt-in-your-mouth prawns, a
glass of wine, plus low-fat yogurt with fruit compote for dessert.
</P>
<P>
   The chocolate-loving companion settles on Fudgie Espresso, an
incredible 500-calorie-plus wedge of cake with ice cream on the
side. He intends to gain 10 pounds on the cruise, he says, so he'll
have an even 50 to lose back home.
</P>
<P>
   Day 2
</P>
<P>
   Up and walking at 7 a.m., I decide to do six miles to compensate
for the 500 calories above my norm I had on Day 1 and the 500 extra
I'll likely consume today.
</P>
<P>
   Others have the same idea, though nobody's going that Olympic
distance. Some are wearing unscuffed, ultrawhite shoes and walking
as if they've just discovered they have legs. As the week wears on,
they'll drop out one by one, yielding to the higher power of fork
and knife.
</P>
<P>
   Mikki Ricker isn't among the neophytes. A fit 72, and an avid
cruiser from Goodland, Kan., she's hustling around the deck. ``My
first cruise, I lost four pounds,'' she recounts. ``They had dance
hosts, and I stayed up till 2 a.m. dancing every night.''
</P>
<P>
   On this cruise, she's taking the stairs, walking around the deck
and having fruit for lunch. ``Then you're hungry for dinner, and
can eat all six courses if you wish,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast is easy to keep light, and delightful, but it's still
higher-calorie fare than my usual two pieces of wheat toast and
coffee. I choose toast, fruit, a thin slice of Nova salmon, coffee,
a small glass of fruit juice, water; I stick to that for the entire
cruise, varying only the type of fruit or fruit juice.
</P>
<P>
   For the buffet-style lunch, I decide to limit myself mostly to
sandwiches, salads and soups, whatever looks interesting that I
wouldn't trouble to make at home, and to keep the portions small.
And no dessert.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there's hope, I think, relaxing on the beach at our first
port, Half Moon Cay, a Holland America-owned island in the Bahamas,
and sipping a late afternoon margarita (200 calories), reading, and
contemplating nothing, except ... what's for dinner?
</P>
<P>
   One of my companions orders two entrees, a filet mignon and
scallops over linguini in marinara sauce. Another samples _ OK,
consumes _ a chocolate tulip and a piece of raspberry cheesecake, a
combination that makes Fudgie Espresso look like the Weight
Watchers special. The chocolate-lover friend starts to talk about
his baby, that belly beginning to drift over his belt. He hopes to
give birth after the cruise.
</P>
<P>
   I settle on a salad, scallops and linguini, a glass of wine, and
fresh strawberries with frozen yogurt for dessert. Still, the day's
total calories are well above my norm.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling stuffed, we all take two turns around the deck, about a
half-mile.
</P>
<P>
   Day 3
</P>
<P>
   Up and walking at 8 a.m., and the herd has thinned. About half
the white-tennis-shoe set is sitting this one out. Some of the
overweight men who'd huffed around on Day 2 appear to have lost
their sea legs.
</P>
<P>
   Hot and sweaty after an hour and a half, I wander up to the
exercise room. A dozen people are using the treadmills, bikes or
weight machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lifting weights helps to shape your body, and it's very
relaxing,'' says Lucano Cammarota, 41, of Milan, Italy, whose bod
is in such good shape that heads often turn when he enters the
ship's dining room.
</P>
<P>
   Overeating, he admits, is tempting on a cruise. ``You don't see
all this food in your everyday life.'' A former model and now a
tour guide, Cammarota counters the cruise calories with a two-hour
workout every day.
</P>
<P>
   A menacing piece of equipment glints in the sun and catches my
eye. The scales, tucked in a corner of the workout room, are
winking at me. I decide not to weigh again until after we dock.
</P>
<P>
   At dinner, I go for a high-fat appetizer, hazelnut Brie cheese
too wonderful to pass up, but balance it _ or so I tell myself _
with a salad and crab legs (no butter, the way I prefer them).
Dessert is low-fat frozen peach yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   Day 4
</P>
<P>
   Off the ship early for the day on St. Thomas, walking and
shopping, shopping and walking, eating a tuna sandwich at a cafe.
We sample and buy some flavored rums. Then back aboard ship, we all
take a strenuous nap before supper. Waking refreshed, I do a
five-mile walk around the deck.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing: Dinner is a sensible fillet of sole, salad
and vegetables, but I have two glasses of wine (100 calories each),
and finish with a buttery apple tart and not one, but two, scoops
of ice cream (easily 500 calories).
</P>
<P>
   My companions scoff at my excess, and in the context of our
table, I suppose I am a model of moderation. One of our group has
ordered two entrees (broiled New York steak with sauteed mushrooms
and fried potatoes and the fillet of sole) and two desserts (the
apple tart and a brownie with ice cream).
</P>
<P>
   Day 5
</P>
<P>
   Off the ship early again for St. Croix, and no exercise today
beyond walking, and walking, through quaint shops, picking up
souvenirs. Lunch is a grilled-cheese sandwich and tomato bisque
soup at a cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner, of course, is much more elaborate: minestrone soup,
orange and walnut salad, an entree of shrimp, salmon and orange
roughy on a bed of pasta, a glass of wine. And dessert: what to
choose? Fresh strawberries would be sensible ... but Key lime pie
it is.
</P>
<P>
   After dinner, we head for the Ocean Bar for a drink (another 100
calories) and to stay up long enough for the Midnight Chocolate
Extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   On the dance floor, Mac and Karen Wiener are at it again: a
cha-cha, a rhumba, a swing, some fox trot. The Elmhurst, Ill.,
couple met dancing more than 30 years ago and haven't stopped
since. They've danced an hour or two every night of the cruise,
their fourth trip on Holland America ships, and they haven't gained
an ounce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrific, pleasant aerobics, but lovely with your own
husband,'' says Karen, 57, an antiques dealer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do it with the primary motivation not to gain
weight,'' says Mac, 60, a stockbroker. ``It's just romantic and
nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs in the ship's cafeteria, hordes of people are dancing
impatiently from foot to foot, awaiting the signal to dish up and
demolish 500-calorie slices of cake. Nobody plans to eat just one.
</P>
<P>
   I duck to the head of the line for photos. You can look and
photograph, and even salivate, but not touch, until 11 p.m. Some of
the chocolate is sculpted in elaborate carvings _ a Chinese dragon,
a sailing ship. The rest is in more edible forms: chocolate cakes,
puddings, pies, brownies, cookies, chocolate-covered strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   When the masses cross the starting line, I watch in horror. Oh,
the humanity. Most succumb to three or four desserts, some load
their plates with as many as six or eight. I'm tempted, but too
stuffed to act on the impulse.
</P>
<P>
   Day 6
</P>
<P>
   The last two days are at sea, and, surprisingly, the biggest
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Day 6 begins well: Six miles around the deck at 8 a.m. with
virtually unimpeded walking and even a little jogging _ most
everyone must be sleeping off their chocolate overdose.
</P>
<P>
   I shower, then head for the usual breakfast, and the deck chairs
to relax and read. Disaster awaits.
</P>
<P>
   We start talking about lunch at 11 a.m., and by noon, we've
worked up an appetite. Though I keep the portions small, I sample
everything on the buffet that looks remotely interesting _ a salad,
slaw, grilled chicken, some veggies, incredible black bread. Then
top it off with cookies and ice cream (300 empty calories).
</P>
<P>
   We return to the deck chairs and take a nap. At 5 p.m., a
companion insists on a particularly low-cal treat: pina coladas
(300 calories) from the poolside bar. We all go along. At 6:30, we
meet for champagne and hors d'oeuvres before the Captain's Dinner.
</P>
<P>
   At 8, we decide we can't disappoint the captain. Our host would
want us to sample everything on the menu, wouldn't he? I indulge in
an orgy of excess: a trio of smoked fish appetizers, Caesar salad,
broiled lobster tails, asparagus spears, another glass of
champagne. Topped off by a huge slice of baked Alaska. Enough
calories for the entire week. The chocolate-lover friend swears
he'll give birth within a few hours. Our waistbands groan in
sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Day 7
</P>
<P>
   I drag myself out of bed at 9 a.m. and walk, but my pace is off.
The morning walks have been an easy and delightful way to start the
day, with a breathtaking view of clear skies and endless sea. But
not this day. Too much food and alcohol the day before, and I'm
feeling like an out-of-shape recruit in Army boot camp, stumbling
ahead because the drill sergeant in my head won't let me quit. Five
miles later, I shower and collapse in a deck chair.
</P>
<P>
   Our group is in a funk. Land is nearly on the horizon, and so is
work. I head to the sauna, running into Odette Amyx, who's
practicing tai chi, a mind and body exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Onboard with a group of more than 100 bridge players, she's been
sitting a lot, engrossed in two or three two-hour games every day.
Amyx has been playing bridge since age 12, but only took up tai chi
five years ago at age 75. Along with walking 30 minutes a day
around her high-rise in Houston, tai chi has kept her fit and trim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may have gained a little weight on board,'' she
acknowledges, ``but I've done so much walking, maybe not. And if
you're careful for the next week when you get home, it will drop
right off.''
</P>
<P>
   With that encouraging thought, we order martinis (155 calories)
before dinner. Still stuffed from the night before, all of us end
the cruise on a more moderate note: one entree apiece. I settle on
marinated mushrooms Greek style, a salad, and grilled tuna steak,
accompanied by a glass of wine. No dessert.
</P>
<P>
   After a turn or two around the deck, we regretfully acknowledge
the cruise is over and retire to our cabins to mourn and pack.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, I put on the jeans I wore from Atlanta for the
return trip. They don't seem any tighter.
</P>
<P>
   Back on land, it's time to tally the score:
</P>
<P>
   MS Veendam: 50,000 gross tons.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate-lover friend: Five pounds heavier.
</P>
<P>
   Me: Two pounds lighter.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Miller writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
