<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: TENNIS  
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
  For some reason, patriotism didn't motivate some of the top men to
rearrange their schedules and accommodate a trip to Sydney.
<TEXT>
<P>
   An uninspired Pete Sampras, for one, decided to turn down the
opportunity to win a gold medal, something most athletes dream
about. If Sampras had been watching in Atlanta, he would have seen
a very moved Andre Agassi (who recently withdrew from the Sydney
Games to be with his ailing mother and sister) treat the gold medal
as something every bit as precious as a Grand Slam title.
</P>
<P>
   The top U.S. women are capable of sweeping the medals with
Lindsay Davenport, Venus Williams and Monica Seles playing singles
and Serena Williams joining the team for doubles.
</P>
<P>
   THE SETUP
</P>
<P>
   There is a 64-player draw, with 32 pairs in doubles. On July 10,
the top 48 players in the world automatically qualified for the
Olympics, but no country may enter more than three singles players
and one doubles team per men's and women's teams. The
single-elimination tournament will take place on a hard-court
surface.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCORING
</P>
<P>
   All matches are best-of-three sets except for the men's singles
and doubles finals, which are best-of-five-set matches. The winners
of the semifinals will determine the gold and silver medals, while
the losers of the semis will play for the bronze.
</P>
<P>
   THE STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. men will have to decide who will play doubles with the
acerbic Jeff Tarango, and the women will have to guard against
overconfidence. The doubles team of Venus and Serena Williams,
which went on a 28-0 streak after the 1999 French Open, looks
dominating even though Serena pulled out of the U.S. Open doubles
because of a foot injury.
</P>
<P>
   THE NAMES
</P>
<P>
   The Americans will face a very tough Australian team. Playing in
front of the vocal Aussies, Patrick Rafter and Mark Philippoussis
will have the home-court advantage. Carlos Moya of Spain, Yevgeny
Kafelnikov of Russia, Tim Henman of Britain and Richard Krajicek of
the Netherlands could also make some noise. Davenport is also a
defending gold medal winner but may have to get by one of her own
teammates to return to the podium.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
