<HEADER>
A6992 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-RUN-ART-$ADV11-NY     09-08 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RUN-ART-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: TRACK AND FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic of winning times for track and field events is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11)  
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Popular in Europe but largely off the U.S. radar screen between
Olympic years, track and field continues to be the flagship sport
of the Games. This year there is added spice as Marion Jones
attempts to become the first woman in track and field to win five
gold medals in one Olympics. Cold, windy weather may prevent any
world records.
</P>
<P>
   THE WOMEN
</P>
<P>
   Jones will attempt to win golds at 100 meters, 200 meters, the
long jump, the 400-meter relay and the 1,600-meter relay. The
record for women is four golds won by Fanny Blankers-Koen of the
Netherlands in 1948. Jones' weakest event is the long jump.
</P>
<P>
   Her top competition in the sprints is her fellow American Inger
Miller, whose father, Lennox, won two sprinting medals for Jamaica.
Miller came within a hundredth of a second of defeating Jones in a
100-meter sprint in Stockholm this summer. Otherwise, she has not
seriously threatened her. Last year, after Jones was injured,
Miller won the world championship at 200 meters in 21.77 seconds,
faster than Jones ran all season.
</P>
<P>
   Others who could spoil Jones' sprinting hopes are Merlene Ottey
of Jamaica, Christine Arron of France and Zhanna Pintusevich-Block
of Ukraine. But Jones hasn't lost a sprint final in three years,
and it seems unlikely she will lose the 100 or 200 in Sydney. But
she is hardly the favorite in the long jump. Fiona May of Italy and
Tatyana Kotova of Russia have jumped farther than a struggling
Jones has this season.
</P>
<P>
   The women's pole vault will be contested for the first time in
the Olympics, and Stacy Dragila of the United States is the world
record-holder at 15 feet 2\ inches.
</P>
<P>
   In the distance events, Regina Jacobs and Suzy Favor Hamilton
will attempt to become the first U.S. woman to win the 1,500
meters. But Svetlana Masterkova of Russia, the reigning Olympic
champion, is back to defend her title after surgery on both
Achilles' tendons. This is the only distance longer than 400 meters
where a U.S. man or woman is considered a medal candidate. Maria
Mutola of Mozambique, who lives in Springfield, Ore., will try to
win the 800 meters against the Clark family _ the sisters Hazel
Clark and Joetta Clark-Diggs and their sister-in-law Jearl
Miles-Clark.
</P>
<P>
   The women's marathon should be one of the most engaging events
at the Summer Games, featuring the world record-holder Tegla
Loroupe of Kenya and the defending champion, Fatuma Roba of
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
   THE MEN
</P>
<P>
   The luster of the sprints has been dulled by cramping injuries
to Michael Johnson and Maurice Greene that caused both of them to
withdraw during the 200 meters at the Olympic trials in July. But
both sprinters have recovered and are still favored to win two gold
medals apiece. Greene, the world record-holder in the 100 at 9.79
seconds, has regained his dominance on the European circuit and
will anchor the 400-meter relay, which should bring a gold medal.
Barring another injury, Johnson appears unbeatable at 400 meters.
He holds the world record of 43.18 seconds and has lost the event
only three times in 11 years. If the early spring weather
cooperates, Johnson believes he could run 42 seconds at the Games.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most redemptive moments of the Sydney Games should
occur in the men's 1,500 meters, where the world record-holder
Hicham Guerrouj of Morocco is heavily favored. Entering the final
lap of the metric mile at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics, Guerrouj
prepared to make his move into first place, only to tangle with
another runner and fall. He has lost only one race since.
</P>
<P>
   The 800 meters will finally have Wilson Kipketer of Denmark in
the field after a long saga. A native of Kenya, Kipketer moved to
Denmark a decade ago. He would have been favored to win in Atlanta,
but he was not yet a Danish citizen, and he declined to run for
Kenya. He has since set the world record but may not be fully
recovered from a bout of malaria that ruined his 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   In the shot put, the world champion C.J. Hunter, Jones' husband,
may not compete after recent knee surgery. The Dartmouth graduate
Adam Nelson is the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
