<SLUG> BC-GORE-NOTEBOOK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BUSH CAMPAIGN THEME MUSIC: SONGS VIRTUALLY THE SAME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Ga.)   (ART ADV: Photos NYT8 and 18 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Some critics have complained that there's no
difference between the two major political parties. If music can be
any indication, they may be right. Vice President Al Gore and Gov.
George W. Bush have picked nearly identical songs as their theme
music for the presidential campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has chosen ``Let the Day Begin,'' a rock number by The
Call. Bush uses ``We the People,'' which was written for his
campaign by Billy Ray Cyrus. Both are anthems to workers and
strivers, drivers and dreamers, Americans of all stripe, leaving no
one behind or out.
</P>
<P>
   The lyrics to the Democrats' tune go like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's to the babies in a brand new world. Here's to the
beauty and the stars. Here's to the travelers on open road. Here's
to the dreamers in the bars. Here's to the teachers in the crowded
rooms. Here's to the workers in the field. Here's to the preachers
of the sacred world. Here's to the drivers on the wheel.''
</P>
<P>
   And more: ``Here's to the winners of the human race. Here's to
the losers in the game. Here's to the soldiers of the bitter war.
Here's to the war that bears their name.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Republicans' lyrics?
</P>
<P>
   ``The farmers rise every morning at five. The truckers drive
them 18-wheelers all night. The factory workers, they build it with
pride, 24/7 down the assembly line.'' In its attempt to honor
workers of all sorts, it also says: ``Here's to every salesman on
the telephone line.''
</P>
<P>
   And it comes with a warning: ``We pay the taxes, we pay the
bills, so they better pay attention up on Capitol Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns said they wanted to reach the common folk. Both
also officially unveiled their theme songs at their conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore fancies himself a music buff, he was not involved
in the selection. He was busy writing his convention speech when a
handful of aides sat down and systematically evaluated the
available repertoire, including Tina Turner's hit, ``You're Simply
the Best.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Simon, a senior Gore adviser and erstwhile drummer with a
band, said, ``It talks about all corners of society _ and you can
dance to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign did not call The Call in advance to see if Gore
could appropriate the tune, but Michael Been, the composer, has
said in published reports that he has no objection.
</P>
<P>
   Tribute to a Son's Surgeon
</P>
<P>
   At a rally in New Orleans on Thursday night, Gore called a Dr.
David G. Kline to join him on the stage. Gore said vaguely that
``one of our children had a health issue'' and that Kline had come
to the rescue. Kline flitted on and off the stage in the blink of
an eye, without further explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Tracked down behind the stage later, Kline said he was the
neurosurgeon who had operated on Gore's son, Albert, in 1989 after
he had been hit by a car in Baltimore and severely injured. ``After
his acute care there, he needed reconstruction of the nerves in the
right arm,'' said Kline, who is chairman of neurosurgery at
Louisiana State University Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   Kline used a procedure he pioneered to examine the nerves by
putting electrodes on them. The testing told them that the nerves
were slowly growing back, something that was not otherwise visible.
``If you looked at him clinically, you probably would have gone in
and chopped them out and that would not have been good,'' he said.
``We were able to clean them up, and God and Mother Nature and
Albert Jr. re-grew them.'' Albert, a senior in high school, has
fully recovered and plays vigorous sports.
</P>
<P>
   Kline kept up with the Gores when their oldest daughter,
Karenna, worked as an intern at The Times-Picayune. When Gore aides
called him earlier this week to invite him to the rally in the
French Quarter, Kline was not surprised. But he was when Gore
called out his name to come up on the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea about this,'' he said. ``I'm not sure I would
have come if I had known that. I thought it was very unusual. It
was very nice of them to do that. It's hard to talk about, but I'm
very busy and in my own little field, very well known, so I don't
need publicity. But it was very, very nice of them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he generally votes Republican and had contributed
money to the Republican Party, but this time he plans to vote for
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Big Fund-Raisers for Party
</P>
<P>
   With a new Republican commercial lambasting Gore for attending a
fund-raising event at a Buddhist temple in 1996, Gore was asked in
a radio interview Friday what lessons he might have learned from
that experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you learned anything?'' he was asked by WBRZ, the ABC
radio affiliate in Baton Rouge. ``Oh sure,'' Gore responded. ``I
support campaign finance reform, and I think it's obvious to one
and all that it's needed now more than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore then headed to two fund-raisers for the Democratic National
Committee in Atlanta, where he planned to raise $1 million. His
first event was a reception with 250 people paying $1,000 each. The
second was a dinner at the home of Ann Cox Chambers, who held a
similar event for Gore after the 1992 convention. Chambers was not
on hand, but the stand-in host was Michael Coles, the cookie heir,
who ran unsuccessfully for Congress against Newt Gingrich in 1998.
About 150 people attended, raising $750,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is to attend a string of multimillion-dollar fund-raisers
next week. He hits Philadelphia Tuesday, Boston Wednesday and New
York on Thursday for a star-studded gala at Radio City Music Hall.
Total take should be in the $6 million region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
