<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACKSLASH-COLUMN-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WIRED FACE OF CUSTOMER SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
 By MATT RICHTEL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Reggie Sioteco is hearing voices in his head.
They help him find you a pair of well-fitting trousers as
efficiently as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Sioteco, a manager at a downtown Old Navy clothing store, wears
a headset while frenetically roaming the sales floor. The headset
is connected to a walkie-talkie, which in turn is connected to Neil
in the fitting room. And to B.J. on the sales floor. And to the
entire stock room staff. In fact, to around 100 headphone-bearing
employees all told.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that if a customer asks for, say, an extra-large red
polo shirt, Sioteco or anyone on the sales staff can radio three
floors up to the stockroom to see if one is on hand. A trip
upstairs is saved, time and energy are conserved, and customer
service is maximized _ with one small hiccup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a confusion to customers who think you're talking to
them, but you're not,'' Sioteco said.
</P>
<P>
   So the only drawback of the customer service-maximizing headsets
is that they can be disorienting to customers?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hang on,'' he said, tuning into the headset. ``One of the
other managers is trying to get a hold of me.''
</P>
<P>
   In this bustling technology nexus by the bay, thoroughly modern
retailers like Old Navy, Gap and Virgin Records are putting
technology to work, enhancing the buying experience by keeping
waiting time to a minimum. With the headsets, employees can stay
close to their posts _ where customers can find them _ instead of
disappearing to another part of the building to confer with
colleagues face to face.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to leave the customer to go ask a question in the
stockroom,'' said Arrickco Bell, manager of the American Eagle
Outfitters store here.
</P>
<P>
   Is that such a problem at American Eagle Outfitters, whose
stockroom is only a few feet away from the compact, single-story
sales floor? Bell said that no distance was too short for
communication over headphones _ he has used his at a range of less
than 10 feet. The deciding factor is the situation, he said, not
the proximity.
</P>
<P>
   Using a radio headset to communicate with someone within
loud-talking distance may seem extreme to the uninitiated, but Bell
said that you have to think of the bigger picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the flagship store,'' he said, explaining that the
headsets also had a symbolic purpose. ``We even use them in our
smaller stores, which have two or three employees.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the rank and file at headset-forward retailers, some
swear by the electronic addenda to their uniforms. Others don't. A
security guard at the Virgin Megastore who would give his name only
as Buddy said he tried wearing the headsets for a while, and
allowed that they had their advantages. But in the end, he said, he
asked his supervisor to relieve him of his, because of the possible
disadvantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll get you killed,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   His point was that if he were to give chase to a thief, the
thief could easily grab the headset and use it to strangle him.
``It's the first thing they'll go for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from risking violent death, some employees say they get
periodic headaches from the constant chatter they hear on the
headsets. And at especially busy times, like weekends, when the
headsets would seem to be most useful, they turn out to be, well,
too useful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm talking to a customer, and I hear in the background:
`Reggie, are you on? Reggie, are you on?''' Sioteco said. He tries
not to answer radio calls, he said, if it would mean interrupting a
customer. He has an ironclad rule that the customer comes first.
</P>
<P>
   Where does the headset come?
</P>
<P>
   Third, he explained _ after the customer and then the employee.
At the moment, three employees were demanding his attention _ two
of them on the headset.
</P>
<P>
   One is calling from the stockroom. The second, a fellow manager,
calls to interrupt the first conversation, saying he needs to chat
with Sioteco privately, which means that Sioteco will have to find
a phone. The third employee is also wearing a headset, but she has
walked over to talk to Scioteco in the flesh, and evidently has
gotten close enough to be eligible for person-to-person contact
wholly unaided by technology _ about a foot away.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many conversations,'' he says, laughing at the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   True, but look at the upside: He isn't being strangled to death.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
