<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MITSUBISHI-$ADV10-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARASSMENT COMPLAINTS IN A MITSUBISHI PLANT RESONATE FAR AND WIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   (For release Sunday, Sept . 10)  
(ART ADV: Photos 38-41 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORMAL, Ill. _ For a short but trying time a few years ago, this
town made national headlines. Horrifying stories had emerged from
the Mitsubishi automobile assembly plant that sits amid the fertile
cornfields here. On its factory floor, some workers contended, some
men felt free to grope women or to ask them to bare their breasts.
Men would display lewd photographs and commonly refer to women in
the crudest of terms, workers said.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi was accused by some of its own workers of ignoring _
even encouraging _ such behavior. In 1996, the federal Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission brought the largest harassment
suit in its history against the company, contending that hundreds
of women were victimized, going back to at least 1990. The Rev.
Jesse Jackson later led a consumer boycott, and the National
Organization for Women organized pickets at Mitsubishi dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which had vehemently denied the accusations, agreed
in June 1998 to settle the suit by paying $34 million to women who
said they had been harassed. That followed its settlement a year
earlier of a private suit, involving similar accusations, for about
$10 million. The settlements were supposed to have started a new
chapter at Mitsubishi Motor Manufacturing of America, which agreed
to take a series of steps to stop harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Although the headlines have faded, many problems have not. In
interviews, current and former Mitsubishi workers painted a
disturbing portrait of a factory that often remained deeply hostile
toward women. Some workers said harassment remained a serious
problem, despite a ``zero-tolerance'' policy against sexual
harassment that Mitsubishi said it had in place even before the
settlement. Many other workers declined to talk about the issue,
and few employees were willing to speak on the record about life at
the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Those who agreed to interviews did say that the most extreme
forms of harassment had apparently ended, and that the number of
incidents had declined sharply. But disturbing events have
continued, according to these employees. One woman, who had been
involved in the government's settlement, was the target of
offensive drawings, a co-worker said. Another woman accused a male
co-worker of tampering with cars on the assembly line just before
they reached her. The rude language continues unabated, employees
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some workers were also harshly critical of how Mitsubishi
handles complaints, despite the company's promises to make it
easier for employees to come forward.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Burmaster is one of several workers who expressed bitter
disappointment. Women still worry about retaliation, she said,
asserting that the department that handles harassment accusations
is largely ineffective. ``We thought we were making a difference,
and we didn't,'' said Burmaster, who is on disability leave from
the plant.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitsubishi experience resonates far beyond this town. The
size and notoriety of the case could be seen as a test of how
effectively the federal government and private lawsuits can force
change on recalcitrant corporations. If Mitsubishi is unable to
address fundamental tensions at its plant, despite the government's
insistence on specific changes and monitoring, what hope is there
for companies that get less press and government attention?
</P>
<P>
   The question is especially apt now. Last Wednesday, a
three-member panel, chosen by the company and the employment
commission to monitor the plant, issued its second annual report.
The 20-page paper credited the company with making ``commendable
progress.'' Mitsubishi ``has sexual harassment in the plant firmly
under control,'' the report concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The EEOC has also declared victory. ``My sense is that we have
made a dramatic difference,'' said John C. Hendrickson, the lead
lawyer for the commission in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Both Mitsubishi and the commission dismiss naysayers as
unrepresentative of employees at the plant. They say the monitors
held extensive interviews and uncovered no serious problems. Just
30 complaints, sometimes by more than one individual about the same
incident, have been filed with the company from December 1999 to
August of this year, the monitors reported. Six resulted in
recommendations of disciplinary action. The company says a dozen
individuals have made complaints so far this year _ a rate that is
slightly lower than the 22 for all of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   For some employees _ and not just women _ the plant remains a
troubled and uncomfortable place to work. In January, Patricia
Benassi, a lawyer who represented women in the private lawsuit,
filed a suit contending racial discrimination. She now represents
about 40 former and current employees who are black.
</P>
<P>
   The company has ``made it clear that African-Americans were
unwanted and despised,'' the suit contends. It describes instances
of racial taunts, of ``KKK'' being scrawled on walls and of nooses
on display. Because the suit is in mediation, both sides declined
to comment, although Mitsubishi has said that it does not tolerate
harassment of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   Why do some employees still describe the plant as an unfriendly
place to work, despite the company's oft-stated policies against
offensive behavior?
</P>
<P>
   Changing any corporate culture, whether in management offices or
on the factory floor, is extraordinarily difficult. Too often,
companies ``fail to follow up,'' said Ellen Bravo, the co-director
of 9 to 5, National Association of Working Women. They fail to
ensure that their workplace no longer fosters or permits offensive
behavior, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of atmosphere where sexual harassment flourishes is
not only where there is a general atmosphere of hostility and
problems,'' she said, ``but where workers do not trust top
management.'' In Mitsubishi's case, Bravo faults the company for
not fully acknowledging the depth of its problems.
</P>
<P>
   But Mitsubishi says its focus is on the future. ``We're trying
to move on. That was then; this is now,'' said Gloria-Jeanne Davis,
who heads the Mitsubishi plant's opportunity programs department,
which was created in 1996 to oversee complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The company's employees do say that Mitsubishi has put an end to
much of the most blatant harassment. It has fired workers that it
concluded were harassing women, and it is doing what it can to
prevent incidents, according to one employee whose wife had
complained of harassment when she worked there.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials at the plant also say that there has been
significant progress. ``It's definitely changed,'' said Justin
West, the president of United Auto Workers Local 2488, which had
been criticized by employees a few years ago as being slow to
address sexual-harassment concerns. ``Are there still pockets of
some resistance? It goes on,'' he said, but he emphasized that both
the company and the union wanted to put an end to that kind of
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   What is troubling to some Mitsubishi employees is not that there
are incidents _ few, if any, workplaces are free of them _ but that
they feel as powerless now as they did before the settlement. They
say that investigations are not kept confidential and that little
effort is made to get to the source of problems. After making
complaints, they say, they are often transferred to other areas of
the plant _ where they must learn new, sometimes more difficult,
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi, they contend, focuses only on the most obvious
outbreaks of hostility rather than tackling an environment that may
foster it.
</P>
<P>
   If a company does not address underlying reasons causing trouble
in its workplace, ``you could expect other problems; you could
predict it,'' said Robert Bruno, a labor relations professor at the
University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign who has studied the
Mitsubishi plant.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi officials, who defend their handling of complaints,
say women workers are moved permanently to other areas only with
their consent. They denied that there was a systemic problem at the
plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to have a good-quality product, we have to have a
quality environment,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 15 years since Mitsubishi joined with Chrysler, now
DaimlerChrysler, to plan operations here, the plant has become
integral to life in both Normal and Bloomington, which are known as
the twin cities. Mitsubishi bought out Chrysler's 50 percent stake
in the plant in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi is a leading employer in the area, which also boasts
two universities and the headquarters of State Farm Insurance. Even
after letting go of about 750 workers last year as part of a
downsizing, the plant employs roughly 3,100 people.
</P>
<P>
   The jobs at the plant pay well: even without much overtime, a
line worker, earning about $24 a hour, can easily make $50,000 a
year, which goes far in central Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   The twin cities bask in pride as the home of Mitsubishi's only
United States plant. The company figured prominently in a recent
manufacturing exhibit at the McLean County Museum of History in
downtown Bloomington, and the local newspaper, The Pantagraph,
closely covers the company.
</P>
<P>
   The plant produces three Mitsubishi models _ the Eclipse sports
coupe, the Spyder convertible and the Galant sedan _ and two
Chrysler models _ the Dodge Stratus and Chrysler Sebring. It
expects to make a record 228,000 cars this year.
</P>
<P>
   Though a money-loser for most of its history, the plant began
turning a profit last year, according to Richard Gilligan, a former
Ford manager who became chief operating officer at Mitsubishi Motor
Manufacturing of America in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the company's Japanese parent, the Mitsubishi Motors
Corp., came to grips with its own problems: After acknowledging
that it had hidden consumer complaints about defects in its
Japanese-made cars for two decades, Katsuhiko Kawasoe, the chief
executive, said he would resign. DaimlerChrysler, which has agreed
to buy 34 percent of the company, said it would it take a more
active management role.
</P>
<P>
   When the plant opened here in 1988 workers were recruited with
promises of high pay and a Japanese-style team approach to building
cars. The employees, called associates, would work side by side
with managers.
</P>
<P>
   The factory floor, built about two-thirds the typical size for
an auto plant, was intended as a model of efficiency. But employees
also describe it as a cramped, noisy place where one worker may
have to squeeze past another to get into a car or to find tools.
The company uses a production system in which workers depend on one
another to complete a group of tasks in an allotted time.
</P>
<P>
   With production on a record pace, employees routinely work
10-hour shifts, six days a week, with every third Saturday off. The
long hours contribute to difficult working conditions. ``There are
hostilities in the plant,'' said West, the union president.
``People are reaching the boiling point.''
</P>
<P>
   Many employees contend that supervisors encourage workers to
give one another a hard time if they do not keep up _ fomenting
antagonistic comments. ``The management actually pits worker
against worker,'' asserted Larry Lehmann, a former union
representative who no longer works at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Gilligan denied that the work environment was unusually hostile.
``This is a tough industry, and it's not for everyone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As in most other auto plants, women and minorities stand out
here as easy targets. In a sea of Mitsubishi maroon shirts and gray
slacks, the uniform worn by all employees on the factory floor, the
faces are mostly those of white men. About one-fifth of the
employees are women, about the same as before the settlement,
according to Davis.
</P>
<P>
   What distinguishes the Mitsubishi plant, however, is the
disappointment that workers feel about working there. Despite the
promises made in the early years by management, employees say they
have little involvement in making important decisions about how the
line will be run. While many expected something different, the jobs
here are typical assembly-line work, monotonous and often
physically grueling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really do feel cheated,'' said Bruno, who surveyed the
work force in the fall of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, some women complained of sexual harassment,
but employees said that the atmosphere grew worse over the years,
and that management ignored the accusations. As the complaints
became public, first in the private lawsuit filed by about 30 women
in December 1994 and later as part of the EEOC suit, employees were
sharply divided. The company responded aggressively, busing
thousands of employees to hold a rally in Chicago to protest the
commission's suit.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, many employees deny that there was ever a
significant problem. ``There was a lot of teasing going on,'' said
Kathleen McLouth, who has worked at the plant for 12 years. She
described the accusations of sexual harassment as ``blown way out
of proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   Some white men who work at the plant complain bitterly that
there is now a double standard, asserting that the company ignores
provocative behavior by women and minorities. One man who spoke
only on condition of anonymity said he thought the plant had gone
too far in catering to their demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at, you know what a factory is all about,'' he
said. ``They're trying to turn it into a Sunday school.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 settlement, which involved nearly 500 women at the
plant, appears to have sharpened some of the resentment. The women
were never identified, but when local newspapers said they received
from $11,000 to as much as $300,000 each, there was heated
speculation about which women had received money and how much.
</P>
<P>
   One woman recalled being barraged by questions. Later, she said,
after being overheard talking to another woman about the
settlement, she became the target of harassment by a male
colleague. She said the man interfered with her work by tampering
with a car before it came down the line and tried to intimidate her
by startling her with loud noises. She said that when she tried to
resolve the matter through the opportunity programs department, she
was told that it was partly her fault for making it known that she
was involved in the settlement. The matter is not yet resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The employment commission did advise women not to talk about the
settlement, and Davis said that the company had a strict policy
forbidding employees to discuss it.
</P>
<P>
   The company's handling of complaints is also criticized sharply
by some employees, who say Mitsubishi has not made it any easier to
come forward. They contend that investigations quickly become known
throughout the plant, even if inadvertently. One employee said, for
example, that someone who is accused of harassment is removed from
the assembly line to be interviewed on the very same day the
accuser is removed.
</P>
<P>
   With so little effort to disguise what is happening, ``the line
knows you've narked on him,'' she said. Employees also say that the
union members who participate in the proceedings may be indiscreet,
too.
</P>
<P>
   The company says it strives to keep the proceedings private, and
George F. Galland Jr., a plaintiffs' lawyer in the original suit
who is now a monitor, says that there is little else Mitsubishi can
do. The union says its members also understand the importance of
keeping matters confidential.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the employee dissatisfaction is aimed squarely at the
opportunity programs department. Some of that may be based on
prejudice _ the department is staffed primarily with blacks and has
no white men, which some employees say makes them uncomfortable.
Others say the department routinely fails to get to the bottom of
the problems on the factory floor.
</P>
<P>
   The department ``was a smokescreen,'' said Lehmann, the former
union representative, who faulted the department for not doing more
to investigate certain incidents.
</P>
<P>
   One investigation, into a harassment complaint made by a woman
after the government settlement, also resulted in no action. A man
denied accusations that he had drawn an unflattering picture that
depicted the woman's body as made of dollar bills. The matter was
dropped without much effort to learn what had really happened,
according to an employee who was involved in the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, however, said that the department thoroughly investigated
any complaint, and that when a definitive conclusion could not be
reached, the department continued to monitor the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the inability to get beyond a he-said, she-said
recounting of incidents rests too much on Mitsubishi's reliance on
reports of fellow workers, according to some employees. Not much
can be done if there is no witness to a complaint, they say.
Supervisors provide little of the oversight needed to address
problems brewing on the line, especially now that they face greater
work demands as the plant produces more cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to be there and they turned their back,'' one
employee said. ``Now they're not there.''
</P>
<P>
   When co-workers do see problems, they are often reluctant to
become involved, especially if someone might be fired for his
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The three monitors _ a former EEOC official who serves as a
consultant to Mitsubishi, the research director of a Chicago
women's organization, and Galland _ have pushed the company to
address complaints even when they are not clear-cut cases.
</P>
<P>
   Women at the plant say they have few places to turn. The union's
ability to handle complaints is limited; the shop stewards cannot
leave the assembly line to look into problems. That leaves the bulk
of the responsibility with union representatives, each of whom
handles the complaints and concerns of several hundred people. The
representatives are also conflicted, some workers said, because
they must protect the interests of the accuser as well as the
accused. Some employees said the monitors failed to pick up on
these concerns because the process of interviewing employees was
flawed. Some employees who want to be interviewed have to notify a
supervisor about their need to leave the line, thus calling
attention to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Galland said the process offered the confidentiality that
employees wanted. By interviewing employees at random, as well as
those who ask to participate, supervisors have no idea who has
volunteered, he said. Workers can also call him directly, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the EEOC stated that there would always be some
discontent at any plant. ``We never expected we were creating an
industrial utopia in Bloomington-Normal,'' said Hendrickson, who
added that he was unaware of any complaints directed to his office.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the monitors, few outsiders are paying much
attention. Lynn Martin, the former Labor Secretary hired by as a
consultant about workplace issues after the government sued
Mitsubishi, and her three-person staff spent two years at
Mitsubishi and were paid $2 million for their efforts. She stopped
checking on the status of her recommendations to create a model
workplace once the settlement agreement was reached, a spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   NOW and Jackson's group say they have not received complaints.
Patricia Ireland, the president of NOW, said, ``The best sign is
that we have not heard cries from women for help there.''
</P>
<P>
   Some workers at the plant have another interpretation of the
situation. They wonder whether anyone is listening hard enough. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
