<SLUG> BC-ATLANTIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    After flawless liftoff, Atlantis heads for space station linkup
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By MARK CARREAU
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ The shuttle Atlantis and its crew of
seven sped toward a weekend rendezvous with the international space
station, following a flawless liftoff early Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis was on course to close within 10 miles of the orbital
outpost late today. (SATURDAY)
</P>
<P>
   With shuttle skipper Terry Wilcutt at the controls, Atlantis
will then maneuver gingerly toward an orbital linkup Sunday shortly
before 1 a.m. CDT, and will remain joined for five and possibly six
days.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle crew plans to equip the station's new Russian-built
Zvezda crew habitat module with an air generation system, a toilet,
exercise devices, fire extinguishers and other gear for the first
resident crew.
</P>
<P>
   American commander Bill Shepherd and cosmonauts Yuri Gidzenko
and Sergei Krikalev are to arrive in early November.
</P>
<P>
   Their four-month stay is intended to kick off at least a decade
of continuous occupation as the station is expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Skirting coastal rain showers that threatened to force a launch
scrub, Atlantis roared into orbit from NASA's Kennedy Space Center
at 7:46 a.m. CDT. The shuttle climbed steeply through partly cloudy
skies on a northerly trajectory.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the station sailed 220 miles over Eastern Europe,
nearly 7,000 miles in front of the ascending space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Wilcutt's crew includes pilot Scott Altman, flight engineer Rick
Mastracchio, mission specialists Ed Lu, Dan Burbank and two Russian
cosmonauts, Yuri Malenchenko and Boris Morukov.
</P>
<P>
   They will be the first to visit the fledgling outpost since the
July addition of the Russian-built Zvezda module, a 43-foot-long
compartment that furnished the station with living and working
quarters for a resident crew of three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect it will look visually stunning,'' said Wilcutt.
</P>
<P>
   Zvezda joined the Russian Zarya and American Unity modules, the
station's first components, which were linked together by a U.S.
and Russian shuttle crew in late 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, the three modules that currently comprise the
station and an unmanned Russian Progress cargo capsule docked at
one end span 143 feet in length and weigh more than 130,000 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle crew plans a near seven-hour spacewalk by Lu and
Malenchenko early Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The men will scale the length of the station, connecting
communication and computer cables to the new Zvezda module and
installing an external guidance device called a magnetometer.
</P>
<P>
   The fliers do not plan to float into the orbital outpost to
begin their installation chores until early Tuesday. Altogether,
they plan to unload more than 5,000 pounds of equipment from the
shuttle's cargo hold and the Progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mission is fairly tight,'' said NASA's Bill Gerstenmaier,
who chairs the Atlantis mission management team. ``The time line is
full.''
</P>
<P>
   Managers have asked the shuttle crew to conserve as much
electrical power as possible by turning off unneeded shuttle
computers, lighting and other instruments to stretch the docked
activities from five to six days and the total length of the flight
from 11 to 12 days.
</P>
<P>
   A decision on the extension will likely be made by the middle of
next week, said Gerstenmaier.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantis flight is the first of three shuttle station
supply-and-assembly missions planned before year's end, equaling
all previous U.S. station activity.
</P>
<P>
   Russian economic problems slowed the development of the crucial
Zvezda module by more than two years and brought all major
construction to a halt after the first two modules were mated.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
