<SLUG> BC-INVEST-EXCHANGE-FUNDS-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGING THE ALLURE OF TRADABLE FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
 By CAROLE GOULD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no question that exchange-traded funds are a hot
investment. Their assets have nearly doubled this year, to $52.6
billion; so has the number of the offerings, which now exceeds 60,
according to Strategic Insight, a fund consulting firm in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But are these funds good for investors? ``They're cheap to
manage, tax-efficient and easy to get in and out of,'' said John
Markese, president of the American Association of Individual
Investors in Chicago. ``I can't believe that they won't become a
popular product worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   Exchange-traded funds are groups of stocks that generally track
popular market indexes. The first were Standard &AMP; Poor's Depositary
Receipts, known as Spiders, which were created in 1993 by the
American Stock Exchange, where all exchange-traded funds still
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Like stocks, exchange-traded funds can be bought or sold all day
long, bought on margin and sold short. In contrast, mutual funds
are priced only once a day.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who place limit orders, buying or selling at specified
prices to take advantage of intraday price fluctuations, may get
better prices in exchange-traded funds, said Albert Fredman,
professor of finance at California State University in Fullerton.
</P>
<P>
   Markese said investors ``might see a lot of index-based mutual
funds moving over into ETF form,'' adding, ``I don't think many
companies will be able to compete without doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vanguard Group, the nation's biggest manager of index mutual
funds, has filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission to add
exchange-traded versions of five of its index mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Managers' costs for exchange-traded funds are lower than for
index mutual funds, which provide services like telephone
operations and, sometimes, branch offices.
</P>
<P>
   The Vanguard 500 Index, the best-known index mutual fund,
charges 0.18 percent of assets a year _ razor-thin by mutual fund
standards, but almost double the 0.095 percent for Barclays Global
Investors iShares Trust, an exchange-traded fund that also tracks
the S&AMP;P 500. (Exchange funds based on narrow market segments or
foreign exchanges can have expenses as high as 1.5 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   But exchange-traded funds have another cost: Because they are
traded like stocks, investors must pay brokerage commissions.
Professor Fredman recommended using low-cost online brokers, not
full-service brokers, to execute trades. ``You don't need much
advice when you buy ETF's,'' he said, ``because you don't need to
evaluate the stocks or the managers.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the brokerage costs, Fredman added, an
exchange-traded fund makes more sense for someone who wants to
invest a large sum at one time, instead of making smaller purchases
on a regular basis, as many fund investors do.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term investors who reinvest dividends might be better off
in index mutual funds. Dividends in exchange-traded funds can be
reinvested only if a broker offers the service, and then only for
full shares; sometimes a fee is assessed. Mutual funds, by
contrast, allow dividends to be reinvested in fractional shares,
and the service is generally free.
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage of exchange funds is tax efficiency. Mutual
funds may have to sell shares to meet investor redemptions,
creating taxable gains typically distributed to investors at
year-end. Because exchange funds are traded in-kind by market
specialists, shares need not be sold to meet redemptions.
</P>
<P>
   The more convenient trading of exchange funds can cut both ways,
Professor Fredman cautioned. ``Because it's so easy to jump in and
out,'' he said, ``people may be tempted to day-trade, and that can
be self-destructive.'' But exchange funds could help index mutual
funds by luring away market timers, thus reducing costs for the
index funds' long-term investors, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Closed-end funds, which are also pools of securities that trade
throughout the day, are actively managed and often sell for sharp
discounts or occasionally at premiums to the value of their
underlying assets. By contrast, exchange-traded funds, which
generally track indexes, are priced efficiently and are more tax
efficient.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
