<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY GETS ODD THANK-YOU FOR SHOWING UP IN CONNECTICUT
</HEADLINE>
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHELTON, Conn. _ How sharper than a serpent's tooth it is to
share the stump with a thankless congressional candidate, Dick
Cheney learned on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   After coming here to campaign at the request of Mark Nielsen, a
Republican who is running for the House, Cheney, the party's
vice-presidential candidate, found that Nielsen had also chosen
Friday to release a new commercial featuring three men as examples
of honesty and integrity: former President George Bush, Sen. John
McCain of Arizona and Connecticut's own Sen. Joseph Lieberman,
Cheney's Democratic rival.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial even appropriates one of Cheney's stock phrases,
which he repeats at nearly every event, about how he and his
running mate, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, will ``restore honor
and integrity to the White House.'' In the commercial, as the
announcer intones, ``Today, when America wants leaders of honesty
and integrity ...,'' President Bush, McCain and Lieberman appear on
the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing was perhaps unfortunate,'' Nielsen allowed,
explaining that his campaign chose to highlight Lieberman in its
commercial because of the senator's popularity in his home state.
``Joseph Lieberman is from Connecticut. He is the local person
whose reputation everyone from Connecticut understands.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the reference to Lieberman, Cheney said, ``He can
mention anybody he wants. He ought to run his own campaign so he
wins in Connecticut.'
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of day for Cheney. It began with him on the
defensive for not voting in 14 of the 16 state and local elections
held since he moved to Dallas more than four years ago. He did not
even vote in the Texas presidential primary on March 14 that
selected his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Morning News reported on Cheney's skipped votes
today, noting that he missed presidential and state primaries,
runoffs, municipal and school board elections, and votes on
constitutional amendments and a school bond issue. An aide to
Cheney explained that he was out of town for this year's
presidential primary and noted that Bush's main challenger, McCain,
had already dropped out of the race by then.
</P>
<P>
   But the report proved something of an embarrassment to Cheney,
who has spent much of the last three weeks traveling the country
and stressing the importance of local involvement and control of
schools. Asked by reporters what his record said about the
importance of school elections, he said: ``I'm sure they are for
people that are connected with them. But I also traveled a great
deal. Dallas was my base, that's where I lived and was
headquartered. But I was not involved in community affairs very
extensively in Dallas. My focus was on global concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's voting record was seized on by the campaign of Vice
President Al Gore. ``Cheney's poor voting record is just the latest
find that Bush's examination of his background, including his big
oil ties, was not too thorough,'' said Douglas Hattaway, a
spokesman for the Gore campaign. Cheney had been in charge of
helping the Bush campaign screen potential running mates before he
agreed to take on the job himself.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted a response from Cheney's communications director,
Dirk Vande Beek. ``Secretary Cheney has voted in every general
federal election for over 20 years,'' he said. ``He is a patriot
and an avid participant in the political process.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, who visited a center for the elderly here to deliver a
speech on Medicare reform, did not so much as acknowledge Nielsen's
presence during the event, making no mention of him in his remarks
and not shaking his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Cheney's failure to mention him at all during
today's visit, Nielsen put on a brave face. ``I don't think there's
anything to be read into it,'' he insisted.
</P>
</TEXT>
