<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7006 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BONFIRE0909-COX     09-08 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE0909-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Famlies of bonfire victims want answersBy Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With the families of two victims of last year's
deadly Texas A&AMP;M bonfire collapse looking on, a state engineering
board ruled Friday that A&AMP;M students broke state law while building
the bonfire _ and warned students not to build an unauthorized
bonfire this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Friday also marked the first time families of those killed and
wounded have publicly criticized the university since the collapse,
which killed 12 people and injured 27. One relative even said that
she was warned by an alumnus against questioning a
university-sponsored investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Board of Professional Engineers voted not to punish
the students who built the bonfire, and decided it needs to
investigate further before deciding whether Texas A&AMP;M or engineers
on campus broke state law.
</P>
<P>
   The families, clearly dissatisfied with the findings of a
special commission that investigated the collapse _ but who didn't
hold individuals responsible _ urged the board to take stronger
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The repeated remarks of 'I didn't know' ... is not
acceptable,'' said Nancy Braus of Hallettsville, whose son,
Dominic, fell 50 feet from the log stack and was seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite having ample time and opportunity, no one, no person,
no agency, has stepped forward to voluntarily accept the
consequences for this tragedy,'' said John Breen, an Austin
engineer whose son, Christopher, died in the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives said they have not decided whether to take legal
action and will wait to see what the board does. So far, no
lawsuits have been filed as a result of the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Breen, Christopher's brother, said his family remains
``cautiously optimistic that the right thing is going to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everyone remains quiet, if it is all swept (aside) without
any thorough investigation being done, that's not justice,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The board, which spent months debating whether it had
jurisdiction in the bonfire collapse, remained deeply divided
Friday _ first over whether to act, then over what actions to take.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all extremely concerned about this situation and want
to do the right thing,'' said board member Kathleen Walker of El
Paso, who steered the meeting and argued vigorously that Texas A&AMP;M
should be subject to state engineering laws for its role in the
bonfire tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The board balked on that issue, which now hinges on whether the
university spent $8,000 or more on Bonfire. If it did, the board
could rule that A&AMP;M also broke the law and punish the university,
including leveling fines of up to $3,000 a day or criminal
penalties.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M spokesman Lane Stephenson said the university is awaiting a
formal request from the board and ``will fully cooperate with the
(board) and provide any information to the best of our ability.''
</P>
<P>
   The board voted seven-to-one _ with Danny Perkins of Houston
voting no and James Nichols of Fort Worth abstaining _ that anyone
involved in building the bonfire violated the law by practicing
engineering without a license.
</P>
<P>
   But the board decided against punishing the builders, who were
mostly students and former students, because the university has
assumed control of all future bonfires and promised to have
engineers oversee all aspects of the construction.
</P>
<P>
   In May, a special commission found that students and university
officials created an environment that allowed ``a complex and
dangerous structure ...to be built without adequate physical or
engineering controls.''
</P>
<P>
   The university later called off this year's bonfire, saying the
revered tradition cannot start again until 2002 at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Board chairman E.D. ``Dave'' Dorchester said the board wanted to
send a message to A&AMP;M students that the board will take action
against any unauthorized bonfires.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can and will issue a cease and desist order,'' he said.
Such an order could be followed with a court injunction, which
would bring criminal penalties if violated.
</P>
<P>
   The board postponed deciding whether members of the school's
engineering department broke the law by not reporting their
concerns about Bonfire's design to the board.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, astonished that such a tragedy happened next to the
state's largest academic engineering department, pushed for a
formal reprimand for the entire department, but the board voted to
let a subcommittee investigate the issue and report back at the
board's next meeting in December.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting left the Braus and the Breen family _ Christopher's
brother Sean and sister Mary also attended _ to wait even longer
for answers they say have not yet come.
</P>
<P>
   Braus, who trembled as she addressed the 9-member board, said an
A&AMP;M alumnus warned her that ``I should not ask questions because
there were very powerful and influential men who were angry at me
for doing so.''
</P>
<P>
   Braus said her son, a sophomore, is back at A&AMP;M and remains in
the corps of cadets. Dominic Braus suffered multiple injuries and
nearly lost his right arm when logs fell on top of him.
</P>
<P>
   Since the accident, she said she has heard stories of
bonfire-related hazing and drinking from students and parents that
have shocked her.
</P>
<P>
   Braus said her son's medical bills have far outstripped the
family's insurance, even with the money they received from A&AMP;M's
insurance and from the fund set up for bonfire victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want something in writing that protects my son's health,''
Braus said. ``This isn't about a lawsuit, this isn't about money,
it's about what's going to happen to my son the rest of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean Breen said he was disappointed that the only action taken
Friday was ``a hypertechnical discussion of whether A&AMP;M spent
$8,000 on this event'' and ``to sanction the students, including my
poor deceased brother as well as the other 11 students who died.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he's frustrated that state authorities seem eager to
talk about future bonfires and forget what happened last fall as
quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no future for my brother,'' he said. ``We have to
look to the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
