A7010 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BAXTER-MCKINNEY0909-C     09-08 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-MCKINNEY0909-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McKinney has second thoughts
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like a cosmic reminder that he can't afford to get
comfortable when things are going his way, Vice President Al Gore's
landing in Atlanta on Friday was made a little bumpier by the flap
over Rep. Cynthia McKinney's Web site musings about his ``Negro
tolerance level.''
</P>
<P>
   There is less to say about this story than most, since after a
day of controversy over the comments about Gore in a news release
on her site, the combative congresswoman took them all back in a
statement at the end of the day. She ``will not stand for it,''
McKinney added in her statement, if any Republicans try to use the
words ``attributed'' to her, on her own Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Which does at least raise new wrinkles in some old journalistic
questions. It has always been the case that if a politician popped
off an unguarded response to a reporter's question, it was
considered fair game, unless there was some agreement the
conversation was off the record.
</P>
<P>
   Should not the same rules apply when the comments are
unsolicited, and offered up on the Web?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never known him to have more than one black person around
him at one time,'' McKinney is quoted as saying in her own press
release. In her later statement she ``disclaimed and retracted''
these comments, which would have been especially incendiary coming
from an Atlanta Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has more than once used Atlanta as a launching pad for
African-American support, delivering a fiery oration from the
pulpit at Ebenezer Baptist Church on Martin Luther King Jr.'s
birthday and cheering on a pep rally of Southern African-American
Democrats early in his campaign last year.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore has the potential to upset Bush in Georgia, as many
Democrats believe, it would come from a bigger-than-expected
African-American turnout such as the state has seen in a couple of
recent elections. Retracted or not, then, McKinney's comments were
hardly what the Gore campaign wanted to deal with on this Atlanta
trip.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney did not retract her support for the suit brought by a
group of African-American Secret Service agents last week, alleging
among other things that Gore had limited the number of black agents
on his detail.
</P>
<P>
   As she noted in her press release, McKinney has had a couple of
high-profile run-ins with the Secret Service when she was not
recognized as a member of Congress by security personnel on visits
to the White House. She has been quoted as saying she was
``absolutely sick and tired of having to have my appearance at the
White House validated by white people.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps anger over the Secret Service issue led to the
incautious posting of the press release on the Web. Perhaps Gore
was just a bystander to the congresswoman's own beef with the
service. In any case, his role has been retracted.
</P>
<P>
   While it may seem outrageous to them, Republicans might heed
McKinney's warning not to use her own words against her. Recall
that it was she who issued one of the most passionate denunciations
of Bill Clinton's behavior, and was one of his most ardent
defenders against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
