u i BC-EU-AUSTRIA-800&AMP;ADD-NY     09-08 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-AUSTRIA-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAY CLEARED TO END EU SANCTIONS ON AUSTRIA 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A panel of experts assessing human rights and political
life in Austria cleared the way Friday for the European Union to
lift diplomatic sanctions that were hurriedly imposed last January
after the Austrians allowed a far right party into national
government.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's recommendation to end the sanctions, which it said
had become counterproductive, allows the European Union to wriggle
free of measures that have become an increasing embarrassment. In
particular, the sanctions had threatened to strengthen opposition
to the union and the common European currency in a crucial
referendum on the euro in Denmark this month.
</P>
<P>
   The experts handed their report Friday to President Jacques
Chirac of France, the current holder of the union's rotating
presidency and gave high marks to the Austrian government,
concluding that minorities, refugees and immigrants enjoy the same
_ if not greater _ rights and protections in Austria as elsewhere
in the 15-member European Union.
</P>
<P>
   But the report went some way to saving the face of those, like
Chirac, who advocated the sanctions by criticizing the far-right
Freedom Party, whose admission into government prompted the
measures. Without naming the party's former leader, Joerg Haider,
the report concluded that some Freedom Party members were still
using xenophobic language and bombarding critics with libel suits
in a strategy aimed at silencing them.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the sanctions _ which included boycotts of school
trips, cultural exchanges and military exercises _ were hurriedly
imposed last Jan. 31, there were critics who said the measures went
too far. Although they have amounted to little more than a crimp in
the social life of Austrian ambassadors, they represented an
unparalleled intrusion in the internal affairs of a member country
and they infuriated the Austrians, who have been demanding that
they be rescinded.
</P>
<P>
   Although the measures were adopted unanimously by the other
European Union members, enthusiasm for them waned quickly. Only a
few countries, including France, have remained adamant.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the European Commission has tried to broker a
face-saving mechanism for backing down. In July, it appointed a
three-member panel to study Austria's human rights record and the
political nature of the Freedom Party before making a
recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac, however, has repeatedly refused to say that he would
follow the panel's recommendation. On Friday, he accepted the
report from the panel members _ Jochen Frowein, the director of the
Max Planck Institute in Germany, former President Martti Ahtisaari
of Finland and Marcelino Oreja, a former Spanish government
minister _ but offered no further comment. His spokeswoman,
Catherine Colonna, said he would consult with the other member
countries about what ``follow-up steps to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many experts say the sanctions are now firmly on their
way out. For one thing, even France has good reason to want to get
rid of them.
</P>
<P>
   France has just taken over the rotating six-month presidency of
the European Union and faces a difficult agenda. Both its prestige
and perhaps even the timely expansion of the union are riding on
its ability to broker deals on how to overhaul the union's
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   With more than a dozen countries heading toward membership, the
European Union must remake its various bodies, or face paralysis.
With such issues to solve before the end of the year, the French
are unlikely to want to be encouraging tensions between members.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, many critics have pointed out that Chirac's
enthusiastic denunciations of Austria's Freedom Party played well
at home, where he is already trying to position himself for the
2002 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   But they did not play well in countries like Denmark, something
of a traditional maverick in the European Union and a nation
already wary of the treatment smaller member countries will receive
from the union. Some experts believe that lifting the boycott _ or
at least indicating that it will end _ could help make sure that
Danes vote to adopt the euro when the issue goes to a referendum on
Sept. 28.
</P>
<P>
   As the report became public, Austrian officials quickly called
for the sanctions to be lifted. Karl-Heinz Grasser, the Austrian
finance minister and a Freedom Party member, said the decision
should be taken before an informal summit of EU leaders in
Biarritz, France, on Oct. 13 and 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were imposed in one day,'' Grasser said of the sanctions.
``They can be lifted swiftly.''
</P>
<P>
   The 45-page report concludes that the sanctions have served a
useful purpose by focusing attention on common values within the
European Union and by pushing the Austrian government to take a
hard look at itself and its behavior.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But is also said the sanction now risked causing more harm than
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the measures adopted by the 14 member states are
maintained, the effect will be counterproductive,'' the report
said. ``The measures have already generated nationalist sentiments
in Austria, above all because they have sometimes been wrongly
interpreted as sanctions against the Austrian people.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Austrian government, which is led by Chancellor Wolfgang
Schuessel of the conventionally conservative Austrian People's
Party, won praise from the panel for ``fulfilling its commitment to
European values'' by taking concrete steps to fight racism,
xenophobia and anti-Semitism. It noted, for instance, that the new
government had adopted a constitutional amendment to protect
minority languages and culture since coming to power.
</P>
<P>
   But it was far more critical of the Freedom Party, which was led
by Haider until he stepped aside in February, in part to ease the
criticisms of Austria. The report described the party as a
``right-wing populist party with radical elements.''
</P>
<P>
   While the report found that there was ``nothing seriously
objectionable about'' most of the party members who were in
government, it said that some members outside of the government had
used xenophobic, even racist, language and had not been reproached
in any way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
