<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING OUT THE BALLOT MEASURE; DECISION FAVORS BUCHANAN 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RULING OUT BALLOT MEASURE
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Supreme Court says that a November ballot initiative
that would have abolished the state's income tax is
unconstitutional and must be stricken from the ballot. The court
ruled Thursday without comment on the measure, Proposition 107,
which would have phased out income taxes and required voter
approval of any new taxes and fees. It also would have provided for
identification on future ballots of all candidates for federal
office who pledged to eliminate the federal income tax.
</P>
<P>
   A written court order on the ruling is to be handed down later.
Opponents of the measure contended that it would have violated the
requirement that amendments to the state constitution cover only a
single subject. They also warned that because income-tax receipts
account for nearly half the state's budget, passage of the measure
would have resulted in cutbacks in services.
</P>
<P>
   DECISION FAVORS BUCHANAN
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan moved a step closer toward the $12.6 million in
federal campaign funds awaiting the Reform party presidential
candidate when the audit staff of the Federal Election Commission
recommended to the six commissioners that he, not his rival, John
Hagelin, get the money. The matter now goes before the
commissioners at a public meeting on Tuesday, when they will vote
on the recommendation. But even then, the loser has the right to
ask the commission to reconsider, a process that could take as many
as 15 days. Distribution of the money could be delayed further if
the loser takes the decision into federal court, as Hagelin said he
intends to do. The Buchanan campaign, meanwhile, was ecstatic.
``It's a huge victory for us,'' Tim Haley, the campaign manager,
said of the staff recommendation. ``We're delighted.''
</P>
<P>
   TODAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   RALPH NADER: Montrose, Colo.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
