<HEADER>
A7025 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-DRUGBAR0909-COX     09-08 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-DRUGBAR0909-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tests nearly useless as new drugs pop up
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At first glance, Olympic officials appear to have
taken strides to clean up the Sydney Games. They wheeled out a test
to detect the use of the banned synthetic hormone erythropoietin
(EPO), considered the drug of choice for endurance athletes.
</P>
<P>
   But some medical experts suggest that the test is just the
latest ploy by the International Olympic Committee to cleanse its
image _ and that some athletes have moved on to a new drug, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   They harken back four years to Atlanta, when the IOC trumpeted
the latest drug-testing equipment, the high-resolution mass
spectrometer (HRMS). The IOC later ignored the five positive tests
uncovered by the lab machines because it feared that the results
could not withstand legal challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``This test is a farce,'' said Dr. Wade Exum, who recently filed
suit after being dismissed as the U.S. Olympic Committee's director
of drug control administration. ``It will definitely be challenged,
if they have the courage to use it.
</P>
<P>
   ``See, the way this often works,'' Exum said, ``is the IOC will
make an announcement they're going to do something, like the case
in '96, and then not follow through. I guess they assume that it is
going to scare some people off. My speculation is that they'll
probably draw some blood or draw some samples. But as far as (using
results) for a sanctionable offense, I highly doubt it.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Yesalis is a Penn State University professor and author
of ``Anabolic Steroids in Sport and Exercise.'' Yesalis dismissed
the EPO test as a public-relations exercise and said that officials
short-circuited the necessary peer-review process to have the test
ready for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense lawyers should be licking their chops on this
one,'' Yesalis said.
</P>
<P>
   The test relies on blood and urine analysis, and both tests must
be positive before any action can be taken. A potential shortcoming
is that the blood test can detect EPO weeks after use, whereas the
urine test is effective only if administered within three days. So,
an athlete could use EPO four days earlier and still beat the
system.
</P>
<P>
   EPO, considered to be a real magic bullet, is thought to be
widely used by athletes in cycling, distance running, swimming and
other endurance sports. The drug increases the red-cell count in
the blood and gives athletes a greater capacity to store oxygen and
therefore increase stamina.
</P>
<P>
   It has been in vogue since the late 1980s, after it was
developed to help people with blood disorders by stimulating bone
marrow to generate more red cells. Two years ago, the drug was at
the heart of the doping scandal that rocked the Tour de France
bicycle race.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the test for EPO proved effective in Sydney, it might be
too late. While researchers were working up tests for EPO, some
athletes were believed to have turned to artificial hemoglobin
products, which can produce some of the same benefits but are
undetectable. They include Hemopure, a drug similar to EPO
manufactured in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scientific handlers are so far ahead of the curve looking
at this Hemopure and doing tests on their athletes,'' Yesalis said.
``And then for (IOC president) Juan Antonio Samaranch to come out
and say because of these (EPO) tests that the Sydney Games are
going to be 100 percent clean _ that is the most idiotic statement
on drug use I have heard in 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
