<SLUG> BC-TIRE-RECALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL HIGHWAY SAFETY ADMINISTRATOR CALLS FOR MORE FUNDING AND
REGULATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   and KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The head of the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration said Friday that she would ask Congress next week
for additional money and new authority to ferret out safety
problems like the ones that have plagued Firestone tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else are we not knowing about, and when don't we know
it?'' said Sue Bailey, who took over the agency Aug. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey said that the agency might already have a handful of
reports about some larger problem that has yet to be identified,
and likened the situation to a submarine with only its periscope or
conning tower visible.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone/Firestone, a Japanese owned company, recalled 6.5
million ATX, ATX II and Wilderness AT tires on Aug. 9 after the
Ford Motor Co. analyzed the tire maker's data on crash reports and
found a pattern of property damage and injury claims dating back at
least to 1997. The tires are suspected of coming apart and
contributing to crashes, and particularly rollover crashes for Ford
Explorer sport utility vehicles, that have been blamed for 88
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   To focus resources on analyzing data and spotting trends, Bailey
said the agency might reallocate internal spending.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, who is scheduled to testify before the Senate Commerce
Committee on Tuesday, said she would provide details of her
proposals then, but added, ``I for one think when it comes to
safety, you can't have too much control.''
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting Friday morning, which highway agency spokesmen had
billed in advance as a get-acquainted session, Bailey said, ``I'm
sure that's going to be an inflammatory statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Bailey made emphatic statements on several steps
she wants her agency to take, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Getting the legal right to demand warranty data and
information on recalls abroad from car companies and tire
companies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewing how the agency gathers and organizes data to spot
trends.
</P>
<P>
   _ Re-writing the standard for tires, which was written 32 years
ago for a generation of tires that is not even produced any more.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is ridiculous; we need to change the standard,'' said
Bailey, referring to the standard written for bias-ply tires, which
preceded steel-belted radial tires.
</P>
<P>
   Both the House and Senate have tentatively set a budget for the
highway agency of $181.9 million for the fiscal year beginning Oct.
1, compared with an request of $286.5 million. Both figures omit
about $213 million that is allocated by Congress to the agency, but
earmarked by law for grants to state safety programs.
</P>
<P>
   But there is considerable sympathy on Capitol Hill for giving
the agency more money and authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be difficult to find someone who would argue against
it right now,'' said one Republican staff member working for a
committee with jurisdiction over the agency. ``You have to have an
incident like this to remind people of the importance of safety and
of funding agencies responsible, '' said the staff member.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, on Friday, said that to make more new tires available for
owners whose car tires have been recalled, it was extending for a
third week the shutdown of three of its factories that make new
Explorers and Rangers, two models which use the same size tires. In
a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, Ford said the
company had tentatively agreed to bear a portion of the costs of
Firestone's recall.
</P>
<P>
   The recall totals 14.4 million tires, of which 6.5 million were
still believed to be on the road as of Aug. 9, but the traffic
safety agency wants the company to expand the recall by 1.4
million, of which less than half are thought to be still in use.
</P>
<P>
   Internal Ford documents continued to dribble out of the
congressional investigations Friday into what went wrong at
Firestone and Ford. A memo to the Ford corporate offices in May
from a Ford dealership in Saudi Arabia, and distributed Friday by
investigators, raised another theory about why the tires failed:
they were too close to the vehicle's exhaust.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ford records, there were at least 19 rollovers in
Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   But an analysis by The New York Times of complaints filed with
regulators in the United States indicates that rear tires more
frequently came apart than front tires, but of those, the failures
are about evenly distributed between the left and right rear tires.
There were 457 complaints involving the rear left tire and 460
involving the rear right tire. Rollovers were somewhat more likely
to be caused by the left rear tire than the right, 83 to 62,
according to the complaint. The exhaust is typically next to the
right rear tire, not the left.
</P>
<P>
   Because Explorers depend on the traction of rear tires to help
avoid rollovers during braking, rear tire failures are especially
critical in sport utility vehicles, and thus perhaps more likely to
be reported to regulators, .
</P>
<P>
   Brook Lindbert, General Motors' engineering director for wheels
and tires, said that a little heat from a vehicle's catalytic
converter and engine radiates downward and is blown back over the
rear wheels because of the vehicle's motion. The exhaust pipe gives
off much less heat and poses little problem, he said, adding that
for rear tires as well as front tires, the overall temperature
outdoors is more important than heat from the vehicle.
</P>
</TEXT>
