<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-SPINA-STATESTREET-$ADV10-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID SPINA, THE OPERATING GUY BEHIND THE FLOWING CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass., Canada)   (For release Sunday, Sept . 10)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ David A. Spina is the corporate incarnation of a soccer
referee. He is also out to change the rules of the game at the
State Street Corp., the financial services company he heads.
</P>
<P>
   At recent employee meetings, Spina waved yellow ``warning'' and
red ``ejection'' slips at executives who discussed their own
projects instead of the company's larger goals. The message: State
Street cannot tackle its long-held technology and global expansion
plans unless it scraps its own turf battles.
</P>
<P>
   The cards, while playful, nonetheless signaled that Spina, 57,
intends to make some changes at State Street, a 208-year-old
institution that has transformed itself from a conventional bank
into a giant back office for the global investment industry. Since
he became chief executive in May, he has made his first goal clear:
As markets and technology systems become more interconnected, his
company, long marked by divisiveness, must undergo a cultural
makeover.
</P>
<P>
   Spina is irked, for example, that his Canadian subsidiary
recently declined to service the local pension plan of a
multinational client. The branch said the plan was too small, but
the client was an important customer in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He winces when he talks about the chaotic Internet strategy he
inherited last fall, when he was chief operations officer.
``Nothing was coordinated,'' he complained. Although State Street
is known as a technology heavyweight, it still offers no Web-based
trading at its money management unit.
</P>
<P>
   Even that unit, State Street Global Advisors, has sought to go
its own way, pushing for a separate listing on Wall Street _ an
idea that the parent company has rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like actions, recommendations or plans that aggrandize
one part of the company,'' Spina concluded.
</P>
<P>
   State Street is not a household name. Its customers are mostly
financial institutions, not ordinary investors. But over the last
decade, it has become the nation's second-largest asset custodian,
calculating daily values for nearly one-third of the United States
mutual fund industry, providing accounting for institutional
investors and pension funds and settling securities trades.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does it keep track of $6.1 trillion in assets, it is
also the nation's third-largest investment firm, managing assets
worth $729 billion, mostly for pension funds and corporate
retirement plans. Although it sold what little remained of its
commercial banking operations last year, it keeps its bank charter
to provide loans to institutional customers.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, State Street's world is not sexy _ it is the
land of the humdrum mechanics behind rocket-fire capital flows.
</P>
<P>
   But the company, which has 17,500 employees around the world,
has enjoyed double-digit annual revenue growth for 22 years. Its
stock performance, though often choppy, has far outpaced gains by
conventional banks lately. The shares have more than doubled since
October, closing on Friday at $122.56.
</P>
<P>
   Now the company is at a crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that you can have a vision that endures a long time
is not valid,'' said Spina, sitting in his dark, wood-paneled
office in downtown Boston, his suspenders splashed with suns, moons
and stars. ``The world changes.''
</P>
<P>
   As its domestic market matures, State Street is looking toward
Europe and Asia, where it is growing but still minor participant
among established competitors.
</P>
<P>
   It also wants to branch out from investment accounting and
processing, its core businesses, into running the entire back
offices of financial firms everywhere. So far, only Pimco, a mutual
fund company in Newport Beach, Calif., has signed up.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is its electronic data, research and trading program,
called Global Link. The company wants this system, which investment
managers use for analyzing global markets and trading securities,
to offer market data from competitors. But the move could undermine
the value of State Street's own market data on the system.
</P>
<P>
   The plans are largely the brainchild of Spina's predecessor,
Marshall N. Carter, who often thumbed his nose at Wall Street by
spending lavishly on technology when analysts urged restraint.
Carter, 60, whose retirement in May jolted analysts, was known as a
visionary who turned his company into an investment services
powerhouse but who stayed out of the daily trenches _ a hands-off
approach that some industry watchers say spawned a divisive
culture.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, as one analyst put it, Spina is ``less
presidential, more collaborative.'' Still, Spina often clashed with
his boss, arguing that the core back-office systems needed as much
investment as showy projects like Global Link.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marsh was ready to issue an order and have others carry it
out,'' mused Spina, whose focus on the back-office business and
love of problem-solving are widely acknowledged to have made him
Carter's successor. ``I might check on how they're carrying it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Manhattan, Spina won an ROTC scholarship to the College
of the Holy Cross in Worcester, Mass. He spent five years in the
Navy, at one point serving as the captain of a patrol boat in
Vietnam. In 1969, he joined State Street as a credit analyst. He
later earned an MBA from Harvard. Regarded by many in the industry
as charming and intellectual, he has never worked at another
company. He is a chocoholic (``What kind? Any kind''), and he does
not do casual Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   State Street has long staked its future on technology. Last
year, it put 20 percent of its $2.3 billion in operating expenses
into high-technology projects like Global Link. But ``the stakes
are higher this time,'' said Michael Mayo, an analyst at CS First
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his teamwork initiative, Spina recently created an
inner circle consisting of him and his top three executives. Though
the group has yet to take any major steps, its purpose is to ensure
that the arms of the company know what the feet are doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've seen where they have to go,'' said Ruchi Madan, an
analyst at PaineWebber. ``David is the operating guy who makes
things happen, but they face some risk of losing momentum.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
