<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-BHAMAN-OPPENHEIMER-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE FUND, WILL TRAVEL: AJEEV BHAMAN OF OPPENHEIMER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: India, Britain, Mexico, Brazil, Korea)   (For release Sunday, Sept . 10)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ AJeev Bhaman was born in Bombay, has lived in England
and was educated in the United States. As a teen-ager, he traveled
the world with his father, the captain of a cargo ship. So he is
not fazed by the travel required in his job, running the $170.8
million Oppenheimer Developing Markets fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it exhilarating,'' Bhaman said recently from his office
in the World Trade Center in Manhattan. ``Exploring the differences
and similarities among cultures, new places and new ideas is like
being a detective. I'm sort of like Carmen San Diego.''
</P>
<P>
   His travels have paid off for the fund's investors. The fund
returned 12.73 percent a year, on average, for the three years
through Sept. 1, putting it in first place among diversified
emerging-markets funds, according to Morningstar Inc. Over all, the
group had a 3.84 percent loss, annualized.
</P>
<P>
   He has managed the fund since its inception in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bhaman, 36, uses a bottom-up approach to investing, looking for
companies with strong growth prospects in emerging foreign markets.
He screens the 15,000 companies in that universe down to 1,000 by
focusing on market and industry trends that he thinks will fuel
global growth over the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   His most important theme is what he calls ``mass affluence,''
which, he said, is grounded in the increasing consumption of
brand-name, personal-care and disposable products, as well as
appetites for entertainment and education. ``It's incredible how
quickly emerging markets have become consumer-driven economies,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   Two more key themes are new technologies and restructuring.
``Most of Eastern Europe is a restructuring story, the
transformation of unprofitable, state-owned enterprises to
cash-generating, profitable companies,'' Bhaman said. ``We think of
it as a caterpillar that metamorphoses into a butterfly.''
</P>
<P>
   He owns a mix of value and growth stocks of all sizes in many
industries around the world. The diversification helps reduce the
volatility of emerging markets and other risks like currency
fluctuations. The fund's prospectus says it can hedge its currency,
but he said that is unnecessary for long-term investments.
</P>
<P>
   His investments are concentrated in Latin America and in Asia
outside Japan (36.6 percent each) and Eastern Europe (14.7
percent).
</P>
<P>
   To pick the fund's 60 to 80 stocks, Bhaman uses fundamental
research to find what he calls ``good companies with good
businesses at good prices.'' A good company, he said, fits one of
his themes and has returns that exceed its cost of capital over the
next three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   A good price lets him double his money in three years, Bhaman
said, or triple it in five.
</P>
<P>
   Equally important is a shareholder-friendly environment. ``The
emerging markets are characterized by poorer shareholder protection
laws than in the developed markets,'' he said, ``and less efficient
information flow.''
</P>
<P>
   He spends at least 25 percent of his time on international
travel, he said, visiting more than 300 companies a year. He talks
to local suppliers, distributors and customers to evaluate whether
a company's stock price reflects what he thinks is its potential.
</P>
<P>
   Many investments are in companies with operations focused on
their home countries, Bhaman said, because they are generally
better aligned with local consumer desires and specific cultural
attributes than large multinational corporations.
</P>
<P>
   He pores over financial statements, particularly focusing on a
company's free cash flow, as well as its ability to generate cash
in the future. He also reviews returns on equity, assets and
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Bhaman sells shares when they become fully valued, or when a
company's fundamentals start to deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   Bhaman's biggest holding is preferred shares of Embraer SA, of
Sao Jose dos Campos, Brazil. The company, which makes small
regional jets and was formerly owned by the government, was
privatized and recapitalized in 1995. He bought shares in March
1998 at 1.76 Brazilian reais, or 97 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The company's growth prospects are strong, he said, because more
countries are building smaller airports and need smaller airplanes.
``Smaller planes are better suited for lower-volume traffic at
cost-competitive prices,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, shares closed at 11.9 reais, or 10.8 times his
projected earnings of 1.1 per share this year.
</P>
<P>
   Another favorite is Grupo Televisa, a Mexico City television
broadcaster with a substantial Spanish-language publishing
operation and satellite and cable TV businesses. It is also a
leading supplier of Spanish-language programming to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the level of affluence increases, the company is well
positioned to take advantage of increased advertising rates on
television,'' he said, ``and to sell programming to other parts of
the world at higher prices.'' A recent cost-cutting program, he
added, should increase profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   He bought shares in July 1997 at $30. They closed on Friday on
the New York Stock Exchange at $67.25 each, or 44.8 times his 2000
earnings estimate of $1.50 a share.
</P>
<P>
   He also likes LG Home Shopping, the larger of two Korean home
shopping networks. Although many Koreans are comfortable using the
Internet, Bhaman said, ``most of the people who buy are women over
30, and TV is a friendlier medium than computers for this group.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, he bought shares at 90,000 won ($81.42) each. On
Friday, they closed at 185,500 won, or 37.1 times his 2000 earnings
projection of 5,000 won a share.
</P>
</TEXT>
