<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE FOOTBALL: KEY GAMES FOR SATURDAY, SEPT. 9 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   No. 1 Nebraska (1-0) at No. 23 Notre Dame (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame, improved this year, held favored Texas A&AMP;M to 255
yards last Saturday. The Irish face a stiffer test against
Nebraska, which rolled up 596 yards (505 rushing) against San Jose
State. Still, coach Bob Davie of Notre Dame, said: ``With a young
quarterback and a not-real-confident defense, I think we showed a
solid foundation on which to build.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 4 Miami (1-0) at No. 15 Washington (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Two offensive powerhouses. Washington's quarterback, Marques
Tuiasosopo, passed for 223 yards and ran for 80 against Idaho and
his teammates collected four fumble recoveries, an interception and
a blocked punt.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 Florida State (1-0) at Georgia Tech (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Florida State held Brigham Young to minus-2 yards rushing.
Georgia Tech is better than it showed against Central Florida, when
it needed two touchdown passes in the last four minutes to win.
</P>
<P>
   EAST
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana Tech (1-1) at Penn State (0-2)
</P>
<P>
   Penn State rushed for only 6 yards against Southern California
and 30 against Toledo. Tailback Larry Johnson says the fault is in
using the same system for years.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College (0-1) at Army (0-1)
</P>
<P>
   Both have struggling offenses. Boston College has better talent.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo (0-1) at Rutgers (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers, with a creative passing game, may become a decent team
yet.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH
</P>
<P>
   No. 9 Georgia (1-0) at South Carolina (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina ended its 21-game losing streak just in time.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt (0-1) at No. 13 Alabama (0-1)
</P>
<P>
   Alabama couldn't handle UCLA's blitz. This should be more
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn (1-0) at No. 19 Mississippi (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Auburn has the weapons to test Mississippi's quick-strike
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri (1-0) at No. 17 Clemson (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   With Woodrow Dantzler's passing, Clemson could reach 9-0.
</P>
<P>
   MIDWEST
</P>
<P>
   Oregon (1-0) at No. 5 Wisconsin (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin, with 26 players serving NCAA suspensions, must step
up against an aggressive defense.
</P>
<P>
   Rice (1-0) at No. 3 Michigan (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   John Navarre, who had never taken a college snap, threw four
touchdown passes for Michigan against Bowling Green.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall (1-0) at No. 24 Michigan State (0-0)
</P>
<P>
   This figures to be the end of Marshall's 18-game winning streak,
the best in Division I-AA.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse (1-0) at Cincinnati (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse's running game should thrive, even after fullback Kyle
Johnson's surgery for a broken ankle.
</P>
<P>
   FAR WEST
</P>
<P>
   Colorado (0-1) at No. 11 Southern California (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado offense, which gained 532 yards against Colorado
State, faces a Trojan defense that held Penn State to 10 first
downs.
</P>
<P>
   No. 18 Ohio State (1-0) at Arizona (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State's defense (four touchdowns against Fresno State)
appears too strong.
</P>
<P>
   Fresno State (0-1) at No. 16 UCLA (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Ryan McCann is UCLA's quarterback because Cory Paus separated
his throwing shoulder on the first play against Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   No. 22 Texas Christian 0-0 at Nevada (0-1)
</P>
<P>
   More woes for Nevada, which totaled minus-3 yards rushing
against Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   No. 21 Illinois (1-0) at San Diego State (0-1)
</P>
<P>
   Should be easy for Illinois, which stopped Middle Tennessee
three times inside the 10-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   MISMATCHES
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana-Lafayette (0-1) at No. 6 Texas (0-0)
</P>
<P>
   Texas, with Chris Simms or Major Applewhite or both at
quarterback, is a six-touchdown favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Middle Tennessee (0-1) at No. 8 Florida (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Florida was so mediocre against Ball State that the Gator fans
booed their team, leading coach Steve Spurrier to say, ``We won't
be too full of ourselves after this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent State (0-1) at No. 14 Purdue (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Purdue held Central Michigan to 161 yards and could do it again.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas State (0-1) at No. 20 Oklahoma (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   In routing Texas, El Paso, Oklahoma turned seven turnovers into
five touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Ratings by The Associated Press.
</P>
