</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7036 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CIVILRIGHTS-CHILDREN0     09-08 3664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVILRIGHTS-CHILDREN0910-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    The children of the civil rights movement
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ericka Brown-Abram says she had a typical childhood.
Her mother's friends were killed in police shootouts. Her family
lived under FBI surveillance. She was constantly shadowed by a
bodyguard, even when she ran to the neighborhood ice cream truck.
</P>
<P>
   Brown-Abram, 30, the daughter of a Black Panther Party leader,
grew up in a communal home and attended a Panther-run grade school
where students read Mao Tse-tung's Little Red Book.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people had this swashbuckling idea of the Panthers,''
she says. ``But when you're a child it all seemed normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing was normal, though, about growing up in the 1950s and
'60s as a child of the civil rights movement. The leaders of the
movement led dramatic lives _ and so did their kids. These children
of the struggle _ the offspring of black militants, nonviolent
activists and even segregationist leaders _ are now adults. Some
are still grappling with their parents' legacies.
</P>
<P>
   The civil rights movement unleashed waves of change that are
still being felt, says Taylor Branch, the Pulitzer Prize-winning
author of two books on the movement. The protest that paralyzed
Seattle this year during a World Trade Organization meeting, the
Million Man March on Washington, even freedom struggles abroad _
all owe a debt to the movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were singing `We Shall Overcome' when the Berlin Wall
came down,'' Branch says. ``They were singing it in Prague. They
were certainly under its influence in South Africa when it became
democratic. Even in China, Tiananmen Square was more or less
modeled on a sit-in.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who joined the movement still miss the adrenalin rush of
being a part of something so monumental.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was invigorating,'' says Elaine Brown, Brown-Abram's
mother. ``It made life important. It made it bigger than you. Even
the notion of dying for something bigger than you was far more
powerful than living out a life of quiet desperation. I was the
happiest in my life when I was in the Black Panther Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the activists didn't commit as vigorously to parenting
as they did to protesting. Changing diapers didn't hold the same
allure as changing the world. Some of the leaders, in fact, simply
weren't suited for parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the movement had a number of people who, by
conventional definitions, were crazy,'' says Clayborne Carson, a
Stanford University professor who has written about the Rev. Martin
Luther King Jr. and the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee.
``But those were the people who saw through conventional truths and
saw other possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   THE CHOSEN ONE: WARITH DEEN MOHAMMED
</P>
<P>
   Elijah Muhammad Sr., a frail asthmatic with only a fourth-grade
education, could make hardened ex-convicts and tough street
hustlers tremble in his presence. The founder of the Nation of
Islam, he spread the message that white people are ``blue-eyed
devils.''
</P>
<P>
   Even his children feared him. They thought he had divine powers,
says Warith Deen Mohammed, his youngest son.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be afraid to think in extremes that would anger
him,'' he says. ``We would be afraid that he would hear our
thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   Elijah Muhammad frightened much of America as well. He
personified black rage. While the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
preached nonviolence and integration, Muhammad preached ``an eye
for an eye'' and racial separation.
</P>
<P>
   Warith Deen Mohammed, now 67, was initially groomed to succeed
his father. Born in Chicago, the youngest son of Muhammad's eight
children, he was the chosen one, the heir apparent.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was a teenager, however, he had begun to doubt
his father's faith. Tutored by orthodox Muslims from the Middle
East, he had become a student of the Koran. He saw no mention of
``blue-eyed devils'' or his father in the holy text. When he shared
his doubts with his father, the elder Muhammad told his son that
his way was the way. End of discussion.
</P>
<P>
   But Warith Deen continued to question his father's beliefs. He
became even more disillusioned when he learned that Nation of Islam
members had been beaten and even killed for questioning his father.
</P>
<P>
   Warith Deen publicly opposed his father. And by 1964, when he
became close friends with one of his father's enemies, Malcolm X
(who had left the Nation of Islam that year after embracing
orthodox Islam), his father banned him from the movement.
</P>
<P>
   After Malcolm X was assassinated in 1965, Warith Deen lived
virtually underground. The FBI tapped his telephones. He worked as
a baker, welder and cabdriver to make ends meet. And he constantly
received death threats from anonymous callers _ one of whose voice
he recognized. It was his older brother, Elijah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understood why,'' says Mohammed, who has since reconciled
with his brother. ``We were all trained to be prepared to sacrifice
everything to protect the honorable Elijah Muhammad.''
</P>
<P>
   But Warith Deen Mohammed eventually became the chosen one again.
In 1975, his father died and the Nation of Islam, reeling from
internal blood feuds and corrupt leadership, picked him to be its
leader. He accepted and set about reforming the group. He removed
its anti-white theology, changed its name to the Muslim American
Society and declared it part of the worldwide Sunni Islamic
community. (Louis Farrakhan broke from Mohammed three years later
to form another version of the Nation).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for us to stop calling white folks the devil,
because there's some black devils, too,'' Mohammed said after
taking over.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Warith Deen Mohammed is a Muslim elder statesman. He has
met with President Clinton and Pope John Paul II and was the first
Muslim to open the U.S. Senate with a prayer. He still lives in
Chicago, with his fourth wife and three youngest children (he has
nine altogether).
</P>
<P>
   And he has a new appreciation for his father. Elijah Muhammad
wasn't a racist, he says, but rather an uneducated man who patched
together a religion that taught black people self-reliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He preached separation of the races, but he was not racist in
that ugly sense,'' Mohammed says. ``He hated the evils of white
people. He was not a racist. He was a nation builder.''
</P>
<P>
   LIFE WITHOUT FATHER: CHEVARA ORRIN AND BACARDI JACKSON
</P>
<P>
   Chevara Orrin has her father's high cheekbones, caramel-colored
complexion and rapid-fire speech. She also has nothing but contempt
for him as a parent.
</P>
<P>
   Orrin, 32, is the daughter of the Rev. James Bevel, a key aide
to the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. and a legendary leader of the
student sit-in and Freedom Ride movements. He also is the man who
persuaded Nation of Islam leader Louis Farrakhan to hold the 1995
Million Man March on Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But Bevel is no hero to Orrin or her sister, Bacardi Jackson,
29. Both say that Bevel never provided for them while they endured
a childhood marked by homelessness, welfare and hand-me-down
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't know my favorite food,'' Orrin says. ``He doesn't
know where I went to high school. He doesn't know what my college
degree is in. He doesn't even know when I was born.''
</P>
<P>
   Orrin's mother, Susanne Jackson, met Bevel in 1965 in Chicago.
He was working with King in the Southern Christian Leadership
Conference; she was an anti-apartheid activist. They worked
together as anti-war activists and had an on-again, off-again
six-year relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Bevel offered to raise Orrin, but Jackson didn't think he would
be a responsible parent. So Jackson raised her daughters as a
single mother, working several jobs at once but still having to go
on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Bacardi Jackson says her father would visit occasionally but
showed no interest in her personal life. Instead, she says, he
seemed interested only in lecturing her about his greatness,
frequently comparing himself to Jesus and Zeus.
</P>
<P>
   Bevel has long been known as one of the movement's most
eccentric characters. ``He's like an Old Testament prophet,''
author Taylor Branch says. ``He hears voices. Sometimes they are
the voices of genius and sometimes they are the voices of lunacy.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 1999 memoir, ``Walking With the Wind,'' Rep. John Lewis
(D-Ga.) wrote that Bevel changed after King was assassinated in
1968. According to Lewis, the SCLC barred Bevel in 1970 after it
heard that he had locked himself in a hotel room with a group of
Spelman College students, declared himself a prophet, urinated in a
glass and ordered them to drink its contents to prove their
loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bevel had so much hope, so much optimism,'' Lewis says. ``I
think it was too much for him and many others when King died.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacardi Jackson finds great irony in her father's leadership
role in the Million Man March. She estimates that he has at least
16 children.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's never said he was sorry once,'' she says. ``He's told a
million black men that they need to atone and take responsibility
for their families, but he hasn't done either in his personal
life.''
</P>
<P>
   She still struggles with forgiving her father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he had been simply an absentee dad,'' Jackson says.
``We could have easily gotten over that. In fact, if he had been
completely absent, our lives wouldn't have been so traumatized. The
two or three times we spent any significant time with him as
children were extremely painful and continue to haunt us to this
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Bevel, 63, says he would have given more support to his
daughters if they had been more dedicated to the movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't understand my vocation,'' he says. ``My vocation is
to deal with the salvation, education and liberation of American
people. That's all I worked on. Apart from this, I don't exist. In
order to be with me, you have to work on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Bevel remains in Chicago, where he runs a program to help
at-risk youths and to teach effective parenting. When asked how
many children he has, Bevel smiles. ``Well, the computer broke
down,'' he says. ``I don't get into counting things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bevel's daughters, meanwhile, say they do admire their father's
dedication to the movement. But everything they personally learned
about activism came from their mother, who works with the National
Urban League in Memphis. She encouraged them to become activists in
college and in their community.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Orrin, who graduated from the University of Memphis, is
an account manager with Docupro, an Atlanta printing company. She
volunteers at two child abuse prevention organizations. Jackson, a
graduate of Yale University Law School, is a corporate attorney who
volunteers and provides free legal services for organizations that
serve poor families. They share a home in Marietta and rarely talk
to their father. Orrin is a single mother herself, with two sons,
12 and 7.
</P>
<P>
   Orrin says that, while people may admire her father for his
activism, his legacy for her is pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a reason to be proud of him,'' she says as she
stares at a picture of her father prominently featured in a book on
the civil rights movement. ``I'm always struck by how much I look
like him. But it bothers me because I don't want the resemblance to
be anything more than skin deep.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson says the real hero in their family is her mother. ``She
showed us that you don't have to choose between being a parent and
serving humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   SON OF A SEGREGATIONIST: ROSS BARNETT JR.
</P>
<P>
   Ross Barnett Jr. can't escape his father's name or reputation.
On Sept. 20, 1962, Mississippi Gov. Ross Barnett Sr., a staunch
segregationist, blocked the admission of James Meredith, a black
man, to the University of Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi would not ``drink from the cup of genocide,'' the
governor declared, defiantly setting off a deadly chain of events.
President Kennedy dispatched 500 federal troops to the university,
where they were attacked by a mob of 2,000 white people. Two people
died and 188 were injured.
</P>
<P>
   That tragedy still touches the Barnett family.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's son believes he is still judged by his father's
actions. Recently, a black journalist refused to shake Barnett's
hand when he learned who his father was.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are racists in all races,'' Barnett, 65, says of the
incident. ``It didn't bother me. I felt sorry for the man. He has a
small viewpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnett was 27 when his father confronted Meredith, and at the
time he supported his father's segregationist stand. ``That was the
plank in every Southern politician's platform,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But he has changed with the times, he says. Married 44 years and
the father of five children, he still lives in Jackson, where he's
a lawyer specializing in criminal and personal injury law. Many of
his clients are black. So, too, he says, are some of his friends.
</P>
<P>
   But some things haven't changed. His father, who died in 1987,
will always be remembered as a segregationist.
</P>
<P>
   But the senior Barnett was much gentler than his public image,
his son says. ``If you spent five minutes with him, you would like
him.'' He loved to tell funny stories and give money to people in
need, the son says. And he wasn't a racist, Barnett insists: He had
black friends and even left money in his will for two
African-Americans, a quail-hunting companion and a masseur.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly four decades after the violence spawned by Meredith's
enrollment, Barnett attributes it to a basic human trait: People
are scared of change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Segregation was the order of the day,'' he says. ``When you
grow up with something and that's all you know, when something
different happens, it's a mind-boggler.''
</P>
<P>
   CHILD OF THE PANTHERS: ERICKA BROWN-ABRAM
</P>
<P>
   Bullets, berets and black leather jackets. Throughout Ericka
Brown-Abram's early life, whether she was attending high school in
Beverly Hills, Calif., or Spelman College in Atlanta, those were
the images people focused on when they discovered that her mother
was a leader of the Black Panther Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``People expected me to wear a beret,'' says Brown-Abram, 30.
``Some would ask, `Do you own a gun? Do you know how to break one
down?' It made me feel like I should whip out a gun and start
cleaning it.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown-Abram is the daughter of Elaine Brown, who took over the
Black Panthers in 1974, when its founder, Huey Newton, went into
exile in Cuba. The organization was about to implode _ many of its
leaders had been wounded or killed, and it was riddled with FBI
informers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Brown-Abram doesn't recall growing up in an environment of
tension, but rather in the nurturing
</P>
<P>
   atmosphere of a communal home in Oakland, Calif. Panther members
did an amazing job of sheltering their children, she says. She
attended a Panther-run school where traditional teaching mingled
with Marxist ideology. Students wore black berets and called
playmates ``comrades,'' but they were forbidden to play with toy
guns. And the school's test scores consistently ranked among the
highest in California, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Panther children were taught to serve the community. Brown-Abram
recalls taking part in programs that provided free breakfasts and
health screenings, and even working alongside migrant workers.
</P>
<P>
   It was a demanding childhood, and at times she craved simple
childhood diversions such as watching cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I didn't want the responsibility of being awake,''
Brown-Abram says. ``I just wanted to be like the other kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother didn't cook for her, because she didn't have time.
The daily rituals that bond many mothers and daughters _ shopping
and combing hair together_ were absent. Yet Brown-Abram doesn't
resent the time her mother spent leading a revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that I don't have the same courage my mom has,'' she
says. ``I'm extremely proud of her, and sometimes I'm overwhelmed,
because I don't know what would make someone that dedicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Brown, an author and lecturer who lives in Atlanta, is
mystified by her daughter's devotion. She still experiences guilt
over the time she missed with her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's fiercely loyal to me,'' Brown says. ``I almost don't
understand it in her. I didn't know when her teeth came in. She
walked three weeks before I first saw her walk. What does that tell
you of me?''
</P>
<P>
   Brown-Abram lives in Macon, Ga., with her husband, Malcolm, and
is a disc jockey and a tour guide for the Harriet Tubman African
American Museum.
</P>
<P>
   She says she is often struck by modern-day reminders that the
Black Panthers' agenda remains relevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can assimilate and become this sparkling race,'' she says,
``but there are still going to be people who will tie us to a truck
and drag us to our death.''
</P>
<P>
   IN HIS FATHER'S STEPS: ALBERT VIVIAN
</P>
<P>
   In 1964, Albert Vivian saw his father get punched in the face on
national television. It's one of his fondest childhood memories.
The confrontation arose as the Rev. C.T. Vivian was attempting to
register as voters a group of blacks turned away from the
courthouse in Selma, Ala. The local sheriff hit Vivian, knocking
him to the ground. But Vivian, his mouth bloodied, stood up to the
sheriff and compared him to Adolf Hitler and the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Americans saw the punch _ and Vivian's courageous
response _ on the evening news.
</P>
<P>
   ``It filled me with a gush of pride,'' says the younger Vivian,
who grew up in Atlanta. ``I remember kids picking at me in school,
saying, `I saw your dad get beat up.' My response was, `If he
didn't do that, you wouldn't be in the school you're in now.' ''
</P>
<P>
   C.T. Vivian, a leader in the Southern Christian Leadership
Conference, took part in voter registration drives throughout the
South. As a result, his family watched the evening news with a
sense of dread. Albert Vivian's mother, Octavia, eventually
instituted a rule that none of her six children could watch the
news unsupervised.
</P>
<P>
   ``She never knew what they might see,'' says the elder Vivian,
now 76. ``What if I had been killed?''
</P>
<P>
   The activists' wives are the unknown heroes of the movement, he
says. They kept the families together; many of the men traveled so
much that they became virtual strangers to their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember being tired and going home to sleep,'' the elder
Vivian says. ``I awoke in the morning and all the kids were sitting
in the room looking at me. It was as if to say, `I wonder what he's
about.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Albert Vivian, 38, is following in his father's footsteps,
taking over a consulting business that offers racial sensitivity
workshops for corporations and city governments. He lives in
Atlanta with his wife, DeAna Jo, and two sons, 9-year-old Louis and
7-year-old Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   A former captain in the U.S. Army, Albert Vivian says he was
inspired to carry on his father's work after watching him conduct a
racial sensitivity workshop on ``The Oprah Winfrey Show.'' He
called after the show ended and said, ``Dad, I want to do what
you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm really enjoying,'' he says, ``is the fact that I'm
giving Dad the time to spend with Mom that he didn't have.''
</P>
<P>
   THE GOVERNOR'S DAUGHTER: PEGGY WALLACE KENNEDY
</P>
<P>
   George Wallace was the subject of many photographs in his
turbulent life, but there was one in particular that he cherished.
It was a shot of him driving his right hand into the bloodied face
of a boxing opponent during a Golden Gloves bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved that picture,'' says Peggy Wallace Kennedy, 50, his
oldest daughter. ``It hung in his bedroom, where he could easily
see it from his bed. He said it was the greatest punch he ever
threw.''
</P>
<P>
   The longtime Alabama governor threw many bruising punches in the
political arena as well. With his bulldog scowl, Wallace was one of
the most visible enemies of the civil rights movement. He once
declared that segregation would last forever.
</P>
<P>
   But her father wasn't a racist, Kennedy says. He was simply a
politician, playing to the wishes of his constituents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that he hated blacks. He treated everybody . . . who
cooked and cleaned for us at the Governor's Mansion like his own
family. I saw it and swore to it. He would never mistreat one of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   She was 8 when her father became governor, and she rarely saw
him. When he was at home, he didn't discuss politics much with his
wife, Lurleen, or Peggy and her siblings, Bobbi Jo, Janie Lee and
George Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's favorite childhood memory of Wallace is of watching
Friday night boxing matches with him.
</P>
<P>
   She never developed an interest in politics. She's a homemaker
living in Montgomery with her husband, Mark Kennedy, a former
Alabama Supreme Court justice. They have two sons, Leigh, 22, and
Burns, 12.
</P>
<P>
   She says that when she married Kennedy _ no relation to the
famous Massachusetts family of the same name _ in the 1970s, her
father received a telegram from Sen. Edward Kennedy, whose brother,
President Kennedy, had sent in the National Guard when Wallace made
his infamous ``stand in the schoolhouse door'' in 1963. The
senator's telegram read, ``I'm so glad we finally got together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad got a big kick out of that,'' the daughter remembers.
</P>
<P>
   What she remembers most about her father is the last years of
his life. He was shot and paralyzed in 1972 while running as an
independent candidate for president. The shooting changed him in
many ways, Kennedy says. He renounced his racial politics, began
reading his Bible every day and started seeking forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would call friends he hadn't talked to for a long time and
say, `If we got anything to straighten out, let's straighten it out
now.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace died in 1998 at age 79. His funeral drew thousands of
people, white and black.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came full circle,'' Kennedy says. ``When you're man enough
to call people you had problems with and say you're sorry, that
says something about you as a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
