<HEADER>
A7040 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-INDIA-PAKISTAN-N     09-08 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-INDIA-PAKISTAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA ANSWERS PAKISTANI CRITICISM ON KASHMIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (With U.N.-MILLENNIUM-SUMMIT) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Two days after Pakistan used the United Nations
summit meeting to deliver a blistering attack on India over its
occupation of Kashmir, India's prime minister counterattacked
Friday without mentioning the name of his country's bitter enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many statesmanlike words have been delivered from this high
tribune,'' Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee of India said when
his turn came to speak Friday. ``Unfortunately, some of them are a
mockery of the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The world must see the reality as it is,'' he said. ``The acid
test of sincerity of purpose is not words but deeds. Terrorism and
dialogue do not go together.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Pakistan's military ruler, Gen. Pervez Musharraf,
told the meeting (without mentioning India, either): ``The people
of Kashmir remain deprived of justice. The consequence of this
injustice has been four wars. The region stands heavily
militarized, even nuclearized.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This situation is certainly not of Pakistan's making,''
Musharraf continued. ``We have been obliged to respond to the
compulsions of our society and have merely acted in self defense.''
</P>
<P>
   India has accused Musharraf, who seized power in a coup last
October, of supporting Kashmiri separatists seeking independence or
autonomy for the disputed Himalayan territory. India continues to
dismiss them as terrorists, a perception that Vajpayee built upon
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all threats to democracy, development and peace in our
times,'' the Indian leader said, ``the most diabolic is
international terrorism, with its links to religious extremism,
drug trafficking and commerce in illicit arms. Terrorism feeds on
violence against innocent people and seeks to undermine plural,
open societies.''
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee, who was re-elected last year, delivered his own appeal
for cooperation with the other leaders. ``I call upon the
international community to act against terrorism before it is too
late,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Musharraf proposed for the United Nations the kind
of role in Kashmir that it played in championing the independence
of East Timor from Indonesia. ``If the people of East Timor could
be given their freedom,'' he said on Wednesday, ``why not
Kashmir?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
