<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-DEPARTURES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIP'S ARE HELPED THROUGH KENNEDY BY A VBP (VERY BUSY PERSON) 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yasser Arafat had deadlines to meet. Take, for instance, the
fact that he was planning to declare an independent Palestinian
state this month. So perhaps such business spurred him to move up
his flight to depart from New York from Friday evening to noon. Or
maybe he just missed home cooking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get the aircraft in,'' Sgt. Vito Asparro of the
Port Authority police said soon after the Secret Service called to
relay the last-minute change. ``We've got a major situation here.''
</P>
<P>
   By noon, Arafat's motorcade had left Midtown for Kennedy
International Airport. That made Asparro sweat. Since 1986, he has
held the title of VIP coordinator in charge of dignitary
protection. For those who need an acronym refresher, Arafat
qualifies as a VIP, as do the other 150 or so world leaders who
flew into town this week for the United Nations Millennium Summit
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, the airport faces the mass exodus. For Asparro,
that means spending the final days of summer in Hangar 12.
</P>
<P>
   All around him, telephones rang and computer screens spat out
information. To keep him company, lots of dark-suited men paced the
room: Secret Service agents, State Department security personnel,
police officers and Port Authority officials and employees from
federal agriculture, immigration and health agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen delegations left on Thursday night, and 80 others were
scheduled to depart over the weekend. The rest had not made plans.
At times like this, having plans and sticking to them could endear
you for life to the sergeant.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, he went to the United Nations and spoke with
representatives from most of the countries that would be sending
delegates. He began listing the things that he needed the
delegations to do to make his job easier. His spoke for more than
an hour and a half, and he would have kept going if they had not
pulled him off the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not everyone heeded the sergeant. For example, he
asked the 50 world leaders who were flying in on their private
planes to bring along tug vehicles to help pull aircraft along the
tarmac. A few delegations showed up empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's delicate, and I would rather not say who it was,'' the
sergeant said.
</P>
<P>
   The private planes ranged from giant Boeing 747s to 15-seat Gulf
Stream 4's. Saudi Arabia came in with a dozen planes. (``You're
talking big, big magnitude,'' Asparro said.)
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the size, all were parked at nearby military bases.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates who were catching commercial flights had to check
in just like everybody else. Their motorcades had to pull up to the
departure terminals rather than the runways, and they had to have
their luggage X-rayed and tagged. What would happen if suitcases
bound for Congo ended up in Iceland?
</P>
<P>
   The sergeant didn't want to think about that. At the moment,
Arafat's motorcade was pulling up, and he had to find a waiting
area fit for a VIP. After all, a stress-free mind always makes for
better peace talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
