<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-COLD-BAND0909-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aussie warmth helps a shivering band
 &HT;    By Ralph Ellis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Fayette County High School band is getting a taste
of Southern Hemisphere hospitality.
</P>
<P>
   Told to pack sweaters, light jackets and long pants for
Australia's late winter, the 160 Fayette students scheduled to
perform at the 2000 Summer Games found occasional sleet and
overnight lows around 38 degrees when they arrived Tuesday at their
practice site in Bathurst, about 100 miles west of Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   But Bathurst residents quickly put the syncopated shivering to
rest by starting a clothing drive for the Fayette students and the
1,830 other band members practicing in conditions resembling
daytime highs at a Winter Olympics site. The townsfolk delivered
``a small mountain'' of coats, sweaters and hats to Charles Sturt
University, Fayette High band parent Phillip Foster wrote in an
e-mail from Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing my daughter had a was a jacket and a
sweatshirt,'' said band parent Donna Thompson of Fayetteville, Ga.,
south of Atlanta, who talked by phone to her daughter, Marly. ``It
is cold. They all had to go out and buy gloves.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
