<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-NIXON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMER OFF ACE CLEMENS TOUGH TO TRUMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He supposes there can be only one thrill that will
trump the night he reduced the Rocket to rubble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully,'' Trot Nixon said, ``one day I can say winning the
World Series was the greatest thing that ever happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then, this will do, the ninth-inning, game-deciding home
run he hit off Roger Clemens in Yankee Stadium May 28, after
Clemens and Pedro Martinez had spent the entire night matching
zeroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an amazing game,'' said Sox closer Derek Lowe, who
was warming up in the bullpen when Martinez loaded the bases with
no outs in the bottom of the ninth, but pitched out of it to
preserve a 2-0 Sox win.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no way I was coming into that game. Hits were so
hard to come by that night, we didn't think anybody was going to
score. Trot's home run was huge. I heard that by the end of the
week, they were selling his jersey in the souvenir shop across the
street.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should. He became a local hero that night.''
</P>
<P>
   That was not the last home run Nixon hit this season. It only
seems that way. The Sox right fielder has hit two more after that,
but none since June 23 in Toronto, when he blew out his hamstring
hustling down the first base line in SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, meanwhile, has lost just once in 16 starts since then,
winning his last seven decisions. He was clobbered by the Mets,
departing down, 9-1, on the night he beaned Mike Piazza, then
lasted just an inning June 14 against the Sox, when he left with a
strained groin.
</P>
<P>
   He went on the disabled list, but since his return has been the
best non-Dominican pitcher in the American League, holding
opponents to three runs or fewer in 11 of his last 13 starts. The
13 strikeouts he had against the Sox in May remains his season
high; he has had just one game since in which he whiffed 10 or more
batters, but with 158 whiffs this season, he is the oldest Yankee
pitcher (38) ever to record 150 or more strikeouts in a season.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility existed Friday night that things could turn
personal between Nixon and Clemens. Nixon claimed Clemens shouted
at him after his first at-bat in May, yelling, ``That's a strike,''
after Nixon looked askance at the plate umpire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I show him a lot of respect,'' Nixon said afterward. ``I give
him a lot of respect. If he doesn't respect me, that's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   When Nixon struck out again on his second at-bat, he returned to
the dugout, raging at himself. He tripled in the seventh, gambling
that he could beat the relay into third. His home run was the final
word that night, but Nixon also was unafraid later to condemn
Clemens for beaning Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how other people feel, but I understand what
Piazza said when he said he didn't respect Clemens,'' Nixon said.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, who was fooled badly on a 2-2 splitter to strike out in
his first at-bat, said he wasn't anticipating any carryover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger is the best pitcher I've ever faced,'' Nixon said.
``He's a guy I've looked up to my entire career, his intensity and
the way he goes about his business and prepares for a game. He's a
gamer. It's a privilege and honor to step into the batter's box and
he's out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, who broke into the majors at the end of the 1996 season,
Clemens's last with the Sox, said he has only exchanged a couple of
words with the Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to play (with the major leaguers) a couple of times in
spring training,'' Nixon said. ``These were guys you saw on TV all
the time, guys that were on the video games that you played.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of nerve-racking. You get the opportunity to be with
these guys and you say, `Geez, that's Roger Clemens on the mound.'
You have to set aside that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   He has never seen a better pitchers' duel than the one that took
place that night in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Clemens and Pedro pitched a heck of a game that night,''
Nixon said. ``Roger was hearing a lot of questions about whether he
still had his stuff. Shoot, I'll tell you when he doesn't have his
stuff. He never lost it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
