<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDAUNTED IN TEXAS, LIEBERMAN ATTACKS BUSH'S HEALTH CARE RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Venturing deep into Gov. George W. Bush's home state
on Friday, Sen. Joseph Lieberman painted a dismal picture of Bush's
record on children's health care, and said the governor could not
be trusted with the issue on a national scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas actually ranks 49th of 50 states in providing health
insurance for kids,'' Lieberman, the Democratic vice-presidential
nominee, said at a forum here. ``In this campaign, Gov. Bush may
say that he has a plan to improve children's health across America.
But I think we have a right to ask, why hasn't he done it in
Texas?''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman and his running mate, Vice President Al Gore, have
made health care a central issue of the campaign, promising to
provide coverage for all of the nation's 11 million uninsured
children by 2004 and prescription drug coverage for older people
under Medicare. Buoyed by opinion polls showing that the public
sees health care as a matter better handled by the Democrats, they
have charged that Bush would endanger Medicare's financial
stability and that his promises to improve health care are hollow.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's foray into Texas _ along with another he plans to
make on Monday _ are a vivid sign of the confidence the Democrats
have found in the last month. They have remained steadily on the
offensive, particularly on health care, and are sure enough of
their standing in traditionally Democratic states to send Lieberman
into a state that is sure to be a Republican stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's remarks by Lieberman may have been the harshest yet in
this campaign, reinforcing the role he is playing as the Democrats'
leading attacker. He charged that under Bush, Texas had done a bad
job of enrolling children in federally financed health care plans,
and that the state had erected bureaucratic hurdles that make it
hard for qualified people to get those benefits.
</P>
<P>
   He cited a ruling by a federal judge last month that Texas had
failed to provide adequate care for children on Medicaid, the
health program for the poor, in violation of a 1996 agreement with
the Bush administration. The state is appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush has just not made children's health coverage and
care a priority,'' the senator said at the Magnolia Multi-Service
Center, in a heavily Hispanic neighborhood here. ``More than 1.4
million children in Texas do not have health insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Bartlett, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, did not dispute
the figures cited by Lieberman, but he said they stemmed from
problems Bush inherited when he became governor in 1995. And he
argued that the state found it hard to enroll people in benefit
programs because ``there is a belief in Texas to scorn government
assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Bush's predecessor, Ann Richards, a Democrat, ``We were
49th then, too,'' Bartlett added. ``The challenges in Texas are not
something that are new in the last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   But the focus of Lieberman's remarks, the Children's Health
Insurance Program, or CHIP, is new. It was created in 1997 by
Congress and President Clinton, providing federal money to the
states to cover uninsured children from low-income families, and
giving the states responsibility for designing their own programs
and enrolling people.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' has been one of the slowest states in signing up poor
children for the program; the Children's Defense Fund ranked its
efforts 45th among the states. Figures compiled by the Health Care
Financing Authority, a federal agency, show Texas had 51,000
children enrolled as of a year ago, about one-third the national
rate, compared to 521,000 in New York, the state with the largest
program.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett said that the creation of a CHIP program in Texas was
delayed because the legislature meets only every other year. Texas
officials say the state's enrollment is up to 90,000 children.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman interviewed working parents here, some with toddlers
squirming on their laps, who told of being unable to find coverage
for their children. ``We had to choose between transportation and
insurance,'' Rosalinda Camarillo said, adding that she had
postponed surgery for her 9-year-old son for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Several parents said they had been wrongly denied Medicaid
coverage, or had their benefits terminated. ``This state
administration has kept in place a very cumbersome bureaucratic red
tape that has kept 600,000 eligible children from enrolling in
Medicaid,'' Lieberman said. Bartlett said the eligibility rules in
Texas go back two decades, and that the state is reviewing them.
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Defense Fund reported last month that Texas was
one of only eight states where the number of children with any form
of health insurance declined from 1997 to 1999, despite CHIP, a
charge Lieberman repeated on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
