<HEADER>
A7054 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-CHAN-CARTOON0909-COX     09-08 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAN-CARTOON0909-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WB hopes kids get a kick out of Jackie, `Shanghai 'toon'
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If you're pitching a new animated series
starring Jackie Chan, there's no better way to sell it than by
letting the international martial arts star do it himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackie would get up and just demonstrate all the things he
wanted to do,'' recalls Jeff Kline, an executive producer of
``Jackie Chan Adventures.'' ``He scared the hell out of WB
executives. That's why they bought the show. We said, `If you
don't, we'll sic Jackie on you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for WB suits, it didn't come to that. The network did
buy ``Jackie Chan Adventures , `` which producers describe as
Indiana Jones meets David Copperfield.
</P>
<P>
   In the series, Chan is an archaeologist and a special government
agent. With the help of his 11-year-old tomboy niece, Chan travels
the globe to recover 12 talismans _ powerful artifacts that hold
unique and magical powers. Along the way, Chan battles everything
from mystical ninja warriors to an evil crime family known as The
Dark Hand.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of each show, a live-action Chan will answer
questions viewers e-mail to the Kids' WB! Web site. So far, kids
want to know if he is ever scared, what kind of ice cream he likes
and why he wanted to be a cartoon character.
</P>
<P>
   The producers say the series will also celebrate Chinese
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to put a different spin on the show,'' Klein
explains. ``Jackie lives in Hong Kong, he was born in China, so it
would've been silly of us not to take advantage of that. So we can
tie into some of the more mystical, historical elements of Chinese
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, but just how did Chan get a cartoon in the first place?
</P>
<P>
   His managers have hinted at the idea for some time. Several
American TV producers also found the concept intriguing. After all,
as Klein notes, more of Chan's films (''Shanghai Noon,'' ``Rush
Hour,'' ``Mr. Nice Guy'') appealed to young moviegoers. Turning his
big-screen persona into a TV cartoon was almost a no-brainer.
</P>
<P>
   But not all bigger-than-life personalities can cut it as a
Saturday morning 'toon. Remember ABC's ill-advised attempt to turn
M.C. Hammer into an animated series? Klein, however, says he's not
that concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackie's already a human cartoon,'' he contends. ``He does
amazing things with his body, and he has big facial expressions. We
just took the action further, without losing his very human,
Charlie Chaplin-like quality.''
</P>
<P>
   John Rogers, who helped develop ``Jackie Chan Adventures,'' has
been a huge fan of Chan's work for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to get bootleg copies of his martial arts films when I
was a stand-up comic,'' Rogers remembers. ``He was always the
reluctant hero. And he had such physical grace. To get over a wall,
he doesn't just climb over it, he does a stagger step up the
corner, and there he goes. It was hypnotizing to see someone move
that beautifully. Plus, there was that amazing kung fu.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Chan is never a bully in his films, Rogers explains it was
important to make Chan a reactionary character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackie will not go out looking for a fight,'' Rogers points
out. ``Trouble just happens to him. That's why we didn't want to
make him a police officer.''
</P>
<P>
   And what does Chan think of the finished product?
</P>
<P>
   ``He loves the idea that he'll never age and that he can do
stuff that won't give him a bad back,'' Klein says, with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Originally Chan was going to do all the voice-over work for his
character. But his hectic film-shooting schedule made that
impossible. His broken English also posed another problem. So the
producers hired another actor to do most of the dialogue. But when
you hear Jackie grunt, moan and yell, that's Chan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He spent a few hours recording only sound effects,'' says
Klein. ``It was the weirdest thing I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen if ``Jackie Chan Adventures `` will catch
on with viewers. In the age of Nickelodeon, The Cartoon Network,
Fox Kids and the rest, the animated TV market is a crowded one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult,'' Klein admits. ``But Jackie Chan means
so much to kids around the world. There's already a pre-sold
element. We were a little bit scared because there's so much
history. But we think we did it right.''
</P>
<P>
   And if they didn't, Klein can just sic Chan on the WB to get
another chance.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
