<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE OF WILLIAMS SURVIVES TORNADO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Fall of the House of Williams appeared imminent.
Timbers came crashing down Wednesday night as a resident champ,
Serena, got jackhammered by Lindsay Davenport. Now, late Friday
afternoon, the foundation was crumbling. The other inhabiting
champion, Venus, had just plunged through the floor, and was
groping in the dark cellar.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Allan Poe must have been chuckling in his grave. This was
a horror story to warm the heart of the author of ``The Fall of the
House of Usher.'' It was so horrifying that the creator of the
House of Williams _ Papa Richard _ walked out on the show at
Flushing Meadows. He's the one who'd been predicting a unique
Williams vs. Williams showdown for the US Open title.
</P>
<P>
   After all, wasn't Serena the 1999 US champ, and hadn't Venus
just won Wimbledon? But in the third set (while the earlier
semifinal victor, Davenport, kicked back and wished nothing but
pulled muscles and major fatigue for the embroiled Martina Hingis
and Venus Williams), you could hear the walls shudder and the beams
splintering.
</P>
<P>
   Venus, serving, was looking for a way out to daylight. But it
was 15-30, 3-5, and Hingis was buzzing about like a malevolent
termite intent on finishing off the razing of the joint: two points
from the final. Venus seemed like Madeline Usher, buried alive.
There was no indication she would survive, 4-6, 6-3, 7-5, and seize
a place in Saturday's final.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was two points away at 15-30 and 30-all,'' Hingis would sigh
later. ``If I would get the next point . . . who knows what would
happen? Still, I served for it at 5-4.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus knew what would happen. ``I just kept fighting and
slugging. At 5-4 I thought, `Well, you waited till the last minute
to break . . . this is the last opportunity.'' The last tango at
Flushing.
</P>
<P>
   And she danced it, with those endless legs churning with endless
energy _ just as she has for so long that Venus ``can't remember
the last time I lost.'' It was 25 matches, and almost three months
ago, to Arantxa Sanchez Vicario in the quarterfinals of the French.
</P>
<P>
   She thought she should have broken Hingis's serve in the eighth
game to 4-4 after a roaring backhand upped her to deuce from 40-30.
But Hingis countered with a backhand winner, then skied a lob that
fell short, within the service line. Should have been easy, if
she'd let it bounce. But Venus didn't and butchered the smash. It
was ugly. Papa Richard winced, and Hingis stepped to 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis was starting to impersonate the whirlwind that destroyed
Poe's House of Usher.
</P>
<P>
   Match game against Venus. She got the opening point. However,
the house was still tilting and began to disintegrate when she
tried a hackerly drop shot. It was either a Chinese Chop or a
Beijing Bunt, an improvisation worthy of a Sunday morning at a
public park.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was some shot,'' she laughs. ``Heat of the moment.'' It
gyrated, and got up to the net, no farther. Papa got up and
departed, watching no further. It was too much for him to see the
House collapse. Maybe he went looking for a gang of construction
laborers.
</P>
<P>
   Did she notice him bugging out? ``Oh, he's up and down and
around. But I don't rely on my parents when I'm playing. I rely on
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Self-reliance was justified. Though she lost the next point to
Hingis's backhand drive, to 15-30, Venus was about to stave off the
whirlwind and save at least half of the House, her quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Even though she'd made a ton of mistakes, outerring Hingis,
47-23, Venus was about to let her ``pretty big heart'' take over.
``I really didn't want to lose. It was just one break. I felt like,
`I deserve to be in the final, and I just need to go ahead and get
it done.' '' The invincible feeling of a long winning streak
uncovered the bricks and plaster from her shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   In a blaze of inspired shotmaking, incredible sprinting and
retrieving, won't-let-you-have-it gumption, Venus was a flash of
lemon, almost outrunning her scanty gown to grab 15 of the
remaining 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis wasn't bending easily as they blasted away at each other,
enthrallingly, at times unbelievably. But bend she did as Venus
raged in the teeth of the whirlwind.
</P>
<P>
   Her ripping backhand along the sideline secured the service
break to 5-5. Venus was climbing out of the rubble, emerging from
the cellar. Immediately, she hooked an ace, and was ahead for good.
She kicked away more debris, and the House of Williams didn't fall
after all.
</P>
<P>
   Venus propped it up, and maybe Davenport should pack a wrecking
ball in her racket bag. Is Venus ever going to lose? Edgar Allan
Poe's raven would croak: ``Nevermore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
