A7060 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DAIMLERCHRYSLER-560&AMP;A     09-08 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAIMLERCHRYSLER-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAIMLERCHRYSLER'S INVESTMENT IN MITSUBISHI COMES WITH MORE
CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKI TANIKAWA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ DaimlerChrysler moved Friday to tighten control over
Mitsubishi Motors Corp., Japan's fourth-largest automaker, which
has been reeling from last month's disclosure that it had concealed
customer complaints about auto defects for more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi Motors' president, Katsuhiko Kawasoe, will resign on
Nov. 1. Takashi Sonobe, currently the executive vice president,
will replace him. Rolf Eckrodt, the chief executive of Adtranz,
DaimlerChrysler's trainmaking subsidiary, is coming to Mitsubishi
Motors as its new chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Under a renegotiated deal announced here Friday, DaimlerChrysler
will keep its stake in Mitsubishi to the 34 percent agreed to in
March, but to compensate for a tumble in Mitsubishi's shares, which
have fallen a quarter in value since the coverup scandal erupted,
DaimlerChrysler will pay 10 percent less: 405 yen a share, instead
of 450 yen, or a total of $1.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi Motors retains control over the posts of president
and chief executive, but the new pact gives DaimlerChrysler
increased leverage over the Japanese automaker and a period to
reassess the alliance, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``DaimlerChrysler's intention now is to take firm control,'' of
Mitsubishi Motors, said Koji Endo, an automobile analyst with
Credit Suisse First Boston in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The move by DaimlerChrysler echoes a similar one by Renault of
France, which took a 35 percent stake in Nissan Motor last year,
and installed Carlos Ghosn as chief operating officer. Ghosn has
since sold off assets and slashed jobs and costs.
</P>
<P>
   And Mitsubishi Motors will be the third Japanese automobile
manufacturer to embrace a foreign executive, after Nissan and Mazda
Motor. The Ford Motor Co. owns a 33 percent stake in Mazda, whose
president, Mark Fields, is an American.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Japanese auto manufacturers, now only Toyota and Honda
are operating under financially independent management. General
Motors owns stakes in Isuzu, Fuji Heavy Industries, and Suzuki.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of the delicate balance between DaimlerChrysler and the
powerful group of Mitsubishi companies like Mitsubishi Heavy
Industries and Mitsubishi Corp., which will hold 34 percent of
Mitsubishi Motors in the deal with DaimlerChrysler, Kawasoe, the
outgoing president of Mitsubishi Motors, is said to have resisted
DaimlerChrysler's demand to raise its stake in the Japanese car
company.
</P>
<P>
   But Mitsubishi Motors did accept DaimlerChrysler's demand to let
it raise its stake in the Japanese auto manufacturer to unlimited
levels three years after the accord, instead of in 10 years as
previously agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had three years, we can recover our performance,''
Kawasoe said Friday. ``Or rather, we have to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   While the incoming chief operating officer, Eckrodt, 58, will be
reporting to Sonobe, 59, his arrival is still sure to be a blow to
the executives at Mitsubishi Motors, which have insisted the
automaker would stay autonomous after entering into the alliance
with DaimlerChrysler, despite huge debts and sluggish sales.
</P>
<P>
   Eckrodt has worked for more than three decades at Daimler, and
was an executive at its Mercedes-Benz unit.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts here praised the new deal and appointment of Eckrodt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is better for Mitubishi Motors to be a DaimlerChrysler
company,'' than a Mitsubishi company, Endo of First Boston said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A foreign executive at Mitsubishi Motors, which sports an
inward-looking, group-oriented culture, could mean a shock to the
car company, which is likely to go through a period of uncertainty
over whether the company will be a truly market-oriented company
with concern for customers and legal compliance.
</P>
<P>
   The outgoing president, Kawasoe, had assumed presidency only
three years ago to replace Takemune Kimura who resigned to take
responsibility for a scandal involving a payoff to gangsters.
</P>
<P>
   Sonobe, the incoming president and chief executive who once
managed the car company's operations in the United States, said
that he was eager to see his company transformed culturally and
become a more ``customer-oriented'' company.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked if he would rethink his company's relationship
with other companies in the Mitsubishi group, he said, ``I want to
see changes at Mitsubishi Motors. Our relations with other
Mitsubishi firms will remain the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have said that DaimlerChrysler means to use
Mitsubishi to fill the holes of its international strategy,
especially in Asia, and that it will try not to become too heavily
involved in Mitsubishi Motors the way Ford and Renault have become
involved with with their Japanese partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes years to restructure a company,'' said Seiji Sugiura,
an automobile analyst with Nomura Securities. ``And share prices of
Mazda and Nissan haven't improved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
