<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7065 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-DRUG-MAIN0909-COX     09-08 1429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-DRUG-MAIN0909-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drug-free Games far from reality
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Edwin Moses, the hurdling icon, looks out on the
Olympic playing field with disgust.
</P>
<P>
   Moses suspects that the drug problem in sports hasn't changed a
bit. All the clues are still there, some more than ever before. The
sudden, drastic change in body shape. The sculpted appearance. The
out-of-this-world performance.
</P>
<P>
   Even the need for braces on the teeth at an older age, a use
that insiders link to skeletal changes brought on by such drugs as
human growth hormone (hGH).
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally have never seen so many (track athletes) get
braces at 30 years old in my life,'' Moses said, snickering. ``I
don't know what that means. But really, everybody seems to have
braces.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Wade Exum, former head of the U.S. Olympic Committee's
anti-doping program, said, ``You look at some of these athletes,
and they're just too cut to be regular human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Exum also is suspicious about the number of athletes,
particularly in track, who surround themselves with a cadre of
personal physicians _ some of whom will accompany them to the
Games.
</P>
<P>
   With the curtain about to open on the Sydney Olympics, athletes
and medical experts alike are convinced that the story will be an
old and familiar one: Performers bent on using steroids and other
substances to make themselves stronger and faster will find ways to
beat the system.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what new test theInternational Olympic Committee
unveils, skeptics hammer the IOC for a history of halfhearted
efforts and, in some cases, for coverups of positive results to
avoid embarrassment. Since drug-testing was introduced, in the 1968
Olympics, only 48 positive tests have been recorded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is there's an innate conflict of interest,''
said Moses, an anti-doping activist since his days as a 400-meter
hurdles champion. ``You're testing your people, and it's not in
your best interest to have your people caught under any
circumstances, because of the level of sponsorship and certainly
the embarrassment. The last place the (IOC) wants anyone to test
positive is at the Olympic Games.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC bears the responsibility of drug-testing at the Games,
and the group's credibility never has been lower, because of the
corruption scandals over selection of Olympic hosts.
</P>
<P>
   The use of performance-enhancers in the Games dates back to
ancient Greece, when athletes consumed psychedelic mushrooms to
gain an edge. In more recent times, East Germans and the Chinese
made an art form of doping athletes, particularly female swimmers
and track athletes.
</P>
<P>
   China sports officials since have cracked down and last week
withdrew 27 athletes and at least one coach from its Sydney team
because of ``suspicious'' results from a blood test. The cuts
include controversial track coach Ma Junren and six of his runners,
along with four men and three women from its 17-member rowing team.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say it is impossible to know how many cyclists,
runners and swimmers are doping. Traditionally, tests have been
performed only at competitions, so cheaters dope before and after.
They also are sophisticated enough to take agents such as
diuretics, which increase the production of urine, to mask the
drugs in their systems.
</P>
<P>
   So cheaters bulk up on human growth hormone and boost their
stamina with erythropoietin (EPO), both modeled after naturally
occurring substances. The IOC plans to test for EPO in Sydney, but
it has no reliable way to check for hGH and other performance
boosters, such as insulin-like growth factor (IGF-1).
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Exum, director of the U.S. Olympic Committee's drug program
until his dismissal in June, estimates that five of eight Sydney
finalists in such sports as track and swimming have used some
banned substances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, that kind of number wouldn't surprise me at (U.S.
Olympic) Trials, either,'' Exum said.
</P>
<P>
   Exum, who has filed a wrongful-dismissal suit against the USOC,
accuses the sports governing body of having a superficial image
when it comes to being tough on drugs. He does not suggest that
athletes are encouraged to use drugs, but he acknowledges that
performance-enhancing drugs work and thus can lead to winning
medals _ which is good for the Olympic business.
</P>
<P>
   He also chides Olympic officials for a system that allows
athletes to stay ahead of drug-testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``During my tenure there, the mindset was that it was a
cat-and-mouse game,'' Exum said. ``It was a game of catch-up. You
have to look at it like, `Hey, they have some new blood
substitutes. Let's learn how to test that stuff before they start
using it.' You've got to get out in front, but that's not the
mindset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that is how the athletes are helped to beat the
system. If we tell the athletes and let them know we're not worried
about stuff that is coming along, that we're still struggling with
trying to catch up with stuff used back in the '80s and '90s, it
basically gives a message, whether straightforward or not, that we
can't find out and we're not going to put a penny toward research
of new methods to find the stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Exum says corporate America wraps itself in the flag and makes
itself oblivious to the pharmecology games. What could send them
scrambling is Exum's fear about serious health problems to athletes
down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern when I got there and saw the amount of drug use
that was going on was that somewhere between 2000 and 2015 we'd
start to see a lot of mysterious illness and fatalities,'' said
Exum, who oversaw the USOC program in the 1990s. ``When that
happens, and happens in bunches, and people start speaking out,
then corporate America will get the word. Until that time, they can
say they're a proud sponsor of the U.S. Olympic team and get
mileage out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The drug issue casts suspicion over any highly successful
athlete. With so many reports of doping, can viewers really trust
that the extraordinary performances they will see from Sydney are
the result of hard work and athletic talent, not drugs?
</P>
<P>
   If Marion Jones wins her five gold medals or runs the race of
her life, what is the public to think?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that whether we took drugs might be a
question,'' said Jones, whose performance has never been linked to
drugs. ``It's unfortunate because you have athletes who have never
even thought about anything like that. It's frustating at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every track-and-field athlete in the world is very cautious
when it comes to taking anything. Even things that you eat. If you
have go to a doctor because you have a cold, it's always in the
back of your mind: ``What am I taking?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Most athletes do things right. And they also know what is
happening in their sports. Fellow competitors voiced concern about
Ben Johnson long before his positive test at the 1988 Seoul Games.
The same for Irish swimmer Michelle Smith, who blew away the
Atlanta competition, only to flunk a surprise, out-of-competition
test two years later.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if uncharacteristically strong performances raise eyebrows
among athletes, Jones said: ``It happens. I'll keep it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   It is understandable that suspicions run freely within the small
fraternity, especially with so much at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is I don't want people to get the idea that to get
on the Olympic (medal) podium, you've got to take the stuff,'' said
Derrick Adkins, defending Olympic 400-meter hurdles champion. ``I
don't want to see everyone get branded because they run fast. But,
sure, it's out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Adkins said that he is aware of athletes resorting to
performance-enhancing drugs and that he had been approached by
athletes suggesting that he would run better if he used them.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches usually maintain contact with drug suppliers, Adkins
said. However, growth hormone and other performance-enhancers can
be purchased just as easily on the Internet these days.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Gray, a four-time Olympian and American record-holder in
the 800 meters, said he has witnessed athletes ``shoot (drugs) into
their systems'' and then come up clean in testing.
</P>
<P>
   The system is not working, for certain, Gray said, but it is not
his job to rat out cheats.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do that to become a better athlete and make money, what
do you really get?'' Gray said. ``How much accomplishment to you
take if you're cheating?''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately in Sydney, the reward still might be a medal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
