<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7068 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-BRICK-ATTACK-2TAKE     09-08 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRICK-ATTACK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS DETAILS OF DELIVERYMAN KILLING EMERGE, SUSPECTS' PARENTS ARE
SHATTERED 
</HEADLINE>
   This article was reported by David Barstow, Sarah Kershaw and
Winnie Hu and written by Barstow.  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They were parents and grandparents who thought they
had fully grasped the perils facing their teen-agers in the tough
working-class streets north of Kennedy Airport in Queens. They said
that they understood the power of peers, the lure of gangs and
drugs, the impact of movies and music and television that, with
relentless repetition, depicted a culture of casual violence.
</P>
<P>
   And, they said, they believed they had taken the necessary
precautions.
</P>
<P>
   They gave their children beepers and cellular phones to keep
better track of them. They lined up mentors, and set curfews, and
encouraged faith. When there were small signs of trouble _ skipped
classes, foul language, low grades _ they cracked down with more
rules. They had heart-to-heart talks about being leaders not
followers, about making distinctions between friends and
manipulators, and of course they prayed, as parents everywhere do,
that all their efforts, however imperfect, had somehow inoculated
their babies from trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, when the detectives began knocking at their
doors with questions about murder and robbery, many of these adults
said that they began for the first time to recognize with
terrifying clarity the limits of their control over their children.
Five teen-agers, ages 14 to 17 _ each from relatively stable
middle-class homes, and none with a criminal record _ are accused
of luring Jin-Sheng Liu, the owner of the Golden Wok restaurant, to
a secluded, vacant house in Springfield Gardens, Queens, and then,
during a bungled ambush to steal their $60 order of Chinese food,
beating him to death with a brick.
</P>
<P>
   According to prosecutors, the teen-agers have confessed to
varying degrees of involvement, and so now _ between waves of
tears, anger and disbelief, between frantic calls to lawyers and
fending off reporters _ five stunned families find themselves
confronting a nightmarish tangle of questions. Where did they fail?
What did they miss? What more could they have done?
</P>
<P>
   ``It just rips you apart,'' said Jean Smith, the mother of James
Stone, the 16-year-old who police officials said threw a sheet over
Liu's head moments before his skull was shattered by repeated
blows. ``It makes you think maybe you failed. But I tell you, I
tried so hard. I tried my hardest. My whole family did.''
</P>
<P>
   The contours of this parental anguish became clear this week
during extended interviews with relatives of three of the
teen-agers and with neighbors, close friends or lawyers for the
other two. Deepening their anguish is an unfathomable reality: An
immigrant who struggled resolutely to build a restaurant business
is dead, leaving behind a wife and two children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so terrible for what happened,'' said the mother of
Robert Savage, 14, who police say was the one who hit Liu with the
brick. ``Can you imagine what they are going through? They lost
their father for what? Stupid food. I cannot believe I raised that
child. He knows better than that.'' She added, ``I can't eat, I
can't sleep. I really had no idea my life could get into something
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday night, only hours before Liu's death, all five
teen-agers seemed fully occupied with the usual rhythms of teen-age
life.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the evening, Jamel Murphy, 17, was flirting with girls
at one of his favorite hangouts _ the Foster-Laurie Police Athletic
League building in St. Albans, Queens. A tall, stocky boy who was
obsessed with the notion of playing professional basketball, Murphy
had spent most every day of the summer at the building, coaching a
basketball team of 9- and 10-year-old boys. His supervisors gave
him high marks.
</P>
<P>
   But that night, children were performing dance routines to the
music of Whitney Houston, and Murphy watched some of the
performances with his close friend, Ebony Cheston, 16. He and
Cheston had talked often recently of their futures, of getting out
of Queens. Cheston said they had both become wary of street
violence. Murphy had vowed to avoid confrontation. ``I'll walk
away,'' he told her.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy left about 7:30 p.m., telling Cheston he was going to see
his friend, Darryl Tyson, 17, another student at Hillcrest High
School in Queens. Tyson lived in Springfield Gardens, in a
neighborhood of twisting dead-end streets and single-family homes
just off Merrick Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Stacy Royster, 17, had already caught a bus to
Tyson's home from her grandmother's house in Rosedale on the
eastern edge of Queens. She knew Tyson from high school, and they
remained close friends even after Royster left school and finished
her studies at home.
</P>
<P>
   Royster was about to begin her first semester at Queensborough
Community College. She had just bought her first batch of
textbooks, said her grandmother, Anastasia Brown, who has raised
Royster since the death of her mother nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Brown worried about her granddaughter; she was fragile, prone to
acting out, vulnerable, she said. For several years the girl had
struggled with bipolar disorder, but doctors assured Brown that
Royster would be fine if she took her medication. Around 8 p.m.,
Brown decided to beep her. Royster promptly called her back from
the cell phone her grandmother had given her for just that purpose.
``Stacy, don't get home too late,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a few blocks from Tyson's home, James Stone was
getting ready to say goodbye to his mother, who was leaving that
night for a church bus trip to Canada. Stone moved to Queens only
last spring. He had lived with his father in Atlanta, but they had
been quarreling. His parents decided he should live with his
mother, who had recently remarried.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 49, a senior teletype operator for Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, said that while her son fit in well at home, he sometimes
struggled at August Martin High School in Queens. He was often
bored by school, she said, and he sometimes cut classes. Nor was
she pleased with some of his new friends. Alarmed, she convened
family meetings. She suggested Bible readings to her son. More
recently, she said, she had decided and he had readily agreed that
he should attend a Catskill boarding school that emphasized
military discipline.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I always worried about Jay,'' she said, ``because he's a boy,
and boys don't like to stay home, and there are so many temptations
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   But that Friday night, she felt certain that her son was in good
hands with her husband, Ralph Smith, a maintenance man. Her son,
she said, had grown close to his stepfather _ he called him ``Pop''
_ and she had also taken comfort in a recent conversation. They had
been watching a movie that showed a grisly murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, man, that's so cold hearted,'' her son had said, prompting
a discussion about the consequences of violence.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, her main worry was that the two men would eat
right while she was away. She stocked the kitchen with steaks and
hamburgers, gave her son $20, and laid out smothered pork chops,
green beans and corn for dinner that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be good,'' she told her son, giving him a hug and a kiss
before driving off about 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Five doors up the road, the parents of Robert Savage were
getting anxious. He had said he would be home by 10, but he wasn't.
So his father went out looking for him. It was a typical response,
neighbors said, describing the 14-year-old's parents as doting but
strict. Recently, they had been warning him to stay away from older
boys, some of whom liked to gather at a nearby dead end and drink
Olde English Malt and smoke marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been fighting about that for months,'' his mother
said. ``I talk to him loud, I talk to him soft, I beg.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear, investigators said, who among the teen-agers
raised the idea of robbing a deliveryman, or how they arrived at
their plan to ambush Liu, a slightly built man, 5 feet 6 inches
tall.
</P>
<P>
   For the last 10 years, Liu had run the Golden Wok, a take-out
restaurant at 192nd Street and Linden Boulevard, in St. Albans, not
far from where the teen-agers were hanging out that night. He made
the deliveries himself.
</P>
<P>
   According to police, the teen-agers had a scheme: Royster was to
order the food from her cellular phone and greet the deliveryman.
When he got there, she would stand up to reach into her pockets, as
if she were going to pay. The four boys, three of them holding a
bricks and one of them holding an old bedsheet to cover Liu's head,
were to wait in hiding, then jump him.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that deliverymen can be suspicious, particularly when
young people order food, they decided that Royster should place the
order because, as a girl, she would be perceived as less of a
threat. Royster placed the first call at 10:52 p.m., ordering
General Tso's chicken, shrimp egg foo yong, chicken with broccoli
and shrimp lo mein _ $60 worth of food in all, according to police
and prosecutors. Murphy told police that he wore a latex glove
because he was going to search the man's car for money, according
to court records.
</P>
<P>
   Having been robbed twice before while making deliveries, Liu,
44, called back to confirm the order and the address, investigators
said. Royster called the restaurant three more times before Liu
arrived, at least once to change the address, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Many restaurant workers along Linden Boulevard, a lively
commercial strip dotted with takeout places and Caribbean-style
restaurants, say they have had to take extra precautions when
making deliveries. Several have installed caller-ID to verify phone
numbers; sometimes they call back and cancel orders if no one
answers. Others avoid venturing into rougher neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the change of address, Liu went ahead with the delivery.
And shortly before 11:30 p.m., he pulled up to the house and got
out of his car carrying two bags of food. He walked across a grassy
patch of lawn toward the stoop, and Royster greeted him and
pretended she was going to pay.
</P>
<P>
   The four boys jumped out of the bushes and descended on Liu in a
flash of chaos and violence, punching and trying to choke him and
then eventually killing him by smashing him in the head with a
brick, according to police and court records. Stone, who had gone
to his house around the corner to get the sheet, threw it over
Liu's head, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-agers gave varying accounts to police of what happened
next.
</P>
<P>
   Stone told investigators that when Liu got to the house, Tyson
started choking him and wrestled him to the ground as he struggled
to break free, before Savage smashed him with the brick, according
to court records. Royster told investigators that after Stone threw
the sheet over Liu's head, all four of the boys were fighting with
him. Savage told the police Tyson first grabbed Liu from behind
while Stone put the sheet over his head, and then Savage hit him
with the brick.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Richard Bellucci, commanding officer of the 113th detective
squad in Jamaica, who oversaw the police investigation, said that
it was hard to sort out exactly how the attack unfolded, but that
he believed Tyson and Murphy had grabbed Liu and started choking
and punching him. The lieutenant said Savage was the only one to
use a brick in the attack, even though two other boys had brought
bricks to the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened all at once,'' he said, adding, ``This went down
very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The teen-agers then fled, taking one bag of the Chinese food
with them, and going to Tyson's house, a few blocks away on 178th
Street, where, they told police, they hid for several hours,
Bellucci said. They ate the food there.
</P>
<P>
   For a few days, their worlds remained intact. Royster prepared
for her first day of college. Stone's mother returned from her
church trip and completed his application for boarding school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard some Chinese man died,'' Tyson told a friend he met at
Green Acres Mall.
</P>
<P>
   None of their parents suspected a thing.
</P>
<P>
   But by Tuesday, having traced the cell phone calls to Royster
and confronted her, detectives from the 113th Precinct fanned out
to make arrests.
</P>
<P>
   When they knocked on Stone's door at 11:30 p.m., his mother
cried out in panic. She assumed they were there to tell her that
her son was dead.
</P>
<P>
   She said her son at first calmly denied everything.
</P>
<P>
   Today, what makes her most angry is the suggestion that a man
died because her son and his friends wanted a free meal. ``He had a
hot dinner on a stove and a house full of food,'' she said, adding
that she had since given her son her Bible to read in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy's father was so angry that a day after the arrest he was
shaking with rage. Meanwhile, the players at the athletic league
were stunned to see their coach on television, head down and in
handcuffs. One of his players, Ebony Cheston's brother, burst into
tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamal was his mentor,'' Cheston said.
</P>
<P>
   Savage's mother, who came to this country from the West Indies,
said she could barely bring herself to talk to distant friends and
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so ashamed of what has happened,'' she said, weeping.
``I'm afraid even to let people know. I'm ashamed of it, even
though I didn't do anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
