<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge: ACLU can sue governor
 &HT;    By Tracie Powell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Protesters who were arrested outside the
Governor's Mansion last fall can continue with their lawsuit
against George W. Bush, a Travis County district judge decided
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Judge John Dietz ruled for the second time that the American
Civil Liberties Union could sue Bush, along with the Department of
Public Safety, for violating protesters' freedom of speech and
assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters were arrested four different times on the
sidewalk outside the Governor's Mansion while demonstrating against
environmental policies that Bush supported. Charges of blocking an
entry were later dropped in each of the cases.
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU filed a lawsuit in August 1999 against Bush and the
DPS. Assistant Attorney General Paul Matula, who is representing
the governor's office, claimed Bush shouldn't be a party to the
lawsuit because security policies at the mansion were made by DPS
without participation from Bush or his office.
</P>
<P>
   But two weeks ago, Dietz decided to allow the lawsuit to go
forward. He later told government lawyers they could file a motion
asking him to reconsider his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Dietz on Friday explained that he was more familiar with DPS
rules now than when he made the original ruling and wanted the
record to reflect that. But Dietz said that does not preclude Bush
from avoiding the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   No trial date has been set, although Dietz said no action is
likely until after the November presidential election. Lawyers on
both sides will meet next week to discuss a settlement, Bush
spokeswoman Linda Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   After the decision, civil rights lawyer David Kahne declared
victory, while Bush representatives said it's too soon to say what
steps they will take next.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's premature for us to make a decision before the
mediation,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights lawyers charge that the governor authorized and
encouraged police to ``exclude people who peacefully express
opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   Police have said they were trying to keep protesters safe.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
