<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7072 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GOLDMAN-NASDAQ-NYT &LR;      09-08 0374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-NASDAQ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN SACHS GROUP IN TALKS TO ACQUIRE SPEAR, LEEDS &AMP; KELLOGG 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs Group, the investment banking firm, is in talks to
acquire Spear, Leeds &AMP; Kellogg, the biggest maker of markets in
listed stocks and one of the biggest traders on the Nasdaq stock
market, according to a person with knowledge of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Goldman declined to comment on the
possibility, as did executives of Spear, Leeds, a private company.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase, if completed would be Goldman's biggest since
going public in May 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman has shown interest in acquiring one of the leading
Nasdaq trading firms to increase its role in electronic trading,
especially technology company stocks, such as Microsoft, Cisco
Systems and WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, Goldman paid $531 million for the Hull Group, a
Chicago-based trading firm that buys and sells futures, options and
stocks electronically on 28 exchanges in nine countries.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman officials considered buying Herzog Heine Geduld, a
market maker based in Jersey City, N.J., before it was bought in
mid-July by Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. using about $1 billion of its
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Spear, Leeds &AMP; Kellogg, which earned $846 million
on revenue of $2.7 billion in the nine months ended June 30, could
be worth several times what Merrill paid for Herzog.
</P>
<P>
   Buying Spear, Leeds, the fourth-biggest Nasdaq market maker,
would give Goldman a 21 percent stake in Redibook, one of a new
breed of electronic exchanges known as electronic communication
networks. Earlier this year, Spear, Leeds sold shares of Redibook
to other financial firms, including Fidelity Investments and
Charles Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition would make Goldman the biggest specialist firm
on the New York Stock Exchange and the American Stock Exchange.
Specialists operate trading posts on the floor of an exchange at
which they match buyers and sellers for particular stocks and often
use their own money to buy or sell shares. Their numbers have been
dwindling through a series of mergers, and some analysts fear that
with the trend toward more electronic trading, specialists will
gradually lose their value.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
