<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7073 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-DEBATES-NYT     09-08 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DEBATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AGREES TO DROP HIS DEBATE PROPOSAL AND NEGOTIATE WITH
COMMISSION 
</HEADLINE>
 (See also BUSH-NYT) 
 By PETER MARKS with FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush abandoned his effort to impose
his own schedule of presidential debates on Friday, and his
campaign said it was prepared to sit down with aides to Vice
President Al Gore to work out an agreement for debating under the
auspices of a bipartisan commission.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's advisers responded that they were willing to meet with
the Bush campaign. The Commission on Presidential Debates, the
bipartisan panel that has been organizing the debates since 1988,
said it had received a call on Friday from Bush's campaign
chairman, Don Evans, and immediately began trying to arrange a
meeting with representatives of both campaigns next week in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor's decision did not appear to guarantee that
Bush would sign off on the commission's original plan for three
debates next month on college campuses in Boston, Winston-Salem,
N.C., and St. Louis, all of which Gore has agreed to. Advisers to
Bush continued to insist on Friday that while the campaign might
agree to two of the commission's debates, it remained opposed to
the Boston event and wanted to replace it with a network-sponsored
debate, perhaps with CNN's Larry King as moderator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows there have got to be two commission debates,
and everybody knows there has to be an agreement soon,'' said an
adviser to Bush who spoke on condition of anonymity. Aides to Bush
repeated their position that Boston was not acceptable, because the
debate is to be held on the University of Massachusetts campus
adjacent to the John F. Kennedy Library, which honors a Democratic
president. ``I can't think of any reason in the world why we'd do
that,'' the adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign announced the shift in the face of what aides
to the governor described as mounting criticism from prominent
Republicans, and a desire to put a distracting issue to rest. Bush
made the proposal on Sunday night, challenging Gore to two network
debates, one on CNN and one on NBC, in addition to one sponsored by
the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Because the network debates were likely to attract many fewer
viewers than the commission debates, which would be broadcast on
multiple networks and cable outlets, many Democrats accused Bush of
trying to avoid wide exposure.
</P>
<P>
   And while Bush tried to used Gore's rejection of the idea to
raise questions about the vice president's credibility, even some
members of Bush's staff suggested the strategy was not working.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Bush advisers on Friday sought to shift blame for
the collapse of their proposal on Gore, saying that he had made it
clear he would not attend a debate proposed by Bush for next week
on a prime time edition of ``Meet the Press'' on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``NBC News has told us that they have received a letter from
Vice President Gore indicating that he will not attend the debate
next Tuesday night,'' Bush's communications director, Karen P.
Hughes, told reporters during a brief campaign layover on the
tarmac of an airport here on Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes added that Gore's refusal came ``despite the fact that he
had accepted that debate and said he will debate anytime, anywhere.
NBC News reiterated today that they will not host the debate unless
both candidates are there.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC News and the Gore campaign disputed the suggestion by Hughes
that the letter was breaking news. Gore's aides announced days ago
the vice presidentwould not participate. And Barbara Levin, an NBC
spokeswoman, said the network has had that rejection letter from
William M. Daley, the Gore campaign chairman, since Sunday, the day
Bush unveiled his debate plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sent that letter within an hour of Gov. Bush's press
conference,'' said Mark Fabiani, the Gore campaign communications
director. ``We faxed it to Tim Russert at his home and at his
office.'' Russert is the host of ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   After learning on Friday that Bush had abandoned his plan, Daley
said he welcomed the opportunity to meet with the governor's staff,
but he seemed inclined to stick with the commission's original plan
of three debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go in and hear what they have to say,'' he said. ``Right
now our attitude is three. It's only four and a half hours in a
campaign that lasts thousands of hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's had contended his proposal, which included the 90-minute
debate in St. Louis sponsored by the commission, plus two 60-minute
debates, on ``Meet the Press'' on Tuesday and on ``Larry King
Live'' on Oct. 3, was an effort to invigorate the debates by
providing a variety of formats. Gore, however, sought to
characterize the proposal as an effort to limit viewership. Two
major networks left out of the Bush plan, ABC and CBS, announced
that they would not carry debates on rivals' programs.
</P>
<P>
   Debate commission officials have said repeatedly that they are
willing to negotiate over the formats of the debates, and would
even entertain the campaigns' suggestions for moderators. But they
have been less willing to forgo the debate sites, which were chosen
from proposals submitted by dozens of institutions around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   There is precedent for holding only two debates. Four years ago,
one of the three commission debates was canceled because President
Clinton had a scheduling conflict.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
