<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WRESTLING-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: WRESTLING  
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Controversy surrounded selection of the U.S. Greco-Roman
wrestling team when welterweight Matt Lindland protested the third
match of his 2-1 loss to Keith Sieracki in the 167.5-pound class at
July's Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
   An arbitrator ruled that the match be rewrestled last month, and
Lindland won, leading USA Wrestling to name him to the Olympic
team.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute eventually hit the courts. Last week, the Supreme
Court Justice John Paul Stevens rejected a request by the U.S.
Olympic Committee to keep Lindland off the team.
</P>
<P>
   THE SETUP
</P>
<P>
   Freestyle wrestlers can use their arms and legs for holds, but
Greco-Roman wrestlers cannot use the legs to attack their
opponents. Wrestlers are divided into eight weight classes for each
style, from 119 to 286 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCORING
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of two three-minute rounds, wrestlers can score
technical points for various holds, maneuvers or throws. A wrestler
wins with a pin _ holding his opponent's shoulders to the mat for
half a second, or by scoring 10 points more than his opponent. A
winner must score at least three points to win a match. If there is
a tie, the match enters a three-minute overtime. If the score is
still tied, or neither wrestler has reached three points, a
majority vote is taken by the referee, judge and mat chairman.
</P>
<P>
   THE NAMES
</P>
<P>
   There is one dominant wrestler: Alexsander Karelin, the
286-pound Russian who has won three consecutive gold medals and
nine world championships. In his trademark maneuver, he lifts
opponents off the ground and throws them over his head. Karelin
beat the American Matt Ghaffari for the 1996 gold.
</P>
<P>
   In Sydney, his leading opponents include Hector Milian of Cuba,
Sergei Mourieko of Bulgaria and Giuseppe Giunta of Italy. Rulon
Gardner, the U.S. entrant in this weight class, is a two-time Pan
American champion and three-time U.S. nationals winner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
