<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7076 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BUSH-REAUD0909-COX     09-08 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-REAUD0909-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    University turns down $12.5 million giftBy Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After being courted by his alma mater for three
years, Wayne Reaud, one of the state's most prominent trial
lawyers, agreed to give Texas Tech University's law school $12.5
million, easily the largest such gift ever to the law school.
</P>
<P>
   But the university board wouldn't take it.
</P>
<P>
   Although the gift had been solicited and negotiated by the
university chancellor, John Montford, and law school dean, Frank
Newton, the board said that under the circumstances, $12.5 million
wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   Reaud (pronounced REE-o) had understood that in return for the
donation, the university would name its 30-year-old law school
after him and his wife, Dana. He's a 1974 graduate of the law
school.
</P>
<P>
   But the board said the price tag for naming a university school
after a donor was much higher _ $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Montford said there was a simple, though unfortunate,
misunderstanding.
</P>
<P>
   What Tech was willing to do, Montford said, was rename its law
school building, not its law school. ``I'm sorry if that got lost
in the translation, and I'm not blaming it on him _ I'm blaming it
on me,'' Montford said.
</P>
<P>
   Reaud, who practices in Beaumont and helped the state sue the
tobacco industry, thinks the real reason for the board's refusal
was political, that Gov. George W. Bush or his business and
Republican supporters couldn't stand the idea of the law school
being named after one of their ``enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that it didn't work because I was a trial lawyer
that had been targeted by the Bush people, or by Bush and his
people, as a large Democratic contributor and an enemy of the
governor,'' Reaud said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly never considered myself an enemy of the governor,
but I was told he considers me such,'' Reaud said last week. He
previously had declined to comment after the Tech board failed to
accept his proposed gift at its meeting in May.
</P>
<P>
   All nine members of Texas Tech's board are Bush appointees, and
Reaud, 52, has not been a Bush supporter. He contributed $75,000 to
the Democratic candidate for governor, Garry Mauro, in his losing
1998 campaign against Bush, a Republican. Reaud's law firm, Reaud,
Morgan &AMP; Quinn of Beaumont, gave another $5,000 to Mauro.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office said it was not involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor's office played no role in this action by the
Texas Tech board of regents,'' said Mike Jones, a spokesman for
Bush. The governor, he said, trusts the regents ``to make decisions
that are in the best interests of the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Sowell, chairman of Texas Tech's board, said the $12.5
million gift from the Reauds had been welcome but fell well short
of the $25 million threshold previously set for a university school
to be named after a donor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very simple, cut and dried _ the gift was not large
enough for us to name the law school after him,'' Sowell said.
</P>
<P>
   Montford said that renaming the law school in honor of a $12.5
million donor could undercut efforts to persuade other wealthy
donors to give $25 million to get a university institution named
after them. Negotiations with at least four such potential donors
are under way, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for politics, Montford said he was not pressured by anybody
to reject the gift and noted that he is a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Sowell, a construction company owner, also denied that Reaud's
politics or status as a plaintiffs' lawyer was a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there are those who don't care for lawyers,'' Sowell
said, ``but shoot, we've got a law school. We're in the business of
training lawyers. So it was certainly no factor from my point of
view.''
</P>
<P>
   Newton, the law school dean, said he was embarrassed by what had
happened after he and Montford had worked hard _ Montford said for
three years _ to persuade Reaud to make a big contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Newton said most Tech alumni he had talked with favored the
potential gift as a great opportunity for the law school. But, he
added, the gift was ``not well received locally.''
</P>
<P>
   Trial lawyers _ also known as personal injury or plaintiffs'
lawyers _ have become a favorite target of criticism from business
interests and Republicans, who say they manipulate the legal system
to force business, insurance and medical defendants to pay
settlements on questionable claims rather than risk even bigger
judgments from a jury.
</P>
<P>
   Reaud has been a highly successful trial lawyer, even before he
helped the state win a $17.3 billion settlement from the tobacco
industry. His Beaumont law firm is one of five Texas firms sharing
in $3.3 billion in legal fees to be paid over the next 25 years for
winning that settlement.
</P>
<P>
   He and the other tobacco trial lawyers also are the subject of
an investigation by Attorney General John Cornyn, a Republican, who
has questioned how they got the contract to represent the state
from his predecessor, former Attorney General Dan Morales, a
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact I was a successful trial lawyer operated to my
disadvantage in this deal,'' Reaud said. (He also said that
Cornyn's probe is ``certainly'' motivated by political
considerations.)
</P>
<P>
   Newton said that what Reaud and the university had negotiated
was in two parts. The Reauds would put up $2.5 million, matched
with $2.5 million from the university, to update the law school
building technologically.
</P>
<P>
   Also, they were going to put up $10 million for a special
scholarship program that Dana Reaud had called a Peace Corps for
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The scholarship program would have paid all of a student's
tuition and fees, plus $1,000 a month in living expenses. In
return, after graduation, the student would be required to spend
three years in some sort of public service _ pushing environmental
cases, for example, or representing battered women _ rather than
immediately sign up with a private law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Reaud said that he's looking elsewhere to make major
contributions, but not Texas Tech. ``They're not on my list _ which
is unfortunate, frankly, for them as well as me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Montford, himself a lawyer, said the Reaud situation was ``my
only fumble'' in his hard-charging Horizon Campaign, which so far
has raised $450 million for Texas Tech. And he said he will try
again to get help from Reaud: ``I'm not going to give up that
easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
