<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7079 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-LIEBERMAN-HNS &LR;      09-08 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Lieberman blasts Bush health care
 &HT;    Democratic VP hopeful visits low-income workers here
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By ALAN BERNSTEIN
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Democratic vice-presidential candidate Joseph
Lieberman slammed Republican Gov. George W. Bush's record on health
care for Texas children Friday at a Houston meeting with low-income
workers who have fought state agencies for family aid.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have conceded the Texas vote to Bush in the
presidential election, so Lieberman's first trip to the state since
joining Al Gore's ticket was meant to be a message about health
care to undecided voters in states where the contest is close.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush may say that he has a plan to improve children's
health across America, but I think we have a right to ask: `Why
hasn't he done it in Texas?' '' Lieberman said at the municipal
Magnolia Multi-Service Center on the east side.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut senator, criticizing the state's performance on
providing medical insurance for children through Medicaid and the
Children's Health Insurance Program, said Bush ``has just not made
children's health coverage and care a priority.'' His remarks
worked in conjunction with a Democratic National Committee
television commercial _ airing outside Texas _ that trumpets a
federal judge's recent ruling that the state has not kept a 1996
legal promise to improve children's health care.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Lt. Gov. Rick Perry led a counterattack Friday in a
news conference at a southwest Houston clinic run by Harris
County's public health care system.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is using the federal aid programs better than most other
states, Perry said, and any remaining problems should be blamed on
restrictions created by President Clinton and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will backfire on Al Gore and Joe Lieberman to come
to the state of Texas,'' Perry said. ``I think Texans are tired of
people using the state as a whipping post for their political
expediency.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were careful, though, to separate the Lone Star State
from the Republican Party's presidential contender. With a Texas
flag displayed to their left, Lieberman and Mayor Lee Brown, who
led off Friday's event, referred to Texas as ``a great state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know Governor Bush very well and as far as I can tell
he is an honorable and decent man,'' said Lieberman. ``But we are
going to talk about (his) record.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that Bush was against providing the CHIP to
children of families who earn as much as twice the annual poverty
standard. The Texas Legislature adopted the policy anyway, and
Democrats say it made about 220,000 children eligible for health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman also charged that under Bush, the state ``has kept in
place a very cumbersome bureaucratic red tape that has kept almost
600,000 eligible children from enrolling in health care.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining with Perry, physician and Republican state Rep. Kyle
Janek of Houston said he and Bush had favored CHIP funding for
children of families earning at 1.5 times the poverty rate, rather
than double, to make sure the poorest children got benefits at a
time when the amount of CHIP funding was unknown. Now, with
assurance that the higher earning limit is affordable, Texas is
enrolling children in the program faster than California and other
states, Janek said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County Judge Robert Eckels said that regardless of
whether Texas children have health insurance from private or
government sources, they can still qualify for free or discounted
health care from agencies such as the county hospital district.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said that Gore as president would expand health
insurance coverage and options for the working poor. He said his
indictment of Bush's performance was bolstered by the stories told
in a talk-show format Friday by eight adults, some of whom brought
their children to the meeting with the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Landscaper Michael Zamarron said he doesn't earn enough to buy
private insurance for his infant, and had to pay for medical care
with money borrowed from relatives while battling with the state to
get Medicaid benefits for the child.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a cop in the military, we didn't have to do half
that paperwork,'' Zamarron said.
</P>
<P>
   Like others in the group, which was hand-picked to include
whites, blacks and Hispanics, Zamarron praised the CHIP program in
Texas and offered no criticism of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   That may not have supported the points Lieberman was trying to
make. But audience member Garnet Coleman, a Democratic state
representative from Houston who specializes in health care issues,
said the children of the people who spoke with Lieberman might not
have qualified for CHIP funds under the rules favored by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Limas said she had to pawn her truck to help pay for her
toddler son's hernia operation. The state agency that administers
Medicaid disqualified her family for aid, she said, because her
husband had enough money to pay child support to his previous wife.
</P>
<P>
   When Limas explained that her husband wanted the family to
scrape by without help from any other government program, Lieberman
said that ``it's your right'' to apply for benefits and that her
husband has an admirable attitude but ``shouldn't be too proud
here.''
</P>
<P>
   He told Angela Gehring, a divorced mother of three children who
lacks sufficient income while seeking a master's degree, ``The
responsibility of government is to cover you.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is scheduled to return to Texas on Monday with
campaign stops in Dallas and Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Outside his Houston event, about 20 labor union members yelled
support for the Democratic ticket, alongside five Republican
boosters who chanted, ``Bush is the cure.''
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
