<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOLDMAN SACHS IS IN TALKS TO ACQUIRE SPEAR, LEEDS
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs Group, the investment banking firm, is in serious
talks to acquire Spear, Leeds &AMP; Kellogg, the biggest maker of
markets in listed stocks and one of the biggest traders on the
Nasdaq stock market, according to a person with knowledge of the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase, if completed, would be Goldman Sachs' biggest
since it went public in May 1999. Goldman has shown interest in
acquiring one of the leading Nasdaq trading firms to increase its
role in electronic trading of stocks, especially those of popular
technology companies, such as Microsoft, Cisco Systems and
WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   BROKERAGE EXECUTIVE PLEADS GUILTY
</P>
<P>
   Randolph Pace, a brokerage-firm executive charged with enriching
himself through a wide-ranging securities fraud conducted between
1994 and 1997, pleaded guilty in federal court in New York to 13
felony counts of conspiracy, money laundering and securities fraud.
Under the terms of his plea, Pace agreed to give $3 million
immediately to the U.S. government. He is subject to additional
fines, to be determined by the court, that will go into a
restitution fund for investors who lost $200 million or more as a
result of the conspiracy, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIER IS SUED BY HIS MOTHER
</P>
<P>
   Saul P. Steinberg, the chairman of Reliance Group Holdings, is
being sued by his mother, who contends that he owes her millions of
dollars. Anne Steinberg filed a lawsuit in state Supreme Court in
New York demanding that her son repay almost $5 million that she
says he borrowed from her in 1997 and promised to repay on Dec. 31,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   VERIZON ANNOUNCES OPTION GRANT
</P>
<P>
   Verizon Communications said it would grant 210,000 employees
options to buy 55 million shares of stock, giving them a stake in
the carrier's financial performance.
</P>
<P>
   CONSULTANTS CORNER VOTER MARKET
</P>
<P>
   Aristotle International, a consulting firm, has compiled the
United States' largest voter data bank _ the names of 150 million
Americans registered to vote. And it is selling them to politicians
like George W. Bush, Joe Lieberman and John McCain in ways that
many fear removes too much privacy from the voting booth. Aristotle
has a client list that reads like a political convention: 45
senators, more than 200 members of the House, state parties and
every major presidential candidate except Al Gore, whose campaign
says it will not hire any firm whose practices could jeopardize the
public's privacy.
</P>
<P>
   SLOW PROFIT GROWTH STALLS MARKETS
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell as evidence of slowing profit growth prompted
investors to sell shares. The Nasdaq composite index dropped 119.94
points, or 2.9 percent, to 3,978.41. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index fell 8.01 points, or 0.5 percent, to 1,494.50. The
Dow Jones industrial average lost 39.22 points, or 0.4 percent, to
11,220.65.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE RENEWS CALL FOR ELECTRIC CARS
</P>
<P>
   California regulators voted to keep a rule requiring that 10
percent of cars offered for sale in the state starting in 2003 emit
few or no pollutants, a goal that the industry has said is
unreachable. The unanimous decision by the California Air Resources
Board, which regulates the state's air quality, is expected to
increase the number of electric cars on the road, not only in
California but in other states that have opted to follow California
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   CRUDE OIL FALLS FROM 10-YEAR HIGH
</P>
<P>
   The price of crude oil fell from a 10-year high, after Saudi
Arabia signaled that OPEC would agree to expand production to trim
prices at a meeting this weekend in Vienna, Austria. Ali al-Naimi,
the Saudi oil minister, said Saudi Arabia wanted to bring prices
down to $22 to $28 a barrel for the group's oil benchmark _ the
price was $33.63 on Friday. OPEC is expected to increase daily
supplies 500,000 to 800,000 barrels.
</P>
</TEXT>
