<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7082 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-DEBATETOWN-HNS &LR;      09-08 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 TOWN-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    In Danville, Ky., the debate spat hits home
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By LYNWOOD ABRAM
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Danville, Ky., loses its moment of fame because of the
squabbling over presidential campaign debates, lots of folks in
Danville will take it personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush is not very popular here right now,'' reported
Vicki Glidewell, who works at Danville's Centre College. Centre is
where the debate between Democratic vice presidential nominee
Joseph Lieberman and Republican nominee Dick Cheney is scheduled
for Oct. 5.
</P>
<P>
   All the debates are up in the air now because Republican
presidential nominee Bush has refused to commit to the debate
schedule, proposed by the Commission on Presidential Debates, that
would have included a vice-presidential face-off in Danville.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic presidential nominee, Al Gore, has accepted that
schedule, and said he won't agree to alternatives proposed by Bush
unless Bush accepts the commission's schedule.
</P>
<P>
   John Roush, president of Centre College and the prime mover in
getting the vice-presidential debate scheduled in Danville, is
especially concerned _ though nonpartisan in his comments.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, Roush said:
</P>
<P>
   ``As our nation's political leaders talk about the schedule for
this year's general election debates, I want them to remember three
things: 1. Centre College and the town of Danville were chosen by
the Commission on Presidential Debates to host a vice-presidential
debate. 2. We've now been preparing for more than a year, and we've
invested over $700,000 as well as countless hours of labor. 3. This
debate still ought to happen because it represents a historic
moment: the first time in American history that a nationally
televised (presidential) debate would originate in a small town.''
</P>
<P>
   For Danville, with a population of about 17,000 in central
Kentucky, the debate would be big news, said John Davis, editorial
page editor of the local newspaper, the Advocate-Messenger.
</P>
<P>
   ``In politics, it's the biggest thing that ever happened here,''
Davis said. ``(President Franklin) Roosevelt came here in the
1930s, Ronald Reagan was here but not as a candidate or when he was
president, and Jimmy Carter gave a commencement address here after
he was president. It's a big deal here.''
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan Commission on Presidential Debates, which has
sponsored the presidential debates since 1968, made a firm
commitment in January to hold the one scheduled vice-presidential
debate in Danville.
</P>
<P>
   Late in August, however, Bush refused to accept the commission's
schedule. He proposed three debates with Gore: on a special edition
of NBC's ``Meet the Press'' Tuesday (Sept. 12) in Washington, D.C.;
on CNN's ``Larry King Live'' and a Spanish-language network Oct. 3
in Los Angeles; and at Washington University in St. Louis on Oct.
17 _ the only one of the three that was on the commission's
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore had said he would debate Bush ``anywhere,
anytime,'' he rejected the single-network debates unless Bush
agreed to the others.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign, which had described its debate proposal as
final, renewed negotiations with Gore's camp and the commission
Friday after NBC canceled plans for its debate. The network had
said previously that it would not air the special prime-time
edition of ``Meet the Press'' unless Gore participated.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said campaign chairman Don Evans
would lead the negotiations for Bush. Hughes said the 1996
presidential candidates debated only after signing a 40-page
agreement on Sept. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Bush proposed two debates between Cheney and Lieberman _ one at
Winston-Salem, N.C., and another at a place to be announced.
</P>
<P>
   No mention of Danville.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Ernie Fletcher, a Republican first-termer whose
district includes Danville and Lexington, on Thursday wrote Bush
``encouraging him to make sure that they agree to holding the
debate in Danville, regardless of what they may finalize about the
presidential debates,'' said Daniel Groves, Fletcher's chief of
staff.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher is in a close race for re-election with Democrat Scott
Baesler.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle reporter R.G. Ratcliffe contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
