<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7083 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SMASH-PALMBEACH0909-C     09-08 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMASH-PALMBEACH0909-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Burglaries shock Palm Beach community
 &HT;    By Chris Barker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Mara Perkons peered across Worth Avenue in
dismay Friday morning, taking in shop windows smashed by three
carloads of brash burglars who struck three stores before dawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly hope that they don't come back,'' said Perkons,
manager of the Louis Vuitton store across the street.
</P>
<P>
   She was just one of many well-coifed denizens who milled around
the renowned retail avenue while police detectives dusted for
fingerprints and crunched through thick pieces of fashionably green
glass left in piles outside Chanel, Gucci and Mystique Created
Gems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked because it didn't look like Worth Avenue
anymore,'' said Mariano Ordenanz, owner of a nearby jewelry store.
He didn't expect to see Worth Avenue bedecked with yellow crime
scene tape and buzzed by police helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was a Friday in the off-season, the burglaries
brought almost as much attention to the island as a presidential
visit, complete with closed streets and TV cameras.
</P>
<P>
   An organized group of thieves quickly smashed windows and glass
doors and made off with jewelry and designer handbags about 5 a.m.,
Palm Beach police said.
</P>
<P>
   As they fled, a stolen Nissan Maxima became the ultimate party
crasher outside Donald Trump's Mar-a-Lago Club on South Ocean
Boulevard. One carload of burglars crashed into some trees and the
sea wall and ran through neighborhoods of the rich and famous,
sparking a hunt that lasted half the day.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's deputies, off-duty police officers and West Palm Beach
police combed the lawns of estates and golf courses in the wee
hours of the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Along with help of two police dogs, a helicopter and boat
patrols, the 50-strong force nabbed four males within three hours
of the car wreck, Capt. Michael Mason said. None were injured in
the wreck, but one was suffering from an old gunshot wound, Mason
said.
</P>
<P>
   To find the fifth man, Mason said he called back the uniformed
officers and sent out officers in street clothes to monitor the
area. The fifth fugitive was spotted emerging from the Lake Worth
Lagoon about 12:30 p.m., soaking wet. He was arrested about 4 miles
south of Worth Avenue, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The five were booked into the Palm Beach County jail and the
county's Juvenile Assessment Center on charges of criminal
mischief, two counts of burglary, grand theft auto, and eluding
officers, police said.
</P>
<P>
   But two carloads of burglars got away carrying an undetermined
amount of people and loot, according to police.
</P>
<P>
   As police wrapped up Friday morning, shopkeepers surveyed the
damage.
</P>
<P>
   Several display cases inside the Gucci store were broken, and
mannequin necks in the Mystique picture window stood empty. At
Chanel, half of the glass front door was shattered, the other
looked as if it had been struck with a sledge hammer.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the retailers put forth their usual positive spin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our jewelry looks so good they thought they were diamonds,''
said Sarkis Kalandjian, general manager of Mystique, which
specializes in high-end, man-made jewels. ``These type of criminals
probably thought they had hit the mother lode.''
</P>
<P>
   The burglars stole about $30,000 in gems, he estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Police wouldn't say exactly what was taken in the burglaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The insurance covers everything but the inconvenience,''
Ordenanz said.
</P>
<P>
   Some shopkeepers said the brazen burglaries should be answered
with more police patrols. Others seemed unconcerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``This probably gives them something to do,'' said Mike Ryytty,
a Federal Express driver who said he makes trips to Worth Avenue
several times a week. ``Most of the time, they're just giving out
parking tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
