u f BC-BROKER-FRAUD-NYT &LR;      09-08 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROKER-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROKER PLEADS GUILTY TO FRAUD IN IPO DEALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Randolph Pace, a brokerage firm executive charged
with enriching himself through a wide-ranging securities fraud from
1994 to 1997, pleaded guilty Friday in Manhattan federal court to
13 felony counts of conspiracy, money laundering and securities
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   In his guilty plea before Judge Loretta Preska, Pace said he had
made $2.86 million in illicit profits through the scheme, which
cost investors $200 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   Pace, who was indicted by a federal grand jury in November 1998,
was co-founder of Rooney Pace Inc., a brokerage firm expelled from
the industry in 1987 by the National Association of Securities
Dealers. Pace, 54, was twice censured by regulators and was
ultimately barred from the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Having been forced out of the brokerage business, Pace began to
act as a consultant to obscure start-up companies hoping to raise
capital from investors in initial public offerings of stock.
</P>
<P>
   He secretly controlled Sterling Foster, a firm that bilked
investors out of $100 million before it closed in 1997. Two other
brokerage firms, both defunct, were involved in the scheme: VTR
Capital and Investors Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Describing his crime to the judge, Pace said that as small
companies in need of capital came to him for help, he developed a
``deal structure'' that would encourage others to participate. That
structure involved issuing substantial amounts of stock to company
founders and consultants, like Pace, at very low prices before the
public offerings. Pace said he offered these deals to friends and
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Pace described how these insiders arranged to sell their shares
upon the company's IPO even though the company's financial filings
stated that the shares were subject to lock-up agreements
restricting their sale. ``I understood that this made the documents
false and misleading,'' Pace said.
</P>
<P>
   The former executive also admitted that he tried to hide his
involvement in certain deals by arranging for other individuals to
get cheap stock in companies on his behalf before their offerings.
He would then split the profits with these people. ``Regulators
became uncomfortable with my presence in some of the deals,'' Pace
said.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 companies in which Pace and others made illicit profits
are Lasergate Systems, Advanced Voice Technologies, Com/Tech
Communication Technologies, Embryo Development Corp., Applewoods
Inc., ML Direct, Interiors Inc., Compare Generiks, Perry's Majestic
Beer, Decor Group and Superior Supplements. None of the companies
have been charged with wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Also pleading guilty Friday to nine felony counts was Warren
Schreiber, a broker at VTR Capital who took part in the scheme.
Schreiber agreed to forfeit a property he owns in Westhampton,
N.Y., to pay restitution to investors who lost money.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement to the court, Pace tried to distance himself
from the fraudulent sales practices conducted by Sterling Foster,
VTR Capital and Investors Associates, which brought the companies
public. He did not apologize for his conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of his plea, Pace agreed to give $3 million
immediately to the U.S. government. He is subject to additional
fines, to be determined by the court, that will go into a
restitution fund for investors who lost money in the conspiracy,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Pace is scheduled to be sentenced on Dec. 21. The maximum
penalty he faces is 135 years, but under sentencing guidelines he
will probably receive a sentence of seven to nine years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 2212EDT &QL; 
