<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, SEPT. 9 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: These corrections appeared in The New York Times on
Saturday, Sept. 9. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-GORE-ECON-NYT (moved Wednesday, September 6)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday,
September 6 about Vice President Al Gore's economic plan misstated
the title of Robert D. Reischauer, who spoke of it favorably. He is
president of the Urban Institute, not an analyst there. In some
copies, the article misidentifed the office of which he is the
former director. It is the Congressional Budget Office, not the
Office of Management and Budget.
</P>
<P>
   BC-GA-LYNCHING-MEMORY-NYT (moved Friday, August 25)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, August 25
about renewed interest in the lynching of Leo M. Frank 85 years ago
in Marietta, Ga., referred incorrectly to the grandfather of Philip
M. Goldstein, a property owner there. The grandfather, also named
Philip Goldstein, did not testify at the Frank trial; the character
witness was Max Goldstein, who was not a relative.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ABC-KOPPEL-NYT (moved Thursday, September 7)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday,
September 7 about the decision of Ted Koppel, anchor of ABC News'
``Nightline,'' to a new five-year contract with the program
misstated the given name of a new executive producer who will
oversee it. He is Leroy Sievers, not Tom.
</P>
</TEXT>
