<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOON-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FAR SIDE OF THE MOON': PEEKING AT SOMEONE WHO THINKS HE'S ALONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.)  
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``The Far Side of the Moon,'' a theater piece
written, directed and performed by the Canadian theater artist
Robert Lepage, is being offered as part of the Henson International
Festival of Puppet Theater, but it's not puppetry that commands the
stage _ it's Lepage.
</P>
<P>
   The puppets here are decidedly secondary figures, not much more
than props. They're done up as astronauts, and they make only a
handful of brief appearances as dream figures; they're part of the
metaphorical backdrop of this show, which posits the race to the
moon by the United States and the former Soviet Union as a kind of
sibling rivalry, and space exploration in general as a symbol of
the desperate rooting around in the dark that characterizes human
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that is ponderous baggage for what is otherwise a piquant
and simple story about estranged brothers after their mother's
death. But the heavy-handedness of Lepage's connections between
inner and outer space is easily _ and perhaps properly _
overlooked. Partly this is because the rest of his show, with the
visual cleverness characteristic of Lepage and his company, Ex
Machina, is so modest and engaging, and partly it's because of
Lepage's virtuoso acting performance here.
</P>
<P>
   An unimposing presence with a doughy face and physique, he plays
two brothers _ Philippe, a haplessly introspective philosophy
student, and Andre, a television weatherman with the chilly
impatience of the deeply selfish _ as well as host of secondary
characters, and it's a tour de force of unactorlike ease.
</P>
<P>
   As a doctor explaining to Philippe that his mother's death was
no accident; as Philippe, working as a telemarketer and, in a
painful coincidence, reaching a potential customer who turns out to
be a former girlfriend, now married; as Andre, stuck in an elevator
with a bookshelf full of remembrances from his childhood, Lepage is
uncanny in his casual verisimilitude; you'll never see a
performance that yields a more powerful sense of peeking in on
someone who thinks he's alone.
</P>
<P>
   The show (which can be seen at the Joseph Papp Public Theater
for three more performances, two Saturday and one Sunday) is told
in a series of blackout scenes, each with its own bit of theatrics
that please with their unspectacular ingenuity. There's the
laundromat evoked by a couple of chairs, a water cooler, a porthole
in the back wall and a behind-the-wall camera that projects the
inside of a washing machine onto a screen for the audience. There's
a hotel lounge, empty except for Philippe, whose loneliness and
isolation are underscored by the vast stage-length mirrored
tabletop that serves as the bar at which he sits smoking. There's a
whole gymnasium full of exercise equipment suggested by, of all
things, an ironing board.
</P>
<P>
   The simplicity of much of this is nearly obscured by the space
race metaphor _ in a kind of accompanying sideshow, the history of
American and Russian space programs is told in vintage film clips,
projections and radio recordings _ and by a weird and beautiful
original score by Laurie Anderson, whose syncopations and vaguely
Asian-sounding dissonances give the show an aura of avant-garde
profundity.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of the show _ the conventional realism of the
emotions of the characters _ shines through in Lepage's acting and
in the simple elegance of his visual imagination almost in spite of
these overlays.
</P>
<P>
   Lepage is not known for narrative economy, and the show, which
runs nearly two and a half hours without intermission, proceeds at
a languid pace. But if it asks an audience for patience, the
narrative shape, seemingly indifferent to conventional peaks and
valleys, also contributes to the idea that real lives are being
glimpsed.
</P>
<P>
   The story focuses on Philippe, a shy fellow whose intellectual
pursuits reflect the sort of nebbishy sadness that is played out in
his personal life. (His doctoral thesis contends that ``man's
interest in space travel is motivated not by curiosity but
narcissism.'') He's devoted to honoring the memory of his mother in
tiny ways; the care of her goldfish, for instance, becomes a
crucial issue between him and Andre, a shallow, mercenary fellow
who is driven nuts by his older brother's ineffectuality and
introspection. Much of Philippe's own sense of failure is
communicated through a video he makes for an organization called
SETI, the Search for Extra-Terrestrial Intelligence, a personal
documentary, of sorts, that is to be digitized and sent off into
the void like a message in a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is the contrast: Philippe's eagerness to send the
mundane details of life into the void, as opposed to the vast
technological machinery that America and Russia spent decades
launching away from the earth. The one, the show suggests, is
human; the other merely egomaniacal, creating dangerous
misunderstandings between nations and brothers.
</P>
<P>
   That's a sentimental and not terribly complex idea, and one
wishes it wasn't presented with such gravity. In the end the space
metaphor is best when it is least grandiose, when it isn't so
conscious of its own epic proportions. A climactic scene in which
Lepage, as Philippe, mimics weightlessness in the laundromat
(helped by a wonderful and uncomplicated use of mirrors) is partly
terrific. That's because what it says about a man _ that he's
unmoored even in the most unethereal circumstance _ is moving, but
what it says about mankind _ the same thing _ is merely weighty.
Sometimes a small step is preferable to a giant leap.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE FAR SIDE OF THE MOON'
</P>
<P>
   Written, directed and performed by Robert Lepage; written with
the collaboration of Adam Nashman; artistic collaborator and
project originator, Peder Bjurman; assistant to the director,
Pierre-Philippe Guay; original music composed and recorded by
Laurie Anderson; assistant set designer, Marie-Claude Pelletier;
costumes by Marie-Chantale Vaillancourt; puppet designer, Pierre
Robitaille and Sylvie Courbron; puppeteer, Pierre Bernier. Produced
by Ex Machina and presented by the Henson International Festival of
Puppet Theater. At the Joseph Papp Public Theater in Manhattan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 2220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0417 </DOCNO>
