</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTV-AWARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AWARDS FOR POP AND SOUL, SO DIFFERENT AND SO ALIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JON PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two awards shows came to New York City on successive
nights this week, and they were as different as the pop moment and
the soul heritage. The MTV Video Music Awards on Thursday night at
Radio City Music Hall had giant production numbers, bared navels,
lip-synching and hype. The Rhythm and Blues Foundation's Pioneer
Awards on Wednesday at the Hammerstein Ballroom offered modesty, a
good heart and great unassisted voices.
</P>
<P>
   Both are about music that never went away and that has, in fact,
come back around. The vocal groups and soul belters who were
recognized by the Rhythm and Blues Foundation, like Stevie Wonder,
the Chi-Lites and Betty Wright, are direct musical ancestors of MTV
Award-winners like Sisqo, N'Sync and Christina Aguilera. Yet while
they can still sing their hearts out, the seasoned rhythm-and-blues
performers aren't as glamorous as their MTV heirs.
</P>
<P>
   The MTV Awards are a binge of promotion through glitter and
approved mild naughtiness. They're chosen from MTV's limited
offerings by a voting panel that's half music-business
professionals, half fans, and in essence they recognize the
successful application of huge marketing budgets _ for grooming
artists, making videos, advertising and promoting songs to radio
stations _ to reach MTV's squealing, allowance-squandering young
audience. The MTV Awards are the happy face of good returns on a
pop investment, and the show presents itself as one branch of
conglomerated show business, tied in to movies, television and this
year to professional wrestling: Kid Rock and the Rock stood side by
side to give an award.
</P>
<P>
   Well-behaved pop professionals dominated the telecast, which was
more about skin than sin. Sisqo and Nelly bared their chests for
their hip-hop come-ons. Britney Spears, determined to prove the
line in her hit ``Oops ... I Did It Again'' that insists ``I'm not
that innocent,'' stripped down to a glittering skin-tight halter
top and pants, ending her number with a showgirl's pelvic thrust.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Durst of Limp Bizkit risked losing any semblance of rock
credibility by stepping onstage to rap with Christina Aguilera.
Everyone's antisocial anathema, Eminem, performed ``The Real Slim
Shady,'' which warns about how many people are ``just like me,''
with dozens of quasi-look-alikes. But the best provocation Eminem
could muster in his acceptance speeches was to show pills falling
out of his pockets and to thank critics of his albums for helping
him sell more of them.
</P>
<P>
   MTV promised feuds it didn't deliver. The show had appearances
by Shawn Fanning, who invented the music-sharing program Napster,
and Lars Ulrich of Metallica, which has sued Napster. Fanning wore
a Metallica T-shirt, but MTV gave Ulrich the advantage: a video
skit that equated sharing with theft.
</P>
<P>
   It took Rage Against the Machine, a band that still believes in
a political rock rebellion, to shake up the show. It performed
alongside video screens showing montages of demonstrations and
phrases like ``Are you getting what you paid for?'' and ``corporate
greed.'' Later, as Limp Bizkit collected an award, Rage's bass
player, Timothy Commerford, tried a little anarchy: climbing up a
tower of television monitors onstage, making it sway and
threatening to jump. (He was arrested for assaulting a police
officer when he eventually came down.) It was a true disruption in
a show that prefers any outrageousness to take place on cue.
</P>
<P>
   The MTV Awards, shown live, have a nationwide reach; the Rhythm
and Blues Foundation dreams of being on television someday, said
its co-chairman, the singer Jerry Butler of the Impressions. The
MTV Awards puts a silvery man-on-the-moon statuette next to young
hitmakers' gold and platinum albums, while the Pioneer Awards gives
checks for $4,000 to $15,000 to aging musicians who may well use
them for medical expenses or, as Sylvia Robinson (the voice of
``Love Is Strange'') announced she would, contribute it to buy a
building for her church.
</P>
<P>
   Others who received awards included Huey ``Piano'' Smith, who
wrote ``Rockin' Pneumonia'' and ``Sea Cruise'' and declared
bankruptcy in the 1990s; Johnnie Johnson, who was Chuck Berry's
pianist; and the songwriter and producer Clyde Otis. Wonder,
receiving a lifetime achievement award, vowed to help make a
benefit album for the foundation that would bring together younger
and older rhythm-and-blues musicians.
</P>
<P>
   The Rhythm and Blues Foundation has been the music business'
nagging conscience. It has given hundreds of thousands of dollars
to musicians in need, and it has pushed recording companies to make
up for past abuses by raising royalty rates on old, exploitative
contracts. Berry Gordy, the founder and former owner of Motown
Records (which is now part of Universal), announced he was joining
on both fronts, contributing $750,000 to help musicians and saying
that he, too, is now in favor of royalty reform, including
revisions to the tough contracts Motown made in its 1960s golden
age.
</P>
<P>
   For its first 10 years, the Rhythm and Blues Foundation made its
awards precede or follow the Grammys, latching on to some of the
current stars who show up for the event. This year Grammy time
became prohibitively expensive, so the foundation slipped in next
to the MTV Video Music Awards instead. Yet while there were
well-known musicians in attendance _ Aretha Franklin, Bonnie Raitt,
Herbie Hancock, Dionne Warwick, Sister Sledge, Brenda Russell _ the
only representatives of the MTV generation were Brian McKnight, who
sang a Marvin Gaye tribute, and Erykah Badu.
</P>
<P>
   Presenting an award to Betty Wright, who had the million-selling
hit ``Clean Up Woman'' in 1971, Badu hinted that current stars had
not eliminated the problems that face their elders. ``I didn't know
what to expect,'' said Badu, whose 1997 debut album has sold three
million copies. ``I thought it was going to be a lot more money.''
</P>
<P>
   The MTV Awards had an appearance by Richard Hatch, the
millionaire winner on ``Survivor.'' But Smokey Robinson, the M.C.
on Wednesday night, called the Rhythm and Blues Foundation ``the
real survivor awards.'' He went on to explain, ``They survived a
tough business where the rats ate you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
