<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-AUTOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA UPHOLDS RULE FOR POLLUTION-FREE CAR BY 2003 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ California regulators voted Friday to keep
a rule requiring that 10 percent of cars offered for sale in the
state starting in 2003 emit little or no pollution, a goal that the
industry has said is unreachable.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous decision by the California Air Resources Board,
which regulates air pollution in the state, is expected to vastly
increase the number of electric cars on the road, not only in
California but in New York, Massachusetts, Vermont and Maine, which
have opted to follow California pollution regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Automobile companies have argued strenuously that they cannot
sell that many electric cars because such vehicles are too costly
and can travel only about 100 miles before the batteries must be
recharged, a process that takes several hours.
</P>
<P>
   The air pollution regulation agency estimated that under the
rule, 22,000 electric cars would have to be sold in California in
2003, 10 times more than the 2,300 now on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a train wreck waiting to happen,'' Samuel
Leonard, a director of the public policy center at the General
Motors Corp., said of the rule. He said the rule would produce a
minuscule improvement in air quality at tremendous cost.
</P>
<P>
   But the board, whose 11 members are appointed by the governor,
said the rule was needed to cut pollution in the long term.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our future depends on the continuing march to zero-emission
vehicles,'' Alan Lloyd, the board chairman, said after a day and a
half of public hearings here. ``We need to stay the course.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that progress toward nonpolluting cars would
``dramatically decrease or stop completely without a clear
regulatory signal.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the board instructed its staff to consider modifications
to the plan to deal with the high costs of electric cars, which the
staff estimated to be as much as $20,000 more each than
gasoline-powered cars. Automobile executives held out some hope
that the rule would still be changed by January, when the board is
to consider the proposed modifications.
</P>
<P>
   ``The train wreck is still a little bit further down the road
and maybe we'll never get to that point,'' said Gloria Bergquist,
spokeswoman for the Alliance of Automobile Manufacturers, a group
that represents 13 car companies.
</P>
<P>
   But Lloyd said it was extremely unlikely that the overall 10
percent goal by 2003 would be changed. It is more likely the staff
will look at more subsidies to help make the cars more affordable
and desirable, agency staff members said.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists, meanwhile, hailed Friday's decision, saying
that it would prod the development of pollution-free cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is about as strong a statement as you can get,''
said Roland Hwang, co-director of the transportation program at the
Union of Concerned Scientists.
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   California has been aggressive in air pollution controls because
of the smog problem in Southern California. And because of the huge
size of the California's car market, the California rules have been
instrumental in prodding the automobile industry to develop
vehicles that pollute less.
</P>
<P>
   The original rules in 1990 called for 2 percent of the cars for
sale in the state to be nonpolluting by 1998, 5 percent by 2001 and
10 percent by 2003, with the program to be reviewed every two
years.
</P>
<P>
   In the previous two reviews in 1996 and 1998, the board removed
the deadlines for 1998 and 2001, saying they were impractical. It
also relaxed the rule for 2003.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   For the six largest manufacturers, only 4 percent of the cars
offered for sale in 2003 have to emit no pollution, a standard
current technology make possible only with battery-powered cars.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the 10 percent goal can be met by
near-zero-emission vehicles, like gasoline engines that burn fuel
more cleanly, natural gas engines or gasoline-electric hybrid
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   This year's review, which concluded Friday, was crucial because
it is the probably the last time the rule can be changed before
auto companies start designing and manufacturing the 2003 cars.
</P>
<P>
   Auto companies had hoped for another relaxation of the deadline,
but environmentalists said that one more slip could effectively
kill the program. They said the companies had not tried hard enough
to sell the cars, or had even discouraged sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
