<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RedHawks focused on Eagles
 &HT;    By Marty Williams
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   YPSILANTI, Mich. _ Geographically speaking, the road from
Nashville to Columbus does not run through Ypsilanti, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   But it does on the map that plots the season for Miami and the
RedHawks better keep that in mind today as they face Eastern
Michigan, a detour ominously sandwiched between last Saturday's
emotionally draining season-opening win at Vanderbilt and next
Saturday's historic visit to Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you win a game the way we did at Vanderbilt,'' coach
Terry Hoeppner said in referring to the comeback that produced two
touchdowns in the final three minutes for a 33-30 victory, ``there
is a natural tendency to let down, to feel too good about yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I didn't see any signs of that this week. The players
worked hard and they were focused. And they were focused on Eastern
Michigan. We (the coaches) weren't thinking about Ohio State and we
weren't talking about Ohio State. And I don't think the players
were, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Eastern also launched the season in dramatic fashion, scoring
with 1:50 left to beat Connecticut, 32-25.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles have had only one winning record in the last 10 years
and a win over Miami would trigger an emotional high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week, we were the hunters,'' Hoeppner said. ``This week,
we're the hunted. Not to take anything away from Eastern, but
beating us would be a big boost for their program.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami has a 14-4 edge in the series and has won seven of the
last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles have been hard to prepare for because of new head
coach Jeff Woodruff, a former assistant at Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really had only the Connecticut game to study,'' Hoeppner
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at Arizona (tapes during the offseason in an effort
to get a read on Woodruff) and he didn't bring anything with him,
offensively or defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Woodruff didn't have to bring was a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   He inherited three-year starter Walter Church, who is breaking
all of the school passing records set by Charlie Batch, now a
starter in the NFL with Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
