u a BC-NYC-COLUMN-SINATRA-NY     09-08 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-COLUMN-SINATRA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO LOVE SONG FOR BLUE EYES IN BRONZE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A statue it may be, but not a statue of limitations.
This is the large bronze representation of Frank Sinatra that the
administration of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, in concert with the
Sinatra family, hopes to put in the heart of Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that Nancy Sinatra badly wants this honor for her
father, the incomparable singer and better-than-fair actor, who
died two years ago. Nancy Sinatra even promises to pay for the job.
One thing is essential to the family: The statue must stand on a
traffic island at Broadway and West 44th Street, opposite the site
of the old Paramount Theater, where Sinatra thrilled 1940s
bobby-soxers and gave rise to the legend of Ol' Blue Eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Great, says City Hall. In its usual fashion, best summed up by
the Sinatra song ``All or Nothing at All,'' it has made the project
its own and is pushing it through the city bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   And what, you may wonder, is the problem with this? Is not a
daughter's devotion worth a price above rubies? Can anyone deny
Sinatra's iconic status?
</P>
<P>
   On that score, you will get no argument here. The singer's
fervent fans include this fellow, who has spent many hours at the
piano running through the ``Frank Sinatra Songbook.'' Truth be
told, some of that time probably should have been spent working.
Call me irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposed Sinatra statue does raise serious questions
about limitations and the use of public space for private purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The same issue came up last week with the unveiling of a statue
of Jackie Gleason as Ralph Kramden, the lovable, bus-driving
schlemiel from the ``Honeymooners'' television series. That
sculpture stands outside the Eighth Avenue entrance to the Port
Authority Bus Terminal.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it all seems innocent enough. Hey there, Ralphie
boy. Har-dee-har-har, and all that.
</P>
<P>
   But if you look at the inscription at the statue's base, you
will notice that it says, ``Presented by the people of TV Land.''
And what is TV Land? A Viacom cable television channel that carries
reruns of the 1950s series.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, this monument taking up precious space on a New
York sidewalk is really a commercial for a big media company.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial potential of the Sinatra statue may be less
obvious, but the basic issue is the same. Here you have a family
with money, fame and influence, in effect being allowed to snatch
up premier space in this city's central square for its own glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every inch of public space is under assault,'' said Kent
Barwick, president of the Municipal Art Society. ``It's forever
being encroached upon.''
</P>
<P>
   His point would seem hard to dispute. In recent years, the sides
of buildings have often become little more than convenient spots
for advertisements. Trucks that are essentially billboards on
wheels are allowed to cruise the streets and pollute the air. Offer
the city enough cash and you can sponsor a concert in Central Park,
with your name slapped all over the place. If you happen to be
Disney, the city streets are yours for a self-promotional parade.
</P>
<P>
   The plans for the Sinatra statue have dispirited Times Square
community groups. Their objections, rehashed with City Hall several
weeks ago, include concerns about extra crowding on sidewalks that
are already jam-packed. Some also doubt that Sinatra is right for
that spot of honor. After all, his links to Broadway are slender.
He made his mark west of the Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   As for those glory days at the Paramount, you might as well
erect a statue of the Beatles outside Shea Stadium. They made a
huge splash there in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels a little tacky for a family to propose a statue to
itself in Times Square,'' said one civic leader in the
neighborhood, whose request for anonymity will be honored. Giuliani
may seem a gentler soul these days, but his capacity for vengeance
still inspires fear.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is why the anti-statue forces have avoided delicate
points mentioned by some others, like the fact that Sinatra
famously avoided the draft during World War II; if approved, his
statue would share an island with the Armed Forces Recruiting
Station. He was known, too, for hanging out with gangsters,
something that perhaps ought to arch an eyebrow on the mob-fighting
mayor.
</P>
<P>
   But some critics suspect that for all their objections, the
project is a done deal. They can almost hear Nancy Sinatra, who
once teamed with her old man for a song called ``Something
Stupid,'' breaking out now in a chorus of ``They Can't Take That
Away From Me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 2227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
