<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: ROWING  
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This has been a big Olympic sport for the United States,
especially in the men's eight-oared competition. This time, the
United States is the only nation to have qualified in all 14 events
(six for women), and it ranks behind Germany and Romania among the
team favorites.
</P>
<P>
   THE SETUP
</P>
<P>
   The 550 rowers will compete in eight sculling events (two oars
for each sculler) ranging from singles to quads and six sweep
events (one oar per athlete) ranging from pairs to eights. The
races include two lightweight events for men (160-pound limit per
man) and one for women (130-pound limit per woman).
</P>
<P>
   THE SCORING
</P>
<P>
   The heats are unseeded and based on a random draw, and usually
only heat winners advance to a semifinal or final. First-round
losers get a second chance in a repechage round.
</P>
<P>
   All races are over a 2,000-meter straightaway.
</P>
<P>
   THE STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   For the favorites, strategy varies from race to race. Faster
strokes are often better, but seasoned crews can win or stay
competitive with fewer but more efficient strokes and high-speed
spurts.
</P>
<P>
   THE NAMES
</P>
<P>
   The favorites in the glamour races, the eight-oared sweeps, are
the U.S. men and Romanian women, with the U.S. women's eight a
strong contender.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Redgrave, a 38-year-old Briton in the fours without
coxswain, will try to become the second summer or winter Olympian
to win gold medals in five consecutive Olympics (Aladar Gerevich, a
Hungarian fencer, won six in a row from 1932 through 1960).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 2228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0424 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7106 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-FSU0909-COX     09-08 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FSU0909-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seminoles unequaled in ACC
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Florida State joined the Atlantic Coast
Conference in 1992, league officials confidently predicted that the
Seminoles' presence eventually would raise the level of ACC
football.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, Florida State begins its ninth year of ACC play with an
8 p.m. game at Georgia Tech (ABC). Given the results in last week's
openers, some people would argue that the level of ACC football is
anything but up since 1992:
</P>
<P>
   _ Wake Forest, a bowl team last season, lost to I-AA Appalachian
State 20-16.
</P>
<P>
   _ Duke, last in a bowl game in 1994, was embarrassed at home
38-0 by East Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   _ Virginia, in the dedication game of newly renovated Scott
Stadium, blew a 21-0 halftime lead and lost to BYU 38-35 in
overtime. BYU had been blown out the week before by Florida State,
29-3.
</P>
<P>
   _ N.C. State needed double overtime to beat Arkansas State,
rated 102nd among 115 Division I-A teams by one preseason magazine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Georgia Tech needed two touchdowns in the final minutes to
beat Central Florida 21-17.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always like the conference to do well, but there's no doubt
about it. We took it on the chin,'' Florida State coach Bobby
Bowden said. ``There might be a sleeper in (the conference). But
the fact that we've dominated like we have makes people think the
conference is not very strong.''
</P>
<P>
   At 62-2 in eight seasons, Florida State hasn't just dominated
the ACC. It has manhandled it, winning those 62 games by an average
of 29.4 points.
</P>
<P>
   One Orlando columnist suggested recently that Florida State
should give up the charade and join the SEC, where it belongs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think that deserves a response,'' FSU athletics
director Dave Hart said.
</P>
<P>
   The ACC points out a few things in its defense:
</P>
<P>
   _ Florida State might be beating up on the ACC, but the
Seminoles are doing it to everybody else, too. The defending
national champions have played in the national title game three of
the past four seasons and have finished in the final AP top four 13
consecutive years. They won more games (109) than any other program
in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, you simply have to recognize the quality of
Florida State's program,'' the ACC commissioner John Swofford said.
``Nobody has done what they have done.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The ACC was 6-5 against non-conference ranked teams last
season and 14-9 the past two seasons. Only one conference, the Big
Ten, has a better winning percentage over those two years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Florida State went 8-0 in the ACC last year, but Georgia Tech
(35-31) and Clemson (17-14) were within a play or two of knocking
them off.
</P>
<P>
   _ The financial commitment to football in the ACC is at an
all-time high. Since 1994, the conference members have spent more
than $400 million in improvements to football-related facilities.
Virginia just completed a new stadium renovation. N.C. State has
$100 million in improvements on the drawing board. Clemson is
getting ready to spend $37 million over the next four years on its
stadium and a new building for its team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at everything we're doing and where the programs
in this conference are, you have to say the future looks bright,''
Swofford said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bright spots, many people think the ACC never get
where it wants to be as a football conference until it expands.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the football dollars Florida State has brought to the
ACC table since 1992, some of the traditionalists didn't want to
bring them into the family back in 1990. Some of those same schools
want no part of any further expansion. It comes down to football
versus basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball has held the upper hand since the league was founded
for the 1953-54 school year. That situation might have to change
for the football landscape to undergo another shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really have to face the issue,'' Hart said. ``If we want to
do what's best for the conference down the road, we have to
(expand). I honestly believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any question that there is going to be
another round of conference realignment,'' Clemson athletics
director Bobby Robinson said. ``At that point, or before it, you
have to decide where you want to be. We're still open to that
discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech athletics director Dave Braine is among those who
think the ACC must add three teams to become a 12-team league with
a conference championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida State and Georgia Tech have a much different
perspective on the issue'' from the other seven conference members,
Braine said. ``We don't recruit against the other ACC schools; we
recruit against the SEC. Those schools use the 12th game, the extra
bowl games and the television package against us in recruiting.
That's why it's so important for Georgia Tech and Florida State to
get to a 12-team league and have a playoff game.''
</P>
<P>
   Swofford says ACC athletics directors talk frequently about
expansion but right now the issue ``is on the back burner.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, it's much too early to push the panic button
on this year in ACC football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to let the season play itself out,'' he said.
``There is a lot of football left to be played.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
