u p BC-GORE-ATLANTA0909-COX     09-08 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ATLANTA0909-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore raises money and support in Georgia
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore collected $1 million dollars
in contributions for the Democratic Party on Friday and told donors
that the November elections were ``a chance to really move Georgia
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This election is not an award for past performance,'' Gore
said. ``I'm not asking for your support on the basis of the economy
we have; I'm asking for your support and help on the basis of a
stronger, better, fairer economy that we are going to create
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spoke to about 250 donors at the Hyatt Regency, most of
whom contributed $1,000 for the chance to shake hands with Gore and
listen to his 20-minute speech. Afterward, Gore dined with a
smaller group of 150 donors who contributed a minimum of $5,000 to
the Democratic National Committee at a private home in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore's visit was thin on new campaign themes, it contained
several symbolic flourishes. Sen. Zell Miller's appearance at both
fund-raisers _ at the invitation of the Gore campaign _ was
intended to send a signal that Southern Democrats aren't running
away from Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are hoping that Miller's place on the ballot will draw
moderate swing voters to Gore, but both campaigns have remained
vague about how much campaigning the two politicians will do
together.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Phillips, Miller's campaign manager, said Miller would
campaign with Gore in the coming weeks whenever it was mutually
convenient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zell Miller has his own race to run and will run his own
race,'' Phillips said. ``He's really got to focus on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also stopped by to shake hands with members of Teamsters
Local 728 at the United Parcel Service's Forest Park hub before
attending the two fund-raising events. The visit was a nod to the
Teamsters union, which voted this week to endorse Gore after
holding out support for almost a year.
</P>
<P>
   He shook hands with several hundred workers at the UPS
distribution center. At one point, Gore climbed into a brown UPS
delivery truck and mugged for the cameras with several drivers
sitting inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in this race for the families that are trying to pay the
bills . . . the working men and women,'' Gore told them just before
leaving. ``We need to raise the minimum wage a dollar an hour and
have tax cuts for middle-class families. Help me out and we can
make this country what it is supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, in his introduction of Gore at the Hyatt fund-raiser,
called the vice president a friend to the state who had responded
to numerous appeals for help _from disaster relief during the 1994
floods to obtaining federal funds for the 1996 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always there _ firm, strong, but with a generous
spirit,'' said Miller, Georgia's governor from 1991 to 1998.
``Every time Georgia has called on Al Gore, he has always
responded.''
</P>
<P>
   While touting the country's strong economic progress over the
past eight years, the vice president acknowledged that the economy
had still left some behind.
</P>
<P>
   He repeated his pledges to establish universal pre-kindergarten
for 4-year-olds, boost job training and create life-long learning
accounts for people who want to continue their education or learn
new skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the information age, what you earn depends on what you
learn,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore criticized his presidential opponent, Texas Gov. George
Bush, for failing to be specific about how he would pay for tax
cuts and proposals to privatize a portion of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need specifics now, not when it's too late,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore concluded his remarks with a nod to Atlanta's rich civil
rights history and the work of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta, Georgia, is the place where America's redemption
began,'' Gore said. ``The South is the place where the march had
its first steps. The South is the place where America's rebirth has
begun.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
