u i BC-U.N.-PHOTO-INTRUDER-N     09-08 0369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-PHOTO-INTRUDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNT INSERTS HIMSELF INTO U.N. SUMMIT PHOTO 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It might take a magnifying glass to spot him, a man
in a navy-blue suit, his chest puffed out, among 180 world
dignitaries in the official photograph of the U.N. Millennium
Summit group. But he is there, right next to the foreign minister
of Niger, and he is not supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   The photograph was meant to be taken of official delegates
representing nations at an extraordinary three-day summit meeting
called to thrash out problems of poverty and peace at the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The man in the upper left corner was Count Carlo Marullo di
Condojanni, of the Sovereign Military Order of Malta _ with no
current ties to the country of the same name _ which claims to be
the smallest stamp-issuing authority in the world. It is based in
Rome, just west of the Spanish Steps. And it is not a nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably got lucky,'' said Hans Grohmann, a U.N. protocol
assistant.
</P>
<P>
   The photograph was taken in a council chamber in the United
Nations shortly after a luncheon of world leaders on Wednesday.
Many of them were accompanied to the chamber by fellow delegates,
and that was probably how the count managed to be in the
photograph, Grohmann said. Two countries, Jordan and Norway, also
violated the rules _ by having two representatives each in the
photo.
</P>
<P>
   Di Condojanni was the official delegate from his order to the
meeting. The group has representation at the United Nations, even
though it is not a nation. It was founded in 1048 as the Knights
Hospitalers of St. John of Jerusalem by businessmen from Amalfi,
south of Naples. Their goal was to build a hospital to serve
pilgrims from the Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   As of the late 1980s, the group had 3,000 Italian members and
2,000 Americans. It now runs 200 hospitals and clinics worldwide.
Since 1966 it has issued more than 300 stamps with distinctive
designs that chronicle the order's history of military and
charitable works.
</P>
<P>
   The order's mission to the United Nations could not be reached
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   But looking closely at the photo, is that a widening grin on di
Condojanni's face?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 2238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0429 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7122 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-TIMOR-NYT &LR;      09-08 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TIMOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST TIMOR ATHLETES ENJOYING THEIR INDEPENDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ It was the starting line, not the finish
line, that once seemed beyond the reach of Aguida Amaral in the
Olympic marathon. A year ago, she did not even have shoes, much
less hope, to participate in the Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1999, her island, East Timor, declared its autonomy
from Indonesia, sparking a violent retaliation by militia seeking
to prevent independence. Amaral joined hundreds of thousands who
fled Dili, the capital of East Timor, and when she returned three
weeks later under the protection of United Nations peacekeepers,
her home had been looted and burned, as had countless other
buildings and government offices. Her running shoes were charred,
unusable.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Amaral continued to train in her bare feet, or in
street shoes, with a desperate resolve. When her feet began to
hurt, she ran on the soft sand of the beaches. Running was the one
possession that had not been taken from her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was proud of my running,'' said Amaral, 25. ``It was my
hobby. That's why I continued.''
</P>
<P>
   Her persistence resulted in her being chosen as one of four
athletes from East Timor to compete in the Sydney Games. Because
the former province is still run by the United Nations and has no
independent government, the athletes will compete as individuals,
not as a national team. They will wear white uniforms and march
behind the interlocking rings of the Olympic flag during the
opening ceremony next Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. secretary-general, Kofi Annan, and the Australian
government persuaded the International Olympic Committee to make a
special allowance for the athletes from East Timor _ two marathon
runners, a boxer and a weight lifter _ to participate in the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Kevan Gosper, an IOC delegate from Australia, has taken
particular interest in the East Timor athletes. In June he traveled
to Dili, asked the barefoot Amaral to stand on a white sheet of
paper and traced the outline of her feet with a red felt pen.
Gosper then folded the piece of paper in his briefcase and returned
to Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shortly thereafter, a pair of running shoes appeared,'' said
Frank Fowlie, a U.N. administrator, who is the leader of East
Timor's Olympic group.
</P>
<P>
   The unlikely East Timor story is one of athletic perseverance
and international brotherhood. It recalls the lofty ideals of an
Olympic movement tarnished lately by scandals involving corruption
and the use of performance-enhancing drugs. Even Gosper had been
widely criticized earlier this year for securing for his daughter a
preferred place in the Olympic torch relay.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of these athletes has a chance to win a medal, but they
will go home the richest athletes in what they gained, in what they
were able to accomplish here,'' Fowlie said.
</P>
<P>
   A former Portuguese colony with 800,000 residents, East Timor
was invaded by Indonesia in 1975 and annexed. When pro-Jakarta
militia reacted violently to last year's vote for independence,
Victor Ramos, a lightweight boxer, fled into the hills with his
parents and his brothers and sisters, carrying a 130-pound sack of
rice. The family made makeshift tents from the leaves of trees and
foraged for fruits and vegetables to supplement everyone's meager
diet.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sept. 11, with 20,000 other refugees as an informal wedding
party, Ramos, 30, married Domingues in the hills above Dili. But
when they returned home, he found that the boxing club where he
trained had been gutted, and all the equipment was destroyed.
Ramos, who won a bronze medal at the 1997 Southeast Asia Games, was
left to fashion his own equipment, making punching bags from inner
tubes stuffed with sand.
</P>
<P>
   Martinho de Araujo, a weight lifter, also fled Dili during the
violence. When he returned, his equipment, too, was unusable. In
need of barbells to train, he improvised with metal rods stuck into
paint cans that had been filled with cement. Anything came in handy
_ scrap metal, parts from a truck transmission. Now, he is a week
away from his first international competition.
</P>
<P>
   Calisto da Costa will compete in the men's marathon. With a
personal best of 2 hours 34 minutes, he has no chance of winning.
It is enough to be here.
</P>
<P>
   It is the same for Amaral in the women's marathon. She has never
even heard of Tegla Loroupe, the world record-holder from Kenya and
the Olympic favorite. Amaral has run only one race as long as 26.2
miles. Her time was 3:15, nearly an hour slower than Loroupe's best
time. But that does not matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that if I try hard, I will get to the finish line,''
Amaral said.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to the starting line on Sept. 24 will be an equally
impressive accomplishment. ``We want to tell the world that we are
able to do it,'' she said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
