A7123 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-U.N.-CASTRO-PHOTO-NYT     09-08 0300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-CASTRO-PHOTO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRONT PAGE RAISES ISSUE OF JOURNALISTIC ETHICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The front-page image on The New York Daily News on
Friday captured the moment that almost every newspaper across the
United States wanted to get: Fidel Castro nearly shaking hands with
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But the photograph was not exactly real. A note at the bottom
right corner of the page read ``Daily News Photo Illustration.''
The image, a composite of two pictures, has officials at the White
House and some in journalism circles questioning the newspaper's
ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Kosner, the editor in chief of The Daily News, said that
there was ``no effort at misrepresentation'' and that the label for
``the photo illustration was in type that we usually use for
captions.''
</P>
<P>
   The handshake, the first between an American president and the
Cuban leader, became news on Thursday after President Clinton and
Castro met at the U.N. Millennium Summit meeting in New York. The
meeting was not photographed by any news agencies, and news
organizations were unable to obtain a picture from the White House
or the Cuban delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Several news organizations have faced criticism in recent years
for prominently using photographs that have been manipulated. Time
magazine was ridiculed for darkening a police mug shot of O.J.
Simpson, and Newsday was criticized for combining two pictures to
make it appear as if Tonya Harding and Nancy Kerrigan were skating
on the ice together at the 1994 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials, who spoke on the condition of anonymity
and who worry that the image could cause problems for Vice
President Al Gore, complained that the words ``photo illustration''
could not be read on The Daily News Web page.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
