<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7129 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-TOY-MOVIESET-LADN     09-08 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOY-MOVIESET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR $199, KIDS CAN BE FILM MOGULS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAM PARK 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As if Hollywood weren't competitive enough, now
8-year-olds can make movies.
</P>
<P>
   A miniature movie studio - complete with a high-resolution color
video camera slightly larger than a matchbox, an adjustable dolly,
an audio system, four action figures, three movie sets, a clapboard
and basic movie-making instructions - is on the shelves exclusively
at Store of Knowledge outlets nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The Virtual Movie Studio, developed by Curious Toys of New York,
is Store of Knowledge's premier education and entertainment toy for
the holidays, said Robert L. Bassett, vice president of
merchandising, marketing and e-commerce for the 91-store chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expending an awful lot of energy on the Virtual Movie
Studio,'' Bassett said. ``We think today it's probably the premier
product in our assortment.''
</P>
<P>
   Cerritos, Calif.-based Store of Knowledge is affiliated with
public television, and a portion of its sales go to public
broadcasting stations across the country. The store concentrates on
selling mind-expanding, fun merchandise for children and adults.
</P>
<P>
   The Virtual Movie Studio costs $199 and is recommended for ages
8 and older. Bassett, 56, said he ``had a ball'' making a short
demonstration film.
</P>
<P>
   Miles Warren, 5, was playing with the studio in the Woodland
Hills store. Hand gripping the camera, he said he would like to
have one.
</P>
<P>
   The virtual studio camera and microphone connects to a
television set alone or with a VCR, or to a stationary or laptop
computer via cords about 6 feet long. Children can see their movie
on the screen as they shoot it or record it with character
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   The camera dolly looks and works a lot like those in
professional movie studios, and the camera can be removed from the
dolly if creativity requires. Children can use the action figures
and stage sets that come with the kit or create their own using
other toys - dolls and dollhouses, for instance. More prepackaged
sets and accessories are planned.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McFarland, president of toy developer Curious Toys, says
the Virtual Movie Studio is the first of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not interested in doing 'me-too' items. All of them have
to be unique,'' McFarland said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Willis, store director for Toys `R' Us in Culver City, said
two Christmases ago his store carried a toy version of a full-sized
camera but with no characters or sets. It sold out quickly, and the
store wasn't able to get more.
</P>
<P>
   Toys `R' Us pretty much covers the gamut of toys, and this one
sounds unique, Willis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far we haven't received anything like that and don't expect
to this year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sounds children make when they see a toy version of a hand
camera are entirely different than when they see a miniature world,
said Richard Isaacs, director of product development for Curious
Toys.
</P>
<P>
   Today's youngsters gravitate toward video games, where they find
more variety and excitement. The Virtual Movie Studio has
electronic components, but kids can manipulate the toys with their
hands, write dialogue, design sets and move the movie camera
around, Isaacs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to speak to where the trends are going, but
translate them to values even parents can appreciate,'' Isaacs
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the American Toy Institute, $23 billion in
traditional toys and $6.9 billion in video games were sold in the
United States last year.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 2254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7130 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WTIMOR-U.N.-KILLINGS-     09-08 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTIMOR-U.N.-KILLINGS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY COUNCIL PRESSURES INDONESIA TO END TERROR BY MILITIAS
</HEADLINE>
 (SUBS for complete writethru with new reporting)  
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The Security Council condemned Wednesday's
murder of three United Nations refugee workers in West Timor and
insisted that the Indonesian government take immediate steps to
disarm and disband the militias that are believed to be responsible
for the killings.
</P>
<P>
   In a resolution approved by all 15 member countries on Friday
night, the council declared itself ``appalled'' by what it called
``this outrageous and contemptible act against unarmed
international staff who were in West Timor to help the refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   It also told Indonesian authorities to adopt ``immediate and
effective measures'' to ensure the safe return of as many as
100,000 refugees who fled attacks in East Timor last year after its
residents voted for independence from Indonesia. Many refugees now
want to go home but have been intimidated against doing so by the
marauding militias.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. workers could not return to West Timor, the council said,
until the Indonesian government credibly guaranteed their security.
This must include ``real progress'' toward disarming and disbanding
the militias, who have resisted independence for East Timor with
covert arms and backing from supporters within the Indonesian
military.
</P>
<P>
   Moctar Ouane of Mali, who holds the council's rotating
presidency this month, announced that the council would also send a
delegation to Indonesia and East Timor to help carry out its
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The council sent a delegation to East Timor a year ago when a
massacre erupted after the independence vote. As a result, the
United Nations decided to administer the territory's transition to
self-rule.
</P>
<P>
   Remarking on the climate that led to the latest murders in West
Timor, the U.S. representative to the United Nations, Richard
Holbrooke, told reporters that ``directly or indirectly, it is
elements within the Indonesian military who are responsible for
this, who could have been removed a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know exactly who's behind it,'' Holbrooke said. ``If
we know exactly who it is, we'll deal with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The three victims, who were killed by a mob linked to a local
militia group, worked for the office of the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees in West Timor. They were Carlos Caceres,
33, who was from from Puerto Rico; Samson Aregehegn, 44, an
Ethiopian; and Pero Simundsa, 29, a Croat.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council adopted its resolution only hours after
Indonesia's president, Abdurrahman Wahid, conveyed his nation's
``very deep sorrow'' for their ``horrific death.'' He promised to
punish the killers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in disbelief and outraged that such unspeakable crimes
were committed against the good people of the UNHCR,'' Wahid said
in a letter to Secretary-General Kofi Annan. ``The people of
Indonesia mourn with the families of those who were brutally
murdered.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think now the situation is very good there,'' Wahid said.
``That is according to the full report I got this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his assurances, sketchy reports surfaced of a new
massacre of as many as 20 civilians, in Betun, about 40 miles from
Atambua, on Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid said that two military battalions had been sent to Atambua
and that the authorities had detained 19 people there on suspicion
of ransacking the United Nations office. Another man, he said, had
been detained in connection with the killing of a militia leader,
Olivio Mendonca, whose funeral on Wednesday brought militia
supporters together before they attacked the office.
</P>
<P>
   The attack in Atambua, coming after continuous harassment by the
militias, has forced the United Nations to pull its staff out of
West Timor. The last of more than 400 employees of the United
Nations and other aid groups were flown out Friday, with no plans
for their return.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more a question of `if' rather than `when,''' said Ron
Redmond, a spokesman for the high commissioner for refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond said his office had repeatedly asked the Indonesian
authorities to separate ``these militia thugs'' from the refugees
in the camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the assurances we have been given have been met, and
now we have three people dead,'' Redmond said. ``So far as we're
concerned, the time for words has passed and we want to see some
action on the ground.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 2254EDT &QL; 
