<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7132 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-BKW-EDWARDS-$ADV1     09-08 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BKW-EDWARDS-$ADV11-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWARDS STANDS TALL WITHOUT WNBA 
(FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The overmatched college players wanted to pay homage after
being beaten by more than 60 points by Team USA. They were not
searching for a WNBA player of the week, however. After quickly
shaking the hands of Lisa Leslie and Sheryl Swoopes, the young
players kept moving through the arena corridor.
</P>
<P>
   They wanted something more lasting and permanent, which is why
they sought out T.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bye, baby,'' Teresa Edwards said, waving to each player.
</P>
<P>
   The slew of college players waved and thanked her for competing
against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice playing with you guys,'' Edwards said. ``Good luck to
you. I'll be watching you all.''
</P>
<P>
   She tossed her braided locks over the stars and stripes of the
warm-up jacket on her left shoulder, slung her Team USA duffel bag
over her right shoulder and trudged on out to the team charter bus
for another ride back to another hotel.
</P>
<P>
   There is a flight to Australia in the morning and another
Olympics to compete in next week _ her fifth in 16 years. At age
36, and with little left to give the game physically, the veteran
point guard is tired. But Edwards is also unbent.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, I can ride the boat or drive it,'' she said.
``It doesn't matter. I just want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Age, a defunct league (the American Basketball League) and
contractual disagreements with the WNBA have conspired against
Edwards during the last two years. Instead of flying downcourt on
Lifetime television and enjoying the novelty and early popularity
of U.S. women's professional basketball, she is a virtual outsider.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Cooper is lauded as the greatest to play the game.
Michelle Timms and her peroxide-blonde thatch elicits a cult
following. But Edwards drifts further toward retirement and
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in two years Edwards tried to come to terms with a WNBA
franchise, but the teams were unwilling to pay a four-time Olympian
more than a standard player's share.
</P>
<P>
   If female players had more bargaining power and clout, Edwards
would be Norma Rae in high tops. But the NBA umbrella is too large.
In that vein, she is viewed as a troublemaker, ruining a good thing
for the girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think her country has done a disservice to her,'' said Dawn
Staley, a close friend on the Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at Hortencia from Brazil,'' Staley said of Hortencia
Marcari Oliva. ``She's the queen of Brazil. And yet T, she's
relatively unknown. And she's played in five Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know why? She stands by things she says and does. I take
my hat off to her for not playing in the WNBA and maybe not giving
in to what she thinks she deserves to play the game. That's
probably why people don't embrace her. She's a woman of her word.
And sometimes, people can't handle that.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said, ``I respect my game and myself too much to settle
for what they were willing to pay me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1984 U.S. Olympic basketball team photo, the first woman
on the left standing in the back row looking slightly in awe,
standing next to Lynette Woodard and Cheryl Miller, is Edwards, her
life and career in front of her. At 20, she was the youngest member
of the first U.S. women's team to win a gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards' teammates have literally intersected eras and
generations. Between 1983 and 1991, the international teams she
played on won 46 straight games. She played professionally for nine
years overseas in Italy, France, Spain and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times have changed,'' Edwards said. ``We didn't have pro
leagues and now we do. You lived overseas, and no one knew who you
were until the Olympics rolled around in those years. Also, we've
been given the opportunity to truly be athletes as well as women.
And that's a new road to travel.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the ABL folded in 1998, Edwards scored 40 points or more
four times in the league's two-plus seasons, when she coached and
played for Atlanta and then Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Against Cuba in the 1992 Summer Olympics, she made seven
3-pointers, and she distributed a record 15 assists against
Australia at the 1996 Summer Games, which were played close to her
hometown of Cairo, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, the most decorated Olympic basketball player, has an
opportunity to win her fourth gold medal at Sydney. She does not
feel forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some shape, form or fashion, I've had something to do with
the WNBA by playing in the ABL,'' Edwards said. ``I don't think it
would have been taken as serious if no one else tried it. I will
always tell myself I had something to do with that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Edwards added: ``They hear about me, trust me. They just don't
hear about me in the same light. It doesn't bother me. I'm getting
exactly what I deserve. There are no expectations on my behalf that
anybody owes me anything based on my accomplishments. That's not
who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards also has no illusions about her value to the league as a
marquee player.
</P>
<P>
   ``My time has come and gone, as far as I'm concerned,'' she
said. ``I wish that the ones with the power and the marketing and
the values on their names, I wish they knew the values of the
players that built this. That's what I wish. Because if they did,
then they would come together.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards' production has waned, but she is not done. Leading the
break during an exhibition in Hawaii last week, she stutter-stepped
downcourt, waiting for Swoopes, her cutting teammate, to come open
for a layup. Edwards fed the Houston Comets All-Star as she once
fed Miller years ago, the ball delivered on the fingertips, in
stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``T is so competitive,'' Staley said. ``We played HORSE today.
And I beat her. And the look she gave me when she lost. I would not
trade that in for anything. Money. Anything. She still has that
drive.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sydney, the U.S. women's team will be severely tested by
Australia, Brazil, Russia and Cuba. Another gold medal is not a
certainty. And yet, after the Games are over and Edwards moves on,
there will still be more opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I do feel like I'm on the outside,'' Edwards said.
``The athletes are just sitting on the shelf in the store. We're
the product. That's the way it is. They have to change things like
free agency. The danger is, if they step up too aggressively, will
David Stern and everyone on top say no to the league? You really
have no power. It's a Catch-22.
</P>
<P>
   ``You step up, you don't want to play because of certain issues.
Now, will the public get behind you, because you're a player who
feels as if you're not being treated right? That sentiment isn't
there. If they do step up, they have to have the public behind
them. The right people, the right lawyers, all of that. And I don't
think America is ready for that. It's not a good risk for the young
girls to take right now. But I think if the momentum keeps growing,
they do have to stand up for themselves eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But once again, you're talking about young women who have made
more money than they have ever made in their life, even though it's
a fraction of what the men make.''
</P>
<P>
   On the way out of the arena last week, WNBA stars such as
Leslie, Swoopes and Nikki McCray drew more of a crowd than Edwards.
After acknowledging the awed collection of college players, Edwards
quietly slipped past a small crowd of autograph seekers and onto
the bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in the right time and in the right place,'' she said.
``Everybody says I'm too late. I feel good. I didn't miss the boat.
I'm the type of player that likes to make waves and be different.
I'm not afraid to be on the battle lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll dig the hole. Everybody else can come through.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
