<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7135 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-CATS-18YEARS0910-COX     09-08 1418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATS-18YEARS0910-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    After 18 years, there'll be no more 'Cats' prowling around
Broadway
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This afternoon, Marlene Danielle will once again
climb the steep backstage stairs of the Winter Garden Theatre to
Room 16, the costume, make-up and memorabilia-cluttered women's
dressing room where she has readied herself to go feline eight
times a week for the past 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that today's matinee is performance 7,485 of
``Cats,'' the final visit of theatergoers to John Napier's
oversized garbage heap environment, the final downbeat to Andrew
Lloyd Webber's faux-operatic and rock score, the final ascension
for one chosen kitty to the Heaviside Layer for spiritual rebirth.
The last chance to buy a coffee mug with the cats-eyes logo on it.
</P>
<P>
   Today marks the end of an era on Broadway, the last performance
for the show that pussyfooted into town in October 1982, launching
a decade of British musical spectaculars that include ``Les
Miserables,'' ``Phantom of the Opera ``and the recently closed
``Miss Saigon.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the last performance for the longest-running show ever on
Broadway, the production which brazenly advertised itself with the
tag line, ``Now and Forever.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you know something, somebody was pretty psychic,'' says
Danielle with a laugh. ``For me, I didn't take 'Now and Forever'
seriously. Even though, in the history of Broadway, we came
close.''
</P>
<P>
   Most theater performers, and certainly the chorus dancers that
are aptly nicknamed ``gypsies,'' move from show to show, season to
season, trying to eke out a career. But not Danielle, whose
professional life for the past 215 months has been a single show _
``Cats.'' Married, the mother of a 26-year-old son who is older
than many of the current cast members, and the owner of two homes
``that ``Cats'' built,'' Danielle has managed a life of unusual
stability in her precarious chosen profession.
</P>
<P>
   Now in her mid-40s, Danielle began more typically as a show
dancer with a nomadic resume. She debuted on Broadway in 1979 in
the short-lived musical ``Sarava,'' before landing in a New York
revival of ``West Side Story'' and then moving on to the original
cast of the off-Broadway romp, ``Little Shop of Horrors.''
</P>
<P>
   As that musical was settling in for its own substantial run,
Danielle was beginning to hear about an improbable British hit
called ``Cats'' which was preparing an assault on New York. ``At
the time, my sister was going to school in London and she had seen
it, was aware of its great success over there and she called me and
said, 'You're got to get this,' '' Danielle recalls.
</P>
<P>
   STARTED AS UNDERSTUDY
</P>
<P>
   She auditioned, along with every New York show dancer worth his
or her jazz shoes, but did not get a call-back by the time director
Trevor Nunn began rehearsing. ``I was very disappointed, but
somehow I didn't totally give up,'' she says. ``They were already
two weeks into rehearsals when, sure enough, they called. A slot
opened up.''
</P>
<P>
   Danielle was only hired as an understudy, but it got her paw in
the door. She soon graduated to the role of Demeter, the
high-strung, intense sidekick to the show's scruffy villain cat,
Macavity. After a couple of years at that assignment, she moved
over to play Demeter's party animal playmate, Bombalurina. ``She's
more relaxed, more into her sensuality,'' Danielle says of the part
she has played for the past 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   She has never had the opportunity to play the featured role of
Grizabella, the Glamour Cat, the has-been who gets to sing the
show's standout hit tune, ``Memory.'' ``There was a time that I
thought I would like to sing that song and do that part, where
you're only out there for total of a few minutes. But really I like
the action,'' she says with a shrug. ``No, the part that I always
thought would be fun to do was (Rum Tum) Tugger, who goes over the
edge to be a bad-boy, fun kind of character that everybody
enjoys.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its record-breaking success _ seen by more than 10
million people on Broadway, who have collectively paid $400 million
for the privilege _ ``Cats'' has long been sneered at by theater
sophisticates as low-brow kitsch. Danielle will have none of that
talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day I watched the show from the front. The
(Jellicle) ball started and I got chills,'' she insists. ``When I
listen to that score, I'm sorry, Andrew Lloyd Webber did create
some beautiful music. Every time I come down those stairs to sing
``Macavity,'' I so enjoy the orchestrations, the chords. They're
fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she can philosophize with the best of them over the
show's message of acceptance and understanding, Danielle's theory
of why it has enjoyed such longevity boils down to its widespread
appeal from the littlest tykes to adults.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling a recent performance, she says, ``There was one man, a
young father holding his daughter, who was dancing in the aisles.
And it just hit me _ I don't know that I'll ever do another show
that grabs people that way, that makes you feel so good that you
want to dance in the aisle.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, ``Cats `` also works on another level. ``We're using
our bodies as animals, and we're in these costumes that show every
curve, every muscle, every line,'' Danielle concedes. The
proverbial tired businessman has done his part to turn ``Cats''
into a hit. ``And businesswomen too, because we've got guys with
great bodies too,'' she quickly adds. ``There is something for
everyone to relax into.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when the cast was asked to stay onstage for a short
meeting after a matinee earlier this year, Danielle was pretty sure
the show's death knell was about to be sounded. ``I just kind of
sensed it. I was looking at the houses. All week long, and even
Fridays and Saturdays, were really kind of anemic.'' Originally
announced to shutter June 25, the show got an 11-week reprieve by a
boost in business. Last week, the show pulled in $659,000, on an
estimated 97.8 percent of capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Danielle is hardly in a position to complain about the closing.
``Cats `` has been very good to her, allowing her to afford to
build a country home in Pennsylvania and restore a townhouse in
Jersey City. ``It made coming to work that much more enjoyable,
because I had a fulfillment at home,'' she says, then corrects
herself. ``At my homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of prudent investments, she is not desperate to land the
next job nor is she thinking of retiring from show business.
``Well, I'm a workaholic and I do like my creature comforts,''
Danielle says. ``I would like to do a transition into television
and film,'' both performing and getting scripts she has written
produced. ``As far as in front of the camera, I would love to do an
action hero, sort of like a Xena counterpart, using my stamina and
strength.''
</P>
<P>
   SPOILED BY 'CATS'
</P>
<P>
   She had auditioned for other shows over the years, but felt
spoiled by ``Cats.'' ``I was able to say, 'Why just go do another
show where I would be dancing in the background?' Here, I'm
featured. How many shows, unless you're the star, do you have your
own bow? There were a lot of things that I considered, but decided
they weren't going to make me as happy as I was.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cats `` has been notoriously hard on dancers, but Danielle
almost made it through 18 years in the show without sustaining a
substantial injury. Almost.
</P>
<P>
   She was sidelined for four months this year with torn muscle
tissue. ``They said they could operate, clear it up and get me back
in a few weeks, but I decided to take the time and let it heal more
naturally,'' Danielle explains. ``I'm a natural kind of girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Danielle, who owns eight cats _ two at her Jersey City home and
another six in the country _ isn't worried about going through
``Cats'' withdrawal. At 8 tomorrow night, when her muscles are
telling her it is time to kick up her heels and prowl, she can
picture where she'll be. ``I'm going to have a bottle of champagne
and I will be working on my projects,'' she says without a trace of
sadness. ``I'm the sort of person that likes to know that I've got
certain things going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hear from some of the other cast members that people
would ask, 'How is that woman who's been there forever? How is she
taking it?' My response is, 'Y'know what? I've had 18 years to
prepare for this moment,'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
