<HEADER>
A7136 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-JETBLUE-AIRLINE-SFCHR     09-08 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JETBLUE-AIRLINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 JetBlue Takes a Dot-Com Approach to Flying  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Call it Airline.com.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when airlines are winning no popularity contests among
passengers, an upstart carrier named JetBlue Airways has turned to
the Internet for tips on building customer loyalty, improving
efficiency and, well, just plain being liked.
</P>
<P>
   And just four weeks after launching dirt-cheap, red-eye service
between Oakland (Calif.) International Airport and New York's JFK,
the airline now says the route is its single-busiest run, with all
nightly flights almost fully booked.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the dot-com model, there's no question that
there's a lot of good practices out there,'' Dave Barger, JetBlue's
president, said yesterday. ``And we're using them.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, JetBlue, which sprang to life only seven months
ago, has embraced technology to streamline its operations. Along
with plenty of high-tech gear in the cockpits of its fleet of
Airbus A320s, the carrier has sought to automate its reservation
and ticketing process as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Today, about 30 percent of JetBlue bookings are made online _
the highest percentage of any U.S. airline.
</P>
<P>
   Taking another tip from the likes of Amazon.com, the carrier
also believes that a happy customer is a loyal customer, and thus
goes out of its way to make flying _ never a particularly joyful
experience _ if not pleasant, then at least tolerable.
</P>
<P>
   All its planes feature leather seats and free satellite TV on
personal 5-inch screens.
</P>
<P>
   But where JetBlue hews closest to the dot-com ideal is with an
acceptance that to make money, you have to burn through money _
lots of it. With $160 million in initial funding, the company has
purchased or leased 41 planes and has options to purchase 42 more.
</P>
<P>
   JetBlue now has about 46 flights a day nationwide. Its intention
to buy dozens of additional jets illustrates the ambitiousness of
its expansion plans.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's pricing. Simply put, JetBlue wants to be the
cheapest alternative out there. Period.
</P>
<P>
   Its same-day fare for a one-way ticket from Oakland to New York
is $249, or about 79 percent less than competing airlines. Advance
tickets are even cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   Barger said JetBlue can accomplish this through increased
productivity. He said each aircraft flies 13.5 hours a day,
compared with the industry average of about 10. And because the
planes are all new, they're more fuel-efficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how you keep fares low,'' Barger insisted.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't hurt, though, that privately held JetBlue is not yet
beholden to shareholders and can afford to operate at a loss.
Barger said the airline saw its first profitable month in August,
but he doesn't foresee sustained profitability until next year.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a huge concern to Wall Street analysts, who see
JetBlue positioning itself as a smart alternative to larger
airlines at a time when passengers almost universally gripe about
delays, cancellations, lousy service and too-small seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the big boys do as terrible a job as they've been doing,
of course guys like JetBlue have a chance,'' said Helane Becker, an
airline-industry analyst with Buckingham Research Group in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great time for JetBlue to be entering the market,''
agreed Glenn Engel, an analyst with Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   For Gary Tam, a researcher with the state Department of Health
Services in Berkeley, JetBlue's rock-bottom fares were what caught
his attention when he went shopping for tickets recently for a trip
from Oakland to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The price was very good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tam was expecting the trip to be a typical no-frills
experience _ one of those grin-and-bear-it visits to the unfriendly
skies. He was pleasantly surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leather seating, the little TV screens. It was great,'' he
said. Tam even liked the blue potato chips offered as a snack and
had no problem with his flight's 11:45 p.m. departure time.
</P>
<P>
   JetBlue was the brainchild of David Neeleman, the company's
chief executive, and San Francisco venture capitalist Michael
Lazarus, managing partner of Weston Presidio Capital (and no
relation to the writer of this story).
</P>
<P>
   Neeleman already knew his way around budget airlines. An earlier
effort, Morris Air, was so successful that it was acquired by
Southwest Airlines in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as a five-year ``noncompete'' clause expired, Neeleman
hooked up with Lazarus to launch a new carrier, one that would be
as noteworthy for its level of service as for its bargain-basement
fares.
</P>
<P>
   They recruited a management team largely comprising veterans of
Richard Branson's Virgin Airways. Lazarus' own firm invested about
$35 million in the startup and arranged more than $100 million more
from the deep pockets of financier George Soros and Chase Capital
Partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now in financially wonderful shape,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazarus, who also serves as chairman of JetBlue's board of
directors, said he expects the company to go public next year.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, potential investors will have had plenty of
opportunities to see for themselves whether the airline's dot-com
approach to air travel will keep it flying for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   JetBlue, based in New York, began service in February to just
two destinations: Buffalo, N.Y., and Fort Lauderdale, Fla. It
subsequently added additional East Coast routes and then headed
west, first to Salt Lake City, Utah, and then to Los Angeles and
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   All its flights are in the wee hours of the morning _ and all
are attracting passengers. The average ``load factor,'' as airline
insiders say, is 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Such numbers have not been lost on the likes of United Airlines,
the biggest carrier into and out of San Francisco International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be monitoring JetBlue closely,'' said Matthew Triaca, a
spokesman for the airline. ``We take all competitors seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, analysts will be watching to see if JetBlue can
attract lucrative business travelers. JetBlue's planes now have
only coach class, but Goldman Sachs' Engel said this will have to
change as the company grows.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to have a problem with the leisure
customer,'' he said. ``Their problem is going to be convincing
business travelers to switch. Over time, they're going to have to
expand to that market.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazarus said JetBlue will face such choices down the road. For
the moment, he said the airline is taking things one step at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``People look at us like a Volkswagen _ great value and
consistently exceeding expectations,'' Lazarus said. ``And the
great thing is, we don't even have to advertise. We're already
loaded.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; dlazarus(AT)sfchronicle.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
