<SLUG> BC-MARINIJ-NEWSPAPER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Marin County, Calif., Newspaper May Be for Sale  &HT;     By Carolyn Said  
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Marin Independent Journal, a
40,000-circulation daily newspaper, may be for sale and newspaper
magnate William Dean Singleton, owner of the Alameda Newspaper
Group, is a likely purchaser.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters at the Marin IJ, owned by Gannett Co., the country's
largest newspaper publisher, said they were told by a senior editor
at a meeting on Thursday that a deal with ANG might be in the works
and could be announced by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Singleton's ANG publishes a string of suburban newspapers in the
San Francisco Bay Area. The newspapers, in Oakland, Fremont,
Hayward, Alameda, San Mateo, Vallejo, Pleasanton, Milpitas and
Pacifica, Calif., have a combined circulation of about a
quarter-million.
</P>
<P>
   Adding the Marin IJ to that stable ``would give Singleton a
footprint in every county that surrounds San Francisco,'' said
David Cole, editor and publisher of NewsInc., a newsletter about
the newspaper business. ``It gives him the opportunity to sell ads
all throughout the Bay Area with one buy, one bill.''
</P>
<P>
   A purchase also would allow Singleton to increase efficiencies
by combining the Marin paper's back-office functions with those of
his other Bay Area properties, Cole added.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, such ``clustering'' is key to Singleton's announced
strategy. MediaNews Group, his Denver company, seeks to acquire
newspapers in contiguous markets ``to realize operating
efficiencies and economic synergies,'' the company's Web site
states.
</P>
<P>
   Cross selling advertising among clustered papers produces higher
operating margins than the papers would earn on their own, the Web
site continues.
</P>
<P>
   MediaNews Group owns newspaper companies with combined daily
circulation of 1.5 million, ranking it as the seventh-largest U.S.
newspaper company, its Web site states.
</P>
<P>
   From a journalistic standpoint, Singleton is known for giving
priority to cutting costs over quality. ``ANG treats reporters and
editors as just so much cannon fodder,'' Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1861, the IJ has been owned by Gannett since 1980.
According to Editor &AMP; Publisher, the paper's circulation has
remained flat during the past three years, while U.S. newspapers
overall have experienced circulation declines.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett uses the IJ's presses to print Northern California
editions of its flagship USA Today paper. Any sale of the IJ would
be likely to include a clause covering USA Today printing, said
newspaper observers.
</P>
<P>
   Singleton and Gannett already have a precedent for such an
arrangement. In March 1999, Singleton purchased the San Bernardino
(Calif.) Sun from Gannett, signing a 10-year contract to continue
printing some editions of USA Today on the Sun's presses.
</P>
<P>
   The IJ has been consigned to afternoon delivery (with some
morning editions available in stores and news racks) because USA
Today usurps the morning press run. Cole said it's possible that
Singleton has enough press capacity elsewhere in the Bay Area that
he could still print USA Today and move the IJ to more-desirable
morning publication.
</P>
<P>
   Several top managers have quit the Marin IJ recently. Phyllis K.
Pfeiffer, IJ publisher since 1993, resigned this week to take on a
job with Contra Costa Newspapers. She will stay with the IJ until
September 29. The director of advertising, the head of online
operations and the managing editor have all resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett declined to comment. Singleton and Pfeiffer did not
return calls.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carolyn Said at  &LR; csaid(AT)sfchronicle.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 2258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
