<HEADER>
A7139 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-ADS-NYT &LR;      09-08 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK SENATE RACE GROWS MORE COMBATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The combative tone of the Senate campaign in New York
has have escalated with an exchange of television and radio
advertisements as the candidates battle to redefine their own image
and that of their opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, the campaigns and their supporters in the past 10
days have released nearly a half-dozen ads, most of them critical,
in a back-and-forth duel between Hillary Rodham Clinton and Rep.
Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides promised more to come _ and exchanged blame for
negativity _ as polls continued to show the candidates in a virtual
dead heat, with many people undecided. Although the candidates are
rarely as harsh on the stump, the bitter tenor left campaign
officials wondering Friday what to expect in the first debate of
the race, on Wednesday in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she airs just a whopper of a lie or distortion, we
occasionally have to respond,'' said Lazio's chief strategist,
Michael Murphy. He is the architect of the candidate's ads,
including a new series asking whether voters can trust Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Kauffman, a spokesman for the state Democratic Party,
which has run a set of attack ads on Clinton's behalf, countered,
saying: ``The big difference between Hillary Clinton and the
Democratic Party and the ads Rick Lazio is running is each of our
ads are based on substantive issues. When they run an ad, it
attacks Hillary personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Two advertisements were announced Friday, one by the state
Democratic Party and the other by the state Republican Party, the
first it had created on Lazio's behalf. Both commercials take a
pointed look at their respective candidates' opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic television ad, which began appearing Friday,
reprises a ``man in the street'' style that the party used in an
earlier commercial that purported to show everyday New Yorkers
reacting in shock and dismay at Lazio's positions on health care
and other topics. In the new ad, people react negatively as an
off-camera narrator questions Lazio's support for education.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party released a tongue-in-cheek radio ad, to
begin running in New York City on Monday, that attacks Clinton's
move to New York through a compilation of recorded snippets from
her past speeches and news conferences. ``Chicago is my kind of
town,'' she says in a recording from the 1996 Democratic National
Convention, though the ad does not tell listeners that Chicago not
only is her hometown, but was the site of the convention.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner was each ad released than the other side began to
criticize it. In the case of the Republican ad, the Democrats
seized on the Republicans' decision to use largely unregulated soft
money donations to pay for the commercial. Lazio has criticized
Clinton for collecting millions of dollars in soft money, but the
Republican radio ad gave Democrats ammunition to accuse him of
hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns once again followed up the ads with e-mail
messages to reporters and supporters, quarreling over who went
negative first and pointing out what they said were inaccuracies in
the opponent's ads.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the ads will be broadcast statewide; some are having
such a limited release _ a few stations, one or two days _ that
they seem designed more to get attention from television stations
and newspapers doing reports on them.
</P>
<P>
   Since Lazio entered the race in May, he has run 8 television and
radio commercials; Clinton, 11; the Democratic Party, 7; and the
Republican Party, 1. In addition, other groups like the New York
Conservative Party and the Republican Leadership Council, which
support Lazio, and the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights
Action League, which supports Clinton, have released
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates themselves have been a little less acerbic toward
one another on the campaign trail. They flick pointed barbs
occasionally through news conferences, and did so Friday about the
coming debate.
</P>
<P>
   Another debate, in New York City, is scheduled for Oct. 8, and
the campaign staffs are negotiating another.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, speaking to reporters after touring businesses in
Westchester County, said he looked forward to the debate, and
perhaps signaling what is to come, took the opportunity to
criticize his opponent's campaign tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where else the first lady comes from, except for
attacking me and trying to distort my record; that's what she's
been doing for most of this campaign,'' Lazio said. ``It would be
wonderful if she didn't, if she just took a positive tack. But
we'll wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, after touring an elementary school in Brooklyn, engaged
in the time-tested strategy of lowering expectations about how she
might do. ``My opponent has debated a lot and he's been on the
floor of the House debating, so you know obviously I've never done
it before,'' she said. ``I'm trying to get prepared but it's a
totally new experience for me.''
</P>
<P>
   When the subject turned to the substance of the debate, however,
she began sounding a bit like some of the harsh commercials made on
her behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does a lot of talking but he doesn't actually deliver for
New York,'' she said, rattling off a host of votes she contends
Lazio did not support. ``He may score a debating point or two, but
when it comes to standing up for the children of New York, he's
been missing in action.''
</P>
</TEXT>
