<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-CAM0909-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    DualCam packs camera and camcorder in one
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The first digital still photograph cameras hit
the consumer market a few years ago and digital camcorders followed
more recently.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's possible to have two digital cameras in one. JVC Co. of
America has a line of what it calls Digital DualCams that can
record moving video with sound and still photographs at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   The top of the line is the GR-DVL9800 Digital DualCam introduced
in February. The device has a high-resolution video camera that
records on tape combined with a high-resolution still camera that
records images on a memory card.
</P>
<P>
   The two components can be used separately, or the still camera
can be used to take digital snapshots of the same scenes being
recorded by the video camera.
</P>
<P>
   JVC says the video camera has progressive-scan technology to
capture video with 520 lines of horizontal resolution and 480 lines
of vertical resolution. It's capable of shooting 30 high-resolution
frames per second so each frame is sharp enough to be downloaded to
a computer or video printer.
</P>
<P>
   The lens can be adjusted to magnify images up to 10 times
optically, and the digital brain can increase magnification 200
times. The camcorder also has a fast-speed shooting mode to create
slow-motion effects.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the resolution selected, the camera can store from
12 to 36 images on a removable 4 megabyte MultiMediaCard. The
memory card, which is about the size of a postage stamp, comes with
the camera.
</P>
<P>
   The camcorder itself is equipped to add digital effects such as
fades, wipes and dissolves to mark transitions between scenes.
</P>
<P>
   JVC sets the manufacturer's suggested price for the GR-DVL9800
Digital DualCam at $1,999, but it's available locally at Click
Camera stores for $1,799, according to a clerk at the company's
Englewood area store.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the camera, visit the Web site at
www.jvc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
