<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7260 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-RADIO0910-COX     09-08 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO0910-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Tuned In &AMP; Turned On
 &HT;    By Bob Batz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Pat Smith is talking as he winds his way through
the mountain of radios, tubes, speakers and other broadcast-related
paraphernalia that fills his delightfully cluttered electronics
shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thrill of the chase and taking something that's 50 years
old and bringing it back to life are what this hobby is all
about,'' Smith declares.
</P>
<P>
   Later, gently running his fingers over a rare 1941 General
Electric brass-trimmed ``jewel box radio,'' he says, ``A woman gave
me this one. It was her first radio. She bought it in 1941. One of
these sold recently on the Internet _ for $2,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, the radio was the most important piece of
furniture in most American living rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Now those vintage Crosleys, Zeniths and Atwater Kents that
brought us such shows as ``Fibber McGee &AMP; Molly,'' ``Gangbusters''
and ``The Lone Ranger'' are among the nation's hottest
collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton area has hundreds of vintage radio enthusiasts and at
least two clubs that enable members to get together on a regular
basis to talk about their hobby.
</P>
<P>
   For radio buffs and others who routinely surf the Internet in
hopes of beefing up their collections or keeping the radios they
already own in working order, Smith _ who makes his living
repairing old radios and selling parts for them _ is definitely a
go-to guy.
</P>
<P>
   You name it and it's probably stacked, boxed or strewn about his
three-room storefront shop. Even the name of the business _
Antique, Classic &AMP; Modern Electronics (ACME) _ has a slightly
cluttered ring to it. Smith likes it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though this place looks disorganized,'' he says,'' I know
exactly where everything is. Well, almost exactly, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   As vintage radio enthusiasts go, the 32-year-old Smith, who has
about 100 radios in his collection, is one of the youngest in the
Dayton area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought my first radio in the mid-1970s, and my collection
has been growing ever since,'' he says, noting that his best
sources for vintage radios are flea markets, garage sales and
widows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't go on a safari looking for old radios, they just seem
to come to me,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The first radios date to the early 1920s. Manufacturers included
Crosley, Atwater Kent and RCA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until 1925 or 1926, all radios were battery-powered,'' Smith
says. ``The radios that are hardest to find are those made from
1921 to 1924. Between 1922 and 1927, radio made huge advances.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to some of the radios in his collection, Smith's
shop holds vintage and newer tubes, speakers in every size and
shape, old hi-fi equipment, radio literature, antennas, knobs and
dials.
</P>
<P>
   Even the two cats who while away the afternoons dozing in the
sun-washed front window of the store have radio-ish names _ Crosley
and Edison.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's collection of classic radios runs the gamut from
A(Airline) to Z (Zenith). He has Crosleys, too, and Philcos,
Admirals, Motorolas, Atwater Kents, Delcos, Silvertones and
Truetones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people collect radios so they can sell them and make
money,'' he explains. ``Others just enjoy showing 'em off. Other
collectors specialize in tubes or literature. One guy even collects
tube boxes, many of which are bright-colored. Collections come in
all sizes. There's a guy in Hamilton who has one of largest
collections in the world. He has thousands of radios.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Gray, 69, who stops by Smith's shop frequently to talk about
radios and see what's new _ or old, says radio collectors come in
all shapes and sizes, and from all walks of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you need to get started is an interest in old radios and
the urge to collect them,'' says Gray, who owns 125 radios, give or
take a Philco or two. He has his radios displayed museum-style in
six of the seven rooms of his home.
</P>
<P>
   Gray got his first radio 55 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a Zenith Tombstone from the mid-1930s,'' he recalls.
``I paid maybe five bucks for it. And I don't have it any more. In
the last five years it has become harder and harder to find vintage
radios, especially the rarer ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most valuable radios are the Zenith Stratosphere and
the Spartan Nocturne. Both date to the mid-1930s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four or five years ago, a Stratosphere sold for $40,000,''
Gray says. ``Most bring $10,000 or more.''
</P>
<P>
   Vintage radio tubes can also have big price tags, Smith says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are very expensive, others, including some still in their
original boxes, sell for as little as a dollar,'' he says. ``I just
sold four tubes on the Internet. I got $1,200.
</P>
<P>
   for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is making an impact on the hobby, Smith says,
noting: ``It's both good and bad. It's been good to people like me.
My hobby has turned into my business. On the down side, it has
driven up prices of old radios.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray says the popularity of collecting vintage radios is growing
fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it'll continue to grow, too . . . as long as we don't
all die out. I'd say the average collector is 50.The oldest I know
is 92, maybe 93.''
</P>
<P>
   Do some people think Gray is a little crazy when he tells them
he has 125 old radios?
</P>
<P>
   ``Some do,'' he says, ``but I just ask them, 'What do you
collect?' This hobby is as much about preservation as it is about
collecting. That makes it fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Anybody with an interest in old radios can get involved in the
hobby for a little money.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can buy a Philco cathedral radio in good working for
around $200,'' Smith says.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest swap meets for radio collectors are held in Elgin,
Ill. (August), Lansing, Mich. (July), and Rochester, N.Y.
(September).
</P>
<P>
   ``They draw people from all over the world, too,'' Smith says.
</P>
<P>
   Smith says the biggest help to a guy who collects radios is a
tolerant and understanding wife.
</P>
<P>
   Smith agrees, adding: ``I know a guy whose divorce was based on
his collection of vintage radios.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 2309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
