<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0446 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7261 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-WINE-MAKERS0910-COX     09-08 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-MAKERS0910-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Wine making alive and well in Colorado
 &HT;    By Lori Cumpston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. To hear Erik Bruner talk about the early
days at Plum Creek Cellars winery in Palisade, you can't help but
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to tell you a story,'' he says, propping himself up
against a stack of wooden barrels in the heart of the winery.
</P>
<P>
   Bruner, clad in worn jeans, a blue-and-white striped shirt and
suspenders, launches into a story about the time he brought in a
load of wine for a local store to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``This older fellow was there and his son was the wine buyer . .
. I said, `I've got some Plum Creek wine,' and he looked over and
said, `Who ordered that sh--?' '' says Bruner, 60, his mischievous
eyes twinkling from behind wire-rim glasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I persisted and we went to every dog-and-pony-show
winetasting. I'd be in liquor stores signing bottles, kissing
babies all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Plum Creek Cellars is the brainchild of Bruner and his close
friends, Doug and Sue Phillips. The threesome, along with a group
of winetasting friends, founded the winery in a garage south of
Denver in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Bruner had been practicing winemaking for quite awhile before
approaching Doug with the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``When were the Broncos in the first Super Bowl?'' he asks.
``That's when I made my first batch of wine out of concentrates ...
that was a catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1978.
</P>
<P>
   As Bruner's confidence grew, so did his yard. He transformed his
Front Range home into a Napa Valley vineyard that even
Oscar-winning movie mogul turned wine entrepreneur Francis Ford
Coppola would have been proud of well, sort of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put in my own grapes,'' recalls Bruner, smirking. ``My back
yard was a total jungle. My ex-wife wouldn't even go out in the
back yard anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   IT'S ALL ABOUT BALANCE
</P>
<P>
   W inemaking is not new to Colorado. In fact, the winemaking
industry was alive and well more than 100 years ago. The demise for
grape growers came in 1916. That's when the state adopted a
prohibition statute forcing vineyards out of business.
</P>
<P>
   That statute was later repealed.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the late '60s that the state's wine industry
started to heat up again.
</P>
<P>
   Bruner's own family hails from the fertile farmlands of West
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather was a mercenary,'' says Bruner. ``He hid out
with the Pennsylvania Germans and the first son walked from
Lancaster to Wheeling, West Virginia, in 1830 and started the
family farm.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruner, a geological engineer by trade, began entertaining the
idea of making wine full time.
</P>
<P>
   He relocated to Palisade.
</P>
<P>
   Doug and Sue live in Denver where they practice law. The couple
commute to Palisade on weekends to help run the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Balance,'' says Bruner when asked what makes a good wine.
``Ripeness and balance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that is the most rewarding is to go to winetastings
where your wine is being evaluated and see how pleased people are
and if they're really enjoying it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Bruner was diagnosed with Parkinson's, a debilitating
disease that is characterized by rhythmic tremors and rigidity of
the muscles.
</P>
<P>
   His health was further complicated by heart and lung problems as
a result of coronary artery disease. In 1998, he underwent triple
bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Bruner was forced into early retirement.
</P>
<P>
   FROM CELLAR RAT TO HEAD WINEMAKER
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was fate that brought Bruner face to face with Jenne
Baldwin, then a 24-year-old personal trainer from Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family has a small mom-and-pop aquarium,'' says Baldwin, a
fresh-faced blonde with an outdoorsy glow. ``We have 14 harbor
seals and over 200 tanks. My grandparents started it over 60 years
ago ... it's a far cry from grapes.''
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, Baldwin, who has a minor in chemistry from Chico
State University in northern California, found herself beating the
grapevines looking for work as a lab assistant.
</P>
<P>
   She began working part-time at Plum Creek as a cellar rat,
eventually working her way up to the office, lab, tasting room and
bottling departments.
</P>
<P>
   Bruner has taken Baldwin under his wing.
</P>
<P>
   His health problems have forced him to step down as head
winemaker but he still holds the title of winemaker emeritus and
lives on the grounds, helping out as needed.
</P>
<P>
   Last January, Baldwin was promoted to head winemaker. She is
believed to be one of only three female head winemakers in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   State regulations do not require winemakers to be licensed,
however Baldwin studies yearly at the University of California at
Davis, which is world renowned for its programs on winemaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not exactly a pioneer,'' says Baldwin, ``but I did see a
lot of wineries start up. Erik took it this far and hopefully I can
take it to another level.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no time to reflect.
</P>
<P>
   The grape harvest has begun. Bruner and Baldwin are awaiting a
load of grapes. It's crush time.
</P>
<P>
   The work day starts at 6 a.m. Equipment is cleaned and sanitized
before the grapes can be processed. That's followed by another
three to four hours of clean-up.
</P>
<P>
   Some days the work isn't finished until 3 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Plum Creek Cellars expects to harvest 150 tons of grapes. That
translates into 11,000 cases of wine.
</P>
<P>
   The winery boasts a wonderful array of red wines, including
Merlot, Cabernet Franc and Cabernet Sauvignon. It also has an
interesting selection of white wines, Chardonnay and Riesling, as
well as dessert and rose wines. In fact, the Riesling Ice Wine is
the state's only ice wine made from 100 percent Riesling grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Past vintages have won awards.
</P>
<P>
   Plum Creek's Cabernet Franc for '97 and '98 received double gold
medals in a national wine competition. The 1997 Cabernet Sauvignon
also received a gold medal at the Indy International Wine
Competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think it's a romantic profession,'' says Baldwin.
``Everyone has seen that Lucille Ball episode where she is stomping
grapes with her feet and that's how they think it is ... that we're
just laughing, running around and dancing. It's very intensive
manual labor.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
