<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LIEBERMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LIEBERMAN'S CAMPAIGN INSURANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, Sept. 9:
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lieberman is now running for two national offices at the
same time _ his Senate seat from his home state of Connecticut and
the vice presidency as the Democratic Party nominee. The
Connecticut Elections Enforcement Commission decided this week that
this double campaigning is legal. That still does not make it fair
to Connecticut voters or smart for the state's Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   By staying in both races, Lieberman is hedging his bets in a way
that benefits him, of course. But it hardly sends a signal of
confidence about the future of the ticket he is sharing with Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, his dual candidacy could lead to a situation in which
Connecticut chooses a Democratic senator in November but has a
Republican installed by appointment. It could also lead to
legislative contortions as Democrats in the state Capitol try to
figure out a way to prevent Gov. John Rowland, a Republican, from
filling the vacancy from within his own party should Lieberman go
to Washington as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, only a few days after the traditional Labor Day
kickoff of the fall campaign, there is still time for Lieberman to
get off the ballot and let the two parties conduct a fair fight for
his vacated seat.
</P>
<P>
   As things now stand, if Lieberman resigns from the Senate race
before Oct. 27, Connecticut's Democratic State Central Committee
would pick a replacement. The name mentioned most often is the
state attorney general, Richard Blumenthal, who would be a strong
contender for the job.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican nominee, Mayor Philip Giordano of Waterbury, is
regarded by some as a place-holder against Lieberman, but the
Republicans would have the option of asking him to step aside in
favor of a a stronger replacement.
</P>
<P>
   If Lieberman wins both his Senate campaign and the vice
presidency, Rowland will pick a replacement who must run for the
office two years later. Rowland can be expected to choose a member
of his own party for the job, giving the Senate one more Republican
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this potential for damage to his own party, Lieberman
has said that he favors a Rowland appointment now because it would
give the political system enough time to work _ with full primaries
and full-fledged elections in the year 2002. If he pulls out early,
he has argued, the process would be chaotic and unfair since a
party committee, instead of a primary, would pick the Democratic
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's spokesman argues that an election this year would be
a hurried affair, without a primary, and that the winner would be
allowed to serve for a full six years. He points out that the
governor's presumed Republican appointee would serve for only two
years at most until facing election. This reasoning is thin and
self-serving.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is prompting Democratic leaders in Connecticut to
contemplate a hasty rerigging of election laws. The thought is that
if Lieberman resigns from the Senate to be vice president, the
Democratic legislature can then pass a bill requiring a special
election in three or perhaps six months to fill the empty seat
sometime next year. Rowland, according to this plan, would have
difficulty vetoing such a bill because it would appear undemocratic
to deprive voters of an election.
</P>
<P>
   But the cleaner, fairer solution is to let Connecticut voters
have a choice in the regularly scheduled general election.
Lieberman should resign from the Senate race right away and leave
that contest to candidates who will definitely be available to
serve. That action would also put a ring of confidence into his
predictions of victory on the presidential ticket.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
