<SLUG> BC-OLY-BKO-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: BASKETBALL  
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forty And 0. Since the United States was first represented by
NBA players in 1992, Olympic men's basketball has been a coronation
rather than a competition.
</P>
<P>
   The Dream Team moniker should have been done away with after
Magic, Jordan and Bird teamed for gold eight years ago. Still, you
can't bet against a crew featuring Vince Carter, Kevin Garnett and
Jason Kidd. Even with only one natural center, Alonzo Mourning, the
U.S. men is not in serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   As for the U.S. women, that's another story. The Australian men
and women could both win a medal, with the women possibly pushing
the United States for gold. A team featuring Lisa Leslie, Sheryl
Swoopes and five-time Olympian Teresa Edwards should be a lock. But
lack of practice time because of commitments for the WNBA and stiff
competition from the host country, Russia, Brazil and Cuba may
prove too much of a task. Unlike the men, they can be beaten.
</P>
<P>
   THE SETUP
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. men have a virtual cakewalk in first three games of the
preliminary round, opening with China, Italy and a watered-down
Lithuania. Russia, Yugoslavia and Australia will mix it up in Group
B, with the highest-seeded survivor eventually advancing to face
the United States for the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   Here is one personal setup: Alonzo Mourning is actually leaving
the Games on Sept. 22 for his home in Miami, and is not scheduled
to return to Sydney until Sept. 26. He is flying 9,330 miles
round-trip so that his wife, Tracy Wilson-Mourning, can give birth
by induced labor to the couple's child. Apparently, coach Rudy
Tomjanovich is not too concerned with the inside game of either New
Zealand or France, the two opponents Mourning will miss.
</P>
<P>
   THE WOMEN
</P>
<P>
   The Australians, who won the bronze in 1996, feature not only
the former Olympians Michelle Timms, Carla Boyd and Michelle
Griffiths but also Lauren Jackson, a 19-year-old Wunderkind who
figures to be the first pick in the 2001 WNBA draft.She gives the
host country a good shot at competing for a medal.
</P>
<P>
   She stands 6 feet 5 inches, can post up or play on the perimeter
and her pulled-back ponytail belies her ferocity. Jackson elbowed
Leslie during an exhibition last fall. The two jawed at one
another. Jackson said afterward: ``I'm not going to sit back and
let some Lisa Leslie go at me. I really don't care what she says to
me because one day I'll be as good as her.''
</P>
<P>
   At some point, Swoopes may have to match up against Brazil's
Janeth Arcain, her Houston Comets teammate.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't falter in the preliminary round and find a way to
claw past Brazil and Russia, the Aussies could find themselves in a
spirited game for the gold against a U.S. team still trying to find
the perfect chemistry over a short period of time.
</P>
<P>
   THE MEN
</P>
<P>
   The lack of marquee players stands out. Beyond the absences of
Shaquille O'Neal, Kobe Bryant, Tim Duncan and Grant Hill from the
United States, neither Rick Fox nor Jamaal Magloire, a 2000 NBA
draft pick, will play for Canada. Vlade Divac is not playing for
Yugoslavia. And injuries to Arvydas Sabonis, Zydrunas Ilgauskas and
star Arturas Karnisovas cripple Lithuania's chances. Croatia, which
could have featured Toni Kukoc, did not even qualify.
</P>
<P>
   France's 7-1 Frederic Weis, whom the Knicks chose with the 15th
pick in the 1999 draft but who has yet to play an NBA game, and
China's 7-foot Wang Zhizhi, taken in the second round of the '99
draft by the Mavericks, will play and make for some good
conversation. Zhizhi, his 7-4 teammate Yao Ming and the 6-11
forward Menk Bater have been christened by the Asian media as the
``Walking Great Wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Still after the Vinsanity dunk-a-thon has ended, the quest is
for silver again on the men's side.
</P>
<P>
   A weakened European field could enable the Australian men to
finally win a medal in the sport. Like Teresa Edwards, Andrew Gaze
is a five-time Olympian. Chris Anstey, Luc Longley and Shane Heal
give the Aussie men three more players with NBA experience. If
either team advances to the gold-medal game, expect the Sydney
SuperDome to shake with sound. The United States could be
susceptible to a hot perimeter team that starts knocking down
3-pointers and builds a quick lead.
</P>
<P>
   And if either Mourning or Gary Payton blows a fuse at a key
juncture, who knows? The U.S. men do not have to worry about
overconfidence, but keeping their composure could be a chore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
