<HEADER>
A7267 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-HOT-ARIZONA0910-COX     09-08 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOT-ARIZONA0910-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    It's easy to have a hot time in Phoenix
 &HT;    By Ray Marcano
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The first thing that hits you about Phoenix is
the heat. Yes, it's dry heat, whatever that means, but 113 degrees
_ the high during a recent trip _ is still hot by any standard.
</P>
<P>
   But there's some good news. The temperatures will soon start to
get cooler, travelers will look for an interesting place to go, and
Phoenix is a nice, affordable destination with more than enough to
do.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: From the East Coast and Midwest, plan on a 3 1/2-
to 4 1/2-hour plane ride. And, if you catch the right fares, it
won't break you. In two trips to Phoenix this year _ one in April,
the other in August _ the fare from Columbus was $219 round trip
for a direct flight. Beware: That fare fluctuated wildly and at one
point, that same ticket was $435. As always, look ahead, plan and
when you see a great fare, don't hesitate.
</P>
<P>
   What to do: To do it all, you'll have to come back several
times. The allure of Phoenix isn't just the city, but everything
that's within four hours.
</P>
<P>
   For those that like the great outdoors, there's no shortage of
hiking, and Camelback is a fun mountain to climb. It's right
outside Phoenix and visible from downtown. Plan on spending 90
minutes to two hours on the 2 1/2-mile hike.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's golf. Phoenix has 180 courses in the area, an
incredible mix of public, semiprivate and private courses to fit
most budgets. Summer greens fees can be as low as $25, depending on
the course.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're not into hiking or golf, Phoenix is big on the Old
West. Among the attractions: Rawhide, a mix of theater, action
shows, shopping and food, (480) 502-5600) and Tombstone, one of the
country's legendary Old West cities, is a 2 1/2-hour drive away.
And, of course, you can take the four-hour drive to the Grand
Canyon, a true national treasure.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay: Like any big city Phoenix has an array of hotels.
The Crowne Plaza downtown is a terrific choice for about $100 a
night, depending on the season. And if you stay downtown take the
75-minute tour of Bank One Ballpark, (602) 462-6543, home of the
Arizona Diamondbacks. For $6 adults, $4 children, it's a must for
baseball fans.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites:
</P>
<P>
   Camelback:
hikearizona.com/trails/phoenix/camelback/echo/camelback.htm
</P>
<P>
   Hiking in Arizona: phoenix.linksee.com/Recreation/Hiking/
</P>
<P>
   Golf courses: http://www.allusagolf.com (allows you to make
on-line reservations)
</P>
<P>
   GETTING BUMPED PAYS OFF
</P>
<P>
   When traveling, try never to be in a hurry. It can really pay
off, and save the savvy bargain traveler hundreds of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   My August Phoenix flight was oversold. The attendants asked for
volunteers willing to take a later flight in exchange for a $300
travel voucher and a meal ticket for lunch. That, in an of itself,
is a pretty good deal. But I had to make a few phone calls to tell
people I'd be late, and the airline offered a 10-minute phone card
to take care of that. Then I found out the first-class section
wasn't full, I asked for _ and received _ an upgrade from my coach
seat.
</P>
<P>
   I got to Phoenix three hours later than I was supposed to, but
have a free trip, had a good lunch, got a calling card to make my
calls and flew in style.
</P>
<P>
   So the lesson is: Build in some extra travel time. It could pay
big dividends.
</P>
<P>
   MAILBAG
</P>
<P>
   A few female readers who plan trips by themselves have asked
what precautions they should take when traveling alone. The Web is
full of sites that offer such advice, and a good one is from Travel
and Leisure, whose site offers ``50 Tips for Women Traveling
Alone.'' Go to
http://www.pathfinder.com/travel/TL/tarticles/1132.html and you'll
get right to the page. In addition, most airlines offer tips on how
to handle children traveling by themselves, and there are sites
specifically for seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
