<SLUG> BC-BKC-BOBBYKNIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBATTLED COACH FACES NEW ACCUSATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Indiana University Coach Bobby Knight Friday night denied an
accusation that he physically and verbally assaulted a student on
Thursday afternoon after the student addressed him by his last
name.
</P>
<P>
   In a live news conference on the school's campus in Bloomington
on Friday evening, Knight said he had had a brief encounter with
the student about ``manners and civility'' but said he never swore
at the student or manhandled him.
</P>
<P>
   One of Knight's assistant coaches, Mike Davis, who said he had
witnessed the incident, said that the accusation was untrue.
</P>
<P>
   The university had confirmed earlier that it was investigating
what Christopher Simpson, a school spokesman, described as an
``extraordinarily serious'' accusation. Four months earlier, Myles
Brand, the president of the university, suspended Knight for three
games in the 2000-1 season, fined him $30,000 and warned him that
any future instances of unacceptable behavior could result in his
immediate firing.
</P>
<P>
   Brand acted after a seven-week investigation by the school's
board of trustees concluded that Knight had displayed a ``pattern
of inappropriate behavior'' that had embarrassed the university.
Among the accusations investigated by the trustees were that the
often-volatile Knight had once choked a player during practice and
had hurled a vase near a school secretary during a fit of anger.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest incident, Mark Shaw, a former Bloomington-area
radio talk-show host and a critic of Knight, told ESPN that his
stepson _ a 19-year-old freshman _ had been grabbed by Knight and
cursed at after he greeted him on campus at around 2 p.m. Thursday
by saying, ``Hey, what's up, Knight?''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw told the Indianapolis Star that he saw finger marks on his
stepson's arm and reported the incident to Simpson later that
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, his stepson and four other witnesses also reported the
incident to campus police. Shaw asked that Knight apologize and
that the incident be reported to a committee headed by athletics
director Clarence Doninger and charged with devising a code of
conduct for Knight and all university coaches.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference Friday night, Knight said he was coming
through a door at Assembly Hall, where the basketball team plays
its games, when Shaw's stepson, Kent Harvey, greeted him by his
last name.
</P>
<P>
   ``My name is not Knight to you,'' the coach said he told the
student. ``It is Coach or Mr. Knight.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight said he had his hand on the inside of the young man's arm
as he addressed him, but said the accusations of any pulling or
spinning of the student were false.
</P>
<P>
   Knight used a blackboard to diagram the encounter and then used
Davis as a prop to demonstrate Knight's version of what occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never said a cuss word, he never raised his voice,'' Davis
said of Knight.
</P>
<P>
   Knight noted to reporters that the student is the stepson of a
person he termed his ``most vitriolic critic.'' He also said that
in the wake of his recent sanctions, he would have to be an
``absolute moron'' to get involved in a public confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Jerry Minger of the campus police said that investigators
were scheduling interviews with the younger Shaw as well as other
witnesses but that it was difficult to determine how long it would
take to complete the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw did not return phone calls or e-mail messages to his Web
site, which describes him as a lawyer, author and movie producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if we're talking about Bob Knight, the president
of the United States, or some guy off the street, that kind of
conduct is not tolerated,'' Shaw told the Indianapolis Star.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
