<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7277 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANATOMY-FILM-REVIEW-N     09-08 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANATOMY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANATOMY': DWINDLING STUDENT BODY, IN MORE WAYS THAN ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Any dummy who didn't already know that dissecting a
corpse is a lot like having sex is instructed to study ``Anatomy,''
the clumsy German horror movie that sneaked into the AMC theater
complex Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The bad girl in this preposterous Germanic imitation of American
teen horror movies like ``Scream'' is a boy-crazy medical student
named Gretchen (Anna Loos), who gives ``anatomy tests'' to her
dates on a dissecting table in the ultramodern lab of a renowned
medical school in Heidelberg.
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen discovers to her annoyance that such a setting is not
conducive to sexual ardor, even when she does an aggressive
striptease. And she is eventually punished for her meanness by Hein
(Benno Fuermann), a spurned boy-toy who lurches around like a
glowering caricature of a Hitler Youth recruit transplanted into
the 21st century and divested of his Nazi insignia.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the other students and most of the faculty, Hein
happens to belong to a secret ``anti-Hippocratic'' society whose
members believe that medical research is worth the sacrifice of
human lives.
</P>
<P>
   Since ``Anatomy'' is a horror film, that lodge's philosophy has
become a rationalization for the wholesale murder of innocent
students. It is carried out by drugging them, injecting them with a
substance that turns blood into a rubberized plastic and announcing
proudly, ``It's statue time.'' If you wondered why the models in
the anatomy lab are so incredibly lifelike, there's your answer.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's plucky Nancy Drew who smells a formaldehyde-dipped
rat on the premises is Paula (Franka Potente), a brilliant medical
student whose beloved dying grandfather is a university legend. One
of the many sad lessons that nosy, high-minded Paula eventually
learns is that Grandpa wasn't quite the pillar of medical ethics
that she thought he was.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the movie, she gets herself into such a pickle
that she finds herself in danger of literally being pickled. Or
worse.
</P>
<P>
   Stefan Ruzowitzky, who wrote and directed ``Anatomy,'' has
learned a few things from American filmmakers about setting up
diversionary booby traps and finding the proper camera angles to
show the glint of a concealed knife. But the movie, which is
crudely dubbed into English, lacks the raucous,
anything-for-a-shock carnival humor of its American prototypes.
</P>
<P>
   After it's over, the only question worth asking is whether dear,
cozy old Heidelberg can survive the slander.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anatomy'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying parent or
adult guardian). It includes gory violence and nudity.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ANATOMY'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Stefan Ruzowitzky; in German, dubbed
into English; director of photography, Peter von Haller; edited by
Ueli Christen; music by Marius Ruhland; production designer, Ingrid
Henn; produced by Jakob Claussen and Thomas Woebke; released by
Deutsche Columbia Pictures Film Productions and Sony Pictures
Releasing. At the AMC Empire 25, 42nd Street at Eighth Avenue, New
York. Running time: 99 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   With: Franka Potente (Paula), Benno Fuermann (Hein), Anna Loos
(Gretchen), Holger Speckhahn (Phil), Sebastian Blomberg (Caspar)
and Traugott Buhre (Professor Grombek).
</P>
</TEXT>
