<P>
   (NYT50) ATLANTA -- Sept. 8, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. SEPT. 10 --
CIVILRIGHTS-CHILDREN-COX-6 -- Peggy Wallace Kennedy, 50, the oldest
daughter of former Gov. George Wallace of Alabama. What she
remembers most about her father is the last years of his life. He
was shot and paralyzed in 1972 while running as an independent
candidate for president. The shooting changed him in many ways,
Kennedy says. He renounced his racial politics, began reading his
Bible every day and started seeking forgiveness. ``He would call
friends he hadn't talked to for a long time and say, 'If we got
anything to straighten out, let's straighten it out now.''' Kennedy
at her Montgomery, Ala. home. (Jay Sailors/The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT49) ATLANTA -- Sept. 8, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. SEPT. 10 --
CIVILRIGHTS-CHILDREN-COX-5 -- C.T. Vivian, a leader in the Southern
Christian Leadership Conference, took part in voter registration
drives throughout the South. In 1964, Albert Vivian saw his father
get punched in the face on national television. It's one of his
fondest childhood memories. The confrontation arose as Rev. Vivian
was attempting to register as voters a group of blacks turned away
from the courthouse in Selma, Ala. Albert Vivian, 38, is following
in his father's footsteps, taking over a consulting business that
offers racial sensitivity workshops for corporations and city
governments. ``His actions filled me with a gush of pride,'' says
the younger Vivian. Vivian and his father, at the Rev. Vivian's
Atlanta home. (Louie Favorite/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
