<P>
   (NYT11) HAVANA -- Sept. 8, 2000 -- CUBA-OLYMPICS-COX-2 -- Over
the years, the performance of Cuban athletes has been remarkable,
especially in the Olympic Games. Cubans have always been sports
fanatics, with a near-legendary love for baseball. But ever since
Fidel Castro's 1959 revolution, they've had the active
encouragement of their government, which early on identified sports
as a key element in its vision for an egalitarian, socialist
society. Cuban baseball players at baseball practice at the
National Sports City complex in Havana. (Mike Williams/Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) HAVANA -- Sept. 8, 2000 -- CUBA-OLYMPICS-COX-1 -- Many
Cubans are talking about the upcoming Sydney Olympics. And like any
die-hard Georgia Bulldog or Texas Longhorns or Florida Gator
football fan, they are firmly convinced their team is going to win,
and win big. Despite being one of the world's smaller countries,
with a population of only 11 million, Cuban athletes took home 31
Olympic medals in 1992's Barcelona games, placing fifth among all
nations. Cubans playing soccer at the National Sports City complex
in Havana. (Mike Williams/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BENNINGTON, Vt. -- Sept. 8, 2000 -- CARS-COLLECTING --
Terry Ehrich, 59, the publisher and editor in chief of Hemmings
Motor News and a major shareholder in its parent company, at the
wheel of a 1924 American LaFrance fire engine, one of the 78 cars
in his collection. In contrast to the pampered cars in many
collections, the Hemmings fleet is actually driven -- in parades,
for movie shoots and, each summer, by journalists who come to
Vermont for a day of deja vu on the roads. (Paul O. Boisvert/The
New York Times)
</P>
