<P>
   (NYT50) ATLANTA -- Sept. 8, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. SEPT. 10 --
CIVILRIGHTS-CHILDREN-COX-6 -- Peggy Wallace Kennedy, 50, the oldest
daughter of former Gov. George Wallace of Alabama. What she
remembers most about her father is the last years of his life. He
was shot and paralyzed in 1972 while running as an independent
candidate for president. The shooting changed him in many ways,
Kennedy says. He renounced his racial politics, began reading his
Bible every day and started seeking forgiveness. ``He would call
friends he hadn't talked to for a long time and say, 'If we got
anything to straighten out, let's straighten it out now.''' Kennedy
at her Montgomery, Ala. home. (Jay Sailors/The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT49) ATLANTA -- Sept. 8, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. SEPT. 10 --
CIVILRIGHTS-CHILDREN-COX-5 -- C.T. Vivian, a leader in the Southern
Christian Leadership Conference, took part in voter registration
drives throughout the South. In 1964, Albert Vivian saw his father
get punched in the face on national television. It's one of his
fondest childhood memories. The confrontation arose as Rev. Vivian
was attempting to register as voters a group of blacks turned away
from the courthouse in Selma, Ala. Albert Vivian, 38, is following
in his father's footsteps, taking over a consulting business that
offers racial sensitivity workshops for corporations and city
governments. ``His actions filled me with a gush of pride,'' says
the younger Vivian. Vivian and his father, at the Rev. Vivian's
Atlanta home. (Louie Favorite/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT48) CHICAGO -- Sept. 8, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. SEPT. 10 --
CIVILRIGHTS-CHILDREN-COX-4 -- Warith Deen Mohammed, 67, was
initially groomed to succeed his father, Elijah Muhammad Sr. The
youngest son of Muhammad's eight children, he had begun to doubt
his father's faith by the time he was a teenager. By 1964, his
father banned him from the movement. Today, Warith Deen Mohammed is
a Muslim elder statesman and has a new appreciation for his father.
``Elijah Muhammad wasn't a racist,'' he says, ``but rather an
uneducated man who patched together a religion that taught black
people self-reliance.'' Warith Deen Mohammed with a painting of
Malcolm X, in the background. (Jean Shifrin/The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT47) CHICAGO -- Sept. 8, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. SEPT. 10 --
CIVILRIGHTS-CHILDREN-COX-3 -- The Rev. James Bevel, 63, a key aide
to the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. and a legendary leader of the
student sit-in and Freedom Ride movements. Two of Bevel's
daughters, who live in Atlanta, still struggle with forgiving their
father for not providing for them while they endured a childhood
marked by homelessness, welfare and hand-me-down clothes. Bevel
says he would have given more support to his daughters if they had
been more dedicated to the movement. (Jean Shifrin/The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT46) MARIETTA, Ga. -- Sept. 8, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. SEPT. 10
-- CIVILRIGHTS-CHILDREN-COX-2 -- Chevara Orrin, 32, left, and her
sister Bacardi Jackson, 29, the daughters of civil rights activist
the Rev. James Bevel, a key aide to the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
and a legendary leader of the student sit-in and Freedom Ride
movements. Both say that Bevel never provided for them while they
endured a childhood marked by homelessness, welfare and
hand-me-down clothes. Both Orrin and Jackson were raised by their
mother Susanne Jackson, who met Bevel in 1965 in Chicago. (Jean
Shifrin/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT45) MACON, Ga. -- Sept. 8, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. SEPT. 10 --
CIVILRIGHTS-CHILDREN-COX-1 -- The civil rights movement in the
1950s and '60s unleashed waves of change and the leaders of the
movement led dramatic lives. And so did their children. The
children of the struggle -- the offspring of militants, nonviolent
activists and even segregationist leaders -- are now adults. Ericka
Brown-Abram, now 30, the daughter of a Black Panther Party leader
says she had a typical childhood. ``A lot of people had this
swashbuckling idea of the Panthers. But when you're a child it all
seemed normal.'' Abram at the Tubman African American Musuem in
Macon, Ga., where she works. (W.A. Bridges, Jr./The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
