   (NYT26) RAMALLAH, West Bank -- Sept. 8, 2000 --
PALESTINIANS-SCHOOLS-2 -- For decades, Palestinians in the West
Bank have used Jordanian textbooks and those in Gaza have relied on
Egyptian ones, making for a disjointed and ultimately borrowed
educational program. As part of the process of building
institutions for an emerging Palestinian state, the Palestinian
Authority, with money from European countries, is now trying to
create from scratch a genuine Palestinian curriculum, starting with
two grades as a pilot effort. Nesrin Alayan, left, holds a
Palestinian passport during a lesson on national identity in the
first grade classroom of Al Mustaqbal or The Future School, earlier
this week. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
