<DOCNO> NYT20000908.0457 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7287 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-NEWYORK-HNS &LR;      09-08 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 YORK-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Clinton, Jiang talk about trade
 &HT;    China assured bill in Senate will pass
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By PATTY REINERT
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ As the U.N. Millennium Summit wrapped up
Friday, President Clinton assured Chinese President Jiang Zemin
that he would deliver on China trade legislation, which is
scheduled for a Senate vote next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the legislation will pass, and I'm pleased at the
progress it's making in the Senate,'' Clinton told reporters during
a photo session before the two leaders began their meeting. ``But
of course we still have some work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade bill, already passed by the House, would mean
significantly lower tariffs for Americans selling goods in China.
</P>
<P>
   In a 90-minute meeting at The Waldorf Astoria hotel near the
United Nations, Clinton and Jiang had ``frank and friendly''
discussions on Taiwan, missile proliferation and religious
restrictions in China, a senior administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   The two presidents did not reach any specific decisions, the
official said, but the meeting served to review their eight-year
relationship, lay out where they stand on the issues and to ``get
these two men on the same wavelength a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think on that level this meeting served exactly the purpose
that we sought,'' the official said, adding that all of Clinton's
top foreign affairs officials also attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has been conducting private meetings with world
leaders on the sidelines of the U.N. summit for the past three
days, also met separately Friday with Irish Prime Minister Bertie
Ahern and Bolivian President Hugo Banzar Suarez.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, he was to attend a fund-raising dinner at a
private home in New York. Both Clinton and his wife, New York
senatorial candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton, were to speak at the
dinner, which was expected to raise $615,000 for the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's meeting with Jiang was their first since the two
countries reached agreement on China's entry into the World Trade
Organization more than a year ago. They are to talk again at a
meeting of Asian leaders after the U.S. presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Despite ongoing controversy over human rights and religious
restrictions in China, Clinton has urged Congress to grant the
country Permanent Normal Trade Relations status. Normalizing trade
and bringing China into the WTO, the president has said, would
encourage China to cooperate in dealing with hot spots around the
globe and to curb human rights abuses at home.
</P>
<P>
   The administration official, who briefed reporters after
Clinton's meeting, said Clinton told Jiang that he believed the
Senate would pass the PNTR bill. ``He's working hard on it; he
thinks we will get it,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The official added that Clinton has discussed human rights
issues at every meeting he's had with the Chinese leader, but does
not take the stance of rewarding China PNTR status in exchange for
a better human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has said publicly that he has felt the Chinese
are on the wrong side of history on how they handle these issues,
so this is not a new topic or one where they pull a lot of
punches,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Senate is to take up an amendment offered by
Sens. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., and Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., that
would lower the bar for imposing sanctions on China and other
countries determined to be involved in weapons proliferation, The
Associated Press reported. The administration opposes the measure
and supporters of the trade bill say its passage this year could be
doomed if the Thompson language is attached.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the toughest issue that we have to face on PNTR,'' Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Jiang also discussed Taiwan for the first time since
the island's opposition party won the presidential election.
Clinton encouraged Jiang to create a real dialogue between Beijing
and the new government in Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese are in a wait-and-see attitude,'' the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also emphasized the importance of continuing discussions
between the United States and China on missile defense, even though
the president has left any decision on developing a national
missile defense shield to the next president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he'll encourage his successor to engage in serious
dialogue with the Chinese and others so as to try to get a clearer,
common understanding of the threat and how we can all end up more
secure by what we do about it,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
