<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROMIS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWELL APPLAUDS KANSAS CITY'S VOLUNTEERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONALD BRADLEY, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ Retired Gen. Colin Powell hailed Kansas City on
Friday as the city doing best at keeping America's Promise.
</P>
<P>
   The pledge was born at a 1997 national summit in Philadelphia in
which delegates to ``America's Promise _ The Alliance for Youth''
were sent back to their cities to mobilize an army of volunteers to
provide caring adults, safe places, healthy starts, marketable
skills and volunteer opportunities for millions of needy children.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, ``Kansas City has done better than anyone
else in the country,'' Powell, chairman of America's Promise, told
a cheering audience of about 2,500 Friday at the American Royal's
Hale Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the audience were connected to the 900 promises made by
businesses, churches, schools and other organizations to provide
Kansas City children with mentors and tutors, and to provide
parents with books to read to their youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's celebrate today, then wake up tomorrow and figure how to
reach more children,'' Bob Rogers, chairman emeritus of the Ewing
Marion Kauffman Foundation, told the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said the
Promise movement was much like military training, in which soldiers
are given the best training and resources before being sent into
battle.
</P>
<P>
   Today the enemies for many children are drugs, violence, crime,
despair, broken homes and lack of education, Powell said. And when
parents are unable to help, the responsibility falls to the rest of
society.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to step in. We can't stand back,'' Powell said. ``We
owe our children nothing less.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every child is a gift from God _ not just to the parents but
to everyone in the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell compared America's Promise volunteers to women in the
south Bronx neighborhood where he grew up. The ``aunts'' lived in
tenement buildings and kept watch on neighborhood children from
upstairs windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those aunts never went to the bathroom,'' Powell said. ``Every
time I looked up, one of them was looking down.''
</P>
<P>
   At Friday's ``A Salute to Kansas City's Promise,'' there was
much talk about community service. Senior citizens talked about
adopting young children; teen-agers talked about adopting seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Berry, 17, described tutoring fourth-grade pupils in math
and how she felt when one girl smiled when she got an answer right.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what sticks with you,'' Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   Another teen, Marcos Harders, told what volunteering brought to
his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you self-respect and pride,'' Harders said.
</P>
<P>
   William C. Nelson, a delegate to the 1997 Philadelphia
convention and chairman of Friday's event, said Kansas City had
50,000 Promise volunteers. A forum will be held in November to
expand the movement, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done more than any city in America, and it is that
commitment that brought General Powell here today,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Beene, president of the United Way of America, also lauded
Kansas City for the way the city had embraced the Philadelphia
dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to start, harder to keep going and harder yet to
take to the next level,'' Beene said. ``Kansas City is a model for
the rest of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In his keynote speech, Powell encouraged corporate leaders to
jump on the Promise bandwagon and to try to help at-risk children.
Such outreach would produce future employees and customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You invest in the promise now or later with hgher taxes to
build new jails,'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   He also stressed community service for high school students _
something he would like to see made mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``But people tell me, `Slow down _ you're not a general
anymore,' &UR; '' Powell said. ``They say you can't make a youngster do
something against their will.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well they made me take algebra against my will.''
</P>
<P>
   The event was nonpolitical. But afterward at a press conference,
Powell stumped for Texas Gov. George W. Bush. He said a Bush
presidency would be better for America's children.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that as recently as Thursday, Bush had talked to
him about a possible job in a Bush administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
