<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOREOIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Gore shifts tack, backs oil tax break
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By BENNETT ROTH
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore dropped
his standard rap against big oil and plugged his tax incentives for
the energy industry Friday during a visit to a state where oil and
gas exploration fuel the economy.
</P>
<P>
   In an address at Delgado Community College, Gore noted that, as
part of a long-range economic plan unveiled this week, he has
proposed extending tax incentives for deep gas exploration in the
Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said such exploration will ``reduce our overdependence on
foreign oil. That's good for our environment and our economy and
American families.''
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to one of a handful of Southern states where Democrats
still are competitive on the presidential level, Gore said, ``Of
course, Louisiana plays an important role in our economy as a
leading producer of oil and gas, and natural gas is a proven source
of clean energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore did not reprise his usual criticism of his Republican
opponent, George W. Bush, and running mate Dick Cheney for their
ties to the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore camp has regularly branded the Republicans as the ``Big
Oil ticket.'' Bush previously worked as an energy company
executive, and Cheney resigned from Halliburton, a Dallas-based oil
industry company, to run with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett said it was ``highly hypocritical to
attack Governor Bush for his knowledge and expertise in the oil and
gas industry and at the same time cozy up to those constituents in
Louisiana.''
</P>
<P>
   At the community college, Gore stepped up his criticism of
Bush's Social Security plan, questioning how Bush could pay the $1
trillion transition costs of partially privatizing the system.
</P>
<P>
   That attack was amplified by a letter sent Friday to Bush by
Robert Ball, Social Security commissioner from 1962 to 1973, and
Henry Aaron and Alicia Munnell, two entitlement experts.
</P>
<P>
   The letter said that, in proposing to let younger people invest
a portion of their Social Security payroll taxes into private
accounts, Bush has not detailed how he would make up for the funds
drained from the retirement system. Those funds, estimated to be
about $1 trillion, would still be needed to pay current retirement
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do not include any general revenues to replace the money
that is drained by your individual account proposals. Is Social
Security too small a detail to include in your detailed budget?''
the authors wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett responded that the authors of the letter were
``partisan Al Gore supporters who have done partisan events for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he acknowledged that the transition costs for
Bush's Social Security plan would mean it would take four years
longer than Gore's plan to eliminate the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron, a scholar at the Brookings Institution who has written
extensively about Social Security, said he had been contacted by
the Gore campaign and ``asked, was I willing to sign onto a draft
letter.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron said that since the letter expressed the same views that
he had outlined in numerous published articles, he did not have any
problem signing on to it after recommending minor changes.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron said that while he supports Gore, he has not done any
campaign events for him.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's visit to Louisiana underscores his campaign's belief that
he has a chance in a state that twice went for President Clinton
but which is also a neighbor of Bush's Texas. On Thursday evening
in drizzly weather, Gore addressed an enthusiastic rally of more
than 8,000 in the French Quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Upon leaving New Orleans, Gore flew to Atlanta for two scheduled
Democratic National Committee fund-raisers before heading back to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
