<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGURES ON SAVINGS RATE MISLEADING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're worried about the anemic U.S. savings rate, relax. It
can't be as bad as the numbers indicate.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Commerce Department last month reported July's
personal savings rate at a negative 0.2 percent, there may be less
importance to that number than meets the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Americans aren't the spendthrift grasshoppers the declining
savings rate of recent years implies. At least they don't appear to
be when official savings numbers are compared with those measuring
real-world nest-egg-building.
</P>
<P>
   Another report came out about the same time the government was
saying the savings rate had hit its lowest mark since Washington
began keeping such stats in 1959. That report, from the Investment
Company Institute, didn't get as much media attention as the
savings debacle headline-grabber and certainly deserved more
scrutiny than it got.
</P>
<P>
   It revealed that mutual funds added 5 million new stakeholders
over the last year. That brought the total number of Americans
owning mutual funds to nearly 88 million. Measured in the context
of household ownership, almost half of American households now have
a stake in mutual funds. This is nine times the number of
households that owned mutual funds in 1980, the institute reported.
</P>
<P>
   There are two particularly interesting aspects to these numbers.
One is that small investors are responsible for much of the mutual
fund ownership growth. Over the last two years, the percentage of
households with annual incomes of $25,000-$35,000 owning mutual
funds has grown by nearly one-third. Overall, about one-third of
households with total incomes of $50,000 or less have a stake in
mutual funds. Almost 60 percent of households occupied by the 45-54
age group own mutual funds, an increase of 11 percent since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Another interesting angle to these numbers is that over the last
three decades the personal savings rate has been highest when the
economy was weakest. A chart accompanying the /{Wall Street
Journal/} savings story showed the rate from 1970-82 ranging from 8
percent to 12 percent as a percentage of disposable personal
income. Most astonishingly, the rate spiked to about 15 percent in
1975, at the trough of one of the worst recessions of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Just when the economy began to recover in 1982 is precisely when
the personal savings rate began its steady decline. Doesn't it seem
paradoxical that the savings rate has shown continuing decline
during a period when the number of households saving and investing
through mutual funds has exploded ninefold?
</P>
<P>
   As for the practical meaning of savings data, there seems little
to be concerned about given that the most prosperous period in U.S.
economic history has occurred during the worst deterioration of
savings statistics.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem counterintuitive to a generation nurtured on the
notion that saving is critical to prosperity and growth, but there
obviously has been a disconnect somewhere along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Is it the methodology used to measure U.S. personal savings, or
have the rules of the game changed? The only logical conclusion is
that it must be faulty measuring tools, because the investment
capital supplied by savings is now and always will be critical to
economic growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-00 2345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
