<HEADER>
A7296 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-NYT     09-08 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS DISMANTLES RED SOX WITH A REVITALIZED FASTBALL
</HEADLINE>
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Red Sox fans loathe Roger Clemens for leaving Boston.
They taunt him because he plays for the hated Yankees. They have
one more reason to despise Clemens, now that he's all but buried
Boston in the American League East standings.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens overpowered the Red Sox Friday night, striking out seven
and limiting them to five hits in eight innings, as the Yankees
shut out Boston, 4-0, to push the Red Sox seven games out of first
place _ the largest margin this season. David Justice singled and
hit his 37th homer.
</P>
<P>
   The game was delayed for several minutes in the ninth inning
after the Yankees' Ryan Thompson smashed a line drive off the face
of Boston pitcher Bryce Florie. With a gash under his right eye and
blood pouring from that cut, his nose and his mouth, Florie got up,
stepped onto a cart and was taken away for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is 12-6 with 259 career victories. The Red Sox went 0
for 5 with runners in scoring position; in Clemens' 15 starts since
June 9, he has held opposing hitters to 9 for 88 (.102) with
runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   American League hitters cannot hide from Clemens' revitalized
fastball. His legs and back are healthy, and his fastball was
clocked at 98 miles an hour once, 97 mph a couple of times, more
consistently at 95 to 96 mph, thumping loudly against Posada's
mitt.
</P>
<P>
   More telling than the speed readings, however, were Boston's
swings. They reacted to Clemens' fastball as if they were swinging
at dragonflies.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there was a river of adrenaline pumping through Clemens,
rather than just a steady stream, for this was his first game in
Boston since the Red Sox hammered him for five runs in two innings
in a playoff game here last October, and Fenway fans taunted
mercilessly. Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching coach, said it
was the worst he had ever seen any player booed in a place where he
had once been a star.
</P>
<P>
   But Clemens was pitching the same way against the Red Sox on
Friday night as he has against the rest of the league since coming
off the disabled list. He has not lost any of his last 15 starts, a
streak similar to his performance for Toronto in 1998, when he
didn't lose in the last four months of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Each time Clemens throws a fastball, the effort causes his lips
to part and bears his teeth, his mouth guard visible in a menacing
grimace. But there was no question Clemens was enjoying himself
immensely: He covered first base on a ground ball to Tino Martinez
to end the fourth inning, and after crossing the bag and getting
the out, Clemens popped the umpire Fieldin Culbreth on the backside
with his glove, a genial gesture.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees led, 1-0, in the sixth. Nixon led off the inning by
lofting a ball against the left field wall, a double, the tying run
in scoring position. But after Nixon advanced to third on
Offerman's grounder to first, Clemens overpowered Everett, who
fouled out, and retired Nomar Garciaparra on a fly to right. The
Red Sox shortstop is 3 for 28 in his career against Clemens, with
11 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   There were two outs and nobody on base in the eighth when
Everett came to bat, intent on at least unsettling Clemens,
stepping out of the batter's box a couple of times. Clemens looked
exasperated, backed away from the rubber. With two strikes he
pumped a high fastball, Everett swung and missed. The yellow radar
gun readings flickered above Fenway Park: 96 mph. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
