<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS OFFENSE PUNCHLESS IN 2-0 LOSS TO PHILLIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Friday night was the eighth day of September, a month
when the Mets have unraveled in different and dramatic ways for the
last two years. Their latest tumbling has not escalated to a
drastic stage yet, but they were back home at Shea Stadium, and
they wanted to stop this spell before it became too serious. They
wanted Mike Hampton to boost them.
</P>
<P>
   This was the type of pivotal game perfectly suited for Hampton.
The Mets acquired Hampton to help guide them into the post-season,
and, to get that far, they would obviously need him on nights like
this. While the Phillies might be one of the worst teams in
baseball, this was a spot for Hampton to perform like an ace. And
he did. Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton held the Phillies scoreless until Scott Rolen pounded a
two-run homer in the eighth inning, and that was enough to doom the
Mets in a 2-0 loss. After Rolen clubbed Hampton's 3-2 pitch,
Hampton immediately went down into a crouch and never looked up. He
remained in the crouch as the ball soared into the left-field
bleachers and stayed there until Rolen was rounding third base.
</P>
<P>
   But Hampton was not as relaxed as he looked. When Hampton walked
the next batter and was removed from the game, he did not even make
it to the first-base dugout before he whipped his glove like an
errant fastball. He rumbled down the steps, took a stack of towels
and slammed them repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton turned around and used his right forearm to almost knock
over a water cooler and almost knock a cup out of an unsuspecting
Todd Pratt's hands. After the forearm, Hampton walked toward the
clubhouse and flung his cap down the steps ahead of him. He was in
a volatile mood and showed a lot more power than the anemic offense
had shown all evening.
</P>
<P>
   The sputtering Mets are still having trouble scoring, and that
is why they lost for the sixth time in their last seven games.
Bruce Chen and four relievers stifled them on nine hits, holding
them without a hit in seven at-bats with runners in scoring
position.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies, who terrorized the Mets by sweeping a crucial
three-game series last September, ended an eight-game losing
streak. In the National League East, the Mets slipped to three
games behind the Braves, pending the outcome of their game against
the Expos Friday night, and in the wild-card race the Mets watched
their bulge over the Diamondbacks shrink to four and one-half games
as Arizona defeated Florida, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   With Jay Payton on first base and one out in the seventh,
manager Bobby Valentine elected to let Hampton bat. Valentine did
not want Hampton to bunt, either, as Hampton went up swinging and
slapped a single to center field. The hit put men on first and
second and knocked Chen out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets did not capitalize after Hampton's hit. Vicente
Padilla retired Derek Bell and Edgardo Alfonzo on groundouts. Chen
limited the Mets to eight hits in six and a third innings to
increase his scoreless streak to 202/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine claimed that the Mets had not played much differently
during this streak than they had played all season because they
were pitching ``pretty well,'' hitting ``OK'' and playing ``pretty
good'' defense. Still, even if the Mets have played similarly, the
results have been bad. The fans booed often at Shea Stadium as the
Mets stranded 11 runners, not the type of noise a team with
post-season aspirations expects to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a pretty good team,'' Valentine said. ``I think we're a
really good team, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton was antsy in the fourth as he gave up an infield single,
walked two and uncorked two wild pitches to load the bases. He
tugged on his sleeve, stomped down off the mound to retrieve the
baseball from Mike Piazza and was staring at a perilous situation
that he was almost fully responsible for. But Hampton retired Gary
Bennett on a groundout.
</P>
<P>
   After Hampton struck out the first two batters in the fifth,
Bobby Abreu sliced a shot that bounced inside the left-field line
and into foul territory for a double. Hampton did not flinch, and
he struck out Doug Glanville with a nifty changeup.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had a terrific opportunity against Chen in the first
when Bell and Alfonzo slapped back-to-back singles with one out.
Piazza, who was 3 for his last 16, tapped a ball back to Chen, who
got the fielder's choice at second. Todd Zeile then flied out to
right. There were several other scoring chances, but the most verve
any Met showed came when Hampton whipped equipment around like a
cranky toddler. Saturday is Hampton's 28th birthday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
