<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7314 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     09-08 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS REFUSES TO FOLLOW HER FATHER OUT OF THE STADIUM, AND BEATS
HINGIS 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just when Martina Hingis believed she had neutralized
her opponent's vaunted power, she was suddenly confronted with the
specter of Venus Williams' heart.
</P>
<P>
   It's a very big one, everyone should realize, after Hingis let
Williams off the hook and Older Sister surfaced from the depths of
a third-set deficit to claim a U.S. Open semifinal victory that was
deliciously desperate, if not uniformly pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Hingis took Williams apart in an Open final
between one polished teen-ager and another who was as raw as a cold
rain: ``A yearling,'' Williams said, laughing as she remembered her
1997 rookie Open run after her 4-6, 6-3, 7-5 victory sent her to
Saturday's final against Lindsay Davenport. ``I didn't know what I
was doing, basically.''
</P>
<P>
   What Williams did know Friday, after 24 consecutive victories
that included her Wimbledon title, was what it took to win just
about the time she looked worn out. She knew not to be afraid to go
for it, to ``take the opportunities, because when you don't,
they're gone.''
</P>
<P>
   In her game of punch and counter with the crafty Hingis,
Williams was the superior athlete and nothing about that will ever
change. But Williams deserves credit for so much more now because
stride and muscles alone do not make the legs chase the ball as if
it were life itself.
</P>
<P>
   At the point Hingis had a 5-3 lead in the third set, moments
before Williams' own father couldn't take the specter of defeat and
walked on out, it appeared Hingis' game plan of softening Williams
up with shots down the middle, into the body, was going to work.
Now Hingis, feeling the weight of nearly three sets at the
shot-making pace only a Williams can force, played the more
percentage angles, sent her ground strokes into the corners and bet
the tournament that Williams was in no shape to extend her angular
frame to dig them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was maybe my hope towards the end of the match,'' Hingis
admitted. ``That she would still miss some return or she'd give me
a chance to survive and finish it off.''
</P>
<P>
   At 3-5, 15-30, Hingis had a much-discussed overhead to put away
that could have set up double-match point. Hingis is sure to
remember the puny shot she returned to Williams' backhand for a
down-the-line winner. Not to be forgotten is how Williams
frantically stayed in that point, sprinting side to side, somehow
keeping the ball and her hopes in play.
</P>
<P>
   Williams and Hingis do not represent the classic matchup of the
baseliner versus the serve-and-volleyer. They are not Navratilova
and Evert, or McEnroe and Borg. But rarely in any tennis match are
we treated to the furious rallies of the type that filled the
second and third sets; the kind of points that reminded us these
two players don't have to embrace each other, or like each other,
but they sure should know that they bring out the best in each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it's a great time,'' Williams conceded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I do enjoy it,'' Hingis said. ``If you win, you enjoy
more than if you lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis had left the Arthur Ashe Stadium and appeared in the
corridor outside the women's locker room on the verge of tears.
Then came Williams, a little glassy eyed herself, with a distinct
wobble to her step. Her father, Richard, was already gone from the
National Tennis Center, out into New York's evening rush. Who knows
_ who cares _ why he bolted after his daughter netted a drop shot
for 15-30 in the ninth game of the third set? A pack of reporters
followed him out, just as the real story was about to unfold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah,'' Venus Williams said, about to author the headline.
``I've got a pretty big heart these days.''
</P>
<P>
   No brag, just fact.
</P>
<P>
   After saving her serve for 4-5, Williams broke Hingis at 15 to
pull even. On the 15-30 point, Hingis got a short ball and angled a
backhand crosscourt that looked like a winner. Williams was on it,
though, with an elastic stretch and a primal scream. Suddenly, the
two-hand backhand was down the line, deep in the corner. Hingis
spanked it into the net. Her shoulders sagged and her expression
finally seemed to say, ``I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   She is a wonderful player, Hingis is, who stands in tall even
against all these women who have half a foot on her. She had a plan
Friday, a thirst to win her first Grand Slam title since January of
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Yet just when Hingis began to believe she could be the toast of
the Open again, Venus Williams refused to follow her father out
into the street. He walked. She ran.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
