<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7316 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-ARYAN-NATIONS-NY     09-08 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ARYAN-NATIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A SOUND VERDICT IN IDAHO 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Sept. 9: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The $6.3 million verdict against the Aryan Nations, the white
supremacist group, and its leader Richard Butler may well put the
organization out of business. The defendants argue they should not
be punished for their racist and anti-Semitic ideology. But this
case was not about free speech or the right to hold odious views,
which the First Amendment protects. It was about holding an
organization responsible for assaults committed by its security
guards.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict of an Idaho jury sends a strong message that hate
groups will be held financially liable for the violence they
commit. It was properly about compensating victims who had been
terrorized and injured by the Aryan Nations' security guards.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs, Victoria Keenan and her son Jason Keenan, were
attacked by the guards after they stopped their car on a road near
the entrance to the Aryan Nations compound to retrieve a wallet
that had fallen out of the car. The guards thought the Keenans were
Jewish agents sent to attack the compound. They got into a truck,
chased the car, shot at it with an assault weapon, forced it into a
ditch, and then surrounded and physically beat the Keenans. The
guards were drunk at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the guards are now in prison for assault, and a third is
a fugitive. The lawsuit by the Keenans, who were represented by
lawyers with the Southern Poverty Law Center, charged the Aryan
Nations and Butler with negligence and recklessness in training and
supervising the guards. The jury awarded the plaintiffs $330,000 in
compensatory damages and $6 million in punitive damages, with the
bulk of that amount to be paid by Butler and the organization.
</P>
<P>
   The law center has sued other hate groups for violent acts
committed by their members. The purpose is to shut down groups that
engage in conspiracies or aid and abet violence. In 1990, the
center brought a civil suit on behalf of a black man who was killed
by neo-Nazi skinheads in Portland, Ore. A jury in that case awarded
the man's family $12.5 million against the skinheads and the White
Aryan Resistance, a white supremacist group that recruited and
trained skinheads.
</P>
<P>
   While free-speech issues are inevitably raised in these cases,
the Constitution is not violated when verdicts are rendered to
punish conduct and not speech. Clearly, if a supermarket had hired
drunken guards who shot at innocent passers-by, it would be liable
for the conduct of its employees, and may even be put out of
business by a large verdict. The same applies in this case. The
fact that the Aryan Nations and its members are motivated by a
political ideology does not shield them from liability to injured
parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
